<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS FACE NEW CHALLENGES IN PREPARING FOR SCHOOL YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For some teachers, preparing for back-to-school
Tuesday has meant more than just learning students' names,
absorbing new curriculum and planning the year.
</P>
<P>
   It also means some serious manual labor.
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Gonzales, for example, a second-grade teacher at
Pinewood Avenue Elementary School in the growing Tujunga
neighborhood, was busy this week moving and arranging student
chairs in her classroom, squeezing them in past a stack of 30 boxes
filled with new textbooks and class materials.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of material that has to be unboxed,'' she said
with some understatement, as she maneuvered a cartload of blue
plastic chairs into her room.
</P>
<P>
   The school has three custodians, but they were all busy on other
projects like stripping and redoing the floors _ plus Gonzales'
aide quit Wednesday, leaving her to rely on help from a school
volunteer's two children.
</P>
<P>
   As for the intellectual heavy lifting, like reviewing new
materials and getting mentally prepared for the start of school,
she said, ``That's what Labor Day weekend is for.''
</P>
<P>
   This always is a hectic time of year for teachers, a time for
last-minute preparations and staff development, of rearranging
furniture and wondering exactly what kind of students they'll have
to deal with for the next nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them spent at least some of their summer getting ready.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Schaffer, a seventh-grade math teacher at Hale Middle School
in suburban, affluent Woodland Hills, wanted to identify with her
students more, so she spent the summer reading all four Harry
Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the books they argue over,'' she said. ``I want to
see what they're reading. And you know what? They're fun to read.''
</P>
<P>
   While not every teacher will have as much physical work as
Gonzales, many in the primary grades of the Los Angeles Unified
School District will have to rearrange their classrooms because of
a new reading program called Open Court.
</P>
<P>
   The program requires students to make eye contact with the
teacher at all times, and deal directly with the teacher more,
rather than a teacher's aide. That means teachers who had their
classrooms arranged in clusters of desks, where students face each
other, are now rearranging them into a semicircle surrounding the
teacher's desk.
</P>
<P>
   It was once different:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a teacher's aide would say, this is the group I work
with and the teacher has this group. (Now) it's all
teacher-directed,'' said Pinewood Principal Esther Macias.
``Everybody's seats have to be facing the front so they can all be
looking at the teacher. In the past, it wasn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   For certain other teachers, moving will be a constant chore
throughout this school year.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``rovers,'' some teachers at year-round schools have to
change classrooms every time the track switches.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, that meant Sharon Levine, a teacher at Hart Street
School in middle-class Canoga Park, had to change classrooms every
other month.
</P>
<P>
   She did have movers helping her, she said, but she was never
quite sure when they'd arrive, or whether all her stuff would
survive the move. Plus, it was disruptive to the educational
process to constantly change classes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not roving, it's really good because you get a break
during the year, the kids get a break during the year,'' Levine
said. ``But if you're the rover, it's horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
