<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSAICHI PEGASUS ON TRACK TO WIN ECLIPSE AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fusaichi Pegasus (remember him?) is scheduled to
fly from Los Angeles to New York on Sunday to prepare for the final
races of his career.
</P>
<P>
   This will be his third visit to New York in 2000. He went to
Aqueduct in April and won the Wood Memorial. After winning the
Kentucky Derby brilliantly and losing the Preakness in a subpar
effort, he went to Belmont Park in June with an eye on the Belmont
Stakes, only to suffer a hoof injury in his stall and miss the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus hasn't competed since then, and he resumed
workouts only last week, recording a pair of 3-furlong works at
Hollywood Park. He is expected to have one prep race at Belmont
before bowing out in the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky., on Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the anticipation for his return to action is the fact no
other 3-year-old has come along all spring and summer to replace
him as the leader of the division. Fusaichi Pegasus was No. 1 in
his age group in the NTRA media poll as far back as March. He
remains No. 1 this week.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a revolving door at Nos. 2 and 3. Six different
horses have inhabited those slots since May - Red Bullet, Aptitude,
Commendable, More Than Ready, Dixie Union and Unshaded. They and
other pretenders to the 3-year-old championship have taken turns
knocking each other off.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet upset Fusaichi Pegasus in the Preakness, but skipped
the Belmont, finished third in the Dwyer, and is out for the year
with physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Other major-race winners were similarly humbled: Commendable won
the Belmont, but ran fourth in the Dwyer to begin a three-race
losing streak. Albert the Great won the Dwyer, but finished seventh
in the Jim Dandy and second in the Travers. Graeme Hall won the Jim
Dandy, then was sidelined with a knee fracture. Captain Steve won
the Swaps at Hollywood Park, then ran second in the Haskell. Dixie
Union won the Haskell, then ran fourth in the Travers.
</P>
<P>
   And so on. The challenger of the moment is Unshaded. He's the
new No. 2 in the rankings following his Travers victory Saturday at
Saratoga. But can he wrest the Eclipse Award for outstanding
3-year-old away from Fusaichi Pegasus?
</P>
<P>
   It gets complicated. At this time of year, the top 3-year-olds
are expected to begin to take on their elders. So if Unshaded wants
to win a race over Fusaichi Pegasus, he may have to beat leading
older horses like Lemon Drop Kid as well.
</P>
<P>
   There remains some skepticism that Fusaichi Pegasus will
actually race again. While he has been away, he was sold by owner
Fusao Sekiguchi to Ashford Stud for a reported $60 million and
scheduled to begin breeding duties in the winter. Surely his health
won't be put at risk if the slightest thing goes wrong in his
training.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does race, it's possible both he and Unshaded will
step up to the 3-year-olds-and-up division and use the 1-mile
Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont on Oct. 14 as a prep for the 1-mile
Breeders' Cup Classic. Unless Fusaichi Pegasus uses the 1-mile
Jerome Handicap against 3-year-olds at Belmont on Sept. 23 as his
stepping stone instead.
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded will have to meet and beat Fusaichi Pegasus in one of
those races to have any shot at the 3-year-old title.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will win the title if he captures the Gold Cup
or the Breeders' Cup Classic. Or, the way this year has gone, even
if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Classic recap: Skimming's victory over Tiznow in the $1
million Pacific Classic was the most exciting possible outcome for
Del Mar's marquee race. Skimming is an up-and-comer with an
aggressive front-running style, and Tiznow is a promising
3-year-old with the added intrigue of being Budroyale's full
brother.
</P>
<P>
   But how strong was the race? The exacta horses outran
third-place Ecton Park and fourth-place General Challenge, neither
at his Grade I-winning best. And although Skimming put up fast
fractions, he might have been carried by the Del Mar surface's
apparent affinity for pacesetters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Skimming's 1-mile clocking of 2:01 1/5 was the slowest in the
Pacific Classic's 10 runnings, but it earned a 117 Beyer speed
figure because the track wasn't playing all that fast. That's the
fourth highest Beyer figure of the year in races of more than 1
mile. Tiznow's 114 is third fastest among 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed signals will have to be sorted out when Skimming faces
sharper horses with more early speed on a more representative
track. He is pointing for the Oct. 15 Goodwood Handicap at Santa
Anita.
</P>
<P>
   More Pacific Classic fallout:
</P>
<P>
   --General Challenge's season appears to be over after he came
out of the race with swelling in his right foreleg. This was his
third defeat in a row since his Santa Anita Handicap victory. He'll
be sent to owners John and Betty Mabee's Golden Eagle Farm in San
Diego County for R&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   --Bobby Frankel's victories on consecutive weekends in the
Arlington Million (Chester House) and Pacific Classic lifted him
over Bob Baffert and into the national earnings lead.
Frankel-trained horses have earned $7.2 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day weekend: Del Mar's full stakes schedule for the long
weekend includes Saturday's Del Mar Debutante for 2-year-old
fillies (with Notable Career going for her third straight victory)
and Sunday's Del Mar Breeders' Cup Handicap (headed by Prime
Timber).
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga marks the end of its season Monday with Perfect Sting
running in the Diana Handicap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
