<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AIDSKIDS-AZR &LR;      09-01 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDSKIDS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-AIDSKIDS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MEDICAL ADVANCES OFFER KIDS HOPE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MAUREEN WEST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - One of the myths smashed in the recent foster-care
tug-of-war over Phoenix juvenile AIDS patient Stephanie Ray is the
idea that AIDS means imminent death.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly emerging medical fact is that acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, though ultimately deadly, is a chronic disease
that, given proper medication and vigilance, can last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   A life, especially a young life, can be planned.
</P>
<P>
   This change in outlook is most visible at Phoenix's only
juvenile AIDS clinic, the Bill Holt Pediatric Infectious Disease
Clinic at Phoenix Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a hospice for the dying, but a place where a longer
life is increasingly presumed.
</P>
<P>
   When clinic patient Onyx Teasley was born a decade ago with
rapid-onset AIDS, his life expectancy was only two to four years.
</P>
<P>
   But now at age 10, Onyx is doing well.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of 60 Valley children, including 14-year-old
Stephanie, treated for HIV or AIDS at the hospital's clinic.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the fortunate first wave of AIDS children who have
lived to see a better medical day. Ten of the 60 kids are older
than 10 and are thriving, thanks to effective medication and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the children treated at the HIV clinic since
it opened in 1995 were infected at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Although AIDS infection at birth is a growing nightmare around
the world, U.S. medical care has reduced the chances of an AIDS
mother in this country passing the disease to her child to about 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five years of the 1990s, more than 800 American
children annually were diagnosed with AIDS. But last year, only 93
children younger than 13 were discovered. Many states have reduced
the incidence to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, however, had as many new AIDS children last year as
larger states such as Texas and California. Among the reasons
health experts give for the high incidence in Arizona are:
relatively greater high-risk sexual activity, failure to routinely
check pregnant women for HIV or AIDS, patients with the disease
immigrating from Mexico, and better efforts to identify those with
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the 13 AIDS-infected children reported in Arizona
last year is only a fraction of what was fearfully predicted a
decade ago, according to the federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 13 new cases mean 13 Arizona families thrown into a
living horror, and not everyone survives: Four juvenile funerals
were held this year among the Phoenix clinic's patients.
</P>
<P>
   For the increasing numbers of survivors, lives must be planned
in a society that still treats the disease like a medieval plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we try to help enroll (the HIV clinic patients) in
school, we've had Valley schools tell us that they don't see why
they need to go to school; they're dying, aren't they?'' said Dr.
Jan Piatt, medical director of the clinic. ``No, they're not. And
we need a whole philosophy change. These kids need structure and
discipline and an education.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Onyx Teasley was one of 812 children in the United
States newly diagnosed with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his classes, Onyx has a teacher of his own at
Longview Elementary School. This is so he can avoid the normal
germs and viruses of large classrooms, which his fragile immune
system cannot handle. There is every expectation that, in the years
ahead, medical progress will strengthen him so he can lead a more
normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to live to be 100,'' said Onyx, when asked what he
wants to do with his life.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most difficult challenges is in meeting new kids.
Each time, he must explain his complicated medical condition, not
an easy thing for a 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   A normal life is still quite far from what most children at the
HIV clinic experience. Complicated family arrangements and frequent
personal and financial crises are the norm, according to Shawn Cox,
a social worker at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Messy family situations are not unusual, she said. Most families
are not as visible as that of Stephanie Ray, who has defied a
Wisconsin court order to live with a foster family, choosing
instead to remain with relatives in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Families often break up from the strain of the disease, Cox
says. Fathers often aren't around. Caregivers wear out. Most of the
time, the principal caregivers are mothers who themselves have AIDS
and who sometimes die leaving an unplanned family situation.
</P>
<P>
   These mothers often lack the energy and money to care both for
themselves and their child, so they neglect themselves. The daily
struggle, getting here and there, trying to find the rent or
mortgage money, reacting to a bad-sounding cough in the night,
overwhelm many people's ability to plan ahead or think straight.
</P>
<P>
   Some children with AIDS must go to foster care, where some
caregivers may not have the right training or patience to deal with
the disease or the children properly, Cox says.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of foster care, of death, of the truth, or an inability to
understand how to ask for medical care, medical experts say, keeps
some parents from even seeking proper care for their children.
These children are the most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The number of untreated children is unknown. But as the disease
makes its shift from killer to chronic condition, the horror
aspects that strike paralyzing fear into people may fade.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Children's Hospital clinic will soon help conduct a
long-term study of young people with AIDS, following them from
birth to age 24. The study will seek an understanding of the
effects of puberty on the course of the disease, and an explanation
of why AIDS juveniles often do not grow to normal height.
Psychological differences will also be studied.
</P>
<P>
   From her own observations, Piatt finds that older children with
AIDS seem kinder than other children their age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it is an empathetic response made possible by their
own struggles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Clarke-Steffen, who will direct the study at the clinic,
says the disease now is similar to where pediatric cancer was a
decade ago: no clear cure, but longer lives and lots of hope for a
down-range cure.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, she says AIDS resembles cystic fibrosis and
diabetes, in that it requires strict regimens and is characterized
by recurrent episodes of serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his overall health, Onyx had 40 sick days last year,
often missing school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with the virulence of the virus, the training of
the people doing the treatment, how good an advocate a parent is,
and close attention to changes in the child - and plain luck,''
Clarke-Steffen said.
</P>
<P>
   A child's will to live is an important factor, too, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke-Steffen also credits the advocacy of parents. Planning,
finding the right research programs, medications and clinical help
make all the difference. The fight is now moving into the schools
as the happy few survivors try to live their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system isn't prepared for us to live as long as we have
lived,'' said Onyx's mother, Melissa Teasley. She now talks to her
son about finishing high school and going on to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do this,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
