<SLUG> BC-JEWS-DIVIDED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LIEBERMAN'S SPEECHES DIVIDE U.S. JEWS  &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senator Joseph Lieberman's folksy mix of campaign rhetoric and
religious speech has revealed a widening rift between secularists
and observant believers in the American Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   The split came to the surface this week when the two national
leaders of the Anti-Defamation League asked the Orthodox Jewish
candidate for vice-president to tone down his stump speech about
God, faith and the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel G. Freedman, the author of ``Jew vs. Jew _ The Struggle
for the Soul of American Jewry,'' said the debate illustrates a
``complex mix of emotions about Lieberman _ feelings of Jewish
pride and the gnashing of teeth about him being too religious.''
</P>
<P>
   In Freedman's view, Lieberman's candidacy shows how the center
of the American Jewish community is shifting away from
secular/cultural Jews and ``towards more religious observance, not
just among the Orthodox, but also among the Reform and Conservative
movements.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other observers note that the American Jewish community
is being pulled into &LR;  two extreme directions.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread intermarriage is causing many Jews to lose touch with
their ethnic and religious heritage _ the ``Seinfeld and schmear''
camp.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many other Jews are reconnecting with
traditional practices such as eating kosher food, joining
synagogues, observing the Sabbath and exploring various forms of
Jewish mysticism.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the three main branches of organized Judaism (the
Orthodox, Reform and Conservative movements) have major
disagreements over homosexuality, the ordination of women and
whether to recognize the offspring of mixed marriages as Jewish
children.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, it's not surprising that the Jewish
response to Lieberman's pious campaign rhetoric has been all over
the map.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, in a campaign appearance in one of Detroit's
largest black churches, Lieberman said Americans must ``reaffirm
our faith and renew the dedication of our nation and ourselves to
God and God's purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks by the first Jewish vice-presidential candidate in
the nation's history prompted a quick and surprisingly strong
response from the Anti-Defamation League, a Jewish group dedicated
to fighting anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   It called such ``overt expressions'' of religious belief on the
campaign trial ``inappropriate and even unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Doug Kahn, executive director of the Jewish Community
Relations Council in San Francisco, said he has heard similar
concerns this week from other Bay Area Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling by many that it would be better to turn down
the religious volume by several notches,'' Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said many Jews fear that Lieberman's call could be ``taken
up by those who want to dismantle the wall of separation between
church and state _ even though Sen. Lieberman himself does not want
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern that it could make our work harder when
trying to deal with issues like prayer in public schools,'' Kahn
said. ``It muddies the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious language has always been a part of our political
discourse,'' he said. ``It's a long way from a candidate speaking
religious language to the state imposing religion on people.''
</P>
<P>
   By talking about their faith, Freedman said, centrist Democrats
like Lieberman are showing that ``religious language is not the
property of the Religious Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Some see another lesson behind the diverse Jewish reaction to
Lieberman's unapologetic discussion of his Orthodox Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Jews made the bet that to be accepted they couldn't
be too Jewish,'' said Rabbi Alan Lew, the spiritual leader of
Congregation Beth Sholom in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's galling to these people to see that the Jew who is
finally nominated to national office wasn't someone who'd given up
his Judaism,'' he said. ``That threatens people who feel
uncomfortable about being Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lew is not impressed with the level of the
religious rhetoric coming from all the major candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using their religion to condemn and distance
themselves from President Clinton sexual indiscretions, Lew would
like to hear the candidates discuss ``how their religious practice
gives them a sense of connection and responsibility toward
others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What upsets me is that Lieberman and Gore don't sound that
much different from the way the Religious Right talks about God,''
said Lew. ``Let's talk about homeless people dying in the
streets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
