<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-RACIAL-PROFILING-SFCH     09-01 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-PROFILING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO STUDY RACIAL PROFILING AMONG LEGISLATION SENT TO
GOV.  DAVIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ After a last minute compromise with Gov. Gray
Davis, the Legislature voted Wednesday to insert California into
the emotionally charged national debate over racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The bill orders legislative analysts to study statistics
voluntarily being collected by some 70 law enforcement agencies
around the state on the ethnicity of persons they detain.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill caps a fight between Davis and more liberal
Senate Democrats over determining how widespread is the practice of
police officers and sheriff deputies detaining persons solely
because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling was just one of hundreds of bills lawmakers
zipped through as they raced toward a midnight deadline to complete
their work for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like college. You have a whole semester but you do
your best work right before finals,'' said Sen. Don Perata,
D-Oakland. ``That's what we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other bills sent to the Democratic governor were
measures to decriminalize abandoning newborns in some cases, spend
$30 million to help clear the way to build two new runways at San
Francisco International Airport, and provide $500 million in aid to
cities and counties which can be used to improve local services
like libraries and recreational programs.
</P>
<P>
   The racial profiling bill was a good example of the frenetic
activity of the final day of the legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Killed once this week by liberal Senate Democrats, the bill
resurfaced late Wednesday night and was sent to Davis at 8 p.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals in the Legislature had wanted to order all law
enforcement agencies to compile statistics on the persons they
stop. Davis didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Among the jurisdictions collecting data are Alameda County,
Solano County, Hayward, Fremont, Oakland, San Francisco, San Jose
and the California Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill hope the legislative study will show how
often _ if at all _ members of minority groups are being stopped
simply because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, including Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles, said the
bill contained no ``meaningful police accountability'' and failed
to expand data collection.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also requires California's police officers and sheriffs
deputies to take ``cultural diversity'' training. And it requires
peace officers take a refresher course.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the road but a significant step
forward,'' Murray said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also made California one of the first states to allow
mothers to anonymously abandon newborn babies at hospital emergency
rooms without fear of criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, by Senate GOP Leader Jim Brulte of Rancho Cucamonga,
was approved unanimously, and brought together usual adversaries
such as Planned Parenthood and the National Right to Life Committee
in its support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a small subsection of our population that leaves kids
to die. This bill is intended to give those mothers another
option,'' Brulte said. Under the bill, mothers _ or someone else
who has legal rights to the child _ could turn in the baby to a
hospital emergency room within 72 hours of birth and would be
immune from criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The child would be given any necessary medical treatment and
then would be turned over to a child welfare agency. The mother or
other legal guardian could return to the agency within 14 days with
positive identification and reclaim the baby.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief proponents of the bill is Debi Faris, a mother
of three from Yucaipa (San Bernardino County), who started the
Garden of Angels in 1996 after hearing on the radio about a baby
boy found on the side the road. She took charge of burying the boy
and two others who were also at the coroner's office awaiting
cremation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also approved a measure spending $30 million to help
buy 19,000 acres of salt ponds in the South Bay owned by the
Cargill Salt Co.
</P>
<P>
   The land purchase is intended to be the environmental mitigation
for filling 1,000 acres of the bay to build two new runways at San
Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase of the property is estimated at $30 million, with the
federal government kicking in half. Restoring the salt flats to
wetlands is estimated to cost at least another $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling has received mounting national attention this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Seven states, including Rhode Island, have required law
enforcement agencies to collect information on traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, President Clinton ordered federal law officers to
collect data on traffic stops to see if racial profiling occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's bill is supported by Davis who has also pledged $5
million in state grants to police and sheriff departments that want
to gather data on persons they stop.
</P>
<P>
   The governor vetoed a bill last year that would have ordered all
state law enforcement agencies to collect data on traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said it was ``questionable'' whether the
information would halt the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature also approved another racial profiling bill,
this one on student suspensions. It includes data collection.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ SB 444 by Sen. Richard Alarcon, D-Los Angeles _
requires school districts to break down suspensions and expulsions
by age, race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Districts are required to report to their school boards when and
for what reason a student is suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the state's 1,054 school districts now collect
data on the ethnicity of suspended students, said Alarcon. They
are: Oakland, San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   One bill sent to Davis would give cities, counties and special
districts $212 million they can spend on what they wish.
</P>
<P>
   The money was approved earlier this year in the state budget but
lawmakers struggled for the last two months over how to distribute
it.
</P>
<P>
   A second bill -- by Senate President John Burton, D-San
Francisco -- offers future fiscal relief by capping the amount of
local property tax revenue raked off by the state.
</P>
<P>
   By 2004, the bill would leave $300 million that would have gone
to the state with cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
   The then cash-strapped state began taking $3.4 billion in local
property taxes in 1992 during the height of the recession.
</P>
<P>
   Because the assessed value of local property has increased since
1992, so has the state's take. This year, the state grabs slightly
more than $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's bill would stop the annual increase in the amount of
property tax money the state takes from locals. The cap would be
phased in one-third each year for three years, beginning in the
state's fiscal year beginning July 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The first year cities and counties would receive approximately
$100 milion in new money, $200 million the next year and $300
million the third year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
