<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBBER-SOLE SURVIVOR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This limp? Ah, it's nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I was strolling quickly along Market Street, the sidewalk was
hot, and I blew out one of my Firestone-tread  &UR; huaraches  &LR; (Mexican
sandals).
</P>
<P>
   I went down, rolled twice, fortunately crashing into a homeless
guy's cardboard shack. Hope he's got non-homeowner's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   My attorneys contacted Firestone, which is blaming the huarache
maker, and also claiming that my bunions were dangerously
underinflated.
</P>
<P>
   They say excessive speed contributed to the blowout, and I
thanked them profusely.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO VIGILANTES Snag Serial Squatter.
</P>
<P>
   That's your tabloid headline of the day. Gotta sell papers.
</P>
<P>
   But a true and heartwarming tale it is, of neighborhood
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Juri Commons is a tiny park near Guerrero and 26th. It is
well-used and often abused. One major problem was the Midnight
Pooper.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, in the children's playground area, was a fresh
pile of human stuff. A group of neighborhood folks who try to keep
an eye on the park reported the problem to police.
</P>
<P>
   But the cops could never catch the perp with his pants down.
</P>
<P>
   This went on for about five months, same bad news every morning.
Three child-care groups stopped coming to the Commons.
</P>
<P>
   You should know that these neighborhood activists are not
anti-homeless. They worked hard to get a J.C. Decaux sidewalk potty
installed nearby for the street people. But the park was being
fouled.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one neighbor set up a hidden camera, and six nights in
a row captured on video a man pooping on the pavement and peeing in
the kids' sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   The video was delivered to the police, who immediately made an
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Now the kids are back. Tell me this isn't a movie crying out to
be made.
</P>
<P>
   SANDBOXES, by the way, are passe.
</P>
<P>
   People and cats mistake them for rest rooms. Wine bottles and
needles go there to die.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad, but playground rubber mats are safer and cleaner than
sandboxes.
</P>
<P>
   But it ruins an old joke. This doesn't work: ``I didn't make it
through kindergarten. I flunked rubber mat.''
</P>
<P>
   GAY BOWLERS outed!
</P>
<P>
   I've got tabloid fever, so sue me. (Readers Sue Sensationalistic
Scribe!)
</P>
<P>
   Japantown Bowl is going out of business, and among those being
tossed out of the alleys and into the streets are the city's gay
bowlers.
</P>
<P>
   Six different gay men's leagues bowled at Japantown. I checked
it out last Friday, the final night for the Friday Community Trios
league. Serious bowling. These guys rolled four perfect games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling has the best team names. This league includes the Slo-mo
Homos, Bitch Magnets, Los Reynitos (Little Queens) and Sodomy
Mucho. Come on, folks, it's all in fun!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, now the boys will have to lug their balls all the way to
Serramonte.
</P>
<P>
   And another bit of the city's character fades away.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY GARCIA impounded!
</P>
<P>
   The city hauled off an anonymously placed statue of the late
leader of the Grateful Dead because the city's art bureaucracy had
been end-arounded.
</P>
<P>
   That was galling to Garcia fans, but (sigh) laws are laws.
</P>
<P>
   So how come the city hasn't confiscated the massive
double-escalator still-life art installation at Hallidie Plaza?
Surely the Arts Commission didn't OK that eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S UGLY, the local trial where as many as 14 people involved
in public-housing voucher bribes have plea-bargained and could
testify against a high-ranking Housing Authority official.
</P>
<P>
   With all that singing, the trial should be held at the Opera
House.
</P>
<P>
   And which is uglier? The alleged deeds of the ringleader, or the
fact that everyone else will skate off easy after snitching?
</P>
<P>
   A key witness, who casually admits she shook down poor and
desperate people for voucher bribes, brags that she is Willie
Brown's goddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Willie the Godfather. That has a chilling ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN IRISH ice are tinkling:
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt (``Angela's Ashes,'' `` 'Tis'') dropped by the
Buchanan Grill in the Marina. Frank's little brother Michael tends
bar there.
</P>
<P>
   Michael can tell a story or two, too, and folks are always
asking him when  &UR; his  &LR; book is coming out. Michael's reply:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday. And it will expose this nonsense Frank wrote about
Irish poverty. I spent my youth on the polo fields of Limerick and
wandering the vineyards of the McCourt estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the watercress crop failed, and we had no sandwiches for
tea. So we fired all the servants and sailed for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Check, please!
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S KILLING whom?
</P>
<P>
   Joe the Cabbie and R.L. both alert me to some disturbing AT&AMP;T
Cable billboards around town.
</P>
<P>
   The billboard says that if you sign up for AT&AMP;T Cable, you'll
get to see the TV show ``Homocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   Spellcheck, please!
</P>
<P>
   IN CLOSING (as I stack the chairs onto the tables, and Sinatra
slouches sadly toward the door):
</P>
<P>
   Be kind to dot-commers. In a special blood drive this week,
local dot-com employees gave 122 pints.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' says Rebecca Rivera, ``Even vampires have hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   The cool thing is, the blood has already quadrupled in value.
</P>
</TEXT>
