<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE'S LORIER IS OFF TO QUICK START AT LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ben Lorier said Cal State Northridge football
coaches told him to do two things: Play hard and play fast.
</P>
<P>
   He did both. And the freshman earned a starting spot in the
Matadors linebacking corps for the season opener against Air Force
on Saturday in Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Lorier was listed as a backup to Pieter Keus at weakside
linebacker when fall camp started. It took only a couple of weeks
for him to move into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to me,'' Lorier said. ``I didn't think they
were going to redshirt me but I didn't think I was going to get
!ital!that!off! much playing time. I guess it was meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorier, who is 6-foot, 210 pounds, had an outstanding high
school career. He helped Westlake High beat San Luis Obispo to win
the Southern Section Division IV Championship last year, blocking a
field goal attempt late in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   And, apparently, he's made a good transition to college
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very productive,'' linebackers coach Terrance Johnson
said. ``He has a natural instinct for the ball. He's done some good
things. He may be out of position (sometimes) but he'll find a way
back to where he's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorier might feel some pressure: His first game as a starter
will be against a Division I team and before a crowd that could
reach 52,480.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest game ever was the Southern Section game in high
school,'' Lorier said. ``That was only 8,000 (fans) or so. This is
(52,000). It's a lot bigger than I'm used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who played linebacker for the University of Colorado
from 1986-90, said he'll tell stories about playing in front of big
crowds to ease any anxiety Lorier might have.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't worried that the young player will be overcome by
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finds the ball, diagnoses the play and gets involved,''
Johnson said. ``You can't coach that. He's going to be tested. I
don't think he's seen the speed that will be displayed Saturday,
but once he gets used to it, he'll be fine. As he gets over the awe
he'll be fine. Hopefully, he'll be able to get some sleep Friday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   If he gets any sleep, he'll probably be dreaming of Air Force's
option.
</P>
<P>
   Turn that dial: This will be the first season fans won't be able
to listen to Matadors football games on the radio. CSUN couldn't
raise the $12,000 needed for the KCSN broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Once Matadors coach Jeff Kearin learned the money wasn't raised
through normal channels, he thought about trying to raise it
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were going to have it, I was going to have to raise the
$12,000,'' Kearin said. ``But I had to fight other battles. I'm
sick about it, but that's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
