<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON'S AVERAGE ON THE UPSWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Asking the Anaheim Angels' Garret Anderson to take a
pitch might be like asking Darin Erstad to take a nap, or like
asking Mo Vaughn to lay down a bunt. They might do it, but not
without a grimace and a grumble.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's approach at the plate is what makes him the hitter he
is - which can be both good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   The good: Anderson has a career-high 31 homers and his 89 RBI
are second on the team only to Vaughn's 100. Anderson needs four
more RBI to establish a new career high.
</P>
<P>
   The bad: His on-base percentage (.295) is among the worst in the
majors. He's among the league leaders in hitting into double plays
and has walked only 21 times all season. He was a .300 lifetime
hitter going into this season, but is hitting .270 entering
tonight's game against the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia and hitting coach Mickey Hatcher
rave about Anderson's tools, his quick hands and pretty stroke.
They know Anderson could be a better hitter if he had more
discipline at the plate, but they don't want to change him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work within the strengths of a hitter and utilize them the
best you can,'' Scioscia said. ``With Garret, as he matures as a
hitter he'll understand how to be aggressive but selective within
the strike zone. I think you'll see him become the total offensive
package. Right now, his strength is he puts the ball in play
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, Anderson was hitting .241 and admitted he
was ``embarrassed'' by his average. But he didn't change much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a checklist of things that I go through to make sure I
have the right approach,'' he said. ``I keep it simple. There are
not a lot of adjustments to make. I take bits and pieces of what
people say, but I know what I've done in the past and what I did to
get here. I know what works for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His approach has worked since. He hit .337 in July and .295 in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has been more disciplined and has gotten more
counts in his favor,'' Scioscia said. ``It's why his average is
creeping up to the range is should be. But if you look at Garret as
a player that has to get on base and set the table, you're asking
him to do something he hasn't been real comfortable with in his
career. These things take a little time. But in the long run we're
all very happy with where Garret is now and with the numbers he's
putting up.''
</P>
<P>
   Players needed: Despite the fact rosters may be expanded to as
many as 40 players beginning today, the Angels will add only four
players for a total of 29.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Justin Baughman and relievers Bryan Ward and Ben Weber
were called up from Triple-A Edmonton and catcher Matt Walbeck was
activated from the disabled list. All four will join the team
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
