<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-01 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE'S GOODWILL AMBASSADOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For at least a few minutes Thursday, I forget about such warm
sporting subjects as the status of the Sydney Olympic torch, Tiger
Woods, Dennis Miller's mindless cant, Davey Johnson's future,
Isaiah Rider's past, Oscar De La Hoya's loyalty, UCLA, Cory Paus,
the NFL, Damir Dokic and Gary Payton's big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to stroll around the most uplifting, most lively, most
colorful, most inclusive and most intellectually stimulating place
in Long Beach with one its greatest goodwill ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, means walking the Long Beach State campus with
the school's president, Dr. Robert ``Fightin' Bob'' Maxson, which
means watching the energetic man go through an exhausting ritual of
high fives and hand shakes with a gaggle of smiling students.
</P>
<P>
   When I went to college, I never saw its president, much less
said hello to him. I didn't even know the bloke's name.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Maxson knows everyone on campus - from the janitors to the
professors to the secretaries to the fast-food workers to seemingly
every student - and there is no doubt he is the person responsible
for the feel-good atmosphere that pervades Long Beach State these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Disneyland is the happiest place on earth, then Long Beach
State is the second happiest,'' says Wayne Stickney-Smith, a campus
leader, to a beaming Maxson as we stand in the upper tier of the
Student Union area that is teeming with noontime activity.
</P>
<P>
   Maxson is beginning his seventh year at Long Beach State, and he
has instilled a sense of provincial pride among the student - ``Go
Beach'' signs and banners are everywhere - that was notably lacking
before his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``How're you doing, Tayyiba?'' Maxson asks Tayyiba Haneef, the
6-foot-6 volleyball star who suffered a pulled stomach muscle
during a recent practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hurting right now, but I'll know later when I meet
with the trainer if I'll be able to play,'' replies Haneef, whose
team opens its season tonight against St. Mary's at the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Maxson spots Rudy Williams, the basketball player who's had
recent surgery on both legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, no more shin splint problems,'' says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have a giant season,'' predicts Maxson.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the women's volleyball coach, Brian Gimmillaro makes
an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people hurt and that bothers me,'' says
Gimmillaro, who has reinstalled the Blonde Bombshell from Colorado,
Brittany Hochevar, as his setter and moved the capable Keri
Nishimoto to the back row. ``But once we get healthy we're going to
be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Maxson smiles broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gimmillaro is one of his favorites, not only because
Gimmillaro's teams win so consistently but also because he and
Gimmillaro share a similar passion - a devotion for Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, the basketball transfer from UCLA, Travis
Reed, expected to be the 49ers' starting center this season, pumps
Maxson's ever-moving right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to help lift our program to a higher level - into
the NCAA playoffs,'' says Reed with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Maxson nods approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I proudest of since I've come here?'' says Maxson,
echoing a reporter's question. ``Well, I guess what I'm proudest of
is the way so many students feel so good about attending Long Beach
State. They really seem to be enjoying themselves here, and that
makes me feel very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxson spots one of Dave Snow's top players, shortstop Bobby
Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a young man who recently played on the U.S. National
team, and batted over .300 against the top amateur teams in the
world,'' says Maxson. ``He's going to be a first-round draft pick
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Maxson continues his non-stop interaction with the students,
and savors every moment of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``First week back to school is always special for me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend also will be special for Bob Maxson and his wife
Sylvia. Their daughter, Kim, a Las Vegas attorney, is getting
married Sunday in Corona Del Mar to Ric (cq) Rushton, a former race
driver now in private business.
</P>
<P>
   As Bob Maxson surveys his domain, he says softly, ``I couldn't
ask for things to be better than they are for me at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the school he commands, a school he
has upgraded dramatically during his bright tenure. ...
</P>
<P>
   --One of my most hallowed theories in life is that human beings
don't change, especially ones with sociopathic traits with lengthy
histories of bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   So, natch, I don't envision the Lakers' acquisition of Isaiah
``J.R.'' Rider, excommunicated from Portland, Minnesota and
Atlanta, as being a move that will turn out favorably for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Rider is an extraordinary athlete with explosive
offensive skills, but he's also been an extraordinary pain in the
posterior throughout his basketball career who's been habitually
tardy for practices and feuded with teammates, coaches and fans.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that Rider can play.
</P>
<P>
   Also no doubt he won't last long with the Lakers. . .
</P>
<P>
   --Phil Jackson's hand prints were all over the Rider
transaction. If Jerry West still were around, his wouldn't have
been. . .
</P>
<P>
   --Are Laker execs like Mitch Kupchak serious when they say there
isn't any downside to having Rider on the roster? Obviously, those
who recite such rubbish never have toiled in a work place alongside
a combustible personality and endured the constant tension of such
a harrowing experience. . .
</P>
<P>
   --Dennis Miller is such a bust he's not even worth mentioning
any longer. The poor guy has become the Carlos Perez of Monday
Night Football. . .
</P>
<P>
   --But Will His Groovy Mug One Day Wind Up On Mt. Rushmore? As I
interviewed Pat McCormick the other day, I asked the four-gold
medal- winning Olympic diving champion of the 1950s and Seal Beach
resident if she knew local policeman Ravishing Rick ``The Macho
Cop'' Paap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Paap is a sacred part of Seal Beach history,'' she
retorted, honest to goodness, cross my heart and hope to die - or,
even worse, force you to watch one of Paap's campy puppet acts - if
I'm lying.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the fiftysomething, aspiring actor, aspiring bon
vivant, aspiring millionaire, aspiring retiree still is hosting the
wildly popular ``Talk of the Town'' show on the Seal Beach cable
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   While Paap's gig hasn't exactly had a widespread impact - I
originally thought Paap was destined to be the next Ed Sullivan -
it still has proved to be quite entertaining, as next Thursday
night's 7 o'clock show figures to be featuring such former boxing
luminaries as Scrap Iron Johnson, Joey Orbillo, Carlos Palomino and
Armando Muniz. . .
</P>
<P>
   --I'm biased, certainly, but an athletic fanatic would be
depriving himself scandalously if he didn't regularly punch up Joe
McDonnell's LA Sports 2000 (www.lasports2000.com) on the Internet,
a madcap mixture of national sporting articles and the Big Nasty's
unique fulminations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
