<HEADER>
A8056 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DON'T-PAY-RANSOMS-ECO     09-01 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DON'T-PAY-RANSOMS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIGH PRICE OF PAYING RANSOMS: MORE HOSTAGES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 675-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   These are cracking good times in the hostage business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, according to an insurance company that tries to keep
count, the numbers taken captive increased by 6 percent over 1998,
and it has been like that for several years: kidnappings for ransom
are up by 70 percent over eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Most are in Latin America, but the numbers have risen sharply in
former Soviet states too. The remarkable deal just concluded in the
Philippines helps to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Muammar Qaddafi, trying these days to shake off Libya's
pariah status and ingratiate himself abroad, seems to have bought
the release of several western hostages held by a band of Islamist
bandits on the Philippine island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
   Though some remain captive, including an American snatched on
Aug. 29, one batch of liberated westerners passed through Libya
this week to thank the colonel for his role in their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Whether with his own money or other people's, he paid, it seems,
$1 million per western head _ above the going rate for the group's
Asian hostages, nine of whom had earlier been released for roughly
$5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many had been held since April. Others _ curious journalists, a
group of evangelists _ had been snatched on visits to the
kidnappers and their prey. A German journalist was freed after his
employers had paid a ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers, evidently, have learned two lessons: holding a
few hostages keeps the army away; grabbing more keeps the money
rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   It is a principle that seems to apply elsewhere too. A month ago
in India a notorious Tamil bandit snatched a hugely popular film
star, sparking riots among his outraged fans. This week 51
prisoners, all cronies of the bandit, were due to be released in an
effort to please him. Only India's Supreme Court is resisting such
dubious deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   All over the world the habit has caught on. The ragtag West Side
Boys who seized 11 British soldiers and one of their own
compatriots in Sierra Leone last week want the release of their
leader, ``Brigadier Bomb Blast.'' They are no doubt inspired by the
snatching _ with impunity, if not reward _ of hundreds of U.N.
troops by rebels in May.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear whether George Speight's recent kidnapping
of Fiji's prime minister and much of its cabinet will be judged a
success or a failure for Speight personally, but it has certainly
inspired an attempted coup in the Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Afghan gunmen diverted a plane from Kabul to
London, copying hijackers who had escaped scot-free after taking a
plane from India to Afghanistan a few weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In some poor, gun-ridden parts of the world, selling the freedom
of foreigners or rich locals is a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, it is known as ``miraculous fishing,'' as rebels
block roads and hook out victims. In the delta region of Nigeria,
oil workers are snatched in return for money _ even for jobs. In
Yemen, villages win public works for releasing unwary tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnapping has many causes: inequalities of wealth, availability
of guns, rebel armies looking for funds, underpaid police. But the
main reason for the boom is simple: the rewards.
</P>
<P>
   For the hostages, of course, freedom is worth any amount of
money. But as the Philippine government points out, that money buys
more guns and bombs _ and more hostages. Reports from Jolo suggest
that the rebels have already bought new weapons and a speedboat.
</P>
<P>
   The way to reduce kidnapping is to show that it does not pay.
Ideally, that means capturing the kidnappers and punishing them.
But it may also mean making it illegal to pay a ransom, as it is in
Italy and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
   For victims and their friends and families, the temptation is
always to shell out. But thereby the practice continues.
</P>
<P>
   The hard rule is best: don't pay ransoms. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
