<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8058 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-GORE-THE-POPULIST-ECO     09-01 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-THE-POPULIST-ECONOMIST-LEX-700&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE, THE PEOPLE'S PRINCE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 2 trims,125; 1,100 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 975-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 700 (75 WORDS) AND 925 (50
WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Who could have guessed it? America is into the tenth
year of the longest economic boom in its history. The country is
minting millionaires so fast that psychologists have discovered a
whole new mental disorder _ ``affluenza'' _ that results from
having huge piles of cash dumped on your head.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Al Gore, Tennessee princeling and ultimate Washington
insider, has revived his fortunes not just with a kiss, but by dint
of one of the most antiquated ideas in the political lexicon: the
class struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago it looked as if nothing could help the hapless vice
president. He boasted about his long-standing interest in the new
economy _ and a slip of the tongue transformed him into the man who
invented the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He embarked on a ``Prosperity and Progress Tour'' accompanied by
the spectacularly prosperous Robert Rubin _ and his poll numbers
continued to sag.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no sooner had he reinvented himself as a class-warrior than
Americans discovered that they loved him after all.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decision to declare class war caused heart attacks among
leading Democrats. President Bill Clinton had built his political
career on exactly the opposite premise: that the best way to win
votes is to embrace business rather than bash it.
</P>
<P>
   The New Democrats, who have made the intellectual running in the
party for a decade, urged Gore (who was surely one of them) to move
further in the same direction: forget about all those waitresses
and truckers that they sing about relentlessly in Nashville and
embrace consumer choice and wired workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore desperately needed a way to connect with a restive
Democratic base (and to slow Ralph Nader's advance in key states
like California).
</P>
<P>
   And a group of Democratic pollsters, including Stanley Greenberg
and Ruy Teixeira, argued forcefully that the real swing voters in
this election are not suburban professionals but the 55 percent of
the population who belong to the white working class.
</P>
<P>
   So a man whose earliest experience of this ``forgotten
majority'' was ringing for room service in Washington's Fairfax
Hotel became a champion of the people against the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Populism a la Gore has gone down better than anybody expected.
It has endowed him with an independent identity after years in
Clinton's shadow. It has provided his schizophrenic campaign with a
theme. And it has allowed him to tap into his family's political
roots in Tennessee populism, putting a little zing into his
normally dull speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's post-convention bounce has not only held up remarkably
well across the country, with the candidates neck-and-neck in the
polls. It has held up well in blue-collar states such as Michigan,
Minnesota and New Jersey, where Bush had long enjoyed an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Populism is a high-stakes strategy, of course. It risks
associating the Democrats with the ancient canard that big
government in Washington can solve all America's problems. It also
risks identifying them with the losers in a society obsessed with
winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to lead a nation by dividing it,'' says an
increasingly worried George W. Bush. ``That's the rhetoric of the
past; that's class warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, a man whose career has been more or less made for him
by his father's friends, is hardly the best advertisement for the
idea that class has no place in modern America.
</P>
<P>
   And his vice-presidential choice, Dick Cheney, a genuine product
of the meritocracy, is compromised by the fact that he not only
received a $13.6 million golden handshake from his old employer,
Halliburton, but also voted for a $9.5 million payoff for one of
the most disastrous bosses of recent years, Procter &AMP; Gamble's Durk
Jager.
</P>
<P>
   Gore picks his targets carefully, hammering away at the evils of
big oil, big tobacco and big health-care conglomerates. This week,
for example, he went to Florida to criticize the ``exorbitant''
cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He is also well-protected from the charge that he is a
root-and-branch enemy of business. He spent the past eight years in
the White House without making any noticeable attempt to
nationalize the means of production, and his crusade against ``big
oil'' has not prevented him from having large family holdings in
Occidental. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 700) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   His party has also taken the precaution of dumping the one group
that has always doomed populist campaigns in the past: the
underclass.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush senior squashed Michael Dukakis by accusing him of
caring more about criminals and freeloaders than about hard-working
families. But Bill Clinton's decision to embrace mass incarceration
and welfare reform means that the only idle freeloaders that matter
in this election are retired chief executives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason why Gore's campaign has caught fire, however,
is that he has succeeded in articulating the fury that almost all
Americans, gold-collar as well as blue, feel about their treatment
at the hands of big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't hate America's HMOs, for example? Dealing with Aetna
U.S. Healthcare is like dealing with a particularly incompetent
branch of the old Soviet bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   If you move from one sort of coverage to another within the
company, you are brutally told that your coverage has been
terminated; and if you try to rectify the situation, you are
confronted with weeks' worth of tedious and confusing paperwork,
with bills mounting up and doctors yapping at your heels.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs are only the tip of a horrific iceberg. Cancellations
and delays are now as routine a part of air travel as overcrowding
and stale pretzels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 925) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The staff in chain stores cannot perform even the most basic
mental operations: try visiting a CVS Pharmacy in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   And telephoning an American company is a guarantee of an
automated nightmare of options, starting with the most improbable
and long-winded, and culminating in an endless wait to talk to a
human being. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,100) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Most people know in their heart of hearts that Gore cannot do
anything to solve these irritations. They know that the Democratic
Party is just as deeply in hock to special interests as the
Republican. They know that Washington cannot just mandate better
service.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gore pledges to spend every day as president working
for ordinary people against insensitive monstrosities like Aetna,
they cannot help but feel a surge of foolish enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   That surge may well be enough to carry him into the White
House. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
