<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT NOW' TIME FOR SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If last season was ``Now Time,'' according to the
Seahawks marketeers, what is this season?
</P>
<P>
   Irrefutably, it's ... not now time.
</P>
<P>
   No one around the Seahawks will agree directly with that. But
outside of the professionally trained optimism of the players, no
one is arguing much, either.
</P>
<P>
   Now time was then; this is a step back.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mike Holmgren has dropped enough chubby hints about
diminished expectations that he will be vulnerable to the claim
that he is creating early cover. Almost certainly, by the time the
2000 season is reflected upon, the Seahawks coach/GM/premier won't
be accused of overselling his product.
</P>
<P>
   Already he has said the Seahawks are going to take a big hit
against the salary cap ($10 million to players not on the roster)
this season instead of spreading the damage. He's also called it a
teaching year for the welter of young players, some of whom should
be on the second unit instead of the first, and still more who
should be on the practice squad instead of the second unit.
</P>
<P>
   But he is professionally obliged to avoid the truth. He knows
that football coaches who tell the truth this time of year
typically are soon selling life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to surprise some people who think were not going
to do so well,'' is how he put it this week. He failed to identify
who these people were, nor did he say specifically what the
accusations were. But if he can find one of them who said the
Seahawks will go 2-14, he will be on safe ground.
</P>
<P>
   That is how football coaches dodge reality. If he works at it
diligently, it can get him to the White House as occupant well
before he will return as Super Bowl-winning guest.
</P>
<P>
   Probably few if any Seahawks fans will be perturbed by the oral
soft-shoe, because they operate comfortably in an atmosphere of
diminished expectations. After all, this is a team that in its
first quarter century has won four postseason games, none since
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Even Holmgren's considerable rsum as well as the AFC West
Division championship last season cannot quickly alter the
perception that if there is an upturned iron rake somewhere in an
overgrown yard, inevitably the Seahawks will step on it.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, last year's rake was discovered Nov. 28, when
Tampa Bay, despite just 156 yards of total offense, throttled the
Seahawks 16-3 in the Kingdome. That defeat turned an 8-2 seasonal
start into a NASDAQ-style header that finished with six losses in
seven games, including a 20-17 home playoff loss to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, the season-opening opponent Sunday, proceeded to
lose their next game 62-7 to Jacksonville. That indicated either
the Seahawks had administered to Miami a horrific beating the
previous week, or the Dolphins and Seahawks might have been two of
the worst playoff teams since the installation of the face mask.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay loss was the start of something bad. The Bucs'
formidable defense created a template used by the Seahawks
remaining opponents: Stick eight defenders between the tackles and
dare quarterback Jon Kitna to win going deep.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't. Not with a sore toe, a busted-up running back and a
deep threat who couldn't get out of the way of his pouting lower
lip. Even if the three biggest parts of the Seahawks offense were
to recover, continued success was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game shook our confidence,'' Holmgren said. ``It stunned
Jon a little, like a fighter who gets hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Holmgren admitted to blunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a coaching error that game,'' he said. ``I kept trying
to play it the way I wanted to. I should have played the game to
win 9-6. Instead, I kept throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Five interceptions and a Kitna fumble later, the early season
NFL darlings were exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The off-season brought few fig leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks lost eight starters, and this week replaced the
veteran kicker and the veteran backup quarterback with rookies.
Those two departures, along with most of the others, were for
reasons of salary cap constraints, meaning their replacements are
almost exclusively young and cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The unit where help was most needed, the offensive line,
suffered a big off-season injury and a stupid rookie holdout.
Tackle Chris McIntosh demonstrated in mini-camps that he didnt know
a pass block from a block party, but instead skipped an entire
preseason of desperately needed instruction to gain virtually
nothing in his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he take himself almost out of the 2000 picture,
McIntosh figures to diminish the effectiveness of the brightest
off-season addition, rookie running back Shaun Alexander. The
eventual replacement for Ricky Watters will fend largely for
himself behind yet another patchwork line.
</P>
<P>
   At least Holmgren will be able to rely on two able coordinators
that he didnt have a year ago, Gil Haskell on offense and Steve
Sidwell on defense. That should cut down on the indecision and
tentativeness that plagued the Seahawks sideline.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing they can do can fix the travail of playing a
first-place schedule with a second-rate team. At least they can
make a little local history together _ playing the first big-time
football games in the perpetual whitecap of Seattle's
post-Thanksgiving outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   If it is to be a bad season, there is virtue in playing it on a
lake bottom.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
