<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8062 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-HILLARY-COATTAILS-ECO     09-01 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-COATTAILS-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SMOOCHER AND THE MOOCHER: WILL GORE CARRY HILLARY?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 2 trims, 225; 1,050 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 625 (100 WORDS) AND 850 (125
WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Al Gore planted that kiss full on Tipper at the
Democratic Convention, he may have given almost as much pleasure to
the current First Lady as the (maybe) next one.
</P>
<P>
   This random act of passion helped give the vice president such a
lift in the opinion polls that the George Bush campaign has
abandoned any lingering thoughts of putting up a serious fight in
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   If, as now seems likely, Gore carries the state by a mile on
Nov. 7, many supporters of Hillary Rodham Clinton believe there is
no way she can lose the Senate election on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Are they right? Certainly, things have mostly gone Mrs.
Clinton's way during recent weeks. She has maintained a frenetic
program of public appearances around the state, while her
Republican rival, Rick Lazio, has taken a more traditional relaxed
approach to campaigning during August _ or perhaps has simply
failed to get his act together.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lazio received a welcome boost when the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) decided not to proceed with
insider-trading charges, he spent much of August looking as if he
had something to hide by failing to make public his tax returns,
despite frequent requests from the Clinton campaign. (When he at
last produced them, all seemed to be in order.)
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Convention did nothing for Lazio, who put in a
brief appearance but declined an opportunity to speak _ apparently
for fear of being too closely associated with Bush, who has high
negative ratings in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mrs. Clinton, who has been struggling with New York's
crucial Jewish voters, was cheered by Gore's vice-presidential
choice of Joseph Lieberman. Her platitudinous speech to the
Democratic Convention was well received by delegates, and her
Hollywood friends donated a fortune to campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Gore's amorous performance. Bill Schneider, one of
America's leading pollsters, reckons that Gore's likely triumph in
New York will give Mrs. Clinton a decisive winning edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was 1998 or 2002, Hillary wouldn't win, because of all
her negatives. But in a presidential year, there is a higher
turnout in New York City and amongst minorities. With Gore well
ahead, that should give her victory by a couple of hundred thousand
votes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After all, in New York, registered Democrats exceed Republicans
by around 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many Americans, New Yorkers like Mrs. Clinton's husband,
and gave him his third-biggest margin of victory in the 1996
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious parallels with 1964, when Lyndon Johnson won
New York by a landslide and Bobby Kennedy, another famous
carpetbagger, was elected on his coattails.
</P>
<P>
   Other pollsters take a very different lesson from 1964. Then,
Johnson carried the state by 2.5 million votes, whereas Kennedy's
margin of victory was only 719,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks Gore will win by anything close to 2 million; more
likely 1 million at most. On the other hand, as in 1964, voters are
likely to differentiate between the president and the carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Zogby, who has regularly polled New York
voters, ``The Senate race stands on its own. It is all about
Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, Zogby's latest poll has Gore over 20 percentage
points ahead in the state, and Mrs. Clinton up by only two points _
well within margins of statistical error.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, New York simultaneously elected Clinton and sent a
Republican, Alfonse D'Amato, to the Senate; though admittedly,
unlike Lazio, he was an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Some Lazio supporters think that the Bush campaign's abandonment
of the state may even increase their man's chances. There will be
few presidential campaign ads or appearances in New York, leaving
the airwaves and journalists free for the Senate race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 625) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's negative ratings in the state would be more of a handicap
for Lazio if Dubya were campaigning aggressively. Instead, the
Lazio team can associate their man unequivocally with John McCain,
who polls strongly with the sort of Democrat who has doubts about
Mrs. Clinton, and features in a new commercial applauding Lazio's
support for campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   With the Gore campaign no longer needing to fight hard in New
York, and winding down its activities, the Democratic turnout may
be less than it would be in a fiercer contest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   And although the selection of Lieberman will probably increase
Jewish turnout for the Democratic presidential slate, this may also
help Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews, in particular, are now more likely to vote, and
many of them loathe Mrs. Clinton, whom they suspect is pro-Arab.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns say they are focusing their efforts on the 5-10
percent of voters who are undecided. Most of those dislike Hillary,
but are looking for a more powerful reason to cast their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton hopes to score by flushing out differences in
positions on ``the issues,'' particularly during face-to-face
debate, which she has hitherto avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has so far been content to be the ``anti-Hillary''; but
senior Republicans now want him to present, aggressively, a
positive image of himself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 125 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They remember how, in 1994, George Pataki ran neck-and-neck with
Governor Mario Cuomo by simply being the unCuomo, but then plunged
in the polls during October. Only a last-minute series of
tax-cutting speeches and advertisements allowed him to rebound to a
shock victory.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they want to get the positive message out sooner.
This will include emphasizing Lazio's voting record in Congress,
which mostly shows him to be more moderate than the Democrats paint
him, particularly on education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Expect advertisements (perhaps fronted by Mrs. Lazio) stressing
that he is pro-choice and does not want Roe v Wade overturned, and
that his opposition to late-term ``partial birth'' abortion is
shared by two of New York's (Democratic) political heroes, the
outgoing Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan and a former mayor, Ed
Koch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio team currently estimate that they will lose by up to
500,000 votes in New York City, but win by over 700,000 combined in
the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Will Mrs. Clinton prove them wrong? Thanks in part to her old
friend Al, she starts as favorite. But this race is far from over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
