 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; BIG OIL MOMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Chevron have named one of their oil tankers, the Condoleezza
Rice, after George W. Bush's foreign-policy adviser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVERYBODY'S HAPPY: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a win-win outcome.'' (Al Gore replying to a
reporter who reminded him that George W. Bush once said that, if he
lost, he could be happy just going fishing. US News &AMP; World Report,
Sept. 4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHALLENGE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's raining. You want to leave, leave. It's your choice. But
I'm stayin' to talk specifics and after the speech I don't care if
the lightning is coming down, I'm going to stay and shake hands! If
you don't want to hear specifics, now is your time to leave!'' (Al
Gore in Hannibal, Mo. No one left. U.S. News &AMP; World Report, Sept.
4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALPHA MALE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Al Gore that will air on ESPN, a sports TV
channel, the electorate will be reminded that Gore was captain of
football at high school while George W. Bush was captain of
cheerleading. (U.S. News &AMP; World Report, Sept. 4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FULL DISCLOSURE (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas, a Hollywood screenwriter whose credits include
``Basic Instinct'' and ``Showgirls,'' has taken out a full-page
advertisement in the Daily Variety, a trade paper, urging the movie
industry not to contribute to the Gore-Lieberman campaign until
they explain their position on ``freedom of creative expression.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FULL DISCLOSURE (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A new camera, set up in the Gore HQ in Nashville, gives viewers
an updated picture of campaign-staff activities every ten seconds.
(Chicago Tribune, Aug. 29) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLL OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As summer ends, a poll reports that of those people likely to
vote in November, 81 percent are now paying quite a lot of
attention to the election; 9 percent are paying some. (USA
Today/CNN/Gallup Poll) &QL;
</P>
