<HEADER>
A8070 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-LIBYA-INVESTORS-ECONO     09-01 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-INVESTORS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROVELING EUROPEANS ITCHY TO DO BUSINESS WITH QADDAFI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 800-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TRIPOLI _ Securing the release of six hostages _ French, German
and South African _ from their Philippine kidnappers has won
Colonel Muammar Qaddafi more western praise than any single act in
his 31-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   At a handover ceremony in Tripoli on Tuesday, European ministers
trotted on to the podium to heap thanks on the Libyan leader and
his charitable foundation. Two of the hostages wore Qaddafi
T-shirts. Libyans, South Africans and Europeans hugged and kissed.
</P>
<P>
   Libya had come in from the cold. But the ceremony itself invites
questions about whether the Great Leader has indeed changed.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the backdrop. The ceremony was held in the
Azizia barracks, a concrete fortress in the heart of Tripoli
fortified with tanks, lookout posts and beds of nails.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the podium lay the ruined shell of Colonel Qaddafi's
military headquarters, bombed by the United States in 1986 and left
untouched except for the sculpture of a green fist crushing an
American aircraft. People were taken on guided tours to the spot
where the colonel's adopted daughter, Hana, was killed by an
American missile.
</P>
<P>
   This was hardly the theatre of reconciliation. Then there was
the treatment of the international press, invited and lodged at
state expense.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of waiting for the hostages, the handover should
have been a crowning moment. But Libya botched it. On arrival in
the barracks, the security forces herded the press pack into a
hall, locked the door, drew the curtains and posted guards with
machine guns at the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Grateful governments may prefer not to remember that the reason
for Libya's clout with the Abu Sayyaf hostage-takers is its
reputation as the bankroller of revolutionary movements worldwide.
Libyan officials did little to disguise the fact that the
Philippine rebels were trained in their country.
</P>
<P>
   Seif al Islam, Colonel Qaddafi's 26-year-old son who keeps
Bengal tigers as pets, staged a press conference in which he
reiterated Libya's support for the Muslim struggle for autonomy in
the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as president of the Qaddafi Foundation, the front for
Libya's mediation in the Philippines, he insisted that Libya itself
had not paid a ransom. All the money, he said, had come from
foreign individuals and, he paused, ``institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   It had seemed as if he might have said ``governments.'' Had his
charitable foundation served as a conduit for governments wanting
to transfer cash to rescue their nationals?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer, Europe's readiness to do business with
Colonel Qaddafi over the hostages smacks of its readiness to do
other business with him as well.
</P>
<P>
   For a ceremony billed as heralding the return of Libya, as well
as the hostages, to the fold, the affair was modest. The colonel
himself stayed away and there were more European ministers present
than Libyan.
</P>
<P>
   Some wondered whether it was Libya or Europe that was so anxious
to rehabilitate the image.
</P>
<P>
   Obstacles remain, but step by step the rehabilitation is going
ahead. The prosecution in the Lockerbie trial of two Libyans
suspected of blowing up a Pan Am airliner in 1988 would like a
speedy conclusion, and the fallout from the judgment may be
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the United Nations released the text of a letter its
secretary-general, Kofi Annan, had written to the Libyans in 1999,
giving his assurance that the trial ``would not be used to
undermine the Libyan regime.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, a court is due on Sept. 8 to examine Libyan
responsibility for a French airliner brought down by a bomb over
Chad in 1989. Diplomats expect sanctions to be lifted _ they are
currently suspended _ once the judicial process is complete.
</P>
<P>
   In North Africa's most totalitarian state, diplomats no longer
talk of human rights. They talk of contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities are vast. Libya has a ten-year backlog of
infrastructure to upgrade and annual oil revenues of $10 billion to
spend. Its telephone system is North Africa's most archaic. And
even its four-star hotels have power cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is one of the hopefuls. Although no contracts have yet
been signed, British Airways was the first airline back in Libya
after the embargo was lifted last year, and British Aerospace is
said to have begun training programs for Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Qaddafi is even awaiting an invitation to the
Euro-Mediterranean summit in Marseilles in November. Some say that
only the seating arrangements remain to be fixed (he doesn't want
to share a table with Israel).
</P>
<P>
   And, lest Libya run out of hostages to trade for political
leverage, the Abu Sayyaf group has helpfully abducted an American,
Jeffrey Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Libya's foreign ministry has already said it would be prepared
to negotiate his release, if asked. Now Libya is waiting for the
White House to call. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
