<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WIZARD-HEALTHCARE-ECO     09-01 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIZARD-HEALTHCARE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDTRONIC BOSS NOW WANTS TO REVOLUTIONIZE HEALTH-CARE SYSTEM  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minneapolis)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 925-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Hearts that beat out of time usually need a shock to
get them into a better rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   One of Medtronic's niftiest new products is an implantable
cardiac defibrillator that is not only forceful enough to jolt the
organ into productive beating but, thanks to its powerful computer
chip, smart enough to tell how the heart has gone wrong, and to
deliver the right signal to alter its course.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same could be said of Medtronic's boss, Bill George.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the Minneapolis-based firm in 1989, it was a $1
billion company with most of its sales in pacemakers. Today it is
worth $63 billion, and its $5 billion in sales worldwide come from
a variety of cardiovascular devices, neurological stimulators,
drug-delivery systems and spinal implants.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic is widely seen as the most innovative and market-savvy
firm in the $160 billion-a-year medical-device industry, and George
as one of the best strategists in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Although George talks with impressive ease about
``supraventricular tachycardia,'' he did not train as a doctor, but
as an engineer and manager. He joined Medtronic as chief operating
officer after stints at Litton Industries and at Honeywell, where
he was head of research and development for solid-state
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   With George in charge, Medtronic came in for reconstructive
surgery. Lead times for devices were reduced from four years to 18
months. George's policy is that 70 percent of revenue should come
from products launched in the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   The devices are getting smaller and more sophisticated. But in
order to make the grade they have to cost less to manufacture than
their predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   George reckons that his background in other technologies has
stood him in good stead at Medtronic; in many ways, the device
industry is ``more like Silicon Valley than New Jersey.'' where
America's pharmaceutical giants are clustered.
</P>
<P>
   Developing even the most complex device needs only a third of
the money and half the time required by a fancy new drug. Unlike
most drugs, whose formulation remains virtually unchanged in their
long years of patent protection, Medtronic's devices go through a
quick succession of incremental improvements, much like the various
incarnations of Microsoft Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Key to Medtronic's technical success, says George, is iterative
innovation, where the company's engineers sit down time and again
with doctors to see how a device can be improved. Indeed, it is
doctors who usually come up with the ideas in the first place,
helping Medtronic spot potentially lucrative unmet medical needs.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of pressures, long faced by medical-device
companies, are now also confronted by firms in industries such as
pharmaceuticals and biotechnology. How to stay creative while your
firm is ballooning through consolidation is a pressing issue for
pharmaceutical executives.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic, which has spent $9 billion acquiring companies with
top-flight research and strong sales in the past two years, tries
to keep its research and development units small in order to avoid
swamping their bright sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic has long had to wrangle with Medicare, America's
government-sponsored health insurance, to get it to cover the use
of new devices, and to persuade short-term-oriented managed-care
companies that expensive devices can yield long-term savings.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, drug firms are struggling to come to grips with cost
containment and demanding purchasers. But Medtronic's success shows
that it is possible to sustain a profitable business in the face of
such obstacles, so long as you have a good eye for new
applications, good research and forceful marketing.
</P>
<P>
   George now has his eye on higher hurdles. Perhaps the biggest
challenge facing health care is to cope with a rise in chronic
disease in ways that satisfy increasingly demanding patients
without bankrupting national health care systems.
</P>
<P>
   Making devices for such chronic conditions as heart failure and
Parkinson's disease, Medtronic has an obvious interest in finding
better ways of managing long-term disease, and making money in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Key to success, in George's view, is enabling patients to take
more control of their own health. To do so, they need better
information and here, George has turned to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Medtronic signed a $100 million deal with
Healtheon/Web MD to provide material about chronic disease and the
firm's technologies to those who visit the Web site. This alliance
allows Medtronic to reach out beyond doctors to patients, just as
drug firms have succeeded with direct-to-consumer advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But George has even grander plans than this. Some of the firm's
newest devices are essentially ``black boxes'' for the body, which
continuously monitor functions such as the heart's electrical
activity, and record this information on a chip that can then be
read by special equipment at a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Medtronic is now developing technologies that could send such
data, via radio signals and the Internet, to doctors, allowing
monitoring from afar and even the reprogramming of the device
without having to reopen the patient.
</P>
<P>
   George would like to see all this in place before 2010. He will
be long gone by then: he plans to step down next year, having
completed what he believes to be the optimal life cycle of a chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Faulkner, a medical-devices analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q, an
investment bank, wonders how Medtronic will do without George,
since he casts a long shadow for even the most able successor.
</P>
<P>
   But no doubt he will be monitoring Medtronic from afar, if not
delivering a few more shocks to its system. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 0251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
