<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-GAS-SAVING-SUVS-ECONO     09-01 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-SAVING-SUVS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL-EFFICIENT VEHICLES: KEEP ON TRUCKING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 975-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Is bigger really better? That it is has been a
seemingly immutable truth for American motorists since the finned
dinosaurs of the 1950s roamed the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a period after the oil shocks of the 1970s when small
briefly did look beautiful, the spirit of the 1959 Cadillac
Eldorado convertible has been reincarnated in the massive (and
massively gas-guzzling) Cadillac Escalade and similar so-called
sport-utility vehicles (SUVs).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many analysts believe the success of SUVs has been a
populist reaction against America's restrictive fuel-economy laws,
which force manufacturers to sell small, efficient passenger cars,
but permit them to get away with ever larger light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   At present, an American vehicle-maker's range of passenger cars
must deliver, on average, 27.5 miles per American gallon (8.6
litres/100km), while SUVs, pick-ups and other trucks squeak by at a
mere 20.7 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least, the political will has not been there to make
these rules fairer. But this year's unexpectedly steep rise in
American gas prices has created a new mood of conservation _ and
this time consumers, rather than legislators, are taking the lead.
</P>
<P>
   In response Ford, for one, has announced plans to boost the
fuel-economy of its SUVs by 25 percent between now and 2005. On
average, that would save 1,700 gallons of fuel over the life of a
vehicle, and even in America, where gas remains reasonably cheap,
that adds up to a saving of several thousand dollars. But achieving
this goal will not be easy for Ford or, indeed, for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   There are several obvious ways to improve fuel-efficiency, but
improved aerodynamics is probably the easiest and most
cost-effective. Reduce wind resistance and you can reduce fuel
consumption by several percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   With SUVs, that may mean reducing ``ride height'' (the distance
between the underside of the vehicle and the road). The challenge
is to do this without limiting a vehicle's ``off-roadability.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen's new Audi All-Road SUV offers an innovative
solution: a system that brings the vehicle nearly 5cm nearer to the
ground at highway speeds by lowering the suspension pneumatically
as the vehicle travels faster.
</P>
<P>
   Better engines are another route to fuel-efficiency. General
Motors's ``displacement-on-demand'' system is one approach. It
works by shutting one or more cylinders off when their power is not
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Saab, a Swedish firm, has a different idea. Its Variable
Compression Engine can alter its compression ratio (the volume in a
cylinder when the piston is up compared with the volume when it is
down) from 14-1 to 8-1, depending on the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   This allows the vehicle to run at maximum torque all the time,
and could thus reduce fuel consumption by up to 30 percent,
according to Peter Augustsson, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the engine is optimized, however, the gearbox can still
be a source of inefficiency. The automatic gearboxes so popular in
America are an important source of energy losses. They rely on a
fluid, rather than a mechanical clutch, to transmit the engine's
torque to the wheels, and this is inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   However, new six-speed gearboxes should help, by matching the
engine's speed more closely to the vehicle's road speed. And
automatically shifted ``manual'' transmissions, in which the
process of de-clutching and changing gear is done
electromechanically, will eliminate the inefficiencies of current
automatic gearboxes without the tedium of using a gear stick.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to reduce fuel consumption is to reduce weight.
According to a series of studies by AutoPacific, a market-research
firm, American motorists are reluctant to trade size and
performance for the better fuel-economy they seem to desire.
</P>
<P>
   But while size matters, mass, apparently, does not. And trimming
excess weight can have a dramatic effect: every 100lb (about 45kg)
removed from a Ford Focus, for example, improves its fuel-economy
by a full mile a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that lightweight materials will be used much more
in the light trucks and passenger cars of the not-very-distant
future than they are in those of today.
</P>
<P>
   Plastics and composites are already the materials of choice for
interior panels. Magnesium cross-members and steering-wheel columns
are increasingly common, as are aluminium engines and suspension
components.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen has already put two aluminium-intensive vehicles
(admittedly not SUVs) into production: the luxury Audi A8, and the
mass market Audi A2.
</P>
<P>
   And Honda's new Insight sedan car is made largely of aluminium
and composites. The Insight also uses another weapon in the
fuel-efficiency armory. It is a hybrid, powered by both a small
internal combustion engine and a battery-driven electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   During acceleration, the electric motor acts as an ``electric
supercharger,'' providing extra power to supplement that generated
by the gas engine. During braking, it becomes a generator,
recapturing energy normally lost as frictional heat.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not yet clear that hybrids make economic sense.
Although they use less fuel than conventional vehicles, they cost
more to manufacture; Toyota, which currently makes a hybrid sedan
car called the Prius, is estimated to lose $20,000 on every one it
sells.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ford intends to introduce a hybrid version of its
new Escape SUV in 2003. Whereas the basic, four-cylinder version of
the SUV gets 23 mpg, the Escape HEV (hybrid-electric vehicle)
should average 40.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, meanwhile, intends to release hybrid-electric
versions of its Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra by 2003. Its
engineers forecast at least a 15 percent increase in mileage.
</P>
<P>
   And DaimlerChrysler's American Dodge division has an HEV version
of its Durango SUV in development, although it says that it will
not launch it unless the American Congress enacts a proposed tax
credit for fuel-efficient vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But if the whole SUV-phenomenon really is caused by an anomaly
in the law, perhaps it is that which needs correcting in the first
place. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
