<P>
   &UR; FIRESTONE, FORD, MITSUBISHI: CORPORATE CRIME AND PUNISHMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CORPORATE-CRIMINALS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a company's products turn out to have hurt people, or
worse, that slavering sound you hear is of a thousand lawyers
licking their lips. Shareholders, meanwhile, hold their breath. So
it was in the past two weeks with Ford's and
Bridgestone/Firestone's recall of 6.5 million tires, and with
Mitsubishi's separate recall in Japan of 620,000 cars. Punishment
of some sort will presumably be meted out. The question is whether
it will be meted out to the right people. Given how the system
currently works, that looks unlikely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
