   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRESTONE, FORD, MITSUBISHI: CORPORATE CRIME AND PUNISHMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CORPORATE-CRIMINALS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a company's products turn out to have hurt people, or
worse, that slavering sound you hear is of a thousand lawyers
licking their lips. Shareholders, meanwhile, hold their breath. So
it was in the past two weeks with Ford's and
Bridgestone/Firestone's recall of 6.5 million tires, and with
Mitsubishi's separate recall in Japan of 620,000 cars. Punishment
of some sort will presumably be meted out. The question is whether
it will be meted out to the right people. Given how the system
currently works, that looks unlikely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HIGH PRICE OF PAYING RANSOMS: MORE HOSTAGES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T-PAY-RANSOMS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These are cracking good times in the hostage business. In 1999,
according to an insurance company that tries to keep count, the
numbers taken captive increased by 6 percent over 1998, and it has
been like that for several years: kidnappings for ransom are up by
70 percent over eight years. The kidnappers, evidentally, have
learned two lessons: holding a few hostages keeps the army away;
grabbing more keeps the money rolling in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA'S SHIFTING BALANCE PROMISES TRICKY TIMES AHEAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA-OFF-BALANCE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new threat looms over Asia: the threat of diplomatic
chin-wagging. In a region with an already awkward balance between
America, China, Japan and Russia, the thaw between the Koreas has
set everyone scrambling. In theory, an easing of tensions along
East Asia's last Cold-War frontier ought to benefit all. In
reality, bad habits and new forces at work on old rivalries mean
tricky times ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AL GORE, THE PEOPLE'S PRINCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE-THE-POPULIST-ECONOMIST-LEX-700&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Who could have guessed it? America is into the tenth
year of the longest economic boom in its history. The country is
minting millionaires so fast that psychologists have discovered a
whole new mental disorder _ ``affluenza'' _ that results from
having huge piles of cash dumped on your head. And yet Al Gore,
Tennessee princeling and ultimate Washington insider, has revived
his fortunes not just with a kiss, but by dint of one of the most
antiquated ideas in the political lexicon: the class struggle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 optional trims, totaling 125; 1,100 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SMOOCHER AND THE MOOCHER: WILL GORE CARRY HILLARY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HILLARY-COATTAILS-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Al Gore planted that kiss full on Tipper at the
Democratic Convention, he may have given almost as much pleasure to
the current first lady as the (maybe) next one. This random act of
passion helped give the vice president such a lift in the opinion
polls that the George Bush campaign has abandoned any lingering
thoughts of putting up a serious fight in New York state. If, as
now seems likely, Gore carries the state by a mile on Nov. 7, many
supporters of Hillary Rodham Clinton believe there is no way she
can lose the Senate election on the same day. Are they right? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 optional trims, totaling 225; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLD MUGABE HAD A FARM _ EE-EYE, EE-OH NO! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUGABE-FARM-FIASCO-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAKEFIELD FARM, ZIMBABWE _ It was a rollicking party. Robert
Mugabe, Zimbabwe's president, arrived in one of his helicopters.
Cows were slaughtered, beer gushed, crowds danced, and TV cameras
recorded the joyful event for posterity. The occasion was the
resettlement of 51 black families on Wakefield ``A,'' a large
commercial farm, bought by the government from willing sellers two
years ago. The aim was to build a class of successful, independent
black farmers in Zimbabwe. The government promised the new
smallholders seeds, fertilizer, and all the help necessary to get
them started. It then forgot about them. Wild grasses have since
reclaimed what were once prime tobacco fields. This is the
land-reform program that Mugabe is now seeking to accelerate _
despite its disastrous toll on the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 175-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OMAN'S SULTAN QABOOS: NOT JUST ANOTHER DESERT DESPOT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAVVY-SULTAN-OMAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSCAT _ Not so very long ago, Oman's borders were sealed to the
outside world and Muscat's gates clanged shut at sunset. Everything
began to change in 1970, when Sultan Qaboos, then aged 30,
overthrew his medieval-minded father, unlocked the gates, and
ushered in a brave new world. The sultan has even moved his
country, very gradually, towards a slightly more democratic system.
Women can both vote and stand for election. It would be foolish,
says the sultan, to waste half the country's talents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sept. 14 election _ 4th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
