<SLUG> BC-ONE-OF-A-KIND-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-OF-A-KIND PRODUCTS STAND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Illustrations showing the Parabounce balloon, the Solo
watercraft, the Pow-R-Tube, the Breathing Observation Bubble,
Motosk8s, the trike built for seven, and the catbox are available
on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By CLIFF GROMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rise above the crowd or sink beneath it. Leave other skaters
breathing your dust and out-slalom skiers. Get the upper hand on
your cat's litter box. Stand out, be different. The gear and
gadgets you see here are one of a kind, and your ticket to
coolness. Each item will add a dimension to your world that you can
get nowhere else, and chances are you'll be the only one on your
block who has one. And believe us, that counts for something.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHEADED
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, you've conquered your fear of heights and
you're ready to celebrate. You're not ready for skydiving and hang
gliding's just not your thing. Airplanes are, well, boring and with
those big balloons, who knows where you'll end up? Climbing a tall
ladder's no fun, so what's left? Why, your own personal, one-man
Parabounce balloon, of course. Tethered to the ground, over water
or even indoors, this 22-foot-diameter, polyurethane-coated nylon
sky chair inflates with helium in about 45 minutes and deflates in
15 minutes. It packs down small enough to fit inside your car
trunk, so you can carry it wherever you want. Parabounce will lift
you up to 100 feet so you can float quietly or, when that gets old,
try the flip chair for 360 degree somersaults. Or just wave to the
neighbors as they sulk with envy. Parabounce comes in yellow for
$20,000 from Hammacher Schlemmer.
</P>
<P>
   TOW 'N' GO
</P>
<P>
   Get me down, you say. You're a water person. No problem. We've
got the gear to give you a one-of-a-kind thrill over, on, or under
aqua pura. Waterskiing is a blast except when your towboat pilot
doesn't show because he's recovering from last night's party.
That's where Solo comes in _ a three-cylinder, 70-hp jet personal
water craft that offers self-service waterskiing and wakeboarding.
All controls, including turning, accelerating, stopping and horn,
are in the tow handle. Solo pulls you at a price tag of $6995.
</P>
<P>
   FLOATING ON AIR
</P>
<P>
   No thirst for that type of adrenaline rush? Maybe you like your
water sports on the mellow side, say, tubing down a quiet river,
fishing or just sightseeing on a calm lake or stream. Pow-R-Tube
with Pow-R-Pack, a motorized inner tube, is just the ticket.
Imagine the looks on downstream tubers' faces as you wave to them
tubing upstream. The system uses a 30-pound thrust Minn Kota
electric motor with five forward and three reverse speeds. You
steer with your feet. Deflated, the unit takes up less space than a
set of golf clubs. The tube will float $580 out of your checkbook,
with the Pow-R-Pack costing an additional $339.
</P>
<P>
   BUBBLE MACHINE
</P>
<P>
   Now that you've seen what's on the water, check out what's under
it with BOB (Breathing Observation Bubble). This underwater scooter
dispenses with conventional scuba gear. Sit comfortably, breathe
normally and smile at the fishes from inside your air-filled, clear
acrylic dome. BOB uses a ballast weight, an air tank and a
battery-powered 40-pound thrust electric motor for cruising at
speeds up to 2.5 knots. A steering wheel and instrument console
complete the $12,000 package. The scooter will dive to 40 feet and
allow you to be submerged for about 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   FOR GOODNESS' SKATES
</P>
<P>
   Inline skating may be all the rage, but Motosk8s will have every
other skater eating your dust as you smoke by 'em at an effortless
25 mph. The secret is a 22.5cc 1.5-horsepower 8-pound two-stroke
engine that's built right into one skate. The 15-ounce fuel tank
will keep you going for over an hour, and if you run out of gas,
you can skate conventionally to the nearest full-service filling
station and have the gas jockey fill you up. Don't forget to tell
him to wipe the windshield and check your air. If gas prices go any
higher you may find yourself surrounded by econo-minded
Motosk8ters, in which case consider springing for the hop-up kit
(bigger carburator, exhaust and more) to maintain your advantage
with a 35-mph top end. Motosk8s cost $549.
</P>
<P>
   MAGNIFICENT SEVEN
</P>
<P>
   What could be more cozy than a bicycle built for two? How about
a tricycle built for seven? Here's the perfect exercise machine for
large families, Sierra Club corporate board meetings or for taking
the whole neighborhood for a ride. Hand-built in the Netherlands,
this trike uses a heptagon-shaped base so that all riders face each
other. The frame mounts three motorcycle wheels set up like a
tricycle. Everybody grabs onto the circular handlebar. Seven sets
of pedals connect to the chain-drive system. The captain sits at
the rear, looks out for traffic and controls the steering and disc
brake while yelling at the galley slaves to pedal harder. An
exclusive Hammacher Schlemmer offering, the steel tube-constructed
trike sports an automotive paint finish and sells for 16 grand.
Shipping is $200 extra unless, of course, you ride it home. This is
one machine guaranteed to stop for any hitchhiker.
</P>
<P>
   CAT'S MEOW
</P>
<P>
   This automatic self-cleaning litter box is the next best thing
to your cat learning to flush the toilet. When your cat exits the
box, an electric eye signals the sifting comb, which sifts the
length of the box, harvests the ``crop'' and deposits it into an
airtight holding cartridge. The Littermaid cat box is available for
about $200 at all major pet stores and mass retailers.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
