<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     09-01 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ''separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of man using seatbelt, a photo of factory worker
using spy technology, an illustration of a recording head, a photo
of the T-6A military plane, a photo of soldiers with guns, and a
photo of a warship are available on Newscom or by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOE PREDICTS A DARK FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy (DOE) says the way electric utilities
currently generate and distribute power could lead to massive
blackouts. A report by scientists at its Sandia National
Laboratories in Albuquerque, N.M., urges utilities to investigate
using a ''distributed power grid.'' The idea is to add hundreds of
traditional and nontraditional generation and storage devices _
including wind turbines, solar collectors and other generators _ to
the national electric power distribution network. ''Less reliance
on large-scale power plants would give the grid a more stable
foundation,'' says a lab spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   VALUE OF DNA MAP IN DOUBT
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from several research centers say the much heralded
''working draft'' of the human genome has limited value.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled in June as a description of the biochemical code for
humans, it is acknowledged to have errors. More significant, only
85 percent of the DNA code has been assembled in the correct order.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing the job will take about two years. Locating all the
genes and describing their functions could take two decades.
</P>
<P>
   SEATBELTS INFLATE IN CRASHES
</P>
<P>
   Airbags work best when you sit crash-dummy straight. Trouble is,
people slouch. Behold the BF Goodrich inflatable seatbelt.
</P>
<P>
   ''During a significant crash, the system rapidly inflates a
bladder that runs the length of the belt,'' says a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Working with the existing airbag system, the belt inflates in
the first 10 milliseconds of a crash. Airbags deploy after 25 to 30
milliseconds. In the fraction of a second before airbag deployment,
the belt pushes the occupant into the proper seating position.
Thus, the force of the airbag is better tolerated and the bag
itself offers more protection, especially for kids. The belt's
cushioning also distributes the force of restraint across the body.
</P>
<P>
   SmartBelts will be available in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   SPY GEAR IN THE FACTORY
</P>
<P>
   Technology that was first developed for American spies will help
Ford Motor Co. track inventory and race parts to the right spot on
the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   California-based WhereNet Corp.'s stamp-size devices transmit
ultralow power signals that are so weak they normally disappear in
ambient electromagnetic noise. It's a clever way for one spy to
discreetly find another spy.
</P>
<P>
   In Ford plants, the WhereNet Material Call System receiver grid
listens for signals that let the person searching for parts know
when they are within 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   WhereNet devices may soon appear outside the workplace. The
company says an amusement park may loan parents devices that will
help them track wayward kids.
</P>
<P>
   NARROW TRACKS CUT DATA COSTS
</P>
<P>
   An improved production process makes it possible to construct
silicon recording heads that lay down three times as much data on
magnetic media.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of machining heads, Alditech processes batches of heads
on a single silicon wafer, using a method similar to making
integrated circuits.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a head that can read and write on narrower tracks.
A digital cassette that holds 30 GB of data can now store 100 GB,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Alditech (www.alditech. com) estimates media storage costs will
fall from dollars to pennies.
</P>
<P>
   TRAINING WINGS TAKE OFF
</P>
<P>
   Future Air Force and Navy pilots are getting new training wings.
The T-6A, a military version of Raytheon's Beech/Pilatus PC-9 Mk
II, will replace the aging fleets of Air Force T-37s and Navy
T-34s. The first fully aerobatic aircraft was accepted during a
ceremony at Randolph Air Force Base in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Built on an all-aluminum frame, the T-6A has a maximum takeoff
weight of 6,500 pounds. The high thrust-to-weight ratio makes for
fast climbs. It can reach 18,000 feet in less than 6 minutes. It
has a 31,000-foot ceiling and true airspeed in excess of 270 mph.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER NIGHT VISION
</P>
<P>
   The elite 75th Ranger Regiment has completed field testing the
next generation of night sights to be used on Army and Marine Corps
M-16s.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing less than 3 pounds, the rugged thermal targeting sights
will also be able to identify targets in bad daylight weather.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, the developer of the sights, says the same technology
can be incorporated into night vision aids for drivers and,
someday, helmet sights.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Ranger's stamp of approval, Sanders hopes to begin
production in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   THREE HULLS ARE BETTER THAN ONE
</P>
<P>
   The first of what may become a new class of fighting ships, the
trimaran warship, has been launched at Vosper Thornycroft's
Southampton, England, shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the length of a football field, the research vessel
Triton is the world's biggest seagoing trimaran.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hull design _ a thin center hull and two outriggers _
was inspired by ocean racing yachts. It allows more open deck space
and is inherently faster and more stable than monohull designs.
</P>
<P>
   The British Defense Evaluation and Research Agency says it will
evaluate the design for its future surface combatant, a ship
intended to replace Type 22 and Type 23 frigates.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
