<SLUG> BC-MANAGING-KNOWLEDGE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING KNOWLEDGE: HOW TO MAKE MONEY WITH WHAT YOU KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Sept. 5, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day, knowledge that is essential to a business walks out
the door. Employees leave, customers come and go _ and valuable
information leaves with them. This drain costs a company time,
money and market share.
</P>
<P>
   The best way for a company to prevent this loss is to develop a
knowledge management (KM) program. When done right, it can help a
business understand its customers better, bring products to market
faster and run its operations more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a successful KM program? Here are tips from
leading-edge companies.
</P>
<P>
   DEFINE THE PROGRAM'S VALUE PROPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   A company must be explicit about what it wants to achieve as a
result of its KM program. Most KM efforts are driven by one of
three objectives: increased customer intimacy, faster time to
market or operational excellence.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-tech industry, for example, time to market is often
the main focus of a KM program. However, a company that doesn't
launch many new products _ like Chevron _ will focus its KM efforts
on operational excellence.
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSE A PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   Most KM efforts fall into one of three categories:
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-directed. The company provides the database technology,
and employees use it to find the information they need. These
databases depend on user initiative. They are a good, low-cost
system for capturing the explicit knowledge of the organization,
but they can't capture the tacit knowledge in employees' heads.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knowledge networks. Consulting companies have experimented
widely with knowledge networks. Index Consulting, for example, the
firm that championed re-engineering, tried to capture the knowledge
learned on various re-engineering projects to make it easier to
tackle the next project that came along. Typically, employees are
happy to use the networks for information, but less excited about
putting in the time required to keep them updated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Facilitated transfer. In addition to the previous components,
this approach designates specific individuals who integrate best
practices or encourage knowledge transfer throughout the
organization. Facilitators assist with implementation by linking
best practices to business problems. They also show others how to
participate in knowledge sharing and transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ENLIST THE RIGHT PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Facilitators usually come from inside the organization: They may
be internal consultants, change agents, team leaders or
benchmarking coordinators. One suggestion: To keep balance in the
recruiting process, recruit individuals from every discipline and
geographical location.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE SURE THE TECHNOLOGY SUPPORTS THE DATA
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of software programs to facilitate the IT part
of the knowledge management equation. Raytheon wanted a program
that would be useful to a broad cross section of people, says Bill
Baker, Raytheon's ``benchmarking/knowledge transfer champion,'' so
it decided on a Lotus Notes application.
</P>
<P>
   Team members from all over the company act as knowledge editors
in the system, adding key words and reworking the material to make
it more searchable.
</P>
<P>
   The Lotus Notes Knowledgebase is accessible through Raytheon's
intranet. Employees can search through a benchmarking library and
the best practice Knowledgebase as well as submit best practices.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST IN TRAINING KNOWLEDGE WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Employees need a system for getting information to flow. For
instance, newspapers provide information management skills to
reporters so they're not constantly reinventing the wheel with
every story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspeople traffic in information every day, producing
knowledge products on time, on deadline and without missing a beat.
It's a team effort,'' says Amy Zuckerman, a consultant and author.
Employees need to be trained to practice KM in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   In the corporate world, according to Zuckerman, ``the investment
in technology is there, but often the people skills are
shortchanged, because management thinks that knowledge management
is all about the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS ON STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   At Chevron, the central theme of the corporate KM strategy is
``connections.'' Jeff Stemke, an internal consultant, refers to
himself as ``an evangelist for KM.'' The practice focuses on four
variations on the connections theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We connect people to the explicit knowledge we have _ for
example, on the intranet,'' he says. ``We connect people to others
who can solve problems with a yellow pages/expertise locator. We
connect people to communities of practice to share what they know,
to learn from each other and to develop new knowledge. Finally, we
look for ways to connect our knowledge and people into our
processes, products and services.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
