<P>
   SURVEYING CUSTOMERS ... ELECTRONICALLY
</P>
<P>
   SURVEYING-CUSTOMERS-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ In the digitized
future, every company may utilize some form of customer-management
software, which collects and analyzes large amounts of data about
and from customers. Meanwhile plenty of marketers have a more
modest ambition: using the Web to measure customer satisfaction and
gather customer feedback. Can it be done? Yes. Here's how. By the
editorial staff of the Harvard Management Update newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGING KNOWLEDGE: HOW TO MAKE MONEY WITH WHAT YOU KNOW
</P>
<P>
   MANAGING-KNOWLEDGE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ Every day, knowledge
that is essential to a business walks out the door. Employees
leave, customers come and go _ and valuable information leaves with
them. The best way for a company to prevent this loss is to develop
a knowledge management (KM) program. When done right, it can help a
business understand its customers better, bring products to market
faster and run its operations more smoothly. By the editorial staff
of the Harvard Management Communication Letter.
</P>
