<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: RESENDING TO CORRECT BYLINE
 &HT;    Electricity brought life to the great Northwest
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONNEVILLE DAM, Ore. _ After 10 days on the road with the North
Fayetteville Moyes in their new land yacht, we are appoaching
Portland and Delta back to Atlanta. I'm still waiting on Alex to
cook his specialty lamb chops, the main reason I agreed to this
adventure in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Unless I dozed through the film and got my facts mixed up,
Bonneville is the first super-dam Franklin Roosevelt decided to
build when he moved into the White House. The Columbia River,
bigger than the Savannah, the Chattahoochee and the Altamaha rolled
into one, has been spinning Bonneville's turbines since the middle
1930s. It generates enough electricity to run a half-million homes.
</P>
<P>
   When rural electrification came to the rural Georgia of my
youth, our way of life was forever changed _ for the better. REA
ended the era of kerosene lamps and outdoor toilets. Washers and
dryers in the house eventually replaced backyard washpots and
clotheslines. Butter and milk could be kept fresh in a Frigidaire
rather than lowered into a water well. After REA, you could go to
Edward Travis' hardware store in Fayetteville, and for a few
dollars buy an electric fan to cool hot nights.
</P>
<P>
   Rural electrification began to tie the nation together as it
never had been before. Radios were no longer dependent on expensive
batteries prone to go dead. The most isolated dirt-road, back-swamp
family, with a little imagination, got news and entertainment just
like folks in New York and Chicago, or London. REA made such an
impact on the rural South that Terry Kay wrote a book about it:
``The Year the Lights Came On.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the HMS Moye followed the Lewis and Clark Trail into the
deserts and mountains of the American Northwest, I thought the
South had been the leading beneficiary of rural electrification. I
was wrong. Out there, electricity isn't a luxury. It's life.
</P>
<P>
   In a dry summer like this one I'm satisfied to sprinkle the lawn
and keep the garden reasonably moist. In the states we visited _
Colorado, Wyoming, Utah, Idaho, Washington, Oregon _ a hunk of the
earth bigger than Europe _ they have to irrigate everything that
grows. Without Roosevelt's dams, Lewis and Clark might as well have
stayed home. Except for scenery, much of the Western United States
would be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Moye says he bought a motor home so he could have a
ground's-eye view of the America he spent all those years flying
over when he was piloting for Eastern Air Lines. There's a lot you
can see but much you can't grasp at 20,000 or 30,000 feet. What
struck me was the size and diversity of this country geographically
and otherwise. We're so different it's a wonder we aren't a dozen
countries rather than one nation under God.
</P>
<P>
   I was happy when most Westerners seemed to understand our
Southern drawls. I didn't try to order grits, and didn't make a
fuss when the restaurant in Washington served sliced light bread
and called it biscuits. The country ham was for sissies but the
beef jerky wasn't bad, although expensive at $5.75 for a bag the
size of a modest serving of fried pigskins.
</P>
<P>
   The closest anyone came to making mirth over our Southern way of
talking was a friendly comic in Utah. ``You folks ain't from
England, are you?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   We felt better after a tour conductor in Toppenish, Wash., who
seemed to be right well educated, ``clumb'' a hill and stepped
across a ``crick.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the old saw about New York, the American Northwest is a
great place to visit, but I wouldn't want to live there. I think it
could be a hard life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what the Democrats say, everyone in this country isn't
prosperous. In Wyoming, for example, you hardly ever see a Mercedes
or a Lexus. A lot of old Chevies and Ford pickups are on the road,
and practically no late-model SUVs, unless a tourist is at the
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho is mostly potatoes and runaway truck ramps. I don't think
I'd have the nerve to drive a tractor or a combine on those
mountaintop wheat fields in Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   The people have pride. When Toppenish industry went bust a few
years ago, the townfolk got together and created a tourist
industry. Several dozen murals on store and warehouse walls tell
the history of the town and the pioneers who settled it. Now
Toppenish is prospering.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians who mouth cliches at conventions in Philadelphia
and Los Angeles are right about one thing. America is a great
country. I have some advice for anyone hankering for Switzerland
and the Alps, Norwegian fjords, Australia's Outback or the sands of
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   There's an easier way. Just get friendly with the Moyes, or some
other well-off neighbors who can afford a Conestoga wagon with all
the comforts of home. As Chevrolet used to say, it's a great way to
see the USA. The bathroom is always handy, and you can drink the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
