<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN HAS GREAT EXPECTATIONS FOR BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a gap, you know.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston College football team was not good enough to compete
with Big East champion Virginia Tech last year in any meaningful
way, and the 62-28 score against Colorado in the Insight.com Bowl
speaks quite eloquently for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad matchup for us,'' says coach Tom O'Brien. ``We would have
had a much better chance against Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was an 8-4 year for the Eagles, and by any reasonable
measure of success for this school, at this point in time, 1999 was
a very good year. But lots of schools have a good year every now
and then. That's not enough, not in football, where the price you
pay is high in every way. If you're going to invest the huge gobs
of money and the great chunks of time, not to mention the blood and
sweat (tears optional), in this enterprise, you need more than an
occasional year on the plus side. A quality coach such as Tom
O'Brien is not hired just to make sure a team shows up every
Saturday to fulfill its scheduling obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can get to the point where we expect to win seven
or eight games a year,'' outlines O'Brien. ``Then we can have a
special year every now and then where we win the conference
championship and beat Notre Dame. If you do that, then you would
have a chance to go for everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be the kind of school, like a Florida
State, where you can expect to win nine or 10 every year. But we
can get to the point where a down year is 6-5.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Year 4 of the Tom O'Brien regime. What took place in the
wake of a pair of 4-7 seasons was uplifting but hardly definitive.
The 8-4 season and an appearance in a second-tier bowl was a step
in the right direction, nothing more. The early schedule was
cupcakey, and the team was loaded with talent and experience on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was last year. BC opens its season Saturday down in
Morgantown, W.Va., where the Mountaineers enjoy one of the great
home-field advantages in the nation. O'Brien is very wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a feel for this year's team yet,'' he says. ``I
will say I haven't seen a lot of leadership manifested. Right now
all the experience is on the offensive side of the ball. That's
good for the fans. They love 43-42. But any coach would tell you
that if he had a choice about where his experience would be, he'd
want it on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   If you care even a teeny-weeny bit about college football, then
Boston College is your local horse. For the past three decades, or
ever since Jesuit soulmate Holy Cross decided big-time football
wasn't worth the fuss, BC has carried the torch for all of New
England. The Eagles are our link with the Bowl Alliance and Lee
Corso. If it weren't for BC, the likes of Penn State, Air Force,
Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, Stanford, Clemson, North Carolina, California,
Tennessee, Southern Cal, Ohio State, Michigan, and, of course,
Notre Dame would never have come any closer to us than the
Meadowlands. And don't forget that, thanks to BC's membership in
the Big East, Miami, Syracuse, and Virginia Tech _ Michael Vick
comes to town Sept. 30 _ are visitors to the Heights every other
year.
</P>
<P>
   It's been BC or nothing for the region's college football fans,
although now Connecticut has dealt itself in. Wait till the folks
in Storrs find out just how hard football is, compared with
basketball, in which two stars and three role players get you into
the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right man to steer the ship through big-time college
football's treacherous waters is very difficult. BC is not an
obvious end-of-the-rainbow job for a properly ambitious coach.
Anyone taking the BC job is being asked to fight some quality
opponents with one hand tied at least gently behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a much larger task than I thought it was when I came
here,'' O'Brien declares. ``There were some serious problems with
the football program.''
</P>
<P>
   There still are. Start with the delicate matter of facilities
once you get past the stadium itself, which, in its renovative
state, is perfectly acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every other way, we probably have the worst facilities in
the entire Big East,'' O'Brien maintains. ``In areas such as
meeting rooms, locker rooms, strength and training area, and
practice fields, we are way behind.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a facility being discussed, but there's no need to
commission the champagne just yet. There will be many long
negotiations with the city and, yes, the neighbors, before a spade
ever meets dirt.
</P>
<P>
   He's not whining. He's just answering questions. Anyway, a good
Naval Academy grad and Marine captain does not whine. He copes.
</P>
<P>
   So who is this guy? Well, on the personality scale he's no Jack
Bicknell but he's no Tom Coughlin, either. Is it possible to be a
compassionate disciplinarian?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a disciplinarian, yes, but I'm not going to ask
the kids to shave their heads or do any ridiculous things,'' he
says. ``I believe in accountability, both on and off the field.
I've been part of some very stressful disciplinary situations in
both the Naval Academy and the Marine Corps, and some of the things
I've seen have been good and some have been bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He wonders if people understand the enormity of the task for any
coach at BC's level. ``I know we're headed in the right
direction,'' he says. ``I liked last year's freshman class, and
this one is even better. But it takes time to build. We need to get
to the point where a freshman plays because he is really, really
good, not because he is needed to fill out the two-deep. A program
needs continuity with the right staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A, according to O'Brien: Virginia Tech, last year's
national runnerup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what (coach) Frank Beamer's record was in his
first six years there?'' he says, reaching for the book. ``Are you
ready? 2-9, 3-8, 6-4-1, 6-5, 5-6, 2-8-1. He didn't really turn the
corner until his seventh year.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we get the message. Presumably, BC athletic director Gene
DeFilippo does, too.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing on Tom O'Brien's mind is the subject of rivalry.
He says BC is in desperate need of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Notre Dame,'' he says. ``BC cares deeply about Notre
Dame, but Notre Dame doesn't care about BC. Maybe they will if we
beat them a few more times, but right now their rival is USC. We
need a real end-of-the-year game with a big rival. You look at our
league and the only possibility, I guess, is Syracuse. Ohio
State-Michigan, Auburn-Alabama, Cal-Stanford, or in-state rivalries
such as Clemson-South Carolina or Virginia-Virginia Tech, those
games are huge. We don't have that, and we need it. Those games are
great for college football.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, BC had just such a game for more than five decades.
But that was when Holy Cross was in another mind-set. With all due
respect to the folks at Storrs, serious college football in New
England begins and ends where it has for the past 30 years _ in
Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
