<HEADLINE>
PRESEASON A USELESS CAKEWALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've said it before and we'll say it again. Preseason college
football games serve no purpose and help no one. As examples, we
point to the mismatches we saw last weekend with Kansas State
rolling over Iowa, USC trouncing Penn State, and Florida State
beating up BYU.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't even mention the cancellation of the Virginia
Tech-Georgia Tech game because of a lightning storm that hit the
Blacksburg, Va., area at kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable event at that game was that lightning struck
ESPN analyst Lee Corso's car in the parking lot behind the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, playing games in August _ unless it's the last day
_ is too early to start a college football season. Rarely are these
competitive because the primary team in each game is basically
given a list of opponents from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely will a coach choose a team he feels can beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, these games are being phased out in the next couple
of years. If you are going to play an extra game, play it at the
end of the season in a playoff format, rather than in August.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that one of the main reasons many
people oppose a college football playoff system is because it would
mean too many games for the student-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we see the potential for, say, a team from the SEC or Big
12 to play a preseason game, such as Kansas State did last week,
play an 11-game regular-season schedule, play in the Big 12 title
game, and play in a bowl game. That sounds like a 14-game schedule,
which would be in line with the number of games the last two teams
would have to play with a 16-team playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that Georgia Tech didn't agree to a December
makeup of its game against Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets wanted the August game as a warm-up for the
season. But a December game is a different matter and could be
costly in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, which is adjusting to life without quarterback Joe
Hamilton, could be a 6-5 team at the end of the regular season.
That would make them bowl eligible. Playing _ and losing to Va.
Tech _ would make them 6-6 and not eligible for a bowl, since NCAA
rules state a team must win six games and be above .500 to play in
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A kick in the teeth
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the difference between the elite teams and the
not-so-elite teams. Florida State opened its season with a solid
29-3 win over BYU last week and Seminole coach Bobby Bowden is
moaning over the lack of a running game (FSU rushed for a net 57
yards on 36 carries) and the lack of consistency from quarterback
Chris Weinke, who was 32 of 50 for 318 yards and two touchdowns.
``Unless we run better,'' said Bowden, ``we might not make a bowl
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Bowden should be worried about is his kicking
game. With Sebastian Janikowski gone, the Seminoles don't have a
proven kicker. Heir apparent Brent Cimorelli is on the shelf with a
pulled hamstring and walk-on Matt Munyon had a rough start with a
pair of missed field goals and a missed extra point. The lack of a
consistent kicking game could haunt the Seminoles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For love of the game
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some guys just love to play college football. Check out Nebraska
punter Dan Hadenfeldt, who was granted a sixth year of eligibility
by the NCAA. Hadenfeldt won't play Saturday against San Jose State
because he played in the Hula Bowl last season _ he assumed his
college career was done. For that sin, the NCAA said he had to sit
out one game. But since Nebraska probably won't be forced to punt
Saturday, it doesn't appear to be too stiff a penalty . . . The
Pac-10, which earned some respect with USC's rout of Penn State in
the Kickoff Classic Sunday, can get even more back if UCLA can play
a competitive game against Alabama Saturday at the Rose Bowl . . .
It will be Alabama's first appearance in the Rose Bowl in 54 years
. . . Alabama is reportedly bringing 25,000 fans to Pasadena . . .
One of the question marks at Texas was inexperience at wide
receiver. The Longhorn ranks got thinner when sophomore tight end
Bo Scaife went down for the season with a knee injury . . .
Speaking of Texas, insiders say sophomore QB Chris Simms is likely
to be the starter in next week's opener against Louisiana-Lafayette
over Major Applewhite, but that a rotation between the two is very
much in the works . . . Things don't look good at Wake Forest. The
Deacons have only five starters returning, the fewest of any
Division 1A team . . . When Virginia Tech travels to East Carolina
next week for a Thursday night game, a reunion will take place. One
of East Carolina's wide receivers is Marcellus Harris, who also
happened to be the starting QB in Hampton Roads, Va., when Michael
Vick was a freshman. Vick's high school coach Tommy Reamon knew
about Vick and went up to Harris in the middle of the season and
informed Harris he would be at wide receiver the next week. Two
weeks later, Vick to Harris combined for a couple of TD passes . .
. When BYU plays at Virginia Saturday, one thing seems certain.
Both teams will score. BYU holds the NCAA record for longest
consecutive games scoring (313), while Virginia holds the ACC
record for consecutive games scored (188) . . . Oklahoma coach
Bobby Stoops has been at Norman only for a season, but already OU
officials are trying to make sure Stoops stays around. They have
recommended to the Board of Regents that Stoops be offered a
contract extension through 2005 with a boost in play and a
million-dollar annuity . . . Here's a trivia question. Name the
college football team with the most victories in the 1990s? It's
Marshall, which piled up 114 wins and has a current winning streak
of 31 games . . . Their success is drawing students through
television. ``I saw Marshall play football on TV and it looked like
fun to be in the stands,'' said freshman Bruce Kish, who came to
Huntington, W.Va., from Carteret, N.J. ``I never knew about
Marshall until I saw them play on ESPN.'' Sounds like a nice way to
choose a college . . . With last week's loss to USC, Penn State
coach Joe Paterno still needs seven wins to surpass Alabama's Bear
Bryant as the winningest 1A coach in history. With the Lions
playing last week, this could be one of those 6-5 seasons in State
College. Let's see how the Lions do against Toledo Saturday. Toledo
could be this year's version of Marshall, a sleeper pick in the MAC
. . . The loss to USC dropped Penn State out of the polls for the
first time since 1992 . . . Look for Indiana to use talented QB
Antwaan Randle El at a variety of positions during the year as
Hoosier coach Cam Cameron looks for ways to juice up the IU offense
. . . Michigan QB Drew Henson is responding quicker to treatment
for his broken foot than expected and could be back in a couple of
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
