<HEADER>
A8278 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN0902-COX     09-01 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Live so you'll never have to see the disappointment in your
daddy's eyes
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I was born at high noon 46 years ago, back in
the days when the opening day of dove season began at high noon on
the Friday of Labor Day weekend. The day, as I understand it, my
birthday was Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So my father was pacing, pacing, pacing outside the labor room
and I'm thinking it was every bit as much because he was worried
that he was going to miss the first day of hunting as it was
worried about my delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as the story goes, shortly after my birth he began
pacing, pacing, pacing again until my mother said, ``Go on and go
hunting. You're driving me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He went.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if he got his limit but I would be surprised if he
didn't. My father was the best shot I've ever known, just like he
was the best poker player I've ever known. If you're lucky like I
was, your dad was the best at doing something that you've ever
known. This is true though there may be a million better shots and
poker players. It doesn't matter, he'll always be the best to me.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 birthdays later that my father took me on my first
dove hunt. As the only gun I'd ever shot was a .22-caliber rifle, I
was scared to death when he handed me the .410-gauge shotgun. A
.410 is the smallest shotgun I know of, but it still made a big
noise and it banged against my shoulder, unlike the rifle.
</P>
<P>
   It was a single shot that you had to break open every time you
shot it, remove the old shell and stick another one in. There was
only one chance to shoot at a fast-flying dove. If you missed you
might as well watch the beauty of the dove's flight. Trying to
reload that quickly was useless.
</P>
<P>
   I missed frequently. In fact, I missed always. I'm told doves
can fly up to 60 miles per hour and I can shoot at about half that
speed. I shot an entire box of shells and I'm not sure I even
frightened any doves.
</P>
<P>
   Before sitting me down beneath a tree in a lonely spot in the
maize field, my father had told me that I could only shoot a dove
in flight. It was bad sportsmanship and not like a man to shoot a
dove sitting on a fence or in a tree. Requiring that the birds were
flying, my father said, gave them an even chance.
</P>
<P>
   With me behind the gun, their chances were a heck of a lot
better than even. I sat shooting and missing, thinking about
everyone else coming back at the end of the day with bags full of
game, talking about wonderful shots. I would be coming back with a
bag full of spent shotgun shells.
</P>
<P>
   That's when it happened. A big, fat dove landed in the tree
right above me, sitting on a branch so close it felt as if I could
touch him. Maybe he'd been told by the other doves that this was a
safe zone.
</P>
<P>
   I squirmed and he didn't move. I moved my shotgun and he didn't
move. Then I began thinking about bagging him. I couldn't miss,
could I? And who would ever know I hadn't made the world's best
shot? That dove would taste as good as any other.
</P>
<P>
   So, against my father's explicit instructions, I lifted my gun
and shot. When the smoke cleared, I could see I had gotten my first
dove.
</P>
<P>
   Or had I? As close as I was I still had, unbelieveably, not
gotten a clean kill. Truth to tell, the bird was little more than
winged. When I tried to pick him up, he jumped like a rabbit,
scaring me half to death.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped and I jumped. We hopped all around that field until it
became clear to me I was going to have to shoot the bird again, if
nothing else to put the poor thing out of its misery.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to make sure I didn't miss, I got four or five feet
away, pulled the hammer back and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clean kill, that's for sure _ and I do mean clean.
There wasn't a trace of anything left of that bird, not bones or
feathers. It was as if I vaporized it.
</P>
<P>
   My father always had an uncanny knack of coming upon me at the
exact moment I was doing something wrong. He was standing behind me
when I shot the bird the second time and asked me what I was doing.
</P>
<P>
   I had to explain the entire event not only to him, but all the
other adults. The disappointment in his eyes felt like a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But, as fathers do, he didn't let one error in judgment keep him
from taking me along. He never lost the faith that I would do right
merely because I had once done wrong. On successive birthdays when
my father took me hunting I remembered the rules. I always was a
lousy shot, but I never took the easy way out again.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
