<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN0902-COX     09-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dwelling on the Civil War
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Fergit, Hell!''
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe it? We're in the third century since the late
unpleasantness with our northern neighbors, and ain't nobody
fergittin' nothin'. And nobody is forgiving anything.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago those bumper stickers on pickup trucks were kind
of amusing. They complemented gun racks and went well with a
package of Red Man chewing tobacco on the dash. I thought about
getting one myself, especially after Georgia football slipped from
the championship class and stickers heckling Florida Gators had to
be peeled off or covered up.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. If you are stocking up on Vienna sausages
and sardines in anticipation of a deer-hunting weekend with redneck
friends, pseudo or otherwise, check to see that your bumpers are
clean. Only things like ``I Brake for Animals'' and ``Save The
Trees'' are permissible. Despite something called the First
Amendment, the wrong kind of bumper sticker can cause a lot of
trouble. This from The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa aluminum has a plant in the small town of Badin, N.C. Like
many large companies, Alcoa is facing a discrimination lawsuit by
black employees. Until a few months ago race relations at the plant
were looking up. Although the work force is 3-to-1 majority white,
Allen Williams, who is black, was elected head of the union.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after taking office Mr. Williams took a pencil-and-paper
stroll through the plant's parking lot. He jotted down license
plate numbers of employee vehicles bearing Confederate flag
stickers. Then he cross-referenced the plates with union records,
which include tag numbers. After identifying the offenders, he sent
their names to the attorney representing black employees in the
discrimination suit.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa's management quickly banned all vehicles bearing
Confederate flag bumper or windshield stickers from the company
parking lot. Also banned were vehicles with special license plates
issued by the state to sons of Confederate veterans whose ancestors
fought on the wrong side a hundred and thirty-something years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, when Mr. Williams was elected president of the
union, racial harmony at the plant was thought to be at an all-time
high. Now it's at an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees have kept their stickers and park elsewhere.
Protesters gather every day to fly Confederate flags at the plant's
entrance. Some white union members have started a move to oust
Williams from the presidency. What they have at the plant is a
first-class mess.
</P>
<P>
   Reading between the lines, I had guessed that Gov. Roy Barnes
and other leaders, black and white, were quietly working out an
amicable solution to Georgia's flag problem. Now I'm not sure if
they'll be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Driving through rural South Georgia earlier this summer I saw
Confederate flags sprouting like crab grass after a summer rain.
They're on lawns, on trucks, on tractors, on cars, on houses, on
barns. The Stars and Bars are being flown by people who five years
ago had no idea what the state flag looked like, or even knew we
had a flag. Expect some very nervous legislators to show up in
Atlanta next January.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard it said that the flag controversy has set racial
relations back 10 years. That may be a conservative estimate. Even
people willing to change the flag ask the question: ``What's
next?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure exactly how the discussion about removing Tom
Watson's statue from the Capitol lawn got started. I don't imagine
the timing was welcomed by those hopeful of avoiding a nasty flag
fight like the one they had in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After Tom Watson, who, or what, is next? The three most famous,
or infamous, Confederates are carved into Stone Mountain: Jefferson
Davis, Robert E. Lee and Stonewall Jackson. One presided over the
Confederacy; the other two fought under the Stars and Bars. Do we
sandblast?
</P>
<P>
   With what we now know about the author of the Declaration of
Independence, should we tear down the Jefferson Memorial in
Washington? Andrew Jackson's army happily chased Seminole Indians
from their homes in Florida. His picture on the $10 bill must be
offensive to Native Americans. The newspaper you are reading has
some embarrassing racist moments in its history. Under today's
rules there's not much from the past that can't be construed to
offend somebody.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of water has gone over the proverbial dam since 1864. At
some point we have to have closure. A little forgiving is required
as well as forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Williams mucked an opportunity to cement racial harmony when
he got into tag identification of his fellow employees after they
had elected him president of their majority-white union. Alcoa's
banning employee vehicles from the company lot because of bumper
stickers was constitutionally suspect and bound to boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   The way we're going, we might as well go ahead and issue bumper
stickers to everybody. White folks can have one that says ``Fergit,
Hell.'' Black folks can have one that says ``Fergive, Hell!'' And
we can all use the same parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
