<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0902-CO     09-01 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They built it, and we came
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The final week of the Dragons regular season
found folks in a celebratory mood _ and, after a record-breaking
season, thinking about the possibilities for downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the Arcade?'' businessman Sandy Mendelson demanded
Tuesday night, working at a booth selling raffle tickets for the
Mary Beall Get Well Fund that he spearheaded. ``They need to open
it up. It would make a great little antiques mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown is alive with the scurrying of backhoes and the
pounding of metal as RiverScape and the new performing arts center
take shape. But the ballpark still seems like the cornerstone of
downtown's renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Build it and they will come,' `` said Mendelson, president
of Mendelson's Liquidation Outlet near the stadium. ``They built
this place and people came. The same thing could happen for the
Arcade.''
</P>
<P>
   Build it and they will come. Tony Capizzi only wishes it had
been that easy: The Vision. The Voices. The Ghosts. And presto
change-o! The Field of Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it happened the hard way: The Vision. The Voice _
mainly Tony's, at first, cheerleading that we could make it happen.
And the ghosts of failed downtown dreams: ``Tony, you're a crazy
dreamer. A spendthrift. A menace to our kids' playgrounds and our
neighborhood police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, thanks to Capizzi and a host of others it happened,
and now, we can't help feeling we had our own Field of Dreams this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   It was what they told us it would be, and maybe a little more.
</P>
<P>
   There's the air of relaxed happiness, of an oversized
neighborhood block party.
</P>
<P>
   There's the parking lot guy who smiles his forgiveness if you're
short a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   There's the way you can ``borrow'' empty seats without being
hunted down like the FBI's Ten Most Wanted, or ruffling any
feathers if the real owner shows up. There's the friendly,
volunteer workers who never serve you an attitude with your hot dog
and beer.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come in over budget, unlike the Bengals' new Paul
Brown stadium. The Bengals recently threw an intimate open house
for 130,000 fans that prompted one friend to quip, ``At least they
brought it in for less than the cost of the space shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not do-or-die baseball, it's entertainment in its purest
form. Where else in town can you find corporate executives,
8-year-olds, women who never watch any other sporting event (you
know who you are) and true baseball fans come together for the
sheer joy of rooting on a bunch of underpaid, unspoiled ball
players? It's easy to get lawn seats and join the blanket crowd,
it's easy to park, and, quicker than you can say ``Crazy Cam'' _ or
make a goofy face _ your kid can get his mug on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   They built it, and we came _ 574,000 of us before Thursday's
game, the final game of the regular season. The energy of the place
night in and night out quiets all those Doubting Thomases who
predicted, ``Minor league baseball will never fly downtown.'' Well,
balls fly out of that park nearly every week, much to the delight
of the knothole gang on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into Capizzi at a game the other night, wearing a Dragons
polo shirt and a grin that made him look about 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you ever get tired of coming here?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid question. Tony Capizzi never got tired of coming to the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did we, Tony. Neither did we.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
