<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX     09-01 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classroom woes call for a return to strict rules, accountability
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After two atomic bombs forced Japan to accept unconditional
surrender on Aug. 15, 1945, one of the highest priorities of
American forces was educational reforms for Japanese schools.
</P>
<P>
   American and Allied leaders knew they had to dismantle Japan's
militaristic education system. By early 1946, American educators,
in the form of the United States Education Mission to Japan,
recommended sweeping reforms that were adopted in their entirety
throughout Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms included extended compulsory attendance,
coeducation, support for teacher initiatives and local control by
elected school boards.
</P>
<P>
   Also included among the reforms were new requirements that
Japan's teachers receive their teacher education within Japan's
reorganized four-year university system. Anyone who successfully
completed professional training in a four-year university could
apply for certification as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the American educational reforms were changed
after Allied occupation forces left Japan in 1952, most of the
American-imposed reforms stayed in place and were responsible for
Japan's meteoric postwar rise to international economic power.
</P>
<P>
   Now Japanese school children routinely wipe the floor with
American school children whenever or however scholastic achievement
is compared.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, U.S. school children score near the bottom on
scholastic achievement when compared to most developed nations.
</P>
<P>
   Americans who attempt to defend the dismal academic showing of
the U.S. school system frequently say that Japan's system may
produce results for Japanese children, but it will not work for
American children.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't say is that Japan's school system is the
American school system before it got watered down and dumbed down
with a series of ``reforms'' that took discipline and respect away
from teachers and accountability away from students.
</P>
<P>
   Starting back in the 1960s when the country was split on the
Vietnam War and other issues, a line of thought emerged on college
campuses that competition was bad. It was a tactic used by
militaristic and authoritarian oppressors to humiliate the masses,
or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   This anti-establishment line held that it was important to
respect people as individuals, for who they were, not what the
establishment wanted them to attain. Besides, establishment
oppressors were employing dehumanizing standards just so they could
exploit workers for profits and power.
</P>
<P>
   This genesis of the touchy-feely movement quickly spread across
college campuses and throughout much of the nation's educational
community.
</P>
<P>
   Many college courses dropped grades altogether. Students passed
or failed based on fuzzy subjective judgments. Most students
passed. A failing grade would hurt the student's self esteem.
What's more, no one is qualified to judge another human being.
</P>
<P>
   Once the walls of academia had been breached, anti-establishment
insurgents rushed in with new math, less homework, holistic
grading, social promotions, open classes, whole language reading
instruction, less discipline, more counselors and an endless
procession of ``progressive'' reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Now the two major presidential candidates promise to reform
public education. That's good, of course, if it means increased
learning for America's school children.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising reforms are a step back in time to when
academic standards were high, measurements were precise, students
were held accountable and teachers had the respect of their
students and the community.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more than money, Internet connections and small
class sizes to reform what has been deformed for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
