<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-FILMS0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer movie slump gives way to promising fall season
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``At my signal, unleash hell.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, ``Gladiator's'' Russell Crowe launched the
2000 summer movie season.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's command proved oddly prophetic for studios and audiences
alike. After Ridley Scott's thrilling historical epic, which earned
$181 million, summer's sizzle quickly fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Summer 2000 was mediocre at best, lacking the sort of
blockbusters that draw big audiences to movie theaters, whetting
their appetites for repeat viewings and additional cinematic fare.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to compare with last year's ``Star Wars''
prequel, ``Austin Powers'' sequel and out-of-nowhere sensations
``The Blair Witch Project ``and ``The Sixth Sense.'' Nor were there
any date-night romantic comedies such as Julia Roberts'
back-to-back hits, ``Notting Hill'' and ``The Runaway Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, summer 2000 revenues will likely finish 4.6
percent, or $200 million, below last year's record $3 billion
box-office take, according to industry figures. Paul Dergarabedian,
president of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks movie attendance,
was quoted in the Los Angeles Times as saying that would be the
second best summer in terms of revenue, but higher ticket prices
mean attendance probably was off by at least 10 percent. Hollywood
makes at least 40 percent of its annual receipts between May and
August.
</P>
<P>
   September doesn't look to be a gold-medal month at the box
office. Most studios are avoiding competition with the Summer
Olympic Games in Sydney, which kick off Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Summer 2000's top movie contenders were strong out of the gate
but most tended to fade quickly. Only ``Gladiator,'' ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' and ``Hollow Man'' managed to hold on to the No. 1
spot at the box office for more than one week.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the big earners, such as ``Mission: Impossible 2'' ($212
million), ``The Perfect Storm'' ($175.6 million) and ``Dinosaur''
($133 million), met with mixed response from critics and audiences
alike. Given their budgets, hits such as ``Dinosaur,'' which is
reported to have cost around $140 million, might still be viewed as
financial failures.
</P>
<P>
   Summer was littered with critical and commercial
disappointments, from underachievers such as ``The Patriot'' ($110
million) and ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' ($87 million) to outright duds
such as ``Battlefield Earth ``($21 million) and ``Titan A.E.'' ($22
million).
</P>
<P>
   The most successful trend was comedies by black filmmakers or
featuring black stars.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy scored his biggest opening ever with ``Nutty
Professor 2: The Klumps,'' which has made $110 million to date,
prompting talk of another sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lawrence enjoyed similar success under similarly heavy
makeup with ``Big Momma's House,'' which cooked up $115 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie'' was summer's only surprise hit. The teen horror
spoof, directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans and starring his brothers
Shawn and Marlon, crept up on industry analysts to reap an
astonishing $148.5 million. A sequel begins production this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee's documentary ``The Original Kings of Comedy,''
featuring a quartet of black stand-up comics, opened with an
impressive $11 million on only 847 screens and is now up to $21.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   High-toned horror was also a hit with audiences, as evidenced by
sizable late-summer takes for ``What Lies Beneath'' ($130.9
million), ``Hollow Man'' ($66.6 million and counting) and ``The
Cell'' ($33.7 million in two weeks). But ``Bless the Child'' ($18
million) didn't fare nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Lee's documentary, these films all
received widely mixed to mostly negative reviews. Most dropped
precipitously at the box office after their opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day traditionally is one of the year's lowest
movie-attendence weekends. As such, this weekend's only wide
release is ``Highlander: Endgame'' _ the fourth and supposedly
final entry in the long-running series about immortal Scottish
warriors. The film was not pre-screened for critics, which
typically indicates that it's a bomb. On Sept. 15, the same day as
the Sydney Olympics' opening ceremony, the only wide-release
offering is ``Bait,'' an action comedy starring Jamie Foxx, who no
doubt hopes to repeat Murphy and Lawrence's success.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving Wednesday is ``Turn It Up,'' a drama about a gifted
musician struggling to escape the streets, starring hip-hop stars
Pras Michel and Ja Rule. Following next Friday are ``The Way of the
Gun,'' a bullet-riddled caper-gone-awry story starring Ryan
Phillipe and Benicio Del Toro; ``The Watcher,'' in which burned-out
FBI agent James Spader faces sadistic serial killer Keanu Reeves;
and ``Nurse Betty,'' a comic fantasy in which delusional soap opera
fan Renee Zellweger stalks heartthrob Greg Kinnear while being
pursued by bickering hit men Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four brings much in the way of buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Things pick up dramatically on Sept. 29 with the wide release of
``Jerry Maguire'' writer-director Cameron Crowe's ``Almost
Famous,'' a semi-autobiographical coming-of-age story about a
15-year-old music fan who lands an assignment from Rolling Stone
magazine to interview the up-and-coming band Stillwater. The film
is being touted as a likely Oscar contender and stars Billy Crudup,
Jason Lee, Frances McDormand and Kate Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Also opening Sept. 29 is ``Remember the Titans,'' a fact-based
sports drama set in 1971 Virginia, where high-school football
tradition is put to the test when an all-black school and an
all-white school are forced to integrate. There is talk of an
Academy Award nomination for Denzel Washington, who stars as the
determined head coach.
</P>
<P>
   October looks to be a mixed bag of tricks and treats, with a
seasonal emphasis on supernatural themes. Among the timely
offerings are ``Lost Souls ``(Oct. 13), ``Bedazzled ``(Oct. 20),
``Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2 ``(Oct. 27) and ``The Little
Vampire'' (Oct. 27).
</P>
<P>
   But beware _ ``Lost Souls,'' an occult thriller starring Winona
Ryder and Ben Chaplin, has been shelved for more than a year.
``Bedazzled,'' a remake of the 1967 British comedy with Brendan
Fraser as a poor sap who sells his soul to shapely devil Elizabeth
Hurley, was pushed back from summer. So, too, was Nora Ephron's
``Lucky Numbers'' (Oct. 27), a bad-buzz magnet in which John
Travolta and Lisa Kudrow attempt to rig the state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   October's more promising releases include ``Dr. T &AMP; the Women''
(Oct. 6), ``Meet the Parents ``(Oct. 6), ``The Contender'' (Oct.
13) and ``Pay It Forward'' (Oct. 20).
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. T &AMP; the Women'' is an ensemble comedy from Robert Altman
starring Richard Gere as a frantically overworked gynecologist,
with Helen Hunt, Farrah Fawcett, Laura Dern, Liv Tyler, Tara Reid,
Kate Hudson and Shelley Long as the women in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet the Parents'' is a comedy from ``Austin Powers'' director
Jay Roach starring Ben Stiller as a groom-to-be who has a
disastrous first meeting with his girlfriend's family _ most
notably her intimidating father, played by Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Contender'' is a political thriller starring Joan Allen as
a senator chosen to be the first woman to hold the office of vice
president. Jeff Bridges co-stars as the president, with Gary Oldman
as a powerful adversary who will stop at nothing to discredit
Bridges' nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay It Forward'' stars Kevin Spacey as a social-studies
teacher who gives an assignment to his junior high school class to
think of an idea to make the world a better place and then put it
into action. Haley Joel Osment is the student whose plan for
``paying forward'' favors sets in motion an unprecedented wave of
human kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the phenomenon doesn't extend to Hollywood,
otherwise the studios would never subject us to ``Digimon: The
Movie'' (Oct. 6), the ``Saturday Night Live'' spin-off ``The Ladies
Man ``(Oct. 13) or a Sylvester Stallone remake of the classic
British gangster thriller ``Get Carter''(Oct. 13).
</P>
<P>
   Summer's slide might continue until early November.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
