A8284 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-REVIEW-F150-0902-COX     09-01 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-F150-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford, Harley create super truck
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an era when Ford has paired off with everyone from
upscale jewelers such as Cartier (Lincoln Town Car) to outdoorsmen
(Eddie Bauer Explorer), what's surprising about Dearborn's decision
to market a Harley-Davidson pickup?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. Unless it's the fact Ford has shown remarkable
restraint with its Harley-Davidson F-150. It's a Supercab (four
doors, seating for five) that does stand out in any crowd, though,
thanks to its aggressive front end, chrome side pipes and
monochromatic black finish accentuated by Harley-Davidson orange
pinstriping.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we're talking niche market here _ Ford plans only to build
up to 7,000 _ but this is also an era when people go to extremes to
individualize their personal transportation. Check the aftermarket
ads in any buff publication. So why not let the manufacturer save
you the trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Ford's base price is $32,305 (the test truck totaled $33,205),
but the appeal is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd pay this much for a pickup truck,'' says
Joe Figueroa of Hapeville, Ga., who opted for one. ``I figure it's
an investment of sorts, and I don't drive it except on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-wheeler enthusiasts were impressed. ``Man, it's cool,'' said
Dwayne Humphreys, a service technician at Earl Small's
Harley-Davidson in Marietta. ``And it's good as far as room and
getting in and out of the back and hauling things.''
</P>
<P>
   It does retain its utility, assuming owners can bring themselves
to sully its pristine showroom appearance. Dings and scratches
might provoke shudders, but underneath that rakish appearance is a
work-truck suspension. And if that 360-horsepower V-8 engine with
440 pounds-feet of torque isn't muscle enough, consider what
Figueroa plans for his baby: ``I may do something (different with
the powertrain) ... see if motor sports comes out with a
supercharger or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The cabin is about as good as it gets for pickups, with embossed
leather captain's chairs, power accessories, CD player and a ``spun
metal'' instrument panel. The rear seats _ still strange to talk
about rear seats in a pickup, isn't it? _ are good for three, and
the half-size rear doors facilitate carrying things when people
aren't occupying them.
</P>
<P>
   The ride isn't cushy because of the super-duty suspension and
those 20-inch tires, but it's superior to that of most older
pickups now on the road. The handling is good, and drivers soon
realize that the Harley-Davidson isn't going to rock 'n' roll in
corners as might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   It has benefited from the use of some components developed for
the Ford Special Vehicles Team (SVT) Lightning pickup, a
straight-ahead performance truck.
</P>
<P>
   This really is only the beginning. Coming soon to a dealer near
you to do battle with the Harley-Davidson Ford are the Cadillac
Escalade sport-utility truck and the Lincoln Blackwood pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
