<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-FILMS _ Dave Larsen's summer movie review and look ahead
to fall: ``At my signal, unleash hell.'' With those words,
Gladiator's Russell Crowe launched the 2000 summer movie season.
Crowe's command proved oddly prophetic for studios and audiences
alike. After Ridley Scott's thrilling historical epic, which earned
$181 million, summer's sizzle quickly fizzled. (Larsen, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   E-ARTS _ News about the arts on the Internet. Today's topic:
Ballet compnay's e-war, search engine. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-GUY _ Paul Jenkins' world is a four-color kaleidoscope of
super-powered beings and costumed heroics where he's quickly
becoming royalty. The Lawrenceville resident is one of the comic
book industry's most in-demand writers and the titles he scribes
are heavyweights. ``Peter Parker: Spider-Man.'' ``The Hulk.''
``Witchblade.'' All top selling illustrated tomes. He writes four
books a month plus an array of special projects. Yet the British
native has scraped by for more than a decade in an
often-unforgiving industry. (Fernandez, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   LABUTE-BETTY _ With ``Nurse Betty,'' writer-director Neil LaBute
(''In the Company of Men'') worked for the first time with someone
else's script. He said a new clarity came from the change, an
ability to see what worked and what didn't more clearly than he
could when directing his own scripts. The end result: an intriguing
movie that easily will be LaBute's most commercially accessible
movie. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) EDs: EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHILDSTARS _ ``Child Stars: Their Story,'' which airs Sept. 4
on A&AMP;E. I've always wondered why any parent would let their child
go into show business. Sure, the potential for huge paydays is
tempting. But is the price that must be paid for that possible
fortune worth it? Child stars, for instance, are often robbed of a
normal childhood. Growing up is hard enough. Imagine having to do
it in front of millions of people watching your every move or
snickering about every goofy-looking pimple you get. The pressure
to perform is also insanely intense. Many adult actors can't even
take the heat and often resort to drugs and alcohol to cope. Just
think what it's like for a kid to overhear a producer angrily
talking about low ratings and possible cancellation. And in a
business where rejection is the norm, just what kind of toll does
that take on a child's psyche? (Thompson, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   NEWYORK _ If you've ever wanted to visit New York City, but
never thought you had the means, think again. Whether you're headed
uptown, midtown or downtown, there are tons of inexpensive and even
free activities that let you take Manhattan without taking yourself
to the cleaners. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOSTON _ BOSTON _ Downtown Boston is only a short drive
from a wide variety of prime day-trip destinations _ places that
take on a special charm when late summer begins to feel the first
chill of autumn. So when in Boston, do as the Bostonians do: Get
out of town. To get you started, we've come up with six ``best
bets'' for short escapes from the city _ all within a few hours'
drive of Boston Common: Walden Pond, Rockport, Mt. Monadnock, the
Arnold Arboretum, Newburyport and Martha's Vineyard. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   OUTBACK _ Keyed to the opening of the Summer lympics (9/15): The
vast majority of the Australian continent is nothing like Sydney or
Melbourne. It's an arid, sparsely populated moonscape that the
world knows as the Outback. The spiritual heart of it is called the
Red Centre, after the red sand that ripples under the hot wind. We
journey into the region aboard the Ghan train, kick around the
funky town of Alice Springs and make a pilgrimage to Uluru, the
great rust-colored mountain in the middle of the continent that is
sacred to Aborigines and iconic to all Australians. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HUGHES _ A quick chat with Robert Hughes, whose six-part PBS
documentary on his native Australia, ``Australia: Beyond the Fatal
Shore,'' begins Tuesday. (Auchmety, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
EDs: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MCLAURIN _ Tim McLaurin is used to facing death. Long before he
became a critically acclaimed writer, the Fayetteville, N.C.,
native regularly handled rattlesnakes, copperheads and cobras in
his traveling reptile exhibit. He has survived several poisonous
bites as well as an agonizing struggle with multiple myeloma, a
bone marrow cancer. And so, when the 46-year-old McLaurin was
diagnosed with cancer of the esophagus a few months ago, he was
well prepared to die. He had lived a full life, he told himself. An
ex-Marine who had kicked a debilitating drinking habit after 20
years, he had been married and divorced twice, had two teenage
children, and had worked as a Peace Corps volunteer in Tunisia. ``I
wondered if ... it was time for me to die ... to chronicle that in
writing, straightforward and honestly,'' he says, ``and I was
willing to do that.'' (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) EDs:
EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
