<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Making a bad finish worse
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some queries gleaned from the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a polyurethaned wood bookshelf unit in my family room
that I'd like to reface. When it was built, the plywood was used as
the ``outside'' wood, and it looks like, well, polyurethaned
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering if, since this is urethaned, I could use some
paper-backed white oak veneer on top of it, to make the appearance
more uniform. Paper-backed mainly because this is almost entirely
vertical surfaces, and because the polyurethane would be almost
impossible to strip completely without more work than it's worth.
Or am I better off just living with the plywood?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've never done anything like this, nor would I. I hesitate
to say it would be a disaster, since I've no personal experience,
but the common rule of thumb in woodworking is not to use any kind
of finish as a glue surface.
</P>
<P>
   I assume the writer is talking about fir plywood, and if that's
the case one can scarcely blame him for wanting to cover it up. Of
course it would be best to strip the finish off. Then he could do
anything with it. If he applies veneer over the varnish and it
deteriorates, he's got a terrible mess on his hands. I'd try
painting over the varnish rather than applying veneer on it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm thinking about ordering some wood by mail for a project,
but I'm totally stumped how I'm supposed to figure out how much I
need. If I start with a cut list, I can figure out how many board
feet I need. That's easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, most mail-order places ship random lengths and widths, so
there's no good way to know what pieces I'll be able to get out of
what boards. Not to mention that if I order anything less than
select, I've got to deal with an unknown amount of waste to get the
clear cuttings I need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there some rule of thumb I can use? Or should I just resign
myself to ordering a lot more than I need so I can pick through it
to get what I want and stock the rest for future projects?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ordering wood sight unseen for a particular project is a
chancy thing. One can call the suppliers and ask how far they will
go in handpicking the wood for you. If they can only pick out the
board feet you want and adhere to minimum lengths, there's little
to do but order more than you need.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine why one would need to mail-order unsized
wood unless one has no means of hauling it. If that's the case, it
might be more satisfactory to rent a truck, go to the wood lot and
pick out your stock yourself.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
