<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ While some of the American educational reforms
were changed after Allied occupation forces left Japan in 1952,
most of the American-imposed reforms stayed in place and were
responsible for Japan's meteoric postwar rise to international
economic power. Now Japanese school children routinely wipe the
floor with American school children whenever or however scholastic
achievement is compared. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ I was born at high noon 46
years ago, back in the days when the opening day of dove season
began at high noon on the Friday of Labor Day weekend. The day, as
I understand it, my birthday was Friday. So my father was pacing,
pacing, pacing outside the labor room and I'm thinking it was every
bit as much because he was worried that he was going to miss the
first day of hunting as it was worried about my delivery. (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ``Fergit, Hell!'' Would
you believe it? We're in the third century since the late
unpleasantness with our northern neighbors, and ain't nobody
fergittin' nothin'. And nobody is forgiving anything. (Jim Minter
is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The final week of the Dragons
regular season found folks in a celebratory mood _ and, after a
record-breaking season, thinking about the possibilities for
downtown. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ In case you've forgotten, it's a president we'll
be electing this November, not a national pastor, priest, imam or
rabbi. It would be easy enough to forget, what with the candidates
hosannahing around the country as if they were caught up in a Great
Awakening rather than in what, properly, ought to be a down and
dirty, eye-gougin', ear-bittin' partisan wallow, as God intended.
(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ I have full sympathy for establishments that
have been victimized by thieves with bad checks, phony credit cards
and the like, but the intrusion into my life as a result has grated
me to a raw edge. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The real bias that Joe Lieberman faces these days
arises from his fellow Jews. As Lieberman began his quest for the
vice presidency, some prominent Jewish leaders urged him privately
not to talk so much about his faith. When he ignored their advice,
they went public with their criticism. (Andy Glass is a columnist
for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY.
