<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-CO     09-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    For Saturday, 09-02-00, or thereafter
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Who'll win the debate about the
debates?
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Who wins the presidential election may well be
decided by who wins the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   But right now, more important than that, is the debate about the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's people, with every reason to believe their candidate
is a great debater, want it to be the classic one-on-one kind, with
candidates on a stage, standing behind podiums and facing questions
from a panel of the press.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's people, with no reason to believe their man is
a great debater, want it to be the Larry King kind, a sit-down,
talk-it-over roundtable discourse with King likely doing as much of
the talking as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   The difference could be the difference in the election.
</P>
<P>
   A classic format -- the Kennedy-Nixon debate is a memorable
example -- generally favors the more knowledgeable candidate and
the better debater. Gore handily beat Jack Kemp in the vice
presidential debates, one-on-one, four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable format makes it easier to deflect questions,
especially with a moderator such as King, a convivial interviewer
who prides himself on not being a go-for-the-jugular journalist.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the kind of debate Bush won in South Carolina
against John McCain and Alan Keyes -- Keyes giving an additional
advantage to Bush by distracting the audience from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable, no doubt, would dull Gore's edge. But either
way, Bush has good reason to go into the debates semi-terrified
that he'll be run through the wringer and hung out to dry, having
seen it happen to his daddy in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton slaughtered Big Bush. No great disgrace in that.
Clinton was made for debating, with his spectacular memory and
dazzling ability to express himself in precise sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bush was just the opposite. He was unmade by debating.
</P>
<P>
   When he came off the stage, supposedly he shook his head and
said, ``The guy's programmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Better, perhaps, had he said that from the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a killer line can be a deciding factor. Everybody
remembers Lloyd Bentsen, vice presidential running mate for Michael
Dukakis, telling Dan Quayle, ``You're no Jack Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan had a great line of his own in debating Jimmy
Carter: ``There you go again, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   But expectations also play a role, and here's where Gov. Bush
could have the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, most everybody had predicted Carter would demolish
Reagan, and the very fact that the debate turned out close to a
draw was a setback for the incumbent president.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that sometimes the guy who was expected to lose wins it
by simply holding his own.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, with his total recall of tedious facts, statistics and
policy details, could easily come across stiff as a fence post and
dull as ditch water; such is his nature.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, with his down-home, good-ol'-boy, ``Aw, shucks''
style, could come out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In political debates, the winner isn't necessarily the one who
speaks the best, says the most in the shortest time and has the
greatest command of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, of course, is important -- but not nearly as
important as which candidate the people like the best when the
debate is over.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
