<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH BICHETTE, RED SOX HAVE TOUGH CLIMB TO PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes obstacles text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox team that enters September 1 game behind the
Cleveland Indians in the American League wild-card race bears scant
resemblance to the team that took the field against the Seattle
Mariners in Safeco Field on Opening Day, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley was the first baseman, Gary Gaetti the designated
hitter, John Valentin the third baseman. Jeff Frye was on the
bench. Brian Rose was in the starting rotation. So was Jeff
Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   Rico Brogna, Mike Lansing, Rolando Arrojo, Bernard Gilkey, and
Dante Bichette all wore other uniforms. Lou Merloni was in Japan.
Hipolito Pichardo was in Florida, on rehab assignment. Tomo Ohka
was in Pawtucket. Morgan Burkhart was more myth than reality, Izzy
Alcantara an unknown. Bret Saberhagen updates were still
optimistic. The payroll was closer to $75 million than $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   The team that finished last season 26 games above .500 and won a
second consecutive wild-card spot was 16 games above .500 entering
last September. At this time a year ago, the Sox were 7 1/2 games
behind the Yankees in the AL East, but led the wild-card race by
two games over Oakland and five over Toronto, the only other teams
in contention.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Sons of Jimy Williams begin the final push
eight games over .500, five games behind the Yankees, and as one of
four teams chasing the Indians in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 31 days, a period ending with a Sunday afternoon
game in Florida against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, the Sox will play
32 times.
</P>
<P>
   They will play the Indians, the team they have met in the
postseason in each of the last two years, eight times in 10 days,
including back-to-back doubleheaders in Fenway Park Sept. 20-21.
</P>
<P>
   They will have two days off. Two other scheduled offdays had to
be sacrificed as makeup dates for rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   They will play a rare home-and-home set with the Yankees in a
span of four days _ three games at Fenway (Sept. 8-10) followed by
a makeup date in Yankee Stadium on the 11th. Beginning with
Friday's game against the Mariners, who lead the AL West, 13 of
Boston's next 14 games and 18 of 23 will be against teams in
postseason contention: the M's, the A's, the Yankees, and the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? The Tigers, who started out losing 23 of their
first 32 games but clawed back to the break-even point this week,
may be in the thick of things by the time the Sox visit Comerica
Park for four games beginning Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox play 16 of their next 23 games at Fenway Park, where
they are 35-28. But they are on the road for the season's final
week against the White Sox, who have the best record in the league,
and the Devil Rays, for whom there could be no sweeter revenge for
this week's brawling than knocking the Sox out of the playoff
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have not played well against teams with winning
records. They hold a series edge on only the Yankees _ five wins to
four losses. Otherwise, it's 4-5 against the Angels and White Sox;
.500 against the Indians (2-2), A's (4-4), and Mariners (3-3); and
4-8 against the Blue Jays, the one division rival they won't see
the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   How will this all shake out? You'd have to be another Richard
Hatch to know.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll try handicapping the field, ranking the teams from
least likely to most likely to advance to the postseason. Three
division winners, one wild-card entry, four also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   8. Anaheim _ The Angels' leading winner is their setup man,
Shigetoshi Hasegawa, who has eight W's. Their winningest starter,
Jarrod Washburn, has won seven, but he's on the disabled list and
probably won't be back before the end of the season. They play 20
of their next 26 games on the road. But they have four guys with 30
or more home runs, the first AL team to accomplish that feat
(though the Blue Jays are about to join them), an MVP type in Darin
Erstad, and a terrific first-year manager in Mike Scioscia. They
also have Mo, though the ankle he injured last year is starting to
act up. They've made a gallant run, but it's about that time when
the wheels start falling off.
</P>
<P>
   7. Toronto _ The Sox are lucky they don't have to see the Blue
Jays again, given the way they were slapped around this season.
Toronto has done a remarkable job surviving the loss of slugging
outfielder Raul Mondesi, who had elbow surgery and is lost for the
season. Dave Martinez, who is on his fourth team this season, is
hitting .398 for the Blue Jays, and the team already has tied a
club record with 221 home runs, led by Carlos Delgado, who is
making a serious bid to become the first player since Yaz in '67 to
win the Triple Crown. But New Hampshire's Chris Carpenter stumbled
badly in his return to the starting rotation; another young
starter, Kelvim Escobar, has been shuffled to the pen; and 19-game
winner David Wells (14-2 after a B-J loss) had to come out of his
last start after just five innings, a red flag. Martinez and Mickey
Morandini have been outstanding stretch pickups, giving the Jays a
veteran presence they lacked, but unless the kids grow up
overnight, the pitching comes up just a little short.
</P>
<P>
   6. Oakland _ The A's have lost 16 of their last 24 games,
blowing a great chance to overtake the Mariners in the West. Matt
Stairs, the A's player most likely to come back as a Coors beer man
after he retires, has been unable to shake a season-long slump.
Jason Giambi, the team's best hitter, is playing with an injured
left shoulder. Closer Jason Isringhausen, an All-Star at the break,
was a horror show in August (14 hits, 8 walks, an 8.10 ERA in 10
IP). They lead the league in errors. Third baseman Olmedo Saenz,
who is hitting .440 against the Sox, has been shut down by
hamstring problems. They spend the next week on the road against
the Blue Jays and Sox, then catch a break from the schedule, with
seven games left against the D-Rays and four with the Orioles. But
the team with a payroll of just $32 million doesn't have quite
enough bullets to play with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cleveland _ The Indians' season turned around when manager
Charlie Manuel ordered them to remove the Ping-Pong table from the
clubhouse. Since putting the paddles away July 2, they've been 17-5
at home, 29-21 overall. ``I think they gave it to charity or
something,'' said reliever Paul Shuey, the reigning Ping-Pong
champ. In the absence of table tennis, Kenny Lofton is setting the
table again. Which is a good thing, because Lofton is batting .311
when the Indians win, just .213 when they lose. David Segui has
made a huge contribution since coming over from Texas, Manny
Ramirez is back to putting up monster numbers after recovering from
his hamstring woes, and GM John Hart has picked up some needed
pitching to compensate for the hellacious run of injuries that has
claimed two key starters, Jaret Wright and Charles Nagy. But the
Indians will lose out to the Sox for the same reasons they always
do: They can't beat Pedro Martinez (0-8, including playoffs), they
don't have an established No. 1 starter (Bartolo Colon is close,
but Chuck Finley is 3-5 with a 6.54 ERA and hasn't pitched seven
innings in a game since July 14), and their bullpen (Bob Wickman,
Shuey, Steve Karsay) is vulnerable. The best team that won't make
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   4. Boston _ The defining moment of last season came in
September, when the Red Sox had a 12-game, 13-day trip through
Seattle, Oakland, New York, and Cleveland. Martinez won the day
after they'd lost the trip opener to the Mariners on a
controversial call. He won the series opener in New York, setting
the stage for a Sox sweep with the greatest game he's ever pitched,
a 17-K (the last five batters in succession) one-hitter on the
biggest stage of all. He struck out 14 Indians in the trip's
finale, a gritty 13-inning win in which a sore-elbowed Rod Beck
somehow lasted three innings and Jason Varitek and Trot Nixon sent
everybody home with home runs. Martinez starts this month coming
off another one-hitter. His presence guarantees that there will be
light in even the darkest hours. Prediction: Ramon Martinez,
freshly restored to the rotation beginning Saturday afternoon, will
match the grit that Saberhagen has shown the last two years. The
Sox hit just 18 home runs in August; Bichette has to help. The
couple days off last week did wonders for Nomar Garciaparra, even
as his streak of 15 months hitting .300 or better came to an end
(he hit .293 in August). Carl Everett is swinging the way he did
the first half of the season. Dan Duquette has emptied the Trust's
pockets in an all-out effort to keep playing in October. He'll
worry about the $25 million-plus he has tied up in Valentin,
Lansing, Bichette, and Jose Offerman next season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
