</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... next season.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   3. Seattle _ ``We've been playing bad,'' shortstop Alex
Rodriguez said, ``but we haven't played awful.'' It's a fine line.
The Mariners have lost 14 of their last 17. The ex-Sox pitchers at
the top of the Seattle rotation, Aaron Sele and Jamie Moyer, have
made 11 straight starts without a win. Still, they've probably
weathered their one bad stretch of the season, and should have
enough to hold off the A's. The nucleus of Edgar Martinez, A-Rod,
John Olerud, Jay Buhner, Dan Wilson, and Rickey Henderson has the
experience to hold off Oakland. Besides, the M's didn't play 19
innings against the Sox that night in Seattle to blow it now.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chicago _ Some thought the White Sox would shrink at the
first sight of the Indians making a charge. They stumbled briefly
but came out of August with a winning record (15-13). ``As young as
this team is,'' manager Jerry Manuel said recently, ``I feel good
about what's going on.'' Frank Thomas is having an MVP year, but
the Big Hurt isn't the only big bat. Shortstop Jose Valentin, whose
errors may kill the White Sox in October, leads the club in hitting
since the break with a .340 average. Charles Johnson, imported from
Baltimore, is a big pickup behind the plate. Magglio Ordonez, Paul
Konerko, Ray Durham, Carlos Lee, and Herbert Perry are among the
players who form the heart of this young, committed team, led by
Manuel, odds-on favorite to be named manager of the year. And the
pitching (James Baldwin, Mike Sirotka, Jim Parque) has held up.
</P>
<P>
   1. New York _ You know the details. Glenallen Hill comes over
and decides he's Gehrig. The Rocket is back to being the Rocket.
Andy Pettitte ran off seven wins in a row. David Justice and Jose
Canseco were picked up as if they were sale items at Wal-Mart.
Chuck Knoblauch is out with a sore elbow, but there are veteran
fill-ins Luis Sojo and Jose Vizcaino. And no Yankee team blows a
five-game lead in September. Not to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SEPTEMBER OBSTACLES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seattle &QL; 
Sept. 1-4 (4 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Mariners: 3-3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle starters were miserable in August. Aaron Sele was 1-4
with a 7.03 ERA, Jamie Moyer was 0-5 with a 9.84 ERA. Outfielder
Jay Buhner is on the disabled list with a sprained right wrist.
Alex Rodriguez is batting just .143 (3 for 21) vs. the Sox; the
team is hitting .182 vs. the Sox. Rookie closer Kazuhiro Sasaki has
30 saves in 33 chances. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oakland &QL; 
Sept. 5-6 (2 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. A's: 4-4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jason Isringhausen had an 8.10 ERA with 14 hits and 8
walks in 10 innings as the A's were just 11-16 in August. Ex-Sox
Mike Stanley has 2 homers, 5 doubles, and 10 RBIs in 76 at-bats in
a part-time role. MVP candidate Jason Giambi is playing with a
strained left shoulder. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minnesota &QL; 
Sept. 7 (1 game) &QL; 
Sox vs. Twins: 7-2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First baseman David Ortiz is hitting .450 with 2 homers and 12
RBIs against the Sox. Nine Twins are hitting .300 or better against
the Sox, but they've been outscored, 72-45, as Twins pitchers have
a 7.73 ERA against the Sox. The Sox have 17 home runs in 9 games
against the Twins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New York &QL; 
Sept. 8-11 (4 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Yankees: 5-4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens is 7-0 with a 2.54 ERA in 13 starts since June 9,
his last loss. Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch has been out since
Aug. 3 with elbow tendinitis, and Joe Torre fears he's lost for the
season. The Bombers hit 45 home runs in August. Ex-Cub Glenallen
Hill hit .411 with 10 HRs and 19 RBIs for the month, and newcomers
Jose Canseco and David Justice combined for 11 HRs and 33 RBIs in
the month. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cleveland &QL; 
Sept. 12-14, Sept. 19-21 (8 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Indians: 2-2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe is 18-8 since Aug. 2 and has taken the lead in the
wild-card race. Manny Ramirez is crushing the ball since coming
back from hamstring problems (.365, 14 HRs, 40 RBIs in 38 games
since the All-Star break). The Indians hit .305 in August, with
Travis Fryman driving in 27 runs. They have never beaten Pedro
Martinez (they are 0-8, including two losses in the postseason).
Cleveland is missing starters Charles Nagy and Jaret Wright because
of injuries. New closer Bob Wickman has 10 saves since his trade
from Milwaukee but has blown four chances. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Detroit &QL; 
Sept. 15-17 (4 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Tigers: 5-3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are one game under .500 after a 9-23 start.
Knuckleballer Steve Sparks is 5-1 with a 2.40 ERA in seven starts
since the break. Juan Gonzalez is batting just .235 with 2 homers
against the Sox. Closer Todd Jones has 36 saves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Baltimore &QL; 
Sept. 22-24 (3 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Orioles: 6-3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled Albert Belle is hitting just .221 in August. Orioles
pitchers have allowed 8 runs a game to the Sox. Will Clark and B.J.
Surhoff, the Orioles' top hitters against the Sox, have both been
traded. Cal Ripken Jr., 40, is still not back from his back woes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chicago &QL; 
Sept. 26-28 (3 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. White Sox: 4-5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas plays the big hurt on the Red Sox (.462, 3 HRs, 6
RBIs), and Magglio Ordonez has 5 doubles, 3 homers, and 11 RBIs
while hitting .379 against Boston. White Sox pitching has a 2.88
ERA against Boston. LHP Mike Sirotka has allowed Boston just 1
earned run in 16 innings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tampa Bay &QL; 
Sept. 29-30 Oct. 1 (3 games) &QL; 
Sox vs. Devil Rays: 5-4 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bad blood from brawls and ejections may be remembered on the
last weekend of the season. The Devil Rays are hitting just .254
against the Sox, but their staff ERA is 3.82 against Boston and
closer Roberto Hernandez is 3 for 3 in saves. &QL;
</P>
