<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-VIRTUAL-MANUFACTURER-     09-01 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-MANUFACTURER-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGEN UNCHAINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., Sept. 5, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from HARVARD BUSINESS
REVIEW, the premiere source of information on the art and science
of business and management. For information about purchasing this
article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or about The Syndicate's new
offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING _ contact one of
the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the
end of the text.) 
 By DAVID BOVET and JOSEPH MARTHA  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Biogen was founded in 1978, it had a simple,
research-centered business model: Its scientists would use
biotechnology to discover compounds that might be used to create
new drugs, and then it would license those compounds to big
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   It had no need to build a manufacturing or distribution
infrastructure because it didn't intend to actually produce drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That business model was turned upside down in 1994 when the
company received preliminary FDA approval to market Avonex, a
breakthrough drug that could slow the progression of multiple
sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen suddenly had to find a way to get a product to customers
quickly and dependably while building an efficient delivery system
for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   The company embraced an entirely new way to organize and manage
production and distribution _ a way that renders obsolete many of
the old assumptions underlying supply chain management.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen could have licensed its new drug to a pharmaceutical
company, but it rejected that option. Avonex's market potential was
simply too big for Biogen to give up control.
</P>
<P>
   It could have tried to build a complete supply chain of its own,
but that wasn't feasible. It had neither the time nor the money to
put the necessary assets in place.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the conventional options, the company set off on a
path of innovation: It would work with a network of partners to get
its new product to market. It would become a virtual manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The first step was to determine which tasks it would perform and
which it would outsource. Biogen took a hard look at the four core
tasks of drug production _ bulk manufacturing, formulation,
packaging, and warehousing and distribution _ and determined that
it could handle the bulk manufacturing at its existing facility in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Since it had already been producing smaller quantities of the
drug for use in clinical testing, it was confident it had the
skills necessary for manufacturing on a larger scale.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else, however, it decided to contract out.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing its partners, it looked for organizations that were
big enough to accommodate rapid growth but small enough to give the
Biogen account top priority.
</P>
<P>
   For formulation, which consisted of freeze-drying the drug and
storing it at low temperatures, it chose Ben Venue Laboratories, a
contract manufacturer in Ohio that had served several large
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Packaging Coordinators, a small but innovative company near
Philadelphia, was given the job of packaging.
</P>
<P>
   And for warehousing and distribution, Biogen chose to partner
with Amgen, which had a new distribution center in Louisville, Ky.
Amgen had built too much capacity, so it was willing to give Biogen
an attractive deal on a large, refrigerated space close to an
airport and UPS shipping facility.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen kept tight control over managing the network. It
stationed some of its people at partners' sites, offered their
staffs training and supervision, and installed new computer systems
to manage the flow of shared information.
</P>
<P>
   It also set tough standards for the performance of the network,
establishing world-class objectives for execution and quality, and
insisting on a goal of fulfilling every order without delay.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hamm, a member of the launch team and now Biogen's vice
president of operations, stressed that ``the worst thing that could
happen'' would be to run out of the product. A shortage would not
only hurt the patients who relied on the drug, it would also
undermine Biogen's profits. Because Avonex carried a high price _
$1,000 for a month's supply _ the cost of carrying inventory was
tiny relative to the cost of a lost sale.
</P>
<P>
   As the company waited for final FDA approval of Avonex, it
worked with its partners to develop four detailed contingency plans
for getting the drug to patients as quickly as possible. The plans
were broken down into 15-minute increments. Team members wore
beepers, rented hotel rooms, reserved rental cars and lined up
airplane reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 11 a.m. on Friday, May 17, 1996, Biogen received FDA
approval. The virtual organization worked seamlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The first shipments of Avonex reached pharmacy shelves within 35
hours _ a new record for the pharmaceutical industry _ and the drug
was ready for dispensing by Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months, Avonex had displaced Betaseron, a multiple
sclerosis drug introduced three years earlier, as the market
leader, garnering more than 60 percent of new prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The full value of the production and distribution network became
apparent over time: Between 1996 and 1999, the drug's production
volume increased fivefold, and the virtual organization scaled up
flawlessly to accommodate the growth.
</P>
<P>
   Avonex has never gone out of stock, and there have been no
serious customer service problems or product recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The outsourcing of key operational elements has enabled Biogen
to achieve a competitive cost structure despite its limited
production experience and small scale.
</P>
<P>
   It has also helped the company keep its fixed assets low, even
when production volume increased dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The required capital investment was modest relative to the size
of the business, and much of the investment risk could be shared
with partners.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when companies everywhere are being challenged to reduce
their fixed assets and increase their flexibility, Biogen's story
offers valuable lessons to nearly all executives about how to
manage the crucial back end to deliver the front-end promise.
</P>
<P>
   (David Bovet is a vice president at Mercer Management Consulting
in Lexington, Mass., and Joseph Martha is a vice president at
Mercer in Cleveland.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
