<HEADER>
A8306 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-JOB-SEARCH-ON-WE     09-01 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-JOB-SEARCH-ON-WEB-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE JOBS LIKE CLOTHES? CLICK HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By ANDREA ADELSON  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Last fall, Gage J. Fellows gamely tried to expand 1159.com, a
``best'' Web site about Denver nightclubs, into a national online
travel and entertainment guide. To hire advertising sales
representatives, he turned to a local recruiting agency and bought
newspaper and radio advertisements. Applicants applied, all right,
but most lacked basic computer skills.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows' luck improved with a trial posting on Hotjobs.com, one
of the Internet's largest job boards, with 197,000 listings. In
three days, 1159.com received 100 resumes from better-qualified
applicants. ``People who use Hotjobs have computer skills and
understand the product,'' Fellows said.
</P>
<P>
   With renewed confidence, he agreed to a two-month, $1,800
contract with Hotjobs and posted 30 job openings in six cities.
Now, Fellows is buried by an avalanche of 5,000 resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has mushroomed with e-cruiting sites like
Monster.com, Hotjobs.com and Headhunter.net and pushed Web hiring
into the mainstream by spending millions of dollars on high-profile
1999 Super Bowl commercials aimed at people who might be restless
in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Millions responded, posting their resumes without cost. By
letting job seekers freely search the sites by category and
location, the sites allow them to forward their information to
listed employers with a mouse click, accelerating the traditional
job-hunting process.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites update their postings hourly and offer candidates
e-mail notices about openings that match their criteria. To forge
long-term relationships with consumers, Hotjobs lets job seekers
block some viewers (like a current employer) from reviewing their
resumes. Monster sends registered members newsletters with
career-management tips. E-cruiting traffic peaks, yes, on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance of power has shifted,'' said Richard Johnson, the
chief executive of Hotjobs.com in Boston, whose quirky marketing
taps into worker discontent and belittles corporate loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it's not about the job but the job seeker,'' said
Jeffrey C. Taylor, the founder and chief executive of largest site,
Boston-based Monster.com, which is owned by leading
recruitment-advertising agency TMP Worldwide Inc. Monster's
advertisement suggests the dream career need not be a dream
deferred.
</P>
<P>
   Job hunters with less technical acumen are now posting their
resumes in far greater numbers. Their influence is starting to
broaden the sorts of career-management tools available online, like
salary surveys and certification tests, which still cater to the
Net's early adopters: technology professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be tricky finding a site that has a lot of positions
for the noncomputer geeks,'' said Christine Tetrault, the human
resources director for a software company in Virginia, who found
her job at Careerpath.com. The site is built on newspaper
classified advertisements and is owned by eight newspaper
companies, including The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy and quick and I saved a fortune in stationery and
stamps,'' she said in an e-mail message. ``I also liked the ease
involved in setting search parameters and checking out what comes
up instead of getting all cramped and grimy leaning over the
classifieds.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites earn their meal tickets from employers, who pay for a
range of services, and advertising sponsors. Job lists come from
corporate offices, media buyers and temporary agencies like
Manpower and Kelly Services. (An exception is Hotjobs, which
refuses to list recruitment-agency openings.)
</P>
<P>
   The sites also allow managers and commission-based recruiters to
tally how often their listings are searched. Some include
matchmaking software that pairs resumes with appropriate job
descriptions. Most charge employers for access to peruse a site's
database of resumes. Top executives, still mostly loyal to
headhunters to fill high-level slots, often use job sites to
monitor their in-house recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites' resume databases are all that's needed to fill
job openings for some employers, who expressed dissatisfaction with
recruiters who often expect 33 percent commissions and offer
ill-suited prospects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sites that offer job listings for the
technologically savvy like Techies.com and Dice.com, a crop of job
sites specialized by industry, region and even subjects is
emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Sites for bankers, pharmacists and truck drivers are cited at
Interbiznet.com, the publisher of a Mill Valley, Calif., online
recruiting newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs at summer camps, casinos and the site for the Feminist
Career Center are listed in Career Crossroads, a directory
published by MMC Group of Kendall Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Craigslist.org, a San Francisco bulletin board where residents
post employment and housing ads, was ranked the ``most efficient''
job recruiting site nationwide in a recent survey of 50 recruiters
by Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Another twist comes from Flipdog.com, which searches and
extracts job postings each week on corporate Web sites and lists
them without charge. The site has 505,735 openings, 25 percent more
than Monster, some as obscure as a $7-an-hour Zamboni driver needed
to groom a Michigan ice rink. ``We're building a site and service
that lets people fit in wherever they come from,'' said Brett C.
Walker, the vice president for marketing at the company, based in
Provo, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Late to the party are old-line executive search companies like
Korn Ferry International and Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, which have set
up Futurestep.com and Leadersonline.com, respectively. Analysts
predict that, as with other Net latecomers, established recruiters
will ultimately eclipse Internet-only start-ups, and that local
commission-based recruiters will be the ones most pinched by the
Web's lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the first specialty job sites that failed to draw enough
visitors are already disappearing and being absorbed in general
sites like Monster, which has 3.3 million resumes and most of the
Fortune 500 companies as clients.
</P>
<P>
   But even though e-cruiting revenue is expected to increase
fourfold by 2003, to $2.3 billion from $600 million last year, it
still is expected to make up just 1 percent of recruiting revenue
globally, according to Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
