<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8307 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-FARM-TOOL-NYTSF &LR;      09-01 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-FARM-TOOL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INTERNET IS A PROMISING FARM TOOL, FOR SOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By DIRK JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   EARLVILLE, Ill. _ When it was finally time to trade his old John
Deere tractor for a newer model, Steve Lake, a 55-year-old farmer,
went shopping on the Internet. To find just the used model he
wanted _ a front-wheel-drive machine with 130 horsepower _ he would
have needed to flip through farm magazines and newspapers from all
over the Midwest. But trolling on his computer, Lake took only 30
minutes to discover a dealership in Lowden, Iowa, offering just
what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There it was on the screen,'' said Lake, who stands 6-foot-2
in work boots. ``It was just what I was after.''
</P>
<P>
   With a digital camera, Lake photographed the 1976 tractor he
wanted to trade and sent it by e-mail to the dealership. The dealer
wanted $63,000 for the newer tractor, which had 1,500 hours of use.
The farmer expected $16,000 for his machine, which had racked up
6,000 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Confident that a bargain could be struck, Lake drove to Iowa,
haggled a bit, then returned to the farm. After a few e-mail
messages back and forth, the farmer and the dealer reached a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers are stuck out here in the middle of nowhere,'' Lake
said. ``But the computer gives us knowledge from the rest of the
world, and knowledge is power.''
</P>
<P>
   Mace Thornton, a spokesman for the American Farm Bureau
Federation, says the agricultural business appears to be poised for
a transformation through computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many Web sites have been introduced in the last six months,
it's hard to keep up with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, farmers are using computers mainly to shop for the best
deals on machinery and supplies, especially chemicals to kill bugs
and weeds. To a lesser extent, some farmers are exploring the
Internet to find the best prices for their crops. Web sites in
California and Wisconsin, among other places, allow farmers to sell
produce and meat directly to consumers, yielding a better price at
both ends because the middleman has been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of David Furry, the manager at Strackbein's
Inc., the Iowa dealership where Lake found his tractor, the pace of
e-commerce in agriculture lags behind computer use in other
industries because most farmers are over 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of a certain age are less comfortable doing business on
the computer _ they still want to kick the tires,'' Furry said.
``It's a different story for younger men, the ones who are taking
over for their dads.''
</P>
<P>
   One big problem for computer-savvy farmers is the low quality of
telephone service in many rural areas, which slows transmission on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here on 6 miles of copper lines, so there's a lot of
</P>
<P>
   noise in there,'' Lake said, referring to the frequent losses of
computer connections. ``And when you hit the keys for a search, you
might as well go get a cup of coffee while it searches, because
it's going to take a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake, a fifth-generation farmer whose 1,400 acres are planted
with corn and soybeans _ ``a cow-chow factory,'' he calls it _ has
had a computer since 1988. (He also uses it to stay tethered to the
world outside, reading major newspapers online and scanning
restaurant reviews and museum exhibitions in Chicago, 75 miles
away.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the computer, Lake said, finding and buying used
machinery was a tedious chore that often ended unsatisfactorily.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd just gone to my local dealer, I wouldn't have found
what I was looking for,'' he said. ``So the dealer would have tried
to push me to buy something that he had but that I didn't really
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the Web sites could use some improving, Lake
said, noting that some lack important details.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't have a picture, it just doesn't reach out and
grab you,'' he said. ``And you'd like to know about the history of
the machine.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lake's case, he wanted to be certain that the tractor had not
been used on a big hog operation, which could make the inside of
the cab stink, and that the previous owner was not a cigarette
smoker, which could do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But he found precisely what he had envisioned. The newer John
Deere tractor, painted green just like the older model, has run
like a champ over the past few months during planting season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just flip a button on the dash,'' Lake marveled, ``and it
goes into front-wheel drive.''
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't hurt that the cab is equipped with a stereo.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
