<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BICHETTE-B     09-01 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BICHETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BICHETTE, DUQUETTE ADDS PUNCH TO LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his unrelenting _ and yet unfulfilled _ quest to add
consistent punch to the Red Sox' lackluster lineup, general manager
Dan Duquette Thursday tried again, this time picking up Dante
Bichette, one of the most productive hitters in baseball for much
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox gave up two minor league pitchers, including top
prospect Chris Reitsma, to acquire Bichette from the Cincinnati
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are mortgaging part of our future, obviously,'' Duquette
said in a conference call with reporters. ``We traded these young
players in an effort to win the pennant and make the playoffs this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   A right fielder who batted cleanup for the Reds, Bichette, 36,
was hitting .295 with 16 home runs and 76 RBIs. Only one Boson
player this year has knocked in more runs, Carl Everett (98).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a veteran, proven RBI man,'' Duquette said. ``We have
been looking for a veteran presence to help our lineup, and we hope
that Dante will add that presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, have they have been looking. Ed Sprague, Sean Berry, and
Rico Brogna come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also picked up outfielder Midre Cummings Thursday from
Minnesota in exchange for minor league shortstop Hector De Los
Santos. Cummings, 28, who played in 67 games for the Sox in 1998,
is the league's leading pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, like Brogna, said all the right things in the
conference call with Duquette, even citing Ted Williams as his
all-time favorite player. If that weren't enough, Bichette fell in
love in Fenway's shadow. ``I met my wife (Marianna) there, at the
Gold's Gym right behind the Green Monster,'' he said. ``So I have a
lot of luck there. Hopefully, it will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bichette said he was so hungry to play at Fenway that when he
took the call from Reds general manager Jim Bowden about the trade,
he said to himself, ``Please let it be Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bichette's luck doesn't hold, the Sox could be in trouble.
The team ranks 12th of 14 teams in the league in runs scored, with
only Minnesota and Tampa Bay ranking lower. They managed just one
run in a 3-1 loss Wednesday night to the Devil Rays. And they face
the prospect of losing Brian Daubach, their only consistent power
threat other than Everett and Nomar Garciaparra, for an indefinite
period.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach underwent tests Thursday to determine the severity of an
elbow injury he suffered in Tuesday's bench-clearing brawl with the
Devil Rays in St. Petersburg. Results were not available Thursday
night. The Sox initially listed the injury as a hyperextended left
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Scott Hatteberg said he was not encouraged by how
Daubach looked Wednesday. ``I'm not a medical guy,'' Hatteberg
said, ``but his arm didn't look very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Bichette and Cummings will come as a blow to
several players, whose at-bats could be seriously affected by the
newcomers. In addition, the Sox are likely to recall minor league
sluggers Izzy Alcantara and Morgan Burkhart now that Sept. 1 has
arrived and the team can expand its 25-player roster to 40 players.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on Daubach's condition, the team also may also call up
first baseman Dernell Stenson from Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Sox players who may see their playing time diminished
by the new hitters are first baseman Brogna and outfielders Darren
Lewis and Bernard Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, who averaged more than 28 home runs a year in seven
seasons with Colorado before he was traded to the Reds last
October, has 1,100 hits since 1995, more than anyone in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   He also drove in at least 117 runs each year with the Rockies,
whose batters benefit from hitter-friendly Coors Field. Mike
Lansing, for example, had 27 extra-base hits, including 11 home
runs, in 365 at-bats for the Rockies this year. In 95 at-bats for
the Sox, he has two extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, who broke into the majors with Milwaukee in 1991, hit
.366 at Fenway in two years with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played here in a long time, but I remember when I
wasn't quite an accomplished hitter _ I was a young hitter coming
up _ I always felt very strong here,'' he said. ``It's a great
hitter's park.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston also picked up the final year of Bichette's contract,
which is next year. His salary is $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any sign of concern about Bichette, it's that he has
hit only three home runs since the All-Star break and only one
since July 23. He also has grounded into 18 double plays, which
ranks second in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Reitsma, 22, was a combined 10-6 with a 3.03 ERA in 25 starts
this year for Double A Trenton and Single A Sarasota. The Sox chose
him in the second round of the June 1996 free agent draft, and he
was evolving into one of the team's best young righthanded
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also traded John Curtice. The lefthander, 20, went 4-10
with a 6.49 ERA for Sarasota while recovering from a shoulder
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings leads the AL with 11 pinch hits and 10 pinch-hit RBIs.
He is 11 for 33 (.333) as a pinch hitter. Overall, he is hitting
.276 with four homers and 22 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he will be a good complement to our club,
especially at this time of year,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   De Los Santos, 20, hit .295 with one homer and 11 RBIs in 46
games for Boston's rookie team in the Gulf Coast League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
