<P>
   THE INTERNET IS A PROMISING FARM TOOL, FOR SOME
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-FARM-TOOL _ These days, farmers are using computers to shop
for the best deals on machinery and supplies, especially chemicals
to kill bugs and weeds. To a lesser extent, some farmers are
exploring the Internet to find the best prices for their crops. Web
sites in California and Wisconsin, among other places, allow
farmers to sell produce and meat directly to consumers, yielding a
better price at both ends because the middleman has been
eliminated. A report on how the agricultural industry is entering
cyberspace. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE JOBS LIKE CLOTHES? CLICK HERE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-JOB-SEARCH-ON-WEB _ The Internet has mushroomed with
e-cruiting sites like Monster.com, Hotjobs.com and Headhunter.net.
It has also pushed Web hiring into the mainstream by spending
millions of dollars on high-profile 1999 Super Bowl commercials
aimed at people who might be restless in their jobs. Millions
responded, posting their resumes without cost. The sites earn their
meal tickets from employers, who pay for a range of services and
advertising sponsors. A report on the business of job hunting in
the Digital Age. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
