<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENT: THE MAN WHO WOULD BE KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was the little French guy's fantasy. He would
put on his burglar's accessories _ red bandana, very dark
wraparound shades, sneakers. And he would creep past 15,000 or so
onlookers, sneak into Andre's room, and steal one of the star's
most prized possessions: his place in the US Open. Slick. Very
slick lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Then, says the diminutive French felon named Arnaud Clement,
platoons of gorgeous women would descend on him. They would smother
him in kisses, hailing one of the greatest thefts since Havlicek
stole the ball. He would make the heisting hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fantasy,'' Arnaud the thief says, grinning broadly,
``but some of it happened. You saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of it _ one of the grandest larcenies ever committed at
Flushing Meadow _ was seen up close by Andre Agassi, who lost, 6-3,
6-2, 6-4, in his own throne room of 1999, Ashe Stadium. Agassi had
also won the US title a few yards away in Armstrong Stadium, when
that was the coronation amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi, accorded the monarch's No. 1 seed at this, the last
major of the 2000 campaign, will not see the third round. Clement,
a so-so 22-year-old, a welterweight of 5 feet 8 inches, 140 pounds,
with a No. 39 ranking, has snatched his place.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lovelies lurked among the assembled fans had been
screaming for Agassi, however. They departed forlornly, not blowing
as much as one kiss in Arnaud's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was for him, of course,'' Clement says. ``So many
people there. Andre is a great player, but he wasn't great today.
He did too many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement stops talking and stands up. ``It is better this way,''
he says. He is cramping _ about 45 minutes too late to do Agassi
any good _ but continues, on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was unbelievable, my best victory,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi himself acknowledges the fantasizer was pretty fantastic
after Agassi had staked out an early 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never raised my level,'' says Agassi, who heard the thief
prowling for seven successive games (to 2-0 in the second) but
couldn't discourage or apprehend him. ``Give the guy credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Clement _ the name means mild or lenient in French _
was neither with Agassi. He bounded everywhere, hounding Agassi's
best blasts and somehow redirecting them to his opponent's
frustration, sometimes with backhands down the line that the former
champ couldn't return. Clement was especially unclement with his
improved serve, which grew big on big points for 24 freebies: a
dozen each of aces and handcuffers.
</P>
<P>
   Male reputations aren't mattering much at this US Very Open.
Four days are gone, and with them the champ of 1997-98, Patrick
Rafter; the French Open champ, Gustavo Kuerten; and now Agassi, a
certain Hall of Famer with six majors in his safe. Never has the
tournament been so decimated so early.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi launched the season brilliantly, knocking off two
champions, Pete Sampras and Yevgeny Kafelnikov, to capture the
Australian Open. But his African adventure in Zimbabwe shortly
thereafter started a downturn. In the Davis Cup there, the United
States took a 3-2 victory in which Agassi won both singles. But he
staggered off the court after barely beating Byron Black, exhausted
and dehydrated. He hasn't been the same since, winning no titles
and losing in the second round at the French Open to Karol Kucera
and the semifinals of Wimbledon to Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   He made no excuses, but his mental state can't be great as his
mother and a sister battle cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was focused, but I never found my quality,'' Agassi says.
</P>
<P>
   Clement, a free spirit _ ``something of a clown,'' says a friend
_ was up for the occasion. He'd come within two points of beating
Agassi in the second round of the 1999 French Open, Andre's magnum
opus for that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't notice any strain in Agassi,'' Clement says. ``I was
thinking about what I had to do.'' This is what makes the game:
Nobody is safe from being robbed when two guys go at each other.
Clement's fantasy of a grand caper was going to materialize. Even
though he came in with a 20-20 season record, he had the stealth
and the light-fingered manner Thursday to clean out Andre's room in
only 103 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As the burglar was leaving the scene of his crime, it seemed
Agassi might collar him. In a rousing farewell game that endured
for nine quivering minutes, Clement served his way to 40-15, but
four times Agassi fought off match point. Clement appeared frantic,
looking for the exit as the crowd roared for his blood.
</P>
<P>
   On the second match point, Clement banged an apparent ace, and
he rejoiced. Not so fast, said the umpire. The ball had touched the
tape. Let call. Agassi won the point. On the third match point,
Agassi socked a forehand winner. On the fourth, Clement served ``a
certain ace. The ball was on the line,'' he pleaded. Sorry. Fault
called. Agassi won that point. Deuce again.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was yelling, urging Agassi to pounce on the miscreant.
But Clement had his hands on what he wanted. He ripped a forehand
to earn the fifth match point. Now or never, he thought.
``Aaaaaaagh!'' he groaned, throwing himself into the concluding
serve, his most powerful, at 119 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi swatted it into the net, and the thief escaped through a
window of opportunity. Safe at last, he removed the sneakers, the
shades, revealing jubilant blue eyes. He took off his bandana,
letting swatches of auburn hair hang to his shoulders. It wasn't a
fantasy. He felt like a man who had broken the bank at Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   For the ripped-off Agassi, it was too late to call 911.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
