<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-PET-COMMUNICATION-DIS     09-01 1698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-COMMUNICATION-DISCOVER-$ADV29-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERESY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., Aug. 29, or anytime thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (Color art is available.) 
 By BRAD LEMLEY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Rupert Sheldrake gazes at the TV monitor. The videotape he is
showing as part of a public lecture at Cambridge University
portends, in his view, the shattering of modern biology.
 &HT;    It also features a cute dog.
 &HT;    On the right side of the split screen, the dog's owner, Pam
Smart, is shown gadding about the English village of Ramsbottom. On
the left side, her terrier-cross, Jaytee, who has remained at home,
lies at the feet of Pam's mother, Muriel.
 &HT;    Beneath each of these slow-moving dramas, synchronized videotape
counters confirm that the cameras tracking Jaytee and Pam show
simultaneous activity.
 &HT;    Suddenly, a researcher accompanying Pam tells her it's time to
leave. As Pam exits to get a ride home, Jaytee rises and trots to a
window. The voice-over states that the dog waited patiently there
for 15 minutes until his mistress walked in through the door.
 &HT;    The implication: Though Pam was several miles away, Jaytee
sensed, somehow, the moment she formed the intent to return home.
 &HT;    In itself, the Austrian tape proves nothing _ it could be
coincidence or a hoax. Indeed, that's the judgment of Richard
Wiseman, a British psychology researcher.
 &HT;    Wiseman and two colleagues ran four owner-anticipation
experiments with Jaytee and Pam and, in the August 1998 issue of
the British Journal of Psychiatry, they concluded: ``In all four
experiments Jaytee failed to accurately detect when (Smart) set off
to return home.''
 &HT;    Sheldrake says Wiseman's team arbitrarily established a two-
minute waiting period as the criterion for owner anticipation and
ignored the dog's behavior after the return signal.
 &HT;    ``Wiseman's own data shows the dog spent most of its time at the
window when Pam was on her way home,'' he argues.
 &HT;    Sheldrake has produced more than 200 similar tapes and found
three dogs that anticipate their owners' return 80 percent of the
time.
 &HT;    Controversy follows Sheldrake at every turn, and little wonder.
The existence of telepathy is just a subset of Sheldrake's larger
premises _ that invisible, but nonetheless pervasive ``morphic
fields'' are responsible for both the shape and behavior of all
things, from atoms to zebras, organizing them much as a magnetic
field lines up iron filings.
 &HT;    Just as controversial is Sheldrake's hypothesis that these
fields broadcast across time and space, a phenomenon he calls
morphic resonance. Result: A carrot seed grows into the shape of a
carrot because it is directed by the cumulative morphic resonance
of all previous carrots.
 &HT;    A million blind African termites build a complex 10-foot-tall
nest because they are guided by the morphic resonance of previous
termites.
 &HT;    A newspaper crossword puzzle is easier to solve late in the day,
because the morphic resonance broadcast by thousands of successful
solvers facilitates the task.
 &HT;    A dog anticipates its owner's return because the bond they forge
through close association is what Sheldrake terms a ``social''
morphic field, which stretches, but does not break, when they are
apart.
 &HT;    Humans, Sheldrake says, retain only vestiges of morphic-
resonance telepathy, possibly because telephones and mass media
make the ability less necessary for survival. In animals, he
contends, it remains robust.
 &HT;    Sheldrake's theories certainly seem to resonate with the public.
His fifth and latest book, ``Dogs That Know When Their Owners Are
Coming Home and Other Unexplained Powers of Animals,'' is a best
seller, with 75,000 hardcover copies sold in the United States
alone.
 &HT;    Moreover, Sheldrake has impressive academic credentials. A
former research fellow of the Royal Society, he was director of
studies in biochemistry and cell biology at Clare College at
Cambridge University and a Frank Knox Fellow at Harvard.
 &HT;    But these days, he is unaffiliated with any university and is
viewed as a pariah by many of his peers.
 &HT;    ``Morphic resonance is rubbish,'' says Lewis Wolpert, professor
of biology as applied to medicine at University College London.
``It is unmitigated junk, and a great insult to people who do real
work in the field.''
 &HT;    In spite of such scorn, Sheldrake soldiers on. Here at
Cambridge's Union Society Hall he is showing his videotape and
speaking about his theories to 75 students and faculty members as
part of the society's guest speakers program. His presentation
brings hearty applause. If Sheldrake is deluded, he ushers more
people into his fanciful realm every day.
 &HT;    Sheldrake has pushed the hypothesis of morphic resonance for 20
years and claims that his motivation is a too-rare reverence for
science as a vehicle for addressing deep, difficult questions.
 &HT;    ``My way of thinking about science is that major unsolved
problems are the most interesting things to work on,'' he says. ``I
have noticed that many of my colleagues take the opposite view:
that major, unsolved problems need to be denied, because
recognizing them would show that science is radically incomplete.''
 &HT;    The first fields to captivate Sheldrake were the meadows around
his childhood home in the idyllic Midlands market town of
Newark-on-Trent, where he collected a vast personal menagerie of
creatures, from rabbits to insects.
 &HT;    His father, an herbalist who lectured on plant sources of drugs
at Nottingham University, encouraged the boy to study and learn
from his charges. At ``quite an early age'' Sheldrake determined to
become a biologist himself.
 &HT;    He was dismayed, then, upon entering the biochemistry department
at Cambridge University.
 &HT;    ``The first thing we did when we decided to study a plant or
animal was kill it, then grind it up to extract the DNA and
enzymes. It was the ultimate irony _ to become a biologist because
you love animals, then spend a career torturing and killing them.''
 &HT;    Moreover, the approach struck Sheldrake as incomplete. ``The
idea that the whole truth could be found via reductionism,
examining the smallest particles, has never been proved. It's an
article of faith.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, at Cambridge Sheldrake spent seven years exploring
the biochemical basis for plant shape. But Sheldrake says that
after years of intensive study, biochemistry didn't solve the
problem of why things have the basic shape they do.
 &HT;    Frustrated, Sheldrake resigned his Cambridge fellowship and
worked for six years at an international agricultural institute at
Hyderabad in southern India, improving legume crop yields for
Indian subsistence farmers. It was there that he met Bede
Griffiths, an English Benedictine monk who lived in a Christian
ashram, and to whom Sheldrake dedicated his book ``A New Science of
Life.''
 &HT;    After more than 20 years as an atheist, Sheldrake rediscovered
the Christianity of his youth through Griffiths. He remains to this
day a frankly religious scientist, even producing spiritual-themed
books such as ``Natural Grace,'' co-authored with renegade
Episcopal priest Matthew Fox. Also while in India, he met Jill
Purce, a vocal therapist whom he married in 1985.
 &HT;    Today, Sheldrake, Purce and their 10- and 12-year-old sons live
in a comfortable town house across the street from Hampstead Heath,
the largest tract of wild land in London.
 &HT;    ``When I first saw him, he was giving a talk about his
theories,'' Purce says. ``Critics go to his speeches and fly for
him, but he retains the most extraordinary equanimity and
graciousness.''
 &HT;    A frequent critique of Sheldrake's work is that the fields he
posits seem to be undetectable _ his research doesn't indicate what
morphic fields or resonance actually are.
 &HT;    Sheldrake responds that the phenomena may spring from the
so-called quantum nonlocality that so fretted Einstein, who termed
it ``spooky action at a distance.''
 &HT;    Confirmed by experiments by French physicist Alain Aspect in
1982 and independently corroborated many times since, the
phenomenon is indeed unsettling: Two photons or electrons emitted
by the same atom remain somehow linked, even miles apart (and,
theoretically, on opposite sides of the universe), such that
measuring the polar orientation of one immediately determines the
orientation of the other.
 &HT;    Physicist Hans-Peter Durr of the Max Planck Institute in Munich
has argued that Sheldrake's theories are among the first to
reconcile 20th-century breakthroughs in physics _ which emphasize
the primacy of fields and the indivisible nature of matter _ with
biology, which for the most part remains rooted in 19th-century
Newtonian concepts of particles and separateness.
 &HT;    To Sheldrake, science is all about asking the rights questions
and performing the right experiments.
 &HT;    ``Arthur Eddington, the physicist, said if you drag a net with a
two-inch mesh through the sea, you will conclude there is no such
thing as a fish that is shorter than two inches,'' Sheldrake says.
``The kind of questions you ask determine the kind of answers you
get. The first step is to begin asking the right questions.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Brad Lemley is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
