<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, Sept. 1, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the weekend.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-GARAGE-PRICES (San Francisco) _ Once upon a time in San
Francisco, a $1 million house meant mansion on a hill. Nowadays,
that $1 million property can be a garage. It's so hard to find
parking in the city that folks are having the land under their
houses excavated to build a garage and paying oodles for it _
$100,00, $200,000, even a million bucks. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOME-PRICES (San Francisco) _ A limited supply of homes on
the market, along with sky-rocketing prices, has made San Francisco
the nation's least affordable city in which to buy a home,
according to a National Association of Home Builders survey
released this week. Only 5.9 percent of San Francisco households
with a median income of $74,900 can afford to buy the $510,000
median-priced home, according to the survey. By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-OLD-LETTER (Galveston, Texas) _ Dated Sept. 14, 1900,
the letter from Charles Rodewald Byrne to his wife Frances in
Baltimore, began with a plaintive question: ``Darling, Darling,
Darling, Where am I to begin to tell you this sad, sad story?''
Byrne wrote the letter six days after a ferocious hurricane hit
Galveston, taking at least 6,000 lives and destroying 3,600 houses.
It was and remains the nation's greatest natural disaster. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-BRIBES _ A defense lawyer has tried to pin the San
Francisco Housing Authority's bribery scandal on the government's
star witness. By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   OVERTIME-PAY (San Francisco) _ Despite years of promises from
San Francisco's government to curtail excessive employee overtime,
the city's overtime bill nearly doubled during the last four years
and is expected to keep growing. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIGBUSRIDE (Undated) _ Winnipeg to Tierra del Fuego doesn't
exactly sound like a trip from heaven, and it sounds even worse
when put this way: six people on a double-decker bus with no
running water, lights or restrooms. These twenty-somethings will
spend about nine months together, raising money for the
international relief organization, War Child. The only American on
the trip is Paul Strobl of Houston. By DANIEL VARGAS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ZELLWEGER (New York) _ The last time we talked to Renee
Zellweger, when she starred with Meryl Streep in ``One True
Thing,'' she had no new films planned, no real home to call her
own, a director boyfriend (Josh Pate) and an adored 10-year-old dog
named Dylan. In two years, Zellweger's world has turned
considerably. She's completed four pictures, including the latest,
``Nurse Betty.'' The fourth, ``Bridget Jones' Diary,'' due next
year, made her a favorite target of the British press, which felt a
Texas gal should not play the much-sought title role from the
English best seller. By LOUIS B. PARKS. (For release Sunday, Sept.
3)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRIMINAL-LOVERS (San Francisco) _ In ``Criminal Lovers,''
the ``Bonnie and Clyde'' model of killing-as-erotica gets a shrewd,
funny, decidedly French workout. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-OAXACA (San Francisco) _ The gender-equality situation must
be so dire in Mexico that when a haute-couture fashion rag like
Spanish Elle runs a sensational article on the sordid
``matriarchy'' in the town of Juchitan in Oaxaca state, Mexico, the
community gets defensive, filing a defamation suit. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-PAC-10 (San Francisco) _ The Pac-10 is fighting a losing
battle. Nobody seems to want to accept the notion that the league
always has been _ and always will be _ dumped on to varying
degrees. All that last season and the season before did was offer
up more morsels for the rest of the country to chew on in its
insistence that West Coast football is inferior. By MARK
FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   ROSE-BOWL (San Francisco) _ With six different teams
representing the Pac-10 in the Rose Bowl in the last six seasons,
handicapping the league has essentially become a guessing game.
Take your pick and you're bound to be wrong. Stanford showed up in
Pasadena last January for the first time in 28 years. Two seasons
earlier, Washington State ended a 67-year absence from the big
parade, and three years before that, Oregon materialized after a
37-year hiatus. By MARK FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDON-SCULLING (San Francisco) _ The doctor is in. Or make
that back in. Ruth Davidon, a surgical resident at Stanford, was
one of America's best hopes for a medal in the women's single
sculls at Atlanta in 1996, but, hampered by a fractured rib, she
finished sixth. And shortly after, she took her oars out of the
water. It looked as if her long rowing career might well be at an
end. But elite athletes don't give up easily. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ According to a spokeswoman for
the New York Times, the paper has gotten ``a couple of letters and
a couple of phone calls'' of complaint about a Perry Ellis ad that
ran in the Times Magazine fall fashion issue. A couple of letters
and calls? Let me tell you about this erotic, sick ad. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY-LEWIS-TELETHON (San Francisco) _ Over the Labor Day
weekend, the ``Jerry's Kids'' Telethon, the nation's most visible
disability event, will again hold its talent show to showcase the
``plight'' of disabled children and raise money to cure muscular
dystrophy. Unknown to most of Lewis' benefactors, this event is not
a rallying point for the disabled community. Not even for one who,
like myself, has severe muscular dystrophy. By STEVEN TINGUS.
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANT (Albany, N.Y.) _ As I write this, I am eight months
pregnant. And I am obsessed with shoes. Don't laugh. Or go ahead,
laugh all you like, but to me this is Serious Business. Or at least
Business That's Serious To Me Right Now But in a Month or Less Will
All Seem Shamefully Ridiculous. When one is eight months pregnant
one loses all perspective of one's priorities. One loses all
perspective of one's feet. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
</TEXT>
