<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-PREGNANT-HNS &LR;      09-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGNANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE MOTHER OF ALL SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As I write this, I am eight months pregnant. And
I am obsessed with shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. Or go ahead, laugh all you like, but to me this is
Very Serious Business. Or at least Serious Business. Or at least
Business That's Serious To Me Right Now But in a Month or Less Will
All Seem Shamefully Ridiculous. When one is eight months pregnant
one loses all perspective of one's priorities. One loses all
perspective of one's feet.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to shoes. Pregnant women do not normally shop
for clothes _ not real clothes, not clothes designed for anyone
other than bulbous human beings _ for the simple reason that it's
too depressing. Not only does nothing fit, nothing looks like it
will ever fit again _ not that fashionable pleat _ her skirt, not
that cutesy-wootsy tank top, not those flattering wee capri pants
that face it, chickee, you couldn't get away with anyway. Shopping
for clothes is bad news for the expecting mom.
</P>
<P>
   But shoes. Shoes are something else.
</P>
<P>
   This pregnancy is, for the record, my third; my previous two
produced ebullient girls. My belly was (is) equally ebullient _ out
there, baby, greeting the world with robustness and elan. I am not
one of those women who can hide their pregnancies. There is no
doubt when I have a second life form inside me. I stick out. I pop
out. I joke about having ``projectile pregnancies.'' Close friends,
total strangers _ everyone tells me how large I am (duh), as though
I'd been laboring under the tragic misconception that I look like
Gwyneth Paltrow. You must be ready to go!, they say. You must be
carrying twins! Triplets, even! You're just ... so ... HUGE!
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, I am. I know that. My feet know that. And
because my feet know that, the one luxury I have allowed myself
during each and every pregnancy has been comfortable shoes. First
time out I bought Rockports; second time out (a winter pregnancy),
a pair of insanely comfy light-duty hikers from L.L. Bean. For this
third go-around I faced a bigger challenge: I am older. I am less
flexible. And I can no longer, not without grunting and oofing and
asking for help from my husband, tie my own laces.
</P>
<P>
   I resolved, therefore, to buy cozy summer shoes with no laces,
no Velcro straps, no snaps or buckles that would require me to lean
over and actually touch my toes. My first purchase was a pair of
flexible leather clogs that would go well with a dress. My second
was a pair of blue-suede Bass flip-flops that, I figured, I could
wear with shorts or even get away with at work. (Pregnant woman are
allowed to wear anything that fits right and feels good. That's the
law.)
</P>
<P>
   But the third. The third was the coup de maitre, my podiatric
expression of eternal hope and joy. Mark my words: I will never,
ever make a more satisfying footwear purchase for the rest of my
shoe-shopping career. These two bundles of leather and latex are
the apex, the apogee, the Everest's summit of the cobbler's art.
After this, it's all downhill.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: Laceless running shoes. Pull-on laceless running shoes.
I first spotted a woman wearing them at the Kids' Day on the Empire
State Plaza a few weeks back, and I pounced. WHERE DID YOU BUY
THOSE SHOES? I asked, only yelling a little. After a moment or two
of startled hesitation (Who is this loud pregnant woman accosting
me by the Swing Ride?), she told me: Supermarket of Shoes,
Crossgates Mall. They were made by Skechers. And I needed them.
Badly.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, I wore my new blue footgear into work
(reference ``The law'') and showed them off with pride. ``Look!
Look at my sneakers! Look!'' I demanded, realizing too late that I
hadn't used those particular words in that particular order since
my parents bought me Super Keds in seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   But it's OK: My elation in discovering this latest
sneako-technological breakthrough is unequivocal, unbound by social
expectations or the suspicion that I'm making a complete and utter
idiot of myself. Outwardly I realize that the product-development
gurus at Skechers (and Nike, which has also come out with laceless
shoes) did not design them with me mind, but secretly I'm convinced
that they did. They had to. For what but some grand karmic purpose
were these spiffy little foot-protectors released to the world at
the precise time I entered my late third trimester _ at the very
moment that I stopped being able to tie my own shoes?
</P>
<P>
   Don't answer that. I don't need to know what you think. I just
need to revel in the form-fitting comfort and funky design of my
brand-new Skechers. I need to prop up my feet and regard them with
peace and contentment and the quiet pride of a conquering shopper.
I need to feel happy about my shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But I need to sit while I do it, because I can't quite see them
when I stand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
biancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
