<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PERRY ELLIS' CRASS ADS HAVE NO STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ According to a spokeswoman for the New York
Times, the newspaper has gotten ``a couple of letters and a couple
of phone calls'' of complaint about a Perry Ellis ad that ran in
the Times Magazine fall fashion issue.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of letters and calls?
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you about this ad.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many designer rag pitches these days, the four-page
Ellis spread offers a stylized photo-Rorschach test. Not enough to
merely grab eyeballs with color and lines, the two double-page
vignettes beg us to wonder, ``What is going on here?''
</P>
<P>
   Both ``stories'' are set in what appears to be a large shower or
possibly a public restroom. The vibrant green of the ceramic tiles
is repeated in generously applied eye shadow on both models.
</P>
<P>
   In the first ad an alarmingly pale woman, who looks young enough
to be a teen-ager, is slumped in a corner _ half-sitting,
half-lying. Her large, heavily rouged mouth hangs slack. Her
green-rimmed eyes stare lifelessly at the camera. She could be in a
drug-induced stupor, exhausted or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Straddling her, and grasping the belt of her houndstooth tweed
coat in his right hand, is a naked man. Or at least a man who has
no clothes on as far as we can see, which is just below his hipbone
and to the shoulder of his visible arm.
</P>
<P>
   His tanned, hairy legs are a stark contrast to the bloodless
white of the model's bare thighs. Her only other item of clothing:
black knee-high leather boots.
</P>
<P>
   In the second ad, a model equally pale, wearing the same makeup,
is flat on her back, staring _ again, lifelessly _ at the ceiling.
She wears a sleeveless black dress. Her arms lie on the floor above
her head, almost crossed at the wrists.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the naked man is in a semi-crouch, as if he is about
to lower himself onto the woman. His legs and hips are near her
head. His face, of which we see only a shadowy portion, looms above
her belly.
</P>
<P>
   The only copy on either photo is ``Perry Ellis.''
</P>
<P>
   Because I am 50 years old and came of age when millions of
American women were waking up to the very real, very dangerous
realities of female sexual objectification, I decided to show the
ads to two dozen other women. They range in age from 17 to 60.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reaction was, ``Oh, my God,'' accompanied by a
look of disbelief and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Some other responses:
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me want to vomit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's supposed to be erotic, it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she dead? Is she a heroin addict? Has she been raped? Is
she about to be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a clip from a snuff film.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I'm pretty lenient, but this is definitely
offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gross.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is scary. The woman is totally vulnerable, and there's
nothing gentle about the man. This totally degrades women.''
</P>
<P>
   The only positive comment came from an artist in her 20s, who
said, ``The model is very good at being vacant.''
</P>
<P>
   I checked out Perry Ellis' slick Web site to see if anyone is
taking credit for this ad campaign. No one is. (The site displayed
variations on the ads that ran in the Times Magazine, but not the
specific photos I have described here.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to add this column and the quotes of the women I
checked with to the handful of protests the Times received. I would
also like to ask any woman (or man) who's seen the ads and was
offended by them to complain to the Times or any publication that
runs them.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old who said, ``This totally degrades women,'' was
more than a decade from being born when I was sitting in feminist
consciousness-raising sessions.
</P>
<P>
   In those sessions, young women who'd been raised to accept
sexual discrimination and objectification as the female's lot
helped each other see the misogyny, exploitation and violence that
seeped out of all kinds of mainstream literature, art, film and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   We learned, together, to listen to our gut, that deep, knowing
part of every woman and girl that says, ``This is not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't care what Perry Ellis meant to convey with its latest ad
campaign. I don't care if some feted advertising genius insists
that it's ``cutting edge.'' I don't even care if it turns out that
the entire creative team responsible is female.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes being hipper-than-thou can blind a person to her own
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Ellis' dead-chicks-on-green-tile is not OK. And it's
incumbent on those of us who recognize it to say so _ to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   As www.perryellis.com declares: ``After all, we're not just
helping consumers choose the clothes they wear. We're designing
lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
