<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-JERRY-LEWIS-TELETHON-     09-01 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERRY-LEWIS-TELETHON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JERRY'S TELETHON BROADCASTS THE WRONG MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVEN TINGUS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Labor Day weekend, the ``Jerry's Kids''
Telethon, the nation's most visible disability event, will again
hold its talent show to showcase the ``plight'' of disabled
children and raise money to cure muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to most of Lewis' benefactors, this event is not a
rallying point for the disabled community. Not even for one who,
like myself, has severe muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   The net benefits of his fund-raising for medical research are
dwarfed by the overall damage done to the struggle for independence
and respect by people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The message behind Lewis' marketing is clear: You should feel
sorry for these kids.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis smiles awkwardly beside young and otherwise attractive
children whose natural beauty is interrupted by the heavy,
robotic-looking medical accessories that confine their little
bodies. The kids, perhaps for the first time ever, get social
recognition. Good for them, the viewer thinks. Jerry has given
their lives real meaning.
</P>
<P>
   For another year, disability is again horrific and demeaning in
the minds of everyday Americans. The telethon drives public
perception of physical limitations as pitiful.
</P>
<P>
   The message for disabled youth is even more damaging. They come
to perceive of themselves as charity cases in the literal sense.
This is devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking of oneself as incomplete or, even worse, as broken,
serves no purpose but to internalize the inadequacy society
regularly ascribes to us.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the images of the telethon are in sharp contrast to the
real lives of people with disabilities who have reached
independence, raised families and gone on to hold jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Successful people with disabilities don't perceive of themselves
as inadequate or inferior. They recognize their disabilities as the
only reality they'll know. They reject the dichotomous comparison
with the able-bodied in which they always come up short.
</P>
<P>
   Although they certainly have greater physical challenges to
overcome, they discover authenticity in them, not embarrassment or
shame.
</P>
<P>
   The National Council on Disability notes that the public's
perception is overwhelmingly negative toward disability and issues
such as the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA).
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because people with disabilities aren't as active as they
should be due to a host of social and policy barriers to their
participation.
</P>
<P>
   The able-bodied can play a major role in seeing that today's
essential disability reforms are put into place so that inclusion
and independence are no longer a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   By lending their talents to support issues like access,
assistive technology or employment reforms, the able-bodied can
participate in a philanthropy that is free.
</P>
<P>
   This non-charity will unlock the door for millions who can't
wait to get out of institutions and backrooms so they can share in
America's prosperity. By supporting the Independent Living movement
directly, those unfamiliar with disability can tear down the walls.
</P>
<P>
   They can support the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act
of 2000 (S 2341) to ensure that local kids with disabilities have
access to public education _ something they've only enjoyed since
1973.
</P>
<P>
   They can write their representative to Congress to oppose the
``ADA Notification Act'' (HR 3590), a bill that will dilute ADA
enforcement by essentially allowing businesses to wait until they
are sued before making facilities accessible.
</P>
<P>
   They can also voice their support for technology needs
assessment as part of the Individual Education Plans required by
local school districts. This way, students with disabilities can
get the technology they need to learn.
</P>
<P>
   These activities have a unified goal: giving people with
disabilities the tools they need to work and live on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Telethons have never empowered individual achievement among the
disabled. Not when a paraplegic man scaled El Capitan last year,
nor when John Hockenberry, who uses a wheelchair, rose to the ranks
of top national news reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The great achievements of people with disabilities throughout
history have been individual: Franklin Delano Roosevelt's long
tenure as president, James Joyce's quintessential modern novels or
the impressionist paintings of Monet and Van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for most Americans, disability still conjures images of
Jerry Lewis and his kids, rather than the real social obstacles
that prevent independence for the disabled. That the most visible
disability event in the nation has nothing to do with empowerment
is a sign of how far we have to go.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Tingus is the public policy director for the California
Foundation for Independent Living Centers. Born with a rare form of
muscular dystrophy, Tingus holds a doctoral degree in physiology
from the University of California at Davis.)
</P>
