<HEADER>
A8373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      09-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORTS LAUNCHED TO AID, EDUCATE AFGHAN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As American schoolgirls and college women go back
to classes this fall, nearly all their counterparts halfway around
the world in Afghanistan are staying home, their education
forbidden by the ruling Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan women's plight outrages Jesse Mostipak, who started
her sophomore year at Brandeis University this week. She has joined
a national ``back to school'' campaign for Afghan girls in hopes of
raising money for underground schools and increasing international
pressure on the fundamentalist Islamic government to lift
repressive gender-based rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I learned about how the Taliban treats women, I couldn't
believe something like this was going on today,'' said Mostipak,
18, whose family lives in Buffalo. ``It's humiliating and
degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   The Feminist Majority Foundation is looking for thousands of
people who share Mostipak's views, launching an adopt-a-school
project, a scholarship program, and a new petition drive urging the
US government to increase efforts on behalf of Afghan women.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is hoping that US schools will donate money for
the underground schools for girls _ $60 buys supplies for 300
students, $36 pays a teacher's monthly salary _ and that US
colleges and universities will set up scholarships for Afghan women
that include tuition and room and board.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, which controls 90 percent of Afghanistan, has
prevented almost all girls and women from attending schools or
working in jobs and requires that all women wear a veil, called the
burqa, that covers the face and body. In scattered Muslim schools,
young girls attend segregated classes, and in some isolated
villages the local power broker has allowed girls to attend school.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Taliban in New York cited the religious
schools and said the Feminist Majority was engaging in propaganda.
``They are playing politics,'' said Noorullah Zadran. ``They have
not visited Afghanistan for 40 years. And what about the collection
of the money? They raised $16 million in California through Jay
Leno's wife, and not one cent has gone to Afghan schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke,'' said Julie Bernstein, a spokeswoman for
Feminist Majority, who said the organization has raised $140,000
over the past two years toward Afghan school projects. ``And the
few girls allowed to attend school are 7 or 8 years old, and
they're only learning to memorize the Koran.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, which grew out of fundamentalist Islamic
universities in Afghanistan and Pakistan, forbids girls and women
to learn a variety of subjects based on its interpretation of the
Koran, an interpretation that nearly all Islamic scholars disavow.
Of Afghanistan's 25 million people, 12.5 million are women, and of
that 5.3 million are girls under age 14.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said Thursday that past campaigns by
the Feminist Majority for Afghan women have produced as much or
more mail than any other foreign policy issue has. The group
delivered several boxes last week to the State Department that
contained 211,000 petitions, demanding more US pressure on the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, noted tht
while ``all international pressure is useful to keep the Taliban's
feet to the fire,'' international charities and diplomats were
often in disagreement about how to impose that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some do not think it's wise to get into direct confrontations
with the Taliban because it could force them to show how pure they
can be in following Islam,'' the US official said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright has been among the
fiercest critics of the Taliban's treatment of women, calling it
``medieval.'' US aid for Afghan citizens has increased to $110
million, up from $70 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Eleanor Smeal, president of Feminist Majority, said it was
nowhere near enough. ``There is a massive need for aid,'' she said.
Leading the Afghan project is Mavis Leno, the wife of the talk show
host.
</P>
<P>
   Smeal said her organization almost entirely focuses on US
issues, including abortion rights and domestic violence, but it
decided to take on the Afghan project because the ``magnitude of
the problem is so great. This is the worst example of misogyny ever
in recorded history.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to her from a 22-year-old Afghan refugee,
the young woman wrote: ``We do not have a future. I know I have
very bad destiny. I cannot go to school. I do not have a job. I
cannot take care of my old mother. I cannot take it any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why God made me a woman?''
</P>
<P>
   The last line, Smeal said, ``just cut into me.'' She showed it
to President Clinton, who, she said, suggested that the group start
a scholarship program for women like the refugee.
</P>
<P>
   The first seven Afghan women have arrived for courses this fall.
The group doesn't include the letter-writer, and Smeal acknowledged
that it's a small step. But for one of the seven, it has meant new
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine being a teacher in a country where it is a crime to
teach girls to count,'' said Frayba Wakili, a refugee who began
classes this week at the University of Maryland. ``Imagine living
in a country where a child could be killed for learning the
alphabet and opening a book. Imagine being beaten for organizing an
underground library that distributes books to girls. This is
happening in Afghanistan every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation will send donations to private charities that
already work with underground schools for girls. With great
secrecy, such charities will be able to facilitate exchanges of
photographs and letters between Afghan and US schools, Smeal said.
She wouldn't name the charities.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the foundation's Afghan campaign, see
its Web site, www.feminist.org, and click on ``Stop Gender
Apartheid.'' For more information on the Taliban's position, see
its Web site, www.taleban.com, and click on the heading ``News,''
under which there is a rebuttal to the foundation's program.
</P>
<P>
   Mostipak, the Brandeis student, hopes to begin fund-raising
soon, launch a petition drive and urge her university's leadership
to offer scholarships for Afghan women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandeis was formed with a mission for social justice, so
there's a lot of support,'' she said. ``What outrages me the most
is that women were treated fairly equitably over there, and then,
overnight, the Taliban stripped away every right they had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
