<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      09-01 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING UP THE STICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's only so much fishing, diving, and lazing around that one
person can do in Hawaii, right? ``What was happening was that I was
getting bored, but I wasn't being honest about it,'' admits Bill
Kreutzmann, the Grateful Dead drummer who had retired to Hawaii and
hadn't toured since Jerry Garcia died five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kreutzmann is back on the road with the Other Ones _ the
post-Dead band that includes fellow Dead alums Bob Weir, Mickey
Hart, and Bruce Hornsby. The group is already off to a great start
after Bonnie Raitt joined them recently for a few songs in San
Francisco and Steve Winwood sang ``Dear Mr. Fantasy'' with them in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adventure again _ and that's what we've been looking
for,'' says Weir.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an exhilarating feeling that all the Deadheads
want to feel,'' adds Hornsby. ``That feeling didn't happen that
often in the last years of the Dead because of various problems,
including burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the main story of this band now is Bill Kreutzmann, who
had to get it all back together and he's done that,'' says Hornsby.
``His attitude is great and he's playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heaven. It's like a piece that's been missing,'' says
percussionist Hart, who is once again teaming with Kreutzmann
during mid-show ``drums and space'' segments. ``I remember the day
that Bill said he was hanging up his sticks _ and my heart just
stopped. But I always hoped he'd come back. We're tied at the hip.
When he returned, it was just like getting back on a bicycle. We
locked instantly. We didn't miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the new guy,'' says a chuckling Kreutzmann, who surprised
his mates by showing up unannounced at an audition for drummers for
the tour. ``I passed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the rhythm is good, life is good,'' says Hart. ``And to
see this form out of the ashes (of the Dead) is great. The spirit
is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones, with a different lineup, toured two years ago.
Dead bassist Phil Lesh was in that group, but has since left to
form his traveling collective, Phil Lesh &AMP; Friends. Lesh and the
remaining Dead survivors have exhanged some shots in the press _
and the friction still hasn't subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big void after Garcia (died), and Phil tried to
slip in as the ultimate ruler,'' says Hart. All agree, however,
that Lesh is ``irreplaceable,'' though new bassist Alphonso Johnson
(ex-Weather Report) has been filling in beautifully, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't hate anybody. I worked with Phil for 30 years and I
love the guy. He turned me on to Coltrane when I was 17,'' says
Kreutzmann, adding, ``I hope that Phil finds his musical happiness
in whatever he wants to do. He wants to do it his way, but this
band is about doing it the music's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kreutzmann, ever the peacemaker, says, ``It's very
refreshing to play with a new bassist, as it must be for Lesh to
play with a new drummer!''
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones have rehearsed as many as 80 songs, says Weir,
enabling them, just like the Grateful Dead, to not repeat any songs
in subsequent nights. However, the group's jams _ and expect a lot
of them this time _ have centered on a rejiggered 6/8 rhythm on the
song ``The Other One,'' and on the recurrent musical themes of
``Dark Star'' and ``Bird Song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really enjoying playing with Alphonso,'' says Hornsby.
``He's very versatile and we've been able to create new harmonic
areas, new chord sequences in the jams. We miss Phil _ Phil had
perfect pitch _ but Alphonso has been a joy.''
</P>
<P>
   And filling Garcia's shoes again is the twin-guitar lineup of
Steve Kimock and Mark Karan. ``One is a raunch king (Karan), the
other is more ethereal,'' says Kreutzmann. ``But they're sorting
themselves out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Other Ones are playing a lot of well-known and obscure Dead
tunes _ and even did an acoustic version of ``Deal'' recently. And
several new songs _ with lyrics by longtime Dead songwriter Robert
Hunter _ will be added shortly, possibly one or two by the Boston
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't be the last tour by this band. We're enjoying it
too much,'' says Hart. ``We might even tour again in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleetwood Mac legend returns: Eric Clapton may have been
nicknamed ``God'' in the '60s, but guitarist Peter Green wasn't far
behind. Green played in John Mayall's Bluesbreakers (as did
Clapton) and also in Fleetwood Mac, back when the Mac was a
blues-rock powerhouse that scorched the Boston Tea Party club a few
times. The Mac boasted a three-guitar lineup that was unmatched for
explosiveness, especially when Green cranked up the volume.
</P>
<P>
   Green later became a celebrated dropout, turning his back on
music to become a gravedigger in England for a while. ``I was
trying to make an LSD vision come true,'' he says of that era. Or
as his guitar-playing partner of today, Nigel Watson, recalls,
``Pete had a long holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and Watson (who joined Fleetwood Mac in 1971 when Spencer
left the group) just released an engaging album, ``Hot Foot
Powder,'' filled with mostly acoustic, but some electric, versions
of Robert Johnson songs. ``We tried to take the songs and stretch
them a little for a wider audience,'' says Watson, noting that the
CD also features such guests as Dr. John, Otis Rush, Hubert Sumlin,
and Honeyboy Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Blues history is about to be made when Green and Watson, in a
long-awaited Boston visit, share a bill at the Roxy on Wednesday
with fellow English royals, John Mayall &AMP; the Bluesbreakers. They
just did a 30-date overseas tour, and it was a smash.
</P>
<P>
   Green no longer goes for in-your-face volume, but rather a
``devotion to simplicity'' in his playing, he says. For blues fans,
seeing Green back in Boston should be a genuine treat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
