<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OPEN HOUSE' FEELS COZY DESPITE THE CLICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
OPEN HOUSE 
By Elizabeth Berg 
Random House. 256 pp. $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you realize that the person at the center of your world
doesn't love you anymore, what then? It's a familiar story, told a
thousand ways. Some versions are despairing, some inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   In Elizabeth Berg's ``Open House,'' we have Samantha, a 40-ish
housewife and mother, living with David, her cold, overprivileged
WASP husband, and Travis, their adorable 11-year-old son, in an
unnamed Boston suburb. Things are fine, or at least bearable, until
one day she realizes that they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   `` `David?' I said. He looked up. I said, `You know, you're
right in saying we have some serious problems. But there are so
many reasons to try to work things out.' I hoped my voice was
pleasant and light. I hoped my hair wasn't sticking up or that my
nose didn't look too big and that I didn't look fat when I sat up
to adjust the pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy this somewhat unsurprising, cliche-heavy story about
how Sam puts her life back together after painful separations from
both husband and son, it helps to overlook the obvious and
concentrate instead on the humor. Thankfully, Samantha, who goes by
Sam, has a sense of humor. Her first steps as a soon-to-be-divorced
mom are awkward and painful and amusing by turns, sometimes all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   First, she goes on a wild spending spree with her estranged
husband's checkbook. Though it's not a very original way to cope
with her shock and anger, we are soon swept up by the
outrageousness of how far she takes it: straight to Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man shows me the figures for the cost of the silver and
the china. With the cost of the bracelet, my total will be over
twelve thousand dollars. Twelve thousand! The number zips a finger
up my spine, thrills me deeply in a way that reminds me of sex.
From what I can recall.''
</P>
<P>
   Things really liven up when Sam decides to get a roommate to
help defray the mortgage payments on the house. She starts with the
elderly mother of a cashier at her favorite grocery store. When
that nice lady moves in, Travis gets upset because she snores, and
he threatens to move out and live with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Well, what, Travis? What's the big deal? So she snores.'
`She woke me up! I have to go to school tomorrow! I have to get a
good night's sleep!' I refrain from commenting on this new interest
in academic repsonsibilities, say instead, `Tomorrow's Sunday,
Travis.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her coping strategies continue. Sam tries to win David back;
later, she and her best friend scan the personals. Sam finds paid
employment in the form of temporary jobs. The jobs have no serious
connection to her life, but they boost her confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Other scenes are a bit predictable, including Sam's first
Thanksgiving alone, arguments with her mother and her best friend
as Sam begins to live more on her own terms, and one disastrous
blind date.
</P>
<P>
   What lifts Sam out of her despair over losing David are her
relationships with other people. She gains a new understanding of
her mother and son, finds new friends and a new love interest.
These are the more entertaining passages of this ultimately
uplifting story. If they fail to offer an intellectual challenge,
they fit Sam's character.
</P>
<P>
   Her new friendship with a man named King, an MIT graduate who
likes to take life one day at a time, literally, is an example: ``
`What are you doing with all these dogs, anyway?' I asked when we
stopped in a park to rest. And he told me walking dogs was his job
for the day, he took jobs by the day. Yesterday he'd handed out
samples of cheese at a supermarket. Smoked gouda. Very good. `I
see,' I said. I didn't really see. I think what he does is pretty
nutty. But I like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg finds humor even in the serious moments between Sam and her
husband, and between her and her son. As Sam tries to help her son
make sense of what's happening to their family, she struggles with
what she wants to say to him, versus what she should say:
</P>
<P>
   `` `We both love you very much, and we will both continue to be
your parents. It's just that Dad and I can't live together any
more.' `Why?' `Well. . .' Sometimes people, even when they really
love each other, they kind of grow apart. . . `Because your father
is a very, very selfish person who thinks only of himself. Always
has, always will. He deserted me, Travis, just like that. . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a novel that sets out to challenge our ideas about
love and belonging. It does explore the tension that exists for
many of us, especially many women, when the need to please other
people comes up against the need for self-realization.
</P>
<P>
   If you can ignore some of the obvious plot devices for the sake
of the big-hearted, hopeful outlook of Sam and her interesting
array of friends, reading ``Open House'' is like receiving a warm
embrace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
