<HEADLINE>
$ADV06 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, Sept. 6, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again seeking substance where others go for sensationalism,
ABC News' ``Nightline'' will spend three consecutive nights
(beginning tonight at 11:35 p.m.) trying to explain hip-hop music,
style and culture. With its huge sales and rebellious attitudes,
hip-hop is perhaps the leading influence on today's kids,
especially teen-age boys. Host Ted Koppel and correspondent Robert
Krulwich will look at the upside as well as the down, with
in-studio discussion and profiles of DJ Grandmaster Flash,
entrepreneur Russell Simmons, rapper Jay Z and 22-year-old clothing
designer Kevin Leong.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Another house mouse is nominated for
banishment. Julie Chen continues her determined effort to destroy
her journalism career. And Dr. Drew Pinsky offers more fatuous
insights. This show is a three-month-long slow-motion car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline,'' NBC at 8: Maria Shriver has a chat with Minnesota
Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill,'' Fox at 8: Bobby goes overboard with
pranks. Guest voices include Matthew McConaughey. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Fatal Shore,'' PBS 9-11: With the Sydney Olympics
just over a week away, a lot of shows will take a look at
Australian culture. Among the best is ``Beyond the Fatal Shore,'' a
six-part documentary by Time magazine art critic Robert Hughes.
Hughes wrote the bestselling history ``The Fatal Shore,'' and
brings his native land to life here. Hours three and four include a
look at class issues in the allegedly classless society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew Carey Show,'' ABC at 9: Speedy takes a dislike to Kate.
Ryan Stiles (Lewis) also directs. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing,'' NBC at 9: Marlee Matlin guests as a pollster, as
the president (Martin Sheen) awaits his favorability rating and Sam
(played by former tabloid bad boy Rob Lowe) is photographed giving
a gift to a call girl. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC at 10: In an episode cleverly titled
``Untitled,'' a sick murder leads the detectives into the
modern-art world. And I think we can guess how Detective Lenny
Briscoe (Jerry Orbach) feels about that. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7,'' ABC at 10: Documentary series looks deeply
into hospital life. Part three of six.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Living Edens,'' some PBS stations at 8: Before the grown-ups
watch ``Beyond the Fatal Shore,'' the whole family can gather
'round this pre-Olympic look at the wonders and dangers (saltwater
crocodiles, for starters) of Australia's Kakadu National Park.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis, USA at 7:30: Live from Flushing, N.Y. CBS airs
a wrap-up show at 12:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' VH1 at 9, followed at 11 by a ``Where
Are They Now?'' edition devoted to the entirely fictional heavy
metal band: The 1984 mockumentary led some of our finest comic
minds _ Harry Shearer, Christopher Guest, Michael McKean, Rob
Reiner and more _ into a scarily dead-on parody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO at 9: Charlotte gets engaged, and Mr.
Big is back in the picture for Carrie. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corner,'' HBO at 11: HBO begins a repeat of its acclaimed
limited-run series ``The Corner,'' directed by Charles S. Dutton
and based on a book by David Simon of ``Homicide.'' Khandi
Alexander, T.K. Carter and Sean Nelson star in this unflinching
look at drugs' effects on a Baltimore family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Jamie Foxx and
musician Ben Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Howie Mandel and
musician Rickie Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
Debra J. Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05: William
Shatner. Rerun. (Note time after tennis update.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Al Franken and
Rolling Stone's Jann Wenner.
</P>
