<HEADLINE>
HARDWARE FIRMS RIDE BIOTECH WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a stock market full of companies bursting with the kind
of high-tech promise that might change people's lives but scant
sales to show and no profits to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   We might be talking about the Internet stock bubble, as an
extraordinary episode in the recent past. But we could just as
easily be talking about the biotech investing frenzy going on right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Many biotech companies ``have the type of risk profile of public
venture capital,'' says Linda Miller, manager of the $500 million
John Hancock Health Science fund. ``You'd better be assuming
valuations that leave you venture capital rates of return.'' Sound
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Internet investors discovered most of their enduring gains were
made not with the scores of high-concept start-ups but with those
established companies whose equipment was needed to turn the
promise of the Web into reality. Will history repeat itself?
</P>
<P>
   The ``pick and shovel'' companies of the Internet include big
players such as Cisco Systems Inc. and EMC Corp., whose routers and
storage equipment build a virtual world for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable players in the biotech market are instrument
companies whose equipment is used by pharmaceutical giants, biotech
companies, and government sponsored labs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies have ridden the biotech hardware wave like Waters
Corp., a Milford, Mass. company that went public with a modest
stock offering five years ago and zoomed to a market value crossing
$10 billion for the first time last week.
</P>
<P>
   Waters shares increased a staggering twentyfold since their IPO
in 1995, but have staged some of their biggest dollar gains of all
this year with a 200 percent advance.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Waters or any other instrument company will
become the next Cisco. We can envision a world with almost endless
demand for computer data routers as the global Internet continues
to expand. The same cannot be said for the mass spectrometers and
other pieces of equipment used by drug and biotech researchers.
</P>
<P>
   But instrument companies such as Waters and the larger PE
Biosystems Group of Norwalk, Conn., do benefit from the biotech
boom. They may not hold the same kind of blockbuster business
potential of their customers. But they have established businesses,
solid track records for profits, and much less risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``These instrument companies are in some ways part of the fuel
to the (biotech) revolution,'' said Kristen Tongberg, a medical
equipment analyst at MFS Investment Management in Boston. ``They
feed the pace at which research can be done and enable a larger
amount of research.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Waters, though cautious about forecasting the
future for their business, don't discourage comparison with
Internet gear companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waters provides tools to the pharmaceutical life science
industry just like Cisco provides tools to the Internet,'' said
Brian Mazar, a senior vice president. He points to the company's
steady 25 percent earnings growth since it went public.
</P>
<P>
   Tell Mazar that Waters stock is expensive and he responds that
it would have seemed that way two years ago, at a fraction of its
current price. Some others don't seem to be persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly a value,'' said John Borzilleri, a health
care analyst at State Street Management and Research. He said
Waters stock ``was a value play six months ago, but not now.''
Those shares finished Thursday at $79.56, or nearly 70 times
expected 2000 profits.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the question revolves around assumptions about future
business growth. Tongberg, the MFS analyst, believes Waters could
grow revenues 20 to 25 percent a year over the next decade, but it
might happen in surges and lulls.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 cents of every current sales dollar at Waters comes
from ``life science'' customers such as drug and biotech customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's longstanding bread-and-butter business, selling
High Performance Liquid Chromatography instruments, still accounts
for two of every three sales dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the most rapid and closely watched sales growth involves the
company's mass spectrometry instruments used in the fast growing
field of proteomics.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say proteomics, identifying proteins in cells, could
supply information needed for more practical medical products than
gene-sequencing genomics. Complex proteins command bodily functions
and the vast majority of all drugs work by interacting with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing belief that proteomics can be bigger than
genomics,'' said Mazar. ``Proteomics should tell you a lot more
about disease states than genomics.''
</P>
<P>
   Basic mass spectrometry instruments may run $150,000, but a
complete system involving sophsticated computer hardware and
software, capable of analyzing thousands of proteins in a blood or
tissue sample, can cost nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers spend about $100 million a year on instruments used
in proteomics, but some aggressive estimates believe that figure
could grow to $1 billion. Waters is not alone in that field, but
counts itself among a group of leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Who will produce the breakthrough biotech products of the future
remains an investor's crap shoot, but every competitor will need to
buy the equipment to try.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
