<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PSYCHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD, CLEAN `PSYCHO' FUN AT THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
PSYCHO BEACH PARTY 
Directed by: Robert Lee King 
Screenplay by: Charles Busch (based on his play) 
Starring: Lauren Ambrose, Thomas Gibson, Nicholas Brendon, Kimberly
Davies, Matt Keeslar, Beth Broderick, Danni Wheeler, Busch 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Psycho Beach Party,'' Norman Bates meets Gidget. It's a
cheeky little pop tart that somehow does campy, cockeyed, cartoony
justice to both of its sources and will leave you smiling at its
genial outrageousness. One doesn't think of Alfred Hitchcock as a
sand-in-his shoes type, but the big kahuna of suspense is given
some mischievous spin here, while Sandra Dee's squeaky-clean Gidget
is stood on her golden pony-tailed head. Lauren Ambrose's surfer
girl, Chicklet, is a beach party hoot when ``Vertigo''-like circles
hypnotize her into a couple of multiple personalities with attitude
and a very possibly lethal mean streak.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latter that appeals to Thomas Gibson's surfing dude,
Kanaka. He's perpetually ready to forgo his surfboard if it means
he can be on the receiving end of some S &AMP; M, but then much of the
appeal of ``Psycho Beach Party'' lies in its subversion of movie
icons. The muscled, mindless surfers, for instance, are too dumb to
notice that they're homosexual, and that one reason they're against
having girls join their gang is that females would be utterly
superfluous. Charles Busch, who wrote the stage play on which the
film is based (it's been running for years in San Francisco), knows
his way around gay icons and juggles them smartly.
</P>
<P>
   Busch himself plays a very butch cop investigating the ongoing
killings about which Chicklet, schizophrenic tomboy that she is,
may know more than she realizes. Moms come in for more than a bit
of ribbing. The straighter they are, the more Busch twists the
knife. He's aided no end by the timing of Beth Broderick as
Chicklet's conventional mom, and Kimberley Davies as the B-movie
queen renting a haunted beach house to escape the rigors of filming
such items as ``Tarantula Queen of Hoboken.'' In fact, the women
have it all over the surfing dudes when it comes to sheer
over-the-topness, although Matt Keeslar's Swedish exchange student
doesn't go down without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   From its blatantly back-projected waves to its drive-in
cheesiness to its climactic oceanside luau, ``Psycho Beach Party''
is more light-handed than its caricaturing of various beach-blanket
bimbos makes immediately apparent. Robert Lee King's direction
offers noticeably less wattage than Busch's savvier, more sharply
focused writing. Still, ``Psycho Beach Party'' aims to win you over
rather than bowl you over, and it succeeds with flamboyant aplomb.
At many points, the film's fun and games with the demon butcher of
Malibu Beach are more entertaining than the stuff it's parodying.
Annette and Frankie never had it so bad. Or ever realized that mere
surf could be so thick with sexual subtexts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-STRIKE-ART-B     09-01 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-STRIKE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 STRIKE HIGHLIGHTS GULF BETWEEN PROFESSIONAL, BLUE-COLLAR FUTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ While an estimated 200 Raytheon Co. strikers
rallied on Lexington Green Thursday, Charlene Palmer stood among
them, holding a cigarette, a sign, and a lot of anger.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old tester and trouble-shooter, a member of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 1505, views
the strike that caused 2,700 members to take to the streets Sunday
as an all-out push to save her union's dwindling ranks and add more
top-of-the-line manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Palmer's eyes, white-collar employment at Raytheon has
surged, but there seems to be less need for veteran plant people
like herself. ``We were the ones who worked around the clock,'' she
said bitterly. ``We were the ones who built this company. Our
generation of workers was taught about quality of work. Now, we've
got a lot of managers that don't even know what they're building. .
. . All these new people want is a quick dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokesman David Polk denied that the company values its
longtime manufacturing workers less, but stressed that the industry
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an increase in the need for software and chip
technology and a corresponding decline in hardware,'' he said.
``That is why we need more engineers, particularly software
engineers and the like.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that factor, corporate America's increased reliance on
white-collar engineering, technical and service staff, and a
corresponding push to subcontract manufacturing jobs or move them
to lower-cost states or countries, that has unions like Local 1505
up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   For these workers, as for the 85,000 telephone employees who
struck Verizon Communications on Aug. 6, a key sticking point
between management and labor in the new economy is job security and
the future of work among a group of employees who have come to the
painful realization they can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Raytheon is not the only company in the state that
has slashed jobs. But to Charlene Palmer and many others who
protested Thursday just a few miles from Raytheon headquarters in
affluent Lexington, the qualities that used to matter _ seniority,
loyalty, and continuity _ don't seem to count anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Polk, meanwhile, points to the company's final contract offer as
proof that the company values its veteran plant workers as much as
its new engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we assaulting our employees with a 14.7 percent wage
increase over the life of a four-year contract?'' he asked. ``Are
we assaulting them with a $1,500 contract bonus to help offset the
escalating cost of health care premiums? Are we assaulting them
with an improved pension formula?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there are roughly 13,000 Raytheon employees in
Massachusetts, and only 3,000 are represented by the union,'' Polk
continued. ``That is a fact. The other 10,000 are engineers,
technologists, and administrative people. . . . Obviously, there
has been a change in the employment profile, not only in our
industry, but also in our region.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend has spread far beyond Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost 30,000 manufacturing jobs in this state since
1995, and Raytheon is only a part of that,'' said state Senator
Susan Fargo, a Democrat whose district includes Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Fargo told The Boston Globe this week that Raytheon's lobbyist,
Dennis G. Austin, has told her in the past that she should be most
concerned about the company's white-collar employees, particularly
those from her western suburban district.
</P>
<P>
   But, Fargo said, ``I support the strike. These people have been
worked over.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk maintains that the union, whose membership has declined
from a high of about 10,000 in the early 1990s to 2,700 today,
could see a net increase of 75 manufacturing jobs in Massachusetts
at the end of the year as a result of the consolidation of
facilities at Raytheon, Hughes Aircraft Co., and Texas Instruments.
But that's not enough of an increase to appease the strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 18 months, 439 union jobs have been transferred
out of the state, and 514 were brought into Massachusetts. Since
1998, the union has lost about 1,000 jobs because of business
divestitures, program delays, and reductions in volume, said Polk.
Those numbers do not account for the deep losses that occurred in
prior years when the company, rocked by changes in the defense
industry, began eliminating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``High technology mandates that the process of making high-tech
and low-tech products requires more advanced training,'' said Brian
Gilmore, executive vice president of Associated Industries of
Massachusetts, which represents about 5,000 companies. ``So, what
we are seeing is part of the restructuring of the defense industry.
That sector has been very hard hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no consolation to union members.
</P>
<P>
   They can't forget that in 1995, after referring to the high cost
of doing business in Massachusetts, company executives said
Raytheon would have to look at moving its 17,000-employee defense
electronics division out of the state if it could not cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The union, fearing job losses, agreed to wage freezes and job
restructurings. Then, the Legislature granted the company's request
for a change in the state's corporate tax structure. At the time,
researchers estimated that the change would save the company $21
million a year in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, union workers who backed the measure because they thought
it would mean job security and retention are angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, we gave them work-rule changes,'' recalled IBEW Local
1505's president, Stanley Lichwala. ``We had more than 420
different job classifications, and we agreed to reduce them to 40.
We gave them modified work weeks, we gave them a wage freeze, and
we asked for and got training. Now, we're overstaffed with support
people and managers making $75,000 and $100,000 a year but they
don't want to cut managers. . . . It's ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
