<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS REJUVENATED BY REINFORCEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ From the bleach-blond hair and pierced tongue
of David Segui to a smiling Manny Ramirez in uniform to long looks
at pagers that relay out-of-town scores, there is nothing subtle
about the signs of change in the Cleveland clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Segui represents the five players acquired at the trading
deadline to bolster Cleveland's playoff chances. Ramirez ready to
play symbolizes the Indians' return to health. The attention to
other American League scores serves as a reminder of the tight
wild-card race the Indians are trying to win, finding themselves
facing stiff competition for a postseason berth for the first time
since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the familiar Tribe of the recent past. The team that
collapsed in the 1999 American League Division Series and last
faced Boston at the beginning of June has reinvented itself,
overcoming adversity and working toward a postseason berth that's
not assured for the first time in six seasons. Although the Indians
have comfortably won the Central Division since 1995, the Chicago
White Sox appear poised to take that title. Cleveland finds itself
contending for the wild card against Boston, Oakland, Anaheim, and
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing start triggered by injuries left the team
trailing Chicago by 10 1/2 games at the All-Star break, Cleveland
restocked its roster just before the trading deadline,
rehabilitated injured players, and reemerged in the playoff
picture. By putting an 18-28 midsummer skid behind them and playing
well throughout August, the Indians take a 1-game wild-card lead
over Boston into September. The Red Sox and Indians face each other
eight times this month, including two doubleheaders. The contests
should prove crucial in determining the AL wild-card
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult, but we've battled through it,'' said Jim
Thome, who's batting .324 in the second half with nine home runs
and 26 RBIs in 42 games. ``I think the way we've come back tells
about our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Indians are on a hot streak. Cleveland has won 18
of its last 26 games, posting a .692 (18-8) winning percentage
since Aug. 2 and gaining 3 1/2 games on Chicago since the break.
The Indians are quick to credit late-season moves and a more
regular, injury-free lineup for the surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things weren't going right for us and we were playing flat
before the trades. Something was needed to get things going,'' said
Omar Vizquel, who has hit in 50 of his last 64 games and owns a
.285 batting average. ``(Wil) Cordero and Segui are going to move
things around. They were pretty good additions. The pitching was
the big question mark. (Jason) Bere, (Steve) Woodard, and (Bob)
Wickman are a good trio for helping the team win. Manny coming back
at the right time helped, too. We've been playing pretty good
baseball the last couple of weeks, and it's just by getting
everything together. Everybody here knows how important these games
are.''
</P>
<P>
   A chain reaction of deals involving the Indians actually started
June 29, when Cleveland sent outfielder David Justice to the
Yankees for Ricky Ledee and two players to be named. Moving Justice
freed payroll room ($18 million for the rest of this season and the
next two) and made future trades by general manager John Hart
easier to accomplish. Hart saved his big moves for the days leading
up to the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, the general manager traded Ledee to Texas for Segui,
who is signed only through 2000, which shows Hart is not looking
past the current playoff race. Cleveland acquired Milwaukee closer
Wickman and starters Bere and Woodard in exchange for power hitter
Richie Sexson, young pitchers Paul Rigdon and Kane Davis, and a
player to be named. After leaving as a free agent last winter,
Cordero returned to the Indians in a deal that sent infielder
Enrique Wilson and outfielder Alex Ramirez to the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest keys to this whole year has been the loss
of Richie Sexson, who was one of our real good prospects,'' said
relief pitcher Paul Shuey. ``But we needed the pitching we got in
that trade. We got three seasoned veterans in that trade, and
they're helping us win now. That's a huge key to us . . . And with
the trades to get Segui and Cordero, it's a totally different
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The deadline deals helped, but the return of valuable, injured
players also gave Cleveland strength. Excluding the long-term
ailments and rehabilitation efforts of starting pitchers Jaret
Wright and Charles Nagy, the Indians are now essentially healthy.
But at different points during the season, catcher Sandy Alomar,
Shuey, Lofton, and Ramirez spent significant time on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   After a period of adjustment that involved veteran Cleveland
players showing particular disappointment with the organization for
trading away 25-year-old Sexson (31 home runs, 116 RBIs in 1999),
the old, new, and recovered have blended into a potent mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Manny back and the players we got (through trades) is
still growing on our team,'' said manager Charlie Manuel, who has
also returned to health after two intestinal surgeries. ``We're
settling down and starting to play. At least, I'm hoping it's that
way. It's just the way the modern-day players are. I think they
were looking to see exactly how these guys were going to help us.
Now, they're really getting to know one another. I like the way
things are coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui and Cordero provide the contact hitting Cleveland needed
in the middle of the lineup. By supplying consistent hitting at
usually the fifth, sixth, or seventh spot, the pair have made
Manuel's job easier, giving the manager more options for moving men
along the basepaths. Since the two players were acquired, the
Indians' strikeouts per game have declined from 7.1 to 5.1. The
club's on-base percentage has improved from .356 to .364, which
ranks first in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   If consistency down the stretch helps produce wild-card winners,
Segui and Cordero should become more valuable during September.
Already, Segui has hit safely in 26 of 29 games he has appeared in
for Cleveland, including his fifth career grand slam July 30 at
Baltimore. Through Wednesday, he was batting .342 for Cleveland
with four home runs and 21 RBIs. With Segui the active leader in
career fielding percentage (.996, through Wednesday) at first base,
it doesn't hurt to have him play the infield, either. In 30 games
with the Indians, Cordero is currently batting .269. Over his last
19 games through Wednesday, he was hitting .295 with 11 runs scored
and 11 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a team that has the talent to win,'' said
Segui. ``If we just play like we're capable of playing, we'll give
ourselves a real good chance (at the wild-card spot). The problem
this team had was doing it on a consistent basis. Anybody can play
well for streaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Add the talents of Segui and Cordero to a healthy cleanup hitter
(Ramirez) and the offensive potential becomes impressive, without
even mentioning Thome, Vizquel, or Roberto Alomar. Although Ramirez
was not the only player hurt, his absence in the lineup was most
sorely missed. A lingering injury to his left hamstring kept
Ramirez out of the lineup from May 30 until July 13. The Indians
went 19-20 without him. Since returning from the disabled list,
Ramirez batted .365 (50 for 137) with 14 home runs, 40 RBIs in his
first 38 games, not including Thursday night. The Indians have gone
27-18 with him off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries forced Manuel to take desperate measures with his
staff. Early in the season, it was nearly impossible for the
manager to get through the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   After going on and off the disabled list a couple times, Wright
had season-ending right shoulder surgery in mid-August. Nagy is on
a rehabilitation assignment after surgery for loose bodies in his
right elbow. Key pitchers Bartolo Colon, Ricardo Rincon, and Shuey
also made appearances on the disabled list. In their absences,
Cleveland used 26 pitchers in the first half, tying a team record.
In the process, 14 unprepared minor leaguers were called up and
instability set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were asking too many minor league pitchers to perform to
the level of a veteran pitching staff,'' said catcher Alomar. ``You
can't ask a rookie to do the job of a veteran. It's impossible. We
were putting a lot of pressure on them, so they got some veteran
pitchers who have been in this type of situation before.''
</P>
<P>
   The revolving door finally stopped spinning in July. The
additions of Bere, Woodard, and Wickman provided the experienced
pitching that had been missing. Since arriving in Cleveland, Bere
has posted a 4-2 record and a 5.59 ERA in seven starts. Woodard
owns a 1-2 record with a 5.72 ERA after picking up his first win
for Cleveland Tuesday night against Texas. Wickman has eight saves
in 10 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players know we came here trying to fit in, but
the only way to fit in is to go out and do your job and be
aggressive and competitive,'' said Bere, who lives in North
Andover. ``This type of team scores a lot of runs, so as a starting
pitcher your job is just to try to go out there, eat up some
quality innings, and get deep into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of Shuey in late June after a monthlong leave gave
Manuel a much-needed setup man. Since coming back, Shuey has
allowed just 11 runs over 25 innings over 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, this is the best shot we've had to be
strong going into the playoffs,'' said Shuey. ``I like the
situation we're in because if we do get to the playoffs we'll have
to be hot to get there. In the past, that hasn't been the case. If
we're hot and get in there, there's a good chance we'll do
something in the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
