<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIC CODE' REVEALS REAL FEELINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE TIC CODE 
Directed by: Gary Winick 
Screenplay by: Polly Draper 
Starring: Gregory Hines, Christopher George Marquette, Draper 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its soft, muted, heartfelt way, ``The Tic Code'' is about as
far away from Hollywood assembly line thinking as American movies
get. It's got more genuine-seeming feelings and a more accurate
take on its particular corner of the world than a coliseum of
summer blockbusters. All you need to know about how right it goes
is that two of its three main characters have Tourette's syndrome,
yet it never seems like a disease movie. It stays an affecting,
naturalistically-textured study of a single mom, her precocious
son, a saxophonist, and the closeness of all three to the world of
jazz, which is inscribed with rare, unforced rightness.
</P>
<P>
   The script is by Polly Walker, who also stars as the mother,
Laura, who conveniently avoids her own issues by focusing on the
needs of her 12-year-old son, Miles. Blaming himself for the
breakup of his parents' marriage, he's still emotionally bruised
after having been abandoned by his jazz pianist father, who
couldn't handle the boy's neurological disorder. Miles may even
have surpassed his father as a keyboard prodigy. Yet one of the
admirable things about the script, based in part on the experiences
of Draper's jazz musician husband, Michael Wolff, is that it
doesn't present Tourette's as the obstacle you might assume it
would be to Miles' music-making.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the film presents Miles' improvisational freedom as the
other side of the same coin of an inability to control his every
move that marks Tourette's syndrome. Not that Miles, habitually
mortified by the involuntary movements he can't control, sees
Tourette's as a blessing. Christopher George Marquette delivers an
arresting and heartbreaking performance as the conflicted prodigy,
trying not to be derailed by the torrents of feeling inside him,
encouraged, yet cautioned by the example of Gregory Hines'
similarly afflicted and even more conflicted saxophonist, Tyrone,
who refuses to talk about his Tourette's and is sitting on a lot of
anger connected to it.
</P>
<P>
   No small part of the film is set in the venerable Village
Vanguard nightclub, where the jazz interludes (supervised by Wolff)
have a rightness and unforced authority virtually unknown in film.
One of the film's peaks comes when Miles, initially too overwound
to speak to the older musician, returns for an improvised jazz duet
that pulses with the give and take of the real thing. The
personalized immediacy and handmade craftsmanship of ``The Tic
Code'' are qualities that attract actors, which is why such
seasoned pros as Camryn Manheim, Tony Shalhoub, Carol Kane, Bill
Nunn, and Fisher Stevens can be seen in smaller roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tic Code'' is not without rough technical patches, and a
forced melodramatic resolution, the only wrong note in a film
that's otherwise enticingly musical in its own right, with subtle
tonalities and intertwining melodic lines that include a deepening,
if problematic, romance between Laura and Tyrone. Draper does an
impressive job of avoiding the inspirational cliches lying like
undetonated land mines in a film of this sort. She even attunes us
to the dynamic of art and its sources more than films that speak
about them overtly, usually in banalities. Ever since his
underrated ``Sweet Nothing,'' one of the best movies ever made
about the effects of drug addiction on a working-class family, I've
been waiting to see what director Gary Winick would come up with
next. ``The Tic Code'' confirms his early promise. A lot more than
money was invested in this film, and it shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
