<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-YOAKAM-BOS &LR;      09-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YOAKAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WITH THE SONGS IN HIS HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be careful what you say to Dwight Yoakam, because you might end
up in a song. Yoakam, a hard-driving country-rock singer, is one of
those people who has music constantly running through his head. The
slightest conversation might spark a fresh song lyric or melody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I communicate with myself musically all of the time,'' says
Yoakam. ``It's been with me so long that I realized the last couple
of years that I had almost come to ignore it on a daily basis. In
other words, I have musical thoughts based off of conversations
that I'll be having. I'll just walk away and I'll hear something. I
think in musical, melodic terms, and I have all my life. So what I
started doing was making myself get to the nearest tape recorder _
I keep several of them around _ and capture that musical thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam has captured enough of those thoughts to become a
Grammy-winning singer whose music has an earthy reality completely
missing from many of today's faux cowboy acts.
</P>
<P>
   From his first album, ``Guitars, Cadillacs, Etc.,'' in 1984, to
his latest, ``dwightyoakamacoustic.net'' (featuring sparkling solo
versions of many of his hits), Yoakam has carved a path as real as
the Bakersfield soil that affected his main influences _ Buck Owens
and Merle Haggard _ though he's also been influenced by
tougher-than-nails rock bands like the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam's ability to fashion music out of everyday life _ through
such hits as ``Ain't That Lonely Yet,'' ``A Thousand Miles From
Nowhere'' and ``Try Not to Look So Pretty'' _ puts him in an ideal
position to maintain a recording career at the same time as he's
trying to build an acting profile.
</P>
<P>
   His acting reached new heights a few years ago in ``Sling
Blade'' (in which Yoakam played a menacing, abusive husband) and
will come around again in ``South of Heaven, West of Hell,'' due
for release next year. It's a ``gothic Western set in 1907,'' says
Yoakam, who wrote, directed, and starred in it.
</P>
<P>
   While finishing the film earlier this year, Yoakam was still
able to write songs on the set _ thanks to having a trusty tape
recorder nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do both, because I've learned to integrate them,'' he
says. ``Music is something that is so a part of my innate makeup
that I just have to keep myself alert to it. And it enabled me to
be finishing the film while writing and recording simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really write when I'm on the road touring. But I can
write when I'm on a movie set,'' he adds with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   While on the set for ``South of Heaven,'' Yoakam finished tunes
that will come out on a new CD, ``Tomorrow's Sounds Today,'' next
month. Unfortunately, the album hasn't been released to coincide
with his current 80-city tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's appropriate that the album is called `Tomorrow's Sounds
Today,' because that's what we find ourselves doing. We're playing
five tracks from it, even though it's not yet out,'' he says with
another chuckle, though a less hearty one this time.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote one of the songs with idol Buck Owens _ the first time
the two have collaborated. It's called ``Sad Side of Town'' and is
also part of the song list for the tour. The collaboration stemmed
from playing a New Year's Eve gig last winter with Owens in
Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting in his dressing room and he played a bit of a
melody,'' Yoakam recalls. ``To me it sounded like classic Buck. It
was a great two-beat idea and I knew I wanted to write something
for it. So we got back together a couple of months later and worked
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam isn't sure how country radio will receive it, but that
has not deterred him in the past. The Kentucky native is a career
artist who writes from the heart rather than for the corporate
suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that radio will play it,'' he says of the
forthcoming album. ``But, in all honesty, I'm not sure where we fit
in the larger picture of country music. Country music is in flux
right now, but I do think the music I recorded, and continue to
record, is still valid and pertinent.''
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world, it seems as if men in general are having a
tougher time getting played on country radio, thanks to the female
invasion led by the likes of Shania Twain, Jo Dee Messina, and the
Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ebbs and flows,'' says Yoakam. ``There also are
times when it's all men. There are moments when you couldn't get
female artists played, or when female artists wouldn't sell. But
it's not something you can worry about all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   His next studio CD will be his eighth in the last 16 years, says
Yoakam, who is happy to have a loyal fan base that will drive miles
to appreciate his tradition-influenced but modern-sounding music
courtesy of producer Pete Anderson, who is also his tour guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first few years that we did this,'' Yoakam says, ``I felt
we were still introducing ourselves to the audience on some level.
Whereas now, it's as if we're coming back to see friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam gave those friends a special gift in the acoustic
double-CD, ``dwightyoakamacoustic.net.'' It grew out of a segment
in his shows when he gives his band a rest and performs solo. These
moments have been well-received by fans, so it was logical to give
them something more expansive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never abandon making records with my band,'' he says.
``But this album allowed me to revisit the material myself in a
more intimate way. It was coming full circle, but at the same time
it was a discovery of new emotional territory.''
</P>
<P>
   However, don't expect an upsurge of acoustic tunes on the new
tour. Yoakam is still rocking with the band for the most part _ and
``doing the acoustic stuff usually at the end,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
