<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY LABOR DAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept 3, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy Labor Day?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But the words lack the oomph and of, say, ``Happy New
Year'' or ``Happy Fourth.'' The weekend to celebrate work has never
been a ripper.
</P>
<P>
   A more appropriate greeting might be: ``Not-so-bad Labor Day,''
or ``Mezzo-mezzo Monday,'' or ``Here we go, ready or not,'' for in
the calendars of our minds, the work year and the autumn begin on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   We're looking at the first day of school for adults here; never
mind that we were at our desks for most of the summer. Desks in the
summer have an entirely different gestalt. They can be left early
without raising too many eyebrows. Their phones are quieter _ and
just about went dead last week.
</P>
<P>
   People sitting at them dress down, in some cases way down, to
Hawaiian shirts, tank tops, and shorts that will prompt memos next
week restating the limits of casual Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us don't need the memo. We can already feel the
corporate circadian rhythms pulling us away from pastels and toward
navy and black. Sandals and slides might hang in for a while,
exposing painted toes as a fashion statement in some cubicles, but
the safest career move will be to minimize skin.
</P>
<P>
   Are the people in the big offices back into serious suits? Then
forget the Dockers at the staff meeting. The first day of school
for adults is pretty much like it was in 9th grade, only longer.
Peer pressure rules.
</P>
<P>
   Briefcases will be back, replacing the lighter canvas bags that
people figured were OK for schlepping papers in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of school demands leather, maybe new leather,
although that decision can also be weighted with political
consequences. Is it better to go with the old beat-up satchel,
exuding the confidence of a veteran who doesn't need to care about
high-end accessories? Or should one strive to be flashy and hip,
catching the wave of Euro-chic with something off the shoulder from
Italy?
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day trains the mind on such matters. It's a picnic with
homework, ``celebrating'' the great American gear-shift that forces
people to deal with everything that was so easily put off in June.
</P>
<P>
   Asking for a raise, for instance, is just not a summertime
thing. A person needs to be wearing shoulder pads and be steeped in
the corporate milieu. A person also needs to have the top of the
executive food chain around, because any manager fielding the raise
question before Labor Day will inevitably say, ``Let's deal with
that when everyone's back.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll be back Tuesday, but they'll be in a meeting. When they
come out of the meeting they will have lists of projects, which
means the rest of us will have lists of projects. So the raise
question is probably best saved for Wednesday or Thursday, although
it will occupy the mind tomorrow, or probably today.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day refuses to let people laze. It demands to see the
agenda, starting with work around the house. Spouses often have
lists as long as the project schedule at work. The kids have lists.
The dog and cat need their shots.
</P>
<P>
   None of this seemed pressing in August, or even on Friday's
start of the long weekend. Friday was still summer. But yesterday,
reality moved in with a mop and a paint brush. ``Back to School''
was no longer a concept. It became a broken lunch box and ripped
pants.
</P>
<P>
   It became the folder in the kitchen drawer, jammed with the fine
print of insurance papers, receipts, phone numbers of financial
planners, the form for increasing contributions to the 401(k), and
an article on tax-free municipal bonds _ all saved for a September
mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Are we there yet? Not quite. We're in transition, ramping up,
and putting summer down. And that's always work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     09-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIC VS. FIBERGLASS ROOF SHINGLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September   03, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What are the advantages of organic roof shingles over
fiberglass? My roofer is Canadian, and recommends organics.
</P>
<P>
   ED LETTIC, Lancaster and Paxton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, let's define the terms. The shingles in question are
asphalt, but the organics have a saturated (with asphalt) felt core
covered on both sides with asphalt and small stones for color and
durability. Fiberglass shingles have a core of fiberglass, also
covered with asphalt and stones.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of organics are their durability, resistance to
cracking, and ease of installing. Two brands of fiberglass shingles
have had problems of premature failure. There are a number of
class-action suits against them.
</P>
<P>
   Other brands of fiberglass have not had any problems. One
advantage of fiberglass is that fiberglass shingles have a class A
fire rating, compared to a class C rating for organics, meaning
they are more fire resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Two manufacturers of organic shingles are Canadian: Iko and BP.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had my house shingled three years ago, and two coats of an
oil stain applied. It peeled in a year. What went wrong and how can
I make sure a new stain won't peel?
</P>
<P>
   ALICE OSTROWSKA, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that oil stain was a solid stain, and solid stains
are like paint, which create a film on the wood and can peel. It
certainly did, probably due to moisture behind the shingles.
Another possible reason it peeled is that it was put on too
thickly.
</P>
<P>
   The cure is to scrape and sand off that old stuff and apply a
semitransparent stain. It will not peel; well, it has a 95 percent
chance of not peeling, which is a far better chance than the
original stain.
</P>
<P>
   Another good thing about a semitransparent stain is that only
one coat is needed. Then, in five years, when you need another
coat, there is virtually no preparation before putting on the next
coat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have four wood chairs with seats of black webbing. The
webbing is hard to clean when it gets dirty. Any secret?
</P>
<P>
   WAITING
</P>
<P>
   A. If the webbing is plastic, make a strong solution of Spic and
Span and water. If there is mold on the webbing, add a cup of
bleach. Apply this solution and let it sit on the webbing for
several minutes; then scrub and rinse. If you use bleach, try it on
a small area to make sure it does not bleach out the plastic, but
if it is plastic, this is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   If the webbing is cloth, clean it with upholstery cleaner, just
as you would clean an upholstered chair or sofa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I think I have some mold on my shower curtain, except it is
red and does not come off with a bleach/cleanser. What will work?
</P>
<P>
   CARL DETTMAN, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The bleach/cleanser is not strong enough. Paint the stains
with a solution of household bleach and water. I had similar red
stains and they came off with bleach. Or, put the curtain in the
washing machine with bleach added. If nothing works, get a new
curtain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is less than a year old, equipped with a ridge vent
and soffit vents. During cold weather the attic stairs were open to
the attic for several hours. I then noticed a lot of water
developed on the nail points coming through the roof, dripping on
the floor. A few days later there was still moisture, but then the
attic was dry a few days after that. Someone suggested putting in
more vents, or to put in gable vents. What happened? Do I need more
vents?
</P>
<P>
   CLAUDIA COOPER, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You do not need more vents. What happened is this: Opening
that attic door allowed warm, moist air in the house to flow up
into the attic; there was so much of it that the vents could not
handle it, and the moist air condensed on the cold nail points.
When you closed the attic door, you stopped that air flow, and the
attic dried out.
</P>
<P>
   You do not need more vents, but if the soffit vents are not a
continuous 2- or 3-inch-wide strip, then install one; it will give
better ventilation than a series of rectangular or round vents,
which are usually spaced too far apart to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. After work was done on the house, a lot of dust was left on
the floor and furniture. It is very gritty and heavy, and I don't
want to scratch when I wipe it. What is best to use?
</P>
<P>
   WORRIED
</P>
<P>
   A. Not to worry. Use a Whizzer cloth or other lighty lubricated
dry cloth to wipe off that grit. Or, wipe with a damp cloth and a
light hand. Or, put a tablespoon of cooking oil in a bucket of warm
water, dip a sponge in this concoction, squeeze out, and wipe
lightly. The oil will help pick up the grit, and also will remove
plaster dust, without scratching.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
