<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TOWN-BOS &LR;      09-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `TOWN' STRIVES FOR PEACE AMID CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TITANIC TOWN 
Directed by: Roger Michell 
Screenplay by: Anne Devlin (novel: Mary Costello) 
Starring: Julie Walters, Ciaran Hinds, Nuala O'Neill, James
Loughran, Barry Loughran, Elizabeth Donaghy, Ciaran McMenamin,
Aingeal Grehan 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Titanic Town,'' filmed a couple of years ago, just before the
still-fragile Easter Sunday ceasefire in Northern Ireland, rides
the intensity and heartfelt conviction of Julie Walters as a West
Belfast wife and mother radicalized into peace activism. The film
loses little time demystifying its title, and letting the irony
fall where it may, by revealing that the town had been known as the
place where the Titanic was built. When Walters's Bernie McPhelimy
and her family move into a neat little row house in a Catholic
neighborhood in 1972, the place is well along the way to sinking
itself, thanks to the deadly combat between British troops and the
IRA. When Bernie's friend is gunned down in one of the frequent
exchanges of gunfire, she sets her lips in a grim, tight line and
decides to do something.
</P>
<P>
   What she's quite likely to do, explains her ulcer-ridden husband
(Ciaran Hinds), is get herself killed. Sure enough, when she
agitates to at least have the gun duels scheduled for hours when
fewer people are in the streets, each side assumes she's the
other's pawn. When she escalates her efforts and gets thousands of
signatures on a petition, the Brits listen, but a TV reporter edits
the context out of her remarks so that it looks as if she's
condemning the IRA. At first, she's saved by her naivete, although
death threats are forthcoming. As jolting as the bullets tearing
through the neighborhood at any given moment, followed by crudely
invasive house-to-house searches by uniformed troops, is the
matter-of-fact acceptance of death as a daily occurrence by
children who have never known anything different.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Michell's film is not without bursts of savage violence.
But it's at its most devastating when Bernie's youngest daughter
asks her older sister, with horrifying logic, if the latter will
leave her all of her dolls in her will. When the little girl
politely hands a British soldier back the rifle he had laid down
during a search, and the rifles of his comrades are cocked in
jangly unison, your heart stops. Throughout, Bernie's family is
inscribed with idiomatic rightness. Nuala O'Neill is a standout as
the adolescent daughter who trades dolls for first love with Ciaran
McMenamin's newcomer to the troubled neighborhood. Hinds projects
quiet strength in the least showy role, that of Bernie's husband,
and Angeal Grehan helps firm up the drama as the friend who sticks
by Bernie when things get dicey and other more risk-averse
neighbors drop away.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding polemics, and displaying an awreness of the lethal
complexities of the political snarl, Michell makes many of the
film's points with telling details. When a truckful of British
troops is advancing down her street on a search mission, Bernie
tells the kids to make sure the beds are made before the soldiers
enter. Later, when an IRA threat takes the form of a rock tossed
through her window, Bernie displays the rock proudly alongside her
other domestic treasures. When she meets with the British
mucky-mucks, she fumbles in her purse until she locates a list of
IRA conditions she's been asked to relay. Once she does, though,
her voice and gaze are steady. Walters's unswerving command of the
moral force Bernie embodies is the engine that drives the vivid and
all-too-authentic ``Titanic Town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
