Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-THEME-PARKS (Dronten, The Netherlands) _ Europeans
visited American-style theme parks in record numbers this summer,
stirred by spreading affluence, booming tourism, and greater
variety. The expansion is gathering momentum and drawing outside
investment, notably from the United States. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Businesses added fewer jobs than
expected in August, the government says in a report that may
bolster confidence that the Federal Reserve will hold interest
rates steady for some time. Over all, nonfarm payrolls dropped by
105,000, chiefly because of a strike by workers at Verizon
Communications, formerly Bell Atlantic, and because of the
elimination of temporary jobs at the Census Bureau. Private-sector
jobs would have grown by 102,000 if not for the Verizon strike. The
unemployment rate rose to 4.1 percent from 4 percent. Factory jobs
fell 79,000, the largest drop since the General Motors strike in
July 1998. Wage growth remained benign in August, slowing to a 0.3
percent pace after July's 0.4 percent increase. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford and other automakers report
August sales. Looking at how sales of the Explorer are doing while
the vehicle's Firestone tires come under increasing scrutiny. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BRISTOL (Undated) _ A federal judge in Connecticut has
ordered Microsoft to pay Bristol Technology $1 million in punitive
damages for engaging in ``wanton, reckless and deceptive'' business
practices. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ Kumagai Gumi, a Japanese construction
company, is asking creditors to forgive $4.2 billion in loans. By
Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
