<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-CHRONOLOGY (Undated) _ In the art world, antichronology
seems to be the rage. Numerous U.S. museums have re-hung their
painting and sculpture collections according to subject instead of
chronology. The one thing curators seem to agree on about
antichronology is that chronology and time are only the surface
issues. The deeper issue is genealogy: whether there is a great
lineage of art, a natural progression of one art movement after
another leading up to the grand finale, abstraction. By Sarah
Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-TECHNOLOGY-LAW (Undated) _ Existing law can fit poorly with
technological developments, mostly because the legislators who
drafted the laws did not anticipate them. By Adam Liptak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOOTED-TREASURES-TAX (Undated) _ On the settlement of the
Quindlinberg art case, in which two Texans agreed to pay the
Internal Revenue Service $135,000 in federal and state taxes on the
sale of several items in a group of valuable religious relics taken
by a U.S. Army lieutenant while he was stationed in Germany in the
final days of World War II. The artworks, long since returned to
Germany, are part of a group of medieval treasures many of which
were kept for a millennium in the treasure chamber of the
Quedlinburg cathedral in Germany. By William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLANDER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Highlander: Endgame'':
Douglas Aarniokoski, director; with Christopher Lambert, Adrian
Paul. Reviewed by A.O. Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
