<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 5 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (w) Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MATTINGLY _ GOP Senate hopeful Mack Mattingly hung out with some
high-profile Republicans this past week _ Dick Cheney in Atlanta on
Wednesday and Nathan Deal in the 9th District on Thursday. He's
hoping for some coattail momentum to help boost his name
recognition after having not been on the ballot for 14 years. But
wonks say he'll need more than that _ namely lots of TV advertising
to become more familiar with voters. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-AD Republicans see no double-standard in play because
in 1996 they assailed Clinton for writing Democratic ``issues'' ads
in the White House while now Bush signs off on Republican ``soft
money'' ads. The reason, GOP says, is that Bush does not have veto
power over what they may or may not say about the Gore campaign.
(Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ While some of the American educational reforms
were changed after Allied occupation forces left Japan in 1952,
most of the American-imposed reforms stayed in place and were
responsible for Japan's meteoric postwar rise to international
economic power. Now Japanese school children routinely wipe the
floor with American school children whenever or however scholastic
achievement is compared. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ I was born at high noon 46
years ago, back in the days when the opening day of dove season
began at high noon on the Friday of Labor Day weekend. The day, as
I understand it, my birthday was Friday. So my father was pacing,
pacing, pacing outside the labor room and I'm thinking it was every
bit as much because he was worried that he was going to miss the
first day of hunting as it was worried about my delivery. (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ``Fergit, Hell!'' Would
you believe it? We're in the third century since the late
unpleasantness with our northern neighbors, and ain't nobody
fergittin' nothin'. And nobody is forgiving anything. (Jim Minter
is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The final week of the Dragons
regular season found folks in a celebratory mood _ and, after a
record-breaking season, thinking about the possibilities for
downtown. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED. JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _
Who wins the presidential election may well be decided by who wins
the debates. But right now, more important than that, is the debate
about the debates. Al Gore's people want it to be the classic
one-on-one kind. George W. Bush's people want it to be the Larry
King kind. The difference could be the difference in the election.
(Murray6, Cox News Service).
</P>
