 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following articles
to mark the opening of the National Football League season. The
articles, for publication Sunday, September 3, and thereafter, will
move Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COVER PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DEEP-STRIKE (Undated) _ When Isaac Bruce caught the
game-winning 73-yard touchdown pass in Super Bowl XXXIV, he could
have kept running and zipped right into the 2000 National Football
League season. Because Bruce and his St. Louis Rams, along with
teams like the Minnesota Vikings, the Indianapolis Colts and the
Washington Redskins, are swaying offenses back to the vertical
passing game. The hunger for big plays this season will be
insatiable. And while teams will yearn for big plays to erupt in
the running game, and they will insist on their surfacing in the
passing game. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-QUARTERBACKS (Undated) _ When the NFL lost John Elway, Dan
Marino and Steve Young to retirement, all in the past two years,
there was concern about who would fill their shoulder pads. But,
surprisingly, there is a healthy surplus of candidates, which is
good news for a league that continues to expand. The number of
solid young passers, more than a dozen, is at its highest level
since 1983, when six quarterbacks were selected in the first round
of the draft. But there is something else happening at the position
besides an increase in young arms. Many of them, like Peyton
Manning and Donovan McNabb, were drafted not only for their
abilities, but also for their capacity to handle the myriad
off-the-field distractions and requests for their time from
increasingly hungry, hostile and intrusive news media and fans. By
Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CONFERENCE RACES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-AFC (Undated) _ Capsule previews of the AFC teams by
divisions in predicted order of finish. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFC (Undated) _ Capsule previews of the NFC teams by
divisions in predicted order of finish. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Dave Anderson sports column on
the ``invisible jackals'' pressuring coaches Al Groh and Jim
Fassel. The Jets new head coach Al Groh is replacing Bill Parcells
while Giants coach Fassel has to win to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Lead item: If there is one troublesome
sign for the Rams _ and there are not very many on a team stacked
with talent _ it is new coach Mike Martz's paranoia and desire to
have Bill Parcells-like control of the media. If Martz loses a few
games, his paranoia will only increase, and players start loosing
confidence in coaches who worry more about who is behind that bush
with a boom microphone than about things that matter like the game
plan. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-TV-SPORTS (Undated) _ While the spotlight may be on Dennis
Miller's hiring on ABC's ``Monday Night Football,'' other new faces
will be present for the ``fall feeding feast.'' By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COLLINS (Undated) _ The fall of 1998 was a fireball of
strife for Kerry Collins, the quarterback and new field leader of
the New York Giants, a stunning decline from athletic idol to
object of scorn, all crystallized in one early morning meeting in
the office of Carolina Panthers' coach Dom Capers. Capers announced
that Collins had done something unthinkable in sport, he had quit.
Capers no longer discusses the meeting and Collins has never given
his side. But late one afternoon last week, Collins said of that
day: ``As it turned out, it was the best thing that every happened
to me.'' By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Undated) _ The Jets' regular season begins Sunday
against Green Bay, but the restiveness that accompanied an
offseason of tumult may linger for awhile. An eerily quiet training
camp _ a quiet assured in some part by the trade of receiver
Keyshawn Johnson _ gives way to a season during which the Jets will
be required to solve their mysteries as a team just as surely as
they must solve opposing defenses. Is Vinny Testaverde healthy?
Whither the passing game, now that Johnson is gone? What sort of
imprint will Coach Al Groh try to put on the team before the
inevitable looming shadow of Bill Parcells threatens to engulf him?
By Judy Battista.
</P>
