<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-GARAGE-PRICES-HNS &LR;      09-01 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-GARAGE-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO'S HOMELESS NOW INCLUDE CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's so hard to find parking here that people
are having the land under their houses excavated to build a garage,
and paying oodles for it _ $100,00, $200,000, even a million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   It's so hard to find parking here that people hunting for a
house to buy often refuse to look at a prospect if it doesn't have
a garage.
</P>
<P>
   It's so hard to find parking here that people can wait two years
to rent a space in a garage, then pay as much as $500 per month for
it.
</P>
<P>
   And those are the options for the lucky ones who can afford to
build that garage, buy that house, rent that stall.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, parking on the streets of San Francisco usually
means endless circling followed by that all-too-familiar,
inevitable, desperate last resort: parking in crosswalks, by fire
hydrants, in bus zones, across driveways and even on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for parking in the city is so acute that the
residential garage construction business is booming. One company,
Add-a-Garage, specializes in it.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Pavlow, 76, had already retired from the general contractor
business when he founded the company 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   A simple two-car space typically costs $150,000 to $200,000. One
of Pavlow's customers, a 38-year-old owner of a Pacific Heights
home, is paying $1 million for a six-car garage that is being built
into the hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the hot real estate market in San Francisco, a house without
a garage will certainly sell, said Mindy Kershner, a real estate
agent with Tower Properties.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``It's always better to have a garage than to not have a
garage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A garage has become so important on the wish list of house
hunters that before an open house, real estate agents are now
getting construction estimates to add a garage, just as they do for
needed roof or termite work.
</P>
<P>
   Those who own a house or rent an apartment without a garage
often look for a private garage to rent. One Internet site had 309
listings as of Thursday afternoon under the parking category, most
from seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, I am begging, if you don't have a car and own a
parking space, have a kind heart and let me use your space,'' said
one ad from someone seeking a spot for $175.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Driveway to Call Home'' beckons another advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Even the well-to-do have it tough.
</P>
<P>
   Maher Kara, 29, an investment banker who just moved here from
New York City, pays $3,000 per month rent for a one-bedroom
apartment, but his new car is homeless. His 10-story apartment
building has a two-year waiting list for parking spaces, and his
classified ads and neighborhood flyers have been to no avail. The
closest he got was a bidding war. He bailed out when the
competition offered $500.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to New York City, parking in San Francisco is a lot
tougher, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much worse,'' Kara said. ``In NYC, if you've got
money, you can get an apartment and parking. There is supply. It's
just a matter of price. Here, money makes no difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-HOME-PRICES-HNS &LR;      09-01 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-HOME-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEWCOMERS STRUGGLE IN SAN FRANCISCO'S HOT REAL ESTATE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD PAOLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Terri Allon wasn't entirely unprepared for
getting into San Francisco's housing market. Research told her that
prices would be high as she prepared to move from Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the home-buying process here has left her shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bidding war scene was unexpected,'' said Allon, who is
moving to San Francisco with her son following her divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the biggest problem for buying here is the mind-set you
need to buy up, above the asking price _ it's difficult to
swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   A limited supply of homes on the market, along with
sky-rocketing prices, has made San Francisco the nation's least
affordable city in which to buy a home, according to a National
Association of Home Builders survey released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Only 5.9 percent of San Francisco households with a median
income of $74,900 can afford to buy the $510,000 median-priced
home, according to the survey. Median means that half of the
incomes or prices are above that point and half are below.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 173 cities in the affordability survey, San Francisco
ranked last. It also was the only city with an affordability rating
below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Northern California cities joined San Francisco at
the top of the least-affordable list: Santa Cruz, 10.7 percent, No.
172; Salinas, 13.9 percent, No. 171; San Jose, 14.4 percent, No.
170; and Santa Rosa, 15.9 percent, No. 169.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, 25.9 percent, ranked No. 165; and the
Vallejo-Fairfield-Napa area, 31 percent, ranked No. 160.
</P>
<P>
   Rockford, Ill., ranked first in the affordability survey. In
that city, 89.3 percent of families with the median income of
$55,300 could afford to buy the median-priced house of $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   A major step toward broadening home affordability in San
Francisco, said Aldo Congi, vice president for McGuire Real
Estate's San Francisco district, ``is to build more housing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a nod to City Hall, Congi noted, ``The current regime has
done a good job making this a desirable city to live in, but they
have to address one result of that: the need for more housing. And
it can't be done without serious regard to keeping the open space.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-density zoning would be a step toward increasing the
city's housing because San Francisco has run out of land,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-$ADV     09-01 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-$ADV03-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS RETURNS WITH A FOCUS ON VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)   &HT;     (Eds: FIXES 15th graf, substituting the word on for the word
with; 18th graf, starting the 3d sentence with the words: But the
vote could be slowed by ; inserting in last graf, 1st sentence,
words showing that Sen. Kennedy's measure would require health
plans to pay for emergency care.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returns to Capitol Hill Tuesday for a
fast-paced final month of work in which members will jockey to
showcase an agenda designed primarily to win votes in November.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative goals are taking a back seat to political strategies
as polls are showing a tight presidential race between Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing the election, Democrats will push popular legislation to
boost the minimum wage and grant patients a bill of rights against
managed care providers.
</P>
<P>
   With the same focus, Republicans will try to override President
Clinton's veto of the so-called marriage penalty tax as well as his
veto last Thursday of a plan to phase out the federal estate tax.
They will also push a measure to expand Individual Retirement
Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some members of both parties will fight behind closed
doors to stymie legislation, hoping to keep certain issues alive
for the campaign. For instance, measures to make prescription drugs
more affordable for seniors are not expected to advance simply
because the two parties' plans are too far apart and not enough
time remains to resolve the differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be much sound and fury but very little actual
lawmaking because each side has an incentive to posture rather than
legislate,'' predicts Jack Pitney, a political scientist at
Claremont McKenna College in Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, says David Rohde, a political scientist at
Michigan State University, ``nobody wants to be seen as an
obstructionist, and each side wants the other side to be seen as
obstructionist.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue are already
tense. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott fired off a letter last
week charging that President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
``are engineering `a train wreck' to affect the political
environment'' by vetoing spending bills. So far, only two of the 13
measures that fund the federal government have been signed into
law.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert shot back, saying Congress is
``well behind in its work,'' and that ``it's time to stop making
excuses and get a budget together.''
</P>
<P>
   That will probably happen _ with plenty of last-minute
compromises _ since no one wants another government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are still stung by the bruising House losses they
suffered after getting blamed for two partial federal government
shutdowns in late 1995 and early 1996 that resulted from budget
stalemates between them and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid a repeat, Republicans in 1996 and 1998 made
major concessions to Clinton to complete the federal budget. Later
many GOP strategists blamed those concessions for additional
Republican losses in the House in 1998. Now Republicans have a
seven-vote majority there and a five-vote majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats remember all too well the legislative gridlock, plus
Clinton's failed health care overhaul, that swept congressional
Republicans to power in 1994. Voters blamed both sides for the
stalemate but punished Democrats at the polls that year.
</P>
<P>
   As the targeted adjournment date of Oct. 6 nears, horse-trading
between Republican leaders and the White House will go into high
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything depends on how vulnerable the Republicans feel and
what they make by way of concessions without alienating their
conservative base,'' says Thomas E. Mann, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the final month of the 106th Congress, President Clinton
will seek to burnish his legacy and drum up support for Gore and
for Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for a U.S. Senate seat
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The following legislation will take center stage as Congress
returns:
</P>
<P>
   _ CHINA TRADE. The Senate will soon consider the landmark,
House-passed bill that would grant China permanent trading
privileges with the United States, which most other countries
enjoy, without an annual review. Since the measure, opposed by
organized labor, is a top priority for Clinton and Lott and is
backed by Gore and Bush, it will likely pass. But the vote could be
slowed by a controversial companion measure by Sens. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. It would prod the White
House to impose sanctions if China fails to stop giving weapons of
mass destruction to rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   _ MINIMUM WAGE. House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., with
Lott's approval, offered a deal to Clinton last week. He said
Congress would agree to the president's plan to raise the minimum
wage by $1 over two years in exchange for a GOP proposal to provide
$76 billion in tax breaks over 10 years for small businesses. While
the House approved the minimum wage boost over two years, the
Senate has insisted on implementing it over three years. A
compromise version has stalled for months, but now, with Clinton
indicating he could accept the tax measure, passage looks likely.
</P>
<P>
   _ RETIREMENT SAVINGS. Lott has pledged to push legislation that
would expand contributions to Individual Retirement Accounts from
$2,000 to $5,000 over three years. The measure passed the House
with 401 votes in July, but the Treasury Department opposes it and
has said it will recommend a veto. Outlook: possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARRIAGE PENALTY. House Republican leaders will try to
override Clinton's Aug. 5 veto of the so-called marriage penalty
tax, a quirk in the tax code that causes some couples to owe more
income taxes if they marry than if they live together but remain
single. An override is doubtful but has a slim chance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESTATE TAX. Hastert will try to override President Clinton's
Aug. 31 veto of a bill that would phase out the estate tax over 10
years. The speaker says it forces family farms and businesses to
break up. But in 1998, only 47,500 estates, 2 percent of the total,
paid the tax, and most of the revenue came from estates worth more
than $5 million. Republicans have been vulnerable to charges they
are catering to the wealthy, and their override attempt is likely
to fall short of the two-thirds majority needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., will
look for chances to attach to spending bills a measure that would
require health plans to pay for emergency care, allow patients to
see certain specialists without prior health plan approval and let
patients sue a health plan in state courts. Democrats claim they
have 50 votes, which with Gore's tie-breaker would allow them to
pass the measure. But they couldn't muster 60 votes to quash a GOP
filibuster, and since the Republicans are not likely to give Gore
such a plum, the measure will probably die.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
