<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBO-HIGHSCHOOL-FOOTBA     09-01 2073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-HIGHSCHOOL-FOOTBALL02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    H `The purest game'
 &HT;    By Ben Wear
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When the old Austin High Maroons get together,
and they do so with some frequency, the talk often turns to the
unusually cold autumn of 1950. To Coach Kitchen and two-a-days, to
bus trips for games at Waco and Corpus and San Antonio and icy
Kerrville, and to that scarf incident on the charter plane to El
Paso. To Friday nights under the lights at a packed House Park. And
to that state championship game in Dallas against the hated Wichita
Falls Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guys were players back then, some just fans and
classmates. These are men with wives and children and grandchildren
and professions. But memories of those days 50 years ago _ a time
before television and the pro sports explosion, when an Austin of
130,000 people focused so much on the one white high school in town
_ still stir them and unite them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take nostalgia trips, without guilt,'' says Hunter Morris,
a Maroon yell leader that fall and now a retired Episcopalian
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The memory machine for more than 1,200 Texas high schools gins
up again this weekend. The bus and car caravans formed Friday and
headed down the road and temporarily double the populations of
nearby towns. The small-town radio football analysts will take over
AM airwaves for a few hours a week. And each Friday, across the
state, dozens of boys will make a run or a diving catch or a
tackle, or a mistake, that will turn into a practiced war story by
the 10-year reunion, mythology by the 50th.
</P>
<P>
   The game doesn't get everyone, of course. Texas is too diverse
for that, and there are many competitors for our attention and our
passion. A good number of people think spectator sports overall are
a ludicrous waste of time and public capital. And that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   But for those in its thrall, the high school game defines autumn
in Texas. Let New England have the turning of the leaves. We'll
take an 0-0 record, the smell of cotton candy, football without TV
timeouts, and the possibility that this might be the year our kids
make it to state.
</P>
<P>
   ``High school football to me is the purest game there is,'' says
Rodney Williams, a halfback and leading rusher for that 1950 Austin
High team. He lives in Fort Worth now. ``There's no big bucks.
You're playing for the school. You're playing because you love to
play. It's just a whole different attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoolboy football _ in Texas especially, but everywhere _ is
essentially cheap and available entertainment. It's 25,000 to
30,000 boys, 5,000 or so coaches and tens of thousands of co-ed bit
players and backstage crew saying, ``Let's put on a show.'' It's an
August-to-December (for the fortunate) miniseries to determine
survivors, complete with bright lights, boot-black makeup on the
actors' faces, music during the breaks, a little sex appeal on the
cinder track, mostly bloodless violence and loosely choreographed
grace on the field, reviews in the morning paper and gold-embossed
statuettes at the end for the best performers.
</P>
<P>
   Its appeal is that it is at once extremely real, and completely
fleeting, to its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Actual injuries occur, some of them disabling or, once in a blue
moon, fatal. Coaches lose jobs over bad teams, or a string of them,
or sometimes one glaringly boneheaded decision. Boys win or lose
scholarships to college, and wide spots in the road make it onto
the map of Texas' consciousness. Players create memories and
self-images, good or bad, that linger into old age.
</P>
<P>
   These things really matter.
</P>
<P>
   But in increasingly urbanized Texas, especially in the big
cities, they don't matter as much as they used to. School board
trustees, scratching for money to pay teachers or the state, aren't
as likely to plow money into first-rate weight rooms and uniforms
and coaches. Athletic kids have so many other options _ whippety,
would-be wide receivers playing forward on the soccer team, rangy
potential defensive ends concentrating on basketball _ and so does
the student body. The fever still burns at suburban Westlake High,
with its sold-out stadium and metronomic success. Austin district
schools, though, mostly play to half-empty stadiums now.
</P>
<P>
   But each fall, at least until the first frost and mostly in
Texas towns still small enough to have a sense of place, high
school football can still grab a community and wring it giddy. In
1950, Austin was still one of those places.
</P>
<P>
   Westlake of its time
</P>
<P>
   Austin High _ a punching bag these days routinely pummeled by
Westlake _ was in fact the Westlake of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   From 1939 to 1950, Austin won 118 games _ almost 10 a season _
and went to the playoffs seven times and played in three state
championship games.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, they weren't the only good high school team in town.
Anderson, descendant of the ``colored'' school created a couple of
years after Austin High in the 1880s, won six district titles in
that same period and was the 1942 state champion among black high
schools. But in the rigidly segregated Austin of that time,
Anderson's victories were like a tree falling in a small grove set
off from the big forest nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The Maroon games were broadcast to a large radio audience, up to
50,000 by one newspaper account. The Maroons played before crowds
of 8,000 to 15,000 all year long. And Austin's march to the 1942
state championship was front-page news for days. Anderson's similar
victory two weeks earlier merited 79 words on the bottom half of
the Austin American's sports page. It was a different time.
</P>
<P>
   Austin High, meanwhile, had almost 2,700 students and an
assembly line of well-stocked B and C teams training boys to run
the varsity's single-wing offense. The 1949 team made it to the
Class 2A state championship game against Wichita Falls, losing by a
single point after a late field goal attempt was ruled wide _
incorrectly as seen through Maroon-colored glasses.
</P>
<P>
   But all but one offensive starter and several on the defense
graduated. Expectations were guarded for 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The season began with a road trip to Waco High and a House Park
game against Fort Worth Arlington Heights.
</P>
<P>
   For Delano Womack, a junior tailback in 1950, Waco was the first
game in a career that would lead to him starting for the University
of Texas three years. Womack, a sinewy and sunny man who even at
age 66 looks as though he could drop 10 pounds and be ready to put
on the pads, wasted no time storing away some memories. He scored
two touchdowns in the 21-0 win over Waco. Then, with less than two
minutes left against Heights, with the Maroons behind and folks
gathering up their stuff in the stands, he broke off a 63-yard run
for the 18-14 win. He can still retrace his steps on the run, and
the key blocks ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't forget something like that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After losing 27-0 to San Antonio Jefferson, the Maroons won
their remaining seven regular season games. Austin, with huge
linemen who routinely outweighed the other side by about 20 pounds
apiece, tended to wear down opponents. A creative Austin American
reporter described the line as ``lumbersome.'' The team's passing
was shaky, at best. But the head-banging approach worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a very dull team to watch _ three yards and a cloud of
dust,'' says Oliver Bradshaw, the spinner back and team leader who
normally got the shotgun-style snap and either ran, handed off or
passed.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights during that run: a 60-12 drubbing of a tiny El
Paso team, a trip memorable mostly for a few moments on the tarmac
at El Paso's airport. Some team members had developed sticky
fingers in the terminal, pinching some scarves for their
girlfriends back in Austin. Authorities observed the act, boarded
the Braniff charter and collected the booty. No one was arrested,
or suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The Maroons won district by easily beating Kerrville Tivy in
28-degree wet weather, eked by Temple in their first playoff game
and then stomped Harlingen. Womack was lost for the season in that
game, breaking his foot on an interception return.
</P>
<P>
   Austin traveled to Houston for the semifinal game in Rice
Stadium. The Baytown Ganders stuffed Austin's offense. But in the
fourth quarter, 140-pound Durwood Watkins caught a punt on the
25-yard line, shot forward and then cut left behind a wall of
Maroons for a 75-yard touchdown. Final score: 7-6, Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in Dallas for the state championship game was, once
again, Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   And it looked for a while like it might be different this time.
Bradshaw broke for an 81-yard touchdown in the second quarter. A
few minutes later, Austin lined up for a field goal that could have
made it 9-0. Again, a close _ and disputed _ miss. Wichita Falls
scored to go ahead just before the halftime break.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a nightmare second half, especially for Bradshaw. His
short punt led to a Coyote touchdown, as did a later interception.
His fumble stopped another drive. The Coyotes darted around the
larger Maroon defense and won 34-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick,'' says Womack, who had spent the afternoon in a
walking cast on the sideline, trying to buck up his increasingly
discouraged friends.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, according to an Austin newspaper story the next day,
``had little to say about the engagement.'' This is what he says
now:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't hold my head up, because I knew I'd
disappointed my parents, my classmates, my teammates and everybody.
And the City of Austin. Good God, that was quite a thing. I never
felt so low in my entire life. ... It still kind of bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another show coming up
</P>
<P>
   For most of the people beneath the lights, unlike Bradshaw and
his teammates so long ago, the emotions and visions linger only
until they reach the car in the parking lot. Or maybe through
Tuesday or Wednesday of the next week, when events have been
massaged to death at work and the talk turns to something else.
After all, there's another show coming up Friday night, one with a
different cast, different costumes, altered stakes and maybe a
different setting across town or an hour or two down the road. And
there'll be a whole other season of shows beginning next September,
with new actors and some not-so-new, maturing into their roles. Who
knows what will happen?
</P>
<P>
   For some _ the players and coaches, but also those who love the
show _ events hang on longer. And that's OK, too. Bradshaw
remembers the jarring hits, the foes knocked into temporary
silliness or proper respect for his guts and leg drive. Womack
remembers the well-timed blocks in front of him providing a
free-form geometry for his serpentine dances to the House Park end
zone. Watkins remembers that wall of protectors forming down the
left sideline of Rice Stadium and the joy of an untouched sprint.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, they remember the pain of a gray December afternoon in
Dallas, when the script went awry and they were cast as foils for
the boys from Wichita Falls. They remember a delirious town and
school suddenly deflated by their failure to get it done. They
recall that feeling of death in the fourth quarter and quiet sobs
in the locker room of Dal-Hi Stadium. They can see these things
clearly, 50 years and lifetimes of marriage, child-raising and
career-building down the road.
</P>
<P>
   A later generation of Maroons recalls a clear and invigorating
night in 1969 when 21,000 people _ 21,000 for a regular-season high
school game _ came to Memorial Stadium to see Austin play two-time
reigning state champion Reagan. They remember the endless choruses
of the Na-Na song and the pep rally that morning in the gym that
surged out of control into a singing march through the drafty old
school's halls, grinning teachers standing by letting it happen.
They can see Kent Marshall's impossibly high rainbow pass down the
northeast sideline dropping into Don Hill's hands for a 50-yard
touchdown. They can see Mickey Macaluso, tall and thick-legged and
yet so smooth, breaking free off left guard and cutting back right
40-something yards into the south end zone. They recall savoring
Reagan's defeat the next day when local TV showed a tape-delayed
version. Ridiculous that we remember all that. We don't care.
</P>
<P>
   These things shouldn't matter. We shouldn't care so much about a
show, should we? But we do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
