<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WEB-SITE-OF-WEEK-LADN     09-01 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SITE-OF-WEEK-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Requiem for a Dream: Web site for the about-to-open independent
movie of the same name from Darren Aronofsky, whose striking sci-fi
first feature, ``Pi,'' also came with a beautifully done Web home
(www.pithemovie.com). &QL; 
Where: www.requiemforadream.com. &QL; 
What's cool: Based on a 1978 book by Hubert Selby Jr. (who also did
``Last Exit to Brooklyn''), the movie's site is a fractured,
phantasmic visual feast, opening with a faux commercial Web site,
then a second one, rended by what looks like technical snafus on
the site itself, and all undergirded by beautiful, haunting music.
It's not big on linearity, but its makers did a great job
stretching the artistic abilities of the Web. &QL; 
Features: Navigation is a challenge, because nothing is obvious or
straightforward. Click around when the screen stops changing, and
you'll probably start something else happening. There's a trailer
to the film (a 5.8-megabyte download, so be patient), but you may
be hard-pressed to find it. Though the film is rated NC-17, there's
nothing inappropriate on the site. &QL; 
You'll like this if: People who like both offbeat Web sites and
movies. &QL; 
___ &QL; 
Think your Web fave is good enough for Site of the Week? Send your
suggestions to davidbloomearthlink.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HURRICANE-CENTENARY-$     09-01 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CENTENARY-$ADV03-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GULF COAST CITY MARKS CENTENARY OF NATION'S WORST DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)   &HT;     (EDS: Stands for CENTURY-OLD-LETTER; note optional trims)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Dated Sept. 14, 1900, the letter from Charles
Rodewald Byrne to his wife Frances in Baltimore began with a
plaintive question: ``Darling, Darling, Darling, Where am I to
begin to tell you this sad, sad story?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God there were none of you here to run the awful risks
and thank God a thousand times you were not here to witness sights
such as perhaps were never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are sodden with grief. We meet people and they tell
us pitiable tales, at every corner, and we can only answer, `God
help you, we can absorb no more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne wrote the letter six days after a ferocious hurricane hit
Galveston taking at least 6,000 lives and destroying 3,600 houses.
A century later, it remains the nation's greatest natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Never before published, Byrne's letter opened with a circumspect
inventory of loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, your people are all safe _ Harris lost three sisters.
The Davenports lost three children, that is, all but one. Our
neighbors Mrs. Fordtran and sister are dead. Fordtran is still
looking for his wife's body. I believe it is under the Ripley house
in our lot. They found his sister in our place,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, he wrote: ``It was chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   On that fateful Saturday in early September, Galveston's
children frolicked in the rising Gulf waters before their parents
sensed the coming danger _ too late.
</P>
<P>
   Those who survived the 120 mph winds and the 20-foot tidal surge
that hours later washed over the narrow island in the Gulf of
Mexico, staggered forth Sunday morning to a sunny new hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out into the streets and most horrible sights you can
ever imagine. I gazed upon dead bodies lying here and there. The
houses all blown into pieces; women, men and children all walking
the streets in a weak condition with bleeding heads and bodies, and
feet all torn to pieces,'' recalled Charles Law, a visiting
salesman caught in Galveston by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed, the saddest of sad stories, told many times over
in the letters and chronicles of the survivors, and the stark
photographs of the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   But it has taken Galveston a full century to tell it publicly.
Now, for the first time, the city is poised to embrace and examine
the cataclysm that changed the city forever.
</P>
<P>
   The four days of commemorative events will include panel
discussions by authors of storm books; memorial services and the
placement of wreathes; a centennial tribute at the local stadium
featuring CBS News anchor Dan Rather as keynote speaker; and the
dedication of a large bronze statute on the granite seawall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approaching it in the same way I'd approach a funeral.
It's a time of reflection on how lucky we've been and how chance is
so involved in our existence,'' said Kenneth Shelton, a Galveston
native and great-grandson of the letter writer, Charles Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will mark a time of a lot of introspection by the people
who love this city for what it was, who love the vestiges and
remnants of it, and also for the great personal loss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Days before it hit Galveston, the unnamed storm pummeled Cuba
and the Florida Keys, before confounding meteorologists, who
forecast a route north. Instead it moved rapidly due west.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Sept. 8, 1900, the storm made landfall about
30 miles west of Galveston. Between 6,000 and 8,000 people died in
and around the island. The exact number was never known.
</P>
<P>
   For months afterward, the bodies of unidentified victims found
in the ruins were burned _ along with the corpses of livestock _ in
funeral pyres on the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge piles of burning wreckage, in which bodies of victims
were being consumed, became such an usual spectacle, as to create
no comment,'' recalled Ben Stuart, a Galveston newspaperman who
weathered the storm.
</P>
<P>
   It was a disaster of epic dimension, many times more lethal than
other, better-known catastrophes such as the San Francisco
earthquake of 1906 (452 killed) or the Chicago fire of 1871 (250
killed).
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, a visitor wandering the city's streets would find few
clues that anything even vaguely noteworthy happened here a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart superstore now sprawls over the beachside site of the
old St. Mary's Orphanage where 10 nuns and 90 children died while
praying and singing, ``Queen of the Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-foot high seawall, built in the aftermath of the
hurricane, is decorated with cartoonish crabs and big-eyed fish.
</P>
<P>
   From the beachside Voodoo Daddy bar to the tee-shirt shops on
the Strand, from the medical school to the new beach homes in the
west, there are no statues or inscribed chunks of marble to
commemorate Galveston's horrific misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than a marker in the cemetery over the graves of some of
the unknown dead, there is nothing,'' said Michael Doherty,
chairman of the commemoration committee and a descendent of storm
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was such a place of business and commerce, and it (the
storm) was bad for business. It was our family story, and you
didn't talk about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such was apparently the case 50 years ago at the half-century
anniversary of the storm. No records exist of any public events
held then and a story about the hurricane published in the
Galveston News appeared on page 5.
</P>
<P>
   But the city has been preparing for two years for the 100th
anniversary, and its approach has prompted new books and re-issues
of volumes published 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Larson, whose best-selling book, ``Isaac's Storm,'' has
introduced hundreds of thousands of readers to the tragedy, said
that for many Americans it is a new story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Texas, few people knew about this storm until my
book came out,'' he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the kind of event that was installed in the
national psyche like the Johnstown flood or the San Francisco
earthquake, so there's a fundamental fascination that anything so
horrible could have gone unnoticed by the culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Galveston where island-born residents are never far from
the radio during hurricane season, the storm of 1900 is unreal to
some.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the more recent arrivals, it's more abstract. Look at the
west end of the island. There are palaces on stilts beyond the
seawall,'' Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Present-day Galveston is a quirky, eccentric place, mixing a
beach town's tacky charm and poor, rundown neighborhoods with
pockets of majestic Victorian homes. Improbably attached to the
east end is the University of Texas Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years ago, Galveston was a far grander place. As the
new century dawned, the ``Oleander City,'' was a center of wealth
and commerce, sustained by an insouciant self-confidence in its own
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston, the first city in Texas to have telephones and
electricity, was cosmopolitan and sophisticated. In 1900 was the
third largest city in Texas, trailing only San Antonio and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In that golden era, Galveston had one of the highest per capita
incomes in America, its port was the busiest in the South.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GALVESTON, Texas: x x x in the South. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Galveston sat low on a narrow, barrier island, and to ships
approaching from the Gulf, it was a mirage, a city that floated on
the waters.
</P>
<P>
   Its sense of invulnerability was also an illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though its highest point was less than nine feet above sea
level, Galveston was sublimely confident that no hurricane could
harm it.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Cline, the subject of Larson's book, was the chief of the
National Weather Bureau station in Galveston in 1900 and had
studied the situation.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech several years earlier, Cline dismissed the
possibility that Galveston could be seriously menaced by a
hurricane as ``an absurd delusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Sept. 8, 1900, there was no hint that
anything beyond a mild storm was in the works. Most expected just
another ``washover,'' that would quickly pass, leaving behind wet
streets and gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sept. 7, the Weather Bureau extended its storm warning
west to Galveston. The next day, Cline became alarmed by the
falling barometer and rising ocean swells, and attempted to warn
people of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   His last cable to his superiors in Washington D.C., transmitted
at 2:30 p.m. said in part that ``the city was fast going under
water and great loss of life must result.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, Galveston was connected to the mainland by three
railroad trestles and one long bridge, and all four were knocked
out by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who holed up on the bayside survived the storm.
Those who chose to ride it out on the Gulf side died by the
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   In the clinically-worded report he filed after the storm, Cline
began, ``The hurricane which visited Galveston Island on Saturday,
September 8, 1900, is no doubt one of the most important
meteorological events in the world's history. The ruin which it
wrought beggars description and conservative estimates place the
loss of life at the appalling figure, 6,000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, martial law was declared, and Galveston was
closed to outsiders. Looters and corpse robbers were shot on sight
and able-bodied men were conscripted at gunpoint to collect the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston's city fathers, who years earlier had considered
building a sea wall, wasted little time in acting after the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers commissioned by the city recommended a three-mile wall
of concrete, 17 feet high, to protect the eastern edge of the city.
The wall would have a concave face to push the force of the waves
upward, and be fronted with boulders of red granite.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers also recommended raising the city's elevation
behind the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The seawall project was begun in early 1903 and finished the
next year. A series of later extensions lengthened to more than
along the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Raising Galveston's grade was more complicated. It involved
jacking up more than 2,000 buildings, including the 3,000-ton St.
Patrick's Church, and then pumping in more than 16 million cubic
yards of sand.
</P>
<P>
   It was completed in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm was total, but the recovery was also total. It was
almost like building a city from scratch,'' said Casey Greene, head
of special collections at the Rosenberg Library, which has the
finest storm archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point I want to make is that we had visionary men and
women back then, to make it happen, and what is amazing is how
rapidly the city recovered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And although Galveston never regained its former prestige and
was quickly eclipsed by Houston, neither did it share the fate of
Indianola, a Gulf city that vanished after being hit twice by
hurricanes in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, the city was again struck by a ferocious hurricane, but
the sea wall protected Galveston. Only eight lives were lost.
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary nears, those who have spent years organizing
the events say they it will have two themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commemoration of the 6,000 dead, but it's also a
celebration of the recovery of Galveston,'' said Doherty, chairman
of commemoration committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the people stayed and rebuilt Galveston. They
built the seawall and they raised the grade of the city. We want
people to understand the tenacity of those who stayed. It's a
dramatic story, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
