<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BONDS-$ADV03-A     09-01 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BONDS-$ADV03-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOMERS TO KEEP BOND RALLY GOING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bond market this year has outperformed the stock market for
the first time in a decade, and Dr. Edward Yardeni, chief global
economist and investment strategist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
forecasts that aging baby boomers will help keep the bond rally
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that the 10-year government bond yield might fall to
5 percent by the end of next year,'' he said, from its current 5.68
percent, ``and to 4.5 percent by the middle of the decade.'' As the
bond's yield falls, of course, its price rises, giving investors a
higher total return.
</P>
<P>
   In making a case for bonds amid strong economic growth, Yardeni
points to a statistical measure, called the ``age wave,'' that he
developed many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although some other prognosticators are skeptical of the
measure's predictive value, Yardeni's arguments are food for
thought. The age wave tracks the percentage of the labor force that
is 16 to 34 years old; as baby boomers have aged, the age wave has
fallen.
</P>
<P>
   The path of that wave has been roughly parallel to that of
inflation and the 10-year government bond yield. All three hit a
trough in the early 1960s, crested during the first half of the
1980s and have generally been falling since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back now,'' Yardeni said, ``it turns out that this
wave has been remarkably well correlated with the wave of both
inflation and the bond yield,'' a trend that he has forecast will
last until 2010, when significant numbers of baby boomers are
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni, who began to write about the impact of demographics on
markets in the late 1980s, contends that there are sound reasons
for the correlation. As the baby boomers have aged, he argues,
productivity has improved, because older workers have more
experience than younger ones and are more committed to their jobs.
``Faster productivity growth,'' he said, ``would be an important
source of disinflationary pressure, pushing bond yields lower.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that older baby boomers tended to favor tax cuts
and less government spending. As the government buys back debt
securities and issues fewer Treasuries, there has been increased
investor demand for those securities.
</P>
<P>
   The age wave, meanwhile, has continued to fall. Having peaked at
51 percent during January 1981, the percentage of the work force
that is 16 to 34 is now down to 38 percent. The five-year moving
average of the inflation rate, as measured by the Consumer Price
Index, is down to 2.4 percent, just above where it should be, based
on the age wave. And the five-year moving average of the 10-year
Treasury note, at 5.71 percent, is about two percentage points
above where the age wave suggests it could be. One economist who
considers a yield drop of that size highly unlikely is Brian L.
Beaulieu, director of the Institute for Trend Research in
Contoocook, N.H., although he is still bullish on bonds, at least
for the near term. ``I think Dr. Yardeni has some valid points,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to using the age wave to predict bond yields,
he added: ``I think his assumptions do not bear up under close
scrutiny. The past is not necessarily prologue _ other factors will
affect the market. For instance, almost no one is looking at Japan,
a huge wild card. Its economy could slip back into a severe
recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at bonds, for the near term to 12 months, Beaulieu
favors government issues over corporates. ``I'm confident about
U.S. government bond yields,'' he said, ``but I'm not confident
about corporate rates, because there is still a fair amount of
inflationary pressure within the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the intermediate term, going out to 2003, both sides of the
bond markets will prosper,'' he said, ``while in the post-2003
period I think all the potential is on the downside for bonds.
There is a significant inflationary cycle headed toward us and that
is going to be sending bond prices tumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Fleming Asset
Management, had a different response to the issue of the age wave
and bond yields. ``Putting aside the powers of various theories, I
have only two thoughts concerning what lies beyond 2010,'' he said.
``One, I hope to still be alive, and two, I hope the planet is
still in one piece.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
