<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8581 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CARSMART-TOYOTA-AVALO     09-01 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSMART-TOYOTA-AVALON-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DO YOU SAY 'LESABRE' IN JAPANESE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By LEONARD M. APCAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Japan's automakers made a name for themselves in
the United States with small cars that were reasonably priced,
economical to own and fun to drive. Detroit sold small cars in
those days _ Chevy Vega owners, please stand up _ but its heart
wasn't really in it.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever Toyota, Nissan, Honda or even Mazda tried to beat
the Big Three at their game _ building trucks or big family cars _
they usually fell flat. There aren't many fan clubs or newsletters
for enthusiasts of the Toyota Cressida.
</P>
<P>
   Then, five years ago, Toyota brought out the Avalon, a
made-in-America family sedan aimed right at the business that
Buick, Chrysler and Oldsmobile had owned for years. Based on the
ever-popular Camry, the Avalon was a smooth-riding, well-padded
cruiser that was long on quality although a little short on flash.
It looked like a fancier Camry, which itself had styling that was
far from the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   Car buffs dismissed the Avalon as a Japanese Buick. But today
even Toyota executives use that description as shorthand for what
the car is about: Easy-riding, mid-range luxury for buyers in their
mid-50s, which is considerably younger than the average Buick
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Buick, by the way, has also transcended its reputation. Last
year, when I tested the redesigned LeSabre with an optional touring
suspension, I was surprised by the car's relatively crisp handling
and taut road manners. Taut? Crisp? These are not words one used to
associate with Buicks.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the Avalon measure up against the LeSabre? Pretty
well, actually.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 model, just about every visible element of the
Avalon was changed. It is wider and taller to give it greater
stature and more room inside. To add space, the dashboard was moved
forward several inches and the rear seat was set back a tad. The
result is a cabin built for stretching out.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most noticeable changes inside is a Buck Rogers
dashboard with a large, back-lighted liquid-crystal display showing
the date, time, compass reading and outside temperature. The
display is eye-catching, with amber lettering on a cool blue-green
background, but it is so large and distracting that it is hard to
get used to.
</P>
<P>
   The interior redesign results in more headroom, and in
significantly more legroom in the rear. Since the Avalon is now
wider, and there is little dead space between the doors and the
seats, it is not a stretch to call this a six-passenger car when it
is equipped with a front bench seat. In no car, including this one,
is the middle seating position comfortable for long, but the room
is there to put three adults abreast in front and rear. There are
three adjustable headrests in the back along with three shoulder
belts.
</P>
<P>
   All this interior decorating has produced an exterior design
that is, at first, jarring. The idea was to make the Avalon look a
lot different from the Camry, and it does. But it also comes off
looking a little dated in some ways, a little heavy and oafish in
others. The body seems high and disjointed, as if it was designed
by committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalon's flat sides hark back to the sheet-metal slabs that
Mercedes has scrapped on its biggest cars. The fixed windows behind
the rear doors serve as reminders of the opera-window craze of the
'70s. And behind the sizable trunk, the tail lights attempt to
mimic Mercedes but miss badly with oddly positioned backup lights
that detract from the otherwise simple design.
</P>
<P>
   But if prospective buyers find the Avalon's look ungainly, it is
not keeping them out of showrooms. Although the car is at the high
end of its price bracket, with a base price of $26,300 and fully
dressed XLS sedans exceeding $34,000, sales are up a whopping 90
percent from 1999. Business is so good that Toyota has increased
production at its plant in Georgetown, Ky., where the Camry is also
made. Clearly, many shoppers think the Avalon is worth its $4,000
premium over a comparable Camry.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, the Avalon is quiet and competent, just what you'd
expect from Toyota. Outside noise is pretty well muted, as are the
bumps and ripples of the road. Braking is superbly confident, and
while there was some minor hesitation in acceleration it was
insignificant. The four-speed automatic transmission was virtually
seamless.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalon executed corners well for a front-drive car of its
bulk, and while it backed away a bit in some twists of the road _
leaning a little here and there _ it fared better than most sedans
in its category.
</P>
<P>
   In a matchup with the LeSabre, I would give the Avalon a slight
edge. The ride is smooth and the handling is impressive, with no
hint of sloth. But a fully equipped LeSabre costs several thousand
dollars less than a loaded Avalon, and Buick currently offers a
$1,500 rebate, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   I was disappointed that the Avalon's 3-liter, 24-valve V-6
requires pricey 91-octane gasoline, particularly since the power
plant is quite similar to the regular-gas engine of the Camry. The
chief difference is that the Avalon V-6 has sophisticated variable
valve timing, which raises the horsepower rating to 210 from 194.
The good news is that the fuel economy rating ranges from 21 mpg in
the city to 29 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000-model test car came with some annoyances that were
surprising, given its $34,033 window sticker. For one, while there
were lots of thoughtful interior touches, like covered storage bins
in the doors, reading lamps and power outlets, the power-window
switches were not lighted at night. There were also inexcusable
rattles, some from the pull-down compartments in the doors. Every
time you closed the door or hit a bump the items inside
jingle-jangled.
</P>
<P>
   There were also rattles in the front cup holders _ particularly
surprising given that their lids, and the glovebox door, are
dampened to glide open slowly and softly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
