<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PBS BOLSTERS ITS PROGRAMMING FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PBS takes the prize for its quality, value-laden weekday
children's programming _ despite worthy competition, especially
from Nick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   What makes PBS the place to go is that it has and remains the
one outlet that consistently provides quality programming to the
youngest viewers, ages 2-6. The obvious bonus: no commercials. (The
same can be said for Nick Jr. during the shows, but those programs
are buffered by ads that have the little ones whining to Mommy
and/or Daddy within 2.3 seconds.)
</P>
<P>
   Now PBS is preparing to venture into the dark morass of Saturday
mornings while at the same time strengthening its weekday lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon has a great lineup of kids' shows, from the
surprisingly deep ``Hey, Arnold'' to the wonderful ``Rugrats.''
Nick Jr., the network's younger cousin, has ``Blues Clues'' and the
sweet ``Maisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it can't touch PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sept. 30, PBS will be offering a revamped
Saturday-morning lineup that continues the public network's
tradition of preschool programming.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the thumbnails for the new shows (check local
listings), which go under the umbrella title ``Bookworm Bunch'':
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Corduroy'': Based on Don Freeman's best-selling books,
Corduroy Bear and his African-American friend Lisa explore
diversity in an urban setting.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Elliot Moose'': From Andrea Beck's book series, this is a
combination of live-action, puppetry and animation.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Timothy Goes to School'': From Rosemary Wells' books.
Timothy is a 5-year-old raccoon who tries to do things on his own
four feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Seven Little Monsters'': From Maurice Sendak, author of
arguably the greatest kids' book ever, ``Where the Wild Things
Are.'' The seven monsters are siblings, each with monstrously
unique features.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``George Shrinks'': From the books of William Joyce, George is
3 inches of kid who's willing to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Marvin the Tap-Dancing Horse'': Set in a carnival, it is a
story of a 9-year-old boy who can communicate with the animals.
</P>
<P>
   The weekday schedule will feature two new kids shows.
``Caillou'' (pronounced ky-yoo) is a realistic animated show (with
some live-action and puppetry) in which the challenges of life is
captured through the eyes of the 4-year-old title character. The
kid is hyper and inquisitive, with more questions than Sam
Donaldson at a news conference after 12 cups of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Slight warning: In a sample episode released to critics, the
subject matter was death. It's handled artfully, but be prepared to
answer a lot of questions from little ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clifford'' sticks to the spirit of the Scholastic books.
Voiced by John Ritter of ``Three's Company'' fame, Clifford is a
really big red dog. The lessons are simplistic and sweet, the
pacing slow enough for younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   All right, ``Teletubbies'' still wigs me out a little bit. And
Loonette and the gang are a little too Insane Clown Posse-ish, but
you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
