<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8599 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-DAVIDON-SCULLING-     09-01 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DAVIDON-SCULLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DAVIDON GOES FOR SCULLS MEDAL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The doctor is in. Or make that back in.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Davidon, a surgical resident at Stanford University, was
one of America's best hopes for a medal in the women's single
sculls at Atlanta in 1996, but, hampered by a fractured rib, she
finished sixth. And shortly after, she took her oars out of the
water.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if her long rowing career might well be at an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I unloaded everything, including my boat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But elite athletes don't give up easily. Davidon kept working
out on a rowing machine, and then began running, biking and
cross-country skiing to stay in shape.
</P>
<P>
   When she could find the time, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were points during my residency when my only exercise
would be hauling some 250-pound guy across the operating table,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But then she began rowing again, under the guidance of coach
Steve Gladstone, and in January, she turned heads all around her
sport when she turned in a super-quick time on the ergometer, the
machine used to simulate rowing.
</P>
<P>
   While pleased with her time of 20:47, which was 1.4 seconds
better than erg standout Amy Fuller and 25 seconds better than
anyone else, Davidon said, ``I was surprised at how terrible I
felt. I was dying. I was coughing and sputtering _ it was
definitely very painful.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain produced plenty of gain, however.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic trials, Davidon, now 36, teamed with new partner
Carol Skricki to win an Olympic berth in the women's double sculls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thrown together right before the doubles competition
at the trials,'' Davidon said. ``We thought we were going to row in
the quadruple sculls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely different than singles. So much of my
energy now is spent in rowing identically with Carol. But it's just
great. I feel really lucky. There are a lot of personalities and
politics in rowing. I'm lucky to have a doubles partner who's got
her head screwed on straight, works hard and really wants to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Their three-month athletic union already has produced some
impressive results: two bronze medals and a silver in three races
in Europe last month.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has never earned a medal in the Olympic women's double
sculls, but Davidon said, ``Our coach seems to think we have the
best chance for a medal of any of the American doubles teams. It's
a very competitive event. The German doubles team is very strong
and accomplished, and everyone is predicting they'll get the gold.
But Carol and I are very hungry for it. Someone has to beat the
Germans some year, and we hope this will be the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidon's competitive rowing future is uncertain, but right now,
her complete focus is on the double sculls starting line in
Australia Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some final technical tweaking and tapering to do
before the start of the racing,'' she said. ``We have to win our
heat to go directly into the final Sept. 23, but if we don't, we'll
have a second chance two days later.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidon realizes she already has gotten one second chance, and
is grateful for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like having been in the Olympics before, and
not getting a medal, to give you the drive and determination to
return and win one,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
