<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHURCH-SCHOOL0902-COX     09-01 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-SCHOOL0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents: Monitor Sunday schools
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Church schools are gearing up for fall. They
promise kids enlightening spiritual lessons. But most parents are
completely in the dark about them.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday schools are arguably one of the most formative
experiences in a youngster's life. And most parents haven't a clue
what goes on inside those classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   They innocently entrust the minds and spirits of their children
to a largely volunteer faculty that has little biblical education
beyond their own Sunday school days.
</P>
<P>
   Most churches accept virtually any willing, warm body as a
teacher. Some offer modest training. Many teachers are simply
thrown into a classroom with a Bible and a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Those gracious, ever-suffering teachers impart to open minds a
sense of morals, values and religious faith that will linger with
the children throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They teach definitively about social issues, human sexuality and
the role of women. They try to shape a child to the will of God as
that church understands it.
</P>
<P>
   Parents know very little of what their kids are taught about
life's most profound subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Kids learn about the nature of God and what God wants of them
according to the way the church or the pastor or an education
committee interprets the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   They learn about themselves and others, about sin and grace,
hope, heavenly bliss and eternal damnation. Serious concepts of
guilt and forgiveness are routinely discussed. Impressions are made
that stick.
</P>
<P>
   Parents tend to ask few questions. They should ask many.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to the pastor. Talk to the church school coordinator. Visit
classes often and observe.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for a copy of the curriculum if there is one. What does it
say about God? About God's children? About the Bible? Are you
comfortable with its style and emphasis?
</P>
<P>
   How does the church treat Holy Scripture? Is the Bible literally
true, or is it an inspired but not strictly factual account of God
and his people? Does Genesis describe the precise manner of
creation?
</P>
<P>
   Some churches believe the Bible is a textbook for religious
behavior. Others consider it a poetic log of a spiritual journey.
Churches teach Scripture in radically different ways.
</P>
<P>
   What does the church teach about human sexuality, sex and the
sexes? Where are girls and women in the divine pecking order? Can
young women aspire to the same heights as their male classmates?
Some churches say no. Some parents want it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Does God forgive easily or condemn quickly? Must the child have
a spiritual conversion experience to be accepted by the church?
</P>
<P>
   Churches can teach children anything they choose. Some are
historically orthodox. Others are bizarrely heterodox.
</P>
<P>
   No one regulates churches. No one censors them. That's as it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   So parents must do their homework.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
