<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     09-01 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Sept. 2. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ President Clinton said Friday he
is not convinced the technology is at hand to build an effective
anti-missile shield and will leave it to the next president _ Al
Gore or George W. Bush _ to decide when, or if, to deploy a
national missile defense that is prohibited by a 1972 arms control
treaty. (Summary from wires) By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2,9, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-POLITICS (Washington) _ A look at the impact on the
presidential campaign of the delayed missile defense decision. By
Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Since he came to power in May,
Taiwan's new president, Chen Shui-bian, has labored to persuade
China that he is not a wild-eyed separatist, driven by dreams of
Taiwanese independence. But Chen's charm offensive has come to an
abrupt end. In an interview here Friday, he took a harder line
toward the Chinese government on the crucial issue of when _ or
even whether _ Taiwan and China will be unified. ``We don't think
unification is the only principle,'' Chen declared. ``There could
be two or three, or countless different conclusions. We see Taiwan
as a democratic country, with the people in a position to decide.''
By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ An appeals court Friday halted
at least temporarily the release of jailed Los Alamos scientist Wen
Ho Lee, who was expected to be home on $1 million bail. The 10th
Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver acted on its own, even before
the government, which is fighting Lee's release, could request the
stay. (Summary from wires) By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   NY-U.N.-INCONVENIENCE (New York) _ Forget that some of the
weightiest world issues are up for discussion next week during the
U.N. Millennium Summit, the biggest gathering of heads of state and
government ``in human history,'' as the United Nations says.
Poverty. Global warming. AIDS. Illiteracy. Urban decay. Let's talk
New York weighty: Unspeakable traffic snarls and 170-some
curb-skipping motorcades around Kennedy International Airport and
United Nations Plaza on the East Side. Several thousand Secret
Service agents elbowing their way through 36 hotels and countless
restaurants in pursuit of their 238 ``protectees,'' from President
Clinton to Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana of Tuvalu. By Dean E.
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Federal regulators issued a
public warning Friday that their review of Firestone's data had
found that tires on 1991 Chevrolet Blazer sport utility vehicles
and on some Nissan and Ford pickup trucks were even more prone to
failure than the tires already recalled on several Ford models,
mainly the Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration issued an unusual ``consumer
advisory'' saying that it had asked Firestone on Wednesday to widen
its recall, but that the tire maker had refused on Thursday to do
so. Firestone officials had no immediate comment. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ In another clear signal that the economy
is slowing in response to rising interest rates, the nation's
private employers created only 17,000 new jobs in August, the Labor
Department reported Friday, and the unemployment rate ticked up to
4.1 percent from 4 percent. The slowing was particularly noticeable
in manufacturing, where 79,000 jobs disappeared and the National
Association of Purchasing Management, in a separate report, said
that its index of manufacturing activity had turned negative for
the first time in 20 months. With consumer demand weaker,
manufacturers appear to be trimming production. The Federal Reserve
is unlikely to raise interest rates before next year at the
earliest, the argument being that the Fed's six rate increases
since June of last year have been enough to slow the economy to a
growth rate that the Fed considers non-inflationary. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-CHRONOLOGY (Undated) _ A little war against time has begun.
Last year, when the Museum of Modern Art opened the show ``Modern
Starts: People, Places, Things,'' Cezanne's ``Bather'' from 1885
was found hanging next to a 1993 Rineke Dijkstra photograph of a
pale boy in a maroon bathing suit. Later the Tate Modern, in its
permanent collection, lined up Matisse's sculptures of women's
backs before a firing squad of ink drawings of nude women by a
contemporary artist named Marlene Dumas. The critics were up in
arms. What got them was not the mixing of media or the mixing of
masterpieces with lesser works. It was the mixing of time periods.
As Jed Perl, an American art critic, put it in The New Republic,
``Chronology, that backbone of the historical sense, has been
collapsed into some kind of postmodern time warp.'' By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
