<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-WARNING-NYT &LR;      09-01 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.8 MILLION MORE FAULTY TIRES MAY BE ON ROAD, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal regulators warned Friday that an additional 1.4 million
Firestone tires pose a possible safety risk to drivers. They issued
the warning after their request that Bridgestone recall the tires
was refused, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The warning follows a recall early last month by Bridgestone,
Firestone's parent company, of 6.5 million tires. Safety
investigators have warned that the treads on those tires can peel
off in high temperatures and high speeds if they are
under-inflated.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration issued the
warning about possible defects to another 1.4 million tires, a
preliminary step to ordering a government recall, saying the tires
pose a possible safety risk.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said their study indicated that some of the 1.4.
million tires have higher rates of failure than some of the tires
included in the company's voluntary recall. The safety
administration said that although Firestone may not offer consumers
new tires, car owners should consider replacing any tires included
in the warning on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the investigation is not yet complete, that review
indicated that the rate of tread separation for certain other tire
models and sizes exceeded those of the recalled tires, sometimes by
a large margin,'' the safety administration said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The safety administration does not have the power to recall
tires until an investigation is complete. The statement said
regulators asked Bridgestone on Wednesday to recall the tires but
the company refused.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone did not immediately issue a response to the warning.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said they might order Bridgestone to recall the tires
when their investigation was finished, but decided to warn
consumers now. The safety administration told consumers with 24
additional sizes and brands of Firestone tires to take special
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should check the tires for wear, make sure they are
properly inflated, avoid driving at high rates of speed in hot
weather and avoid overloading the vehicle, regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety administration on Thursday increased by 26 the number
of deaths in the United States that have been linked to the
recalled Firestone tires. That brings to 88 the number of deaths
being investigated by the agency, along with more than 250 injuries
in 1,400 complaints it has received concerning tire separations on
popular sport utility vehicles manufactured by Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   The warning expanded the number of 15-inch Firestone tires
recalled and also added some 16-inch versions of the tires. A
complete list of the tires included in the warning is posted on the
safety administrations web site at:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nhtsa.gov/hot/firestone/consumer/consumer_09-01-00.html
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the continuing investigation by federal
regulators, congressional hearings will begin next week.
Investigators are hoping to learn why Ford or Firestone did not
recall the tires in the United States until months after learning
of problems with similar tires in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan officials on Thursday accused both Ford and
Bridgestone of conspiring to hide tire defects that caused dozens
of deaths. Venezuela's consumer protection agency asked the
nation's prosecutor to bring criminal charges against both
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies ``had concealed vital information from Venezuelan
consumers,'' said Samuel Ruh Rios, chairman of the Venezuelan
consumer agency. He said the companies were well aware that ``a
macabre combination of a soft suspension and an inadequate tire''
was to blame for at least 80 accidents in which 47 people died.
</P>
<P>
   The tires involved in Venezuela are similar to those being
recalled in the United States in that they are suspected of tearing
apart at highway speeds and causing Ford Explorers to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ford and Bridgestone officials denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In Dearborn, Mich., Jacques A. Nasser, Ford's president,
defended the company's actions in Venezuela and denied any attempt
to mislead authorities. Nasser said on Thursday that the company
did not lie to authorities and would cooperate with any Venezuelan
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser also promised to testify next week before congressional
committees investigating the tire failures and Explorer accidents.
Earlier this week he had said he would not appear, leading to
criticism that Ford was not being sufficiently open with the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser insisted that the problem ``was a tire issue, not a
vehicle issue,'' and said that 1.5 million tires had already been
replaced, representing 22 percent of the 6.5 million Firestone
tires being recalled.
</P>
</TEXT>
