<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AOL-0902-COX     09-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., EUROPEAN SCRUTINY GROWING OVER AOL-TIME WARNER MERGER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Executives for America Online Inc. and Time Warner
Inc. insist their proposed merger is facing no serious antitrust
obstacles. But eight months after their deal was announced,
government scrutiny is growing more intense, both in the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the European Commission, which sets anti-trust
policies for the 15 countries in the European Union, announced it
will take testimony from Time Warner and AOL executives at an
antitrust hearing Thursday in Brussels. The commission also will
hold a hearing Wednesday on Time Warner's plan for a music joint
venture with EMI Group PLC. The London-based company is the world's
largest music publisher and third-largest recording company.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, a confidential European Union document was
leaked to the media. The document, described in The Wall Street
Journal as ``sharply critical'' of both mergers, suggests European
regulators fear a combined AOL Time Warner/EMI would dominate
access to the Internet and wield too much power over the digital
delivery of music, film and sports programming.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to rule on the Time Warner/EMI deal
Oct. 18, and on the AOL and Time Warner merger Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Ken Johnson, a spokesman for Rep. W.J. ``Billy''
Tauzin , R-LA., chairman of the House telecommunications
subcommittee, said the chief executives of AOL and Time Warner will
testify on Capitol Hill later this month.
</P>
<P>
   At the House hearing, whose date has not yet been set, AOL's
Steve Case and Time Warner's Gerald Levin will be asked about the
merger's impact on interactive television, a new technology that
blends the Internet with television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to get a glimpse into the 21st century and see
what interactive television will look like,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Time Warner hope to put their merged company at the
center of the interactive television revolution with the help of a
briefcase-sized box that connects to a TV and telephone line. The
set-top box allows subscribers to AOLTV to use a wireless keyboard
to surf the Internet, send e-mails and flash instant messages on
the same screen where they are watching television. This summer,
AOL has been rolling out the service in eight test markets from
Baltimore to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech last month at a high-tech conference in Aspen,
Colo., Levin said that ``over time, there won't be any
distinction'' between television and the Internet. ``What we are
creating is really the first Internet-powered media-communications
company of the 21st century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the merger fear this next-generation television
technology could get locked up in one company's hands. Many
competitors, especially the Walt Disney Co., NBC Inc. and USA
Networks Inc., are warning that Time Warner could use its extensive
cable lines to force AOL Time Warner services and content on
captive consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said it was likely some subcommittee members will ask
Case and Levin about the antitrust implications of the merger.
``There are a lot of people who still have some concerns about the
competitive aspects of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Federal Trade Commission and the Federal Communications
Commission are reviewing the deal, and are expected to rule this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In his Aspen speech, Levin said he does not believe government
officials ultimately will oppose the merger on antitrust grounds
because AOL, an online access provider, and Time Warner, an
old-fashioned media company, are in different businesses. ``To my
view, I don't think there are any regulatory issues,'' he said.
``This is not a conventional, horizontal merger. There are no
business overlaps.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, AOL spokeswoman Tricia Primrose said the U.S. and
European hearings are ``part of the normal process of review'' and
do not threaten the deal. ``We believe the merger is on track to
close this fall.'' Shareholders of both companies already have
approved it overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more information: America Online at http://www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner at www.timewarner.com/corp
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
