<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOOTED-TREASURES-TAX-     09-01 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOOTED-TREASURES-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET CONCLUSION FOR CASE OF ART STOLEN DURING WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a decade of highly publicized legal wrangling,
international negotiation and criminal indictments, the famous
Quedlinburg art theft case has been quietly put to rest with the
agreement by two Texans to pay a total of $135,000 in federal and
state taxes, penalties and interest.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was reached April 20 in federal tax court but was
not publicly announced.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts and art professionals said the figure was
surprisingly low since until recently the government had been
seeking $8.6 million in federal taxes, $2.1 million in federal
penalties and more than $40 million in interest from the heirs of
an Army lieutenant who stole a group of priceless religious
artworks while stationed in Germany in the final days of World War
II. The heirs had been accused of trafficking in stolen property
when they tried to sell some of the objects, but those criminal
charges were thrown out several years ago, leaving only the tax
case.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the settlement were provided by Don Lan, a tax lawyer
in Dallas who represented Jack Meador, 80, a hardware salesman of
Whitewright, Texas; Jane Meador Cook, 66, of Mesquite, Texas; and
the estate of Joe Tom Meador, the Army lieutenant. Meador died in
1980; Jack Meador and Cook are his brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very favorable settlement,'' Lan said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers and art experts familiar with the drawn-out
proceedings expressed disappointment with the amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slap on the wrist,'' said Thomas R. Kline, a
Washington lawyer who represented the German government in its
efforts to recover the Quedlinburg treasures. ``It was a lost
opportunity to encourage dealers, museum people and collectors to
return stolen objects as a way of avoiding significant estate tax
liabilities. The reverse message was sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Constance Lowenthal, director of the World Jewish Congress'
Commission for Art Recovery, who followed the case closely, said
she, too, was disappointed by the decision of the tax court but
hoped that the case as a whole would act as a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Meadors have had 10 years without peace, and although the
criminal case against them failed on technical grounds they must
now realize that selling their brother's loot was the wrong way to
go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they repent or are regretful,'' she continued,
``but they are the poorer for it.'' Donald Roberts, a spokesman for
the Internal Revenue Service, said that the disclosure provisions
in tax law prohibited him from discussing the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Meadors also escaped the most serious criminal penalties
that might have been handed to them. In January 1996, the Meadors
and their former lawyer, John Torigian, 46, of Houston, were
indicted on federal charges of illegally selling two of the
treasures they had inherited, nearly three years after the German
government had paid them $2.75 million for the entire collection.
(The remaining artworks were not mentioned in the indictment.) Each
defendant faced a possible 10-year sentence and a fine of up to
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The federal indictment charged the three with conspiracy to sell
two of the 10 treasures: the Samuhel Gospels, a spectacular gold,
silver and jewel-encrusted ninth-century manuscript, and a
16th-century prayer book that is also of artistic and historical
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, as the case was coming to trial in Sherman,
Texas, a federal judge dismissed the charges on technical grounds,
saying the prosecutor had collected evidence beyond the lawful time
limit. When that decision was upheld by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in New Orleans, the criminal prosecution came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The artworks, long since returned to Germany, are part of a
group of medieval treasures, many of which were kept for a
millennium in the Schatzkammer, or treasure chamber, of the
Quedlinburg cathedral in central Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They were moved to a nearby cave to shelter them when the Allies
began widespread bombing of German cities in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Meador helped himself to 10 of the best of more than 100 art
objects in the cave.
</P>
<P>
   When returned to Germany in 1993, the treasures were exhibited
triumphantly in Berlin before being returned to the Quedlinburg
cathedral, which had been fitted with a modern security system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
