u f BC-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-NYT     09-01 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE AWARDS CONNECTICUT COMPANY $1 MILLION IN MICROSOFT LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has questioned the truthfulness of statements
made by Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, and awarded $1 million in
punitive damages to a small Connecticut company that brought an
antitrust suit against the giant software publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999 a federal jury in Bridgeport, Conn., found that
Microsoft committed a deceptive act that violated the Connecticut
Unfair Trade Practices Act, but awarded the plaintiff, Bristol
Technology, just $1 on that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives at the time had hailed the minimal fine as
a justification for the company's business practices. But U.S.
District Judge Janet C. Hall, who was permitted to award punitive
damages under the terms of last year's ruling, ruled Thursday that
the deceptive conduct in which Microsoft had engaged ``rises to the
level of reckless and wanton indifference to the harm it caused
Bristol and others.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time she noted that a $1 million penalty against a
company like Microsoft, with $14.5 billion in revenue last year,
would be unlikely to deter the company in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ruled that Microsoft's chairman gave an
intentionally false statement during a 1996 speech, in which he
assured other software companies and customers that Microsoft would
continue to provide its latest products for conversion to UNIX
programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8682 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COL     09-01 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATCHDOG GROUP SAYS POLITICAL LANDSCAPE TILTS TOWARD INCUMBENTS
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The congressional elections are still two months
off, but in the eyes of one monitoring group the results are
already in. And the easy winners are House incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Voting and Democracy says the power of historic
voting patterns dictates that House members will roll to
re-election this November and the parties will probably hang on to
the open seats they are defending. The group says the trend is
particularly true in the South, which it ranks as the least
electorally competitive region in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana and Florida rank at the bottom of the group's
Democracy Index based on the ease with which incumbents were
re-elected over the past decade. Georgia, Mississippi, Tennessee
and Virginia helped round out the bottom 10.
</P>
<P>
   Center director Rob Richie attributed the South's tendency to
stick with incumbents to its one-party past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is coming out of that tradition of a one-party situation,
where there was obviously a disenfranchising of a large part of the
population,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the group's take on what it calls ``dubious democracy''
is that once either the Democratic or Republican party gains
control of a congressional district, it is almost impossible to
dislodge it, resulting in a monopoly that ultimately drives down
voter interest.
</P>
<P>
   The group suggests a variety of solutions, including a focus on
the upcoming congressional remapping to make districts more
competitive and a move to larger, multi-member districts.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some naturally occurring changes in the political
landscape as well. Florida, for instance, has a handful of
competitive races this year and some challengers in Alabama and
North Carolina are raising enough money to throw a scare into
incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about time,'' said Richie, who nevertheless predicts
more than 98 percent of incumbents will be re-elected, most by
landslides.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN ON THE FARM
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers in 10 states in the South and Great Plains need to
devote more attention to education in rural communities or risk
leaving students behind, an interest group that promotes better
rural schooling warned in a new report.
</P>
<P>
   The Rural School and Community Trust said 10 states _ including
Alabama, Arkansas, Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi _ stood out
in a review that compared states by such factors as rural teacher
pay, Internet connections, poverty, enrollment and test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Declining enrollment in schools is widespread in these states,
teacher pay is consistently low and rural adults have low levels of
educational attainment,'' said the trust. It called for a renewed
focus on rural education not just in the 10 states, but across the
nation. ``Every state can improve the policy climate within which
its rural schools operate.''
</P>
<P>
   GUNNING FOR TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Southern states typically don't fare very well when their
policies are reviewed by gun-control groups. But Kentucky set a new
standard in the recent report card issued by Handgun Control Inc.
when the advocacy group ranked states by their efforts to keep guns
away from juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   The group gave the Blugrass State an F-minus for not only
failing to enact tougher safeguards to limit access to guns by
youngsters, but for weakening its existing concealed weapon law.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when we are still losing 10 young people a day to
gun homicides, suicides and accidents, the failure of so many
states to strengthen their gun laws is unconscionable,'' said Sarah
Brady, chairwoman of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Grades of other Southern states included Alabama, F; Florida,
C-minus; Georgia, D; Louisiana, F; Mississippi, D; North Carolina,
C; and South Carolina, C.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON FRESH SCENT
</P>
<P>
   Citrus groves and hog farms might not have much in common, but
they are linked in a congressional fight that will resume when
Congress returns after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The National Pork Producers Council wants congressional
negotiators to strip an import ban on Argentine lemons from a
pending farm spending bill. The group fears the citrus restrictions
could provoke a protectionist response and shut off a potential
market for ``the other white meat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be unreasonable to expect Argentina to delay
indefinitely the approval process on pork and other American
agricultural products,'' wrote council president Craig Jarolimek to
key lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus growers say they are worried such imports could include
diseased fruit that would threaten domestic groves. But the pork
group says rules would be in place to cut such risks.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
