<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8683 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-01 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU KNOW YOU'RE OLD WHEN... 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you do not have your own, personal teen-ager, chances are you
do not fully comprehend how out of touch you are with the younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am lucky enough to have a 14-year-old living in the same
house with me, I am reminded of my out-of-touchness every day. The
generation gap appears to me in increments rather than all at once.
It's less frightening that way, I think, and it makes you more
likely to view teen-agers as people rather than alien life forms.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I felt rather sorry for that segment of the
non-teen-ager-owning population that read the story in last
Sunday's paper called ``Mindset of the Class of 2004.'' The 50-item
list is published annually by the faculty of Beloit College, a
liberal-arts school in Wisconsin. The idea, according to humanities
professor Tom McBride, is to remind the faculty (some of whom may
be 50 years older than the arriving freshmen) of the cultural gaps
between the generations and how these gaps need to be taken into
account when teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The first bitter pill that readers had to swallow was that this
year's freshmen (or first-year students as they prefer to be called
these days) were born in 1982. If you are 50-ish or older, 1982
does not seem that long ago. According to our memories, which are
stuffed with TV commercial jingles from the '60s, Beach-Boy song
lyrics and the names of elementary-school teachers, the period
between 1982 and today zipped by in about 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   We can't remember what we did yesterday but we can easily
remember when we were freshmen in college. Unhappily, that day was
30-plus years ago, an era that today's first-year students have no
more personal memory of than we do of the Bronze Age.
</P>
<P>
   What are some of the ``cultural touchstones'' that identify the
class of 2004?
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan was shot before they were born.
</P>
<P>
   John Lennon, Elvis and Karen Carpenter have always been dead.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody named George Bush as been on every national ticket,
except one, since they were born.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy tragedy was a plane crash, not an assassination.
</P>
<P>
   They were born into war. The Falklands war.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has never been a monopoly in their lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``E.T.'' came out the year they were born.
</P>
<P>
   They have never known a world without ATM machines.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate is as relevant to their lives as the Teapot Dome
scandal is to ours.
</P>
<P>
   They're not angry at the recording industry for making all their
vinyl LPs obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes have always had men's and women's names.
</P>
<P>
   When they use the word ``spam,'' chances are they're referring
to something having to do with computers rather than the canned,
pink luncheon-meat substance.
</P>
<P>
   Same with ``cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   They never thought of Jane Fonda as ``Hanoi Jane,'' nor
associated her with any revolution other than the ``Fitness
Revolution'' videotape they may have found in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   They remember the Vietnam War about as well as we remember the
War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the Cuban crisis was all about Elian Gonzalez, not
Soviet missiles.
</P>
<P>
   They have never known a world without AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Depressing? Sure. But there is a bright side. In 25 or 30 years,
they'll be starting sentences with ``Back in the '80s'' or ``When I
was your age'' and they'll be boring the ears off their own
teenagers with tales of how much better things were ``back then.''
</P>
<P>
   And then they'll be the ones feeling old, like we do now.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
