</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO LEAVE DECISION ON MISSILE SHIELD TO HIS SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 2,9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: See MISSILE-ASSESS and related stories) 
(Will update later if needed) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT with JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Friday that he would not
take the initial steps to deploy a national missile defense shield,
leaving to his successor the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   At a speech at Georgetown University, Clinton said he would not
approve construction of a radar station on an Alaskan island, the
first step in creating the missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that although the technology was promising, the
system was not yet proven. He cited the failure of the most recent
tests, and questions about the ability of the missile interceptors
to deal with decoys and countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore I have decided not to authorize deployment of a
national missile defense system at this time,'' Clinton said. ``We
need more tests against more challenging targets and more
simulations before we can responsibly commit our nation's resources
to deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his decision not to deploy a missile defense would
not significantly delay the deployment if the next president
decided to proceed with building the radar station and beginning to
install the national defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser,
telephoned congressional leaders Thursday evening to brief them on
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Berger told the congressional leaders that Clinton was delaying
the decision because of technical concerns, including the failure
of recent tests, and the objections of Russia and NATO allies, who
argue that deploying a missile defense would violate the
Antiballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in his speech that the Antiballistic Missile Treaty
was an important element of national security and international
stability. Building a national missile defense would, however,
require abandoning or altering the treaty with Russia, something
the Russian government opposes.
</P>
<P>
   He said that despite the end of the Cold War, deterrence was
still important in reducing the risk of conflict with Russia, and
that preserving the treaty was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are no longer adversaries we are not yet real
allies,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Russian reaction to Clinton's decision was positive.
Gen. Leonid Ivashov, head of the international military cooperation
department of the Defense Ministry, told the Interfax news agency
that he was hopeful that the decision meant that the United States
would take a ``considered approach'' before deploying a missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton said that ballistic nuclear missiles were
still a threat to national security and that although North Korea
had reduced its missile testing program, there was still a threat
that a terrorist group could acquire ballistic missile technology
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to determine the feasibility and impact
of a national missile defense,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision comes after opposition not only from Russia
but from European allies, and after a legal dispute over how far
the system could proceed before it violated an important arms
control treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday that the United States should not move
forward until other nations could be convinced that a missile
defense was in the best interests of world security.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation can have a veto over American national security,''
Clinton said. ``But we can never afford to overlook the fact that
the actions and reactions of others in an interdependent world do
bear on our security.''
</P>
<P>
   William Cohen, the defense secretary, a Republican and the
Clinton administration's strongest supporter of the missile
defense, had recommended that Clinton begin construction of the
radar site in Alaska. But Berger and other diplomatic advisers
argued that taking the first step toward deployment was not worth
the consternation it would cause among the Russians and Western
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen issued a statement Friday supporting Clinton's decision to
continue research on the missile defense system and leave to his
successor a decision on deploying it.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will probably delay the next test until January,
administration officials said Thursday. Clinton said it was
important to continue research to answer questions about the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national missile defense should be part of a larger strategy
to preserve and enhance the peace, strength and security we now
enjoy and to build an even safer world,'' Clinton said. ``I have
tried to maximize the ability of the next president to pursue that
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had requested bids for initial construction of the
radar site in Alaska, setting Sept. 7 as the deadline for technical
and cost proposals from contractors. The first contracts would have
had to be awarded by December to permit building to begin next
spring and to have the $60 billion system in place by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush has vigorously endorsed proceeding with the
missile shield, which was first supported by President Reagan to
defend against any threat from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has been noncommittal about whether he
would proceed with a defense, but has said he supports continued
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush reiterated his support for the missile defense,
and criticized Clinton for failing to deploy the system. Bush said
that a system should be tested thoroughly to make sure it works,
but that if he was elected president he would renegotiate the
Antiballistic Missile Treaty with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration missed an opportunity to develop a missile
defense system that will protect all 50 states, protect ourselves,
our allies, from accidental launch or political blackmail,'' Bush
said. ``Should I become president I will seize the moment and
develop an effective antiballistic missile system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
