<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-C     09-01 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S ZEDILLO LEAVES OFFICE A WINNER, DESPITE PARTY'S LOSS
 &HT;    EDs: This story will be updated, re-topped following President
Zedillo's speech scheduled to begin at 7 p.m. CT (8 p.m. ET).
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ He's been dismissed as the accidental president, a
bespectacled economist who often appeared nerdy and ill-tempered.
</P>
<P>
   But three months before he leaves office, Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo is viewed as an exceptionally positive figure at
home and abroad. Friday night, Zedillo delivers his last State of
the Union speech after a six-year term that began in December 1994
with one of the worst economic crises in Mexico's history.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, Zedillo has stabilized Mexico's economy and has
promised that this country will not follow a 30-year pattern of
fiscal crisis that has plagued every new president who takes over.
More than any other accomplishment, however, Zedillo is
acknowledged with helping orchestrate sweeping electoral reforms
that led to the defeat of his own party _ the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI _ after 71 years of presidential
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's defeat, which Zedillo acknowledged gracefully the
night of Mexico's July 2 presidential election, is probably his
greatest legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernesto Zedillo is going to leave office with a great public
legitimacy. I think few Mexicans have much to criticize. Those who
are criticizing him are a small group of PRI insiders who probably
don't number more than 1,000,'' said political analyst Jaime
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who thought the president could still
engineer fraud to win elections,'' Gonzalez added.
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo knew Mexicans were clamoring for fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great defect of Zedillo's presidency,'' Gonzalez said,
``is poverty. And that will remain obscured largely because of what
else he accomplished. Plus, Mexicans know that Zedillo didn't
create poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in December 1995 _ a year after Mexico's over-valued peso
was slashed in half _ 60 percent of the public disapproved of
Zedillo's performance, according to Reforma newspaper. In a poll
Reforma published Friday, of 1,549 Mexicans surveyed nationwide,
Zedillo was given a 69 percent approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Zedillo has assured the country that
Mexico's laws have been reformed sufficiently to avoid the cycle of
crises caused by previous presidents' irresponsible handling of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   His has maintained tight fiscal discipline, which critics said
caused suffering among the poor and middle classes, and hurt his
reputation. And he reformed investment and banking laws to avoid
the damaging speculation that swept Mexico prior to his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo reluctantly became the PRI's nominee for president in
1994. He replaced Luis Donaldo Colosio, who was assassinated just a
few months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of today's high approval ratings, Zedillo's years in
office have been marked by a number of embarrassing events. In 1997
the anti-drug czar he had just appointed, Gen. Jesus Gutierrez
Rebollo, was charged with colluding with one of Mexico's most
wanted traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, 45 people in a pro-Zapatista rebel village
were massacred by PRI loyalists in the southern state of Chiapas.
Zedillo expanded the military presence in Chiapas in response,
deported some human rights observers and has faced criticism for
failing to resolve the original conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The former PRI governor of Quintana Roo state, Mario Villanueva,
went into hiding just as he was to be arrested on trafficking
charges in 1999. And for several years now, vows from Zedillo's
administration to arrest the leaders of a violent Tijuana-based
drug cartel have gone unfulfilled, drawing criticism from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, during a series of crippling floods here, Zedillo lost
his temper when visiting a disaster area and told one man to ``shut
up'' and show him respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zedillo has been unusually stubborn and obstinate,
fundamentalist, and politically, quite clumsy,'' wrote Milenio
magazine columnist Raymundo Riva Palacio. ``But Zedillo is
finishing his term as a president acclaimed throughout the world
for having ushered in the end of a closed system . . . These are
the paradoxes of public life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
