<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POLITICS-AD-0902-COX     09-01 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-AD-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS: BUSH AD IS INDEPENDENT EFFORT
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (p) political categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The Republican National Committee said Friday that it
had complied with federal campaign finance laws in spending soft
money to run an ad questioning Vice President Al Gore's commitment
to campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The legal issues raised by the 30-second television spot, which
began airing in 16 states Friday, revolve around the involvement of
the Republican presidential nominee, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, in
approving the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between coordination and collusion'' with
the Bush campaign, said Bill Pascoe, the party's press secretary.
``We are allowed to preview ads. We are allowed to coordinate the
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``they do not have decision-making authority.
They don't have veto power. They don't have control.''
</P>
<P>
   Pascoe said widespread press accounts that a week ago Bush had
personally blocked another proposed commercial that also would have
questioned Gore's truthfulness and which also would have been paid
for by the party's soft money coffers were in error.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Bush campaign) suggested that it not run,'' he said.
``They did not order us to do it. That would have been illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Such watchdog groups as the Annenberg Public Policy Center at
the University of Pennsylvania and Common Cause maintain that radio
and TV messages paid for by a political party must be produced
independently of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Bush and Gore campaigns have $67.5 million in taxpayer
funds to spend on their campaigns, including all ads. Although
federal regulators have rarely intervened, watchdog groups hold
that the laws set up a ``Chinese Wall'' between the campaigns,
which are blocked from using other funds, and any subsequent soft
money spending on their behalf. Soft money, as opposed to money
given directly to a candidate, can be raised in any amounts and
spent for party-building and advocacy ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous money in American politics is the
unlimited, secret contribution,'' said Fred Wertheimer of Democracy
21, a group that advocates campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The new Republican attack on Gore's credibility _ it also
ridicules his claim that he ``took the initiative in creating the
Internet'' while in Congress _ falls into the broad category of
issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, such ads can criticize or admire candidates,
but they are not permitted to directly advocate their election or
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996 campaign, congressional Republicans asserted that
President Clinton, having accepted taxpayer funds to run his
campaign on the condition that he would not spend any other money,
led a Democratic National Committee effort to raise $44 million in
soft money.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Republicans claimed the president and his aides
broke the law when they personally supervised the preparation of
such issue ads, with Clinton allegedly drafting some of the scripts
himself in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   They called on Attorney General Janet Reno to name an
independent counsel to probe whether improper collusion between the
party and the Clinton's re-election drive had spawned ads that had
violated election laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno held that such close coordination between a party and
its candidate is not in and of itself illegal. In any case, she
said, it was up to the Federal Election Committee, and not the
Justice Department, to enforce those laws.
</P>
<P>
   After auditing both the Democratic and Republican campaigns, the
commission staff recommended that they each repay millions of
dollars in taxpayer money for having allegedly exceeded their
spending limits. But the commission subsequently refused to
penalize either campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike unaffiliated groups, political parties, which are
regulated by the commission, must report their donors and use a
blend of soft and hard money to pay for their issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   For every $100 spent by the parties on issue ads, $65 can be
soft money, while $35 must be hard money, where campaign donations
are strictly limited. Both major parties, claiming they are
handicapped by the rule, have unsuccessfully sued the commission in
a bid to overturn it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
