<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-THEME-PARKS-52     09-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-THEME-PARKS-520(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN-STYLE THEME PARKS FLOURISHING IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRONTEN, Netherlands _ A paunchy kangaroo used to perch atop the
entrance to the old Walibi Flevo theme park here, a red ``W'' on
its sweater for the Walibi Group of Belgium, which ran the park.
</P>
<P>
   The kangaroo is gone now, and the old gate is, too, replaced by
a pastel-and-aluminum art deco facade, capped with the name Six
Flags Holland. On masts nearby flutter the flags of the
Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, France, Spain and the United States
_ the countries where the American owner, Six Flags Inc., a unit of
Premier Parks, operates parks.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd that the Dutch and other Europeans, surrounded
by glories like the canals of Amsterdam and the museums and
churches of Brussels, would flock to an American-style theme park.
</P>
<P>
   But they do. Europeans visited theme parks in record numbers
this summer, stirred by spreading affluence, booming tourism and
greater variety. In the last decade the number of theme parks in
Europe has increased by a third, to an estimated 83, according to
Economics Research Associates, which tracks the industry, while the
number of admissions has risen two-thirds, to 101 million last
year, and revenues doubled, to $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion is gathering momentum and drawing outside
investment, notably from the United States, transforming the
European industry, long known for family-owned, mom-and-pop parks.
Last year, Europe's 83 parks averaged about 1.2 million visitors
each, far fewer than the 2 million that packed into each of
America's 226 parks. And once inside, Americans were induced into
spending an average of $30 a visitor, against $22 in Europe. ``Our
trans-Atlantic cousins can still teach us a few things,'' David
Camp, an analyst in London for Economics Research Associates, wrote
to clients recently.
</P>
<P>
   But as Europeans rush to catch up, the Continent is increasingly
luring American park operators with expertise in design and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to buying the park and five others in Europe from
Walibi in 1998, Six Flags last year acquired Warner Brothers Movie
World, in Germany's densely populated Ruhr basin, and another
Warner studio park being built outside Madrid. The theme park unit
of Universal Studios also acquired control of Spain's biggest park,
Port Aventura, on the Costa Dorada near Barcelona. Universal, a
part of Seagram Co. that was recently bought by the French
conglomerate Vivendi, has ambitious plans to transform Port
Aventura into Europe's No. 2 park after Disneyland Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outflanked, Disney announced a major expansion last
year of its site at Marne-la-Vallee, east of Paris, including a new
studio park alongside Disneyland Paris.
</P>
<P>
   European companies are getting into the action, too. Global
Family Attractions, the theme park division of Lego System, of
Denmark, will open a $138 million theme park south of Munich in
2002. Like Lego's other parks in Denmark, Britain and California,
it will be based on Lego blocks. In Spain a $400 million park,
Terra Mitica, opened its gates this summer near Alicante in the
southeast, and as many as 20 other projects are in the works.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not that selling Europeans on magic kingdoms and Wild West
villages comes easily. In Belgium, laws prevent students from
working more than one month a year, so Six Flags continually trains
new crops of students for summer jobs. And not every slogan
translates well. For a season's-end Halloween festival, Six Flags
marketing experts puzzled over whether to call it a Fright Fest,
then dropped the name as untranslatable.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is every project an automatic winner. In Spain, investors
including Ogden Corp. of New York built a park called Isla Magica
on the site of the 1992 Seville world's fair. But Isla Magica ran
up nothing but losses after it opened in 1997, a victim of poor
marketing and high costs. Last spring, Ogden bailed out and sold
its theme park interests to a Greek investor after a consortium of
Spanish banks effectively took over Isla Magica.
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags' strategy in Holland, a kind of pilot project for its
European parks, illustrates the impact of fresh investment and
aggressive marketing. When the old Walibi park closed in October,
Six Flags mobilized hundreds of workers from a dozen countries to
complete almost $40 million of improvements, including the new
entrance, rides like a 115-foot Ferris wheel, and four additional
roller coasters. To generate more spending in the park, Six Flags
increased restaurant capacity by 50 percent and introduced 20
pushcarts offering snacks.
</P>
<P>
   To lure visitors back, Six Flags introduced a season pass, good
at all its parks. To nudge visitors to buy the pass, it increased
the single-entry ticket to 41 Dutch gilders, about $17, from 33.
The season pass is 160 gilders. Spending for television and radio
ads was sharply increased; to draw visitors for events like
conventions, weddings and birthday parties, marketing executives
fanned out to schools, social clubs and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were good facilities doing a reasonable profit,'' said
Daniel P. Aylward, Six Flags' managing director for Europe.
Aylward, a veteran at turning American parks around, ducks and bobs
as he shows a visitor through the park, snatching up litter as he
walks. ``But there were lots of opportunities for advertising and
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   For local politicians and planners, the investments and the jobs
are welcome. In Holland, the number of park employees, some of them
poorly paid performers, has grown to 700 from 300 in two years. In
Madrid, much of the $300 million investment in the new Warner
studio park is being borne by regional governments. While Six Flags
will manage the park when it opens in 2002, it will have only 5
percent ownership.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herman Otte, 38, who knew the old Walibi park, recently drove 60
miles from his home north of Amsterdam after hearing about the
refurbished Dutch park in a television commercial. ``It's more
attractive for children, and far larger,'' he said, as his family
made its way to a snack bar from the new Looney Tunes area, where
Bugs Bunny and his pals had cavorted in a musical sketch. Earlier,
Otte and his daughter Yanique, 3, had enjoyed the big new Ferris
wheel. ``She wasn't afraid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such visitors cheer executives at Six Flags' American parent,
for whom Europe brings the promise of renewed investor favor. After
Six Flags, then called Premier Parks, went public in 1996, its
share price roughly tripled in two years. The shares have tumbled
by 50 percent since the start of the year, though, with analysts
putting the blame on this summer's bad weather in parts of the
United States and a kind of consumer fatigue with leisure and
entertainment products.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly view Europe as a very ripe market to expand their
business,'' said Jill S. Krutick, an analyst with Salomon Smith
Barney. Last month, she cut her recommendation back a notch, to
outperform from buy. ``In Europe, there's an enormous opportunity
to consolidate the market,'' she said. ``It's very inefficient,
with many parks out there,'' adding that the biggest risk for Six
Flags lay in its management of the new growth.
</P>
<P>
   Kieran E. Burke, Six Flags' 43-year-old chairman and chief
executive, described the thrust into Europe as but one prong of a
broader international strategy that included Latin America, where
Six Flags operates a park outside Mexico City, and Asia, where it
is looking for places to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects,'' he said, ``we are really just getting
started,'' adding that the planned expansion would have
``significant ramifications for the value of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, as in the United States, Six Flags' strategy is to
operate regional parks, mostly for nearby day trippers, who often
become season ticket holders who might drop into the parks more
often, if only for a few hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   At Universal Studios, by contrast, the goal is to transform Port
Aventura, which this season was renamed Universal Studios Port
Aventura, into a destination park, perhaps adding a studio park to
the existing theme park, as well as hotels and sport activities
like golf.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tom Williams, chairman of Universal Studios' theme park
group, does not hesitate to say the goal is ``to turn this
single-gated attraction into a year-round family resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Aventura, which opened in 1995, packed in 3 million
visitors this year by the end of July, roughly the number it drew
in all 1999, when attendance rose 11 percent from the year before.
Under Universal's management, Port Aventura this year opened a $30
million submarine ride, Sea Odyssey, and next season plans another
blockbuster, Temple of Fire, in which visitors walk through flames.
By last year, Port Aventura was employing roughly 3,000 people,
generating $85 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Williams appears to be leading the expansion of Port Aventura
into an all-year destination resort along the lines of Universal
Studios Escape in Orlando, whose creation he oversaw before taking
the Universal job a year ago. The immediate plans for Spain, he
said, involve building two 500-room hotels for occupancy in 2003,
with meeting rooms allowing Universal to draw business and
convention travelers, focusing on a European market that Disney
once had pretty much to itself. Unlike Paris, with its cool and
cloudy climate, the Barcelona site, much like Orlando, boasts 300
days of sunshine a year and average temperatures of 72 degrees.
Indeed, the city was the runner-up to Paris when Disney chose the
location for its European park in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the 7 million annual admissions at Six Flags'
parks in Europe are little more than half the 12.5 million
Disneyland Paris packed in last year, and Disney is hardly in
danger of losing its leadership position. Last year, Disney, which
owns 39 percent of the company that runs Disneyland Paris,
announced plans for a new $615 million, 62-acre park that will
focus on film studios, animation and television.
</P>
<P>
   James Rasulo, the 15-year Disney veteran who is chief executive
of the French unit, Euro Disney, said attendance at the site should
rise from 12.5 million visitors last year to 17.5 million when the
new park opens in April 2002. To accommodate the increase, Disney
is negotiating with tour operators and hotel management companies
to build new hotels with a total 1,500 rooms, to add to the six
hotels with 5,160 rooms it now operates.
</P>
<P>
   Rasulo says the pattern in Europe apes that in America.
Improvements in the design and management of regional parks are
lifting the image of theme parks generally, ultimately benefiting
the market leader, Disney. ``Most of these guys are mimicking us,
in the layout of their parks, in the handling of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the pattern you had in the United States,'' he
added. ``More professionalism, and that drove more business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
