<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CREED-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      09-01 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREED-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: HOW CREED INSPIRES DEVOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Stapp obviously thinks he deserves to be a rock
god. The front man for Creed, the Florida-based band that packed
Madison Square Garden on Monday and plays a sold-out show Sunday at
Jones Beach, works to project the aura of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   At the Garden, in a gleaming white shirt and leather hip-huggers
that would have delighted his idol, Jim Morrison, Stapp made so
many heroic moves that it seemed as if this was his qualifying
routine for the front-man olympics. He pranced and crouched and
swept his arms heavenward, straining his enormous baritone, a
foghorn warning all contenders to watch out for his wake.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden audience clearly supported Stapp's victory bid.
Roaring along so enthusiastically that Stapp could regularly take
microphone breaks and let them take over songs, Creed's fans
reached their zenith on ``Higher,'' which rivals Santana's
``Smooth'' as the people's song of the moment. The audience didn't
just sing: They emoted, some nearly weeping, others raising their
hands as if undergoing a conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Stapp was raised in the Pentecostal faith, and although he says
he is not a practicing Christian, his lyrics resound with a
doubting Thomas' fear of God. ``Higher,'' which he says is about
lucid dreaming, still has a decidedly biblical chorus about golden
streets where blind men see. Such images are the meat of Christian
popular culture and have contributed to the band's phenomenal
success.
</P>
<P>
   That success is evident in the numbers. Creed's two albums, ``My
Own Prison'' (1998) and ``Human Clay'' (1999), have sold a total of
nearly 10 million copies, each spending almost a year on the
Billboard charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher'' is still in the Top 20 singles after 44 weeks,
despite never having been officially released in that form. The
sales are all the more notable because the band records for an
independent label, Wind-Up, as do the much touted teen-age stars on
Jive and the hip-hop artists on Cash Money and No Limit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the praise that the music business usually offers its cash
cows eludes Creed. The group has won awards from industry
publications like Billboard and technical magazines like Guitar
World. But it has no Grammy, boasts only one nomination at next
week's MTV Video Music Awards and has received middling-to-poor
reviews in most publications. Even Spin's recent cover story on the
band mustered only faint praise.
</P>
<P>
   Creed has not fared much better among its peers. Fred Durst of
Limp Bizkit started a feud with Stapp when both bands performed at
a KROQ-sponsored festival this summer, calling him an egomaniac. On
its recent tour, the pop-punk band Blink 182 made fun of Creed
every night.
</P>
<P>
   And so Creed has become the latest rock pariah.
Self-righteousness is part of its problem. Hipsters have little
sympathy for spiritual quests, especially those that bear the
mantle of Christianity. Stapp's lyrics, which have at times been
anti-abortion and anti-affirmative action, don't help.
</P>
<P>
   Yet religious faith is hardly unusual in music. Lauryn Hill made
a profoundly pious 1998 debut album and swept every awards
ceremony. Even the pornography-loving members of Blink 182 embrace
Christianity in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it fair to say that Creed just makes bad music. The
group's metallic rock plunders the outdated grunge style, but the
guitarist Mark Tremonti has his own ethereal approach. Stapp's
lyrics are overblown, but plenty of simplistic pop gets a big
thumbs up from the overextended, product-hungry media.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Creed is that Stapp is a true believer _
perhaps not in Jesus, but in himself, and in the rock 'n' roll he
discovered when he fled his church as a young man. He embodies the
belief that rock music can change lives; it changed his, after all.
He refuses to take it lightly. To many, his furtive embrace of rock
cliches makes him a clown.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music now runs on an engine of subtle self-loathing. Its
movers and shakers agree to believe that this is a degraded realm.
Plastic teen-age pop is admired for being calculated. Sexist and
homophobic lyrics in hard rock and hip-hop are justified because
they are offered in the spirit of a joke. The more self-consciously
trivial an artist can be, the better: He will make for a better
punch line on MTV or VH1.
</P>
<P>
   Earnestness is not completely dead. Artists like Bruce
Springsteen or U2 have earned emeritus status and get away with it.
Young geniuses like D'Angelo and Hill can be serious about soul
music because of their sheer musicality. A few bands have taken up
the countercultural torch, notably Rage Against the Machine and
Pearl Jam. These groups survive the occasional jab because their
fan base so strongly supports them.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, though, a group like Creed plods into the
spotlight, with not a whit of redeeming grooviness, and triumphs.
Such successes shine a harsh light on a void _ the lack of sympathy
for better artists whose passions mount as high. The belief that
popular music can raise consciousness is old hat. Everyone agrees,
except the 10 million people, most more conservative than
countercultural, who love Creed.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Christian rock, by that or any other name, is a
major story. Those who find Creed's pieties troubling might note
that outside the periscope of fashionable pop, such sentiments are
everywhere. The voices raised along with Stapp's prove that faith
is still a strong force for change. But that faith need not only be
self-righteous. It could as easily be pagan, radical and
anarchistic. It can take as many forms as the culture industry
allows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
