<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-01 1839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-GARDENCOLUMN 
JASMINE IN NEED OF A TENDER TOUCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
(c) 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
Q: I bought a night-blooming jasmine that was in full sun at the
nursery. I brought it home and put it in my atrium. The leaves
started turning yellow and dropping, so I figured maybe it had too
much sun, so I brought it inside by a bright window, but not much
direct sun. All the leaves are pale green or turning yellow and
dropping. Can I grow it outside? Supposedly it blooms in summer,
but it is not doing anything. _ C.M., Cypress, Texas
<TEXT>
<P>
   A: &UR;  &LR; Move the plant outside. But since it is in poor condition,
gradually introduce it to sun. Place in a partially sunny area, and
for the first few days, avoid the intense afternoon rays. Don't
overwater. This causes leaves to yellow and drop. Water, allow the
soil to dry some, then water again.
</P>
<P>
   When the scorching heat and drought eases, plant the
night-blooming jessamine (Cestrum nocturnum) in a sunny or
partially sunny spot. Plant in an organically enriched,
well-draining soil. Mulch, and reapply mulch for protection during
cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   This plant does produce small, but highly fragrant flowers mid
or late summer into fall. Those in our garden have just a few buds.
There's a chance yours may bloom this year, but I would just
concentrate on restoring healthy growth for now.
</P>
<P>
   This shrub is inclined to be irregular in form. Prune heavily in
late winter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you advise when and how to fertilize and prune
camellias, crape myrtles, gardenias, hibiscus, jasmine, roses and
wisteria? _ A.J.C., Houston, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: &UR;  &LR; Proper soil and proper light are keys to good shrub and vine
health. An organically enriched soil that drains well will serve
all these plants well and decreases the need of frequent
fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   Grow camellias in a raised bed of equal parts topsoil, sand and
pine bark to help ensure good health and growth. A slightly acidic
soil with a pH of 5-7 is important. Organic matter is important as
it boosts soil porosity, crucial to camellia health, as well as
acidity as the pine bark breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias grow well in containers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias need a moist but not soggy soil. City water is
alkaline, and when used on camellias, it often becomes necessary to
counteract alkalinity by adding agricultural sulfur or a
quicker-acting chemical such as iron sulfate to acidify the soil.
Yellow, chlorotic foliage is a symptom of an overly alkaline soil.
Yellow leaves also can be a sign of poor drainage or too much sun.
</P>
<P>
   A well-draining spot that receives morning sun and some filtered
shade is ideal. Pine trees create an excellent environment for
camellias. It's best to protect the plants from cold winds and hot
afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias are slow growers and therefore do not require heavy
fertilization. Do not overfertilize. Do not fertilize the first
year after planting. The Houston Camellia Society suggests using a
commercial camellia fertilizer after flowering and again around
mid-May. A light application of cottonseed meal, a slow-release
organic nitrogen fertilizer, is helpful in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Prune camellias after flowering.
</P>
<P>
   Crape myrtles are not picky about soil, but a humus-enriched,
well-draining soil is ideal. Crapes have the reputation of being
drought-tolerant once established, but don't skimp water during dry
periods such as we're experiencing now. There are wilted crapes
around town.
</P>
<P>
   The key to a full head of blooms is an abundance of sun and good
air circulation. These conditions also discourage powdery mildew, a
fungal disease that can be troublesome to some crape varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Many prune heavily with the thought that more new wood produces
more flowers. Do not top crapes. Such heavy pruning can lead to
diminished tree health. The vigorous new growth is weakly attached
and prone to snap in bad weather. This, in turn, makes the tree
more susceptible to insects and disease.
</P>
<P>
   In January or February, remove weak and dead wood (some remove
any wood smaller than a pencil) and water sprouts along the
branches. This will encourage a clean, strong and naturally shaped
skeleton. Keep root suckers removed at all times. Remove spent
blooms to encourage more flowers.
</P>
<P>
   When grown in good soil, crape myrtles do not require heavy
fertilization. Crapes bloom on new wood, and an early spring
application of a 3-1-2 formula will encourage that growth. Some
gardeners apply a formula with more phosphorus, represented by the
second number in the formula, but phosphorus does build up in our
soils, so don't overdo it. An application of a balanced fertilizer
in June is beneficial when soil fertility is low. But avoid
late-summer fertilization, which encourages growth susceptible to
early freeze damage.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize gardenias in early spring, around March. Use a
gardenia-specific formula. Gardenias prefer a slightly acidic soil
and such formulas can help prevent overly alkaline conditions. You
might also occasionally apply an organic fertilizer such as fish
emulsion during the growing season. Apply a foliar spray and apply
to the soil around the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The best times to prune gardenias are in early spring to remove
frost damage and after they bloom for shape. Many are setting new
buds in late summer, so those pruned then lose the next season's
blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus evolved in volcanic areas where they became accustomed
to soils high in potassium and magnesium. They prefer fertilizers
higher in potassium, represented by the last number in the
fertilizer formula, than phosphorus, represented by the middle
number. Continued use of a high-middle-number fertilizer will
eventually block the plant's ability to use soil nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus prefer a fertilizer with a dominant ammoniacal
nitrogen. A fertilizer with urea as the main nitrogen source can be
harmful. There are specially formulated hibiscus fertilizers
readily available. Some local nurseries carry their own products.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize regularly, frequently and lightly. Some fertilize
biweekly, others monthly. Water before and after fertilizing,
especially if you use a dry fertilizer. Fertilize in the cooler
parts of the day. Frequent watering washes nutrients away quickly,
so more frequent fertilizing may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   These tropical plants also respond to Epsom salt, a source of
magnesium sulfate. Frequency rate of application varies from three
times a year, lightly, to a tablespoon per gallon of pot size
monthly with the fertilizer. Occasional applications of fish
emulsion also are beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want larger shrubs rarely prune. Those gardeners who
prefer late-spring and summer blooms prune during late fall and
winter. Unless winter protection can be provided, prune when tender
new growth won't be subject to freezing temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Using clean, sharp tools, remove dead or diseased wood. Cut back
into green wood, pruning to about a quarter-inch above an
outward-pointing bud so that new growth will be away from the
center of the shrub. This allows light and air to the interior.
Cuts should be at a slant so water will roll off. Do not leave
stubs, as these invite decay.
</P>
<P>
   Remove branches that grow toward the center of the plant to
promote more light and air penetration. Prune as much as 30 percent
of the plant at one time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure which jasmine you mean, but you'll be safe with an
early application of a balanced, slow-release formula. Prune after
bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Roses like slightly acidic soil _ a pH of 6.5 is ideal _ and
good drainage is essential. A soil rich in organic matter will help
provide nutrients as well as ensure drainage. Amend gumbolike soil
with compost. Many rosarians add smaller amounts of alfalfa
pellets, fish meal, cottonseed meal and/or bone meal to enrich
growing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Begin a fertilizer program with new growth in the spring. Then
fertilize monthly or lightly every two weeks until September. Avoid
overfertilizing, and water before and after applying any
fertilizer. Composted manure, compost and other organic supplements
are beneficial. There are also numerous commercial rose fertilizers
available.
</P>
<P>
   Prune roses on Valentine's Day, as they benefit from pruning
before they break dormancy. Pruning removes weak wood that drains
the plant, decreases the chances of disease, and promotes new
growth. Study each rose to determine pruning needs.
</P>
<P>
   Modern and antique roses vary in their pruning needs.
</P>
<P>
   Antiques grow on their own rootstock and do not require heavy
pruning, just a light shaping. Prune once-a-year bloomers after
flowering. Remove any dead or diseased canes and twiggy growth.
Then give the overall plant a light trim. Repeat bloomers can be
lightly trimmed on Valentine's Day. During the growing season,
occasional light trims may be in order after a flowering spree to
shape a vigorous repeat bloomer.
</P>
<P>
   Modern roses need more. Prune the bush back by about a third of
its height. Make 45-degree cuts a quarter-inch above a growth or
bud eye on the outside of the cane. A growth or bud eye is a small
bulge with a small ``eye'' and a horizontal crease below it. When
the plant breaks dormancy, the eye will become a new shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting to outside bud eyes encourages outward growth rather
than growth toward the center of the plant, which would decrease
air circulation and, therefore, plant health. Cutting at 45-degree
angles prevents moisture from accumulating on the tips, again
discouraging disease.
</P>
<P>
   Prune modern roses to get rid of nonproductive, damaged and
unwanted canes. Look for canes that are brittle, brown or black.
Remove this old or dead wood at the bud union. Remove spindly stems
smaller than a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   Prune any canes that emerge below the bud union that bump at the
base of the plant where a preferred rose has been grafted onto
hardy rootstock. These are rootstock suckers, and they may bloom,
but the flowers will differ from those produced above the graft,
and these suckers sap energy from the desired, productive canes
that grow from the bud union.
</P>
<P>
   Leave three or four healthy canes for an open, vase-shaped
effect. This gives the rose breathing room, opening the center for
better air circulation, which in turn helps discourage fungal
diseases such as black spot. Sunlight better penetrates an open
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Climbers are pruned according to their bloom time. Those that
flower once a year are pruned after they bloom. Repeat-bloom
climbers are generally pruned while dormant, so prune these when
pruning modern hybrid teas. Prune all but three or four healthy
young canes. Remove unproductive canes, dead or diseased canes, old
and weak canes. If the rose is grafted, remove any rootstock
suckers.
</P>
<P>
   Wisteria can be aggressive, so do not overfertilize. A fertile
soil goes a long way. Prune heavily after bloom. Avoid winter
pruning or you'll remove spring flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Huber is the Houston Chronicle's Garden Editor.
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
