<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIVE THE PRESIDENT A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Give the guy a break. President Clinton, that is.
Enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the punishment has fit the crime _ impeachment by the
House, trial by the Senate, public humiliation, ridicule from
late-night comedians, interminable investigations and huge fines
and legal bills not only for himself but his staffers and close
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Robert Ray is pursuing Clinton with the same
relentless zeal that drove Ray's predecessor, Kenneth Starr. In
some eyes, Ray is emulating the fictional Inspector Javert in ``Les
Miserables,'' as Starr did when he was on the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   Ray goes public often. In an article that he recently wrote for
the New York Times he defended his move to impanel a federal grand
jury to consider criminal evidence against Clinton because of ``the
gravity of the situation.'' He conceded that the country may be
``weary of the subject'' but insisted that he is bound by his oath
of office to bring the matter to closure.
</P>
<P>
   In revisiting the Monica Lewinsky matter, Ray's avowed mission
is to prove that no one, not even a president, is above the law. He
said his duty is to present evidence of perjury and obstruction of
justice to the panel but added that he has not yet decided whether
to seek an indictment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ray may be hard put to find jurors who are not familiar with the
intimate details of the accusations against the president and who
have not already made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has acknowledged his affair with the former White House
intern and admitted, in effect, that he lied about it. He has
expressed remorse and asked forgiveness before religious
gatherings. He has said he hopes his backsliding will not hurt Vice
President Al Gore in his quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Those who really count with him _ his wife Hillary and daughter
Chelsea _ have forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   In the excruciating Senate trial, he had only one thing going
for him _ the American people, who did not want him removed from
office. Apparently his transgressions fell short of high crimes and
misdemeanors with the senator-jurors, who also read the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Still hanging over his head is the effort by some Arkansas Bar
Association members to disbar him. Clinton's lawyers say that would
be harsh and unprecedented punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Hasn't he paid enough of a price for his dalliances?
</P>
<P>
   For his detractors, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has done a lot of soul-searching. Two years ago, he
promised to meet regularly with three spiritual counselors, and
they say he has been faithful to that pledge. Rev. Philip J.
Wogaman, pastor of Foundry United Methodist Church here, said
Clinton is still ``on a journey and is making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Another counselor, the Rev. Tony Campolo, an evangelical Baptist
minister and a professor emeritus at Eastern College in St. Davids,
Pa., said that in seeking redemption, Clinton is asking himself:
``What went wrong? How could I have been so wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Campolo said Clinton is looking at his earlier life to find the
answers but added that ``he is not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Campolo also revealed that for Clinton it is ``payback time'' _
he wants to help staffers who are burdened with enormous legal
bills as a result of the unending investigations into his
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People are always asking, ``What will Clinton do after he leaves
the White House?''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. After a decompression period, he will be busy.
Among his priorities: building his presidential library in Little
Rock. He also will write his memoirs, which will command a hefty
advance.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years in the White House he should have a lot to
say. But don't forget that presidential memoirs are usually
self-serving and self-protective.
</P>
<P>
   If he loses his license to practice law, under Securities and
Exchange Commission rules he will not be able to serve on any of
the blue-chip corporate boards that probably would love to add him
to their rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his predecessors, Clinton will seek to travel a lot
as a world peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo said the president is ``looking for a purpose'' when his
presidency is over, and he sees Jimmy Carter, one of the most
activist former presidents, as a role model. Speaking recently at a
fundraiser in New Jersey, Clinton told his fans, ``I'm coming back
to where you are. This is the first time in 26 years I haven't been
running for anything. I'm going to be a citizen activist.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if Chelsea Clinton may be having second thoughts
about going to medical school to become a pediatrician.
Globe-trotting with her parents has made her the most traveled
presidential offspring in history. As a result, she has become more
interested in international and political affairs. Aides say the
attention she has gotten on her journeys to foreign lands has
whetted her appetite for public life. She told CNN-TV interviewer
Larry King she may decide to go to Oxford University in England,
one of her father's alma maters, after she graduates from Stanford
next spring. She has taken a sabbatical from her studies this
semester to help her mother campaign for a Senate seat from New
York.
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
