<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will cover a large area from the central and southern
Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic Seaboard. A slow-moving
disturbance will continue to promote plenty of clouds and clusters
of showers from the Appalachians to the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Weak winds aloft will favor some slow-moving thunderstorms,
which will produce local downpours that can cause flooding in poor
drainage areas. A wavering front from the southern Great Lakes to
northern New England will separate the warm, humid air mass from
much cooler air to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Stifling heat will persist over much of the southern Plains. The
chance for some cooling afternoon showers from northeastern Texas
to Arkansas will be greater than in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool and showery conditions will envelop the
Pacific Northwest and northern Rockies. The Southwest will be sunny
and hot.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: AUGUST EXTREMES
</P>
<P>
   The last days of August were fitting for a summer replete with
extremes. In Dallas and Little Rock, Ark., the nearly cloudless
skies in August's final few days concluded a month in which not a
drop of rain fell in either city. On Thursday the mercury reached
110 in Houston, tying the record high temperature there. Meanwhile,
exceptionally cool summer weather spread over parts of the West
Coast states. On Wednesday, San Jose, Calif., had its coolest
August afternoon on record when the mercury struggled to reach only
66 degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
