</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHLANDER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HIGHLANDER: ENDGAME': IMMORTALS WITH GRUDGES AND ENDLESS BACK
STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The rules have been broken; one of your kind has gone
renegade,'' the good guy immortal, Duncan MacLeod (Adrian Paul), of
the clan MacLeod, is told in ``Highlander: Endgame.'' The evil
immortal, Jacob Kell (Bruce Payne), has gone on a rampage. And such
an earthshaking event hasn't transpired on Earth since, well, since
the last ``Highlander'' movie, when the evil immortal Kane had to
be stopped by good guy Connor MacLeod (Christopher Lambert), of the
clan MacLeod. Kell wants to torture Connor for all eternity because
Connor killed his father centuries before. (Though, to be fair,
Kell and others burned Connor's mother at the stake.)
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Endgame''is only 95 minutes long, there is so much
exposition that some may find it as confusing as the Samuel Beckett
play of the same name. In the ``Highlander'' mythology immortals
walk the earth; they modestly refer to themselves as ``the seeds of
legend.'' Each time one is killed in battle _ his head has to be
cut off, leading to a light show that could be right out of an Ozzy
Osbourne concert _ his spirit and power enter the victor. I'm sure
there's a lengthy monograph on the homoeroticism of ``Highlander''
somewhere at the Sorbonne, and ``Endgame'' lets Kell jokingly
allude to it. This may be the only thing that will keep those
unaware of the ``Highlander'' mythology interested.
</P>
<P>
   The mythology began in the 1986 fantasy film ``Highlander,''
which has the distinction of being one of the most overdirected
films of that decade. The camera flies around so much you assume
the camera operators were being paid by the mile. Lambert starred
in the sequels, which lost whatever sprightliness the first one
had, perhaps because that quality was embodied by Sean Connery,
playing Lambert's mentor and, even more absurdly, a Spaniard with a
Scottish lilt. (The inappropriate accents are a big part of
``Highlander''; Connor seems to have been singled out to be an
immortal because he has the least convincing Scottish accent in the
country.)
</P>
<P>
   Connery's gargantuan, jovial presence _ he seemed to be in on
some private joke _ was glimpsed briefly in the second
``Highlander,'' where he had a cameo that was such a brazen attempt
to bring in an audience that he seemed to be cashing his check on
the set. The other sequels have become increasingly grim and
dolorous; it's no fun having to live forever. That's the theme of
``Endgame.'' And to set up this picture the producers use endless
flashbacks, because the audience unfamiliar with ``Highlander''
movies and the spinoff television series, in which all of the
immortals seemed to have moved to Canada, have to be brought up to
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, looking about as miserable as anyone who has lived for
several centuries can, has gone into seclusion for 10 years, a
revelation that means the movie sequels apparently never took
place, since they were set in the 1990s. (``Endgame'' doesn't even
bother to be consistent with its own phony past.) He leaves the
sanctuary, called Sanctuary no less, to join Duncan so that
together they can keep Kell from being the last surviving immortal.
(The immortal creed is, There can be only one!) There's so much
exposition that Paul, whose impish Duncan was the protagonist of
the television spinoff, doesn't even appear until 10 minutes into
the action.
</P>
<P>
   And the action is the best thing in the picture, taking place in
warehouses and abandoned buildings that make the film look like an
Einsturzende Neubauten stage show. It's nice to see mindless
violence back in a B picture, where it belongs, and the swordplay
is impressive. When ``Highlander'' sticks to the hand-to-hand
battles and doesn't try to offer deeper thoughts on the life of an
immortal, it works on its own terms. (No one explains how the two
Britons, Connor and Duncan, learned sword-fighting techniques that
look Japanese, but it's probably pointless to ask too many
questions here.)
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HIGHLANDER: ENDGAME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Douglas Aarniokoski; written by Joel Soisson, based
on a story by Eric Bernt, Gillian Horvath and William Panzer and
characters created by Gregory Widen; director of photography, Doug
Milsome; edited by Christopher Blunden, Michael N. Nue, Robert
Ferretti, Tracy Granger, Rod Dean and Donald J. Paonessa; music by
Stephen Graziano; production designer, Jonathan Carlson; produced
by Peter Davis and Panzer; released by Dimension Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``Highlander: Endgame'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes violence,
including decapitations of immortals, and brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Adrian Paul (Duncan MacLeod), Christopher Lambert (Connor
MacLeod), Bruce Payne (Jacob Kell), Lisa Barbuscia (Faith/Kate),
Donnie Yen (Jin Ke), Damon Dash (Carlos) and Jim Byrnes (Dawson).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
