<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG JAPANESE COMPANY SEEKS RELIEF FROM CREDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A major Japanese construction company, Kumagai Gumi, is
expected to ask its creditors to forgive 450 billion yen in debt,
or $4.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company joins a number of debt-burdened businesses, many of
them construction companies, that have asked for relief from their
creditors. Japan's construction industry has been among the most
heavily indebted.
</P>
<P>
   Kumagai Gumi said Friday in a statement only that it was in
talks with its main creditor, Sumitomo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But reports here said that in return for debt relief, Kumagai
Gumi had agreed to cut jobs sharply and to reduce back orders to
half their current level. The company, the reports said, is also
seeking a partnership with Kajima Corp., one of the largest
Japanese general contractors, which would inject fresh capital into
Kumagai Gumi.
</P>
<P>
   A number of big contractors including Tobishima, Aoki and Haseko
have already reached accords with their lenders, seeking waivers of
debt in the hundreds of billions of yen. ``All weak construction
companies are close to having some form of debt relief,'' said
Garry Evans, a strategist with HSBC Securities here.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have not been so lucky. Sogo, a major
department-store chain that collapsed in July, had asked banks to
forgive loans totaling 631.9 billion yen, or nearly $6 billion. The
bailout plan fell through when one of the biggest creditors,
Shinsei Bank _ acquired last year by a group of foreign investors
led by Ripplewood Holdings of New York _ balked. (Shinsei is also a
major creditor of Kumagai Gumi.)
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that construction companies are too politically
connected to fail. ``Construction firms are basically not allowed
to go bust,'' Evans said. In Japan the construction industry
employs more than 10 percent of the work force, and construction
workers often campaign in support of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
