<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-01 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   STANDARD CHARTERED ACQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a recent buying spree in Asia where it earns two
thirds of its income, Standard Chartered PLC said it will pay $1.32
billion in cash to buy Chase Manhattan Corp.'s Hong Kong credit
card and retail banking division. The acquisition would make
Standard Chartered the biggest credit card provider in Hong Kong
with one quarter of the market. The British-based bank said it
would fund the acquisition by issuing 50 million new shares at 915
pence and by selling a British subsidiary to Lloyds/TSB for 627
million pounds. Standard Chartered's shares rose by 1 pence to 955
pence.
</P>
<P>
   TELEFONICA PROFIT FALLS
</P>
<P>
   Spanish telecommunications giant Telefonica SA reported net
profit for the first half of the year at 989 million euros ($881
million), a 3 percent drop from the same period in 1999. In a
statement, the company said that positive results from its domestic
cell-phone operations and its international activities helped
compensate for weakness in other areas, such as traditional
services. Earnings from Latin American operations were almost 125
million euros, up 31 percent over the first half of last year,
reflecting that region's improving economy. On the Madrid bolsa,
Telefonica's share prices rose as high as 8.7 percent at the news.
Giving in to pressure from the board, chairman Juan Villalonga
resigned just over a month ago ending months of uncertainty over
the company's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO CHARGES POSSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   Former chairman Kim Woo-Choong of Daewoo Group and as many as 40
executives from the conglomerate may face criminal charges for
inflating the asset values of several affiliates, which worsened
the assessment of the business group's liabilities, the watchdog
Financial Supervisory Commission said Friday. Daewoo Group, which
was at one time the second largest business group in South Korea,
is being sold off in pieces in order to repay debts totaling $79
billion. The state-run watchdog agency said it is considering
possible penalties against accounting companies as well.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN BANK APPLICATION
</P>
<P>
   The Asia Development Bank said that North Korea has applied for
membership status, which would give the impoverished nation access
to low-interest loans to rebuild its outdated infrastructure and
feed its people. As part of its conciliatory gestures, South Korea
has tried to help North Korea gain membership in the development
bank. However, the United States and Japan have opposed even
observer status in the bank, because of concerns about North
Korea's sponsorship of terrorism. The development bank said North
Korea's application has been referred to its shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
