<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS GORE AD A RESPONSE TO ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. _ George W. Bush Friday said a
``tongue-in-cheekish'' ad questioning Al Gore's credibility was
justified by Democrats' attacks on him, and he signaled a new line
of more aggressive campaigning by urging hundreds at a rally in the
bayou heat: ``Let's get after 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading a planned day of rest for two quick stops in the Texas
border states of Louisiana and Arkansas, the Texas governor told
reporters he had no apologies for a Republican National Committee
ad that jabs at the vice president's statements about campaign
fund-raising and inventing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although he personally approved the spot, Bush sought to keep
his distance, saying at one point, ``I appreciate the Republicans
coming to my defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Republican presidential contender said the ad
was justified in light of the $30 million in advertising aired by
the Democrats during the GOP's convention in Philadelphia, as well
as Gore's statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the man's own words,'' Bush said. ``Let the American
people judge whether it's accurate or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain how it was not the type of negative campaigning
he decries, Bush replied: ``I thought it was tongue-in-cheek, I
thought it was tongue-in-cheekish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign disagreed and said Bush was responding to
recent public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's downward-spiraling poll numbers have
apparently made him so dizzy that he can no longer distinguish
negative from positive,'' said Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for the
vice president. ``His ridiculous statement is today's sign of just
how desperate the Bush campaign has become and how out-of-touch
George W. Bush is with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush first stopped in Louisiana, where it was even hotter than
the 105-degree temperatures that have enveloped his hometown of
Austin, Texas. Peeling off his coat and rolling up his shirt
sleeves, Bush dripped sweat as he declared to an airport rally:
``Labor Day's the traditional start, and I'm ready, and I like what
I see. I like what I hear not only here in the state of Louisiana,
but all across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor lambasted the Clinton administration for raising
taxes instead of cutting them, and for failing to get prescription
drug coverage for senior citizens. He noted that the state's
Democratic senator, John Breaux, had pushed a bipartisan Medicare
reform plan that included prescription drugs, but that the
administration quashed his panel's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to have a president who will work with the likes of
John Breaux, and make sure the promise of Medicare and the promise
of Social Security is met and kept, and I'm ready to take the
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also played to the hometown crowd by saying he supported
oil and natural gas exploration off the coast in the Gulf of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate very much your support,'' he said. ``Let's get
after 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush later read to students and delivered a speech on reading at
the College Hill Elementary School in Texarkana, Ark. Saturday he
was to receive his first national security briefing from the
Central Intelligence Agency, standard fare for presidential
nominees since 1952.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
