<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 9.03.00
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   By Wendell Brock, Bob Longino, Dan Hulbert, Shane Harrison and
Eileen Drennen
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Ballet musicians' strike plays out on the Web
</P>
<P>
   You, too, can be part of the Sundance Film Festival _ from home
</P>
<P>
   Tired of boring music awards shows? Create your own for VH1
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA BALLET E-WAR: As the Atlanta Ballet musicians' strike
makes national and international headlines, the ballet's electronic
guest book continues to be a battleground. After numerous
contentious entries were purged recently, the Regional Orchestra
Players' Association picked them up ``unedited, uncensored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are showing them here because they seem to disappear from
that site on a regular basis,'' the site says.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet orchestra site _ aborchestra.com _ is devoted
exclusively to the labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has started to get some attention on national
industry Web sites as well. Musicalamerica.com picked up an
Associated Press rewrite of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's Aug.
26 front-page story, as did the Los Angeles Times, the
International Herald Tribune, the Cleveland Plain Dealer and the
Orlando Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Ballet guest book:
</P>
<P>
   atlantaballet.com/guestbook
</P>
<P>
   /guestbook.html
</P>
<P>
   Regional Orchestra Players' Association: www.ropaweb
</P>
<P>
   .org/bulletins/AtlanGuestBook
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Ballet Orchestra:
</P>
<P>
   aborchestra.com
</P>
<P>
   WEB-DANCE: The 10-day Sundance Film Festival just got bigger _
and more computery. An online festival will be added to the 2001
event, the largest confab of independent films in America. The
Sundance Online Film Festival, to coincide with the regular Jan.
18-28 screenings, will be produced by StreamSearch.com and located
on www.sundance.org. Sundance promises that the Internet fest will
include ``both a selection of new work developed specifically for
the Web and a retrospective of past Web highlights.'' Submissions
must be ``mixed-media pieces'' made specifically for the Web,
including animation, live-action, documentaries and interactive or
experimental works. The deadline is Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   www.sundance.org
</P>
<P>
   ``MY VH1 MUSIC AWARDS'': The folks who bring us ``Behind the
Music'' are set to give us something else we didn't know we needed:
an awards show built from the ground up by music fans. Let's hope
it's as train-wreck fascinating as ``Behind the Music.'' On VH1's
Web site, visitors are asked to suggest categories, nominees and,
eventually, the winners for ``My VH1 Music Awards.'' The show will
be broadcast live on Nov. 30, with the online voting continuing
until the awards are given. It's bound to be better than the
Grammys, but it also conjures up thoughts of such dreaded annual
debacles as ``The American Music Awards.'' The categories that have
popped up on the site's message board so far would make for a
pretty pedestrian show. Best boy band? Worst boy band? That would
make ``The Peoples' Choice Awards'' look suspenseful. Among the
more entertaining suggestions is an award for the best use of
saliva in a heavy-metal video.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   www.vh1.com
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: WEEK OF 9.3.00
</P>
<P>
   Resources for
</P>
<P>
   musicians on the Web
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Federation of Musicians' site is an excellent
compendium of resources for musicians. Its Local News page contains
everything from obituaries to information on jam sessions and an
upcoming exhibit of Italian string instruments. (Not surprisingly,
there's an item about the Atlanta Ballet orchestra strike as well.)
</P>
<P>
   The American Federation of Musicians' site is AFM.org _ but it's
essentially for members only. You may, however, read the cover
story of International Musician. The August issue featured Jason
Marsalis, the youngest member of America's first family of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock
</P>
<P>
   www.atlantamusicians.com
</P>
<P>
   Tony, Tony, Tony _
</P>
<P>
   all the theater news
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Awards site is chock-full of national theater news,
including something you'll never see on television: the original,
uncut thank-you speeches that the Tony winners couldn't sueeze into
their allotted 45 seconds of air time. In case you were dying to
know the name of Brian Stokes Mitchell's (``Kiss Me Kate,'' best
actor in a musical) junior high school drama teacher, Mitchell
thanks him. (We wish we were kidding.) In more substantial news,
Susan Stroman, the all-over-Broadway choreographer (``Contact,''
``The Music Man''), is working with Mel Brooks on his musical
version of ``The Producers,'' expected on Broadway next spring, and
with Harry Connick Jr. on ``Thou Shalt Not,'' a musicalization of
Emile Zola's ``Therese Rauin.'' (No opening has yet been set).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert
</P>
<P>
   www.tonys.org
</P>
<P>
   Smashing Pumpkins
</P>
<P>
   live on online
</P>
<P>
   Though leader Billy Corgan has announced that the Smashing
Pumpkins current tour marks the end of the band, this official site
is still a going concern that ranks high in both utility and visual
artistry. Its newest addition is a streaming radio station that
plays concert recordings from the Chicago band's 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   www.smashingpumpkins.com
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY JAM 2000. Featuring a variety of acts, this
countrypalooza from sites in Grand Junction, Colo., Live Oak, Fla.,
and Eau Claire, Wis., will feature, among others, Trace Adkins
(left), Montgomery Gentry and Chely Wright.
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on www.countryjam.com
</P>
<P>
   MIGHTY SAM McCLAIN. A master of Southern soul blues, his tunes
likely will include ``When the Hurt Is Over'' and ``They Call Me
Mighty.''
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m. Monday on www.hob.com/live
</P>
<P>
   SISTER HAZEL. Named after an African-American woman who ran
Sister Hazel's Rescue Mission in Gainesville, Fla., in the 1970s
and '80s, the rock-pop band churns out generally pleasant music.
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m. Tuesday on www.hob.com/live
</P>
<P>
   THE GO-GO'S. Formed in Hollywood in 1978 and disbanded and
reunited several times, the Go-Go's produced some interesting music
as a group and as solo acts (notably lead singer Belinda Carlisle).
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m. Wednesday on www.hob.com/live
</P>
