u f BC-SEAGRAM-BUYERS-NYT &LR;      09-01 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-BUYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX BIDDERS FOR SEAGRAMS JOCKEY FOR POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Seagram Co. opened its books this week to
prospective buyers of its drinks business in what is the first
stage of a sale that may run through mid-October. Already, the
biggest spirits companies are jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   The number of possible bidders has grown from two to six.
Alliances have been formed, broken and reformed. Absolut vodka, the
centerpiece of the Seagram empire, remains a wild card. And complex
tax issues threaten the very idea of a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of people with lots of interests to defend,''
one executive close to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as the field may be confusing, most analysts expect
just one outcome. Allied Domecq PLC was considered the front-runner
when Seagram first announced plans to sell its wine and spirits
business in June as part of its plan to merge with Vivendi SA, the
French media and utility conglomerate. And the same holds true
today.
</P>
<P>
   Working to Allied's advantage is its ability to bid for the
business independently, thanks to its financial muscle and lack of
regulatory conflicts _ two issues that could handicap competitors.
</P>
<P>
   First, analysts say that Allied is the most likely partner for
Vin and Sprit, the Swedish owner of Absolut vodka, which has hinted
that it will use the change of ownership to secure a better deal,
possibly with a new partner. Vin and Sprit's existing contract with
Seagram is confidential, but analysts estimate that Absolut
accounts for 10 percent of the beverage operation's total liquor
sales, or $75 million to $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Allied's success _ which depends in part on its ability to
raise debt or equity so that it may swallow a company with a market
value nearly twice its own _ is far from assured. It is facing
stiff competition from Diageo PLC of Britain, which is flush with
cash, and could easily match Allied in a bidding war that threatens
to inflate the price to $9 billion _ a value at which analysts said
most companies would be hard pressed to make the deal pay off.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that locking up support from Vin and Sprit will
be crucial in the battle for one of the last gems in a rapidly
consolidating industry.
</P>
<P>
   With brands ranging from Chivas Regal premium Scotch to Captain
Morgan's rum, Seagram's wine and spirits business ranks third
worldwide, behind Diageo, home of Johnnie Walker Scotch and
Smirnoff vodka, and Allied Domecq, which owns Ballantine's Scotch
and Kahlua liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vin and Sprit doesn't want to be in this position again, where
someone decides to sell a business and carve it up,'' the executive
close to the discussions said. ``They would like to get more
control, either through ownership, or some iron-clad rights
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   One way for Vin and Sprit to shore up its prospects is to take a
stake in one of the bidders. Absolut declined to comment on the
contract or the bidding process, as did Allied and Diageo.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, which was formed through the 1997 merger of GrandMet and
Guinness, could have less bargaining power than Allied. GrandMet
used to own the global distribution rights to Absolut, but lost
them to Seagram in 1994, because Vin and Sprit did not want Absolut
sold in tandem with GrandMet's other vodka label, Smirnoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allied will retain the support of Absolut,'' said Graeme
Eadie, an analyst with Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Eadie said he expected Allied to win the auction for three
reasons: An alliance with Vin and Sprit, cost savings that will
allow it to make the deal, and the flexibility that comes with
bidding independently.
</P>
<P>
   Allied will be able to offer the highest price for Seagram's
drinks business, he said, because it will also see the greatest
cost savings. He expects Allied to save 220 million pounds a year,
or $319 million, by pushing Seagram brands through its existing
distribution system _ nearly double the savings seen for Diageo.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the few companies able to bid independently for
Seagram, Allied has more freedom than does Diageo, which has chosen
to bid jointly with Pernod Ricard of France. The two companies are
expected to split the Seagram brands between them, and in this way
Diageo hopes to avoid antitrust issues.
</P>
<P>
   Consortiums have a greater chance of failure, Eadie noted,
especially during the last phase of bidding, because it is often
difficult to get the parties to agree on the fair value of a
company.
</P>
<P>
   Allied, which is one of the few companies that could swallow
Seagram whole, may have another advantage in the form of a giant
tax bill that could be imposed on any company trying to split up
the business _ an issue that flies against Diageo's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax implications are tremendously complicated,'' the
executive close to the discussions said. The Seagram business was
built ``without any thought of it ever being pulled apart.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other players, Bacardi lacks the financial muscle to
bid independently, and after initial talks with Diageo broke down
over how to carve up Seagram, Bacardi has yet to find another
partner. Remy Cointreau's strategy of buying ``tail brands'' on the
cheap makes it an unlikely contender. Then there is the Bronfman
family, which owns 24 percent of Seagram and is said to be keen on
keeping the business that Samuel Bronfman bought in 1924. Even if
the Bronfmans formed a consortium to finance the deal, analysts
said, Allied and Diageo could easily outbid that group.
</P>
<P>
   The first bids are due by the end of the month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
