</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8720 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-COMIC-GUY03-COX     09-01 2752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMIC-GUY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawrenceville man pens best-selling comic books, shakes up genre
with stories that go far beyond cliches of yesteryear
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Jenkins spends his nights exploring the psyche of
Spider-Man and conveying the inner rage of the Hulk. He crafts
comic book characters and conflict that capture the attention of a
growing legion of readers every month. But this is part of a bigger
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old writer is waging a crusade to legitimize comics,
particularly the superhero genre, a much-maligned species that gets
short shrift for respect on the publishing food chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comic creators in Europe and Japan are seen as highly
respected, literate people,'' says Jenkins, of Lawrenceville, Ga.,
his eyes swollen after struggling with a script until 4 a.m. ``Here
we're seen as literary castoffs. People don't take it seriously,
and it's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   From a basement lair in a suburban cul-de-sac not far from the
Mall of Georgia, he writes three of the top-selling comic books in
the United States: ``Peter Parker: Spider-Man,'' ``The Incredible
Hulk'' and ``Witchblade.'' The first two are comic book icons that
have saturated popular media for years; the third, a story about a
female police officer who possesses, or is possessed by, a gauntlet
with mystical powers, was made into a TV movie that was shown on
TNT last week.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the stale cliches of a superhero story that
interest Jenkins, a Briton who moved here last year with his
girlfriend. (``It's a brilliant, brilliant place,'' he says of
Atlanta. ``I always liked the South. Lots of nice golf courses,
seasons.'') Spandex-draped muscleheads duking it out have been done
to death. Instead, he journeys into the minds and souls of these
characters, writing rich, psychological tales full of twists and
metaphors aimed at an audience more sophisticated than the
traditional consumers of the comics genre, pubescent males looking
for a power fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take these superhero characters and tell really good
stories _ for a change,'' Jenkins says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is no starry-eyed prodigy. He has scraped by for more
than a decade in an often unforgiving industry, from marketing
comic books and related merchandise to editing titles. Writing was
a goal he fought to pursue. Now, as the mercury rises on his
career, he's not bashful about championing his ability _ but he
doesn't take it for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing very well,'' he says, his blond, spiked hair limp
after the all-nighter. ``I want to keep the iron hot by doing work
I enjoy, is well-done and not skimping on what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins is most anxious about ``Sentry,'' a character he created
seven years ago to explore the evolution of superheroes and add
fresh context to the genre. Part of the ``Marvel Knights'' line of
books, the title character is a near-omnipotent being who has
forgotten his greatness and suffers from an identity crisis, a
troubled marriage and, possibly, addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a sophisticated take on superheroes and
superheroism,'' say Jenkins, who waited years to see ``Sentry''
published. ``The story is about what if a person like this has a
power. What would it feel like?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sentry'' series, which has just reached print, doesn't
read like a typical yarn depicting good vs. evil. It begins with a
sluggish, middle-aged man with a full midsection having flashbacks
to a possible past as a superhero. These recollections are told
using artistic styles typical of a certain time, from the cartoony
style of the 1960s to the darker images associated with 1980s comic
artwork. So far, barely a punch has been thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't care about the conflicts of people unless we
care about them,'' he says. ``My primary mission is to make people
care about these people before we care about what they do. We in
comics have ignored that directive for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no formula for doing this. He works from his perceptions
and interprets these into text.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just observing them (the characters) and asking, `How can
I see a piece of myself in them?''' Jenkins explains.
``Spider-Man's a great example. He has an old aunt who's a strong
figure. I have an old granny in Wales who's the same way. I write
myself and put myself into that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Handling the drawing chores is Jae Lee, the penciller who teamed
up with Jenkins on ``The Inhumans,'' his 1998 repair job for Marvel
comics. The scripts, Lee says, aim to elevate superhero
storytelling into relevant literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers like Paul treat comic characters as real characters
who just have these abilities,'' says Lee, who's based in Virginia.
``It's a more mature and realistic take. It's not dumbed down for
kids. Paul's part of a movement.''
</P>
<P>
   More character-based, mature storytelling is the current rage in
comics, with the Marvel Knights line _ featuring more humanistic
and darker characters such as the blind superhero Daredevil and the
nihilistic vigilante the Punisher _ leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' graceful presentation is key. Fluid sentences and
descriptive narratives drill into a character's psyche, examining
the quirks, flaws and mental struggles that drive a superhero.
Achieving this requires the writer to channel these characters and
immerse himself into their fictional worlds. When he has tucked
away a Spider-Man tale, he prepares for a round with the Hulk.
</P>
<P>
   Once Jenkins completes a script, he erases that world of
characters from his mind and pores over his notes and preparation
material for the next story. The characters, he says, consume his
thoughts while he goes out for a run _ or cooks _ and he is
constantly sorting through ways to improve story flow or flesh out
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get really tiring when I switch gears,'' he allows.
``It's the most mentally challenging part. But I have to _ I truly
live in the world I create.''
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking a hit of adrenalin won't be disappointed. He may
eschew nonsensical scrapes, but action with context can be an
effective storytelling skill.
</P>
<P>
   For example, nary a punch was thrown in the first four issues of
``The Inhumans,'' but when the action finally exploded, it was a
culmination of substance: The Inhumans' city was attacked by
humans. The Inhumans' leader, Black Bolt _ who has been silent so
far throughout the story _ was viewed as so altruistic by the human
race that it manipulated this weakness to its advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Triton, a character with water-based
abilities, saves a small child _ a passenger on the World War I-era
ocean liner Lusitania _ from drowning. It is Triton's first
exposure to war, and he experiences actions he's unaccustomed to
(such as bravery) while watching an old man attempting to save his
grandson. The grandson reappears later as an old man, searching for
the ``mermaid'' who once saved him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say they want action, but they truly want character,''
Jenkins says. ``You have to establish character early on so you
care. Having powers doesn't mean as much unless it's a real
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a leap from the child who used to write and illustrate
homemade comic books for his mother, with titles such as ``Alfred
and the Egg Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She sees the little boy who sat and drew stories for her and
sees my writing stuff that's published _ which are comics _ and is
really proud,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Old World inspiration
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in England was magical, says Jenkins. He was raised
in the southwestern area of Dorset, which he describes as ``King
Arthur country.'' Forts from the Roman and Iron Ages and royal
burial grounds graced the terrain and instilled in the would-be
writer an appreciation for the age of heroes. He lived for the
fantasy of space travel, he says, which sparked his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a fairyland. My parents divorced when I was
young, and my mother was a single parent in the early 1970s. We
were by far the poorest family. We lived on a farm and I would
often eat food from there _ or (occasionally) the rabbits I
snared.''
</P>
<P>
   He left England in 1988 to teach music to disabled children in
Northampton, Mass., and experience life in the States. He formed a
rock band, Grave Goods (which disbanded four years later), and met
a pair of friends who would soon revolutionize the comic book
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird had just created the Teenage
Mutant Ninja Turtles, a late-1980s black-market comic book that
quickly evolved into creative and financial dynamite. They hired
English major Jenkins to be the editor at Tundra Publishing, the
comic book home of the Turtles empire. He was the third employee in
a company that ignited a cultural sensation and eventually expanded
to include toys, cartoons and a series of movies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jenkins wore an exhausting slew of hats _ editorial,
promotional, licensing and production duties were all on his plate
_ the venture finally fizzled four years later, which he attributes
to inexperience and greed. Still sour after watching the empire and
its potential crumble, he refers to Tundra as a ``spectacular
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad lesson that I learned, a cautionary tale. I wanted
to be trusting, but no matter how much I trust people now, I look
into their eyes _ shaking their hands _ and wonder if what I'm
seeing is subterfuge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins went on to become editor in chief at a struggling Ohio
comic company that went bankrupt three months later. He toiled to
make it work, going without pay for months and incurring debt.
Though he learned that the comic business is prey to all the
problems of any creative industry, Jenkins says he never lost his
love of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   The fix-it man
</P>
<P>
   What he really wanted to do was write. In 1994, powerhouse DC
Comics offered him a shot at writing ``Hellblazer,'' a title in its
adult-themed Vertigo line of comic books. The plots centered on a
``working-class magician'' named John Constantine, who encounters a
series of wicked situations spiked with a dose of the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   It turned into a nearly four-year gig, in which Jenkins culled
inspiration from family members and tales told by his mother. While
jogging around a cemetery in the rain, he remembered a legend she
had recounted about how walking around a graveyard three times
counterclockwise will cause the ghosts of that necropolis to haunt
and curse that person. The myth made it into ``Hellblazer,'' where
the main character ends the chaos resulting from a jogger's taking
this path by reversing a directional sign to a clockwise direction
near a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hellblazer'' was the first step in what became a sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel Comics hatched a plan to invigorate a group of
second-string characters in its pantheon, adding an edge previously
untapped. The concept was dubbed ``Marvel Knights,'' and Jenkins
was enlisted a year after his work on ``Hellblazer'' to tackle
``The Inhumans,'' a royal sect of genetically blessed characters
that were often viewed as a bit of a joke.
</P>
<P>
   The result was more prose than punches. In the 12-issue series,
Jenkins got to explore such themes as the burdens of aristocracy
and the metamorphosis of adolescence, and even worked in metaphors
for civil rights struggles. His effort was rewarded with a 1999
Eisner Award, the Oscar of the comics world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work yourself out onto the page of the book if you really
care about it,'' he says. ``I can look at stories and say, `Boy,
was I really angry at injustice there.' Different things like that
I can see afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   He was soon recruited to perform similar repair jobs on other
flagging comics. The Hulk's sales were sagging. Jenkins provided
the antidote last year _ introducing a new villain, General Ryker,
and examining the intellect of Bruce Banner, the Hulk's alter ego _
which has spiked sales. ``Peter Parker: Spider-Man'' was devoid of
juice and interest was evaporating. Jenkins lent a spark by
returning the title character to his lighthearted roots, creating
the kinds of personal and professional struggles that made
Spider-Man an Everyman inspiration almost 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``On `Spider-Man,' we had one writer doing both `Spider-Man'
titles, and we both were a little tired,'' says Ralph Macchio,
editor of all ``Spider-Man'' titles at Marvel Comics in New York,
who pressed to get Jenkins onto his team. ``Paul told me one of the
characters he really wanted to do was Spider-Man, but he had such a
crowded schedule. I thought if I could just get him to do it, we
could deal with the deadline problems. He knows all the things that
make Spider-Man tick and brought a slew of new ideas. The word of
mouth and letters have been loudly favorable. He has a long-term
commitment to Spider-Man, and I hope he's in for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Witchblade'' is receiving Jenkins' repair skills. Long
dismissed as little more than pictures of a scantily clad,
voluptuous cop, Jenkins plans to turn the comic into a crime drama
and drop much of its cheeky surface. He's three issues into his
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatively, it was treading water,'' he says diplomatically.
``It was intended to be `NYPD Blue' meets `The X-Files.' (Main
character Sara Pezzini) is a beautiful young woman who made
detective on the NYPD, and I think that would be incredibly
testing; what kinds of pressures are put on her? It's detective
stuff with a supernatural angle.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent TV movie is closer to his work on ``Witchblade,'' and
coincidentally he was working on his issues with the crime focus at
the same time the TV project was being sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They actually did a really good job, and the acting was good.
It's a difficult comic to compare to the TV show if you look at it
before I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Witchblade'' is one of three comics that Jenkins is writing
that are receiving the live-action treatment. ``Spider-Man'' is
slated to start filming this fall, and a ``Hulk'' movie is in the
late pre-production stage. He'll be happy if the quality of those
projects is on par with the recent ``X-Men'' movie, which has raked
in about $150 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very fond of blockbuster movies or movies driven by
special effects,'' he says. ``But they tried to give the characters
an edge and it was very good. I hope they do the Spidey movie like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' skill at injecting new life into old characters has put
him much in demand. He's had to turn down several projects because
of his workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in this industry, you're so stuck in the past you
need someone with an outside view who did not grow up worshipping
these characters,'' says Joe Quesada, editor of the Marvel Knights
imprint in New York, who chose Jenkins for ``The Inhumans.'' ``It's
a very humanistic approach to this stuff, and it's what we need
today to make these characters plausible for the general public.''
</P>
<P>
   An outsider's view
</P>
<P>
   Despite spending hours a day charting possibilities for comic
characters, Jenkins reads relatively few titles. He's fond of the
other books in the Marvel Knights line and still reads
``Hellblazer.'' Fellow comic authors he admires include Alan Moore
(``The Watchmen'') and Neil Gaiman (``Sandman''), which is akin to
an actor listing Al Pacino and Robert De Niro as inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the fresh perspective entering the comic industry has
its origins in Britain. Jenkins is among a number of British
scribes whose work is bringing unconventional approaches to the
medium. Others include the legendary Moore, whose ``Watchmen''
series helped revolutionize comics in 1986 with a dark and adult
approach to superheroes; Grant Morrison, who just finished his run
on ``JLA'' (for ``Justice League of America''), DC Comics'
best-selling title; and Warren Ellis (``Planetary,''
``Transmetropolitan''), who was cited in Rolling Stone magazine's
recent ``hot'' issue for his comic book work.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins reasons that icons such as Superman, Batman and
Spider-Man resonate differently overseas, viewed as wild and
wonderful products of a foreign culture. They're not taken for
granted, he says, and therefore are approached from an outsider's
viewpoint and open for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a theory,'' he says. ``But it might be that Brits
have a better perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Fernandez writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
