<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-LABUTE-BETTY03-COX     09-01 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABUTE-BETTY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dark director finds lighter side in `Nurse Betty'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe there's a good reason critics have praised writer-director
Neil LaBute's movies but moviegoers have stayed away. Or, if
they've gone to see them, have argued afterward about whether
they'd just seen a comedy or a tragedy. Or just gotten depressed
about human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Where to start? LaBute's ``In the Company of Men'' (1997)
featured two arrogant businessmen who take revenge on the female
species by seducing and then abandoning a sweet, deaf woman they
meet during a training seminar. Possibly even meaner, ``Your
Friends and Neighbors'' (1998) coolly dissected infidelities and
lies among a circle of supposed best buddies. LaBute considered
giving that movie a title that best described its characters:
``Lepers.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a playwright, whose off-Broadway ``Bash: Latter-Day
Plays,'' which was televised last week on Showtime, included
monologues about an unwed mother who kills her own child and a guy
who boasts about brutally attacking a gay man.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he's off the beaten path,'' says Morgan Freeman,
star of LaBute's latest film, ``Nurse Betty,'' opening Friday.
``He's not making your everyday straight-at-you kind of stuff. He's
doing edgy, offbeat work.''
</P>
<P>
   So who knew that LaBute had it in him to direct something as
beguilingly funny as ``Betty,'' a quirky comedy-drama that manages
to balance its darker side with a genuine sweetness?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a certain, not shrewdness on my part, but a
certain clear-eyed look at where I was,'' LaBute says by telephone,
explaining his decision to make the movie as a change of pace after
his two dark originals. When he read the script (the first he's
directed that he didn't write himself), ``I thought, `This would be
surprising.' People who knew my work wouldn't expect me to write
something like this, let alone direct it. I think that as a
filmmaker you should continually try to surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled, though. ``Nurse Betty'' isn't a totally
lightweight romp. It stars Renee Zellweger (in a luminous, complex
performance) as a Kansas homemaker addicted to a soap opera called
``A Reason to Love.'' After a bout of trauma-induced amnesia, she
travels to Los Angeles, convinced that she's a nurse and the
fiancee of her favorite character on the show, Dr. David Ravell,
aka actor George McCord (Greg Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   Um, did we mention that she's also being trailed by a couple of
hit men (Freeman and Chris Rock), one of whom starts to fall in
love with her?
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating elements of farce, romantic comedy, road trip,
Quentin Tarantino-style violence and a dose of female empowerment,
``Betty'' required LaBute to balance moods much trickier than the
steady black humor of his first two movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This veers so wildly in tone,'' he says. ``The others were
very straightforward in their approach _ they were like a
sledgehammer swinging back and forth. With `Betty,' sometimes the
tone changes in a single scene. Finding the balance where you feel
you've kept the movie still juggling up in the air _ whether it
calls for humor, or a road-picture feeling, or violence _ is very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``Nurse Betty'' manages to maintain a wacky believability
no matter how weird it gets is something that LaBute, 37, credits
to his actors, a pitch-perfect cast that includes his longtime star
Aaron Eckhart as Betty's no-'count husband and the deadpan Allison
Janney (``The West Wing'') as the soap opera's executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about truth in the acting,'' LaBute says. ``They're
not playing the results. They're not thinking it's funny
themselves, as characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman rejects his director's generosity. ``It's all because of
Neil,'' he declares. ``Neil knew what he was doing, and it worked
because the director had a firm grasp of what he was doing and
where he was going with it. He knew it was a gamble, and he was out
on a limb, but that's who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's centerpiece scene _ and possibly its trickiest to
pull off _ is one in which Betty meets David/George at a benefit
and insists to the bewildered actor (and his soap opera colleagues)
that she is his fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make that scene happen, but you also have to make
it work, and have the audience be charmed and not go, `Oh, come
on.' So much of the movie is about Betty. Do you want her to
succeed?''
</P>
<P>
   Largely thanks to Zellweger's performance, you do. ``It's lovely
work, a complete creation,'' the director says. ``You can create a
persona people like, but it's not the same as goodness. Renee can
just look at you and smile, and you go, `I want to help her
along.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as viewers of his other films know, ``I've never been
someone as a filmmaker interested in whether the audience likes a
character,'' LaBute says. ``The key has always been, are these
people interesting. They could be bastards, but they have to be
compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Freeman's work as a surprisingly tenderhearted
hit man. ``Talk about a balancing act,'' LaBute says of the actor's
work. ``Here's a guy who, by his own description, is a killer, a
`garbage man,' but you believe in his dignity and grace. He keeps
winning you back no matter what he does, not only getting laughs on
the way but making you believe how obsessed he becomes with
Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman says, ``What's interesting about the whole idea of him
forming this relationship is that he's doing exactly what Betty is.
This whole fantasy love affair starts to develop, but it's
happening against his better judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute originally was thinking of Eckhart and Gene Hackman as
the movie's hit men. ``The one thing I didn't want was that
black-and-white combination that's in every other movie,'' he says,
referring to the stereotype of African-American actors cast as
villains. But when producer Steve Golin suggested the Freeman-Rock
pairing, LaBute found it hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   As for Freeman, he says, ``About halfway through reading the
script, I knew I had a very interesting character to play there.
And I knew the other character was being played by Chris Rock.
Juxtaposing those two facts, it was a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by first-timers John C. Richards and James Flamberg, and
winner of the best screenplay award at the Cannes Film Festival,
the script was tweaked throughout by LaBute. ``I was very much like
an editor,'' he says. ``I found that it freed me in many ways; I
found myself not so emotionally attached to it. I did a lot of
writing on the dialogue, deciding how to make this or that joke
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards and Flamberg also wrote extra lines during the
shooting, adding more arch scenes for the soap opera clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was also a very conscious effort along the way not to
make it more me,'' LaBute says, acknowledging his tendency toward a
darker view. ``If I had written it, Betty would have died at sea in
the last reel. People wouldn't have expected that, would they?''
</P>
<P>
   In a Neil LaBute movie, maybe they would.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEIL LaBUTE FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age: 37.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Brigham Young University in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home: Fort Wayne, Ind. Married with two kids, a son, 9, and
daughter, 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Next project: ``Possession,'' based on A.S. Byatt's
dual-timeline novel, with a screenplay by LaBute and Laura Jones.
The cast: Gwyneth Paltrow, Aaron Eckhart, Tilda Swinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger stars as a Kansas waitress convinced that her
favorite soap opera is real. And she's chased by hit men. With
Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock and Greg Kinnear. Opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on the movie: www.nurse-betty.com
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
