</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-OUTBACK03-COX     09-01 2286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTBACK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Australia's vast, remote interior is home to 'roos and the rock,
to strange and wonderous animals, natural light shows, awesome
silence and more stars than ever imagined
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia _ The first Australia guidebook I
consulted showed a yellow traffic sign with the silhouette of a
bounding kangaroo. How cute, I thought _ probably one of those
novelty items you can find in the Sydney airport next to the emu
oil and the stuffed koalas.
</P>
<P>
   Then we arrived in the unofficial capital of the Outback, Alice
Springs, the only town of any consequence for hundreds of miles in
every direction. We had just gotten off an overnight train from
Adelaide and had not seen a single bouncing marsupial in 19 hours
of crossing the bush. Now we were waiting at the car rental counter
listening to a clerk recite insurance mumbo jumbo. Something she
said jerked me out of my stupor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't cover kangaroos.''
</P>
<P>
   I chuckled, wondering whether she was pulling my leg, and
assured her that we didn't need any _ wink _ kangaroo insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' she said. ``But if you hit a kangaroo, you pay the
damages.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't kidding. ``Does that really happen?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes. We had a party from California hit one a couple of
weeks ago. Totaled the car. Watch out around sunset; that's when
the boomers come out.''
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me that I was probably standing in the only place
on Earth where such a conversation might take place.
</P>
<P>
   Australians say that if you want to understand their country,
you have to go to the Outback, the vast interior where highway
signs really do warn of kangaroos darting across the roads like
deer. They say this despite the fact that few Australians actually
inhabit the Outback. Though the nation is about the size of the
lower 48 states, it has a population of only 19 million (less than
Georgia and the Carolinas combined), and the great majority are
huddled near the sea, especially along the boomerang-shaped coast
that stretches from Adelaide to Melbourne to Sydney to Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of Australia is barren, remote, inhospitable _
``the ghastly blank,'' as one pioneer diarist called it. American
explorers like Lewis and Clark came back with thrilling tales and
enticing samples of the Western flora and fauna. Burke and Wills,
the most famous Australian explorers, tried to cross the continent
in 1860 and died of starvation. This land demands respect.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, growing numbers of tourists have been venturing
into the Outback to admire the desert vistas and glimpse the lonely
sheep stations and learn something of the ancient Aboriginal
culture. My wife and I were curious, too. After a week and a half
in Sydney, we wanted to see the solitary side of Australia, so we
exercised an option that poor old Burke and Wills never had: We
flew to Adelaide and took the train.
</P>
<P>
   The alien fauna of Alice
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1920s, the main supply route into the heart of
Australia was a camel caravan tended by Afghan herders. The
railroad that replaced it _ still called the Ghan _ was for years
notoriously unreliable. Termites devoured the crossties. Flash
floods washed out the tracks and stranded passengers for days, the
crew shooting kangaroos to feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have to do that. We're well provisioned,'' our
steward, Norbert, assured us as we boarded on a Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   We settled into a holiday class twinette _ a private berth about
the size of a back booth at the Waffle House _ and watched as
civilization slipped away outside our window. Suburbs gave way to
vineyards and then to fields of sheep and finally to flat scrubland
dotted with clumps of saltbush. After dinner in the Matilda car, we
made a brief stop in Port Augusta, a mining town, and turned north
for the void that Australians of a poetic bent call the
never-never.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert pulled down our stretcher-size beds, and the gentle
rocking of the rails soon lulled me to sleep. I didn't wake until
the first hint of day colored the oily dark on the eastern horizon.
The scene was breathtakingly empty and beautiful _ I felt like an
astronaut watching planet Earth from space. I called to my wife in
the upper berth, but she let out a low growl like an irritated cat.
She was in no mood for dawn patrol; the gentle rocking I found so
restful was a fitful tossing in the top bunk.
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning we were in Alice Springs, a place I knew only from
the movies. Thanks to ``A Town Like Alice,'' a love story about a
rancher back from war, and ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of
the Desert,'' a comedy about drag queens on the road, I didn't know
whether to expect cross-dressers or dusty jackeroos.
</P>
<P>
   We saw neither. Alice used to be renowned as an end-of-the-line
outpost that attracted all manner of eccentrics _ an Aussie Key
West. You can still catch vestiges of that spirit every October
during the Henley-on-Todd Regatta, in which beery contestants race
bottomless boats, like Fred Flintstone motoring with his feet, down
the dry bed of the Todd River. But for the most part, Alice has
become a thriving tourist center whose 26,000 residents all seem to
run motels, souvenir shops, art galleries and fast-food joints. The
busiest spot in town appeared to be the KFC, where the Colonel's
original recipe has apparently replaced emu and kangaroo as the
principal protein source among the indigenous population.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Alice's attractions relate in some way to its isolation.
We visited the School of the Air, where lessons are broadcast on
two-way radio to children scattered across thousands of miles of
Outback. And we stopped by the Royal Flying Doctor Service, an
airborne medical corps that provides care to ranching families and
rural communities that are hours from the nearest hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The most engaging place we found was the Alice Springs Desert
Park, a wildlife preserve that answers the question: What could
possibly survive in this Martian landscape?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Red Center, as central Australia is known, was
rather green when we arrived. An Indian Ocean cyclone had doused
the desert, and the crimson sand was bursting with wildflowers,
mulga trees and spiky spinifex grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best rain we've had in years,'' said Mark Richardson, the
curator of botany. ``I'm taking the family camping next week. We'll
never see this many things growing again in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   In half a day at the park, we saw all sorts of strange and
wondrous animals _ bilbies and wedge-tailed eagles and thorny devil
lizards and desert death adders coiled in a dim exhibit hall
devoted to nocturnal creatures. We loved the emus. With their
ruffled gray feathers and beady orange eyes, the gawky, flightless
birds wear a look of perpetual befuddlement.
</P>
<P>
   But our favorites, predictably, were the kangaroos. I felt a
rush of pure childish delight when I entered the fenced enclosure
and caught my first sight of a 'roo in the flesh. He was a boomer
all right, as tall as a man, with a rusty coat to match the dirt.
Yet there was something awkward about seeing him in repose. We're
so used to watching kangaroos leap through nature films that when
we see one just hanging around, propped on his tail and hind legs
like a folded-up tripod, he looks rather tame.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was a real live kangaroo, and we were enthralled. We
must have shot a roll of film as he shuffled around the yard
munching on spinifex, looking up now and then, almost
lackadaisically, as if to say: OK, I'll pose, but no autographs
please.
</P>
<P>
   A big show at a the rock
</P>
<P>
   The next kangaroo we saw was roadkill, a carcass flattened onto
the shoulder of the two-lane blacktop we took to Uluru, five hours
southwest of Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Uluru, or Ayers Rock, is Australia's most familiar natural
landmark. No taller than Stone Mountain, it makes a more dramatic
impact because of the way it erupts from the arid plain like a fist
from the netherworld. The monolith is actually an eroded hunk of
sandstone with a veneer of oxidized iron, a bright red color that
changes in the dawn and dusk like a gargantuan mood ring. Twice a
day, crowds gather to watch the show.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn was the subtler entertainment. We rose at 5 a.m. and caught
a bus for the morning viewing area, already thick with lawn chairs
and spectators wrapped in blankets against the chill. The sun's
first rays dabbed at the rock with pinks and pastels before
settling on the brilliant red you see on the postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Dusk was splashier in every way. We hopped the bus again and
arrived at Sunset Strip (the other viewing area) to find a throng
of tailgaters worthy of a Georgia Bulldogs football game. Barbies
were smoking, wineglasses were clinking, cameras were poised. The
rock didn't disappoint. In the last slanting light of the day, it
went from red to salmon to brown to black. The only downside was
the traffic jam trying to get out.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to a take a closer look at the mountain on the
following morning, but decided against climbing it, as many
tourists insist on doing. The Aborigines who own Uluru discourage
climbing not only because of the rock's near-sacred significance in
their traditions, but because it's dangerous. Thirty-nine people
have died trying to make the steep, windy, milelong ascent.
Aborigines have a word for the climbers, who cling to a chain rope,
single-file, as they scale the sheer slope: minga _ ant people.
</P>
<P>
   We elected instead to take the six-mile hike around the base.
The monolith seemed less monolithic as we walked past caves,
rockslides and other geological details that, like clouds, all
seemed to resemble something. We imagined snakes, fish, a skull, a
pair of lips. It's easy to understand how the Aborigines were able
to conjure so many legends about this place.
</P>
<P>
   It was also easy to see why no one else much wanted to live
around here. As the sun rose higher, the dratted bush flies began
to assault our orifices, and we scrambled to find the face netting
our hotel had given us when we checked in.
</P>
<P>
   That night we did the rock again at the Sounds of Silence
dinner, an evening under the stars that's one of the best parts of
visiting the Red Center. Another bus took us to a sandhill midway
between Uluru and the Olgas, a nearby cluster of sandstone
formations that look like chips off the old rock. We were greeted
with champagne and canapes, and we marked another sunset as a
musician coaxed weird vibrations out of a didgeridoo. Then we were
led to a dining patio, where we ate grilled lamb under more stars
than I ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Southern Cross there,'' pointed out one of our
table mates, Jim McKillop, a retired professor from Queensland. His
accent was a dead ringer for Sean Connery's, so we weren't
surprised to hear that he had come from Scotland as a lad, back in
the days when Australia was desperate to populate its empty
continent.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, we gathered around a fire, and a family of
Italians started singing opera while some Australians fought back
with folk songs, and a couple of Japanese women giggled. Presently,
an astrologer with a plummy British accent commanded our attention
and walked us through the Southern constellations with a high-beam
flashlight and telescope. When he finished, no one said a word. The
silence of the desert night was almost holy.
</P>
<P>
   Travels with Charlie
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday morning, having spent one dawn and two dusks at the
rock, we were starting to hum that old dirge from ``Fiddler on the
Roof'': sunrise ... sunset. But there was one more daybreak we
wanted to experience, not so much for the scenery as for the eyes
we would be seeing it through. It was an Aboriginal tour.
</P>
<P>
   Uluru, after all, is Aboriginal land _ a status the Australian
government recognized in 1985 when it returned the park to the
Anangu people who have lived here for eons. Our tour guide was one
of their descendants, a stocky fellow with a shock of black hair
and threadbare clothes that smelled of campfire smoke. He smiled,
revealing a couple of missing teeth, and introduced himself as
Charlie Walkabout.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours, we followed Charlie down a sandy red trail as he
showed us how to make glue from spinifex, how to use the glue and
bindings made from kangaroo tendons to attach a spearhead, and how
to throw the spear to kill kangaroos. His English was spotty, so he
usually spoke through an interpreter as he told us how the features
of the mountain figured in the creation stories his people have
passed down for generations. I couldn't follow it all, but it
seemed to be a wild tale involving snakes, wallabies, blue-tongued
lizard men and a boulder that resembles an emu drumstick.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the tour, Charlie motioned for us all to come
closer. ``We are all going to die,'' he began, speaking directly to
us in hushed English. ``The rock was here before us, it will be
here after us. Our children will bring their children to see it,
your children will bring their children. The rock isn't just for
black people.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't decide whether Charlie was imparting the wisdom of
the ages or simply saying, ``Y'all come back.'' Either way, I
thought he was one of the most unusual guides I had ever met. The
impression was reinforced when his interpreter handed us business
cards that said ``Charlie Walkabout, Senior Aboriginal Guide'' and
noted an address that was anything but aboriginal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie likes to get e-mail,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
