r t BC-TRAVEL-BOSTON03-COX     09-01 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOSTON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beyond Boston: Day trips reveal New England
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Freedom Trail. Boston Common. The Boston Tea Party
Museum. Each year, hordes of visitors flock to these well-known
Boston destinations.
</P>
<P>
   But as any native will tell you, the tourist spots downtown are
not necessarily the best places to experience the best the Boston
area has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians, in fact, are notorious day-trippers. And for good
reason. Downtown Boston is only a short drive from a wide variety
of prime spots that showcase the region's stunning wild beauty and
provide an authentic slice of New England life. And as late summer
gives way to the first chill of autumn, these places take on a
special charm for history buffs and nature lovers alike.
</P>
<P>
   Lush forests of tall oak and maple _ stretching from the
outskirts of the city to the nearby foothills of the White
Mountains of New Hampshire _ provide a perfect setting for fall
foliage hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool lakes, rivers and ponds _ teeming with fish and, often,
sailboats _ offer a quiet respite from the madding crowds and
snarled traffic downtown.
</P>
<P>
   White-sand beaches along Boston's south shore and Cape Cod are
picture-postcard settings for leisurely encounters with the great
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   And quaint New England fishing villages dotting the state's
rocky north shore are a piece of Massachusetts' maritime history,
along with alluring boutiques, art galleries and some of the best
seafood restaurants in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So when in Boston, do as the Bostonians do: Get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   To get you started, we've come up with six best bets for short
escapes from the city _ all within a few hours' drive of Boston
Common: Walden Pond, Rockport, Mount Monadnock, the Arnold
Arboretum, Newburyport and Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MCLAURIN03-COX     09-01 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCLAURIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author Tim McLaurin faced with cancer, he finds love, healing
and new story
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim McLaurin is used to facing death. Long before he became a
critically acclaimed writer, the Fayetteville, N.C., native
regularly handled rattlesnakes, copperheads and cobras in his
traveling reptile exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   He has survived several poisonous bites as well as an agonizing
struggle with multiple myeloma, a bone marrow cancer. And so, when
McLaurin, 46, was diagnosed with cancer of the esophagus a few
months ago, he was well prepared to die.
</P>
<P>
   He had lived a full life, he told himself. An ex-Marine who had
kicked a debilitating drinking habit after 20 years, he had been
married and divorced twice, had two teenage children, and had
worked as a Peace Corps volunteer in Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered if ... it was time for me to die ... to chronicle
that in writing, straightforward and honestly,'' he says, ``and I
was willing to do that.'' Besides, he had undergone a painful bone
marrow transplant years before, and he didn't want to go through
that kind of treatment again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to deal with the hassle of being sick,'' he
says. ``I didn't want to deal with being poked and prodded and that
loss of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he met a woman who not only changed his life, but helped
save it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Quaine arrived one day in mid-February and offered the
touch of her healing hands. A friend of a friend, Quaine had a
Ph.D. in business, but she also was trained as a healer in Reiki, a
technique developed by a Buddhist monk in Japan in the late 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin says the first time she placed her hands on his chest,
he thought she was using a heating pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every day for three weeks she returned and placed her
hands upon me, wafted fragrant smoke upon my body, lit candles and
rang bells,'' he wrote in a newspaper story. ``She told me that
sometimes when I talked to her, leaves and feathers fell in a
shower from above my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Her love and trust made him rethink his reluctance to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking, maybe your story isn't to end right here,
to tell people how to die. Maybe you've got other stories to
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Declared free of the cancer, McLaurin describes his ordeal and
his relationship with Quaine in a 15-page epilogue for ``The River
Less Run,'' a chronicle of his life from June 1998 to June 1999,
that will be published in September by North Carolina-based Down
Home Press.
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin thought it was the last book he would ever write.
</P>
<P>
   ``The River Less Run'' focuses on a cross-country trip McLaurin
took with his mother, children and other relatives in a Winnebago.
He had already written the memoir when cancer struck and Quaine
entered the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Neither McLaurin nor Quaine credits her alone with saving his
life. She says he was cured ``by some of the best Western medicine
and some of the deepest love.''
</P>
<P>
   The story has an even happier ending. McLaurin and Quaine plan
to be married Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 11th is the day we met,'' McLaurin says, ``and we're
getting married on the 11th day of the 11th month. She's an
incredible blend between the real world and the spiritual world.''
</P>
<P>
   What impressed him most, McLaurin says, is that Quaine had never
read any of his books when she met him, yet she seemed to
understand him immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run into a lot of women who think they know me through my
books, and they don't. She knows me as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   An honest, fearless writer
</P>
<P>
   None of his friends would have bet that McLaurin would graduate
from high school, let alone become a writer. He grew up poor in
North Carolina, shooting squirrels and birds for dinner, a way of
life chronicled in 1991's ``Keeper of the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way he wrote well-received novels such as ``The Acorn
Plan,'' ``Woodrow's Trumpet'' and ``Cured by Fire.'' His work
reflects his hardscrabble childhood and the influence of writers
such as Harry Crews and Jim Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, Tim is a throwback,'' says North Carolina novelist
Lee Smith, who has offered her Hillsborough, N.C., home as the site
of the Nov. 11 wedding. ``He is a writer who is truly tied to the
land in a way most of us have not been for at least a generation.
He carries around a little bag of dirt from the farm where he grew
up. He's lived very deeply on a very elemental, almost mythic
level, in a way few people do. That's evident in his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an absolutely honest and fearless kind of writer,'' Smith
adds. ``He uses his writing as a way to confront his anger and his
fears.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin's editor, Jerry Bledsoe, puts him in the same category
as Crews and Larry Brown _ ``rough South'' writers who come from
poor white backgrounds. ``They are the ones who have been chosen by
whatever forces there are to make sure their own people's stories
are told. Otherwise, no one would be telling these stories.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin wants to memorialize his survival by having a phoenix
tattooed on his chest, where doctors operated. The bird will join
tattoos of family names, flowers and animals that adorn his right
arm and the snakes and birds on his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   And he plans to keep painting his toenails. The first time, a
young visitor painted his two big toenails a metallic blue, a color
favored by halter-topped teens. Since then, he and Quaine have
repainted them a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like it,'' McLaurin says. ``Some people might look
at it and think it's weird, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing as therapy
</P>
<P>
   Even as a child, McLaurin was willing to be the odd man, to
question what he was told. He was taught that snakes were to be
feared and killed. But when he chopped up a harmless rat snake, he
felt guilty enough to read about snakes, learning that most of what
he had been taught was a myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snakes,'' he says, ``represent a way of overcoming ignorance
and fear. And overcoming ignorance in small steps is a way to fix a
lot of what's wrong with the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he finds comfort in the world he and Quaine have made
in Hillsborough with McLaurin's bulldog, Roy Lee; red-tail boa,
bull and Gaboon viper snakes; and an African spur-footed tortoise
named George.
</P>
<P>
   He smokes two cigars a day _ 45-cent Phillies Blunts that he
prefers to Cuban cigars. ``I don't see that big a difference,'' he
says. ``Maybe I cropped so much tobacco growing up that I'm immune
to the finer qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't do anymore is drink. He went on one last epic
drunk in November 1998 that landed him in the hospital. He says it
was deliberate _ one last blow-out so he could walk away from the
bottle once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used that part of my life up until it was dust in my palm
and I could blow it away and it was gone,'' McLaurin says.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't wish his two decades of hangovers on his children, or
his illnesses or his mistakes. But in a sense, he hopes they live
their lives as he has, with a sense of adventure, a courage to look
death in the eye without flinching and to walk away with the will
to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they want to travel and seek and explore _ I hope they
make it to the moon,'' he says. ``I always thought that during my
lifetime, I'd make it to the moon, that by the age of 46, there
were Pan-Am excursions to the moon. But we stopped going to the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin, meanwhile, is hitting the road to promote his memoir.
He'll be in Atlanta this month for the Southeast Booksellers
Association's trade show, and after that he's going back to work on
a novel and another memoir about working in tobacco fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always used writing as a form of therapy,'' he says. ``I
wrote `Keeper of the Moon' when I was going through treatment for
myeloma. Through my words I'm able to leave the hospital bed and
the shell of my own body and go into a place in the past or the
future that's disease-free and peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
