<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8727 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV03-     09-01 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: IF IT TRIES TO ESCAPE, EAT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
 (eds: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can see it now: killer bamboo marches across Central Park.
That was my first reaction when I heard that the Horticultural
Society of New York is holding a festival this month, with the
American Bamboo Society, that actually encourages people to grow
this plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say invasive _ say overly aggressive,'' Michael Alfano,
president of the society's northeastern chapter, said, standing by
an airy hedge of Phyllostachys bissetii in his garden in Port
Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllostachys, or giant bamboo, can form beautiful groves of
canes _ culms, they are correctly called _ from 10 feet to more
than 100 feet tall, depending on the species.
</P>
<P>
   The culms are wonderfully varied in color: green, yellow, golden
orange; yellow with a vertical green stripe; green with a yellow
groove; mottled green and black, like snakeskin; as jet black as a
Steinway.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllostachys is a running bamboo, so called because it extends
rhizomes underground, sending up shoots that grow into tall canes.
If you don't want it to spread, you have to be vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend a little time each fall harvesting the shoots,
you won't have a problem,'' Alfano said. The shoots of
phyllostachys are edible, especially those of P. dulcis, or
sweetshoot bamboo, which has a sweet, nutty flavor. Cut them just
beneath the soil, like asparagus, peel back the leaves and eat the
crunchy white shoots raw or steamed. But remember, if you don't
want that baby to spread, snap off  &UR; all &LR;  its shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Some people use plastic barriers, buried three feet in the
ground, with three inches above. ``But the runners will just go
right over the top and wander on,'' Alfano said.
</P>
<P>
   The P. bissetii in his yard has vigorous, dark green
seven-year-old culms 20 feet tall, and their flexible, leafy stems
sway and sigh on the wind. ``The neighbors love it,'' he said. It
remains evergreen all winter, and it's magical in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Use common sense when planting. ``Bamboos can be aggressive and
destroy neighboring plants, so don't put them next to anything you
deeply care about,'' said Dr. Peter Del Tredici, the director of
living collections at the Arnold Arboretum at Harvard University.
``But it's not invasive in the sense of spreading by seed, on the
wind or by a bird. It's all vegetative.''
</P>
<P>
   If you plant a variety that's an enthusiastic runner, just make
sure you have room to mow around it so it can't take over, he
advised.
</P>
<P>
   Del Tredici moved the arboretum's bamboo, which was growing too
vigorously, to very poor soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the backhoe out and put them in a roadbed where we had
trouble growing anything,'' he said. They're doing fine _ growing
 &UR; slowly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alfano suggests planting a running bamboo near water, which it
doesn't like, or on the edge of a pine woods or in shade. Or sink
it in a pot, and pop up the pot once in a while, to snip off the
runners. Many running bamboos are not hardy in the Northeast, but
they make beautiful potted plants for the terrace or garden in
summer and a cool, sunny room in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano leaned down to an elegantly sheathed seven-inch shoot
poking out of a pot of Phyllostachys aurea koi, a giant golden
bamboo with a green groove, which is not hardy in the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see one of these, just snap it off,'' he said, adding
that in Texas, this little shoot could grow to a 25-foot culm in
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboo is a member of the grass family, just like lawns,
ornamental grasses and corn. Key to life in Asia, it is becoming
increasingly popular in the West as a landscape plant, or as a
sustainable supply of beautiful, sturdy material for things like
trellises, flutes, furniture and houses. And about 300 kinds of
bamboo, from 6 inches to 60 feet, are hardy in the New York area,
Alfano said.
</P>
<P>
   He fell for bamboo nine years ago, after he dug a pond in his
backyard, stocked it with koi and wanted some Asian plants to go
with it. That first pond has grown into a series of ponds and
waterfalls terraced down the precipitous slope off the backyard,
extending a good 80 feet down. The rocky niches are perfect for
containing bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   All along the house are small, delicate varieties, like
Plioblastus fortuneii, a dwarf variegated bamboo with
green-and-white-striped leaves, and some elegant clumpings of
Phyllostachys nigra, a luminous black bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   Another running type, but well behaved, is Sudasa japonica, with
graceful narrow culms perfect for making arrows. Alfano planted
this clumping variety from a one-gallon pot four years ago, and
it's spread only about three feet. Another clumping species,
Bambusa ventricosa, affectionately called Buddha's Belly, swells
gently between nodes, and its green leaves have yellow stripes. B.
ventricosa Kimmei has yellow culms striped with green.
</P>
<P>
   If any little shoot appears from an overly aggressive runner,
Alfano simply eats it.
</P>
<P>
   Some bamboos like sun, others shade; some have delicate
filigreed leaves, others' leaves are wide straps, like those of an
amaryllis. Indokalmis terralotis, for example, has such wide leaves
they're used for wrapping food. It's a shade lover, as is Fargessi
nitida, a delicate clumper, whose slender leaves turn crispy in the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these varieties, as well as the art of cultivation, will
be discussed at Bamboo Fest 2000 next weekend at the Horticultural
Society, 128 West 58th Street, in Manhattan. (Information: (212)
757-0915, extension 200.) The weekend begins Friday evening, with a
bamboo art show and a Japanese flute concert. There's a rare plant
auction on Saturday. Lectures cover such varied topics as bamboo
for northern gardeners, bamboo cultivation, bamboo flowering (a
rare event), bamboo bonsai, bamboo basketry and all kinds of uses
for this plant so dear to the heart of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS WEEK: FEEL A COLD WIND? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PATRICIA JONAS &LR;  &QC;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Begin to pot herbs for winter use: take divisions of chives and
mint, and cuttings of woody herbs like rosemary and lemon verbena.
If tender plants have outgrown their containers, replant in pots a
size or two larger. Use the same type of potting mix. To keep the
plant in the same pot, you can carefully trim roots by as much as
25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Apply organic mulch to cut late-season weed germination. Seeds
of many weeds and self-seeding annuals go dormant over winter. Pull
up annuals that have gone by, or cut off seed heads before they
shatter.
</P>
