   WAN: Atlanta, National, Social Issues
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD _ OXFORD, Ga. _ J.P. Godfrey Jr. thought he had left
``separate but equal'' behind when he joined the Air Force in 1952.
But upon returning home decades later, he found vestiges of
segregation in Oxford, 35 miles east of downtown Atlanta. The
Newton County town is home to 2,000 people, including the 600-plus
at Oxford College. ``I have always been quite fond of this old
place,'' said Godfrey, 63, whose grandparents cultivated corn and
cotton there. ``My grandfather was proud of the fact that he owned
property. He used to say, `When you own a foot of land, you own
something.''' Soon after arriving six years ago, Godfrey searched
for his grandparents' graves at Oxford's only cemetery. ``I
couldn't find them,'' he said, so he began making quiries.
Godfrey's questions stirred ghosts from Oxford's past, entangling
the city in a debate over the sins of a bygone era, the cemetery's
future and a pile of money. (Gentry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
