<P>
   EDITORIAL-BOOKMAN _ ATLANTA _It wasn't government-sponsored
religious persecution, but it was too close for comfort. A few
years ago, while covering the Georgia Legislature, I happened to be
sitting alone in the press gallery early one morning, reading
through the bills filed the day before. On the other side of the
glass partition, legislators were milling about the House chamber,
waiting for the day's session to begin. Over the intercom, I heard
the unmistakable tone of a minister up at the podium, about to
offer the traditional morning prayer. So I set down my papers and
bowed my head, and when the prayer ended, I resumed my work. A few
minutes later, out in the hallway, I was accosted by a red-faced
House usher. ``Somebody saw you back there,'' he told me, waving an
angry finger in my face. ``You have to stand up during the prayer.
If you don't stand up, you're not going to be allowed back in that
chamber.'' (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
