<P>
   LABUTE-BETTY _ With ``Nurse Betty,'' writer-director Neil LaBute
(''In the Company of Men'') worked for the first time with someone
else's script. He said a new clarity came from the change, an
ability to see what worked and what didn't more clearly than he
could when directing his own scripts. The end result: an intriguing
movie that easily will be LaBute's most commercially accessible
movie. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHILDSTARS _ ``Child Stars: Their Story,'' which airs Sept. 4
on A&AMP;E. I've always wondered why any parent would let their child
go into show business. Sure, the potential for huge paydays is
tempting. But is the price that must be paid for that possible
fortune worth it? Child stars, for instance, are often robbed of a
normal childhood. Growing up is hard enough. Imagine having to do
it in front of millions of people watching your every move or
snickering about every goofy-looking pimple you get. The pressure
to perform is also insanely intense. Many adult actors can't even
take the heat and often resort to drugs and alcohol to cope. Just
think what it's like for a kid to overhear a producer angrily
talking about low ratings and possible cancellation. And in a
business where rejection is the norm, just what kind of toll does
that take on a child's psyche? (Thompson, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MCLAURIN _ Tim McLaurin is used to facing death. Long before he
became a critically acclaimed writer, the Fayetteville, N.C.,
native regularly handled rattlesnakes, copperheads and cobras in
his traveling reptile exhibit. He has survived several poisonous
bites as well as an agonizing struggle with multiple myeloma, a
bone marrow cancer. And so, when the 46-year-old McLaurin was
diagnosed with cancer of the esophagus a few months ago, he was
well prepared to die. He had lived a full life, he told himself. An
ex-Marine who had kicked a debilitating drinking habit after 20
years, he had been married and divorced twice, had two teenage
children, and had worked as a Peace Corps volunteer in Tunisia. ``I
wondered if . . . it was time for me to die . . . to chronicle that
in writing, straightforward and honestly,'' he says, ``and I was
willing to do that.'' (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
