<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BOOKMAN03-C     09-01 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BOOKMAN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For release Sunday, September 3, 2000
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: UPHOLDING SEPARATION OF CHURCH, STATE
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _It wasn't government-sponsored religious persecution,
but it was too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, while covering the Georgia Legislature, I
happened to be sitting alone in the press gallery early one
morning, reading through the bills filed the day before. On the
other side of the glass partition, legislators were milling about
the House chamber, waiting for the day's session to begin. Over the
intercom, I heard the unmistakable tone of a minister up at the
podium, about to offer the traditional morning prayer.
</P>
<P>
   So I set down my papers and bowed my head, and when the prayer
ended, I resumed my work.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, out in the hallway, I was accosted by a
red-faced House usher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody saw you back there,'' he told me, waving an angry
finger in my face. ``You have to stand up during the prayer. If you
don't stand up, you're not going to be allowed back in that
chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   I had a couple of thoughts. The first was evidence that a little
boy still lived somewhere inside me. Somebody, I realized, had been
peeking when they should have been praying. Naughty naughty.
</P>
<P>
   The second reaction was more serious: This is government, I
realized, trying to tell me how to pray. And that made me mad. I'm
sad to admit that I got right back in that poor man's face, angrily
telling him that nobody was going to tell me how to pray and
demanding to know who had sent him on his ridiculous errand. He
refused to tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, our little confrontation had played out in
public, and a few days later I got an informal feeler from the
American Civil Liberties Union, inquiring whether I might want to
file suit in the case. It would have been a slam-dunk First
Amendment case: a journalist denied access to a place of government
for failing to pray in an approved manner. I declined the offer,
believing that as a journalist I shouldn't become the story.
Besides, I had already made my point.
</P>
<P>
   Until that moment with the usher, though, I had never
consciously appreciated the importance of the wall between church
and state. The traditional morning prayer at the Legislature had
struck me as more harmless custom than religious exercise, although
I had often wondered how some of the representatives would react if
one day the guest minister offered up praise to Allah instead of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we have the right to pray as we wish, or not to pray
at all, and government has no say in that choice whatsoever. Some
people stand to pray, some people kneel, some merely bow their
heads. Muslims prostrate themselves toward Mecca. And in the Sermon
on the Mount, Jesus told his followers that when they pray, they
should ``enter into thy closet, and when thou hast shut the door,
pray to thy Father in secret.'' He also warned against praying as
the hypocrites pray, ``for they love to pray standing in the
synagogues and in the corners of the streets, that they may be seen
of men.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't presume to know the heart and mind of God. But that
admonition against the public display of prayer seems pretty clear
_ and pretty wise _ to me. It also raises a perplexing question. In
response to a recent Supreme Court decision banning organized
prayer at high school football games, some religious groups have
begun to pray out loud at the games anyway, in protest. Many of
those groups also claim a literal belief in the Bible. I wonder how
they justify their public prayer in light of Jesus' admonition. In
the wake of this column, no doubt I'll be offered enlightenment as
to their thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, of course, did not cite Jesus as the basis of
its decision on prayer at football games. Its argument was founded
instead in the First Amendment, which in turn was inspired by a
strong belief in the freedom of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Our forefathers believed that God has given each of us free
will, so that we might decide for ourselves what constitutes
religious truth. They decided that if God in all his wisdom didn't
coerce faith, it wasn't government's place to do so either.
</P>
<P>
   And they were right. Those who would use government to push
religion on their fellow citizens dishonor their political heritage
as Americans, and belittle the freedom of conscience granted to
each and every one of us. They need to go into a nice quiet closet
and think about that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
