   FOOTBALL/OTHER
</P>
<P>
   FBO-HIGHSCHOOL-FOOTBALL _AUSTIN, Texas _ When the old Austin
High Maroons get together, and they do so with some frequency, the
talk often turns to the unusually cold autumn of 1950. To Coach
Kitchen and two-a-days, to bus trips for games at Waco and Corpus
and San Antonio and icy Kerrville, and to that scarf incident on
the charter plane to El Paso. To Friday nights under the lights at
a packed House Park. And to that state championship game in Dallas
against the hated Wichita Falls Coyotes. Some of the guys were
players back then, some just fans and classmates. These are men
with wives and children and grandchildren and professions. But
memories of those days 50 years ago _ a time before television and
the pro sports explosion, when an Austin of 130,000 people focused
so much on the one white high school in town _ still stir them and
unite them. ``We take nostalgia trips, without guilt,'' says Hunter
Morris, a Maroon yell leader that fall and now a retired
Episcopalian minister. (Wear, Austin American-Statesman) WITH
PHOTOS MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RACING
</P>
