<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush showing campaign confidence
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush claimed today he has the momentum against Al Gore
despite distractions and slipping polls. To Democratic complaints
that a new Republican campaign ad resorts to negative campaigning,
Bush said it is being broadcast by his party to counter attacks on
him. ``I'm going to defend myself,'' he said. Bush said the ad,
which questions Gore's credibility by citing his past in a
``tongue-in-cheekish'' way, comes after $30 million worth of
Democratic advertising challenging Bush's record. Bush was
campaigning today in Lafayette, La., and Texarkana, Ark.,
concentrating on education _ his chosen topic during a week of
distractions, including a ruling by a federal judge demanding
improvements in his state's handling of medical benefits for
low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH READY TO RUMBLE
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential race heads into its final two months, George
W. Bush says voters will begin hearing a lot from him about the
``failed leadership'' of the current administration. Hammering on a
theme he launched in his convention acceptance speech _ that Al
Gore has been part of an administration that ``squandered its
opportunities'' _ Bush said he will continue to beat on this point
in the post-Labor Day run-up to the election: ``I'm going to keep
reminding the American people that it's one thing to give flowery
speeches, to talk big about issues, but they've had a chance to
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   24-HOUR `WORKATHON' FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore plans to burst into a 24-hour ``American Workathon'' to
mark the Labor Day holiday with a presidential campaign blitz
leading up to a major economic speech. Gore plans a five-city tour
beginning Sunday to ``spend time with Americans who are working.''
That's to be followed by a speech Wednesday in Cleveland where he
was to offer a detailed economic plan with specific goals for the
country's economic future.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTING MCCAIN, DOWNPLAYING NADER
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman criticized George W. Bush's plans for Social
Security and Medicare today, using the words of Bush's defeated
Republican primary rival. ``Let me quote my friend and colleague,
John McCain, who said it best and probably said it right here in
Maine earlier this year, `Governor Bush's plan has not one penny
for Social Security, not one penny for Medicare and not one penny
for paying down the national debt.' John McCain was right then and
it is still right today,'' Lieberman also appealed to voters not to
support the Green Party's Ralph Nader instead of Gore. Lieberman
said Nader's national support has ``gone way down,'' and ``a vote
for Nader is a vote for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE INSISTING ON COMMISSION DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign chief said today that Gore would consider
cable and network offers to debate George W. Bush only after
sealing a deal with the Presidential Commission on Debates for
three matchups. Dismissing sole-broadcast forums such as CNN's
``Larry King Live,'' as ``the wrong way to go,'' William Daley said
they wouldn't reach as many American TV viewers as commission
debates which everyone could air. Bush, whose aides were meeting
today with the commission members, hasn't accepted debate offers
yet, while Gore has officially accepted the commission's three
October debates and others.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK AD AS JUNK BOND
</P>
<P>
   Getting personal, Republicans came out with an ad attacking Al
Gore's credibility in a gambit that exploits his greatest perceived
vulnerability while betraying worry about the course of George W.
Bush's campaign. The decision to attack Gore so directly this early
in the stretch to the Nov. 7 presidential election was widely seen
by those who study campaign conduct as a sign of nervousness about
how Bush is doing. That did not foreclose the possibility the ad
would score big. ``This is a political version of investing in junk
bonds,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg, ``a dramatic and
risky move, which has the potential for a significant return.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE WON'T FIRE BACK, HOPES FOR BACKLASH
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee abandoned plans to release an
ad that seriously questions George W. Bush's record in Texas,
choosing to yield the spotlight to a new Republican attack ad
against Al Gore in the hope that it will backfire. After news
reports about the Republican ad appeared, Gore himself immediately
revised his plans for the day, backing away from a speech about
health care so that the Republicans' message _ an assault on Gore's
credibility _ would come through loud and clear. Gore then deployed
running mate Joe Lieberman to denounce the TV spot.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE TO LABOR DAY LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidate significantly ahead in the polls
around Labor Day has won every election for the last 50 years _
largely because there have been few close elections over that span.
That hasn't been the case so far this year, with George W. Bush and
Al Gore virtually tied in many polls as Labor Day approaches. But a
Newsweek poll out today showed Gore 10 points ahead of Bush, and
other polls out late next week will give further evidence of
whether Gore is gaining a lead. ``There's a lot of evidence that
after Labor Day, the polls start to solidify,'' said James
Campbell, a political scientist from Buffalo, N.Y. and author of
``The American Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   SO, DO WE STILL HAVE TO VOTE?
</P>
<P>
   Eight academics presented statistical models at the annual
meeting of the American Political Science Association, predicting
the outcome of the Nov. 7 election. All seven forecast an Al Gore
victory, with his projected share of the vote ranging from 52.8
percent to 60.3 percent. The seven scholars, with their predictions
for Gore: James Campbell, University at Buffalo, 52.8 percent; Brad
Lockerbie, University of Georgia, 52.9 percent; Alan Abramowitz,
Emory University, 53.2 percent, Helmut Norpoth, State University of
New York at Stony Brook, 55 percent; Christopher Wlezien,
University of Houston, 55.2; Charles Tien, Hunter College, with
Michael Lewis-Beck, University of Iowa, 55.4 percent; and Thomas
Holbrook, University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee, 60.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN'S SENATE RACE QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's Democratic secretary of state, Susan Bysiewicz,
says Joe Lieberman should quit his Senate race while running for
vice president. State Democrats generally have supported
Lieberman's decision to stay in the Senate race, but Bysiewicz said
she, and people she has talked to around the state _ ``folks who
think very highly of Senator Lieberman'' _ are ``a little
disappointed'' by it. Lieberman has an overwhelming lead over his
Republican challenger, Waterbury Mayor Phillip Giordano, in the
Senate race. But if he should also win the vice presidency, it
would fall to Republican Gov. John Rowland to appoint a
replacement. Lieberman could quit the Senate race as late as Oct.
27 and be replaced by another Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH STRETCHING OUT, SETS GORE INTERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey, known for chatting about books and spirituality,
will venture into the political arena next month with season
opening guest Al Gore. Winfrey has scheduled a live interview for
Sept. 11, the first show of her 15th season. This is new territory
for Winfrey. She has done interviews with political figures
including first ladies Barbara Bush and Hillary Clinton, but the
context was decidedly apolitical. Producers also have invited
George W. Bush to appear. Bush has not yet responded.
</P>
<P>
   A GOOD SCHOOL EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Pop quizzes, more often than not, spell troubles for
politicians. So Dick Cheney looked vaguely concerned when he got
one Thursday morning as he walked into a classroom full of
6-year-olds in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. His task, explained the
teacher, Rosalyn Robinson, was to guess which solution an egg would
float in: corn starch, food coloring or salt. Cheney chose salt,
and as he dropped eggs into cups filled with each solution, he was
borne out. ``Just don't ask me to spell potato,'' he said,
referring to another quiz met with less success by another
Republican, Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   NOT A GOOD SCHOOL EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly not Dick Cheney's favorite subject. The
Republican vice presidential nominee had gone to Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., to push the ticket's school construction proposal. The plan
calls for the federal government to allow private companies and
school districts to issue tax-exempt bonds for school construction.
But Cheney quickly became muddled when asked about basic points,
overstating the program's cost by about 1,500 percent and turning
repeatedly to an aide for help. ``I think the $2.8 billion is a
five-year figure,'' he said. ``Kathleen, correct me if I'm wrong,
that $2.8 billion is the revenue that would be foregone by the
federal government.'' Kathleen Shannahan corrected him: ``The total
cost is $181 million over five years, for an (annual) average of
$36.2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   NADER WEARING WELL ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader's Web sites are up, running and loaded with
``NaderNews,'' video highlights and anything else needed to make
him more than a bit player in the presidential campaign. The Green
Party presidential candidate is still thirsting for coverage by the
mainstream media, where Al Gore and George W. Bush rule the roost.
But votenader.org and the friskier, ``unofficial'' nader2000.org
are avidly chronicling his every move and utterance. The
votenader.org site extols him as an enemy of ``the political decay
that has turned our government over to a plutocracy and to the
politicians who take its marching orders.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG TAX BILL FOR CLINTON'S HOST
</P>
<P>
   The builder playing host to President Clinton and Senate
candidate Hillary Clinton this weekend in the upstate New York
resort village of Skaneateles has an outstanding state tax bill of
almost $1 million, officials said today. A tax warrant against
Thomas B. McDonald, issued in October 1999, claims McDonald owed
the state $771,662 in unpaid income taxes for 1997 and about
$145,000 in interest and penalties as of October. Interest on the
tax bill is believed to have increased the total owed to
$938,357.48, said Marc Carey, a spokesman for the state Department
of Taxation and Finance. Said White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart: ``People from time to time have issues with either the
IRS or the state and they generally get resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH WALLETS BEING TAPPED
</P>
<P>
   Trailing in the money race, the Democratic National Committee
has launched a high-stakes effort to capitalize on vice
presidential nominee Joe Lieberman with a fund-raising campaign
aimed at Jewish donors who have not been politically active in the
past. The fund-raising drive will be part of a larger DNC push to
raise at least $50 million over the last two months of the
campaign. One Gore money raiser likened it to the outpouring of
support from Catholics for John Kennedy's candidacy in 1960 or the
response from Greek-Americans to Michael Dukakis' 1988 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MONEY GOING TO LAZIO
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio's New York Senate campaign collected more than $10.7
million between July 1 and Aug. 23, a staggering amount boosted by
small checks from thousands of Hillary Clinton opponents around the
country. Lazio far outstripped his Democratic opponent, who took in
$3.3 million during the same period. The figures were included in
reports the candidates filed with the Federal Elections Commission.
The reports include only ``hard money contributions,'' which are
limited to $2,000 per individual donor and go directly to the
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   LONELINESS AT THE POLLS PREDICTED
</P>
<P>
   Despite a spirited race between Al Gore and George W. Bush,
voter turnout in the 2000 presidential election could be the lowest
in modern American history, according to a new study. Curtis Gans,
director of the nonpartisan Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, said low turnout in the primaries, scant political
coverage by the major TV networks and an increasingly disinterested
public were to blame. In the 1996, voter turnout dropped to 49
percent of the voting-age population, equaling the total in 1924 _
the lowest percentage for a presidential election in the modern
era. The study by Gans' organization predicts turnout will be lower
on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUIT AGAINST BUSH TO GO FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has lost his bid for dismissal from a lawsuit
accusing him of violating the free speech rights of environmental
protesters at the Governor's Mansion in Austin, Texas. State
District Judge John Dietz said Bush could be called to testify when
the case goes to trial. No date has been set. The suit alleged that
Bush gave state troopers ``unbridled discretion'' to target
protesters picketing in front of the mansion last year on a public
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE WAY FOR THE DOT-COM MOM
</P>
<P>
   USA Weekend magazine, along with Steve and Cokie Roberts, have
identified the swing voter in the presidential election. ``Soccer
Mom'' has been displaced by ``Dot-Com Mom'' _ the single American
the candidates must capture in order to win the race. The model
Dot-Com Mom is Cherly O'Donnell. She lives in the suburbs of
Cincinnati. She is a business owner, a wife and a mother of two.
The Dot-Com Mom is Roman Catholic and the youngish of the Baby Boom
era. She works part-time and spends a tremendous amount of time on
her e-commerce business. The Dot-Com Mom uses the Internet daily
from paying bills to planning family vacations. So how's she
leaning? So far, O'Donnell is not impressed with either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
