<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-HAMPTONS-SURFING-2TAK     09-01 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-SURFING-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO ESCAPE THE HAMPTONS: PADDLE! 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I was gliding over the chop on my surfboard last Saturday
afternoon, wearing a red bikini and matching long-sleeve rash
guard, hair matted with salt, I greeted the members of the motley
bronzed gang I'd known for three months, but whose names I still
hadn't caught: ``Hey man, catch any good rides today?''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't exactly how I had planned on spending my summer in
the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   True, after learning surf basics during recent vacations in
Mexico and Los Angeles, I had purchased a 1987 black Monte Carlo SS
so I could cart my long board in style to a cramped surf shack near
Ditch Plains, Montauk's surf mecca. But I wasn't ``hard core'' or
anything. I had only rented the place, sight unseen, with seven
other Manhattan surfers I'd met by chance at a club just before
Memorial Day. (That I claimed I could surf and pay rent served as
adequate reference.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to working the tube, I admit that I also had designs
on that party circuit featured in ``The Mix'' pages of Hamptons
magazine. But after the first few weekends of making the 45-minute
commute to party alongside 18-year-old models with sharp elbows, my
will began to wane. The moment of truth came after Jay Z's Fourth
of July barbecue. Around 3 a.m., at Conscience Point, I found
myself showing off my prized surf bruises to a man wearing shiny
loafers, a tennis sweater over his shoulders and a totally glazed
look.
</P>
<P>
   That night, the tug of the Montauk tide won out. I headed east
and never looked back. I gave up trying to tame my hair against the
forces of the ocean humidity and went with the sun-damaged, nappy
look. I closeted my Gucci heels in favor of flip-flops, shelved the
hip-hop CDs and bought the Beach Boys' ``Pet Sounds.'' The
adjectives ``stoked,'' ``gnarly'' and ``epic'' filtered into my
vocabulary. I was converted.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, I was just joining the wave. While there have
been surfers in Montauk since the 1960s, over the last few years a
new set of boarders is turning out in record numbers. Hipsters,
models, photographers and architects can be spotted riding the soup
alongside local teen-agers and fellow Manhattanites, including the
artist Julian Schnabel, the designer Tracy Feith, the Razorfish
co-founder Jeff Dachis, Paper magazine's David Hershkovits (though
he's actually a boogie boarder), and the nightclub impresario Will
Regan of Union Bar and Lotus.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Foley, who opened the Air &AMP; Speed Board Shop in Montauk
five years ago, says his business has taken off in the last two
seasons. ``There's more surfers than ever, particularly among women
and beginners,'' said Foley, who started holding surf camps this
summer to meet the demand for lessons. East Deck, a '50s-style
motel with rickety wood-paneled suites is a favorite surfer hangout
_ the Four Seasons of Montauk _ because of its choice beach
location in Ditch Plains. The motel has had to implement a waiting
list for the rooms closest to the break, known as the ``A''
section, and is planning to install a digital camera on the roof
that will feed real-time images of the waves to a surf forecast Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Gerri Tomitaz, a real estate agent at Remington Realty Ltd., who
has been renting homes in Montauk for almost 10 years, says that
she has been getting calls from more and more surfers and that as a
group surfers are gaining greater social status. ``Years ago nobody
wanted to rent to surfers because they had a reputation for being
slobs and bums,'' Tomitaz said. ``But this new breed is more
affluent and upscale. They're restaurateurs and architects, and are
considered very desirable tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison Haas, 24, a public relations associate at Chanel, started
surfing this summer, after renting a splintery shack in Ditch
Plains with 14 other people. She has abandoned the tonier Hamptons
for good. ``Out here you can wear flip-flops and sarongs all day,''
she said, peeling off her rash guard shirt and spraying herself
with Chanel sunscreen. ``There's no scene out here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-lane dropouts may be heading to Montauk as much for
surf-worthy waves as for its anti-Hamptons attitude, but the
laid-back vibe can take some gelling. In Montauk, tiny houses are
seen as a conceptual style choice, not a sign of an anemic bank
account. Even so, when I first laid eyes on my summer rental,
decent by surf share standards, I was somewhat taken aback. It was
hardly the sprawling bachelor lair I had envisioned; instead, it
was a flimsy pre-fab modular, a low-rent version of the kind in
``The Truman Show.'' In place of a pool or a hot tub in the yard
there was a mosquito-ridden swamp, and the view consisted of a
bulldozer and a few tricycles abandoned by the kids across the
street. Getting my equipment out of the basement was always
worrisome: a cute surfer housemate with a knack for picking up
girls slept down there on a double mattress.
</P>
<P>
   It took some adjusting to give up all addictions to gourmet
coffees and food. Most of the restaurant fare in Montauk is greasy,
overcooked or fried. Brawny athletic types in board shorts lounge
about sipping coffees _ no cappuccinos _ outside delis and packing
post-surf-session carbohydrates at hokey diners like Mr. John's
Pancake House. The most nouvelle option is the Ditch Witch, a
health-food truck that sells wraps and smoothies in the dirt lot in
front of the main break.
</P>
<P>
   Social life out East might not require a lot of thought about
what logos to wear to polo matches, but it has its own etiquette,
like not ``dropping in'' on other people's waves or ``bailing off''
boards on crowded, two-foot waves. Name-dropping is another no-no,
largely because people don't even know each other's names. Like
American Indians or mobsters, surfers tend to be identified by
their most prominent physical characteristics, though admittedly
they're less inventive (``the cute blond guy with the red board'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
