<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8737 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RETREATS03-COX     09-01 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETREATS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sometimes the best vacations of all are spent reaching up to
God, reaching out to others.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting at a beachside cafe sipping pina coladas, reading in a
rocking chair on the porch of a mountain cabin, or sightseeing
across the country may be relaxing vacations away from work and
routine. But there are other rewarding uses of time: meditating on
a spiritual retreat; growing vegetables to learn about hunger;
taking students on a journey of reconciliation. With classes back
in session and fall events gearing up, we gave some Georgians whose
holidays were meaningful the classic back-to-school assignment: How
I Spent My Summer Vacation.
</P>
<P>
   EVELYN WATKINS, 34
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Douglasville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: World Changers Church International.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: Went on retreat at the FieldStone Inn in Hiawassee in
the North Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   IN HER OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``As we traveled there on a Friday evening, we whined all the
way. `There are no Chick-fil-A restaurants. The sheets are going to
be musty in the cabin.' But once we got there, a gentleman came in
and said it was beautiful and the view was wonderful and the air
was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``And God convicted me. He said, `Did you hear what they said
and what you said?' When we woke up the next morning, we opened the
curtains; it was just as though someone had hand-painted the scene.
It was majestic. Somehow all of that worry seemed so insignificant
against what reflected out of the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to think of nature as something we have to control.
But there are some things that are wonderful, functional and
majestic all by themselves. One of the things I enjoyed was how
much nature appreciated nature. The grass under the tree, the
shade, seeing branches move when birds sit on them _ all of
creation seemed to relish what seems so ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back the ride was quiet. There seemed to be a sense of
peace. I wanted to notice the things on the way back that I didn't
notice on the way there. I wasn't looking for a Chick-fil-A.''
</P>
<P>
   DR. LEE WOODALL, 45
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Barnesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: First United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: Woodall, a family physician, made his first trip to do
mission work in Honduras in 1993 under the sponsorship of
Decatur-based Honduras Outreach Inc. He has made several trips
since then, and now serves on the board of Honduras Outreach. In
July, he led a team of eight people to work on clinic and church
repairs in the village of La Ensenada, which has about 120 homes,
mostly mud huts with no electricity. He also treated patients.
</P>
<P>
   IN HIS OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to realize that my work and responsibilities in
Honduras are an important part of God's call to serve my sisters
and brothers. God has been preparing me for this work for many
years, long before I heard or answered this call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through my experience in Honduras, God has allowed me to more
completely experience his love for my sisters and brothers and for
me. I see the world through different eyes than before. I read his
word with a different understanding. I am privileged to have
discovered sisters and brothers whom I never knew, whom I deeply
love, and whom I consider role models for me in my life. I am a
better person because of them and their love for me. I am honored
that God chose me for this. I am grateful to Honduras Outreach Inc.
for the organizational structure that allows this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   CHASTITY GRIFFIN, 15
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Northwest Atlanta; student at Frederick Douglass High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: Mount Ephraim Baptist Church in northwest
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: The Atlanta Garden for Youth, a two-month day camp
project of the Atlanta Community Food Bank, June 19-Aug. 12, to
train a dozen teenagers in how to grow and sell organic food and to
teach them about hunger issues.
</P>
<P>
   IN HER OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``I mulched and weeded and planted and harvested and sold
vegetables. I learned that it's not just people without a job who
get hungry. There are a lot of people who work all day for minimum
wage, and after they pay their rent and utilities and buy clothes
for their family there's not much left for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me realize I need to get a good education, so I don't
have to work on minimum wage. I'd like to go talk to kids in
different schools about what I did this summer, encouraging them to
get involved in creating food gardens and helping the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the project I learned to work as part of a team and
made new friends. Since I have mostly attended African-American
schools, the program allowed me to appreciate people from different
backgrounds more.''
</P>
<P>
   CYNTHIA SHAW, 52
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Avondale Estates, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: Ebenezer Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: Shaw, assistant dean and director of student
development at Emory University, took a group of students on a
``Journey of Reconciliation,'' a service, learning and work trip to
South Africa. The trip was sponsored by Emory's office of the dean
of the chapel and religious life. The journeys are one element in
Emory's ``Year of Reconciliation,'' a series of talks,
performances, projects and events to encourage dialogue on the
theme of reconciliation as it relates to a range of society's most
pressing issues.
</P>
<P>
   IN HER OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this trip, the ones that have gone in the past
and the one to Northern Ireland this year, is to provide Emory
students the opportunity to cultivate relationships with
communities that are engaged in various stages of reconciliation
around the world. We hope to support these communities in their
reconciliation efforts and learn from them. This was my second trip
to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all given African names in a worship service. To a
person, that probably was the most moving experience of the trip.
It is not just that you're given a name; you are usually given the
name of the person standing before you naming you.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Africa when they name a child, they look at the child, they
study the circumstances of the family they're born into, the day of
the week, they factor so many things into how a person is named
that it's a very thoughtful process. When they give away their
name, they're giving away a part of themselves. They're saying that
if you return, because you're a part of me, you will always have a
home here. It's very powerful. Lerato, my African name, means love.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997 my first trip to Africa was going home. You look at
the people there and they look like me _ like aunts and uncles and
sisters. It affirmed for me that I was home, this is where I came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   JUSTIN BUTTIMER, 14
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Acworth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: Transfiguration Catholic Church in
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: Justin, following in the footsteps of his older
brother, Sean, took part in the Ulster Project Atlanta, a
tolerance-building program pairing a dozen Catholic and Protestant
teens from Omagh, Northern Ireland, with teens in Atlanta. The
Irish youngsters spent a month (June 29-July 28) living with the
families of the Atlanta teenagers. The 24 teens participated daily
in social activities, service projects and discussion groups.
Justin and his family hosted Darren Pritchard, 15.
</P>
<P>
   IN HIS OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Six Flags and Stone Mountain, helped clean up a
park, and helped feed the homeless downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to a different church each week. We talked about
conflict and how to get along. I was never very social, but now I
am. Almost everyone in the project became my friend. The kids were
so nice, they brought me out. And I got to meet a lot of girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty cool. The Irish say things differently than us.
You say cool, they say lethal. When they say, `We're having good
craic' (pronounced crack), they mean good fun. I've stayed in touch
with four or five of the kids via e-mail, and have called Darren
several times, but it's expensive. He'll be getting e-mail soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ANGELIA POUNDS, 35
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Religious affiliation: International Gospel Outreach Center.
</P>
<P>
   Activity: Decided to spend vacation with her husband, Cleve,
traveling to the Potter's House, the church led by Bishop T.D.
Jakes, a nationally known evangelist. Before the trip, Pounds said
God told her to donate her family's van to her sister.
</P>
<P>
   IN HER OWN WORDS:
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my sister and told her, `God is telling us to plant
the car in your life.' So we drove down there and gave the van to
them, even though we only have a car for a family of five.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time down there, Bishop Jakes' message was about
`nonsense faith.' That's a move in your life when God establishes
stuff in your life that actually makes no sense. That was a message
of confirmation for us. We called it the Isaac offering, being
willing to give of yourself, not knowing if it's going to come
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the Potter's House and it was an awesome
experience. It was multicultural, a very charismatic high praise
worship service. It challenged you to not just talk about faith but
to live it. God speaks to you best when you pull back from the
normal hustle and bustle that keeps you distracted. We're mindful
that we're not taking a vacation away from God. We take a vacation
so we can spend time with God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
