<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-HAMPTONS-SURFING-2NDT     09-01 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-SURFING-2NDTAKE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: red board'').  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the calendar is different out here. While most Hamptonites
pack up on Labor Day, the surfer season peaks from August through
October, when the hurricane storms create the best swells.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even fall waves on Long Island aren't that big
compared with the macking towers of power found in California and
Hawaii. But that's not necessarily a bad thing. In Montauk, the
summer swells are typically a manageable one to three feet, so it's
easy to come off looking like a pro. Status is measured in other
ways. You're somewhere near the top of the pecking order if you: 1)
have friends who are pro surfers or have met Kelly Slater, 2) have
lived/surfed in Hawaii or know someone who does, 3) know Peter
Beard well enough to cut through his property to get to the break
called Ranch or 4) are self-employed so that you can take off at a
moment's notice if the surf's up.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the word is out. Surfers and ``posers'' alike are
flocking to have a piece of the local motion, the main road through
town is lined with cars and SUVs toting piles of boards on their
roofs and, contrary to the idyllic images on local postcards, on
the weekends the waves are so packed with surfers and boogie
boarders that it looks like the Long Island Expressway during rush
hour. In fact, it's starting to resemble the showy beach scene at
Sagaponack's Sagg Main. One day when a guy who looked like a banker
pulled up in a silver Mercedes carrying an expensive board with no
wax on it (a sure sign of little usage) my housemate Tommy shook
his head and sneered, ``What a Barney,'' surfer-speak for a rich
guy who has the latest gear but can't surf.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't stress on the bunk vibes. Montauk has its own
low-key charms, the kind of mindless, grungy summer pleasures you
might have had when you were a teen-ager. We bought a few Tiki
torches, a hammock and Hula-Hoops from Kmart. With the dozens of
surfboards leaned up against the house, I had to admit it looked
pretty authentic.
</P>
<P>
   We held backyard cookouts and made cozy beach bonfires where we
debated the day's rides and made wide-eyed plans to go on surf
safaris to such tubular paradises as Fiji and Mexico. On the days
when the waves weren't ``working'' we huddled on our sandy couch,
reading surf magazines and watching surf videos and the Weather
Channel. Sometimes at night, we'd pile into my housemates' giant
cargo van and drive to local bars like Cantina, a Mexican-themed
dive with too many cactus paintings, for its weekly surf social.
</P>
<P>
   There we'd consume beer and chips in front of a big-screen TV
and watch more surf footage. A favorite was the amateurish ``Big
Wednesday,'' shot last August off Ditch Plains during eight-foot
hurricane swells. Whenever people at the bar saw someone they knew
riding the tube they'd wave a fist and cheer: ``Ye-ah! Shred it up,
dude!''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-August, tanned and buff, we all decided to make our
summer as endless as possible and extend our rental till November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-MISSILE-DEFEN     09-01 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON PUNTS ON MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While declaring that the missile threat to the
United States is ``real and growing,'' President Clinton announced
Friday that he would let the next administration decide whether to
deploy a controversial system to defend against missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have decided not to authorize deployment of a national
missile defense at this time,'' Clinton said in a speech at
Georgetown University here, adding that he ordered the Pentagon
instead to continue testing the complex system of satellites,
rocket interceptors and sophisticated sensors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made progress but we should not move forward until we
have absolute confidence the system will work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans immediately denounced the president's decision, with
GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush saying the action
``underscores the fact that for seven years the Clinton-Gore
administration has failed to strengthen America's defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bush said that the administration ``first denied
the need for missile defenses, then delayed. Now they are leaving
this important unfinished business for the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected president, Bush, the Texas governor, said that he
would not hesitate to deploy the National Missile Defense (NMD)
``at the earliest possible date.'' Bush supports deploying a more
extensive version of NMD that theoretically would protect the
United States as well as its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans lined up behind Bush. Rep. Floyd Spence,
R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said
Clinton's action would ``leave Americans vulnerable to ballistic
missile attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., called the decision ``dangerous,''
adding that ``the time is rapidly approaching when countries such
as North Korea and Iran will have missiles capable of striking the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last several days, Bush and his running mate, former
defense secretary Dick Cheney, have made the case that the Clinton
White House has undercut military readiness by the combination of
successive years of budget cuts and frequent deployment of troops
to overseas hot spots. The White House and Vice President Al Gore,
the Democratic nominee for president, counter that the military is
the best prepared it has been in years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore defended Clinton's decision on NMD. ``I welcome the
opportunity to be more certain that these technologies actually
work together properly,'' said Gore, who supports a much more
limited NMD system than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., called the decision ``a win for all
Americans'' because it gives the administration more time to work
out the technological and diplomatic kinks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision also was greeted warmly in Moscow and by arms
control groups.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Interfax news agency, Gen. Leonid Ivashov, a
senior Russian defense ministry official, said: ``There is hope
that a considered approach to the solution of the most important
international problems will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Concerned Scientists, which staunchly opposes the
missile defense system, called the action ``the right call at the
right time.'' And the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers said
Clinton ``has come to the common sense conclusion that that NMD is
not ready for prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration says the system is needed to protect the
entire United States from a limited missile attack from North Korea
or Iran, two ``rogue'' country's believed to be the most likely to
fire a missile at the United States. NMD also is being designed to
provide protection against an accidental nuclear missile launch in
Russia, sparked by decaying Soviet-era equipment or a weapon that
falls into the hands of a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   According to current Pentagon plans, the program will be
constructed in several phases. At first the anti-missile system
will use 20 interceptors based in Alaska. But by 2007, the Pentagon
plans to add another 80 interceptor missiles. The cost is estimated
at around $36 billion but could rise to $60 billion or beyond,
depending on how many interceptors and sensors are added.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton said the ballistic missile threat ``is
real and growing and has given new urgency to the debate about
national missile defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that while NMD still faces technological hurdles,
the administration also faces diplomatic obstacles. He said
additional time is needed to assuage the concerns of China, Russia
and several NATO allies. Beijing and Moscow fear that NMD, which is
prohibited under the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, might
render their nuclear arsenals obsolete, forcing both to build
improved classes of nuclear weapons, thereby triggering an arms
race.
</P>
<P>
   From a diplomatic standpoint, the United States has two options:
get Moscow to agree to change the treaty or unilaterally exit the
pact. Russia thus far has been loathe to alter the treaty, which
has served as the basis for nuclear security for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In three flight tests to date in which a mock intercontinental
ballistic missile was fired against the system, two tests ended in
failure and one scored a direct hit and knocked the missile from
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision halts plans to build a powerful radar station
on a remote Aleutian Island off the Alaskan coast that would have
been used to scour the skies for signs of a missile attack.
Construction of the radar station would have been the first steps
in deploying the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's action effectively means that NMD won't be operational
until at least 2006, one year later than previously planned. The
first contracts for the radar would have had to be awarded by
December to begin construction next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
