<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTI-CHRONOLOGY-ART-2     09-01 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-CHRONOLOGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUBBING THE CONCEPT OF CHRONOLOGY IN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little war against time has begun. Last year in New York, when
the Museum of Modern Art opened the show ``Modern Starts: People,
Places, Things,'' the first part of ``MOMA 2000,'' Cezanne's
``Bather'' from 1885 was found hanging next to a 1993 Rineke
Dijkstra photograph of a pale boy in a maroon bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later the Tate Modern, in its permanent collection,
lined up Matisse's sculptures of women's backs before a firing
squad of ink drawings of nude women by a contemporary artist named
Marlene Dumas. And at the modern art museum at the Georges Pompidou
Center, Henri Rousseau's 19th-century ``War'' faced off against a
Picasso sculpture from 1950, ``Girl Jumping Rope.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics were up in arms. What got them was not the mixing of
media or the mixing of masterpieces with lesser works. It was the
mixing of time periods. As Jed Perl, an American art critic, put it
in The New Republic, ``Chronology, that backbone of the historical
sense, has been collapsed into some kind of postmodern time warp.''
</P>
<P>
   David Sylvester, a British art critic, wrote in The London
Review of Books that ``chronology is not a tool of art-historical
interpretation which can be used at one moment, discarded at
another.'' Rather, he said, ``It's an objective reality, built into
the fabric of the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, anti-chronology is now the rage. The
Brooklyn Museum of Art, the Denver Art Museum and the High Museum
of Art in Atlanta have all rehung their painting and sculpture
collections according to subject instead of chronology. And ``The
Art Book,'' published by Phaidon, ``debunks art-historical
classifications'' (in its words) by arranging artists
alphabetically instead of chronologically. That is, Picasso is
found next to Piero della Francesca and Manet next to Mangold.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing curators seem to agree on about anti-chronology is
this: Chronology and time are only the surface issues. The deeper
issues are genealogy and history, whether there is a great lineage
of art, a natural progression of one art movement after another
leading up to the grand finale, abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   In art history, said Linda Nochlin, the Lila Acheson Wallace
Professor of Modern Art at the Institute of Fine Arts in New York,
``there is a tendency to use chronology as teleology,'' as proof of
a march toward a goal. ``To the degree that a nonchronological hang
can destroy that,'' she said, she approves. ``The main thing is to
break up the idea of an uninterrupted flow.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the problem with flow? The problem is the flow chart. In
1936 Alfred H. Barr Jr., the founding director of the Museum of
Modern Art, created a diagram to go with the exhibition ``Cubism
and Abstract Art.'' It showed the evolution of various movements
or, as they are now called, ``isms'': Neo-Impressionism, Fauvism,
Cubism, Futurism, Expressionism, Orphism, Suprematism,
Constructivism, Dadaism, Neoplasticism, Purism, Surrealism. And all
the isms led to abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   With its Hegelian aura of inevitability and objectivity, the
Barr diagram is the casus belli of the chronological war. In ``Tate
Modern: The Handbook,'' Iwona Blazwick and Frances Morris, who
developed the conceptual framework for the new museum's displays,
note that Barr's chart ``came to dominate most modernist
collections around the world,'' and that it ``is still used to
delineate art into periods and movements.''
</P>
<P>
   That chart ``was the religion of modern art, like the chart of
the House of Windsor,'' said Robert Rosenblum, a professor of fine
arts at New York University. ``It represented truth. This one
married that one and begat that one.'' It was neat, easy to absorb
and difficult to eliminate. Floor plans were designed with the
diagram in mind. As Nicholas Serota, the director of the Tate,
wrote in ``Experience or Interpretation,'' the modern art museum
became a one-way narrative, ``a single path with no byways and only
occasional opportunities for exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Now museums are working to undo the diagram. Why now, at such a
late date? Almost everyone thinks the millennium was a motivating
factor. Blazwick said, ``The idea of starting with 1900 and
marching to 2000 was _ well, there is such a thing as museum
fatigue.'' Charles Stuckey, a curator at the Kimbell Art Museum in
Fort Worth, cited ``the pressures of political correctness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to show that the history of art is not about
masterpieces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Crow, the director of the Getty Research Institute, said the
theoretical ideas from art history and the social sciences are
finally seeping into museums.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, bucking Barr is now a museum sport. Some
have tried the nonchronological approach. Others have gone for the
hyperchronological approach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Stuckey ``raked together'' the contemporary and modern
collections of the Art Institute of Chicago and showed them
strictly chronologically, without regard for geography, medium or
movement. ``It was a new way to look at the collection, and it
brought out works that had fallen between the cracks,'' he said.
``It's rather neutral politically. It's nonbiased.'' Like an
alphabetical approach, ``it gives no advantage to a group or a
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim Museum's ``1900,'' a show put together by
Rosenblum that examines a slice of art from 1897 to 1903 with few
works from the modernist canon, was another radical response. ``I
like to shuffle the deck of isms,'' Rosenblum said. ``Showing
everything done at the same time is anti-chronological in a
sense,'' because there is no time passing, no progress. It is a
snapshot of a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog for the second part of ``MOMA 2000,'' ``Making
Choices,'' took a swipe at chronology, too. Rather than surveying a
sweep of time, the book explored core samples of four years: 1929,
1939, 1948, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the most popular way of bucking Barr is the
anti-chronological hang. Both ``Tate Modern: The Handbook'' and the
Museum of Modern Art's catalog for ``Modern Starts'' reproduced
Barr's diagram as a kind of cautionary tale. And both made it their
business to get across the idea that there is no one true history,
but rather many.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tate Modern's installation has no single pathway through it.
And Blazwick noted that in the new museum you can see that
``everything is constructed.'' Even the wall labels are signed now,
and each one expresses the view of its author. In each gallery,
Blazwick said, you can tell that ``someone made a decision.'' That
is, ``by selecting one thing, we are also rejecting something.''
There is no natural order, no objective truth.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no one modernism. The word ``modern,'' Blazwick
said, ``is so flexible and multivalent that we think of it in terms
of modernisms: plural not singular.'' So modern has become
postmodern, a potpourri of choices. Or as John Elderfield, chief
curator at large at the Museum of Modern Art, put it: ``We're not
replacing one orthodoxy with another. We want to show that what was
happening until now was an orthodoxy.'' It is a process of
defamiliarizing the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is something oddly familiar about the new
anti-chronological hangs. The Tate Modern and the Museum of Modern
Art, after pondering various options _ including organizing the
collection or exhibition according to geography, or around certain
manifestos or important exhibitions, or by modes of fabrication, or
by color, or according to the prevailing thinkers _ independently
came up with those old-fashioned categories called genres.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art took three categories for ``Modern
Starts'' _ people, places, things. The Tate took four genres _
still life, landscape, nude and history painting _ and then
loosened them up. In both cases, though, it was back to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The nonchronological hang is an old notion. In the 18th century
museums were just collections of loot, Elderfield noted. And before
that there were Wunderkammern, cabinets of wonders, curiosities and
grotesques, organized every which way. The shift began when the
Louvre opened to the public after the French Revolution and assumed
a didactic function.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arranging paintings in terms of schools and countries was a
19th-century invention,'' Elderfield said. ``There was a ``passion
to systematize.'' So the resurrection of genres in installations is
a way of leapfrogging backward over the 19th-century obsession with
linear progress and evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no natural way to hang things,'' he said, just as in
biology there is almost no natural way to categorize things. ``All
taxonomies are subjective except species.'' And in art history
there are no species.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to agree that every hanging is biased and
incomplete. So maybe the chronology war comes down to whether to
dwell on the biases or not. Donna De Salvo, a curator at Tate
Modern said, ``We want to allow things to feel unsettled,'' to let
people see that museums are constructions, not givens. Or as
Blazwick put it, ``We are trying to make the institution more
transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that too much transparency obscures the art. ``Of
course every historical view is partial,'' Stuckey said. ``But I
think the best system is where you're unaware that someone has
arranged it. A curator should walk on the sand without leaving his
footprints.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
