<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL LEADER DOWNPLAYS U.S. CONCERN ABOUT IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak displayed no anxiety
Friday about reported U.S. concerns that Iraq might be preparing to
attack Israel, calmly brushing aside the news that the United
States has put a Patriot anti-missile battery on alert for possible
deployment in Israel's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this Patriot missile battery really needs to
be bothered,'' Barak said, adding that he did not think Israelis
should worry. Indeed, there is no state of alert here, no palpable
feeling that there is any cause of concern. The lead story on the
evening news was the opening of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a high school in the town of Ramle on Friday morning,
Barak suggested that Israelis not be distracted by the reports. ``I
would recommend that the students concentrate on their studies,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials confirmed Friday that the Pentagon had ordered an
air defense artillery brigade based in Germany to be prepared to
move its Patriot anti-missile battery to Israel. Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser, said, ``A decision was made that it
would be prudent to put these batteries on a shorter leash time
than ordinarily.'' The full battery consists of 64 supersonic
surface-to-air missiles built to intercept incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The alert was first reported in Friday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the Pentagon had specific new information
suggesting an imminent attack or was preparing for the possibility
that Saddam Hussein, the Iraqi leader, might consider the timing
right for a sudden move, with Americans preoccupied by their
presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that he knew of no threat against Israel from Iraq,
adding that given the ``vituperative statements'' that Saddam had
made against Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, and the prospect of sending
inspectors back into Iraq, the batteries were placed on alert.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, a U.S. Embassy official said, ``It's only put on
alert _ and publicly put on alert. It's a way to send a message to
Saddam Hussein that we're paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   If Israel were attacked or threatened with imminent attack by
Iraq, it would be unlikely to rely on a Patriot anti-missile
battery for its defense anyway, military experts say.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier model of the Patriot, deployed in Israel during the
Persian Gulf war in 1991, proved ineffectual against the 39 Scud
missiles that Iraq fired at Israel. In 1998, when tensions ran high
between Iraq and the United States, Israel deployed a
new-generation Patriot missile that is said to be better at
tracking and intercepting incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The more advanced Arrow anti-missile system, which Israel is
developing in partnership with the United States, is still in the
testing stages.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel would be expected to respond not defensively but
offensively to any attacks, or even the threat of an attack.
Israeli military officials note that Israeli F-15 fighter jets have
the capacity to strike targets deep inside Iraq and return home
without refueling. Israel is also believed to possess medium-range
ballistic missiles that could be aimed at Iraqi military
installations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
