   EDS: an early version of this story has moved and will be
updated as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-POLITICS (Washington) _ A look at the impact on the
presidential campaign of the delayed missile defense decision. By
Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Federal regulators issued a
public warning Friday that their review of Firestone's data had
found that tires on 1991 Chevrolet Blazer sport utility vehicles
and on some Nissan and Ford pickup trucks were even more prone to
failure than the tires already recalled on several Ford models,
mainly the Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration issued an unusual ``consumer
advisory'' saying that it had asked Firestone on Wednesday to widen
its recall, but that the tire maker had refused on Thursday to do
so. Firestone officials had no immediate comment. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (TIRE-WARNING by Julian E. Barnes has moved)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Two federal appeals judges on
Friday halted the imminent release on bail of Wen Ho Lee, the
former Los Alamos scientist accused of mishandling nuclear weapons
secrets. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-STOCKS (Undated) _ Dick Cheney said Friday he was ``fully
prepared to forfeit'' oil-company stock options that he would
otherwise continue to hold after taking office if he and George W.
Bush win in November. The vice presidential nominee made the
statement as he prepared to release his financial disclosure forms
and 10 years of income tax returns. (Summary from wires) By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT21.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Undated) _ George W. Bush talks to reporters aboard his
campaign plane about a wide range of issues. By Frank Bruni and
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   NY-U.N.-INCONVENIENCE (New York) _ Forget that some of the
weightiest world issues are up for discussion next week during the
U.N. Millennium Summit, the biggest gathering of heads of state and
government ``in human history,'' as the United Nations says.
Poverty. Global warming. AIDS. Illiteracy. Urban decay. Let's talk
New York weighty: Unspeakable traffic snarls and 170-some
curb-skipping motorcades around Kennedy International Airport and
United Nations Plaza on the East Side. Several thousand Secret
Service agents elbowing their way through 36 hotels and countless
restaurants in pursuit of their 238 ``protectees,'' from President
Clinton to Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana of Tuvalu. By Dean E.
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-RICHES-SCHEME (Mattoon, Ill.) _ Money has never put in much
of an appearance in Mattoon. Folks eat in places like Gill's diner,
circa 1940, where the all-you-can-eat walleye special goes for
$4.99. They work at factories like the Lender's Bagel plant,
sponsor of the annual Bagelfest, the town's biggest event. So more
than a few eyebrows began arching when a handful of people in this
small central Illinois town suddenly seemed to be sitting pretty. A
former police officer built a house with a six-car garage. A
retired electrician started offering people interest-free loans to
build nice houses and start new businesses: the sparkly new
Bluebird Diner, Our Own Original Bakery, Jimmy-John's Sandwich
Shop. This week, federal law enforcement officials gave foundation
to years of Mattoon gossip. They charged 11 Mattoon residents and 8
other people in a bogus financial investment scheme that,
authorities say, hoodwinked more than 10,000 people around the
world out of more than $12.5 million. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
