<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8756 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-R-NITEOUT-AMANDA-PEET     09-01 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NITEOUT-AMANDA-PEET-ART-ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHIPPED' INTO THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add photo number in photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
By LINDA LEE  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There she was, Amanda Peet, but in the crowd on
Tuesday night at the premiere of her new movie, ``Whipped,'' there
was some confusion about which one she was. A stunning woman in a
tight black, backless dress posed for the cameras. ``Is that her?''
one photographer asked.
</P>
<P>
   No. That was Lauren Holly.
</P>
<P>
   Peet swept into the Chelsea West Cinema wearing a skimpy,
blinding blue dress with teeny little straps. ``I get all my
fashion advice from her,'' she confided later in the lobby, while
the movie was being shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her'' was a friend from her days as a history major at
Columbia (and yes, Peet graduated, too): Tina Chai, another history
major, who had found her destiny first at Vogue and now as a
fashion editor at Us magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Chai was there to support Peet, who seemed to need a lot of
support. She was being attended to by her manager, Eric Kranzler,
from California, who was so completely involved with his client
that his lips moved along with hers as she answered hard-hitting
questions from E! Entertainment about what it feels like to kiss
three men in one movie. Photographers jostled and the crowd looked
stumped, for the most part, by the no-name stars of the movie, who
gathered with Peet for a group photo.
</P>
<P>
   All breezed into the theater for a few words from the
director-writer-producer, Peter Cohen, who wore the obligatory
baseball cap. And then the movie commenced, 88 minutes about four
men sitting around talking about scoring with women, and the woman
( Peet) who brings them to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes into the movie, Peet sneaked out with Stephen
Hirsh, her agent, to grab a Cosmopolitan from the vodka bar set up
in the lobby. New York was Peet's hometown. She grew up in
Manhattan and attended Friends Seminary; later she worked at City
Crab on Park Avenue South.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days when she was struggling, and only Hirsh
would take her on as a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been rejected by four agencies,'' she recalled.
``William Morris said, `You're not ready. You have no confidence.'`
So I practiced having confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peet has every right to be confident now, even though her
manager and agent anxiously followed her through the night like
pilot fish. She is taping her second season of ``Jack and Jill,'' a
series on the WB Television Network. (Believe it or not, she plays
``Jack.'') And ``Whipped'' is a breakout movie for her, a real
starring role. It's her third film to be released this year,
following a flurry of blink-and-you-missed-it movies: ``Isn't She
Great,'' starring Bette Midler as Jacqueline Susann, and ``The
Whole Nine Yards,'' a forgettable movie starring Bruce Willis as a
hit man and Matthew Perry as a dentist. Peet, however, got raves
for playing the dentist's receptionist. ``She's like grapefruit
sorbet: she cleanses the palate,'' Elvis Mitchell wrote in The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   All that only eight years after she started out with Hirsh,
rushing to her first audition and ripping her dress ``all the way
up my butt,'' she said, miming how she walked into the casting
office holding her skirt together behind her. ``I asked the
receptionist for a safety pin,'' she recalled, before doing her
monologue from Woody Allen's ``Interiors.''
</P>
<P>
   Peet didn't get the part, and complained bitterly to her agent.
``I have a potty mouth when I'm disappointed,'' she confided.
Surely she didn't learn that at Friends Seminary, a private Quaker
high school in Manhattan. ``No,'' she said. ``But you've got to do
something since you can't hit people.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Hirsh went back to watching the movie through the doors
at the Chelsea West Cinema. Then he whisked her into a car for the
10-block ride to the Lotus lounge on West 14th Street, where people
like Holly, Stephen Dorff and Linda Evangelista gathered to
celebrate one critic's grapefruit sorbet, Hollywood's latest
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
