<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV03-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING A DEAF EAR TO TALK ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miami)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, investors have won big by following the crowd. Piling
into index funds, a handful of big-company technology shares or any
stock that happened to be moving up was the name of the game.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, however, many of the hottest shares have been
of some companies found off the beaten track. Shares of midcap
companies and utilities, for instance, have been the market's
unlikely stars.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is becoming a stock picker's market, one where
individual stocks can outshine the indexes. Getting into stocks
ahead of the herd is now the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   But identifying which stocks have the most promise has never
been more difficult for investors. In-depth analysis has virtually
disappeared from Wall Street; most equity analysts are so busy
bucking for investment banking business from companies that their
stock picks can be highly suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Better to poll investment professionals famous for their
skepticism, people who know how to take a sharp pencil to corporate
financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the few in that group are Bob Olstein, manager of the
Olstein Financial Alert fund, and Ravi Suria, the Lehman Brothers
convertible-bond analyst who shot to fame last June with his
devastating report on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Olstein's fund has risen 25 percent a year, on
average; it is up 15.5 percent this year. He says that he tries to
avoid investment mistakes by tearing apart company figures. ``We
don't talk to management and we do not listen to Wall Street
research,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He points to four stocks that he thinks will rise 50 percent in
the next two years:
</P>
<P>
   _Emerson Electric, which makes electronics and instrumentation
for industrial automation, is an old-economy'' company heading into
a rapid-growth phase, he said. The company is generating $1.4
billion in excess cash flow and should earn $3.30 a share this
year.
</P>
<P>
   _National Semiconductor has $800 million in cash and no debt on
its balance sheet, and its shares have lost almost half their value
since March. Olstein expects the company to earn $2.95 a share next
year, giving the stock a price-to-earnings ratio of 15.
</P>
<P>
   _Furniture Brands has new management that will bring earnings
growth back to the company, Olstein said. At $16, the stock has a
P/E ratio of 7, yet he thinks the company will soon generate $100
million in excess cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   _Winnebago Industries is an even cheaper stock, trading at less
than 6 times earnings. ``The company has $50 million in cash, no
debt and $20 million in excess cash flow,'' Olstein said.
Recreational vehicles are a good way for investors to profit from
the aging baby boom population.
</P>
<P>
   Suria, who remains negative on Amazon.com, is decidedly upbeat
on At Home, an Internet service provider offering Web-based content
through the Excite network. The company's stock has tumbled from a
high of $59.75 last year to $14.50; its two convertible-bond issues
yield around 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors view At Home through the wrong lens, Suria said.
Rather than weigh its prospects as an Internet portal, he said, At
Home should be considered a subscription-based services company
whose customers are growing in number _ from 1.8 million
subscribers now to 3 million by year-end. ``As long as the
subscriber base is increasing, cash flow will increase,'' he said.
``When free cash flow starts opening up, it pushes enterprise
valuations. That's what made a lot of people a lot of money in
cable companies in the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   Also compelling is the fact that AT&AMP;T, which owns 24 percent of
the company, has offered to pay $48 a share to buy up to $3 billion
of At Home stock owned by Cox Communications and Comcast beginning
next January and extending until June 2002. ``To me there is no
better indicator of actual value in the company,'' Suria said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
