u a BC-WORM-LIFE-SPAN-ART-NY     09-01 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORM-LIFE-SPAN-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUG DISCOVERY EXTENDS LIFE OF ANIMAL FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This story is accompanied by a graphic, SCI-NEMATODE-BRKTHRU, in
the Current NYTRENG Graphics folder on the art library. Graphic by
Anna Hallquist, Press Democrat. A photo is also expected at
Wieck.) 
 By TIM TESCONI   
 The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Researchers for the first time have used
drugs to increase the life span of an animal, a scientific
breakthrough that could lead to a potion that helps humans live
longer, healthier lives.
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging results are from a major study, reported in
Friday's issue of Science magazine, that found synthetic drugs
extended the life of laboratory worms by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The research, the product of work at the Buck Institute on
Research and Aging, in Novato, Calif., offers the promise that
drugs could one day boost human life expectancy to 120 years and
eliminate many of the illnesses associated with old age.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first robust demonstration that drugs can extend
life span,'' said Simon Melov, a founding faculty member at the
Buck Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The Buck Institute, the only center of its kind in the United
States dedicated to biomedical research on aging and age-associated
diseases, is working in collaboration with Eukarion Inc., a
privately held biopharmaceutical company in Bedford, Mass. Eukarion
developed the synthetic, anti-aging drugs under study.
</P>
<P>
   Melov said continuing studies by the institute and Eukarion
could have far-reaching implications on human health and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   But don't rush to the drugstore just yet. It may be at least
four years before these new drugs are on the market, and then they
would be used for the treatment of such age-related illnesses as
Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, drugs may be developed that prevent the onset of
old-age diseases that so often destroy the quality of life during
an elderly person's last years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could imagine that by staving off the aging process it
could delay or prevent the diseases that come because of advanced
age,'' Melov said.
</P>
<P>
   Melov's research on the anti-aging drug therapy is continuing
with mice, with preliminary results showing that the drugs appear
to help mice live longer.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, scientists in Massachusetts will test the drug in
clinical studies of older people who have suffered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Melov, who initiated the pilot studies, worked in collaboration
with scientists in England, Atlanta and Massachusetts on the drug
therapy research reported today in Science.
</P>
<P>
   Melov said the findings, which studied microscopic worms or
nematodes, is relevant because nematodes, though primitive life
forms, share many of the fundamental biological processes of higher
species, like humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worm is great in establishing a concept. That information
is then used in further studies of more complicated life systems,
like mice,'' Melov said. He said once the research with mice is
completed there will be definite information on the drug's efficacy
in extending the life span of mammals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further studies on higher organisms in the near future will
allow us to answer whether or not we have to reconsider aging as an
inevitability,'' Melov said. He would not speculate when the
research project using mice would be completed.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of Melov's scientific research is that synthetic
enzymes produced in the laboratory can mimic the anti-aging action
of naturally occurring antioxidants in living organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Melov and other scientists said it appears oxidative stress is a
major factor in determining the rate of aging. But his research
shows oxidative stress and its impact on life span _ at least in
nematodes _ can be counteracted by drug intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Melov's experiments involved groups of adult nematodes that were
either treated or untreated with synthetic catalytic scavengers, or
SCS's, as scientists call them.
</P>
<P>
   Melov said he and other researchers found that nematodes treated
with SCS's had life spans that were 50 percent longer than the
untreated nematodes.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, researchers discovered that a strain of mutant
nematode, identified as having a shortened life span because of
oxidative stress, lived a more normal life span after being treated
with the SCS's.
</P>
<P>
   These SCS's are synthetic versions of superoxide dismutase and
catalase, which are naturally occurring enzymes involved in the
control of oxidative stress. When people get older their bodies
produce less of the natural enzymes, which causes tissue stress and
the release of toxic chemical by-products.
</P>
<P>
   These toxic chemical by-products have been found to cause the
irreversible cellular damage that occurs in patients suffering from
Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease, as well as stroke
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Malfroy, Eukarion's chief executive officer and
co-founder of the company, has spent nine years studying SCS's for
the treatment of degenerative and age-related health disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This work on nematode life span further strengthens our belief
that SCS's have tremendous potential as therapeutics,'' Malfroy
said. ``Our priority now is to move these compounds toward clinical
trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Malfroy said clinical trials will start in 2001, using SCS's to
treat stroke victims. In 2002, clinical trials will study the use
of the drug on older people with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   He said the clinical trials are aimed at studying the
therapeutic value of the drugs but researchers will glean valuable
information about the drug's impact on aging as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aging, to a large part, is the diseases one gets when they get
older,'' Malfroy said.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that the development of new drugs is slow and the
research meticulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask when they can go to the supermarket and buy the
drug,'' he said. ``That we cannot know.''
</P>
<P>
   But he speculated that in four or five years there could be a
drug available to treat age-related diseases, such as Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Malfroy said bringing a drug to the market involves a rigorous
testing process and then evaluation by the federal Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Eukarion holds five U.S. patents for its SCS technology and has
been awarded more than $2 million in grants from the National
Institutes of Health to further its research.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
