<HEADER>
A8769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-01 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH HOPES SAVVY WILL RUB OFF ON YOUNGER PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He will be one of the calming voices Sunday,
the perspective younger players may need, the inspiration that
Pepper Johnson once was to him.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Smith was plucked off the waiver wire by Bill Belichick for
a purpose, that being Smith knows his defensive system. But he also
understands that what he adds in leadership might be his greatest
attribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has never asked me to take a player aside and talk to
him, but he expects his leaders to lead,'' said Smith. ``I know
that if I have something to say, they will listen. I haven't played
in the league for 11 years not to be a guy players on the team will
listen to. I have a lot of experience to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not a player who will need a big break-in period. Last
Thursday against Carolina he intercepted a pass and recorded a sack
on a blitz. It's instinctive that Smith knows what Belichick is
trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   He looks around the secondary and he knows Ty Law. He knows
Lawyer Milloy and Larry Whigham. He's not going to tell them
anything they don't already know, but he can help Kato Serwanga,
Antwan Harris, Tebucky Jones, and Tony George. And he already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ty and Lawyer were great players when they were young,'' said
Smith. ``They're that much better now. I have been able to pass
some things on to the younger DBs and hopefully that's helped. This
is what you do when you get to be 34, 35 years old. You begin to
share the wisdom you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom is one thing, but being able to play the game well is
another. He will turn 35 in another month, but Smith said, ``I feel
like I did when I was 26. I keep myself in the best shape all year
round. I never get out of shape. As you get older you have to
approach it that way. You have to be in great condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, his life has been a steady traverse up and down
Interstate 95. He was with the Eagles from 1991-94 and a member of
the Jets in 1995. He was cut during the '96 season and hooked on
with the Patriots. He helped the Patriots advance to the Super
Bowl, intercepting a Mark Brunell pass in the AFC Championship Game
and returning it 47 yards for a touchdown for the final points in
their 20-6 win over Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, he returned to the Jets, playing for Belichick
and Bill Parcells. He stayed there until the Jets cut him last
week. Smith's cap number, more than $1 million, was too high for a
player who wasn't going to be the starting corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either you start or you're gone,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was out of work for about 24 hours when Belichick and
Scott Pioli were on the horn, telling him to make the drive up 95
once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how it's turned out,'' said Smith. ``I'm grafetul
I've been able to play on the East Coast because I'm an East Coast
guy and I haven't had to uproot my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Or learn new names. He used to cover Terry Glenn and Troy Brown
in practice, then in real games for the other side, and now he's
back covering them in practice. When he faces the Jets Sept. 11, he
will oppose former Jets teammates Wayne Chrebet and Dedric Ward, as
well as former Patriots mate Vincent Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess everybody is familiar with everybody else,'' said
Smith. ``I think that's what makes these games so fun is that
there's history between all of us. Even the other guys in the
division are guys I've been playing against for a long time now.''
</P>
<P>
   When he looks around his new/old surroundings, he has flashbacks
of his first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same number (45) and I'm sitting in the same locker
I used to have,'' said Smith. ``I still see some of the same faces,
but there are a lot of new ones I have to get to know. Both this
team and the Jets are pretty talented. There's good talent level on
both teams, so it'll come down to who gets the breaks, who has the
better coaching, and how well the players execute. It always comes
down to those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has changed some things. He used to have Sam Gash, Keith
Byars, Corwin Brown, and Jerome Henderson around him when he sat at
his locker back in '96. Now he has Tony George, Chris Floyd, Harold
Shaw, and Rob Holmberg in his general vicinity. The '96 team was
deep, with veterans making up the last spots on the roster; now
they are filled by rookies. The business of the game has changed a
lot since he was here last, but his goal has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to take care of my responsibilities on the field,''
said Smith. ``I'm here to help Bill (Belichick) win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
