<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN PRESIDENT TAKES HARDER LINE ON UNIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Since he came to power in May, Taiwan's new
president, Chen Shui-bian, has labored to persuade China that he is
not a wild-eyed separatist driven by dreams of Taiwanese
independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's charm offensive has come to an abrupt end. In an
interview Friday, he took a harder line toward the Chinese
government on the crucial issue of when _ and even whether _ Taiwan
and China will be unified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think unification is the only principle,'' Chen
declared. ``There could be two or three, or countless different
conclusions. We see Taiwan as a democratic country, with the people
in a position to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen said his remarks were not a shift in his position. But they
are a radical break from the guiding policy of the Nationalist
Party, which ruled Taiwan for 55 years until Chen's election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen's predecessor, Lee Teng-hui, antagonized China in
the last year of his term by asserting that Taiwan and China ought
to negotiate as equals, his party adhered to so-called National
Unification guidelines, which have as their ultimate goal the
unification of Taiwan and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KMT government made unification the only possible
conclusion for Taiwan's future, the only resolution of cross-strait
relations,'' said Chen, using the initials for the Nationalist
Party's Chinese name, Kuomintang. ``This way of handling it is
contrary to public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that a majority of Taiwan's 23 million people opposed
unification with China, at least under the terms Beijing has
proposed. And he said his government needed to develop a new
consensus on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's remarks are likely to anger the Chinese government, which
views him with deep suspicion because of his record as an advocate
of Taiwanese independence. Beijing regards Taiwan as a renegade
province and has fought to deny it recognition as a sovereign state
in the international community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does make it seem like he's backtracked on all his
goodwill gestures,'' said Antonio Chiang, the publisher of The
Taipei Times, an English-language newspaper that has supported
Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the president said his tougher tone could upset the
tenuous stability in cross-strait relations that he has achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as both sides were willing to work toward
reunification, but without a timetable, there was fragile ground
for mutual trust,'' said Ma Ying-jeou, the mayor of Taipei and a
leader of the Nationalists. ``When the president says reunification
is only one option, he opens a Pandora's box.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Chen, talking softly has had limits. By pledging in his
inauguration speech not to declare independence, the president
probably defused a confrontation across the Taiwan Strait. But
China has dismissed Chen's subsequent overtures as empty gestures
unworthy of reply.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has also tried to isolate Chen by
inviting delegations of Taiwan business executives and academics to
Beijing, while studiously ignoring the president. The
state-controlled media do not even mention Chen by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tactics of divide and conquer are pervasive,'' Chen
said. ``Not only are they trying to divide the parties; they are
also trying to divide the government and the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I don't think they can deny the fact that the
Taiwanese people elected me as president last March.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen made his status harder to ignore last month when he went on
a 13-day tour of Central American and African countries that have
diplomatic ties with Taiwan. His trip included a stopover in Los
Angeles, where congressmen sympathetic to Taiwan tried to arrange
meetings with him. Under pressure from the Clinton administration,
Chen demurred.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said Friday he still planned to push for closer economic
links between Taiwan and China, which had been one of his campaign
themes. But he cautioned that negotiations on direct links in trade
and transportation could not be divorced from the larger political
issues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Chen's election was a stunning victory over the entrenched
Nationalists, he won with only 39 percent of the vote. And with
Taiwan's legislature dominated by the losing party, Chen's
government has little muscle. Critics accuse it of incompetence and
legislative paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has even been criticized by officials of his own party, the
Democratic Progressive Party. Political analysts said the
president's sharper tone toward China is also calculated to shore
up his domestic support.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drumbeat of criticism, Chen seems unruffled. Looking
relaxed and speaking forcefully at the end of a long week, the
49-year-old president said Taiwan was going through a natural
period of upheaval as it adjusted to the first government in its
history drawn from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five months, some people are not psychologically
adjusted to this change,'' Chen said. ``Those who support us have
high expectations. Those who don't like us hope there will be
chaos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
