<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV05-H     09-01 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOMBS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sept. 5, 2000)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the oddest political developments in this
odd campaign year is the sudden emergence of military readiness as
a hot issue.
</P>
<P>
   A review of our national defense, of course, is inevitably an
essential, underlying element of any presidential competition.
Among other roles, the White House occupant is commander-in-chief
with the burden of sending uniformed men and women into harm's way
if need be.
</P>
<P>
   But in a post-Cold War era of unprecedented peace and
prosperity, military spending is not what most voters are thinking
about.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, arguments about the shape of our armed forces tend
to be too complex for non-expert civilians to understand and easily
subject to distortion and exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush initiated this particular go-around by
declaring during his convention acceptance speech that two of the
Army's 10 divisions were not ready for duty in a major war. It
turned out to be an inaccurate statement based on outdated
information that was quickly disputed by Pentagon brass.
</P>
<P>
   His running mate, Dick Cheney, a former secretary of defense,
conceded the specific error but enlarged the debate with an
accusation that the Clinton-Gore administration had cut defense
spending in general so drastically that ``our military today is
overused and under-resourced.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore promptly countered that our armed forces
remain the world's finest despite minor problems of adjustment to a
changing world in which fresh, scattered peacekeeping tasks outrank
preparation for a traditional full-scale war.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in military spending actually began under Bush's
father, President George Bush, and Secretary Cheney after the
collapse of the Soviet Union, our most dangerous foe. But Cheney
says the cutbacks have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   He overlooks the fact that Congress and the administration
recently increased military pay and spending on weapons
procurement, the two most criticized areas of budgetary decline
over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of dispute is whether to go ahead with installation
of a missile defense system that would violate a key arms control
treaty and anger both the Russians and our NATO allies. President
Clinton on Friday decided to continue research on the proposed
system but leave the construction of a crucial radar station and
further deployment development up to his White House successor. So
far, the technology has passed only one test and flunked two
others. The thing doesn't work yet and may never do so. So what's
the hurry?
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports Clinton's cautious, temporary delay. Bush,
however, comes down hard on the issue by emphasizing that as
president he would ignore the treaty and barrel full-speed ahead to
build a giant antimissile shield regardless of the diplomatic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's doubtful that the Republicans can generate enough fear
of a missile attack against America to make this a political
winner. Any remotely possible nuclear threat would come not from
Russia or China but some minor, irresponsible terrorist nation we
could certainly overcome. Who's afraid of big bad North Korea,
which can't even feed its people?
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Republicans have mined the issue of military
preparedness, earning a popular hawkish reputation and painting
Democrats as soft on defense. Ronald Reagan, with his fanciful Star
Wars missile defense, was an expert at that.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few Democrats managed to turn the tables on the GOP, most
notably John F. Kennedy in his 1960 presidential campaign. He
charged that the Dwight Eisenhower administration had created a
``missile gap'' by letting the Soviet intercontinental ballistic
missile stockpile grow much larger than our own.
</P>
<P>
   One month into the Kennedy administration, however, Secretary of
Defense Robert McNamara conceded to reporters there really was no
missile gap. Oops, guys! Sorry about that.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans still hold a political advantage on military
spending as a general issue. A recent USA TODAY-CNN-Gallup Poll
showed that 54 percent of those surveyed felt the GOP could best
handle national defense, as opposed to only 38 percent who thought
the Democrats would be best. In a poll taken shortly before the
Democratic convention, Bush held a significant lead over Gore on
only one issue _ that of national defense, where voters preferred
him by nearly 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   But other polls show that voters are not as concerned about
national security these days as they are about domestic social
issues. A majority lists health care, education, protecting Social
Security and Medicare and maintaining a strong economy as the most
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   And those are the issues voters want to hear about. Unless we
are suddenly drawn into some terrible armed conflict somewhere,
every minute the candidates spend arguing about military
preparedness is a wasted minute politically. Both presidential
hopefuls are qualified to deal with issues of war and peace. The
subject is important to the country in the long term but not to the
short-range outcome of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
