<HEADLINE>
PLATTERS FOUNDER WINS COURT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal judge told singing group founder Herb Reed
Friday that ``only you'' have the rights to the Platters name.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge George O'Toole granted an injunction
keeping the fake Platters from joining The Drifters and Danny and
the Juniors on stage Friday night at the Festival of the Three
Saints in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, an Arlington resident, has fought for nearly six years for
the exclusive right to represent the group he helped found in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago the First Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed his
sole ownership of the name as the only working performer left from
the group that crooned such hits as ``Smoke Gets in Your Eyes'' and
``Twilight Time.'' The only other member of the original Platters
lineups from the 1950s who is still alive, Zola Taylor, is retired.
</P>
<P>
   Despite court judgments in his favor, Reed is still frustrated
by groups that use the Platters name in shows across the country,
said his attorney, Christopher Donnelly. He filed suit against this
particular group, its New York booking agent and the festival's
organizer, the Saints Alfio, Filadelfo and Cirino Society, because
it hit ``too close to home,'' Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Reed) feels that his legacy is being misused by these
other groups,'' Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the society and King B Productions, the New York
firm that booked the bogus Platters, could not be reached for
comment Friday. Donnelly, however, said he expected that the other
two groups would take the stage and perform as scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
