<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-01 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THEY'RE NO EINSTEINS, BUT IT'S A THEORY
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, it is the economy. And some academics say you'd be stupid
not to see it as the main force that they believe will elect Al
Gore on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   That's the upshot of a quadrennial high-wire act at the American
Political Science Association convention. Professors from around
the country plug pieces of data _ largely measures of the economy
and consumer sentiment _ into various forecast models and predict
the winner and his share of the national, two-party vote.
</P>
<P>
   With today's strong fiscal picture and Americans' overall belief
that the future looks rosy too, this year those variables strongly
favor the incumbent party in the White House. All seven models
presented point to a Gore victory _ with estimates that the
Democrat will win from 52.8 to 60.3 percent of the popular,
two-party vote.
</P>
<P>
   So why even wait for the national polls that will begin pouring
out this weekend? Historically, the candidate leading in the polls
at Labor Day has a strong shot at winning two months hence, so
they're a good measure. But many of the presidential models have a
better and more exact record than most of the public opinion
samplings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, most academic forecasts were as accurate as public
opinion polls taken the day before the election, and the professors
made their predictions at least three months out.
</P>
<P>
   And don't campaigns matter? Well, yes, but the political
scientists see the campaign as reinforcing the fiscal findings key
to almost all the models.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is the answer to every question,'' said James E.
Campbell of the State University at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   According to Campbell's data, the ``in'' party has won eight of
the 10 post-World War II presidential elections in which
second-quarter gross domestic product growth, annualized, has been
at least 2.5 percent. This year that was a booming 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions, both narrow losses, held special circumstances _
1968 when Democrat Hubert H. Humphrey lost because of the upheaval
of Vietnam and 1976 when Republican Gerald R. Ford, the unelected
president, faced the wrath of Watergate and his pardon of former
President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a special circumstance now, given President
Clinton's status as an impeached president and Gore's position as
No. 2 in a scandal-ridden, two-term administration?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, seemed to be the consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the separate ``time for change'' models constructed by
Alan Abramowitz of Emory University and Thomas Holbrook of the
Univeristy of Wisconsin at Milwaukee, economic factors and the
president's consistently positive job-approval ratings outweighed
any ``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a Republican who pointed to his ``Alpha Males for
Bush'' button, couldn't find much hope in the Democratic scandals.
Just in case, though, he urged the Bush campaign to have women
dressed as Buddhist nuns waving bags of money _ or maybe a Janet
Reno look-alike _ at every Gore rally.
</P>
<P>
   As Campbell demonstrates, the academics aren't all pinkos or
``pointy-eared geeks,'' as Republican talking-head Mary Matalin
described the modelers when their predictions first began appearing
in late spring.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell holds out little hope that the unexpected will upset
the forecasts. For some comfort that a last-minute development can
move voters, he reached back to the 1884 campaign, when a
Republican cry of ``rum, Romanism and rebellion'' stirred up enough
Roman Catholics in New York to tip the state _ and the election _
to Democrat Grover Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen, but I wouldn't bet on it,'' said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of betting, Christopher Wlezien of the University of
Houston, said he'd been called by an Oklahoman who apparently is
betting _ perhaps heavily _ based on forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Wlezien, whose model with Columbia University's Robert Erickson
puts Gore at 55.2 percent, conceded that ``uncertainty surrounds
our forecasts.'' But even at that, he said, ``Gore has an
advantage, and it's a pretty good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Norpoth, of the State University of New York at Stony
Brook, whose model is based on primary election performance of
candidates but comes up with the same ``Gore Wins'' result (at 55
percent) as the heavily economic forecasts, concedes some
nervousness. The group, he said, could become the Misery Loves
Company Panel.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of the academic parlor game or recreational
political science about the forecasts, but that won't make those
naps in Austin _ or Crawford or Kennebunkport _ any more restful
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
