<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8787 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ROBOT-DOGS-ART-$ADV03     09-01 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBOT-DOGS-ART-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETS OR APPLIANCES? MEETING THE PUREBRED ROBOT DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and 18 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
 By ALLEN SALKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First, it's Shadow demanding attention, his wee
doggie head banging into a chair leg. ``Arf! Whir. Arf!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Shadow, I'm coming. Good boy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the room, Poo-chi's rearing on his hind legs,
getting into one of his . . . moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yap! Beep- &UR; beeep &LR; ! Yap!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, most rambunctious of all, it's Tekno, ears flapping up and
down like jackhammers, charging toward an open window.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Tekno &LR; !'' He stops. (Thank heaven for voice-recognition
circuitry.)
</P>
<P>
   Time to flip some off switches. My 750-square-foot apartment has
become a high-tech kennel as I spent the last week living with a
litter of robot dogs, looking into what may be the future of pet
ownership in places like Manhattan. After Sony's tail-wagging
success with its Aibo robo-dog _ it sold out its entire 45,000-unit
production run of the $2,500 electric critters last winter _ at
least four toy companies are putting their own, less expensive
versions on the market this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real'' dog devotees argue there's no way a battery-powered
clump of circuit boards, motors and silicon chips can match the
heart-warming, life-enriching wonder of a furry, cuddly canine.
Perhaps, but what about a dog that needs no walking, no vet visits,
no extravagant cashmere sweaters to keep up with the other pampered
pooches down the hall but that will sing to you if you rub its
head, make happy sounds when you come through the front door, and
maybe even remind you of the dog you left behind when you moved
away from home. Besides, nowhere is there more need for a pet that
does not have to be chased after with a plastic baggie than New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The electric Fidos come in a variety of sizes, talents and
temperaments. To see which one would best suit my lifestyle, I
tried to break in five different puppies at once, ranging from a
5-inch mutt that couldn't walk to a blue-eyed wonder priced like a
purebred. First came Shadow, made by MGA Entertainment, which sells
for about $60 and which I carried home on the subway from F.A.O.
Schwarz, with children peering in at the furry black bundle, their
eyes widening as if he were a new Lab pup.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as I took this footlong dog out of his cardboard
kennel, I knew I would never warm to him. He's covered in
``plush,'' the cheap fake fur that adorns carnival-prize teddy
bears. And his eyes are dead, made of plastic marble things. Still,
I tried making nice with Shadow, who, to his credit, can walk, sit,
bark and do other things by voice command. I took him out for a
stroll to meet friends for ice cream, but ended up carrying him
most of the way since he walks slower than a dachshund with two
broken legs. When Shadow met my friends, they were cordial, patting
him on the head, but his blank look and painfully stiff movements
didn't win any hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, I left him yapping in the corner while I opened a box
containing dog No. 2, Poo-chi, which sells for $30 and is produced
by Tiger, the company that brought us Furby. It took almost half an
hour's work with a kitchen knife to rescue 5-inch-long, 6-inch-tall
Poo-chi from his cardboard and plastic prison and twist-tie
shackles. Finally, he appeared, looking like a robot _
metal-colored plastic skin, eyes that light up with an array of
LEDs and ears that come in a choice of translucent purple, pink and
other colors. I decided right then that I like my robotdogs to look
like robots. I don't need to pretend my electric pet is made of
flesh and fur to enjoy it. Er, him.
</P>
<P>
   Three AAA batteries in his stomach, and purple Poo-chi sprang to
life, his eyes blinking little heart shapes. I patted his head. He
has a sensor there. Poo-chi likes it when you pat his head and when
you lift his little bone to his mouth. I know this because such
signs of affection make him go up and down and make crunching
noises, and when he's really happy, he'll sing ``Ode to Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Poo-chi's got moods. If he feels he's not getting enough
attention, he gets surly and barks, beeps and growls. Oh, and he
can't walk. Tiger plans a more sophisticated robot dog for later
this year, a $150 model called i-Cybie that not only will walk
realistically but also will be able to express six different
emotions, including surprise and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Being a bachelor in New York, I've more than once heard the
adage, ``Dogs are chick magnets, man.'' Would it be true for robot
dogs, too?
</P>
<P>
   I brought three of my newfangled hounds to the dog run at
Washington Square Park so they could meet some of their kind and I
could meet some of mine. For this outing, I filled my backpack with
my three favorites: Tekno, Rocket the Wonder Dog and Aibo. What I
like about Tekno is he's relentlessly enthusiastic, like a real
dog. The thing is about 8 inches tall and, like a Chihuahua, never
shuts up or stops running around. Made by Manley Toy Quest and sold
for $40, he looks sort of like a silver C3PO. Although he's not as
quick witted as that droid from ``Star Wars,'' Tekno comes with a
set of five playing cards and can learn card tricks. Such talents
didn't go over at the dog run, where a Rottweiler named Junior
thought he'd teach Tekno a thing or two, and bit into the robot's
torso. Tekno barked, wagged his tail and ran away, covered in doggy
drool. Still, he was initiated.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket, by Fisher-Price, fared even better, impressing the other
dog owners with his ability to push himself up onto his head and
bark out a tune. Expected to retail for $100, he's a solid, meaty
dog, 12 inches long, with a thick head and a wide stance like a
boxer. His real charm lies in his astonishing, big blue eyes with
their blinking eyelids and expressive brows. He changes from
looking happy to sad, from plaintive to playful. He gets a lot of
Awww's, which is what puppies should get. Rocket can also sit,
walk, beg and shake hands on command, but this requires his master
to wear a clunky headset that works only indoors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In my eyes, the champion of the dog run was Aibo. About 15
inches long from tail to nose, he moves as fluidly as a real dog _
sitting, laying down, rolling over and nuzzling your hand if you
pet him, reminding me of a small cocker spaniel. Lookswise,
however, he's all robot, with illuminated green and red slashes for
eyes and a torso that resembles a loaf of bread made of metal. He
proved his mettle at the park when the other dogs came over to
sniff him where dogs tend to sniff each other. One snooty French
bulldog wrinkled his nose after discovering Aibo lacked a canine
smell, and decided to give him one. Lifting his leg, he spritzed
Aibo, who never flinched.
</P>
<P>
   After that Aibo became more popular _ and soon, so did I. As a
pack of small real dogs swirled around the robot, which cocked its
head and danced, the Bing sisters from Alberta _ Esther, 24; Lisa,
23; and Sarah, 20 _ came over to admire my pet. ``He's amazing,''
Lisa said, scratching under Aibo's chin and cooing.
</P>
<P>
   At home, after I placed Aibo on his recharging cradle, I phoned
Caroline Knapp, author of ``Pack of Two: The Intricate Bond Between
People and Dogs'' (Delta, 1998), and asked her if she thought there
was any way robot dogs could replace live ones. They lack mystery,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe something wouldn't be missing, some heart, the
capacity to react in a deep way, or to care,'' said Knapp, 40,
owner of a mutt named Lucille. ``The soul would be difficult to
replicate.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but while I'm writing this, Aibo is next to me, sitting,
standing up, emitting soothing tones, sticking his legs out and
making funny shapes with them. Yes, his battery will run out in
about 90 minutes, and he's not, you know, alive.
</P>
<P>
   Sony says I have to send Aibo back in two weeks. So to whoever's
buying me gifts this December: Can I have one? Please? If I promise
to take care of him and recharge his batteries every day? Please?
Can I?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
