<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8790 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ALA-UCLA-PREVIEW0     09-01 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALA-UCLA-PREVIEW0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '46 Bama team is going back to Rose Bowl
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ On Thursday, the Alabama football team that
will play UCLA today in Rose Bowl Stadium boarded a plane in
Birmingham. They arrived here just four hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' said Hugh Morrow of Lookout Mountain, Tenn. ``I guess a
lot has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot, indeed. Morrow was on the last Alabama team to play in
the Rose Bowl, some 54 years ago when the Crimson Tide faced
Southern California in the Jan. 1, 1946, Rose Bowl. The 37 members
of that squad boarded a train in New Orleans on Dec. 23, 1945, and
did not arrive in Pasadena until four days later.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow will be one of several players from that team who will be
in the Rose Bowl today, where UCLA plays its regular-season games.
For most of these men, it will be the first time they have been in
the stadium since that unforgettable afternoon when the Crimson
Tide upset Southern California 34-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great to see the guys again,'' said Harry
Gilmer, the Hall of Fame quarterback who led Alabama to a 10-0
record as a sophomore. ``It's going to bring back a lot of great
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Such memories as:
</P>
<P>
   Alabama coach Frank Thomas, also in the Hall of Fame, having to
talk his team into making the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been to the Sugar Bowl the year before, and it had
messed up our Christmas,'' said Gilmer, who influenced a generation
of quarterbacks with his famous jump pass. ``We took a team vote
not to go, but he didn't even listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The train trip to California. The Alabama team was given three
club cars attached to a long line of empty cars, which would be
bringing soliders from World War II back from the West Coast. They
ran into several such trains on the way to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war was winding down, and so trains coming back from the
West had the right of way,'' Morrow said. ``So every time we met a
train, we had to pull off and let them pass. Because of that it
took us four days to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood and its stars, who came out in full force to meet and
greet the team. Among the stars were George Raft, Ida Lupino and
Johnny Mack Brown, former Alabama player turned cowboy star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us had never been anywhere like that, so we were
pretty starstruck,'' said Vaughn Mancha, Hall of Fame center who
lives in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Alabama was unbeaten and ranked No. 2
behind Army, the West Coast media gave the team no chance against
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand why,'' Morrow said. ``We were a bunch of
18-19-year-old kids and had not played a national schedule. But we
had beaten Tennessee and Georgia, and those teams were mighty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who played for Knute Rockne and roomed with George Gipp
at Notre Dame, was an offensive genius and had his team
well-prepared _ Alabama led 27-0 in the third quarter before USC
ever made a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget. (The media) called us the Swamp Rats. The
Alabama Swamp Rats,'' Gilmer said. ``But the old Swamp Rats played
pretty good that day.'' Gilmer would go on to a career in pro
football and was an assistant coach with the Atlanta Falcons under
Norm Van Brocklin.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Crimson Tide's sixth and final trip to the granddaddy
of all bowl games. And no Southern team has played in the Rose Bowl
since. The next year, the Big Ten signed a contract to send its
champion to Pasadena each year.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the number of men who made that memorable trip is
dwindling. The survivors are in their mid-70s. But the bond that
began forming in the summer of 1945 is still very strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to keep up with each other pretty good. When
something happens to one of us, we know about it pretty quick,''
Morrow said. ``Unfortunately, it's getting easier to keep up with
everybody, because there are fewer of us left.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours today, the Alabama team of 1945 will bask in the
glory of that special afternoon long ago. And their memories will
be forever young.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
