<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION: A GATHERING OF LEADERS OF DIVERSE FAITHS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For four days this week, the United Nations and then
the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel played host to an unusual assembly of
religious figures from around the globe, who came together for an
event called the Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and
Spiritual Leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As a body, these men and women _ 800 of them in all, according
to the event's organizers, with around 1,000 other participants _
made a colorful sight, especially when seated in the United
Nations' General Assembly hall in their robes, turbans and clerical
collars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of some underlying tensions among some of
the groups, the conference seemed to focus on its declared
objective, getting the leaders to talk about the cause of world
peace. And by Thursday, the closing day, many participants had
signed a declaration pledging themselves to work for just that _
along with combating poverty and pressing for environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
   But what was really accomplished by the conference _ sponsored
by foundations and so not officially a United Nations' event _
remains to be seen, though several participants identified its
primary value as simply allowing people of diverse religious
backgrounds to meet and talk with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest challenge the organizers initially faced
was dealing with strong criticism about the absence of Dalai Lama,
the spiritual leader of Tibet, whose presence at the United Nations
had been blocked by China. But the Dalai Lama's voice was not
entirely absent from the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a message, delivered to participants, in which he
declared that leaders of different faiths ``can play a pivotal
role'' in creating peace by explaining to their followers the need
to respect the beliefs of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to embrace the spirit of pluralism in the field of
religions as well,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said there would be no peace ``as long as there is
grinding poverty, social injustice, inequality, oppression,
environmental degradation, and as long as the weak and small
continue to be trodden by the mighty and powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   These are issues that religious leaders need to work together to
eliminate, the Dalai Lama said, and ``are the enemies of peace and
true tyrannies of our times.''
</P>
<P>
   His broad plea, for religious leaders to engage in interfaith
understanding and cooperation, was echoed by many others. Rabbi
Jonathan Sacks, the chief rabbi of Britain, said that mass
migrations and new communications technologies had brought people
into close proximity who had previously been strangers to one
another. And therein lay a theological challenge to believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has brought us eyeball to eyeball with the diversity of
His world,'' Sacks said. ``And right now He is asking us: Can we
recognize God's image in someone who is not in my image? Can
strangers, even enemies, become friends?''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi also struck a note that others at the conference
voiced: that religious leaders around the world often have real
influence, much more so than politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the conflict zones in today's world,'' Sacks said,
``and you will see that they coincide almost exactly with zones of
religious tension. The question is, is religion part of the
solution, or is it part of the problem? Let none of us doubt the
difference we can make.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama and Sacks each spoke as leading figures within
geographically far-flung faith groups, Buddhists and Jews, who were
well-represented at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller faiths had, not surprisingly, far fewer
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The conference drew only a handful of Zoroastrians, for example,
members of an ancient religious tradition that emerged in Persia,
now Iran, nearly 3,000 years ago. One who came was Dastur Firzone
M. Kotwal, a dastur, or high priest, who lives in Bombay, long the
major center for the world's Zoroastrians.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what message his faith could offer the conference, Dr.
Kotwal offered a reply drawn from its ethics: ``Zoroastrianism lays
stress on a very good standard of morality. Do justice, fairness,
honesty and righteousness. When you are standing, lift up the poor.
God has given you wealth in excess, use it to help the
downtrodden.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated the number of Zoroastrians worldwide at about
135,000, nearly half of them in Bombay. ``We never convert,'' he
said. ``In this time, this is the best policy. We believe you must
follow the religion of your birth and seek salvation from your own
religion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
