<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    JUSTICE'S RULING: GRIN AND BEAR IT, BUSH
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ George W. Bush isn't the first Texas governor to be
struck between the eyes with a ruling from U.S. District Judge
William Wayne Justice.
</P>
<P>
   He is just the first Texas governor who was running for
president of the United States when the blow came. And the news was
made worse in his case by the sensitivity of the issue, health care
for children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush isn't even the first state official to try to downplay the
significance of Justice's findings by labeling the veteran jurist
as an ``activist, liberal judge.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of state officials _ Republicans and Democrats alike _
have applied that tag to Justice over the years since his
appointment to the federal bench by President Lyndon B. Johnson in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   Justice has been a strong champion of civil rights and on more
than one occasion has found state government in Texas
constitutionally deficient in performing public services.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known decision, handed down about 20 years ago, forced
state government to make extensive improvements in an overcrowded
prison system. State officials widely criticized Justice for that
ruling, but the blame ultimately belonged to the critics _ mostly
Democrats then _ who had not fulfilled their responsibilities to
run a constitutional prison system.
</P>
<P>
   Politically motivated legislators _ and at least one Democratic
governor and a Democratic attorney general _ liked to ridicule
Justice for ordering ``country club prisons,'' but their rhetoric
was pure blather.
</P>
<P>
   Justice may wear the ``activist, liberal'' tag as a badge of
honor. Or he may consider himself a ``strict constructionist'' of
the Constitution, but with a somewhat different view of that
document than Bush and many other elected state officials.
</P>
<P>
   No one, at least, can accuse Justice of ``coddling criminals''
with his latest ruling, which held that Texas was providing
inadequate health care to low-income children in the Medicaid
program.
</P>
<P>
   Justice determined that Texas has failed to comply with some of
the terms of a 1996 consent decree entered in a class-action suit
against the state. Most of the ruling concerned an early screening
and treatment program of preventive care.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is appealing the ruling, but the timing was awful for
Bush. The order gave fresh ammunition to Democrats, who already
were attacking the governor over the health care issue. And it
became public just as the Republican nominee was struggling to
regain the offensive in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Bush didn't learn of the order until it
was two weeks old _ and after it first had been reported in the
media. He and his campaign staff were blindsided while flying
around the Northeast with a planeload of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Since nobody ever said politics was fair, Democrats will use the
ruling to continue to attack Texas' health care record, even though
that record isn't the governor's fault alone.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has historically lagged behind most other states in health
care, education and other social issues, a dubious tradition dating
back to when Democrats controlled state government.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 consent decree in the children's health care suit,
which Justice addressed, was entered into during the Bush
administration. But the suit was filed in 1993, when Democrat Ann
Richards was governor.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, however, the issue of health care _ for
children, senior citizens and the rest of us _ should be addressed
in the presidential race. And Bush may have to continue defending
not only his own record, but that of his state as well.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility comes with the territory. He is the governor
and a presidential candidate claiming credit for a strong economy
and other positive news from Texas. He has to take _ or at least
share _ the blame for the not-so-positive news as well.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential politics aside, Bush and legislators from both
parties cooperated last year in creating a new health-insurance
program for thousands of low-income children who aren't poor enough
for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice's order is a reminder that the need still outpaces
the bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
