u w BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI &LR;      09-01 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK MURKY FOR PIPELINE SAFETY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returns to work Tuesday bracing for a
furious month-long sprint that leaves Washington state lawmakers
little time or maneuvering room to achieve their highest priority _
a tough and comprehensive pipeline safety bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state's lawmakers aren't conceding defeat yet, they
acknowledge that something will have to happen in the next two
weeks if a pipeline bill is to have any chance of becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a major push for pipeline safety in the wake of last
year's gasoline pipeline explosion and fireball that killed three
people in Bellingham, Wash., and a renewed sense of urgency after a
natural gas pipeline explosion in New Mexico killed 11 people,
legislation is languishing in both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash., are
pushing hard for action. Murray has said she will get ``creative''
in finding a way to push the issue forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise I will be creative in my approach to achieving
meaningful pipeline safety legislation this year,'' Murray told her
colleagues in July.
</P>
<P>
   That vow was reiterated last week by her chief of staff, Rick
Desimone. Murray's words are code language for attaching a pipeline
provision to a must-pass bill. If she resorts to that approach it
improves chances that pipeline safety provision will become law _
but at a price. It would be considerably weaker than if the bill
were passed independently.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too early to know how it might play out, Congress
historically is hesitant to attach a ``rider'' as sought by Murray
and other advocates that alters federal policy in substantial ways.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Congress often compromises by agreeing to language
calling for an independent study of the issue _ in this case the
need for new pipeline standards _ with the understanding that
Congress will come back to the question once the study is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   That option clearly would not satisfy Washington state lawmakers
who have been working for more than a year to pass a more
comprehensive law.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be the best they can do. The reason for the
uncertainty and maneuvering is that Congress will be focused on two
goals _ dealing with essential legislation, and getting out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Congress must finish work on the remaining appropriations bills
that keep the government running. There's a lot of work left. Only
two of the 13 bills have been signed into law and all must be
passed by Sept. 30, the end of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The second _ and for most members, equally important _ order of
business is to keep things moving fast enough so the session will
end on time Oct., 6 which allows them a full month of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   With only 23 work days scheduled before adjournment and with the
preoccupation with November elections, lawmakers are in little mood
to deal with complex and politically challenging questions such as
overhauling the way pipelines are regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Every member of the state's delegation supports some form of
pipeline safety legislation and many have been outspoken about the
need to enact tougher standards governing the operation and
maintenance of pipelines. The most aggressive changes would would
set specific federal standards and techniques for inspecting
pipelines, allow states to institute more stringent standards than
federal law, and require that employees on duty during an accident
be relieved until an investigation determines a cause.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline industry strongly opposes allowing states to set
tougher standards. They say most pipelines cross state lines and it
would be difficult to abide by such a ``patchwork'' of regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The industry and its allies in Congress also oppose any mandate
that employees be relieved during an accident investigation,
arguing that it would unfairly punish some workers and actually
weaken pipeline safety by removing key personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has been making more progress on pipeline safety than
the House. It has a bipartisan bill ready to come to the floor for
a vote, although Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who controls
which bills come to the full Senate, has not committed to bring it
forward.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington's cause got a boost when New Mexico's two
senators, Pete Domenici and Jeff Bingaman, called for a pipeline
bill in the wake of the accident in their state.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and Gorton have been working to clear objections and
convince Lott that the bill should come to the floor quickly.
Gorton, who spoke to Lott about the matter recently, remains
hopeful the pipeline bill will come to the floor. ``He was
receptive,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton also said there has been progress in forging a compromise
that would remove much of the remaining opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's concern, however, is that the bill could get bogged down
in debate, siphoning critical time from must-pass bills. ``He has
never been against the substance of the bill,'' Gorton said of
Lott. Opposition comes from the pipeline industry, which fears more
regulation will lead to higher costs, and from oil state lawmakers
who worry jobs could be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton conceded that passing a pipeline bill will take luck,
given congress' other priorities and dwindling amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   But Bellingham Mayor Mark Asmundson, for one, remains
optimistic, and believes there is a better than even chance that
both the Senate and House will take up a pipeline bill. Asmundson
says lawmakers are appearing cautious _ even doubtful _ in public
``because nobody wants to offer expectations they can't fullfill.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlook in the House is considered bleaker than the Senate.
The chairman of a key committee has indicated a willingness to hold
a hearing on pipeline safety but has not set a date. That
uncertainty has frustrated Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., who has
sponsored one of the pipeline bills. ``We have been very
disappointed that the majority party has not scheduled a markup and
floor action on this,'' Inslee said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pounding on the door for just under a year ... and
we can't even get a vote. That's what's discouraging,'' he said.
``We get paid to pass legislation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
