<SLUG> BC-MARC-RIBOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN-ISM 
</HEADLINE>
 Daring guitarist starting a 
different kind of revolution 
(For use on or after Sept. 5, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When percussionist-band leader Machito moved to New York to
kick-start the mambo craze in the '40s, it's doubtful even he could
have envisioned Los Cubanos Postizos (the Prosthetic Cubans)
guitarist Marc Ribot's rhythmically infectious salute to the
foundations of salsa.
</P>
<P>
   A leading light of Manhattan's downtown avant-garde jazz and
rock scenes, Ribot dedicated his ensemble to the songs of Arsenio
Rodriguez, a late superstar of Latin music known for his skillful
playing of the !ital!tres, a three-stringed guitar central to Cuban
music 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, Buena Vista Social Club fans. This ain't some kind of
purist approach. Not that he's going expressly for laughs, but
Ribot, widely regarded as one of today's most inventive and
adventurous guitarists, reveals the humor between the !ital!clave
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arsenio was pushing the envelope of what was possible in some
of his soloing,'' Ribot (pronounced !ital!Ree-bow) said. ``But it's
not all about solos. It's about a group sound, group arrangements.
Even though he was the band leader, on a lot of the classic
records, you're lucky if you get three minutes of soloing on the
whole thing. But what there is, is brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribot and his ``fake Cubans'' appear in two shows Wednesday at
the Conga Room in Los Angeles in support of the group's second
album, ``Muy Divertido! (Very Entertaining!)'' (Atlantic).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Cubans who've heard us laugh their heads off,'' said
Ribot, 46, an in-demand session player who has cut multiple albums
with Elvis Costello and Tom Waits. ``This is music that would be
known by any Cuban musician of a certain age. I liken our version
to what would happen if some Australian aborigines found a Duke
Ellington record and came back 20 years later with their own
version of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With a guitar style defined by an edgy and eclectic harmonic
approach and a loose, playful attitude, Ribot formed Los Cubanos
Postizos three- and-a-half years ago, drawing praise from Jazziz
magazine for ``some of the scruffiest, most deliciously different
Cuban music you're likely to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, classic Cuban music has exploded thanks to the
worldwide success of Havana's Buena Vista Social Club and its many
offshoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to present this as a work of scholarship or make
any claims to authenticity,'' Ribot said. ``This is my usage of
Cuban music. But let me express my dismay at the fact that this
turned out to be trendy even though I think there's a common cause.
A lot of great archival Cuban music compilations became available
in the U.S. starting in the early '90s and it's natural that
musicians would pick up on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's quite beautiful about now is that 20 or 30 years ago,
only musicologists had access to all this sort of world music
material. Now anybody can get it at Tower.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
Who: Marc Ribot y Los Cubanos Postizos. &QL; 
Where: Conga Room, 5364 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 9 and 11 p.m. Wednesday. &QL; 
Tickets: $17 general or $40 reserved. &QL; 
Information: (323) 938-1696. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
