<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8806 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-FALL-FASHION-BOOKS-$A     09-01 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-BOOKS-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL READING, FROM HEAD TO TOE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manolo Blahnik says that the secret to toe cleavage, which he
describes as a ``very important part of the sexuality of the shoe''
in ``Manolo Blahnik'' (Harper Collins, this month) by Colin
McDowell, is in showing only ``the first two cracks.'' While I
don't own a pair of Blahnik's famous pointy shoes, I know exactly
what he means. There's something a little vulgar, a little
splayed-looking, about a shod foot with more than three toes
exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The sex-toe connection and other revelations (like Blahnik's
predilection for jam and sugar scarfing, or the character sketches
he concocts for each shoe he makes: ``She's from Jaipur, where she
has a marvelous house, all cool colonnades and superbly polished
tiles'') make this coffee-table biography both delicious and
instructive. Blahnik, who has been making exciting shoes for more
than two decades, is emerging as a kind of polymorphic celebrity: a
bon vivant/shoemaker, whose unabashed eccentricities fascinate.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn a lot from books like McDowell's. Indeed, for the
style-minded reader, fall books have never felt so prescriptive, so
inspirational and so useful. Now I know the new rules of glamour,
the importance of a red bedroom, and what to do with a princess
skirt.
</P>
<P>
   To sort through it all, it's important, stylish reader, to know
who or what you aspire to. ``Bright Young Things'' by Brooke de
Ocampo, a contributing editor at Vogue and ``card-carrying BYT
herself,'' according to the book's introduction, displays a huge
menu of possibilities, and possible settings. This is a book of
terrific apartments in New York City, where de Ocampo's BYTs tend
to live _ a portfolio of photographs and the decorating narratives
of Hearsts and Rockefellers, von Stauffenbergs and Von
Furstenbergs, Laurens and Lauders and Guerrand-Hermeses, with a
couple of wild cards thrown in, like the painter Damian Loeb and
Moby, the musician.
</P>
<P>
   Every BYT included herein has a fabulous job, a witty apartment,
a great piece of art. If I were an editor at House &AMP; Garden, I'd be
tearing my hair out. There are 27 apartments in here, more than two
years' worth of magazine features on leopard-print club chairs
(Aerin Lauder Zinterhofer); plum-colored walls (Plum Sykes) and
Warhol-designed wallpaper (in a panel made by the artist for the
21st birthday of Peter Bacanovic, the lucky banker who lives in the
brownstone apartment where ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' was filmed).
</P>
<P>
   For a richer experience, cross-reference ``BYT'' with ``RSVP:
Menus for Entertaining From People Who Really Know How'' (Clarkson
Potter, November) by Nan Kempner. You'll find offspring in the
former, like Eliza Reed Bolen and Lulu de Kwiatkowski, and their
parents in the latter, including Annette and Oscar de la Renta (mom
and step-father to Eliza), who serve a mean lobster salad, and the
de Kwiatkowskis, of Calumet Farm (mom and dad to Lulu). In distinct
contrast to ``BYT,'' whose ``author,'' Brooke de Ocampo, hasn't
written its narratives, there's a fuzzy, friendly feel to ``RSVP,''
if only because it's offered in Kempner's distinctive voice, well
seasoned with personal pronouns and memories. You will also find
the best recipe for roast chicken in its pages, from Robin Hambro's
Italian cook, Luciana Guarduci.
</P>
<P>
   See if you can guess the identities of the models pictured in
``Vintage Style: Buying and Wearing Classic Vintage Clothes''
(Harper Collins, October) by Tiffany Dubin and Ann E. Berman
without looking in ``BYT.'' Dubin, who is the marketing director
for the Auction Channel and who created the fashion department at
Sotheby's, and her collaborator, Ann E. Berman, a writer for Town &AMP;
Country, make the rather trenchant point that since so-called high
fashion right now is directly ``inspired'' by fashion's past, it
would behoove you, stylish reader, to shop from the same vintage
sources as the designers. In other words, why buy Gucci or Prada
for thousands of dollars when you can buy original Giorgio di
Sant'Angelo or Ossie Clark, in pristine condition, for mere
hundreds, or much less?
</P>
<P>
   Like de Ocampo and Kempner, Dubin has collected her pals in her
pages, but she skips the details, so each model seems as
``generic'' as the item she wears. For instance, a
porcelain-skinned brunette in a princess skirt is identified only
as ``Marina, writer'' (though you know from ``BYT'' that she's
Marina Rust, a great-great-granddaughter of Marshall Field III, a
contributing editor at Vogue and the owner of a Sargent sketch). On
closer reading, you learn that the skirt was made by Carolyne
Roehm, in the late 1980s _ it's something of a shock to think of
this period as ``vintage.'' You learn by Rust's example that it's
OK to wear a princess skirt with a white T-shirt and a knotted
denim shirt ``for a morning's shopping in a resort town,'' but that
``on assignment'' you might consider a tiny tank top topped with a
gold bolero jacket trimmed with fringe and crystals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sloan, talk show host'' models a waist-length, pink plastic
bomber jacket, by Courreges. (A quick glance back at ``BYT''
reveals that it is Sloan Lindemann Barnett, a former assistant
district attorney and a co-host of ``SheCommerce,'' a cable show
produced by Oxygen Media, and that she has a husband named Roger
Barnett, a Chagall and a predilection for pink decorating
flourishes like mauve walls and fuchsia ostrich feathers.) Try the
jacket, as Sloan does, with white jeans, or a pleated skirt, or a
little black dress.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
