<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-FALL-FASHION-BOOKS-$A     09-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-BOOKS-$ADV03-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: black dress.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If these stylish scrapbooks are making you ache with envy _ the
apartments! the pedigrees! the clothes! _ an evening with ``4
Blondes'' (Atlantic Monthly, this month) by Candace Bushnell will
bring you right down: ``4 Blondes'' is aversion therapy for social
climbers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the characters in Evelyn Waugh's ``Decline and Fall,''
Bushnell's ersatz blondes make it hard to decide which is more
depraved. There's Janey (``Nice 'n Easy''), an over-the-hill model,
who sleeps her way into a summer house in the Hamptons each year;
Winnie (``Highlights''), a not-quite-smart-enough magazine editor,
who loathes her feckless writer husband and for whom a $500 pair of
Manolo Blahniks _ toe cleavage! _ generates a sly plot twist; and
Cecelia (``Snow Angel''), a pill-popping princess-by-marriage, who
may or may not have murdered her best friend. The fourth blonde is
Bushnell's stand-in, a sex columnist on assignment in England;
she's the ``nice'' one, who wins a love interest on the last page.
</P>
<P>
   A more appealing quartet of blondes appears in a rather
startling photograph in ``The Vogue Book of Blondes'' (Viking
Studio, last month) by Kathy Phillips with a foreword by Donatella
Versace, in which RuPaul towers over Kurt Cobain, Courtney Love and
their daughter, young Frances Bean Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't always have the longest legs or the perkiest
breasts,'' Louis Licari, the self-described ``King of Color,'' says
in this cheerful and sort of chaotic encyclopedia of blondness,
which ranges from Jean Harlow to Brad Pitt, ``but being blond is
part of the fantasy you can achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than splitting blond hairs, maybe you should just paint
your bedroom. ``Paint just one wall in your bedroom in a really
great color such as russet, ochre or Venetian red,'' advises
Frederic Fekkai in ``A Year of Style'' (Clarkson Potter; October).
``Red makes you look more beautiful when you wake up.'' Of course,
you learned that already from ``BYT,'' in which Plum Sykes, a Vogue
editor, opines that ``a white room is the most boring thing in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Fekkai, the handsome French hair stylist with salons in New York
and Beverly Hills, Calif., is full of ``Why Don't You's,'' a whole
year's worth. Here are a few. ``By all means wear fabulous
sunglasses, but if you do, be ready to eliminate other
accessories.'' ``Read the latest best-selling biography. Everyone
will be talking about it this fall.'' And my favorite: ``Get a
hands-free, cordless telephone with a headset. Holding the receiver
to your ear is so 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Growing Up: Simple Ways to Be Yourself at Last''
(Clarkson Potter, October) by Veronique Vienne is a nice companion
for ``A Year of Style.'' You'll find it on the ``Self Help:
Happiness'' shelf of your local bookstore, but don't let the label
fool you; this is a style book, too. Vienne, the author of ``The
Art of Doing Nothing'' and ``The Art of Imperfection,'' has
compiled 10 ``New Rules of Glamour,'' which she describes as ``just
another word for a little extra discipline.'' The first of these
is: ``knowing how to choose a hat, clean paintbrushes and
effortlessly negotiate a grand marble staircase in a tight evening
gown.''
</P>
<P>
   Attitude-beautifiers will only take you so far. Style is,
ultimately, visual, as any good BYT will tell you. Flip through
``Obsessed by Dress'' (Beacon Press, October), a book of quotations
compiled by Tobi Tobias, the dance critic for New York magazine and
a vintage-clothing wearer, for razor sharp remarks from social
observers like Jean Rhys, Henry James and Wayne Koestenbaum, who
wrote this one: ``At a now-defunct boutique called Ben's Village, I
bought a pair of cotton tropical-print unisex pants that I named
`fish pants' because blowsy fish swam on them in wallpaper
patterns. A friend had advised when I told him there was no room in
my life for fish pants, `change your life to fit the pants.'''
</P>
<P>
   Toe cleavage optional.
</P>
</TEXT>
