u a BC-ATTICA-ANGER-NNS &LR;      09-01 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTICA-ANGER-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GUARD'S WIDOW, ATTICA STILL BURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, Sept. 1, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of Ann D'Arcangelo Driscoll (NNS1). For
information about purchasing this photo call 202-383-7824.  
 By PAM GREENE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, N.Y. _ Ann D'Arcangelo Driscoll was 22 with an infant
daughter when her husband John, a corrections officer, was killed
during the 1971 riot at the Attica Correctional Facility in upstate
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``John went to work and never came back,'' she said this week
from the kitchen of her Auburn home. ``I was absolutely devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, I went to the prison. It looked like a war zone.
They (the prisoners) were chanting, `Kill the pigs.' You could
smell the fires burning.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the corrections employees killed during the riots
did not die at the hands of inmates. Ten of the 11 who died _
including John D'Arcangelo _ were hit by gunshots fired by police
after then-Gov. Nelson Rockefeller ordered an all-out assault on
the prison by state police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it was friendly fire,'' Driscoll said. ``I hate that
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine years later, Driscoll is still bitter about what she
calls the state's disregard for the families of corrections
employees killed or injured during the four-day riot. The state
gave her $36 a week for 16 years (stopping after her daughter
turned 16) as compensation for the death of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday a federal judge announced how an $8 million federal
court settlement will be divided among 502 families of inmates
brutalized by police and corrections officers after the riot.
Driscoll said the news turns her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   A corrections officer who was held hostage and stabbed by an
inmate during the riot said he is more angry than sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they (the inmates) should get a damn thing,''
said Anthony Prave, 62, who also now lives in Auburn. ``They blew
the place apart. They started it and they should get paid for it?
We didn't get anything _ why should they?''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Michael Telesca, in ending a 26-year
lawsuit against the state, said the inmates and their families
should get money because after the riots, police brutalized the
prisoners. The state admitted no wrongdoing in the settlement. The
judge's decision, though, spoke of allegations of inmates being
sodomized by nightsticks and brutally beaten as they ran through a
gantlet of troopers and correction officers, of authorities playing
Russian roulette with prisoners in their cells and constant
taunting and racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   The Attica riot, which grew out of inmates' objections to their
treatment, food, showering procedures and clothes, is categorized
as one of the largest and bloodiest prison riots in history.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the inmates afterward were treated ``like
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Prave, now retired as a corrections officer, is among those
still haunted by the riot. His only compensation was six months'
disability payment. He tacked on 11/2 months sick-time he was owed
by the state and recuperated for 71/2 months. He said the state
assumed that those held hostage during the riot were sleeping
between the hours of midnight and 7 a.m. and would not pay overtime
for those hours.
</P>
<P>
   While Prave was trying to control the inmates at the onset of
the riot on Sept. 9, prisoners took him captive, stripped him
naked, blindfolded him and bound him at the wrists and ankles. He
was 33 at the time with four young children. He bears the scar of a
stab wound in his stomach from the riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has flashbacks,'' Sue Prave said. ``He'll never get
rid of them.'' The state will not pay for counseling, Anthony Prave
said.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 30 years, the state is trying make amends with
victims such as Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 New York state budget allotted $550,000 for the widows
or children of murdered correction facilities employees, amounting
to $50,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll, a member of the political lobbying group the Forgotten
Victims of Attica, said it's not enough. State Sen. Dale Volker, a
Republican from the Attica district, agrees. He sponsored the bill
to get money for the victims' families, but said they are entitled
to much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair, but it's more than the inmates will get
individually,'' he said. ``How do you put a value on human life?''
</P>
<P>
   The $50,000 offer was modeled after today's state accidental
death policies, which is far better than the standards of 1971,
Volker said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of the widows has applied for her $50,000, Volker
and Driscoll said. Driscoll said she just misses the love of her
life and needs closure.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, 1971, the day police stormed the prison,
inmate-executioners marched John D'Arcangelo to the roof of the
prison. Police gunned down some of the hostages along with the
inmates. Reporters recorded video footage of the officer's death,
which his wife said sickens her to see over and over again on news
programs and documentaries about Attica.
</P>
<P>
   ``When John graduated college in the '60s he said he wanted to
leave his mark on the world,'' she said. ``I don't think he meant
he wanted to leave his blood on the walls of Attica.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pam Greene is a staff writer with the Syracuse (N.Y.)
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GORE-DETAILS-BOS &LR;      09-01 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DETAILS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FOCUSES ON THE DETAILS HE SAYS MAKE HIM BETTER THAN BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is no doctor, but he
practically played one on the campaign trail this week.
</P>
<P>
   When an elderly woman showed Gore her prescription for Vioxx, an
anti-inflammatory drug, he nodded knowingly and asked about her
arthritis. When another woman asked the difference between Medicare
and Medicaid, Gore walked her through the bureaucracies, explaining
which one she would qualify for.
</P>
<P>
   It was vintage Gore, minutae-oriented and, at times, dull. But
it was also a window onto the central Democratic strategy these
days: Purposely projecting Gore as a wonk, whose ideas alone
qualify him to be president.
</P>
<P>
   By rattling off details _ many of which voters aren't listening
to or can't understand _ Gore is betting the serious image this
projects will overpower the easygoing manner of Texas Governor
George W. Bush, even at the risk of his appearing boring or failing
to move crowds with soaring rhetoric. And for now it seems to be
working. A Newsweek poll released Friday showed Gore with his first
significant lead of the race, beating Bush, 49 to 39.
</P>
<P>
   The poll numbers, collected before the burst of campaign
activity expected to begin Labor Day, could easily shift once
again. But they reflect just how tight the battle is, and suggest
Bush will need to confront Gore's ``details campaign'' more
directly than he originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what Gore says goes over people's heads, but the
general image of Gore will stick,'' said Larry Sabato, a political
science professor at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it fits in with the subtext that most people already
believe, that here is a man who is boring and dull and unattractive
but who really knows his stuff...and Bush is a nice guy and a great
fella to have a beer with, but does not have the depth that Gore
has,'' he continued. ``It's perfect spin.''
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of the Gore approach is that it suits his character,
and on the surface, appears to be anti-spin, several political
analysts said. By simply ``focusing on issues,'' as Gore says he is
doing, the campaign can claim it is rising above politics or
personality _ and imply that Bush is relying on both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the closer we get to election day, the more
people focus on the issues and ask for specifics,'' Gore told
reporters on board Air Force Two on Thursday night. ``And I think
that's to the advantage of Joe Lieberman and me, because we have
spelled out the specifics and are happy to engage on the substance.
And I think that people are responding to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took a similar, but more limited, approach during the
Democratic primaries, zeroing in on former Senator Bill Bradley's
health care proposal and claiming it would give poor Medicaid
recipients only $150 a month to buy health insurance. The claim was
not entirely true, but Bradley mounted a feeble defense, and the
health care debate was later seen as a big part of his defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore is applying the same math to Bush, accusing him of
wanting to squander the federal budget surplus on a tax cut rather
than shoring up Social Security or Medicare (even though Bush has
said he could afford to do all three).
</P>
<P>
   But with Bush, Gore has found an even simpler card to play: That
the Texas governor doesn't have any detailed policies at all.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gore campaign, Bush is ``unable to win on the
issues'' and has ``failed to provide details'' on any number of
topics. In particular, Gore has attacked Bush repeatedly for not
fully explaining how he would provide a prescription drug coverage
to Medicare recipients _ and attacked him so hard that Bush was
forced to say he would release a more detailed prescription drug
plan this week.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic has confounded Bush campaign officials, who note the
Texas governor has laid out several detailed proposals _ only on
other topics, such as education and military readiness. ``I think
what this is a political strategy to hide the fact that Al Gore has
not offered any new ideas or policy proposals,'' Bush spokesman Dan
Bartlett said. ``This strategy is just that _ a strategy. It's an
excuse to recycle old attacks with a new tag line.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet ever since the first real offensive in the Gore
``details campaign'' _ his convention speech, in which he pledged
to be a serious, if dull, president _ Bush's command over the race
has slipped. After losing his double-digit lead in the polls, Bush
then found himself responding to Gore on the health care issue,
rather than setting the terms of the debate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Bush torn apart Gore's policies in detail. Scott Reed, a
Republican strategist who ran Bob Dole's 1996 campaign, said the
Bush campaign should be hammering Gore with the cost of his
prescription drug plan, which would provide every senior drug
coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand it,'' Reed said, when asked why the Bush
campaign had not gone on the health care policy offensive. ``The
Republicans need to do that to Gore, and that's what the RNC
(Republican National Committee) should be doing in their paid
advertising, taking apart the Gore plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the RNC this week launched a negative personal ad
against Gore, opening Bush up to further criticism that he is
running on personality rather than policy.
</P>
<P>
   That could change this week, when Bush plans to emphasize policy
contrasts between his campaign and Gore's. According to Reed, Gore
will suffer when his proposals are laid out next to Bush's and
scrutinized. Additionally, other analysts said, Bush should have a
natural advantage in his stump speech, which is filled mostly with
lofty rhetoric and generalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detail does not inspire in the same way as soaring rhetoric,''
said Marvin Kalb, Washington director of the Shorenstein Center on
the Press, Politics and Public Policy. ``The tendency of most
candidates is to use soaring rhetoric to inspire a crowd, to rally
the troops, and to escape the need to deal with the details of
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb said that Gore ``has had a good mix of detail and
rhetoric,'' enough to satisfy policy-wonks and inspire regular
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, his strategy seems to be working,'' he said.
``But it's a fragile mix. It can easily come unhinged. Because it's
still, in my judgment, a very volatile election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
