   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ President Clinton says he will
not break ground on a national missile defense system, leaving to
his successor the decision on how, or even whether, to proceed on
the politically charged and diplomatically sensitive issue of
building an anti-missile shield. Clinton acknowledges that the
threat of a long-range missile attack from potentially hostile
countries ``is real and growing'' but says he will not authorize
even initial construction of a still unproven system in light of
test failures and objections from Russia, China and our European
allies. By Eric Schmitt. (Eds.: an early version of this story has
moved; the 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 2-column, 3-line hed.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,9, and graphic, an analysis and sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   Inside: MISSILE-POLITICS, MISSILE-ASSESS, MISSILE-REACT,
MISSILE-HISTORY.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Two federal appeals court judges
halt the imminent release on bail of Wen Ho Lee, the former Los
Alamos scientist accused of mishandling nuclear weapons secrets. By
James Sterngold. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
