   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-U.N.-INCONVENIENCE (New York) _ Forget that some of the
weightiest world issues are up for discussion next week during the
U.N. Millennium Summit, the biggest gathering of heads of state and
government ``in human history,'' as the United Nations says. Let's
talk New York weighty: unspeakable traffic snarls and 170-some
curb-skipping motorcades around Kennedy International Airport and
U.N. on the East Side. Several thousand Secret Service agents
elbowing their way through 36 hotels and countless restaurants in
pursuit of their 238 ``protectees,'' from President Clinton to
Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana of Tuvalu. By Dean E. Murphy.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-RICHES-SCHEME (Mattoon, Ill.) _ Money has never put in much
of an appearance in Mattoon. Folks eat in places like Gill's diner,
where the all-you-can-eat walleye special goes for $4.99. They work
at factories like the Lender's Bagel plant. So more than a few
eyebrows began arching when a handful of people in this small
central Illinois town suddenly seemed to be sitting pretty. A
former police officer built a house with a six-car garage. A
retired electrician started offering people interest-free loans.
This week, federal law enforcement officials gave foundation to
years of Mattoon gossip. They charged 11 Mattoon residents and
eight other people in a bogus financial investment scheme that,
authorities say, hoodwinked more than 10,000 people around the
world out of more than $12.5 million. By Pam Belluck. (Scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 900 words.
</P>
