u f BC-MARKETS-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      09-01 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STATISTICS BOOST MARKET HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three new economic reports provide further evidence that the
Federal Reserve's campaign to slow down the economy by raising
interest rates is taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   In the most widely watched report, the Labor Department said
Friday the nationwide unemployment rate inched higher in August,
from 4 percent to 4.1 percent. A survey of analysts earlier in the
week had predicted the number would hold steady.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said 105,000 jobs were lost during the month,
but attributed them almost entirely to a cutbacks at the US Census
Bureau and a strike by workers at Verizon Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In the other reports, the nation's corporate purchasing managers
said their monthly index of manufacturing strength slipped in
August, and the government said construction spending dropped by
more in July than it had in any single month since January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term interest rates six times since
June of last year in an effort to slow the economy and ward off
rising prices. Some analysts think it may have finally finished the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was genuinely good news,'' Jeff Davis, chief investment
strategist for State Street Global Advisors, said of the reports.
``There's still no saying what the Fed will do, but the picture is
becoming clearer and looking better.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks gained slightly in light trading as investors prepared
for the long Labor Day weekend. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 23.68 points to close at 11,238.78. The Nasdaq Composite
index, which includes many of the nation's big technology stocks,
rose 27.98 points to close at 4234.33.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, though, said the stock market is likely to remain
hypersensitive to all kinds of economic reports and forecasts in
the months ahead _ at least until the Fed makes its intentions
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every piece of data that comes down the pipe will continue to
get dissected for hints about where we're going,'' he said. ``A lot
more evidence on the upside is needed before you'll see a true
relief rally.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed policymakers voted last week to hold interest rates at their
current levels, citing evidence that the economy was cooling from
the average 6 percent growth of the last four quarters _ a pace
central bankers worried would lead to increasing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is decelerating from 6 percent to 3 percent
economic growth,'' said Mark Vitner, an economist at First Union
Corp. in Charlotte, N.C. ``It will take some time for that to
translate into lesser inflation pressure. Don't write off the Fed
yet, but they're probably on hold through the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's reports came on top of previous indicators that
consumer spending grew in the second quarter at the slowest pace in
three years, that home resales slumped in July and that factories
reported the largest-ever drop in new orders in July _ a sign
consumer demand is weakening. Auto sales also have cooled; analysts
estimate last month's sales were 1.8 percent below those of August
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
