<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     09-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG FAT MESS IS CAUSING ERROR MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I would have sent this question by e-mail, but
my system is down for the count. Everything was frozen.
Control-Alt-Delete would not work. Now I'm getting this message
after the system starts: ``ScanDisk encountered a data error while
reading the FAT in Drive C.'' I tried to reinstall Windows 98, but
when it finished loading files and rebooted the system, it froze
again. Is there any fix for this that doesn't require me to
reformat Drive C?
</P>
<P>
   _ Critical Condition
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CRITICAL: Yes, but it involves a very large wooden mallet.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I had a better answer for you, but look at the bright
side: All that physical exertion will flood your body with
endorphins, and you'll forget your worries in no time at all. Not
buying it, are you? Oh, well. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's normal for ScanDisk to run after an improper Windows
shutdown, like when you hit the reset button or the power suddenly
goes bye-bye. And you didn't do anything wrong. Sometimes,
computers freeze for no apparent reason, and absolutely the only
way to get things running again is to turn them off. When the beast
starts back up, ScanDisk checks your hard drive and tries to repair
any errors the bad shutdown may have created.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's the way it's supposed to work. Unfortunately, it
looks like you've got some errors in your FAT, the file allocation
table. I often compare it to the table of contents of my
comprehensive journalism textbook from college. After I
accidentally ripped out those pages to mop up a spilled beer, there
was no way I could ever find the chapters on ethics and responsible
reporting, so I just gave up looking. That's what your PC is doing,
although there probably wasn't any beer involved. It can't find all
the files needed to make your computer work.
</P>
<P>
   The FAT is such a mind-bogglingly important file that there's
always a backup copy, just in case the real one gets corrupted. One
of the things ScanDisk tries to do is restore a corrupted FAT from
the backup, assuming it can find the thing and it isn't hammered,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Your last hope might be a better disk-repair program, such as
Disk Doctor, part of Symantec's Norton Utilities suite. I wouldn't
bet the farm on it, though. Maybe you should just think of this
whole episode as a wonderful opportunity to make a completely clean
start with your computer. Not buying that either? I didn't think
so. I must be losing my touch.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I bought a computer from a very close and
trusted friend (mistake). I allowed my wife to use said computer
(mistake). She found all the Web sites my trusted friend and his
spouse visited. How can I completely erase everything, or did I
make the third mistake: buying this unit?
</P>
<P>
   _ The Original Novice
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NOVICE: Mistake? C'mon, guy, this is your chance to
blackmail your friend for years to come. Listen, I told you I
didn't read that ethics chapter.
</P>
<P>
   If you insist on being Mr. Nice Guy, just dump the browser cache
and all the temporary Internet files. Any browser will let you do
that. Just look in Tools/Internet options/General in Internet
Explorer or Edit/Preferences/Navigator and /Advanced/Cache in
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to do a more complete job of hiding all the weird
things your friends were into, download a shareware tweaking
utility like System Mechanic (www.iolo.com). Unless I can bring you
to the Dark Side, that is.
</P>
<P>
   (We took a look at Dr. Emilio Bombay's browser cache while he
wasn't looking. You really don't want to know what we found. Write
him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
