</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ In another clear signal that the economy
is slowing in response to rising interest rates, the nation's
private employers created only 17,000 new jobs in August, the Labor
Department reported Friday, and the unemployment rate rose to 4.1
percent from 4 percent. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-THEME-PARKS (Dronten, the Netherlands) _ Europeans
visited amusement parks in record numbers this summer, stirred by
spreading affluence, booming tourism and greater variety. In the
last decade the number of theme parks in Europe has increased by a
third, while the number of admissions has risen two-thirds, and
revenues doubled to $2.2 billion. The expansion is gathering
momentum and drawing outside investment, notably from the United
States, transforming the European industry, long known for
family-owned mom-and-pop parks.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (The story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center right upper)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock and bond prices rose only slightly
Friday, even after new economic reports indicated that the economy
was slowing enough to preclude another interest rate increase by
the Federal Reserve in the near future. The Labor Department said
that new jobs were created at a much slower pace in August and that
there was a small rise in the unemployment rate. The National
Association of Purchasing Management reported a decline in its
factory index.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET)
</P>
<P>
   (Center right lower)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BRISTOL (Undated) _ Questioning the truthfulness of
statements made by Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, a federal
judge has awarded $1 million in punitive damages to a small
Connecticut company that brought an antitrust suit against the
giant software publisher.
</P>
