<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-690&AMP;A     09-01 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR FIGURES SHOW ECONOMY IS SLOWING AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another clear signal that the economy is slowing in response
to rising interest rates, the United States' private employers
created only 17,000 new jobs in August, the Labor Department
reported Friday, and the unemployment rate rose to 4.1 percent from
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The slowing was particularly noticeable in manufacturing, where
79,000 jobs disappeared and the National Association of Purchasing
Management, in a separate report, said that its index of
manufacturing activity had turned negative in August for the first
time in 20 months. With consumer demand weaker, manufacturers
appear to be trimming production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is clearly cooling down,'' said Gary R. Thayer,
chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, a brokerage firm based in
St. Louis. Like many other Wall Street forecasters, he said that
economic growth in the second half of the year would be markedly
slower than in the first half, increasing at an annual rate of 3
percent to 4 percent, instead of the 5 percent of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board, as a result, is unlikely to raise
interest rates again before next year, at the earliest, the
argument on Wall Street being that the Fed's six rate increases
since June 1999 have been enough to slow the economy to a growth
rate that the Fed considers noninflationary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data on the economy have got to be music to the Fed's
ears,'' said Richard Rippe, chief economist at Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The steady slowing in job growth is now unmistakable. While job
creation in the private sector averaged 202,000 a month last year _
and 229,000 a month in the fourth quarter _ that pace has fallen to
162,000 on average this year, and only 90,000 a month since May.
</P>
<P>
   There were other weaknesses evident in the August numbers. Total
job growth, covering government as well as private payrolls, fell
by 105,000, after a decline of 51,000 in July as the Census Bureau
continued to shed workers who had been hired temporarily to count
the population. From a peak of 618,000 in May, the census counters
shrank to 41,000 in August.
</P>
<P>
   All of the nation's workers also put in fewer hours in August
than in any other month this summer or spring, particularly in
manufacturing. The average hourly wage of production workers, who
held roughly 80 percent of the 131.5 million jobs in August, rose a
mild 4 cents, to $13.80 an hour. Over the last 12 months, this wage
has risen only 3.8 percent, despite the tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the rise in the pool of unemployed came mainly from
layoffs, dismissals and new people entering the labor force, rather
than people quitting their jobs confident of finding another in a
strong economy. That had been the tendency last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these statistics indicate that the tight labor market
is beginning to unravel; we clearly remain at full employment or
close to it,'' said Jared Bernstein, a labor economist at the
Economic Policy Institute. ``But they signal a potential reversal
in trend that deserves to be watched.''
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector, the August number was not quite as weak
as the 17,000 new jobs suggested. If not for the strike at Verizon
and a couple of other companies, private-sector job growth would
have totaled 102,000. While that would have been an improvement,
102,000 is hardly robust, said Thomas Nardone, chief of the
division of labor-force statistics at the Bureau of Labor
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are seeing the job slowdown clearly in construction,
manufacturing and mortgage finance,'' he said, pointing to
industries sensitive to rising short-term interest rates. Adjusted
for inflation, interest rates are now at one of their highest
levels in this decade. In a separate report Friday, the Commerce
Department said that construction spending fell in July for the
fourth consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market usually responds with enthusiasm to data
suggesting that the economy is weakening and that the Fed therefore
will not raise interest rates. But the Dow Jones industrial average
rose only 23.68 points Friday, to 11,238.78, and the Nasdaq
composite index was up 27.98 points, to 4,234.33.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Clinton administration greeted the latest employment report
with enthusiasm _ as evidence that Americans are still enjoying ``a
Tiger Woods economy,'' said Alexis Herman, the secretary of labor.
Still, she acknowledged that the economy was slowing. ``We have
gone from spectacular to steady and stable,'' she said in a
telephone interview, acknowledging that ``interest rates are having
some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The one bright spot in manufacturing was in electronics, a
reflection of the heavy spending on computers and
telecommunications, by both consumers and business. Electronics
manufacturers added 4,000 jobs in August and 42,000 since April
1999, although total manufacturing employment keeps declining.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recent job loss in manufacturing reflects a build-up
in inventories. Companies are apparently cutting production until
these stockpiles of unsold merchandise are worked down.
</P>
<P>
   Employment in retailing fell by 34,000 in August after rising by
132,000 in June and July. Still, job growth in retailing has
averaged only 28,000 a month this year, down from 36,000 in 1999.
Department-store hiring has been particularly weak.
Service-industry employment, in contrast, grew by a robust 160,000
after rising only 11,000 in July. The growth came mainly in job
training, management, engineering and temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate, rising from 4.02 percent to 4.14 percent
before rounding, reflected slightly higher unemployment in almost
every group, with unemployment among teen-agers and blacks rising
more than others. Teen-age unemployment rose a percentage point, to
14.4 percent, and the rate among black men and women edged up to 8
percent from 7.7 percent, with black men hurt the most. Their rate
jumped to 7.4 percent from 6.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
