<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8824 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HEMLOCK-MEETS-BOS &LR;      09-01 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMLOCK-MEETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT-TO-DIE ADVOCATES MEET; `NOT DEAD YET' VOWS PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The woman rushed up to Dr. Philip Nitschke as if he
were a rock star. ``Your speech was the best,'' she said. ``I'm
going to Australia for the Olympics _ do you have a schedule of
your clinics?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Nitschke, billed as ``the first doctor in the
world'' to assist in an explicitly legal suicide under a
short-lived Australian law, and he described a typical ``clinic:''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone'll come in, put six pills on the table and say, `I've
saved all these tablets. If I take them, will I die?' '' Nitschke
then advises them. ``It's very practical advice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian doctor was mobbed by fans Friday in the hallway
of the Park Plaza Hotel, scene of the World Conference on Assisted
Dying this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, sponsored by the Hemlock Society, has drawn fire
from the Massachusetts Catholic Conference, the Massachusetts
Medical Society and the Massachusetts Nurses Association. In
addition, the hundreds of participants are bracing for the arrival
of Not Dead Yet, a group of advocates for the disabled who have
chained themselves to doorways at other assisted-suicide gatherings
and vowed to protest.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, conference-goers were looking inward _ greeting old
friends, stocking up on pamphlets called ``The Art and Science of
Suicide,'' and giving an award to Dr. Pieter Admiraal, a leader of
the physician-assisted suicide movement in the Netherlands who, one
speaker affectionately recalled, kissed one dying patient and said,
``Have a good trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any subculture, the movement has its own heroes (Admiraal),
seminal texts (``Final Exit,'' by Derek Humphry), controversial
figures (Dr. Jack Kevorkian) and lively internal debates between
the radical and the less-radical.
</P>
<P>
   The conference even offers a nightly film festival. Samples
include a rerun of Kevorkian giving a lethal injection to Thomas
Youk on ``60 Minutes''; ``One True Thing,'' based on the Anna
Quindlen book about a young woman who may have helped her
terminally ill mother die; and _ remarkably _ ``Soylent Green,''
the Charton Heston cult classic about a nightmare government that
bakes dead people into crackers and offers suicide on demand.
</P>
<P>
   The conventioneers are not a dour, death-obsessed group, said
Mary Gallnor, president of the World Conference. Rather, she said,
they want to ensure that their loved ones _ and eventually, they
themselves _ die with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as Not Dead Yet ``don't need to be frightened of
us,'' she said, offering to talk with them about how best to ensure
disabled people's rights in assisted-suicide legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say such legislation _ currently in force only in Oregon
_ makes terminally ill people a separate class, ``candidates for
death,'' said Daniel Avila of the Massachusetts Catholic
Conference, the church's public policy arm. He said death with
dignity is best offered through hospice care.
</P>
<P>
   Hospices traditionally oppose assisted suicide. But one
conference speaker, Douglas Aberg, a Northern California hospice
nurse in his 30s, said they should provide it, so that social
workers and chaplains could stay involved. Currently, he said, some
hospice personnel covertly condone it, but are required to ``stop
short,'' watching patients refuse food and water without offering
drugs to hasten the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramage, 76, a hospice volunteer, disagreed. Although he
supports assisted suicide, he said, it could get hospices into
``all kinds of trouble,'' politically and financially.
</P>
<P>
   A similar debate simmered between people such as Nitschke and
Humphry on one side, both of whom teach suicide techniques to get
around prohibitions, and those who fear those techniques inflame
the public against their main goal _ passing legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Livermore, whose husband heads the Michigan chapter of the
Hemlock Society, said she opposes Kevorkian not only because he is
``bad PR,'' but because he provides no safeguards: he often does
not know his patients and gets no second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In case the law comes too late for her, she grabbed Aberg by the
elbow to verify: ``If you stop eating or drinking, how long does it
take, four to five days?'' Longer, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Ken Haslam, an intensive-care anesthesiologist
who said he has seen ``technology going crazy,'' bought four how-to
pamphlets for $10 each, including ``Helium and the Exit Bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gases are my business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Haslam, 66, recently bought his own helium tank from a party
store, for demonstrations, and perhaps someday for his own death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I was having a going-away party,'' he said. ``And by
the way, could I have a dozen balloons?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-NMD-0902-COX     09-01 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NMD-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PASSES ON DECISION ABOUT NATIONAL MISSILE DEFENSE TO
SUCCESSOR
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaving a critical national security decision for
his predecessor, President Clinton said Friday he would not deploy
a controversial missile defense system, citing technological
deficiencies and objections from the global community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the technology for NMD is promising, the system as a
whole is not yet proven,'' Clinton said during a speech centered on
the subject at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   While he stressed that no country can dictate U.S. defense
decisions, Clinton also cited concerns raised by U.S. allies and
objections from Russia and China, nuclear powers that threatened to
beef up their arsenals if the United States built the controversial
weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States can't ignore the potential security
implications of a renewed nuclear race that could threaten the
strategic balance of power or undermine the global arms control
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Testing and development of the missile defense system is to
continue, leaving open the possibility that Clinton's successor
could deploy the complex $25-billion system, a combination of
sophisticated radars and rockets, designed to blast an incoming
missile out of the sky on its way toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee,
released a statement supporting Clinton's decision and saying that,
if elected, he would continue to monitor the system's development
with an eye toward making a deployment decision as the technology
matures.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee who has placed
national missile defense near the center of his security agenda,
pounced on the decision, saying it was further evidence of poor
security stewardship by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to deploy a missile defense system ``at the
earliest possible date,'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton and Vice President Gore first denied the
need for missile defense, then delayed. Now they are leaving this
important unfinished business for the next president,'' Bush said
in a prepared statement. ``I welcome the opportunity to act where
they have failed to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and other proponents say the system is needed to protect
the United States against the threat of a missile attack from a
country such as North Korea, Iraq or Iran _ all of which are
believed to be at work on weapons of mass destruction and the
long-range rocket technology required to launch an intercontinental
attack _ or a rogue state or terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Should the next president decide to deploy the system, it could
be up and running as early as 2006, said Clinton. That's roughly
one year later than earlier estimates suggested it could be ready
if Clinton ordered construction to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, told
reporters that the administration had not delayed action on the
system, but had spent $5.7 billion, to date, on developing it.
</P>
<P>
   But after only three of 19 planned test firings _ two of which
failed _ and in the face of widespread opposition from abroad,
Clinton said the time was not right to begin building the so-called
national missile defense, or NMD, system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply cannot conclude, with the information I have today,
that we have enough confidence in the technology and the
operational effectiveness of the entire NMD system to move forward
to deployment,'' Clinton said. ``Therefore, I have decided not to
authorize deployment of a national missile defense at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is not abandoning the NMD program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made progress,'' said Clinton, who made his decision
over the past two days after consulting Tuesday with Defense
Secretary William Cohen. ``But we should not move forward until we
have absolute confidence that the system will work.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton stressed the system's technological deficiencies,
he made clear that global resistance to NMD, particularly within
former U.S. Cold War foes Russia and China, played a key role in
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Clinton, as persistent objections from U.S. allies
made clear, far more diplomacy is required before an NMD system
might be deployed without provoking unpredictable reactions among
U.S. friends and foes around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation can ever have a veto over American security,''
Clinton said. ``But we can never afford to overlook the fact that
the actions and reactions of others in this increasingly
interdependent world do bear on our security.''
</P>
<P>
   In measured rhetoric with Cold War echoes, Clinton warned that
Russia's huge nuclear arsenal, the world's largest, remains
dangerous. The United States, Clinton said, can neither ignore
Moscow's sentiments on arms issues nor risk the unraveling of the
arms control treaties that have formed the basis of two generations
of mutual restraint in the deployment of the most devastating
weapons on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are no longer adversaries, we are not yet real
allies,'' he said. ``Therefore, for them, as well as for us,
maintaining strategic stability increases trust and confidence on
both sides. It reduces the risk of confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving forward with a missile defense system would require that
the United States either amend or withdraw from the Nixon-era Anti
Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty, a cornerstone of the U.S.-Russia
arms control regime.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin has so far rejected NMD, saying
it would tilt the U.S.-Russia balance of power in favor of the
United States, and he has refused to negotiate ABM amendments that
would allow the system to be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States to unilaterally walk away from the ABM
treaty, said Clinton, would be a dangerous breach of U.S.-Russian
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategic stability based on mutual deterrence is still
important, despite the end of the Cold War,'' he said. ``Why?
Because the United States and Russia still have nuclear arsenals
that can devastate each other, and this is still a period of
transition in our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Putin applauded the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision not to take upon
himself the responsibility for deploying the national anti-missile
defense system is seen in Russia as a well thought-out and
responsible step,'' Putin said in a statement. ``Doubtless (it)
will lead to strengthening strategic stability and security in the
whole world, and will raise the United States' authority in the
eyes of the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also cited concerns about China, which threatened to
expand its nuclear arsenal in response to a U.S. NMD system.
</P>
<P>
   If China were to do that, Clinton said, it could raise tensions
in East Asia, including Japan and Taiwan, and could provoke India,
a long-standing rival of China's, into building additional nuclear
weapons. That, in turn, could prompt India's neighboring nemesis,
Pakistan, to expand its small nuclear arsenal, raising the nuclear
stakes across the already volatile Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement took the issue off the front-burner for
important diplomacy next week, when Clinton participates in the
United Nations Millennium Summit, expected to be the largest
gathering of heads of state in history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to meet privately with Putin, as well as
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and a constellation of other world
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Non-proliferation analysts also heaved a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy the right decision was made,'' said Stephen Young,
deputy director of the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, an
alliance of 17 groups devoted to containing the threat of nuclear
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case for going ahead was very weak,'' said Young, whose
group has expressed concern for months that pressing forward with
NMD could push countries like Russia and China into building new
nuclear weapons to try to compensate for any strategic advantage
the new defense system might give to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia and China weren't kidding,'' Young said. ``This was
going to make them very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
