<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVES MISSILE SYSTEM DECISION TO SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton abandoned his long-stated goal
Friday to become the US leader who launched a national missile
defense system, leaving the decision to his successor because he
deemed it technologically unproven and potentially dangerous to US
national security interests.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at Georgetown University, Clinton said he had
determined there was an emerging threat that countries such as
North Korea, Iran or Iraq could launch a missile at the United
States in coming years. But he said it was wiser to wait until more
work was done on the national missile defense program.
</P>
<P>
   The work, he said, wasn't just with technological wizards in
laboratories, but also among the world's corridors of power where
savvy diplomats needed to persuade US allies as well as Russia that
building such a defense network was in their best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not move forward until we have absolute confidence
that the system will work and until we have made every reasonable
diplomatic effort to minimize the cost of deployment and maximize
the benefit not only to America's security, but to the security of
law-abiding nations everywhere,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's consideration of a system _ $5 billion has
been already spent on testing _ had caused almost universal
consternation or worse from heads of state around the world. China,
for instance, had warned of an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted China's fierce opposition, and said that if the
next president decides to deploy a missile defense system, ``he
will need to avoid stimulating an already dangerous regional
nuclear capability from China to South Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite high-level Clinton administration lobbying efforts,
Russia strongly protested a missile defense system, saying it would
violate the terms of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty and
raising the specter of the collapse of several historic arms
control agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The issue immediately burst into the US presidential campaign,
with Texas Governor George W. Bush criticizing Clinton, saying,
``The administration missed an opportunity to develop a
missile-defense system that would protect all 50 states, protect
ourselves and our allies from an accidental launch, political
blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Texarkana, Ark., Bush added, ``Should I be
president, I'll seize the moment and develop an effective
antitballistic missile system.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, meanwhile, supported Clinton's decision,
saying it allows more time to be certain of the technologies, costs
and national security ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, at the end of the day, I would not be prepared to let
Russian opposition to this system stand in the way of its
deployment, if I should conclude that the technologies are mature
enough to deploy and are both affordable and needed,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision settled a rift within his administration that
pitted pro-missile defense Pentagon officials against many of
Clinton's senior advisers in the White House, State Department and
National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen met with Clinton on Tuesday
night at the White House to spell out his support for the system.
Cohen, a Republican from Maine, released a tepid statement on the
issue Friday, carefully not saying that he supported Clinton's
decision but that he supports ``this approach'' of having the next
president fully involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen _ the lone GOP member on the Cabinet and of whom National
Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger said in an interview earlier this
summer was the ``best team player'' among senior administration
officials _ also refused White House requests to call members of
Congress Friday informing them of Clinton's decision, according to
a US official. That job fell to Berger and Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright; on national security issues, Cohen is the
administration's preferred liasion because of ties gained from 24
years as US senator and congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and several Pentagon officials supported giving a
conditional go-ahead to the national missile defense system in
order that work begin next spring on concrete pads for a radar
station in Alaska next spring, allowing for a possible 2005
deployment of the system. The Pentagon had already solicited bids
for construction of the site, setting Sept. 7 as the deadline for
cost proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of Clinton's decision, the earliest deployment
would be 2006 or 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the system applauded the decision, saying it
shouldn't have been a close call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president's decision is the only logical one he
could have made given how poorly the program has performed,'' said
Joseph Cirincione, director of the non-proliferation project at the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, a Washington
think-tank. ``They've had two successive test failings and they
still don't understand why the last shot failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirincione predicted the decision would seriously set back the
program. ``It's been like a balloon and the president's speech just
let out the air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore A. Postol, an MIT professor of science, technology and
national security policy, returned to Boston Friday from a meeting
at NATO headquarters in Belgium with senior European officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the meeting, there was universal concern about the possible
problems this missile defense system would create,'' Postol said.
``They were all rather concerned about where this could take the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Several European countries reacted positively to Clinton's
decision Friday. Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Petersen said
his government ``noted with satisfaction'' the postponement, saying
US and Russian negotiators needed more time to talk about
amendments to the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said a former US official who was part of high-level
discussions on missile defense, the decision was ``a no-brainer for
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding thing was this guy didn't want to be seen as
the president who broke the ABM treaty,'' the former official said.
``Allies also were pushing very hard not to make this decision yet.
The administration had not done enough spade work to allay their
concerns. Should Russia lash out against this project, you would
want to have the allies standing with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed those points directly in his speech,
especially the impact on the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The president said if the national missile defense system was
deployed, the ABM treaty would have to be adjusted, something
Russia is not willing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the US-Russian relationship, he said, ``While we are
no longer adversaries, we are not yet real allies. Therefore, for
them, as well as for us, maintaining strategic stability increases
trust and confidence on both sides. It reduces the risk of
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe Staff Glen Johnson contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
