<HEADLINE>
DEBATE COMMISSION TELLS BUSH IT CAN'T CHANGE SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials of an independent commission that organizes the
presidential debates told aides to Gov. George W. Bush Friday that
they will not revise the locations or schedules for three debates
in October that the Bush campaign has sought to modify.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Brown, executive director of the Commission on
Presidential Debates, said the panel's position was spelled out at
a meeting in Washington with Joe Allpaugh, the Bush campaign
manager, and two other Bush lieutenants involved in debate
preparations. She said that she told the officials that the
arrangements are far too advanced and the job of ensuring network
coverage too complex for the process to be tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed the extensive work that has already been done,''
Brown said. ``And we underscored things like the difficulty of this
fall's television schedule, with the Olympics scheduled for so late
in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials have indicated recently that they are
not happy with some aspects of the debates organized by the
nonpartisan commission, which has been supervising the presidential
debates since 1988. They have said that their objections include
the plan to broadcast all three debates in prime time, and to the
holding of the first debate at the University of Massachusetts in
Boston because the location is adjacent to the John F. Kennedy
Library, an institution commemorating a Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday why he was reluctant to agree to the commission
debates, Bush said, ``I'm looking at the options. You know, it
seems like to me that there will be some really interesting formats
other than what we're told will have to be the format.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's resistance is the sticking point in the October
showdowns. Vice President Al Gore has already agreed to the
commission's proposals; in fact, he has accepted invitations to
more than 50 debates, though his campaign chairman, William Daley,
added the stipulation Friday that Bush must consent to the
commission debates before the other offers would be entertained.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush, meanwhile, have been exploring other options,
meeting with officials of broadcast and cable networks this week to
discuss debate formats.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the candidates on Thursday, Tom Johnson, chairman
of CNN, proposed Larry King as the referee of a first debate, to be
produced by his network. ``One could not ask for a fairer, more
balanced, more enthusiastic moderator,'' he wrote. Other networks
have made similar approaches on behalf of their news stars.
</P>
<P>
   King might indeed be the gentle sort of inquisitor that the Bush
camp is seeking. Bush is said to prefer formats in which the
candidates can converse, rather than formally debate, an activity
at which Gore is generally thought to be the more skilled. Mindy
Tucker, a Bush spokeswoman, would say only that CNN's proposal was
``one of the many letters that have come in.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that one network would get such a coveted
designation, because Gore, who met Friday in Nashville, Tenn., with
Daley and others advising him on debate preparations, says the
commission's debates are his priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the commission schedule is the best way to conduct
debates, so that they are seen by the most people on free
television,'' said Mark Fabiani, the Gore campaign's communications
director. ``Once the Bush campaign agrees to the commission's
presidential debates, we then would be pleased to consider these
other opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that she told Bush's representatives that the
commission has always been open to employing a variety of formats
for the debates, which are to occur on Oct. 3 in Boston; Oct. 11 in
Winston-Salem, N.C., and on Oct. 17 in St. Louis. She added that
the panel would consider Bush's proposal that a second
vice-presidential debate be added.
</P>
</TEXT>
