<SLUG> BC-OPED-VIRTUAL-WORK-RICE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONLINE COMMUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Sept. 2, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By SCOTT RICE    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Six miles south of where I live, in a lovely
pastoral setting known as Coyote Valley, Cisco Systems is busy
transforming almost 700 acres of fields, orchards and streams into
a huge office complex that will eventually house 20,000 of its
employees. Such a facility makes obvious sense. When you
concentrate bright, skilled people in the same proximate space,
they energize one another. And given the intellectual nature of the
work, and the brain pool that it will house, it deserves to be
called, in familiar Silicon Valley language, a ``campus.''
</P>
<P>
   If I worked at Cisco, I would probably have endorsed the idea,
but then I would have crossed my fingers and hoped that no outsider
asked the obvious question: After all the talk about the
sufficiency of virtual experience, what has happened to the wired
utopia we were promised? The on-site office was supposed to be the
first to succumb to the ease of Internet communication. When a
high-tech giant sets this sort of example, it's difficult to
believe in the promise of satisfactory virtual substitutes like
telecommuting, online shopping, online entertainment, and _
something that concerns me greatly as a teacher _ online education.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just Cisco. One of its top rivals, Juniper
Networks, recently announced its own 80-acre Silicon Valley
expansion. Juniper's and Cisco's workers are the computer whizzes
trailblazing our digital future. If they don't function better in
the virtual workplace, then how can they sell it to the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   Several decades into the Information Age, Silicon Valley
freeways are as clogged as ever. Only moguls get to telecommute,
dialing in occasionally from their yachts. The worker bees continue
to slog to work every morning, as their ancestors did.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies will continue to build campuses because
they know that the intellectually demanding work they do is best
tackled in groups. If it seems hypocritical for them to promote
something different for the rest of us, just remember who is
selling the gear and tackle to construct that wired virtual campus.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Rice is a professor of English at San Jose State
University.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
