<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IT MEANS TO BE AN ALABAMA FANATIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most, Alabama football - at least when I was growing up in
the northern part of the state in the '60s, '70s and '80s - was
about Bear Bryant stringing together the filling of what would turn
into 323 win during his marvelous coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   It was also about players who excelled in college football like
Major Oglivie, Steadman Shealy and Johnny Musso. And NFL Hall of
Famers Ozzie Newsome, Lee Roy Jordan, John Hannah, Kenny Stabler
and Joe Namath and some others - like Tony Nathan and Richard Todd
- who went on to solid professional football careers.
</P>
<P>
   It was about linebacker Barry Krauss knocking himself silly
while keeping a Penn State runner out of the end zone in the 1979
Sugar Bowl during one of six national championship seasons under
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   It was about Bryant leaning against the goal post while his team
went through pregame warmups and mumbling his waying through his
television show the following day.
</P>
<P>
   It was about a group of players terrified Bryant would come down
from his tower during practice sessions and the same men refusing
to call him anything but Coach Bryant even after they were long
gone from the university.
</P>
<P>
   It was about a big Alabama home game being held in a stadium
that was more than an hour away from the campus in a place known as
``The Football Capital of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about weddings being scheduled around football season and
children learning to say `Roll Tide' about the same time as `Mama
and Daddy.' It was about a father of an acquaintance of mine
telling his son that sure he could consider going to Auburn but if
he decided to take that route then he might as well pack up all his
belongings because he wasn't welcome at home anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It was about Bryant's death bringing grown men to tears and his
funeral virtually shutting down businesses statewide so people
could line the highwayfrom Tuscaloosa to Birmingham as his body was
taken to its resting place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I don't really expect everyone to understand what it was it
was to be an Alabama fanatic. And there are plenty who don't know
Major Oglivie from Sargeant Slaughter and think that Steadman
Shealy are the first two names of a law partnership.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with not getting it, because, frankly, for
a long time I rooted against the Tide. For some reason - probably
cause I was friends with a couple of obnoxious Alabama fans - I
rooted for Tennessee and there was a time when I felt Robin Weber
was an American hero.
</P>
<P>
   We'll take a minute for a history lesson to tell those who don't
known who Robin Webber is - which is probably most of you not
educated in Alabama or Notre Dame lore. It was Weber, who was a
tight end at Notre Dame, whose catch and 37-yard gain moved the
Irish out of the shadows of their goal post in the final minutes of
the 1973 Sugar Bowl game. Notre Dame ran out the clock to claim the
national championship with a 24-23 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty safe to say that I was the only kid in my
neighborhood that night happy about the outcome. And, I was also
the only kid who showed up at school wearing a USC t-shirt the day
after the Tide was given a share of the national title with the
Trojans in 1979 even though USC had won a regular season
head-to-head meeting.
</P>
<P>
   What's funny is I didn't really become a full-fledged Alabama
fan until Bryant's career - and it turns out his life - was coming
to a conclusion. And it took a guy named Jim Bunch for me to make
the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Bunch was an offensive tackle at Alabama from 1976-79, a starter
on Bryant's Bryant's last two national championship teams and an
All- American. He was also a co-worker of mine - although I'm sure
he doesn't remember this - at a steak restaraunt in the spring of
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Now, understand, Alabama football players - particularly
All-Americans - were a pretty big thing around Tuscaloosa. Big
enough, in fact, the the guy interviewing for the position used
Bunch working there as a perk in helping me decide whether to
accept the job.
</P>
<P>
   So I show up for my first day ready to meet an Alabama
All-American offensive lineman, who I figured was going to dwarf
everyone. The first person I saw was a guy no taller than me - I'm
about 6-foot - and didn't appear to be a particularly muscular
fella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ok,'' I quickly reckoned, ``that's not Jim Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, though, I was wrong. It was Bunch and he had been an
All-American, but he didn't look any different than anyone else,
which was pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   It got me to thinking that Bryant's teams were filled over the
years with guys like Bunch. Oh sure, he had plenty of talent, but
he also had a knack of choosing some outstanding players who
wouldn't have fit in today's combine-filled world of football. And
he turned his players into winners - which was pretty cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
