<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RUDE EYE OF REBELLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 3, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The relationship between ``labor'' and management is much more
complicated than the power struggles that erupt regularly in the
headlines. The Verizon strike is ended. But a painful walkout by
3,000 members of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers at Raytheon Co. is simmering and now Bridgestone/Firestone
Inc. is facing a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   These hotspots are the result of gambles taken in the ebb and
flow of politics. They have to do with Democrats and Republicans,
the New Economy and the Old, the images of Big Labor and Big
Business. They are attempts to manipulate the narrative on a grand
scale.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the really intimate workplace dynamics between
managers and those whom they supervise? Few topics are more
interesting to us in our own lives, but these topics are not well
covered in the psychology and political science courses we took in
college, business school curricula, or by the constant flow of
inspirational business books. The best way to get at them may be
fiction. Who has written about corporate competition better than
John Le Carre? Or consider the new novel ``Labor Day'' by Floyd
Kemske.
</P>
<P>
   Kemske is familiar to readers of this column. A jack-of-all-
trades who resides in Pepperell, Mass., he makes a living as a
specialist in direct mail advertising, a sometime trade journalist
and a dot-com entrepreneur. Mainly, however, he is an author.
``Labor Day'' is his fourth ``corporate nightmare,'' another in a
series of entertaining parables of the high-tech corporate world.
Kemske catapults entirely believable characters into slightly
fabulous situations and lets them play out their roles with more
than enough angst and lust to keep the story moving along.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Human Resources,' the turn-around artist at a biotech
copmpany turns out to be the very worst kind of asset-stripper. In
``The Virtual Boss,'' it is self-aware software that runs the
company; the omniscient program forces the hero to make a painful
choice between his woman and access to its own expert systems. And
in ``Lifetime Employment,'' the only way to get ahead is to team up
with other Suits to murder the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor Day'' continues the tradition: a union-buster is called
out of retirement by the very union president who earlier had ended
his career in the course of a cataclysmic organizing campaign. The
old-timer's task is to prevent his former antagonist's 53-member
union staff from affiliating with a competitive union. The
illustration on the cover of ``Labor Day'' is of many hands joined
together at one end of a rope in a game of tug-of-war. Its settings
are Edenic: Jolly Jim's Refresh and Refuel, just off exit 39 in
northern New Jersey; the headquarters of the Federation of Office
Workers in the edge city of Forestdale. Employees respect and trust
the managers; managers are fair, well-informed and egalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   Into these situation step a pair of crafty and unethical
entrepreneurs working in the service of lofty goals: a young union
organizer and the old ``prevention and decertification
consultant.'' They search for the malcontents and the de facto
leaders among their target populations. For a long time they remain
unknown to one another. The old man is reading Shakepeare's ``King
John.'' The young man taunts him with a single line, slightly
abridged, from its story of war between England and France:
``Thread the rude eye of rebellion.'' The old man knows that
Shakepeare really wrote ``Unthread the rude eye...,'' but it
doesn't matter. In the organizing battle, as in the play, the two
sides are too hard to tell apart.
</P>
<P>
   The subtext thoughout is betrayal. Both men target the same
memorable union vice president for their skillful lies _ and both
win and lose her trust. The organizer's mentor turns out to be a
person well-known to the union-buster. The idealistic union
president undergoes a thorough transformation. The nice
philanthropic lady from Philadelphia fires the entire staff of
Jolly Jim's _ and then hires them back with many fewer benefits as
contract workers from Preventive Leasing. The Pinkertons who turn
up to resolve the situation at the union office are packing tear
gas and stun guns.
</P>
<P>
   What Kemske is saying in ``Labor Day'' is that the capacity of
idealists to delude themselves and others is very great on both
sides _ that vanity often trumps solidarity, in the workplace and
in the marriage bed. A metaphor that appears more than any other is
of serial killing _ of businesses, not persons. Joint enterprises
work best when there is cooperation and not just division of labor,
he says; organizing too often takes the form of
(itals)disorganizing(unitals) successful enterprises through the
exploitation of rivalries and jealousies.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, there is no doubt that Kemske believes that
labor's struggles are worth it; that organizing attempts are born
to victory even though they are defeated all the time, or make a
desert often when they are successful. That's the point of
insistent allusions to England's King John in ``Labor Day.'' For
all his tiresome wars with France, it was he who nearly 800 years
ago signed the Magna Carta _ the charter which has permitted the
peaceful threading of the rude eye of rebellion ever since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
