s l BC-CHOW-HOTSPOT-ART-ADV0     09-01 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOW-HOTSPOT-ART-ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE FOOD WITH EXTRA GLAMOUR, CELEBRITY CHIC AND GOOD LIGHTING
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT20  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
By   GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent weeknight in August, the commotion at Mr.
Chow belied all conventional thinking about what goes on in New
York during the very end of summer. Presumably, nothing goes on _
and the kind of nothing involving no ones _ because all the
someones are busy doing nothing somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   But here's how the somebody map of Mr. Chow, the eatery on East
57th Street, read that night, a Tuesday: Marin Hopper, Elle's
fashion director, stood at the bar waiting for her table just a
foot or two away from John Cusack, the actor, who was seated in the
restaurant's coveted spot above the main dining room, which meant
that if he cared to (but he probably didn't) he could glance over
at James Truman, Conde Nast's editorial director eating with
Samantha Boardman, the socialite, who in turn could wave to her
sister, Serena, seated a few tables away. Cusack was chatting with
two bodyguards, phone cords sprouting out around their ears, who
were minding a young man who looked an awful lot like Wyclef Jean,
the hip-hop performer. As it turned out, the young man wasn't
Wyclef Jean, &UR;  &LR; but the mistake was an easy one to make since he,
like Puffy Combs, has been eating at Mr. Chow quite a lot this
summer; last week, he showed up twice. (Cusack's dinner companion
soon arrived _ Uma Thurman.)
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chow, owner of the three restaurants that bear his name,
never intended to deliver diced squab to the unremarkable. But for
a good portion of the 1990s it was largely the cachet-deficient who
showed up, not only in New York, but also in the Mr. Chows in Los
Angeles and London. ``There were about five years there when you
could have shot a cannon off in the place and no one would have
heard it,'' said Chris Denton, the maitre d'hotel of the Los
Angeles Mr. Chow.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year or so, though, the Mr. Chow here has re-emerged
as a destination for all subspecies of the moneyed and glamorous,
with dumpling connoisseurs from the suburbs there, too. It's in the
pantheon of Manhattan restaurants whose patrons come less for the
food than to be with their own kind _ like Michael's, for the
publishing crowd, and Swifty's, for ladies of a certain position.
But Mr. Chow attracts two kinds, standing out as the theater of
artifice where the worlds of fashion and hip-hop play out their
fascination with each other every night, even if they don't
actually mingle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an incredible mix,'' remarked Marvet Britto, a
publicity agent and Mr. Chow regular, who represents hip-hop and
sports stars, including Foxy Brown and Latrell Sprewell. ``Damon
Dash is having dinner with Harvey Weinstein,'' she said, referring
to a partner of Roc-A-Fella Records and a co-chairman of Miramax,
respectively. ``And Puffy could be having dinner with Diane Von
Furstenberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chow opened his third restaurant, a sleek art-filled room,
in 1979, five years after he got a branch going in Beverly Hills
and 11 years after he established himself with a London spot in
Knightsbridge that catered to the kind of people who would be
parodied in the Austin Powers films decades later.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Michael Chow moved to Manhattan, Tina Lutz, the
model, jeweler and fashion muse, had already become Mrs. Michael
Chow, thanks in part to an introduction made by the British
designer Zandra Rhodes. Tina Chow brought the fashion crowd to
reign at the new restaurant in New York alongside Andy Warhol,
Julian Schnabel and Jean-Michel Basquiat. Some artists and dealers
remained loyal to Mr. Chow during the '90s slump, a period when
Chow himself, distracted by his interests in art and film, decided
to pay less attention to the business' operations. Following the
death of Tina Chow from AIDS in 1992, the fashion world moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chow recaptured some of its glitz when the hip-hop
contingent discovered it, following the record producers and
industry executives who have their offices nearby. Most say it took
off about two years ago with a flurry of record release parties.
Steven Stoute, president of Black Music Division at Interscope
Records, gave his 28th birthday party at Mr. Chow about two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Combs was already a frequent diner, and in the spring of last
year, when he started his men's clothing line, Sean John, he took
over all of Mr. Chow for a party. It created a setting in which
people like Kal Ruttenstein, the longtime fashion director at
Bloomingdale's, were sharing chicken skewers with people like Heavy
D.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Sean John party, Paul Wilmot, the fashion
publicity agent, who represents Combs and who had gone to Mr. Chow
on and off for years, reclaimed his status as a regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are fabulous places in Chinatown,'' Wilmot
said, ``but you have to look in a Zagat's and you have to tell me
how to get there and the lighting is horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a fortunate thing that the lighting at Mr. Chow is not
horrible, because if the restaurant encourages anything, it
encourages you to look, and if fashion types in sheer, strappy
dresses and hip-hop singers slathered in roped gold and mink share
anything, it is the wish not to go unnoticed. The back wall is
mirrored, and the open staircase leading into the dining area _
surely the subject of more discussion than the dumplings _ ensures
that every entrance has a note of Norma Desmond.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chow occupies an odd place in the New York dining orbit
because it manages to be unusually pretentious and democratic at
the same time. Mr. Chow is a Chinese restaurant in which it is rare
to escape paying less than $100 a person. In the 1980s, the
restaurant, in an effort to seem even more clublike than it already
was, kept a sign-in book. Menus have never been provided; you are
supposed to know enough to have the green prawns, the crispy beef,
the sauteed string beans.
</P>
<P>
   All that aside, Mr. Chow has become perhaps the only expensive
restaurant south of 96th Street with an obvious racial mix. ``You
don't see it anywhere else,'' said Britto, the publicity agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
