<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN RETURNS TO NORMALCY AS BIG NAMES PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Will replace with Selena Roberts' story later this evening)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 6-8, 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if they did not want to spend a moment longer in
the sauna-like conditions of the U.S. Open Friday, most of the
prominent seeds eliminated their opponents as quickly as possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Martina Hingis disposed of Tathiana Garbin in a tidy
37 minutes in her third-round match, 6-1, 6-0, at the National
Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park. Hingis committed
just five unforced errors to earn a fourth-round confrontation with
11th-seeded Sandrine Testud of France, who defeated Kristie Boogert
of the Netherlands, 6-0, 6-1, in 41 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to have an easy day today,'' Hingis said. ``I'll
go have a massage, just take it easy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After top-seeded Andre Agassi's stunning loss to Arnaud Clement
on Thursday, the Open seemed to undergo a cosmic adjustment back to
the predictable Friday. There were a few minor upsets among the
lower seeds, but most of the players who command attention kept
their court appearances to cameos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magnus Norman, at No. 3 the top seed remaining in the men's
draw, was a model of efficiency in his 6-3, 6-4, 6-3 pummeling of
Cyril Saulnier in the second round. Norman won the Hamlet Cup in
Long Island the week before the Open and said he felt no additional
pressure as the new favorite here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great this week, even though I haven't played a 100
percent yet,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One high-profile player to struggle was sixth-seeded Monica
Seles, who took the full three sets to defeat Chanda Rubin, 6-3,
4-6, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the deciding set, they traded two service breaks each to
leave Seles with a 5-4 lead on serve. A fatigued Seles closed out
the match with a sizzling forehand winner that clipped the line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to get into long points,'' Seles said. ``I just
did not feel my legs at all today. It was really strange.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seles will play 15th-seeded Jennifer Capriati in a history-laden
fourth-round encounter. Seles defeated Capriati in an epic
semifinal on her way to her first Open title in 1991 when both were
precocious teenagers. Burnout later claimed Capriati, and a fan
stabbed Seles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Seles knocked out Capriati in the fourth round.
Capriati has a 3-6 record against Seles. Most of their matches have
been blistering exchanges of ground strokes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the type of game that I like,'' Capriati said.
``Unfortunately, I have the game that she likes, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Capriati was a 6-2, 6-3 winner of Adriana Gersi in 49 minutes,
making brief comments to the press before walking away to see her
boyfriend, Xavier Malisse, defeat Richard Fromberg, 7-6, 4-6, 6-3,
7-6. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other matches involving high-seeded women, No. 8 Nathalie
Tauziat of France beat Janet Lee of Taiwan, 6-3, 6-2, to set up a
match with No. 9 Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, a 7-6, 6-0 winner over
Allison Bradshaw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, eighth-seeded Alex Corretja of Spain swept
Marc Rosset of Switzerland, 6-3, 7-6 (4), 6-3 and 14th-ranked
Nicolas Kiefer of Germany also required the minimum three sets to
oust Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden, 6-1, 6-4, 6-3.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin, unseeded and the 1999 Open runner-up to Agassi,
escaped the steamy conditions with a 6-4, 6-2, 6-4 win over the
baseline veteran Michael Chang. Martin had lost to Chang in five of
six previous matches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the match gone on, it would have gotten more difficult,''
Martin said. ``I was really on my game. It only helped me and it
hurt Michael.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Moya topped Slava Dosedel, 6-3, 4-6, 7-5, 6-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a minor upset on the women's side, Magui Serna of Spain beat
13th-seeded Amanda Coetzer of South Africa, 7-5, 7-6 (3).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
