<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8861 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WHITE-DW&AMP;K-$AD     09-01 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WHITE-DW&AMP;K-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: EDWARD WHITE OF GW&AMP;K EQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward White is passionate about his golf game. ``Hitting a tiny
ball one-eighth of a mile and having it land where you want takes
incredible skill,'' White said. With a handicap of 12, he is no
Tiger Woods. ``If I weren't so busy managing money,'' he said of
his time-consuming job running the $91.7 million GW&AMP;K Equity fund,
``I could get it down to a 4 or 5.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has certainly beaten par for his investors. The fund
returned 27.37 percent a year, on average, for the three years
through Aug. 31, according to Morningstar Inc., putting it in first
place in its peer group of large value funds, which returned 9.68
percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   White, 56, uses a bottom-up investment strategy, and balances
the fund's big blue-chip companies with lesser-known, smaller
companies with market capitalizations of $250 million to $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is less efficient with companies that aren't in the
radar scope of most Wall Street analysts, because their market caps
or revenues are too small,'' White said from his Boston office,
which overlooks the Charles River. ``That's where we find future
all-stars when they're still draft choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Although classified as a large value fund, GW&AMP; K combines value
plays, defined as attractive businesses that sell at discounted
price-to-earnings or price-to-book multiples to the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500, with growth companies, those with rising earnings or
sales. And it holds both large and small companies.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity in styles, sectors and company sizes helps the
odds that the fund will perform well in all types of markets, White
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, Welsh &AMP; Kotler, the fund's sponsor, manages $3.7
billion, primarily for wealthy individuals. The fund was created in
1996 from a limited partnership the company started in 1991 to
invest clients' annual gifts to their children, grandchildren or
others. In June, it added two more funds: GW&AMP;K Small-Cap Growth and
Large-Cap Growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the Equity fund, White starts by screening the nation's
roughly 10,000 publicly traded companies for those with revenue
growth of at least 10 percent a year and above-average and rising
profit margins in their industry. That whittles his universe to
about 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Then he works with four analysts to review company fundamentals
and to pick the fund's 50 or so stocks. His main goal is to
understand why a company is growing consistently and whether it can
keep doing so.
</P>
<P>
   One key is analysis of a company's product. What is its
competitive position? Is its edge based on superior service?
Design? Technology? Or is the company just lucky? To get answers,
White talks to customers, competitors and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Company management is also important, especially among smaller
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger companies like Merck and Pepsi-Cola have deep
management teams, and they're constantly quizzed by analysts,'' he
said. ``In the small-cap world, those checks and balances are
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   He examines how companies reflect two modern themes:
Productivity enhancements of the technology revolution, and
transfer of wealth to baby boomers as their parents age.
</P>
<P>
   Technology accounts for the largest percentage of the fund, at
28.4 percent of assets, but White says, ``I've never bought a
dot-com stock.'' He prefers companies that provide Internet
infrastructure, like semiconductor, data storage and fiber optics
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps a sharp eye on prices. While he generally wants a
company to have a price-to-earnings ratio no higher than its
earnings growth rate, he may pay up to twice that rate for a
business that is growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   White buys stocks with the goal of holding them at least five
years, but he may sell if profit margins stop expanding or because
of deteriorating company or industry fundamentals. The turnover
rate is a relatively low 30 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   White likes Equity Office Properties, a real estate investment
trust in Chicago that owns and operates Class A office space
nationwide, mainly in Boston, Washington, New York and San
Francisco, where demand is particularly strong. He bought shares in
June, when its price fell to $24.28 because of rising interest
rates. He got a close-up view of its operations when it bought the
Boston building where he works; he learned, for example, that
management offered tenants good deals from telephone, Internet and
other service providers. In 1999, the REIT's revenue rose 15.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The stock now trades at $29.00, or 10.2 times his 2001 earnings
projection of $2.85 a share. His 12-month price target for the
stock is $36.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Techne Corp., a science and biotechnology
company in Minneapolis. Techne makes cytokines, blood substances
that help regulate the immune system, he said. It markets them to
biotechnology and drug companies for research, drug development and
drug delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has tremendous potential to help find better drugs and
better ways to get them to the right part of the body,'' he said,
praising the chief executive, Thomas Oland, as a ``deeply committed
scientist.'' The company's revenue grew 35.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares in February at about $75.25. They now trade at
$101.88, or 82.2 times his estimated earnings of $1.24 a share for
the year ending in June 2001. His 12-month price target is $180.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes AES Corp., an independent power producer based in
Arlington, Va. He bought shares in 1991 at about $4.50 after
federal deregulation of the power industry.
</P>
<P>
   AES builds relatively small power plants in developing
communities and for isolated manufacturing or commercial
facilities. White likes the company's management, adding that
environmental safety was among its primary concerns. Revenue grew
35.7 percent in 1999. The shares are now at $67.00, or 45 times his
projected 2001 earnings of $1.49 a share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
