<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MISSILE-GEORGETOWN-NY     09-01 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-GEORGETOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHOSE FRIENDLY PLACE FOR MISSILE-DEFENSE ANNOUNCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MISSILE-DEFENSE and related stories) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a well-known member of Georgetown University's
class of 1968, President Clinton has proudly shown his allegiance
to the school during the last eight years, speaking on campus 12
times.
</P>
<P>
   As governor of Arkansas, he spoke on campus four times. He also
appeared on campus the day before his inauguration in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, when Clinton and his advisers needed a comfortable
environment to make a major announcement on the future of the
national missile defense program, there was one safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   The president decided on the site during his flight from
Cartagena, Colombia, to Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A White House aide said that Clinton had considered speaking
before one of the many foreign policy organizations here, but was
worried that news of the event might leak to the media. The
president was confident, the aide said, that Georgetown would keep
the engagement quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The president has found Gaston Hall, a large lecture hall with
stained glass windows and vaulting supports, to be a perfect
auditorium: cozy, dignified and easy to fill with a friendly
audience. The auditorium is in leafy Healy Circle, an area on the
front side of campus where students often congregate.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken on serious topics at Gaston Hall, including the
world AIDS crisis, social security reform and youth violence.
Clinton also spoke at the memorial service for Lane Kirkland,
president of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to 1995, at the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, before nearly 800 people, including many students and
faculty, Clinton recalled his early days on campus, where he was
elected president of his freshman and sophomore classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 35 years ago when, as a sophomore, I was in charge of
the freshmen orientation,'' Clinton said. ``So I thought I should
come and help this year's orientation of freshmen get off to a good
start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
