<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-1ST     09-01 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BRISTOL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE AWARDS CONNECTICUT COMPANY $1 MILLION IN MICROSOFT LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to expand and update earlier version.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questioning the truthfulness of statements made by Microsoft's
chairman, Bill Gates, a federal judge has awarded $1 million in
punitive damages to a small Connecticut company that brought an
antitrust suit against Microsoft..
</P>
<P>
   The ruling late Thursday in Bridgeport, Conn., was hailed as a
vindication by the plaintiff, Bristol Technologies. Bristol was the
developer of a ``software bridge'' intended to ease the creation of
programs that could run on both the Unix operating system and
Microsoft's industrial-strength counterpart, Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   The company accused Microsoft of an unfair effort to change the
terms of their business relationship after Windows NT gained a
foothold in the market and Microsoft lost its incentive to foster
the use of Unix.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, a jury found that Microsoft committed a deceptive
act that violated the Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices Act, but
rejected the rest of Bristol's case. And rather than the hundreds
of millions of dollars in damages that Bristol sought, it awarded
the company just $1. Microsoft executives at the time hailed the
jury's finding and minimal fine as a validation of the company's
business practices.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Janet C. Hall, who was permitted to award punitive
damages under last year's verdict, ruled Thursday that the
deceptive conduct in which Microsoft had engaged ``rises to the
level of reckless and wanton indifference to the harm it caused
Bristol and others.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she noted that a $1 million penalty against a
company like Microsoft, with $14.5 billion in revenue last year,
would be unlikely to deter it in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Connecticut ruling is another legal problem for
Microsoft, which is appealing the landmark antitrust case brought
by the Justice Department and 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given Microsoft's resources, this is an extraordinarily
light-handed sanction,'' said William Kovacic, a professor at the
George Washington University law school. ``But it is something that
Microsoft must continue to watch. It's conceivable that the state
courts will pay close attention to her findings.'' Microsoft faces
a number of class-action suits by consumers in the wake of the
federal antitrust decision in April.
</P>
<P>
   Hall specified that the decision in the Justice Department case
was not relevant to the issues at the heart of the Bristol case.
But she was critical of Microsoft's business practices, asserting
that Gates gave an intentionally false statement during a 1996
speech in which he assured other software companies and customers
that Microsoft would continue to provide its latest products for
conversion to Unix programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stripped from the veil of Microsoft's protestations that it
merely engaged in highly competitive behavior,'' she wrote,
Microsoft's deceptive statements ``are, at their core, like a
classic bait-and-switch tactic'' against independent software
vendors, developers and ``Unix users whom Microsoft sought to
convert to Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Bristol said that when renegotiating the contract
for its link-up software, Microsoft did offer Bristol a new
license, but charged four times the previous price and granted far
less access to Microsoft technology.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said Friday that the company planned to
appeal the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Bristol, a small software company based in
Danbury, Conn., said that based on the Bridgeport ruling, the
company planned to ask for a new trial. ``This is a vindication
that we were right,'' said Jean Blackwell, Bristol's vice president
for sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Bristol lawyer said Microsoft might find itself
in a more difficult position in a European Commission antitrust
investigation into the company's business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling is a brief to the European Commission,'' said the
lawyer, Patrick Lynch. ``It involves exactly the area where they
have focused their investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol entered into a contract with Microsoft between 1994 and
1997 under which Microsoft was to provide Bristol with access to
the programmers' instructions for an early version of Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   But as Microsoft's power in that marketplace began to grow, the
company had less interest in letting companies like Bristol develop
products that would ease the integration between Windows and Unix,
which had gained an earlier foothold.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling Thursday, the judge cited a 1994 open letter by a
Microsoft manager stating the company's commitment to make its
application program interfaces ``universally available'' for Unix
computer systems. Application program interfaces are the keys to an
operating system that enable programmers to make their software run
efficiently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
