<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SINGAPORE-SPEAKERS-CO     09-01 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGAPORE-SPEAKERS-CORNER-ART-915&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CONTROLLED SOCIETY, A CONTROLLED EXPERIMENT IN FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Late at night, when he hoped nobody was looking, Ong
Chin Guan said, he scouted the scene and hid an old wooden drawer
in the bushes. He had already told his boss he would not be coming
to work Friday. And he had whispered his plans to a few trusted
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, all my friends kept a distance from me,'' said
Ong, 38, who drives a bus for a living. ``They didn't call me the
whole week. Most of my friends, they were afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ong was undaunted. When the sun came up Friday morning, he
pulled his old drawer from the bushes, placed it squarely in the
center of Hong Lim Park, climbed up onto it and began to speak.
</P>
<P>
   His subject was the declining birthrate in Singapore, but that
didn't really matter, even to Ong. What mattered was that _
trembling a little and smiling nervously _ he had become one of the
first citizens of Singapore to speak out legally in public without
a permit.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, as the sun grew hot, then faded again on the other
side of the tiny park, more men climbed onto stools, benches and
plastic milk crates to speak their minds and inaugurate Singapore's
new experiment in free speech: Speakers' Corner.
</P>
<P>
   Some spoke about the issues of the day as small clumps of people
listened: high government salaries, low birthrates, immigration _
and free speech. Some shared with the public their personal
grievances: a contract dispute, a delayed pension payment, an
irritating son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   All knew they were making history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came because I feel proud to be a Singaporean,'' said Ong,
who described himself as ``just a man in the street, a Tom, Dick
and Harry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really opening up,'' he said. ``We are globalizing. And
now we are one of the few countries in the world to have a
Speakers' Corner. Do you have a Speakers' Corner in America?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though its name suggests the Speakers Corner in London's
Hyde Park, there may not be another public forum quite like the one
in Singapore. From now on, it is to be open every day from 7 a.m.
to 7 p.m., but only to people who show their identification cards
and register first with the police. Their names are posted on the
police station wall and will remain on file for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers are not to use megaphones or microphones or musical
instruments _ though they are free to bring their own boxes to
stand on _ and they are not to touch on sensitive issues of race,
language or religion.
</P>
<P>
   And they must watch what they say. Speakers here will be
subject, just like everybody else, to the Internal Security Act,
under which they can be jailed without trial as threats to national
security, and to the laws against libel and slander that have been
vigorously employed in Singapore to harass and bankrupt opposition
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ong and his timorous friends, speakers here must also
combat one of the strongest weapons Singapore uses to keep its
people quiet: self-censorship.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted last month by the Chinese-language newspaper
Lianhe Zaobao, 9 out of 10 people said that if they disagreed with
any government policies they would not say so in public. One-third
said they wouldn't even tell their family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends see the opposition politicians prosecuted and they
are afraid,'' Ong said. ``After I come here maybe they will say,
`Wow, you can speak and nothing happened to you!'''
</P>
<P>
   Free speech is a difficult issue for Singapore, a tiny,
multi-ethnic city-state of 4 million people that sees itself as a
sort of gravity-defying bumble bee _ surviving and succeeding
through sheer force of effort and inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   To muffle any ethnic conflicts and build its resource-poor
economy, it has chosen the path of tight government controls on
just about everything, from financial investment to artistic
expression to chewing gum, which is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of these controls are laws and regulations that
include censorship of film, television, publications, music and the
arts. Access to the Internet is controlled and home television
satellite antennas are banned.
</P>
<P>
   The government controls the only television network and the only
newspaper publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   And if Ong had wanted to speak out in public before Friday _ or
if he wished to speak Friday in any place other than Hong Lim Park
_ he would need a special, hard-to-get permit from the police.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an opposition politician, Chee Soon Juan, was jailed
twice for speaking in public without a permit. Among the things he
said: ``It's time to break the atmosphere of fear, to say it's all
right to criticize the government, to hold it accountable for its
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the divide between the government and its critics is
not a wide one in Singapore. Even dissidents like Chee acknowledge
that the ruling party is responsible for the nation's success and
prosperity and seek only careful, incremental changes.
</P>
<P>
   And even the country's rulers _ who hold 81 of the 83 seats in
Parliament _ acknowledge that Singapore must loosen up and lighten
up in order to stay on the crest of an ever-faster-moving and more
flexible economic future.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in their Singaporean way, they are trying to mandate
(and calibrate) free speech, artistic expression, creativity and
risk-taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next decade, we need to think and act like
revolutionaries,'' said Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong in his
National Day speech last month. ``We have to change national and
individual mindsets and attune them to a very different future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The future will not be kind to people and nations that play
safe, as Singapore has come to do, he said. The nation and its
leaders will need a change of mindset every bit as daunting as the
one Ong had to undergo when he dragged his wooden drawer out of the
bushes and climbed onto it this morning to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who acknowledge the need for more free
expression _ like Singapore's creator, Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
_ find it a bit distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, crazy artistes or crazy painters or playwrights who
write trash and pretend that it's art _ we'll just have to put up
with it,'' he said not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the authorities will have to put up with Bellamy Cai, 54, a
graphic designer, who stood on a stool at Speakers' Corner Friday,
waved the morning's newspaper and declared, ``What they do in
parliament, they never fight for the bloody issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Antonio Rio, 67, a former prison guard unhappy with his
pension who complained: ``I wrote to the prime minister in June but
no reply! No reply! No courtesy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Richard Kwek, also 67, a taxi driver, who offered what
sounded like his usual monologue about government misdeeds for free
Friday _ no meter ticking _ and asserted, ``Taxi drivers are 70
percent against the government.''
</P>
<P>
   They will have to contend, too, with a new generation of
political activists who are already working for more openness. One
of these is James Gomez, 35, who recently self-published _ and got
away with it _ a slim book called ``Self Censorship: Singapore's
Shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez arrived Friday at Speakers' Corner as the shadows were
lengthening in the late afternoon, bringing with him several even
younger idealists who are helping him create an on-line discussion
network called Think Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we celebrate Speakers' Corner as a psychological
lightening of the restrictions on free speech, let's keep it in
perspective,'' Gomez said. ``What we need is more opposition in
parliament, a repeal of restrictions on free speech, more
independent institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, he said, he was happy to accept any opening
the government provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's come here and exercise our right to free speech,'' he
said, ``and get over our fear of public speaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
