u f BC-MARKET-655&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      09-01 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS AND BONDS RISE SLIGHTLY AFTER LATEST REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock and bond prices rose only slightly Friday, even
after new reports indicated that the economy was slowing enough to
preclude another interest-rate increase by the Federal Reserve
Board in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said that new jobs, excluding laid-off
census workers and strikers, were created at a much slower pace in
August and that there was a small rise in the unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management reported a
decline in its factory index.
</P>
<P>
   More important, these reports came on top of other economic data
and warnings of lower profits and slower revenue growth from some
retailers and technology companies that all reflect a slowing
economy. Based on some of this earlier data, Federal Reserve
policy-makers had already decided to leave their benchmark
short-term interest rate unchanged at 6.5 percent when they met a
week and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts still disagree, it seems that many investors
now think that the Fed has finished raising interest rates in its
effort to slow economic growth and curb inflationary pressure. This
is the feeling despite the Fed policy-makers having said after
their last meeting that they were still worried about inflationary
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The new data, said Richard E. Cripps, chief market strategist at
Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore, ``just highlighted the idea
that the Fed is out of the market as a factor for the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But because both the stock and the bond markets have rallied as
this view formed over the last few weeks, the reaction on Friday
was muted.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of July, the Nasdaq composite index had climbed
11.7 percent before trading Friday, while the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 6.6 percent and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
increased 6.1 percent. In the bond market, the yield on the 10-year
Treasury note, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, had already dropped to 5.72 percent on Thursday from just
above 6 percent at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the bond market closed early for the Labor Day
weekend, and many were watching stocks from the beach _ also
contributing to the muted response. Volume on the New York Stock
Exchange was 768.45 million shares, well below the year's average
of about a billion shares a day. ``You would have expected to have
seen some profit-taking after a good month and a long weekend ahead
of you,'' Cripps said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which performed best of the major indexes, rose
27.98 points Friday, or 0.67 percent, to 4,234.33. The Dow
industrials climbed 23.68 points, or 0.21 percent, to 11,238.78,
and the S&AMP;P 500 rose 3.09 points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,520.77. All
three indexes gave up much of the gains they had made early in the
day. Market breadth was positive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the S&AMP;P is now just under seven points from its all-time
high and the Dow is 484 points below its record. The Nasdaq, which
had suffered most from the technology sell-off earlier this year,
has rebounded somewhat and needs to add a further 814 points to
match its record. For the year, the Nasdaq is now up 4.06 percent,
while the S&AMP;P 500 has climbed 3.51 percent. The Dow is still off
2.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the yield on the 10-year Treasury note slipped to 5.68
percent from 5.72 percent on Thursday _ its lowest since July 1999.
The price rose 10/32, to 100 18/32.
</P>
<P>
   Some technology and oil stocks led the market higher Friday.
Hewlett-Packard rose $4.25, to $125.25, while Texaco climbed 71
cents to $52.21. The telecommunications company Global Crossing
jumped by $5.06, to $35.13, after it raised its sales forecast for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial stocks finished lower, led by J.P. Morgan, down
$7.50 to $159.69. Viant, a Web-site designer, plunged by $5.69, to
$8.19, after reporting that it expects a third-quarter loss because
companies are reassessing their Internet strategies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After excluding the layoff of temporary census workers and those
on strike against Verizon, nonfarm payrolls rose by 140,000 in
August, well below the 222,000 average for the first seven months
of the year. There was a surprising drop of 79,000 manufacturing
jobs, while construction employment remained flat. The unemployment
rate inched up to 4.1 percent from 4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management reported that
its factory index dropped to 49.5 in August from 51.8 in July.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Berner, the chief U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said the data ``has a soft tone to it'' and this indicated
that third-quarter growth was going to be slower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   But he maintained that ``by and large the economy is doing quite
well, despite these numbers.'' And he was not ready to declare that
the Federal Reserve has finished raising interest rates, in part
because of inflationary effects from the sharp rise in energy
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Cripps also warned that if the economy continued to slow,
corporate earnings would become a concern for investors. The first
two quarters of this year have seen extraordinary earnings growth,
of over 20 percent. But ``earnings numbers are going to decelerate
along with the economy,'' Cripps said. ``This fact hasn't hit the
broad market as yet. But it could if the slowdown continues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
