u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-01 1728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS MIGHT REGRET ALCANTARA MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox have had a lot of things go wrong this year, but the
worst could turn out to be Jimy Williams stuffing Izzy Alcantara in
the closet for seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara returned to the scene of his embarrassment Friday
night after ripping the cover off the ball in Pawtucket, while
almost everyone in the Boston lineup was floundering. How ironic
was it that on Wednesday night in Tampa, when the Red Sox were
being humbled by Albie Lopez (a four-hitter), Izzy was knocking
them dizzy with a winning homer for the Pawsox, his 29th home run
of the season in just 299 at-bats. That's one home run for every 10
at-bats. At that pace, if he didn't sit for seven weeks in Boston
while Williams ignored him, Izzy would be on a pace to hit more
than 50 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is the present Red Sox team can't hit and here
you have a guy who can help them sitting in the minors because he
upset the manager when he loafed in a game in Chicago. When he
first came up, general manager Dan Duquette talked to Williams
about the move. Williams agreed with it, saying the club needed
more hitting. However, Duquette told Williams Izzy was out of
options and that he would have to stay in Boston. Duquette did not
want to put Alcantara on waivers and risk losing him to another
team. He said at the time that Izzy had value and he was right.
This is why he wasn't shipped back to Pawtucket when Williams got
mad at him. Instead, he sat for seven weeks until the Red Sox could
send him back with a ``medical rehabilitation'' designation that
protected him until they could bring him back Friday when the
rosters could be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Sox miss the playoffs by a game or two, they'll have
to look back at that handling of Alcantara, who can certainly hit
better than several players currently in their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vote is unanimous for Indianapolis. The four rival AFC East
coaches pick the Colts as the team to beat in the division this
year, while Jim Mora thinks the Buffalo Bills could be the best
team in the AFC. ``I said at the end of last season that Buffalo
was the best team in the AFC and I meant it,'' said Mora, the
Colts' head coach. ``And I think they will be one of the best teams
in the league again this year. If they hadn't lost that crazy
playoff game in Tennessee, I think they would have gone on to the
Super Bowl. Buffalo has a dominating defense, a good offensive
line, solid running backs, and a good quarterback situation. I
don't think the guys they lost (Andre Reed, Thurman Thomas, and
Bruce Smith) will hurt them. They'll have some other guys ready to
step in and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Bill Belichick thinks that Indianapolis first,
and Buffalo next, have to be considered favorites in the division.
``Those are the two teams that have continuity,'' he said. ``The
Colts won it. They have the same (running) back and the same
players. Buffalo hasn't changed much. The rest of us, here, Miami,
and the Jets, all have new coaching staffs and are in transition.
No one knows what will happen until we start playing. But you have
to like Indy's chances going into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Groh, Jets: ``The Colts should be favored. They have
tremendous firepower on offense. They have the confidence of
winning it last year and playing sound football the whole season.
It seems, in recent years, a team gets close, misses, and then
comes back even stronger the next year. Buffalo still is strong.
They've made a lot of (roster) changes and have a lot of young
players, but they will be tough to beat. I like our team here. We
should be good on offense, right from the start. How well we do
will depend on how we play defense in the early part of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade Phillips, Buffalo: ``No doubt the Colts are the team to
beat. They won it last year and have the same team back. But I
think we can give them a run for their money. If (quarterback) Rob
Johnson can play the way he did in preseason and play the way we
feel he can, we will be very good. I'm optimistic about our team.
Something like 40 percent of the players on the roster are either
first- or second-year players, but we have a good group of starters
and a winning tradition up here that will help us. I think we'll be
very good on defense and our offense should be better than it has
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he doesn't expect Doug Flutie to be able to play
for another month. ``We have three games and then a bye week. I
think Doug will be back after the bye week. There's no sense in
rushing him. He hurt (his groin) pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie tore the muscle away from the bone and this type of
injury is not corrected by surgery, so Flutie will have to wait
until it heals on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wannstedt, Miami: ``The Colts have such a great offense you
have to like them. In our division, the strength of every other
team looks like it will be on defense. Buffalo, Patriots, us, are
all better on defense. We've got seven new guys in our offensive
lineup this year so it could take us a while to get going. Injuries
will be a key. All any team has to do, no matter how good they are,
is get a couple of key injuries and that changes the whole
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora says the balance of power has definitely swung to the AFC
and the numbers back him up. ``The AFC is the dominant of the two.
The better teams are over here,'' he said. ``This is the second
year in a row everyone in our division went through the preseason
without a losing record. We're the only division that has done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '99 season, the AFC beat the NFC in head-to-head
games by a wide margin, plus 17, and added to the trend by whipping
them, 37-14, this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's almost 40 going on 25. Ray Bourque, who has the look of
someone 15 years younger, is preparing to head for Colorado and
what he feels could be ``the'' year with the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very excited about this season because I think we can go
all the way,'' he said. ``It's not one of these situations where
you go into a season and you think, `Well, if we overachieve, we
might have a real good season. This team (Colorado) has the talent
to win the Cup. We just have to play to that talent. So it's
exciting for me to think about that, and get started into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, one of the best-conditioned athletes in any sport, is
giving it everything he has to prepare for the season. In recent
years, he has used Mike Boyle's workout program during the summers.
This year, he is using Boyle, formerly of Boston University, one of
the most respected athletic trainers in this part of the country.
``Ray is unique,'' said Boyle. ``He is in here at 8:30 in the
morning and he wants to do everything a kid 20 years younger than
him can do. There is nothing he won't do. Even at his age, he is
preparing himself to play 30 minutes a game in the National Hockey
League. When he comes to the gym, he never acts like a superstar.
He is always quiet, polite, he doesn't want to be treated any
differently than anyone else. Even after he goes through a real
difficult program in the morning with us, I know he works out again
in the evening at home, riding a bike or doing some cardiovascular
work.'' Bourque still intends to make his home in the Boston area
when he is finished playing, but will take his two sons with him to
Colorado for this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Donna Harris-Lewis put out the story that she lost more
than $2 million in her first failed trial against Dr. Gilbert
Mudge, we said it was bogus _ and it was. Now comes Bogus II. After
failing for a second time to win a lawsuit against Mudge, whom she
claims was responsible for her husband's death, her attorneys now
claim in papers filed in court that she lost $1.5 million the
second go-round. That's also bogus. Harris-Lewis, who received more
than $12 million from insurance companies after her husband Reggie,
a former Celtics star, dropped dead of a heart attack, must think
people are going to feel sorry for her when they are not. You could
put the expenses of both trials together and they wouldn't come to
$1 million. Both lawyers, Robert Hartley of New York in the first
trial and Neil Rossman of Boston in the second, worked on a
contingency basis. When she didn't win, they didn't win. The court
stenographers walked away with more money than her lawyers, who
both put on great trials. They just didn't win. Harris-Lewis fouled
it up twice herself. Both times she reportedly had the chance to
settle for more than a million dollars and gambled on winning the
bigger bucks. She lost. Now she is at it again, trying to get
permission to put the matter before an Appeals Court, even though
Rossman told her there was nothing to appeal. This is when she went
looking for a third set of lawyers. It would be great to see the
judge who is going to hold the initial hearing ask her to bring in
her financial records to show how she spent all this money on legal
fees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Edelstein said in his pro football letter this week that
Drew Bledsoe may be traded to the Seattle Seahawks next year. It's
not going to happen. Edelstein, who is tight with Bledsoe's agent,
Leigh Steinberg, paints this scenario: Bledsoe has just two years
left on his contract and he carries a big salary-cap number ($8.8
million this year and $9.3 million next year), which would lead the
Patriots to trading him. However, as long as Bob Kraft owns the
team, Bledsoe will be with the Patriots. Steinberg is trying to use
the media to leverage a new deal. He tried to work out a new
contract with the Patriots and he wanted too much money. Kraft will
wait it out, and if he can't make what he feels is a reasonable new
deal for Bledsoe, then he will designate him as the ``franchise''
player, which will keep him with the team after this contract
expires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Observers of the Pawtucket club can't understand why the Sox
didn't call for Sang Lee earlier. Lee was 5-2 at Pawtucket, struck
out 71 batters in 96 innings, and was untouchable in August with a
0.59 ERA for the month. And he's a lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will McDonough is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
mcdonough(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
