<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: MILLER ASIDE, A WILD YEAR IN THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This little tidbit comes from the comedian Dennis Miller, who as
the new analyst for ``Monday Night Football'' has gotten more press
than Al Gore. It definitely falls under the category of too much
information. When asked what's the biggest thing he has learned
since getting his new gig, Miller responded, ``I learned that when
I have to take a whiz, I have to go in a thermos jug.''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Dennis. Even my new puppy can hold it for a couple of
hours. Can't you break away from the game during one of those
fifteen television timeouts?
</P>
<P>
   When Miller _ someone who has never played the game, never
coached it, never covered it and can't even figure out a way to
work in a potty break during a measly three-hour telecast _ is one
of the biggest stories of the upcoming NFL year, the season is
either going to be very boring or very interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to your trusty football expert _ it will be the latter.
This might be one of the most exhilarating seasons ever, better
than last year, when the Rams became the first team in league
history to go from last in its division to Super Bowl champion.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 season begins on Sunday, and never has the sport been
so wide open. Any team can win, and an abundance of good stories
are circulating like a Miller joke on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, the best pickup for the Rams was Trung Canidate,
who will spell running back Marshall Faulk. The rookie with the
election-sounding name will end up being one of the defending
champions' most valuable players.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles strongly believe they are a playoff
team. They're right.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos think they will win the AFC West. They're
right.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Panthers feel the NFC West can be stolen from the
Rams. They're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson and Terrell Davis, two stars coming off knee
injuries, will each gain more than 1,300 yards. Edgerrin James in
Indianapolis will get 1,500. Stephen Davis in Washington will have
1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins owner Daniel Snyder will explode by Week 5, and coach
Norv Turner will be on the Dallas sideline by next season. Wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson will be lobbying the Buccaneers' brass to
trade for Jets backup thrower Ray Lucas by the first week of
October.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville's Tom Coughlin will win nine games this year, quit,
and then coach Notre Dame for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets will start 0-2 and then make the playoffs. Despite
their denials, quarterback Vinny Testaverde and Jets coach Al Groh
have already gotten into at least one argument. That's a fact. Bill
Parcells will coach again, probably in Miami. That's a fantasy _
for Dolphins fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' Ron Dayne is privately miffed at fan and media
reaction over his slow preseason start. Tiki Barber will be the
team's offensive MVP. Michael Strahan will have 12 sacks. Kerry
Collins will throw only eight interceptions and coach Jim Fassel
will get a two-year contract extension after making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens' Ray Lewis, who didn't have a pleasant
off-season, will lead all linebackers in tackles, sacks, and
interceptions, and be named the league's defensive MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer remains bitter with Bill Walsh for calling him the
next Joe Montana, saying it is a weight on his shoulders he did not
need or want. Peyton Manning is the next Montana, and Ryan Leaf is
still a dud.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo linebacker Sam Cowart is the best player no one has ever
heard of.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And what would an NFL season be without a few players in trouble
with the law? Oakland signed Andre Rison this week, despite the
fact the wide receiver faces legal problems in four states. They
include allegedly writing $158,000 in bad checks to a jewelry store
in Missouri, giving police a fake name after a bar fight in
Wisconsin, owing $34,000 in child support to a son which might lead
to garnished wages in California, and a trial on felony charges
that he took $1,000 in recording equipment from a Kansas music
store. One more state and Rison would qualify for frequent flyer
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a beautiful father, and I've got a beautiful life,'' he
said. ``I'm not saying I'm a saint. I'm not saying I'm perfect. And
I'm not saying I'm wrong. But I am a Raider.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be a good season.
</P>
<P>
   So this weekend when heading for that friend's house to grill,
to the parking lot to tailgate, brace yourself for what will be a
fascinating year, and remember to pack the thermos jugs. Just make
sure they're empty first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
