</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BJT-ADVISORY-STILTSVILLE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post story slugged STILTSVILLE will not move this
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8878 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ILL-RICHES-SCHEME-2ND     09-01 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-RICHES-SCHEME-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MATTOON, Ill.: receive $255,000.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that for years, Hood had an investor phone line
with recorded messages saying the payoff was just around the corner
and blaming the delay on bankers or the government.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a classic Ponzi scheme, where early investors make a
profit so that they will help entice other investors, Omega
investors never made any money, prosecutors say. But, partly
because of the fund's Christian overtones, many investors, some of
whom planned on using the money for charity, apparently still
believe that Omega will pay off, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Stark, of Apple Valley, Calif., said she invested $1,600
in 1998, sending money orders to Diamond for forwarding to Hood.
She thought she would receive $5,100 for every $100 in two months.
She said Diamond told her, `` `Everything is going well and be
patient.' She was very, very nice, always a delight to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said she knew about 20 people in her community who had
invested with Omega, most of them Christians like her. ``I hold no
animosity,'' she said of Hood and Diamond. ``It saddens me they
have to sit in jail. Their lives are spoiled by their greed.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation progressed, Hawaii and Missouri issued
cease-and-desist orders to keep Omega from marketing itself there.
Yet the fund continued to solicit investors in those states,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mattoon, sometimes called Toon Town, people watched the
sprouting of places like the Bluebird Diner, made from three shiny
silver trailers and positively dazzling by Mattoon standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they built the Bluebird Diner, we thought they must have
been doing better than we thought,'' said Shelli Kaczmarek, a
manager at Gill's. ``Me, my husband and 3-year-old paid $20 there
for breakfast. I can feed my whole family, all four of my kids, on
that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Chris Engel, a construction contractor whose business is
accused of funneling some $6 million of Hood's money, prospered
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not like New York, where a construction company with a
fleet of 40 or 50 new vehicles, people probably wouldn't think that
much about it,'' said the police chief, David O'Dell, who said the
last time the town faced a scandalous crime was the 1968 murder of
five children by a jilted boyfriend. We're a small town. It was
just obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Mattoon has come down hard on Hood and his
accused co-conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   At Jimmy John's sandwich shop, which prosecutors say the former
police officer and a lawyer bought with Hood's money, Seth
Wilcoxon, the manager, said, ``The owners weren't aware of where
the money was coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   And Melissa Yates, a secretary at Our Own Original Bakery, which
never became a bakery but served as an office for Hood, said, ``All
I know is that he has done a lot for this community. He has helped
hundreds of people around here, even strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Morgan, a 52-year-old retired trucker having a chili
mac under the I Love Lucy poster at Gill's, was feeling embarrassed
for Mattoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of hurts the reputation of the community,'' he said.
``Especially people that you've knowed, involved in something like
this. It kind of makes you wonder if you can trust your next door
neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Securities and Exchange Commission warned
investors not to participate in such schemes, called bank debenture
scams, in which con artists exploit suspicions about the government
and financial institutions. The schemers tell investors that there
is a secret banking system open only to the very rich which
provides huge returns but they can participate if they pool their
money with someone who has an ``in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
