</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCEPT OF U.S. MISSILE SHIELD HAS LONG HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MISSILE-DEFENSE and related stories) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dream of a defense against ballistic missiles goes all the
way back to the Eisenhower era. But it was in the thunder and flame
of the Gulf War, the world's first antimissile war, that support
grew for the kind of system that the Clinton administration has
been considering.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republicans won control of Congress six years ago,
momentum to field such a weapon grew rapidly. By 1996 the
administration began an effort to ready a limited missile defense
for deployment, its price tag eventually put at $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The range of its nonnuclear warhead was to be much greater than
that of the old ground-based interceptors, because it was
``smart,'' small and lightweight. In theory at least, such
interceptors at a single base could, for the first time, race out
of their silos to defend the whole nation from an attack of up to a
few dozen warheads.
</P>
<P>
   After being launched into space by a rocket, the so-called
Exo-Atmospheric Kill Vehicle was to guide itself toward a target,
using its tiny computer to analyze sensor readings and fire
thrusters.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the big challenge was whether it could ignore
the decoys amid the nuclear warheads that an enemy would inevitably
deploy in a bid to outwit the defense system. The sensor was to be
smart enough to find the real warhead amid the clutter, seeking out
its heat rays. Then, zipping along at about 2 miles per second, the
kill vehicle was to slam into the warhead and demolish it.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including some from the antimissile industry itself,
said the plan would never work.
</P>
<P>
   Test flights began in 1997. Mock warheads were always launched
into space from California and interceptor rockets from Kwajalein
Atoll in the Pacific Ocean. The first two tests studied only sensor
accuracy, the interceptors flying nearby to look at mock warheads
among decoys.
</P>
<P>
   Then came intercept tests, the first last October. The Pentagon
hailed the experiment as an unqualified success but later
acknowledged that the kill vehicle had initially drifted off course
and picked out a decoy balloon rather than the warhead.
</P>
<P>
   In the second test, in January, the interceptor missed the
target altogether because of a sensor coolant leak.
</P>
<P>
   The third intercept try, in July, meant to be the last before
President Clinton's deployment decision, was also a disappointment.
The final stage of the two-stage interceptor failed to release the
kill vehicle, and the two tumbled out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement Friday that he had decided to pass the
contentious issue onto his successor is likely to produce very
different results depending on who wins the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Deploying space arms could cost up to hundreds of billions of
dollars. So far all of the efforts over the decades have been
nothing short of colossal and have cost more than $130 billion,
according to the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, a
private group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The allure of space arms is that they could, in theory, hit
rising missiles in their boost phase before they release payloads
of warheads, chaff, balloons and other decoys, increasing the odds
of success and offering protection against large strikes. But there
are countermeasures, and global coverage could be hard.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a national missile defense began in the late 1950s
when President Eisenhower, facing the prospect of Soviet missile
fleets, embarked on a secretive crash program of antimissile
research that included ideas for space-based arms and in time
involved thousands of the nation's top scientists.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid 1960s, designers had settled on a less ambitious
approach that involved ground-based interceptors tipped with
nuclear arms. In war, these were to thunder out of their
underground silos and race skyward to battle incoming waves of
enemy warheads, in theory incinerating them in nuclear fireballs.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson administration, trying to seize a Republican issue
before the 1968 presidential election, proposed plans for deploying
such interceptors.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Nixon administration that actually built them.
Switched on in North Dakota in October 1975, the Safeguard system
was meant to shield nearby missile fields from a disarming first
strike. But the $25 billion weapon was abandoned after just 133
days as strategists concluded that Moscow could overwhelm it with a
rush of new warheads then being fastened atop new missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of just such costly spirals of antimissile action and
reaction prompted Moscow and Washington in 1972 to sign the
Antiballistic Missile Treaty, which in time limited each side to
one interceptor site. No matter how good the interceptors, experts
reasoned, these single sites would be unable to defend large
territories.
</P>
<P>
   The goal in hobbling defense was to reinforce the idea that all
sides would lose in a nuclear war and thus to deter such an
apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan's Star Wars plan, announced in 1983, meant to
see if enemy missiles could be rendered ``impotent and obsolete.''
The program of crash research pursued weapons that were quite
advanced, including lasers and particle beams, and proposed to base
them in space.
</P>
<P>
   That step sought to extend the antimissile reach beyond the
range of ground-based interceptors and to produce many lines of
defense so in theory a shield might be nearly leakproof, even in a
downpour.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, after many programmatic zigs and zags, and failures, a
less futuristic and more realistic space weapon was proposed.
Called Brilliant Pebbles, it was hailed as being so cheap and small
that up to 100,000 of them could be shot into orbit, always ready
to ruin rising enemy missiles by force of impact.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Cold War ended, political support for such plans
evaporated and all the orbital arms initiatives came crashing back
to Earth after an expenditure of tens of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the Gulf War, when waves of Patriot interceptors
sought to blast short-range Iraqi Scuds out of the sky, did hopes
revive for a missile defense system in the United States. That
fiery duel in the Persian Gulf War helped to build support for more
advanced kinds of ground-based interceptors, including ones for
nationwide defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
