u a BC-LEE-TRIAL-655&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-01 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-TRIAL-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE MOVE BLOCKS RELEASE OF SCIENTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Two federal appeals court judges on Friday
halted the imminent release on bail of Wen Ho Lee, the former Los
Alamos scientist accused of mishandling nuclear weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in Lee's release, which had been scheduled for noon
Friday, was a result of last-minute maneuvers by prosecutors that
provoked charges of deception from defense lawyers at an unusually
emotional court hearing Friday. The prosecutors denied any
deception.
</P>
<P>
   The one-line order from the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in Denver _ ``Release of appellee Wen Ho Lee is stayed pending
further order of this court'' _ came as a district court judge in
Albuquerque was starting to hear arguments on the prosecution's
request that he further delay the release of Lee.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24, the district court judge, James A. Parker, reversed
an earlier order in which he had denied bail to Lee based on the
government's assertions that he posed a grave threat to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent hearing, an FBI agent admitted to having testified
incorrectly on several critical issues, making Lee appear deceptive
when he had not been. Also, defense experts disputed the value of
the secrets Lee is charged with illegally downloading from a
government computer, prompting Parker to order Lee released to home
detention on $1 million bail. The judge had given prosecutors until
noon to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   At the noon hearing Friday, when it was expected that the
government would announce its appeal, a law clerk strode into the
nearly empty courtroom and handed Parker a piece of paper. Upon
reading it, the judge announced that the appeals court had already
issued an order temporarily halting Lee's release, circumventing
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The order, which appeared to have taken the judge and Lee's
lawyers by surprise, was a clear indication of the intensity of the
government's desire to keep Lee imprisoned before his trial, which
is scheduled to begin in November.
</P>
<P>
   John Cline, one of Lee's lawyers, leapt to his feet, and stated,
``If they filed something without telling us, I think it's an
outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cline explained that he had, as is common, insisted that he
receive advance notice of any filing, to give him time to respond,
and said he had understood the prosecutors would do this. That the
prosecutors had apparently done an end run around the defense and
the district court here was, Cline insisted, an abuse of the normal
process, under which the appeal would have been filed only after
Parker had issued his ruling and the hearing here had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Cline said he had already prepared a response to any government
motion to halt Lee's release. The motion was now all but useless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way the system is supposed to work,'' Cline
said, while Lee, sitting a few feet away, grimaced and closed his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Parker responded with the unusual admission that he had planned
to deny the government's request for any further delay in Lee's
release, but that with the appeals court's ruling, it was out of
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not clear to me that this is any longer under this
court's jurisdiction,'' Parker said dryly; then he called a recess.
</P>
<P>
   But the hearing reconvened an hour later, and sparks again flew.
</P>
<P>
   The second hearing had been requested by the lead prosecutor,
George Stamboulidis, to clear up, he said, the impression that he
might have misled the defense or the court.
</P>
<P>
   Stamboulidis explained that the stay, issued by Judges Deanell
R. Tacha and David M. Ebel, was made on the appellate court's
initiative as the noon deadline loomed. He suggested that the stay
had taken him by surprise, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government doesn't play dirty pool,'' Stamboulidis said.
</P>
<P>
   Cline responded: ``What I think Mr. Stamboulidis has said is
half-truths at best. It is part of a pattern of misleading conduct
that, I think, is outrageous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To that, Nancy Hollander, another of Lee's lawyers, explained
that she had just spoken with the clerk of the appeals court in
Denver and had been given a different version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander said she was informed that an official with the
Department of Justice in Washington had called the court earlier in
the day to say that a notice of appeal was being filed shortly in
Albuquerque and Denver along with a request for a stay of Lee's
release until the appeal was heard by a three-judge appeals panel.
The request for a stay was the one that Parker had already said he
was prepared to deny.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander said she had requested and been given an assurance
that she would be informed of any filings by the government and
given a chance to respond. In any case, she said, the appeals court
judges had acted in response to the government's request, not on
their own, as Stamboulidis had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the government circumventing this court and essentially
not being truthful,'' Hollander said.
</P>
<P>
   Stamboulidis rejected that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointment in a result is not justification for taking
shots like that,'' he said. ``There was no sneakiness, no
inappropriateness.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has insisted in several hearings that
Lee was engaged in what amounted to one of the most serious cases
of nuclear espionage ever, he is not charged in the 59-count
indictment with spying. He faces a maximum sentence of life
imprisonment if he is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Later on Friday, Cline and Hollander faxed to the appeals court
a response to the government's actions, noting their anger at what
they said was deceptive behavior that violated some of the court's
own rules. They asked the court to lift the stay.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the court. The appeals
panel is expected to consider motions by the prosecution and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   After expecting to return home for the first time since
December, when he was imprisoned, Lee returned to prison in Santa
Fe. The prosecution has said his confinement, in harsh conditions,
is essential, because of concerns that he might find a way to
spirit nuclear secrets to a hostile country.
</P>
</TEXT>
