<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTINGLY0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP Senate hopeful discloses finances
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a home on St. Simons Island valued at nearly $1
million and a generous federal pension from years in the U.S.
Senate, NATO and a U.S. ambassadorship, Senate candidate Mack
Mattingly holds assets worth as much $2.9 million, according to
disclosures released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year and a half, Mattingly, the leading
Republican candidate to fill the unexpired term of the late Paul
Coverdell, supplemented his $69,000 retirement by consulting for
aeronautical giant Lockheed Martin, earning roughly $108,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly has suspended his consulting work for the company in
connection with construction of the F-22 fighter, the C-130J
transport and other aircraft, forgoing a $6,000 monthly salary,
until the Nov. 7 Senate race is over, his campaign said. He's also
taken a leave of absence from a paying board position on
CompuCredit Corp., a credit card marketing company, and resigned as
chairman of the board of the conservative Southeastern Legal
Foundation to conduct the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures filed Friday paint the picture of a successful
businessman with a stock portfolio mingling standards like
Coca-Cola and General Electric with high-tech leaders like Cisco
Systems and Dell Computers.
</P>
<P>
   But while he's lived a comfortable life since leaving the U.S.
Senate in 1986, Mattingly apparently hasn't been as active in
securing board positions as his rival, Zell Miller, who was
appointed to Coverdell's seat following the senator's death from a
brain hemorrhage in July.
</P>
<P>
   Of Mattingly's nine board memberships, five were non-profits,
another is a Census group and one offered compensation of $250. His
assets are worth between $1.3 and $2.9 million, with income during
the past 19 months of just a little more than $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's disclosures, filed last week, show the former governor
earned more than $680,000 in 1999, the year after he left office,
from work for three colleges, an array of corporate boards and a
consulting arrangement with tobacco company Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must file personal financial disclosures within 30
days of establishing their candidacy _ a threshold they cross,
according to federal standards, by raising or spending $5,000 on
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wood, one of the five other Senate candidates, a
Realtor/owner of an agency, said he will file disclosures early
next week showing about $375,000 in earned income last year and two
businesses worth about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats noted Mattingly took a leave of absence from several
positions rather than severing all ties to outside interests, as
Miller did upon his Senate appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he's only suspended his (consulting) tells me
he's not planning on winning the election,'' said Georgia
Democratic Party Chairman David Worley.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattingly campaign spokesman Bill Wood said Mattingly
already has made preparations to leave the paying boards after
victory in the Nov. 7 non-partisan special election.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
