<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: JUDGE INDICTS ARGENTINE
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon indicted a former Argentine military
officer on charges of genocide, torture and terrorism, acts he said
were committed under Argentina's military government two decades
ago. Garzon, who led a drive to extradite the former Chilean
dictator, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, on human rights charges, acted
after hearing testimony from Argentines in Europe who said they
were tortured by the officer, Ricardo Miguel Cavallo. Cavallo is in
Mexico awaiting possible extradition to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: SPEED BLAMED IN SUBWAY ACCIDENT
</P>
<P>
   The derailment of a Paris subway car on Thursday was probably
due to excessive speed, investigators said, contradicting earlier
reports. The speed limit on the curve leading into the station at
Notre-Dame-de-Lorette was 19 miles an hour, and the train was going
about 22 mph. A national radio station reported that the driver,
still not identified, had been disciplined several times for
speeding. Twenty-four passengers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: ULTIMATUM ON RELIGIOUS IDS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Costas Simitis vowed to press ahead with a
decision to remove religious affiliation from new state identity
cards despite a threat by the Greek Orthodox Church to mount a mass
petition drive for a national referendum on the issue. The church,
which led protest rallies in June, has given the government until
midnight Sept. 14 to begin talks on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: REBELS ASK U.S. FOR RANSOM
</P>
<P>
   A Muslim rebel spokesman demanded a $10 million ransom for
Jeffrey Schilling, 24, an American kidnapped a week ago on a remote
southern island. In a conversation with a government negotiator
broadcast on a local radio station, the spokesman, Abu Sabaya, also
asked for food and medicine to be sent for Schilling, who U.S.
officials say has serious health problems. U.S. officials have
ruled out paying a ransom.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: PRESIDENT PRESSES FOR TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid said the corruption trail of former
President Suharto must proceed even though the former leader failed
to attend its opening, citing ill health. But Wahid repeated his
promise to pardon Suharto, 79, once the trial is completed, ``on
condition he returns all of the wealth he illegally collected
during his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: 19 NAMED IN VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian state prosecutors named 19 civilians and military
officers as suspects in the killings, kidnappings and destruction
that ravaged East Timor last year. The list excluded several
prominent names, most notably the former military commander,
General Wiranto, who was implicated by an earlier fact-finding
commission.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH AND SOUTH KOREA: ACCORD ON MILITARY TALKS
</P>
<P>
   After extending talks in Pyongyang for a fourth day, North and
South Korea agreed to ease tensions on the divided peninsula by
opening a dialogue among military officials, according to a
statement released in Seoul. With the talks under threat of ending
without a significant agreement, South Korea's unification
minister, Pak Chae-kyu, traveled by train to a remote province of
North Korea to meet its leader, Kim Jong-il, a move considered
pivotal in reaching an accord.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: ACCUSATION DENIED
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leader Ranil Wickremesinghe denied accusations
made by President Chandrika Kumaratunga that he knew in advance
about a suicide bomb attack on her last December by separatist
Tamil rebels. Wickremesinghe said the president was trying to smear
him and his party in advance of Oct. 10 parliamentary elections.
``I deny this false allegation completely and without
qualification,'' he said in a letter to Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: VIETNAM RETURNS BODY
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam has handed over to a Canadian family the body of a woman
who was executed in April for drug smuggling. The body of Nguyen
Thi Hiep, a Canadian citizen, was missing an ear, family members
said. Her mother was also released as part of a general amnesty.
Both women were convicted in a trial in Hanoi that Canadian lawyers
say ignored evidence that they were being used as unwitting
couriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
