<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TIRES02-COX     09-01 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds: More Firestone varieties pose 'potential safety risk'
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal officials issued a warning Friday that two dozen more
varieties of Firestone tires may fail at higher rates than the 6.5
million tires that the company voluntarily recalled last month.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said it was
warning consumers of the ``potential safety risk'' after
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. refused Thursday to expand its Aug. 9
recall to include the additional tires.
</P>
<P>
   The government agency said it had met with Firestone officials
Wednesday to recommend that the recall be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone officials said Friday they disagreed with the safety
agency's analysis, but offered to inspect customers' tires and
replace them for free if they are concerned about their safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've said all along, public safety and customer
satisfaction is our top priority. Every possible resource of this
company is aimed at those priorities,'' said Firestone spokeswoman
Chris Karbowiak.
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA said it may order Firestone to recall the tires once
it completes its investigation. The agency has received more than
1,400 complaints about Firestone tires, including reports of 88
deaths that reportedly were the result of blowouts, tread
separation and other defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although its investigation is not complete, that review
indicated that the rate of tread separations for certain other tire
models and sizes exceed those of the recalled tires, sometimes by a
large margin,'' the NHTSA said in its consumer advisory.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory is available on the NHTSA Web site at
www.nhtsa.gov. The Web site includes detailed listings of the tires
subject to the advisory as well as the earlier recall, and a
database of consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The warning covers several varieties of Firestone ATX, Firehawk
ATX, ATX 23 Degree, Widetrack Radial Baja, Wilderness AT and
Wilderness HT tires in sizes ranging from 14 inches to 16.5 inches.
All but three of the additional tires include the plant code ``VD''
for Firestone's Decatur, Ill., plant that has been a focus of the
earlier recall.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.4 million of the tires subject to the advisory were
manufactured from 1991 to present, but far fewer probably remain in
use, the agency said. Most were sold as replacement tires for a
wide variety of vehicles and not originally installed on new
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said Firestone ATX tires included in the advisory
were installed as original equipment on fewer than 10,000 of its
1991-model Chevrolet Blazers. ``It would be highly unusual that any
of the original Firestone tires'' are still in use on those
vehicles,'' said Brook Lindbert, director of GM tire and wheel
systems. He said only two complaints in NHTSA's database of almost
1,500 complaints involve 1991 Chevy Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA officials recommended consumers ``consider replacing the
tires'' and retain their receipts, even though Firestone is not
required to pay for replacing the tires unless a recall is ordered.
The agency also warned drivers to take precautions such as
monitoring the tires' condition and air pressure, and avoiding
driving at high speeds, particularly on hot days or in an
overloaded vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone officials estimated that fewer than half of the tires
are still in use, and said it will inspect, fix and replace tires
at its company-owned Firestone Tire and Service Centers or at
authorized dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if there is a problem, we will fix it,''
Firestone's Karbowiak said. ``If a customer is still concerned
about their tires, we will replace the tires at no cost to the
customers. We will use competitors' products if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA advisory comes as a growing number of consumer safety
advocates and attorneys have called for Firestone to expand its
voluntary recall beyond three types of 15-inch ATX, ATX II and
Wilderness AT tires that were installed mostly on Ford
sport-utility vehicles and pickups, as well as on some Mercury and
Mazda vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the 47 million ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT
tires are covered by the recall. Firestone estimates about 6.5
million are still on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The NHTSA said it is investigating all those tires, plus other
models on which it has received complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The recalled models are all P235/75 R15 Firestone ATX and ATX II
tires made since 1991 and P235/75R15 Wilderness AT tires
manufactured since 1996 at Firestone's Decatur plant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
