<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts, travel, financial and style articles this week
for release Sunday, September 3, 2000. If you have questions about
stories, call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (moving in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-FIENNES-THEATER (London) _ It is almost a rite of
passage for promising Shakespearean actors to play ``Hamlet.'' More
than most, though, Ralph Fiennes seemed made for the part. To
Jonathan Kent, the slim, ascetic-looking Englishman was born to
play the ill-fated monarch in Shakespeare's ``Richard II.'' To this
fairly obvious choice, however, Kent, an artistic director at
London's Almeida Theater Company, added a more innovative idea. Why
not twin ``Richard II'' with ``Coriolanus,'' another Shakespearean
political tragedy. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   CORIOLANUS-THEATER (New York) _ Among Shakespeare's tragic
heroes, Coriolanus stands apart. The others seduce us. This one _
Rome's greatest warrior turned Rome's fiercest scourge _ scorns
even to try. Perhaps the Almeida Theater Company's production of
``Coriolanus,'' directed by Jonathan Kent, which comes to the
Brooklyn Academy of Music for a limited run beginning September 9,
will challenge entrenched opinion. The title role is entrusted to
Ralph Fiennes, the protagonist also of the Almeida's ``Richard
II,'' that will alternate with ``Coriolanus.'' By Matthew
Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SONGWRITERS-THEATER (New York) _ There are many ways a
songwriter today can be unfashionable. Choosing to write for the
American musical theater is merely one of the surer routes. Though,
even here, different songwriters go about being unfashionable in
entirely different ways. Take Michael John LaChiusa and John
Bucchino. Both write songs in the classic Broadway manner as
descended from the American popular songbook. Beyond this
commonality, however, their work is strikingly dissimilar. Where
LaChiusa's music flouts tradition with incendiary rebelliousness _
both lyrically and melodically, Bucchino's teases it with
reassuring gentleness. By Barry Singer.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BESTMAN-THEATER (New York) _ Gore Vidal wrote ``The Best Man''
in 1959, a time when Joseph McCarthy's legacy endured, when Adlai
Stevenson and Richard Nixon were among the nation's leading
politicians, and when Vidal counted as his friend a young senator
from Massachusetts named John Kennedy. The play drew on these
influences to become a tale of politics that may seem improbable
today: a stark struggle of two men of obvious complexity, set
during a national political convention where decisions of
consequence were actually made. Now ``The Best Man'' is returning
to Broadway. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIE-FILM (Undated) _ One of the great things about having pay
cable is the opportunity it provides for discovering little films
that were denied theatrical release. Films like the awkwardly
titled ``And Then You Die,'' a hard-as-pig iron 1987 gangster drama
that used to pop up on HBO well past the shank of the evening. For
its first five minutes, ``Die,'' which charts the treacherous
skirmishes between warring Quebec mobs, works solely in somber and
gripping imagery, neatly sketching out the conflicts; it was
superbly directed by Francis Mankiewicz. It's an instance where you
can literally see the filmmaker running out of money and the
picture eventually compromised by budgetary shortfalls, though the
director's control is evident throughout. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   MCQUARRIE-FILM (Undated) _ To hear Chris McQuarrie tell it, the
origins of the new film he wrote and directed, ``The Way of the
Gun,'' lay in disgruntlement, frustration and anger. McQuarrie,
author of a screenplay that was nonpareil in its genre, was finding
no one who would let him direct a movie about a 20-year-old who had
conquered the world. This is his tale. By Jamie Malanowski.`
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-VIOLIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Rare as great performers are,
even rarer are great teachers of performance. Today, in the field
of violin playing at a supreme virtuoso level, there are only two:
Dorothy DeLay and the rest. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUNICH-OLYMPICS-TV (Unated) _ If the 1972 Summer Olympics in
Munich had ended on its 10th day, it would have been remembered for
Olga Korbut's pixieish dance along the balance beam or Mark Spitz's
record run of seven gold medals in swimming. But before dawn on the
11th day, eight Palestinian guerrillas scaled an unguarded fence in
the Olympic village and invaded the apartment building housing the
Israeli team. They took 11 athletes and officials hostage and, over
the course of a slow-motion 20-hour siege that riveted the world,
killed them all. If any innocence remained at the Olympics, it
ended that day. Of the eight Black September terrorists, only one,
Jamal al-Gashey, a teen-ager at the time, survives. He is the
subject of ``One Day in September,'' a documentary to be seen on
Sept. 11 on HBO in which he describes his life as a Palestinian
refugee and his pride in what the Black September terrorists did to
the Israelis inside the Olympic village at 31 Connollystrasse. By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUPPET-DANCE (Undated) _ There are two bloodlines in modern
puppetry: the ``low'' subversive tradition of Punch and Judy, which
is sometimes called ``marketplace puppetry''; and the ``high''
tradition of Asian religious ritual and court ceremony, including
Indonesian shadow puppets and Japanese Bunraku. High puppetry is
gestural and exploits the same kind of control that is meaningful
in ballet: it is a language for the superhuman, for gods and
heroes, for stories told time out of mind to audiences that
frequently know the motion by heart. By Andrew Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IONIDES-ART (New York) _ Back in the 1920s, the designer Basil
Ionides was one of Britain's brightest aesthetic lights. His books
_ ``Color and Interior Decoration'' and ``The Modern English
Interior'' _ were best sellers, the former chockablock with
watercolor illustrations of his homes, prime examples of a
scientific approach to the play of light on bold but carefully
graded color schemes. Ionides' professional piece de resistance was
the 1929 mirror-and-glass decoration of the Savoy Theater in
London, whose icy glitter still staggers the eye. Ionides was also
an outstanding collector. By the time of his death, in 1950, at 66,
he had helped amass an impressive haul of early Chinese porcelain.
A dish from this cache will be a centerpiece of an exhibition at
the Chinese Porcelain Co., which opens Oct. 12 and closes Oct. 28.
By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPERA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAMOS-OPERA (New York) _ Mark Lamos belongs to two worlds, in
more ways than one. First, he seemed headed for a career as a
classical violinist. Then he discovered the theater, where his
acting career lifted off in felicitous fashion, with an early
Broadway appearance as the heartthrob Christian de Neuvillette
opposite the Cyrano de Bergerac of Christopher Plummer and a
subsequent Hamlet at the Old Globe in San Diego. Next, Lamos
settled down as a director, first of straight plays, then also of
opera. Right now, his mind is on Donizetti's ``Roberto Devereux,''
which opens the New York City Opera season at the New York State
Theater on Sept. 12. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
