<P>
   GENERAL-ELECTRIC (Undated) _ In a few months, John Welch will
step down as chief executive of the General Electric Co., ending a
remarkable 20-year run of earnings growth and near cultlike
devotion. The three front-runners to succeed this 20th-century
business icon fit a pattern: All are gung-ho results-getters for
the company _ and all are white men. Where are the women? The
blacks? The Latinos? The Asians? Together, these groups make up
about 40 percent of GE's domestic workforce, but they are not easy
to find in the executive corps of GE, which is regarded as
America's most admired corporation. By Mary Williams Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   JOHNNIE-COCHRAN (Undated) _ Talking money with celebrity Johnnie
Cochran. Success is not new to Cochran, now 62. Long before his
mustache and sharp ties became a daily staple of the grisly O.J.
Simpson murder trial, he was a big-time lawyer with a heavy
criminal practice. His disciplined, relentless cross-examination at
the trial, however, made Cochran one of the most famous _ and
controversial _ lawyers in America. But it didn't leave him as rich
as it left him famous. Now, he is determined to close that gap. By
Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
