   SENIORS-COLUMN-ROLLATORS (Undated) _ As athletes say, the wheels
go first: seniors often find that mobility is their most vexing
problem, even if otherwise healthy and able to be active and
self-sufficient. Enter the little-known rollator, which looks like
a sawed-off grocery cart with fat rubber wheels, bicycle handle
bars and hand brakes. It helps people walk easily under their own
power, over floors, sidewalks and grass. It even has a seat if the
user needs to take a rest, and folds up so it can be taken along in
a car or on a plane. By Fred Brock.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ So, what ever happened to
medical savings accounts? These accounts _ which permit people or
their employers to put away a certain amount of tax-free money
every year to pay for health care costs _ was presented an a
panacea to the Big Health Insurance problem by supporters only a
few years ago. And how it failed to ignite says much. By Jennifer
Stenhauer.
