<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER HOMETOWN WELCOME, LIEBERMAN TOUTS GORE'S MEDICARE DRUG PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman returned to the warm
embrace of his hometown on Friday, where he criticized Gov. George
W. Bush, telling a group of older residents that Bush would do
nothing to strengthen Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, joined by family members, was welcomed like a
returning son to the Bella Vista retirement home here as he made
his first swing through Connecticut since accepting the nomination
as the Democratic vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Looking drawn at the end of a six-day, cross-country campaign
trip, Lieberman hoisted his 3-year-old granddaughter, Tennessee,
onto his hip _ the first time in weeks he had seen her. He kissed
her cheek and said, ``This is what I missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Millie Shea, 76, kissed the senator's cheek, shook his hand and
then said: ``I'm praying for you all the time. I know God is with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Casotti, 82, told him that when he was nominated, ``I
nearly fainted with joy.''
</P>
<P>
   To the knowing nods of some 300 residents who crowded into a
sweltering community room, Lieberman talked of meeting a retired
veteran this week in Portland, Ore., who must spend a third of his
income on medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unacceptable,'' Lieberman said. ``In the greatest
country in the world, at the time of our greatest prosperity in
history, no one in this generation in particular, who survived the
Depression, fought the Second World War, should have to face
poverty to take the medicine that your doctors tell you you're
supposed to take to stay well.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Gore's proposal to add a prescription drug benefit to
Medicare, at a cost of more than $250 billion over 10 years, and to
set aside some of the federal budget surplus to extend Medicare's
solvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opponents can't do it because they won't have any money
left after they've given it all away in a big tax cut'' that
benefits mostly the wealthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he cited the words of a Republican, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, who criticized Bush's fiscal plan during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the Bush plan doesn't have one penny for Social
Security, one penny for Medicare or one penny to pay down the
debt,'' Lieberman said. ``He was right when he said it earlier this
year, he's right today and he'll be right on Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said last week that he would propose a prescription drug
plan under Medicare this week, and he has argued that the surplus
would be large enough to accommodate that goal and his tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Lieberman has his facts all wrong,'' said Dan Bartlett, a
spokesman for Bush. ``Gov. Bush dedicates $240 trillion pennies to
Medicare. His budget doubles Medicare funding over the next 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he is popular among voters in Connecticut, Lieberman's
visit came with a hint of controversy. He is running not only for
vice president but also for a third term in the Senate, which would
leave the seat in Republican hands if he and Gore win because
Connecticut's governor, a Republican, would appoint his
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   That has caused some grumbling among Connecticut Democrats,
though most insisted publicly that they supported his decision. On
Thursday, the Connecticut secretary of the state, Susan Bysiewicz,
a Democrat, said in an interview on WVIT-TV that Lieberman should
give up his Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Lieberman had said for weeks that he expected to run for
re-election to the Senate, and his aides have said it more
forcefully. But it was not until Thursday night that the senator
himself, said definitively, ``I'm staying in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is one of a handful of states that allows a senator
to run simultaneously for re-election and for national office, and
his decision is not without precedent. Lloyd M. Bentsen, in 1988,
and Lyndon B. Johnson, in 1960, both Texas Democrats, ran for
re-election to the Senate while also running for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Democrats hold onto the White House, Lieberman would
have to give up his Senate seat, and Gov. John G. Rowland would
appoint his replacement. Republicans hold a 54-to-46 advantage in
the Senate, and the loss of Lieberman's seat would hurt the
Democrats' slim chances of taking control.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman quit the Senate race, officials in both parties
said, any number of prominent Democrats, including Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal, could step in and defeat the Republican
nominee, Phillip A. Giordano, mayor of Waterbury.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said on Friday that he agreed with Lieberman's
decision. ``I believe it is absolutely the right decision for the
citizens of Connecticut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that at this late date, the selection of a
candidate to replace him, made by party leaders and not by voters,
would be undemocratic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
