<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     09-01 1762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE NEW NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to the new National Football League, where the road from
ruin to riches can take less than a season to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Where free agency and the salary cap mitigates against great
teams. Where great defenses no longer exist. Where good
quarterbacks are rare, and good defensive backs rarer. Where games
may be closer, but not better. Where anything can happen, and
probably will.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be the old kind of NFL, where brief dynasties
reigned in Dallas, San Francisco, Green Bay and Denver, but it's
working. The NFL big picture shows rabid crowds everywhere (except
Oakland) and a feeling that every team is a few breaks away from
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The late '90s Rams, Falcons, Titans and Colts all went from
nowhere to the top of their conferences without any prelude, so
who's to say the next Super Bowl won't be just as outlandish?
</P>
<P>
   The guys who watch football for a living agree that there's no
great defense around, not even Tampa's. ``They lose (linebacker)
Hardy Nickerson, who called their coverages, and (lineman) Brad
Culpepper, who called their stunts,'' said Fox analyst John Madden.
``I don't think they'll be as good defensively as they were last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   They concur that a quarterback shortage, offense may increase
because there are plenty of good receivers. Some offenses are also
finally taking advantage of mobile quarterbacks rather than trying
to make every quarterback a pocket passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many pocket quarterbacks are there? (Troy) Aikman,
(Peyton) Manning, maybe (Drew) Bledsoe,'' said Raiders Hall of
Famer and Fox analyst Howie Long. ``If you can't protect a pocket
quarterback or get the ball out quicker, you're in trouble, so
having a mobile quarterback is the big trend.''
</P>
<P>
   They agree that fundamentals are down and continuity is gone.
``Tackling is at an all-time low,'' said Mike Ditka, now a studio
analyst at CBS after coaching New Orleans last year. ``It's
something you have to want to do. I'm not saying players lack
courage, but it's not something they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL has become a situational league,'' said CBS analyst
Craig James. ``Teams rotate new players in every down. With the
cap, they're rotating players on the roster every year. The
continuity of the league has changed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   So dramatic that the Rams can win the Super Bowl with an Arena
League walk-on. Coming next: Super Bowl XXXV, Ryan Leaf's Chargers
against Ricky Williams and the Saints? Never say never.
</P>
<P>
   One man's preview, by division, with an emphasis on schedules
and appropriately written-in-pencil predictions:
</P>
<P>
   AFC East: Miami and New England are in retreat. The Dolphins
have no appreciable running game and choosing between QBs Jay
Fiedler and Damon Huard is like choosing between Gummo or Zeppo as
the funniest Marx Brother. The defense ranked fifth last year, but
it has a sagging pass defense that can't tackle. The Patriots are
short rushing and long against the rush, bad news when Edgerrin
James, Curtis Martin and Antowain Smith are on the schedule. The
early schedule should bury them -- Tampa and Minnesota in
September, Denver and Indy twice in October.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Al Groh will work with a 300-pound G.M., Bill
Parcells, over his shoulder. But a healthy Vinny Testaverde and
Curtis Martin should keep the Jets competitive and on the playoff
bubble. Buffalo cut loose Bruce Smith and Thurman Thomas, but a
solid young nucleus. The defense was top-ranked a year ago. Playoff
hopes will depend on four road games in their last six, including
dates at Tampa and Indy.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis has the best triplets in Manning, James and Marvin
Harrison, harkening to the Cowboys Super Bowl era. Manning never
gets sacked (14 in '99) and the offense rarely is stopped. Jim Mora
believes its defense will be better because of last year's
experience, better depth and attention to forcing more turnovers.
The Colts had just 10 picks a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Indianapolis, 12-4. Wild card: Buffalo, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   AFC CENTRAL: It's quite an advantage for Tennessee and
Jacksonville to count six wins against the Bengals, Browns and
Steelers before the opening kick. Cleveland hit a parlay last year,
finishing 31st in offense and defense. The defense should be
better, but there's no backup to quarterback Tim Couch and his
receivers are average. Cincinnati is excited about Akili Smith and
rookie receiver Peter Warrick, but defense, not skill talent, has
always been the Bengals' problem. Pittsburgh's steady loss of
personnel to free agency has finally caught up with them. They're
gasping on both lines and in danger of being non-competitive,
especially with Kent Graham-Kordell Stewart the weakest QB 1-2
north of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore is a hot pick because Brian Bilick's offense played
great late and its defense ranked second. Rookie RB Jamal Lewis and
WR Travis Taylor bring depth and speed to the offense, and the
defense has eight dynamic players. Jacksonville may be in decline
because of losses on the line, the injury-plagued RB Fred Taylor,
and the loss of defensive back Carnell Lake for the year, but they
could make a late run with games against the Browns, Cards, Bengals
and Giants in December.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fisher's Titans should be improved in '00 with Carl Pickens
adding speed at receiver and a defense that is more steady than
flashy despite the presence of Jevon Kearse. The second half slate
is an advantage: three straight home games in November and December
games versus the Eagles, Bengals, Browns and Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Tennessee (12-4). Wild cards: Jacksonville
(11-5), Baltimore (10-6).
</P>
<P>
   AFC WEST: Three teams are in transition. San Diego will try to
win with Ryan Leaf, and it may not be his fault if they don't.
Leaf's not exactly surrounded by great players. Junior Seau's
defense wore down in the second half a year ago. It's a shame
ex-Raider aide Gunther Cunningham inherited Kansas City at a time
when the team's personnel is in decline. Seattle backed into a
playoff spot last season it didn't deserve, and Mike Holmgren can't
rebuild as fast as he'd like because of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves your Raiders, who lost 8 games by 34 points last
season and haven't been to the playoffs since 1993. Al Davis was
praised for a savvy first-round draft pick of kicker Sebastian
Janikowski, but maybe he was just saving money, since kickers don't
get the same draft money as regular players. The Raiders ranked in
the top ten in offense and defense last year and were in every
game, but it's a mistake to assume they'll get better.
</P>
<P>
   Denver gets a healthy Terrell Davis back, quarterback Brian
Griese has gained experience, and the defense still has a lot of
good parts. By throwing their season finale, they also secured a
fifth-place schedule that gives them games against the three NFC
West dregs and both entries in Ohio. Five wins is a nice head start
for a team anxious to get back on top.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Denver (11-5).
</P>
<P>
   First round playoffs: Denver over Buffalo, Jacksonville over
Baltimore. Second round: Indianapolis over Jacksonville, Tennessee
over Denver. AFC title game: Indianapolis over Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   NFC East: Arizona, the team most likely to seek asylum in Los
Angeles, is naturally the dreg of the NFC. They suffer from
personnel malnutrition because of a cheap owner and injuries.
Dallas (Joey Galloway) and New York (Ron Dayne) add potential
solutions in an effort to keep pace with Washington, but they still
look short on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia believes the combo of Donovan McNabb and Duce
Staley can take the Eagles into the playoffs, and while its defense
is small, it gets after people. The Eagles also have a fifth-place
schedule. Washington may be everyone's pick to click, but it also
has the most to lose with owner Dan Snyder micromanaging the club.
The Redskins should open 4-0 and close 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Washington (12-4). Wild card: Philadelphia
(8-8).
</P>
<P>
   NFC Central: The best division in football offers five teams
that appear capable of slobber-knocking each other. Chicago's
fast-paced offense will bother some, but opening at Minnesota and
Tampa projects 0-2 and the opportunity for panic. Detroit is
considered a sleeper based on James Stewart filling Barry Sanders'
shoes and early home games with Washington, Tampa, Minnesota and
Green Bay at home early. But they also have a three-game road trip
after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota may overcome the rawness of Daunte Culpepper at QB,
but the defense remains a sieve. The quick hook Green Bay gave to
Ray Rhodes could lead the Packers back, but they're weak up front
on defense and they can't depend on Dorsey Levens to stay healthy.
The Bucs made it to the NFC title game on its defense and added
Keyshawn Johnson on offense, which should be enough to outdistance
the division competition.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: Tampa Bay (11-5). Wild cards: Green Bay (9-7),
Minnesota (9-7), Detroit (9-7).
</P>
<P>
   NFC West: The Saints eternally fill holes and stumble about.
They play five of seven on the road after the opener and will try
to win with Jeff Blake on offense and six newcomers on defense. The
49ers probably won't be any better than they were a year ago
(4-12), when the salary cap devastated their personnel on defense.
Atlanta's Chris Chandler can't stay healthy and Jamal Anderson
won't be the same back after ACL surgery. Carolina rallied late
last season behind Steve Beuerlein, but it addressed age and injury
concerns by signing a bunch of aging and infirm free agents.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Super Bowl champ St. Louis. Oddly, everyone is
doubting a Rams repeat because Mike Martz is a rookie head coach
and some still think they were a fluke. Well, the schedule's no
fluke. It still includes eight games against a weak division and
only four games against playoff teams. Of their first 10 opponents,
nine were non-qualifiers a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Issac Bruce, Marshall Faulk and Kurt Warner all get hurt,
they should clinch the division before Thanksgiving and play all of
their playoff games on their own rug, until the Super Bowl, which
is outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Division champ: St. Louis (12-4).
</P>
<P>
   First round playoffs: Tampa Bay over Minnesota, Green Bay over
Detroit. Second round: St. Louis over Green Bay, Tampa Bay over
Washington. NFC title: St. Louis over Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Indianapolis over St. Louis. Just because we don't
want to see Georgia hoist another trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
