</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HURRICANE0903-COX     09-01 3132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    History remembers one family ravaged by deadly hurricane of
1900By Kevin Robbins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON ISLAND, Texas _ The father and his son pose on the log
with their backs to the sea. Behind them, waves lick the beach, but
the water retreats until the next swell comes, racing up the shore
as far as it can before it dies in a puddle of foam. Then it races
back.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Ratisseau men: William Louis Ratisseau and his
father, Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows when the picture was made, but family history tells
us it was sometime before the late summer of 1900, when the sea
exploded and buried Pierre. William Louis survived, but his wife
died, and so did three of his children, and for that matter so did
most of the Ratisseaus who long ago settled this narrow spit of
sand on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical cyclone swept into coastal Texas on a September
morning a century ago. Rain fell. Winds whistled. The water of
Galveston Bay pushed one way and the water of the gulf pushed
another and, as evening began to fall, the two met somewhere in the
middle of the doomed island. For almost six hours on Sept. 8, 1900,
there was not a fleck of land left. There were no streets. There
was no beach. There was no Galveston. There was only water.
</P>
<P>
   CITY DESECRATED BY HURRICANE
</P>
<P>
   A bustling port city with aristocrats and elegant bathhouses on
piers, Galveston knew a population of more than 37,000 the morning
of the storm. The fury of the hurricane cut that by a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Galveston died all day long, but the hurricane
took most of its victims early that night, when a 4-foot surge of
salt water crashed through the streets like something no man had
seen, with the power of wet concrete and the speed of quicksilver.
At dawn the next day, a shimmering morning on the beach, at least
7,000 islanders were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Ratisseau was among them.
</P>
<P>
   His son was not.
</P>
<P>
   William Louis Ratisseau survived the deadliest hurricane in the
history of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his family did not.
</P>
<P>
   The storm erased many lives. Many families suffered. But by the
time the victims of the great storm of 1900 had been burned or
buried or lost forever to the sea, it was likely the Ratisseaus had
lost the most.
</P>
<P>
   So this much is known: The photograph of the old man and his son
was made before the morning the water kept encroaching the shore
and the city of Galveston became the floor of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   CALM BEFORE THE STORM
</P>
<P>
   Heavy swells washed ashore the night before the storm, but there
were few clouds. The constellations burned in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa Ratisseau and her five young children left their home to
walk the few blocks to the beach. The young ones wanted to watch
the waves. The children _ three boys and two girls, all younger
than 12 _ scampered up and down the packed sand, stopping to look
at the horse-drawn buggies clattering along the shore. The beach
hummed. A crowd had gathered to see the seas strengthen. Wave after
wave hammered the shore in the stark light of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere over the gulf, a wall of wind marched toward Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa's husband, a plumber, had been called to Beaumont to
supervise work on a new hospital. William Louis was a respected
tradesman, a man from a large and well-known island family who kept
a shop on Tremont Street and attended Mass at St. Patrick's
Catholic Church. He was known as one of the best plumbers around,
which is why, as his wife and children rose on the morning of Sept.
8 to a bronze sky and a sun with an unsettling ring around it, he
was miles and miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   George Albert Ratisseau was the first to notice the strange
skies.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old boy and his mother stood by the window at their
home on Avenue R, watching the clouds, and the disappearing sun.
Flecks of rain dotted the glass. The breeze freshened from the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, observers at the National Weather Bureau Office
studied their data. The barometric pressure had dropped slightly
overnight, noted the chief observer, Isaac M. Cline. He began a
telegraph to bureau headquarters in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually heavy swells from southwest, intervals one to five
minutes overflowing low places south portion city three to four
blocks from beach. Such high water with opposing winds never
observed previously.
</P>
<P>
   The gulf was rising against the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The highest elevation on Galveston Island stood 8.7 feet above
sea level. But the early settlers knew a good port when they saw
one, so they sailed their ships into Galveston Bay and began to
build their city.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston was founded in 1839, but the 32-mile-long island
already had its reputation. Years before, during the colonization
of Texas, Stephen F. Austin visited the island and declared:
``Galveston is the best natural harbor that I have seen.'' The
island protected the bay from the ornery surf of the gulf. Wharves
were built for the ships. Soon, much of the cotton grown on
American plantations was aboard ocean-going vessels loaded in
Galveston and bound for faraway lands.
</P>
<P>
   And a French-born cattle rancher and stained-glass artisan named
Pierre Auguste Alfred Ratisseau sailed into the bay.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY TAKEN BY THE STORM
</P>
<P>
   The rain worsened. The wind roared. The needle on the barometer
at the weather bureau slipped, closing on low pressures never
before recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Late that morning at the Ratisseau home, Louisa ordered her two
oldest sons to strip the clothes from the line outside and haul
them downtown, where a Chinese family owned a laundry above their
father's office, so the clothes could dry.
</P>
<P>
   George and his 8-year-old brother Benton, whose nickname was
Lump, obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys were the great-grandsons of Pierre Auguste Alfred
Ratisseau. When the 1850 census was taken, there were six people
with the last name of Ratisseau in Galveston, and they owned $600
in property. By 1900, the family had blossomed. George and Lump had
many aunts and uncles and many more cousins on the island. Most of
them still lived on the sparsely populated west end, where the
original family established a cattle ranch in the 1830s. Everyone
in town knew the Ratisseau cows: they were branded with the shape
of a French wineglass.
</P>
<P>
   The rain worsened.
</P>
<P>
   As the boys made their way downtown, the west end of the island
was drowning.
</P>
<P>
   The wind screamed.
</P>
<P>
   The northeast gusts rose to storm velocity. The weather
observers hoisted the hurricane flags at the bureau inside the Levy
Building, alerting residents to evacuate at once. Whether the
west-end Ratisseaus ever saw the flags is open to speculation, but
this much is fact: The weather bureau stood more than 50 city
blocks from the Ratisseau ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The barometric pressure sank.
</P>
<P>
   George and Lump splashed through deepening water as they made
their way downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, their mother rounded up the three youngest children.
They had to go. Their house was flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Their grandfather had a plan. He loaded everyone into a skiff.
Then Pierre Ratisseau, 69, pulled his grandchildren and their
mother to a larger home in the neighborhood, one with three
stories.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived, the first floor was full of seawater.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre began handing the children to other refugees through a
second-story window.
</P>
<P>
   He lifted Bessie, who was 6. Then came Kyle, 5. Then Alecia, who
was 18 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother made it inside the house, too.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfather did not.
</P>
<P>
   When his family last saw him, Pierre was groping the foamy water
for the child of the family's housekeeper, a little girl who also
had been on the boat. He dove for her and never came up.
</P>
<P>
   Today, far from coastal Texas, a woman pauses to settle herself
as she tells that story.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Ratisseau never knew her great-grandfather Pierre. She
only knows what her father told her about him.
</P>
<P>
   She knows he wore an earring. That was how the men who found him
knew who he was after the water went down.
</P>
<P>
   She knows he was the old man in the picture she owns, the man
sitting next to her grandfather on the log on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   She knows that moments after he died, the water forced her
grandmother and her children to the third story. She knows that, in
a rush of water and wind, the house then disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Ratisseau also knows the family lore, which is this: As
the hurricane destroyed the three-story house, her grandmother
Louisa held Bessie, Kyle and Alecia as high as she could, so their
heads were above the water. Then, according to a refugee in the
house who survived, Louisa said to her children: ``I'll see you all
in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley is sobbing now. She is on the telephone at her home in
California.
</P>
<P>
   She is thinking of her grandfather, William Louis Ratisseau.
</P>
<P>
   The plumber was far from home that night, when the water
swallowed his island.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand,'' Shirley, 71, is saying, ``I don't think he
ever stopped mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows this. Because the storm of 1900 became part of her,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT WAS EVERYTHING WE HAD AND WOULD BE.''
</P>
<P>
   As the gales blew harder, as the sea rose higher and as more of
their family died, George and Lump Ratisseau waited inside the
laundry for the storm to clear. But the worst was on its way.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:15 p.m., the weather bureau recorded 84 mph sustained
winds, with gusts of 100.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wind gauge vanished.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 p.m., according to the weather bureau's official report,
the gulf flooded Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The water swelled four feet in four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 p.m., the bureau logged a barometric pressure of 28.48.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lowest reading ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Water and wind toppled house after house. The flooding gulf
pushed a wall of debris _ timber, brick, mortar, sand _ that buried
people in its path. Oyster shells scored the air like shrapnel.
Pieces of roof slate cut people like sawblades. Telegraph lines
snapped. Lightning fired above. And the Ratisseau family was being
dismantled, one soul at a time.
</P>
<P>
   On the west end of the island, one of William Louis' sisters
perished with her family when the water sprang her home from its
foundation and spun it around on a ghostly, invisible axis.
</P>
<P>
   One of William Louis' brothers and his family sought refuge on
their roof. The swells battered them. Everyone slid in and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, William Louis' sons, George and Lump, were safe in the
sturdy laundry building.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere else, the hurricane was taking his family.
</P>
<P>
   His cousin Charles Ratisseau died in the storm. So did his wife.
So did their seven children.
</P>
<P>
   His brother John Baptiste Ratisseau died. So did his wife and
their four children.
</P>
<P>
   His brother August Ratisseau died, with his wife and three
children.
</P>
<P>
   His sister Anna Stillman died. So did her husband. So did their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Just as no one knows how many Texans died in the storm of 1900,
no one knows how many Ratisseaus _ and people related to the
Ratisseaus _ were lost. So many were never found. Others were
burned in funeral pyres before they could be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Early estimates suggested 43 relatives of William Louis
Ratisseau died.
</P>
<P>
   His son George _ Shirley's father _ later calculated 78.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Shirley Ratisseau thinks her family was reduced that day by
204.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just people,'' she says. ``It was everything we had
and would be.''
</P>
<P>
   FATHER RETURNS TO RUIN
</P>
<P>
   William Louis Ratisseau got home as soon as he could. He left
Beaumont after the storm, and at the coast found there no longer
was a bridge to cross the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The family lore blurs here. Some versions of what happened next
suggest William Louis got to the island in a rowboat shared by
newspaper reporters from New York. Others say he swam.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Ratisseau tells this story:
</P>
<P>
   Her grandfather found ice tongs near the shore. He pulled them
apart. He straddled a railroad tie lying nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Using the sharp ends of the tongs to dig through the debris, he
pulled himself across Galveston Bay.
</P>
<P>
   He found the body of a child in the water, ``as though God had
put her right there,'' Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   It was his daughter Bessie.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on land, he found the body of one of his sisters. He
walked up and down the ravaged beach, searching for the rest of his
family. He fell to his knees and dug with his hands through the
piles left by the water. He found some Ratisseaus. He never found
others. He dug until he tore his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time my father saw him, his hands were just
bleeding,'' Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   George, Lump and their father were reunited on the island. Their
home was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The storm leveled more than 3,600 houses on Galveston Island.
Many more structures were ruined. The wind sheared the tower at St.
Patrick's Catholic Church, for example, causing it to crash through
the roof of the sanctuary where William Louis Ratisseau once knelt
and prayed his petitions at Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He never found his wife.
</P>
<P>
   William Louis told George one day: We're never going to find
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepted that,'' Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a steamship picked up a man afloat on a raft fashioned of
timber and castnet line. It was one of William Louis Ratisseau's
brothers. The man had lost his wife, his children and his eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   Days passed. All over the island, horses pulled wagons piled
with bodies, funeral pyres smoked and bagpipes cried for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Some islanders vowed to stay. Others looked elsewhere to start
over. William Louis sent George and Lump to live with relatives in
Mansfield because there were so few relatives left in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Then, broken by the weight of his loss, he left.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY HISTORY DOCUMENTED
</P>
<P>
   Shirley can still hear the voice of her grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want,'' he would say, ``to tell you about your
grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley was about 12, she remembers. ``If nobody came into the
room, he would just kind of go systematically. He would tell me
about his grandfather. He would tell me about the children, how
they named them.'' William Louis would tell his granddaughter about
his wife, Louisa, how she came from a family of Virginia
aristocrats named Maclin, and he would show her pictures of Louisa
when she was young. ``He would smile,'' Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   Then he would tell her about the storm. The smile would vanish,
as his relatives vanished in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone,'' William Louis Ratisseau would say, reciting the names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone. All of them, into the Gulf of Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley wrote about the ordeal much later, for the newspaper in
San Antonio. The year was 1964. Her story, which summarized the
family research she had done over the years, was published the day
after Hurricane Hilda slammed coastal Louisiana, killing 25.
</P>
<P>
   William Louis Ratisseau died at the age of 86.
</P>
<P>
   His son George owned a hunting and fishing lodge in Rockport
until he died the night before Shirley was to graduate from high
school. After Shirley married, she and her family operated the
lodge until Hurricane Carla demolished it in 1961. Then Shirley
moved away from the coast forever _ first to inland Texas,
including many years in Austin, where her two children, Darin
Ratisseau and Leiane Alden still live, and then to California.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane followed her. Long ago, before he died, her father
took Shirley aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very ill,'' Shirley says he told her. ``I want to find out
exactly _ and prove _ the history of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   She has done that ever since. She has researched her family for
four decades, as far away as the National Archives in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only monument I could build to my people,'' Shirley
says.
</P>
<P>
   Her people: The Ratisseaus of Galveston. There were many a
century ago. After that September day, when the sea swallowed the
island and the wind ripped through town and everything changed
forever, there were few. Now the 100th anniversary of the storm
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   And there is one.
</P>
<P>
   STARTING OVER
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Ratisseau sits on the sofa in her dark home wheezing.
</P>
<P>
   Her hair is pulled neatly back, but she has trouble talking for
long stretches. The bronchitis keeps her inside most of the time.
The metal storm shutters on her windows keep out the light. At her
age, in her health, Evelyn has little interest in venturing outside
on this sticky Galveston morning in August. She is 86, after all,
born on a January day in the middle of Tennessee, two years after
the plumber William Louis Ratisseau celebrated the birth of a son
he and his new wife named Roger.
</P>
<P>
   His family in ruins, William Louis traveled to New Orleans after
leaving Galveston island. He married his second wife there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1902, William Louis and his new wife returned. They started a
new family in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had sand between their toes,'' Evelyn says now. ``They
couldn't stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   Their Galveston changed over the years. A seawall was built to
baffle future storms, and it did just that when the hurricane of
1915 battered the Texas coast. The seawall saved the island. So did
the fact that after the storm of 1900, the elevation of the entire
city was raised (the effort took six years) to protect it from
floods.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn married Roger Ratisseau in 1938, at his family's home.
</P>
<P>
   Roger became a plumber like his father. He and Evelyn lived in
LaMarque for a time, but moved back to Galveston in 1950. They
never left again. They raised five children. Roger died years ago.
All of his children are grown. None of them live in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Only his widow is left: Evelyn, the last Ratisseau on the island
where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks south of her home, where the palm trees are bent to
the north by the constant and staggering wind, the caramel surf
pounds the beach in a fury of foam. Red flags at the lifeguard
stations snap in the gulf breeze: heavy swells. A storm is near. It
is hurricane season.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn knows. She tracks tropical storms on a newspape map
under the coffee table, marking their movements with a blue ink
pen. She has been watching this one because she, a Ratisseau,
understands the force the weather exacts on the open water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, it was 120 miles from Brownsville,'' she says of
the storm. ``It could come up the whole coast.''
</P>
<P>
   The barometer on her wall reads 31. The sky is as clear as
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the waves roll up the beach. It is the week before
school starts. Hundreds of families are vacationing in Galveston.
They are out there splashing in the surf, getting a sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere over the gulf, the winds swirl. The waves roll up the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Then they roll back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
