<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8895 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-JOHNNIE-COCHRAN-ART-$     09-01 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNNIE-COCHRAN-ART-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A `DREAM TEAM' FOR HIS FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  ART ADV: Photo NYT 16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Cosby has a jet named Camille, for his wife, and
even Oprah got a jet,'' Johnnie L. Cochran Jr. said recently over
lunch at City Hall, a restaurant near his law office in Lower
Manhattan. ``She wanted a plane just like Bill Cosby's. It's, like,
amazing. He goes to sleep on the plane. It's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly dazzled by the luxury of personal transportation,
Cochran has studied the subject. He is now getting a jet, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, who broke into the top-level national law leagues when
he successfully defended O.J. Simpson against charges that he
murdered his former wife, is now hitting the major money leagues as
well, and he has the status-symbol issue down pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting a GII,'' he conceded, his voice showing a
tinge of disappointment that he is not buying a Gulfstream model
favored by many chief executives. ``My plane won't be that big _
more like a Hawker or a Citation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cochran, showing his newfound financial prudence, will not
make the purchase rashly. His law firm, which is building a
national practice, is still deciding whether to buy or lease the
plane. ``We are going to see how often we would use it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Success is hardly new to Cochran, who is now 62. Long before his
disciplined, relentless cross-examination and his flamboyant attire
became a daily staple of the grueling O.J. Simpson murder trial, he
was a prominent lawyer with a busy criminal and civil practice. His
performance at the televised trial, however, made Cochran, a member
of the ``dream team'' defense, a celebrity in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not leave him as rich as it left him famous. Now he
is trying to close that gap, adopting a new money-management
philosophy that includes putting more money into the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   His success ``allowed him to move up the lawyer food chain,''
said his accountant, John Baiardi, a partner at Mitchell &AMP; Titus,
the nation's largest minority-owned accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran no longer takes criminal cases, but he has a thriving
personal practice that includes intellectual property,
personal-injury and business lawsuits. And last year, in a move
that leverages his brand name, he merged his firm with Schneider,
Kleinick, Weitz, Damashek &AMP; Shoot, a personal-injury firm based in
New York. Partners share the legal fees in cases they win together.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran says his net worth is more than $5 million _ in
retirement plans, private investments, a sprinkling of stocks and
his major holding, real estate. His properties include homes in Los
Angeles, including beach homes in Marina del Rey for himself and
his parents, a new condominium in Manhattan where he now spends
one-third of his time, and two apartment buildings in West
Hollywood that he bought as an investment. That net worth figure
does not include the value of his law firm.
</P>
<P>
   But he may be about to make a quantum leap.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, his net worth could soar to $25 million or
even $50 million, Baiardi said, as fees roll in from the exploding
demand for his legal services.
</P>
<P>
   To which Cochran replied, ``I hope we will do that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Brickman, a law firm compensation expert and a professor
at the Benjamin N. Cardoza School of Law, agreed that the
personal-injury fees could contribute to a bump-up in Cochran's net
worth. Lawyers in that area are very selective about the cases they
take on, have a high success rate and often reap big financial
rewards. But maybe not as high as Baiardi suggested. ``It is in the
realm of possibility that Cochran can net over $10 million a
year,'' Brickman said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Cochran was earning $1 million or so annually by
the time the Simpson trial ended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I was interested in earning money,'' Cochran said.
``Now, I'm interested in what happens to it. I don't want to be
haphazard _ I want a team I can count on.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of people like Earl G. Graves Sr., the publisher
of Black Enterprise magazine and leading black entrepreneur, whom
he had met through some business dealings, he is tapping into the
African-American financial establishment in New York. The goal is
to help build that dream team and to create a network of
relationships in the financial sphere, much as he once did in the
legal establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's new focus on finances started in early 1997, when he
decided that he had been spending so much time in Manhattan for his
program on Court TV that he ought to put down roots. So he bought a
pied a terre on West 57th Street in Midtown for about $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   After settling in, he called Graves. ``He is one of my gurus,''
Cochran said. ``Earl is into wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves said Cochran peppered him with questions. ``He said,
`Tell me what I need to know in town,''' Graves recalled. First, he
steered him to Carver Bancorp, the largest black-run bank in the
country, where Cochran's personal-injury clients could borrow
money. ``Then Johnnie told me, `The way you look is the way I ought
to look.''' So I sent him to the John Atchison hair salon on West
56th Street. He told me it was too expensive, so I sent him a gift
certificate.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Cochran's finances, ``I asked him, `What are you going to
do about your own money?''' Graves added. ``And he asked me who I
should invest with.'' Graves introduced him to Bert N. Mitchell of
Mitchell &AMP; Titus and other black financial leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has been a real eye-opener for me,'' Cochran said.
``Most of the people in L.A. who have money are entertainers. And
L.A. is more spread out _ here you talk, you find out what other
guys are doing. In New York, everything is geared to business.''
</P>
<P>
   The team that Cochran has assembled is ethnically diverse.
Guided by Baiardi, who is white, and Jeri Norris, a black financial
consultant and a stockbroker at Merrill Lynch, Cochran is educating
himself about more sophisticated investing strategies. ``We didn't
grow up on Wall Street, but we should move there now,'' he said,
remembering something that Jesse Jackson said while trying to
encourage blacks to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have gotten into the stock market earlier,'' Cochran
said over the recent two-hour lunch of seafood and creamed spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Norris is seeing to that. Wanting to preserve Cochran's capital,
she said, ``we want a mix of old-economy and technology stocks.''
Among her picks for his portfolio are Sun Microsystems, J.P. Morgan
and the American International Group. Her long-term goal for him is
70 percent equities, 20 percent bonds and 10 percent cash.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said he preferred to leave the decisions to Norris: ``My
wife and I don't want to wake up worrying about the market,'' he
said. But he did make one choice: Last year, he bought about
$150,000 worth of Time Warner stock. He knew the company because it
owned Court TV, where for two years he had a talk show on legal
issues, but he does even know today what the value of that
investment is _ except that the stock has gone up.
</P>
<P>
   Though he does not want the final responsibility of making
investment decisions, Cochran wants to know the issues and speaks
often to Norris. To cement the relationship, he and his wife
recently took Norris and her husband to the theater and to dinner
at Aquavit in Midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran is also listening to advice about his real estate and
about the kinds of deals in which he invests. Gone are the days of
jumping into deals heard about at cocktail parties. Cochran says
future deals will be more carefully vetted by Baiardi, ``who is my
sounding board.''
</P>
<P>
   if Cochran cannot resist gambling in venture capital and private
equity, Baiardi wants him to go only with blue-chip
recommendations. ``It is one thing if your brother-in-law
introduces you to someone who has a deal,'' Baiardi said. ``It is
another thing when you go to an investment bank and they do some
private equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Baiardi would also like Cochran to sell the two apartment
buildings in West Hollywood. ``If you are in real estate, you have
to collect your own rents,'' Baiardi said. ``It's one thing to own
commercial property that Trump manages. It is another thing to own
rental properties and collect rent.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Baiardi is not having a problem convincing Cochran. Though real
estate had represented his main investment for years, the risks
became apparent in the late 1980s. ``You never thought about the
stock market when I started buying real estate,'' he recalled.
``You just assumed real estate was stable and would keep going up.
Then it went down, so that was unsettling.''
</P>
<P>
   A Merrill Lynch team suggested that Cochran borrow the entire
purchase price of his new condominium against his existing real
estate, rather than raising cash to make a large down payment. The
move let him deduct all the interest and reduce taxes. ``His first
instinct was to pay off as much as possible,'' Norris recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. ``My first thing is always to pay things off,''
Cochran said. But he said he had learned that ``you can get
deductions and it does not always pay to pay it off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to get good tax advice,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran is even toning down his lifestyle a bit _ to be less
showy. No more Rolls-Royces, like the one he drives around Los
Angeles. Today, he said, he likes ``stealth wealth _ Jeeps, all
that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now, where I am, I would not drive a Rolls in New
York,'' he added. ``But as a young man, it was a sign of success.
My clients wanted to see that. Driving a Toyota or a Mazda was
terrible. If you didn't have a Rolls, you weren't very
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   He has given up his Rolexes, too. ``After a period of time,
that's not as important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran has also become more pragmatic about his personal life,
which was once in disarray. The other night, he said, he and his
wife of 15 years, Dale, a marketing executive who is now starting a
new business, were watching an episode on HBO's ``Sex and the
City'' that dealt with prenuptial agreements. ``I mentioned a
prenup and we laughed about it,'' he said. ``But absolutely I would
have one now. My estate has gone up, and I think in this world,
that's the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's current life is a far cry from a childhood that began
in Shreveport, La., where his father was once a sharecropper. But
the family was ambitious. By the time he was 6, his father and
mother had packed up their four children and moved to California,
where the elder Cochran eventually became a successful insurance
salesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Cochrans were also determined that their children receive a
good education. They sent Cochran to Los Angeles High School, which
had a far better academic reputation than the school closer to his
home.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the homes of wealthy white friends whom he met at
school was a revelation for Cochran, who grew up without television
or other entree to that world. ``I had no way to know how they
lived before that,'' he said. ``Remember, there was a big class
thing. How would you know unless you worked for them?'' he added,
speaking of his friends' families.
</P>
<P>
   And though Cochran made friends at the school whom he has kept
until this day, he said he did not bring them to his house.
</P>
<P>
   His parents encouraged him to become a professional. His mother
wanted him to be a doctor, but Cochran thought that law would suit
him better, letting him use his skills of persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, after graduating from Loyola Law School in Los Angeles,
he became the first black law clerk in the Los Angeles city
attorney's office, making $608 a month. His job involved
prosecuting people, primarily black, who were charged with avoiding
arrest. But that, he came to believe, was aimed at keeping them
from filing civil suits against the city for compensation for their
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   By 1965, he and Gerald Lenoir, a seasoned criminal lawyer, had
started a practice together. Their first windfall came fast. When
rioting exploded in Los Angeles' poor, mainly black, Watts
district, Cochran was alone in the office. As the rioting escalated
and the police began making arrests, clients came to the office
until 11 or 12 at night, putting retainer fees on his desk _ in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time I became aware: `Geez, you can make a
lot of money doing this,''' Cochran said. ``People would come with
$3,000 or $4,000. It was sad. You had a weird feeling. The city was
going up in smoke. But it was the first time I knew the practice of
law could be remunerative.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran learned quickly that criminal defense lawyers need the
money up front. ``They used to say, `Get the money while the tears
are falling,''' he recalled. Otherwise, he added, an acquitted
client would say, ``I was innocent anyway,'' and a convicted one
would ask, ``What did you do for me?''
</P>
<P>
   His practice expanded to civil cases, including police brutality
suits. ``Later, I started getting the big fees from contingency
cases,'' he said. ``You get one-third after you win, so you got to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   In those years, Cochran worried a lot about the cash flow, often
asking whether any checks had come in while he was in court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he set parameters. When a known drug dealer showed up
with a suitcase filled with $600,000 in cash, Cochran refused to
represent him. ``It was the most money I had ever seen,'' he said.
``But I knew drugs were killing kids in the black community, and I
didn't take the case. I knew where the money had come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, as word spread about his successes, the money poured
in. And Cochran was not shy about spending his earnings on his
family and personal luxuries. ``I would buy clothes and nice
cars,'' he said. At one point, he had six fancy cars. ``It wasn't
always wise,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He spent money on a handful of deals, involving oil, a supper
club, radio stations and other things, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   He also spent a lot of money on an extramarital relationship,
according to ``Life After Johnnie Cochran,'' a 1995 book by his
former wife, Barbara Cochran Berry. In 1965, he started a
relationship with Patricia Sikora, who would become the mother of
his only son, Berry wrote. In 1973, according to Berry, he took out
a loan to help pay for a house he was buying for Sikora, and he
tried to get Berry to sign an agreement that she had no rights to
the house, an accusation that Cochran has denied. In the view of
Berry, with whom he has two daughters, he used his money as a form
of manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money and the gifts it bought were the sum and substance of
what a woman had a right to expect from a man,'' she wrote,
interpreting what he conveyed to her. ``This need of women for
money and security were tools to be used in their control, to keep
them in their place.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said: ``This is ridiculous. My poor dear ex-wife _ it is
not true. She saw a chance to write a book and to try to make some
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Cochrans divorced in 1977 and Cochran married his
current wife in 1985, he continued to send Sikora $4,000 a month,
according to a palimony suit that Sikora filed in 1995 after, she
said, Cochran cut her off.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said he sent the money because ``I was supporting my
son.'' Now 27, the son, Jonathan Cochran, is on his own, working
for the California Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was dismissed and is on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran's financial contributions extended to other family
members as well. For years, he helped his parents and a brother;
his widowed father now lives with him in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He even sent his first wife a television set as a wedding
present when she remarried. He has also given money away, most
recently creating the Johnnie L. Cochran Jr. Art Fund, financed
with several hundred thousand dollars to help minority artists.
</P>
<P>
   Though he spent his money liberally, his investment strategy was
conservative. (He agrees with a friend who once told him that his
ties were more flamboyant than his investing style.) He stuck with
real estate and he avoided the stock market _ a strategy that
several experts say is common among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market is still the easiest way to get into the
wealth game,'' said Brooke Stephens, author of ``Talking Dollars
and Making Sense: A Wealth-Building Guide for African-Americans.''
``But many blacks don't trust it and don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said his conservatism was in part a result of memories
from childhood that left him worried about taxes. ``You would hear
stories about Joe Louis and Sammy Davis Jr.'' he recalled. ``They
took Sammy's house away from him. And I would think: I am never
going to be like that. I want to pay my taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up with certain fears,'' he added. ``You want to be
secure. If you have been poor, you understand that if you worked
real hard, you don't want to go back and be there anymore. Tax
problems have always been a big problem for people who became
successful in our community. I vowed that would never be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
