<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-2TAKE     09-01 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING ISSUED ON THE DANGER OF ADDITIONAL FIRESTONE TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This replaces TIRE-WARNING, an early, undated story by Julian
E. Barnes)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., struggling to cope
with a large recall and strained relations with its biggest
customer, received another blow Friday when federal regulators
warned of safety problems in many Firestone tires sold as
replacements for factory-issued tires on sport utility vehicles and
pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Friday
that Firestone had rebuffed on Thursday a request from regulators
to broaden its current tire recall. The agency took the rare step
Friday of issuing a ``consumer advisory'' suggesting that people
buy new tires at their own expense anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The agency found that 1.4 million more Firestone tires were even
more prone to failure than tires recently recalled on Ford
Explorers and other Ford models.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency's review, ``indicated that the rate of tread
separations for certain other tire models and sizes exceed those of
the recalled tires, sometimes by a large margin,'' the consumer
advisory said. It added that, ``We are continuing our
investigation, which may result in an order directing Firestone to
recall these tires and any other defective tires. However, in view
of the potential safety risk, NHTSA believes that it is important
to alert the public of its concerns now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone said in a statement that it disagreed with
the agency's analysis of the data. But Firestone dealers will
provide free inspections of tires and will, if customers insist,
replace tires covered by the advisory with other Firestone tires,
or with tires from other manufacturers, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Firestone dealers are already struggling to cope with
thousands of owners of Ford Explorers and other sport utility
vehicles, who are still seeking replacements for tires covered by a
recall on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer advisory could cause considerable confusion at
Firestone dealerships and auto dealerships across the country over
Labor Day weekend, and perhaps a lot of canceled road trips, as
millions of Americans try to figure out whether the tires that they
bought for their sport utility vehicles and pickups are covered by
the regulators' warning.
</P>
<P>
   Determining whether a tire is covered by the advisory requires
parking the vehicle on a level spot away from traffic and then
crawling under it with a flashlight to read a code embossed on the
interior sidewall of each tire. The code must then be matched with
a list issued Friday by the regulators.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Firestone, a unit of Bridgestone of Japan faces a possible
strike on Saturday by union workers, although the company expressed
optimism that it could reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ford Motor Co. cited the advisory as evidence that
scores of fatal crashes involving Explorers were the result of tire
problems, not vehicle defects.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has said that it alerted Firestone to problems in Venezuela
in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona state officials said in interviews Friday that they
had contacted Firestone in the summer of 1996. Robert Descheemaker,
the commodities unit administrator of the state's purchasing
office, said that he sent a letter to Firestone in late July 1996,
alerting the tire maker that the Arizona Game and Fish Department
was having trouble with Firestone tires on its light trucks.
Firestone sent experts out to examine the tires and ended up
sending some of the tires back to its research laboratories for
analysis in early 1997, Descheemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone concluded that the tires had been improperly
maintained, Descheemaker said. The tire maker continued to say that
Friday about many of the crashes that have occurred. Catherine
Babonis, the bureau chief for support services in the game
department, said that the department had received some credits from
Firestone for new tires.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia McCafferty, a Firestone spokeswoman, said that while she
was not aware of the company's relations with Arizona officials,
Firestone has tried to satisfy all customers with concerns.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Friday's consumer advisory is the strongest action that the
government can take if it has some indications of a problem, but
not the extensive body of engineering and statistical analysis
needed to justify forcing a company to carry out a recall against
its will. While the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
frequently issued such advisories during investigations in the
1970s, it has very seldom done so since then except in a handful of
cases involving child safety seats, said Clarence Ditlow, the
executive director of the Center for Auto Safety, a consumer group
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency's staff and budget were cut in half at the
beginning of the Reagan administration, as part of an effort to
reduce the weight of government regulation on businesses, and the
agency has never regained the size and influence it had in the
Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the replacement tires listed in Friday's advisory have
the letters ``LT'' in their code. This means that they are light
truck tires, often designed for off-road use, and are not passenger
car tires, which have the designation ``P'' in their code. Light
truck tires have been subject to different regulations from car
tires since the 1960s. The light truck tires are designed to carry
more weight but are also not designed to be driven as fast as car
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen R. Kratzke, the safety agency's associate administrator,
said in an interview two weeks ago that the government tested light
truck tires at a top speed of 80 miles per hour, compared with 85
miles per hour in the car test. The government is considering a
requirement that light truck tires meet the same standards as car
tires, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the tires covered by the recall on Aug. 9 were passenger
car tires, which can be used on sport utilities and pickups that
are mostly driven on paved roads.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tires listed in Friday's advisory were original
equipment on sport utility vehicles. Regulators said that these
included some tires on 1991 Chevrolet Blazer sport utility
vehicles, 1991 to 1994 Nissan pickup trucks and 1996 to 1998 Ford
F-150 pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   GM said that fewer than 10,000 of the 211,450 Blazers that it
sold in the 1991 model year had the tires cited in the advisory.
These tires have an excellent safety record, said Brook Lindbert,
GM's director of wheels and tires. Out of more than 1,400
complaints that regulators have received about Firestone tires,
only two involve 1991 Blazers, but one of these complaints said
that a death occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that only 500 tires covered by the advisory had been
installed at the factory on F-150 pickup trucks. Nissan said that
fewer than 20,000 pickups had been equipped with tires mentioned in
the advisory. GM, Ford and Nissan all said that they would do
whatever necessary to satisfy customers with complaints about
factory-issued tires, including possibly replacing the tires.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The recall on Aug. 9 covers 14.4 million 15-inch tires produced
as original equipment for sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks
from 1991 until January of this year, but Ford and Firestone
estimate that only 6.5 million of these tires are still in use.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's consumer advisory said that many of the 1.4 million
tires are probably no longer in use either.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tires covered by the consumer advisory Friday were
manufactured in Decatur, Ill., a factory that Ford has cited as
having quality problems. The Ford pickup tires in the advisory are
P235/70R16 Wilderness tires, which means that have a 16-inch
diameter. All of the tires covered by the current recall are
15-inch tires, but plaintiffs' lawyers have called for 16-inch
tires on Explorers and other sport utility vehicles to be included,
and regulators have been reviewing the 16-inch tires as well since
they began their investigation in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has said repeatedly that the 16-inch tires are safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
