<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-NYT     09-01 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING TO REGAIN GROUND, BUSH TURNS UP THE HEAT ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. _ Undaunted by a blistering sun, Gov. George W.
Bush delivered a fiery denunciation of Vice President Al Gore's
credibility on Friday, telling more than 2,000 sweaty but
boisterous supporters that the Clinton administration had
repeatedly failed to fulfill its campaign pledges of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on a theme likely to be a central part of his fall
strategy, Bush mocked his Democratic opponent for making pledges
this year that sounded like ones he made in 1992: to cut taxes on
the middle class and create a prescription drug benefit for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its kind of like an echo from the past,'' Bush said. ``They're
having to campaign on it again. But our message is: You had your
chance, you have not led, and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the Republicans began broadcasting a tough new
commercial attacking Gore's character, Bush continued to vow that
he would elevate political discourse in Washington if elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's better days are ahead when we have leadership that
will work to change the tone in our nation's capital,'' he said
from a podium on the airport tarmac here.
</P>
<P>
   Kym Spell, a spokeswoman for the Gore campaign, said of Bush's
remarks, ``It's hypocritical of Bush to talk about a change of tone
in Washington while launching a negative personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The two weeks since the end of the Democratic convention have
not been particularly good for Bush, who has seen his lead in most
national polls evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a morning news conference aboard his campaign plane, Bush
expressed few concerns and said he felt that the campaign was ``in
excellent shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do I feel we're in good shape, by looking at the
polls, I feel our team is unified and enthused, and I'm very
pleased with where we are in the campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides often point to the size of his crowds as evidence
of his momentum. He has drawn thousands of energized supporters in
the last few days. And while Bush often seemed subdued early in the
week, on Thursday and again on Friday, he looked loose, confident
and animated.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Gore of being unable to work with Republicans, Bush
praised a Democratic senator from Louisiana, John B. Breaux, who
has co-authored a bipartisan plan for revamping Medicare that Bush
broadly supports. Gore opposes the plan, which calls for
introducing more private competition into the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to bring Republicans and Democrats together to make
sure the promise of Medicare is kept to our seniors,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the audience here were pleased with the
Republicans' tougher tone this week, saying they were worried that
Bush was slipping a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he has to go on the offensive,'' said Elaine Curry,
55, a secretary to an oil company who met Bush on Friday. ``Dang,
it's a campaign, and you have to fight.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
