<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-PRE     09-01 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-PREVIEW0902- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast start a must for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLOWERY BRANCH, Ga. _ When the Falcons open their season Sunday
at the Georgia Dome against the 49ers, it will count as just one of
16 games on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the game is far more important than that; openers almost
always are.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves knows that better than most.
</P>
<P>
   As an NFL player, assistant and head coach, he is 26-8 on
opening day, 11-8 as a head coach. Of the 26 times he has been on
the winning sideline, his team has gone to the playoffs 22 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back through history . . . very few times has a team
lost their opening game and made the playoffs,'' he said. ``It sets
the tone for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, of the 12 teams that ended up in the playoffs, eight
won their openers, and three of the other four _ Buffalo, Seattle
and Washington _ lost to eventual playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, with more youth than perhaps any team in the league,
aren't likely to end up in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the eight times Reeves has been on a losing sideline in
an opener, that team failed to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, when he was coach of the Broncos, Denver went 11-5 and
missed the playoffs. If his team had not lost its opener, the
Broncos would have made the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Falcons are 17-17 in opening games but have put
together just eight winning seasons. In those eight, however, they
won the opener six times.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just about the effect in the standings. It's also about
the attitude that victory fosters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all mean the same in the end record,'' quarterback Chris
Chandler said, ``but in the momentum you can build, and with it
being a division game with the 49ers, it's kind of like birdieing
the first hole to get your round off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's good that the Falcons are playing a division foe
right away. Atlanta is 11-4 in openers when the opponent is from
the NFC West, including 2-0 against the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were 4-1 in the preseason, and made earnest efforts
to address Reeves' chief concerns of improving the running game and
run defense, but concerns remain.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the last time the Falcons had a winning preseason, in
1990, they followed up a 4-0 mark with a 5-11 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   More important, after five mostly injury-free weeks, they have
been hit with a number of problems. The team is light in personnel
on both lines and at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But defensive tackle Travis Hall, who will start at end because
of Brady Smith's pulled groin, said he thinks the preseason was
positive enough to build on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can carry over the way we've been playing, and start out
with a bang and get rolling, I think it's a huge, huge
difference,'' Hall said. ``If you don't win your first game, you're
always reeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were reeling last season after a season-opening
17-14 loss to the Vikings in a game they had chances to win. Before
they knew it, they were 0-4.
</P>
<P>
   This game is even more important because the next two are on the
road, at Denver and Carolina. Then comes a home game against the
defending Super Bowl champion Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Denver is stout at home, and Carolina is widely picked to finish
ahead of the Falcons in the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   So three of the first four games will be against division
rivals, and the other played in a stadium difficult on visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Denver also will be jacked up for Reeves' first return as a head
coach since he was fired eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we start is really important,'' Reeves said. ``If you
don't do well in your division, you usually don't make the
playoffs. The first four games are really crucial for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
