<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0902-C     09-01 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayfield's run of bad luck ends with pole
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Jeremy Mayfield's car at Darlington Raceway
was almost as fast as his recovery from an injury he suffered last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield won the pole position for Sunday's Southern 500 with a
qualifying lap of 169.444 mph, narrowly edging runner-up Johnny
Benson (169.409). Ward Burton, who won the spring race at
Darlington, was third quickest in Friday's opening round of
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   The last four races have been tumultuous for Mayfield. He
wrecked in practice the day before the Brickyard 400 and was
diagnosed with a head injury. He missed the Indianapolis and
Watkins Glen races. Mayfield then climbed back in the car at
Michigan and had a poor finish. He was wrecked by Bobby Hamilton at
Bristol last Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the two races has refreshed Mayfield's racing desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the toughest part of my whole career,''
Mayfield said. ``You think it's hard getting (to Winston Cup) and
then when you get here, it's even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the time we've got the No. 12 car where it needed to be
_ running good every week, then I got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I never had a headache, never got dizzy or
(anything), so I think I'm OK. The doctor is saying `You better not
race,' and you start thinking about a lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield was so frustrated about not being able to drive in the
two races that he elected to stay at his home rather than be an
observer at the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two weeks seemed like two years to me. When I did get
back in the car at Michigan, I wasn't sure what was going to
happen. It was probably the most nervous I have ever been in my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the wreck at Indianapolis, Mayfield was one of the hottest
drivers in the Winston Cup Series. He had won at California and _
in possibly the season's most memorable finish _ bumped Dale
Earnhardt aside on the final lap to win the first Pocono race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I got hurt, my confidence was higher than it's ever
been,'' Mayfield said. ``Then when I got back in the car at
Michigan, I felt like I was starting all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it is important for me to come here . . . and sit
on the pole. It has boosted my confidence back up to where I think
it needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's teammate, Rusty Wallace, has won three out of the
last five Winston Cup races and finished runner-up in another.
Wallace, who has never won at Darlington, qualified for the 16th
position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
