<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-ROOKIES0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL teams get look at rookies
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. _ Next week, the Thrashers are expected to
bring nearly 60 players to their second training camp. The fact
they are having a pre-camp for prospects to see who even makes it
there presumably is a sign of progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers brought 24 rookies to a six-team, four-day camp
and tournament beginning today. The stakes might not seem high to
some, but as Thrashers right winger Brad Tapper, the NCAA's top
goal scorer last year, said, ``I don't know how my play here will
affect Atlanta's decision. But I'm not taking anything for granted.
I know it's only a rookie camp, but I'm only a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell helped form this camp
three years ago when he was Detroit's assistant GM. The idea,
hatched by Red Wings GM Ken Holland, was to have extra time to
evaluate prospects before training camp. By the time the camp began
two years ago, Waddell had taken the Thrashers' job. A four-team
tournament with Detroit, St. Louis, Chicago and Nashville has
expanded to six with the Thrashers and expansion Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Thrashers' prospects at the camp, Waddell expects eight
to 12 to be invited to training camp in Duluth, beginning next
Saturday. Though some, including Tapper and 1999 draftees Zdenek
Blatny and Luke Sellars, are obvious, Waddell said, ``I'm not
making any decisions, yet. We're not going to reward guys based on
bad play at the camp.''
</P>
<P>
   As to what this camp means to this year's team, that depends on
Tapper and Blatny, the two players given the best chance to make
the NHL roster. Blatny, a 6-foot-1 center from the Czech Republic,
was a third-round pick a year ago who evolved into one of the
scoring forwards in the juniors. He finished with 47 goals and 44
assists for 91 points for Seattle and Kootenay of the WHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who goes to training camp hopes to make the team,''
Blatny said. ``All I can do is try to play like I did last year and
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Blatny is 19 with remaining junior eligibility, the
Thrashers must either sign and keep him or send him back to
juniors. The same rules don't apply to Tapper, who is older (22)
and has played four years at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute. He
led the nation with 31 goals in 37 games.
</P>
<P>
   POSITION FILLED
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will announce the hiring of long-time NHL
executive Jack Ferreira later this week. Ferreira, who has been the
general manager of three teams (Minnesota North Stars, San Jose and
Anaheim) and last season was vice president of hockey operations
for the Mighty Ducks, will be the Thrashers' player personnel
director, a newly created position. Ferreira will run the team's
pro scouting department and provide input on personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   BUZEK NOT CLOSE
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said Friday that negotiations with restricted free agent
Petr Buzek are getting worse, saying, ``We're a long ways apart.
But I assure you that come (reporting day) Sept. 7, our training
camp will begin, with or without Petr Buzek.'' A contract proposal
from Buzek and agent Rich Winter earlier this week wasn't close to
the three-year offer from the team. Waddell has countered by
pulling his original deal off the table and tendering a one-year
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
