<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN COURT SENTENCES ISLAMIC MILITANT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a speedy closed-door trial in Nablus on Friday
evening, a Palestinian state security court sentenced to 12 years
an Islamic militant whom the Israelis failed to capture in a
botched raid on a West Bank house last week.
</P>
<P>
   The militant, Mahmoud Abu Hanoud, 33, a leader of the Hamas
organization's military wing in the West Bank, was convicted of
forming and arming a military cell that acted at cross-purposes
with the Palestinian Authority, the Palestinian attorney general,
Khalid Kidra, said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud has been wanted for years by Israeli authorities, who
said he played a crucial role in terrorist attacks that killed at
least 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian court did not consider the Israeli charges.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, an elite undercover unit of the Israeli army
staged a raid on his house without coordinating the operation with
the Palestinian police. Three Israeli soldiers were killed by fire
from other Israeli soldiers during the raid, the army said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud, who was shot in the shoulder, escaped. He later
turned himself in to the Palestinian authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
