<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MISSILE-ASSESS-ART-80     09-01 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-ASSESS-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON DECIDES TO KEEP U.S. OPTIONS OPEN ON ANTIMISSILE
DEFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MISSILE-DEFENSE and related stories) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In declaring that his administration would not
deploy a national missile defense, President Clinton made the case
Friday that the United States could pursue an arms control agenda
but must also explore ways to meet the post Cold War missile
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Among arms control experts, this is known as ``having your cake
and eating it too,'' or more specifically, keeping the landmark
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty by amending it to allow for a
limited national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Republican presidential nominee, George W.
Bush, has said that the ABM Treaty, in which the two superpowers
sought to prevent nuclear war by agreeing to remain equally
vulnerable to the other's attack, is an anachronism of the Cold
War. His top foreign policy advisers believe the treaty should be
scrapped, paving the way for a sea- or space-based missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else Clinton did Friday, temporarily at least, he took
the missile defense decision out of the realm of election-year
deadlines and test schedules _ and returned the discussion to the
fundamental question of whether the United States wants to preserve
or tear up the ABM treaty, a cornerstone of superpower arms
control.
</P>
<P>
   He said that America's security in the 21st Century depended on
deterrence, diplomacy and defense. And he added that strategic
stability required that all three of these concepts be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that America and the world will be better off
if we explore the frontiers of strategic defenses while continuing
to pursue arms control _ to stand with our allies and to work with
Russia and others to stop the spread of deadly weapons,'' Clinton
said in his speech at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   In making this argument, Clinton was acknowledging the
opposition to a limited missile defense from every important corner
of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with Washington's closest ally, Britain, the uneasiness
about a national missile defense has been constant among NATO
members, and was only slightly muffled after the administration
made efforts this year to better explain its reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which was to be the base for an upgraded radar
necessary for a national missile defense, tentatively accepted the
administration's calculation that North Korea presented a threat.
But France and Germany never agreed with this assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, said in an
interview earlier this year that a missile defense would be
disruptive to the Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are members of the alliance who wonder if this won't
lead to unequal security,'' he said. ``If there is a real threat,
why are you protecting only yourselves?'' In any event, said
Vedrine, North Korea was a country that harmed its own population
more than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the allies were troubled by the opposition from
Moscow. Consistently, the British said they would cooperate with a
national missile defense only if it was done in agreement with the
Russians and in the context of the ABM Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, despite nearly a year of negotiations by Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who tried to convince them
otherwise, the Russian leaders did not believe that the missile
defense system was designed just to counter North Korea. Rather,
the Russians believed the plan would start a new arms race to
deploy anti-missile defenses, which their broken economy and
beleaguered military forces would be unable to match.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Chinese refused to accept that the proposed
limited missile defense plan was geared against North Korea, a
country they knew to be far poorer than themselves. The Chinese
said they viewed missile defense as aimed at them because it would
destroy China's ability to deter nuclear attack by neutralizing its
relatively small force of nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Chinese said, the Clinton plan would initiate an arms
race and they would have no choice but to expand their own nuclear
forces in response.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton appears to have listened hard to all those
arguments, candidate Bush and his defense experts, as well as some
conservative Democrats, have brushed many of them aside.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the intensity of the subject and the stature of those
who have participated in it _ including former secretaries of
states George Schultz and Henry Kissinger _ those who have promoted
a more muscular national missile defense than Clinton are part of
the mainstream debate.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, the Bush camp argues that the ABM Treaty is an outmoded
piece of security architecture that does not fit the needs of a
world where a handful of countries _ North Korea, Iraq, Libya, Iran
_ have or will have the capability of using nuclear blackmail
against the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some experts argue that the ABM Treaty should be unilaterally
scrapped, if necessary. R. James Woolsey, the Clinton
administration's first director of the CIA, believes the treaty is
illegal because it has not been resubmitted to the Senate since the
breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In a widely noticed article earlier this year, Henry Kissinger
wrote: ``In the existing strategic environment the ABM Treaty
constrains the nation's defense to an intolerable degree.'' He
accused the Europeans of being stuck with outdated slogans, saying
they should understand that a system that protected America against
limited nuclear attacks would ``enhance rather than diminish our
willingness to defend our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush picked up on this theme in a speech last May in Washington.
Answering a question, he said that the ABM Treaty was an
obstruction ``that makes it hard for us to fully explore the
options available.''
</P>
<P>
   The starkest declaration for the need to do away with the ABM
Treaty came from Bush's senior foreign policy adviser, Condoleezza
Rice, who was a Soviet expert on his father's National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote in Foreign Affairs in February that her first option
would be to ``engage the Russians'' in a discussion on the advent
of the new threats and the changed strategic environment. ``The
United States should make clear that it prefers to move
cooperatively toward a new offense-defense mix, but that it is
prepared to so unilaterally,'' Rice wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In another difference with the Clinton approach, Rice has said
that a Bush administration would want to make an anti-missile
system available to America's European allies, ensuring that the
defense of the European allies was not separated from the defense
of the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
