<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BICHETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICHETTE TRIES OUT GREEN MONSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before entering the batting cage at Fenway Park, Dante
Bichette shook hands with the man who traded for him.
</P>
<P>
   After depositing a number of baseballs over the Green Monster,
off the wall behind the center-field bleachers, and into both
bullpens, Bichette exited and shook hands once again with Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be in Boston, Dante?
</P>
<P>
   You bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thrilled to be here,'' said Duquette Friday night.
``There's a mutual admiration society between him and Ted Williams,
and he's a .366 lifetime hitter at Fenway. Those are all positive
reasons to indicate he can help us this year and next year.''
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime .300 hitter, Bichette was acquired from Cincinnati
Thursday for minor league pitchers John Curtice and Chris Reitsma.
In exchange for those promising prospects, the Red Sox got a
36-year-old slugger with 255 homers and 1,078 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   And a man who always wanted to wear a Boston uniform _ even if
his initial fitting wasn't exactly tailored to his 6-foot-2-inch,
236-pound body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tight and a little short,'' said Bichette, who
donned No. 19 before the series opener against Seattle. ``I'll go
back in and try a few more on so I can get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a perfect fit career-wise for Bichette, whose only
postseason appearance was spectacular: In 1995 for Colorado, he hit
.588 (10 for 17) with a homer, three doubles, and three RBIs
against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the place where I really wanted to play,'' said
Bichette, a four-time All-Star with Colorado. ``Ted Williams was my
favorite guy, I met my wife here, and a lot of good things happened
to me in Boston. I'm glad to have this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   And Duquette is glad to give it to him. ``He's one of the best
RBI men in the big leagues the last six or seven years, he's proven
that,'' Duquette said. ``His strength is his bat. He's a pro
hitter. He'll give us another presence in the lineup and he's a
good pull hitter. He can drive in a run when it counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Batting practice pitcher Bill Moloney said, ``(Bichette) has a
real quick bat. You can see that right away. There were some balls
that were a little off the plate and he had no trouble getting the
head of the bat on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bichette, despite his practice barrage, didn't want to
speculate about where he hopes to hit the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get too caught up about that green wall.
That's probably something you have to fight here as a righthanded
hitter. Pitchers aren't going to let you do that as easy as you
might think. I just want to be consistent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, who batted fourth as the designated hitter, batted
.295 for Cincinnati with 27 doubles, 16 homers, and 76 RBIs. In
August, he hit .319 (29 for 91) with 17 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella said the addition of Bichette
gives Sox manager Jimy Williams more options. ``He's already
batting Nomar Garciaparra in that second spot tonight and that
could give (Garciaparra) an extra at-bat late in the game,'' said
Piniella. ``Bichette is a good hitter, no question about that. He's
a tough out.''
</P>
<P>
   And an even tougher one with men on base. With runners in
scoring position, he has a career .311 batting average (514 for
1,655). Over the course of the last six seasons, he has hit .341
(351 for 1,029) and driven in 537 runs with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, he has 1,100 hits, the most in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be in the middle of the lineup where I think I
can help out. That's fine,'' said Bichette. ``If they want me to DH
the rest of the games, that's fine, too. I can fit in and help
these guys reach their goal this year, that would be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
