<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO SAYS HE TAKES PRIDE IN IMPROVEMENTS FOR MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a State of the Union address delivered with
solemn nostalgia, President Ernesto Zedillo declared Friday that he
was leaving Mexico a better country than when when he took office
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   True to his typically guarded and technocratic style, Zedillo, a
Yale-educated economist, extolled the measures that he took to save
Mexico from financial ruin, and he boasted about the transparent
elections that have propelled the nation on a seemingly
irreversible course toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans now have all the ingredients of a modern democracy,''
Zedillo said in his prepared remarks, ``individual guarantees,
civil liberties, a multiparty system, free elections, pluralism and
now, as a result of the determination of our citizens, the
alternation of parties in power.''
</P>
<P>
   The address, known in Mexico as the Informe, was also a painful
final rite for the one-party dynasty that has controlled Mexican
politics for most of the last seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party was
defeated in the most open and competitive presidential elections in
Mexican history. The man who will take office on Dec. 1, Vicente
Fox Quesada, will be the first president in 71 years to be chosen
by the people, rather than by his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Fox chose not to attend the ceremonies in the Legislative Palace
so as not to distract attention from Zedillo's address. But Fox's
electoral victory permeated the atmosphere, and Zedillo
respectfully acknowledged the president-elect in his address.
</P>
<P>
   For Zedillo, 48, whose term began in 1994 with a devastating
peso devaluation and civil unrest in Chiapas, the speech was a
triumphant political finale.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo did not mention his Institutional Revolutionary Party by
name. Its leaders are still rankled by their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with sentimental appreciation and praise for the
government _ for the public schools, health centers and scholarship
programs that helped him move from a gritty working-class childhood
to Yale and onto the presidency _ Zedillo offered the PRI a veiled
farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe all of us, absolutely all of us, have to acknowledge
one fact,'' he said. ``Mexico has completed its journey toward
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo arrived unexpectedly at the presidency after the
assassination of the PRI candidate, Luis Donaldo Colosio, in 1994,
an event that thrust him into presidency. And on Friday night he
offered personal reflections about his time in office and his faith
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably absent were references to the litany of unpopular
policies, unfulfilled promises and scandals that have plagued his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Zedillo's former tourism minister and campaign
finance manager, Oscar Espinosa, disappeared after facing charges
that he had embezzled $45 million in government money in his years
as regent of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the director of a vehicle-registration program, hired by
the administration, was detained by international law enforcement
agents on charges of torture during Argentina's military
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   The president tried to explain his commitment to the unpopular
economic programs that he initiated at the start of his presidency,
including a $100 million bailout to save Mexican banks and to
secure loans to some of the wealthiest business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis severely damaged people's living standards in
1995,'' Zedillo said. ``Yet I am certain that the damage would have
been much greater and longer lasting had we not adopted the
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper polls show that many people have accepted that hard
reality and that Zedillo is enjoying the highest popularity ratings
of his presidency. Seven out of 10 Mexicans polled by the newspaper
Reforma said they approved his performance as president, compared
with three out of 10 five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that popularity is generally attributed to the
democratic reforms instituted in the Zedillo administration,
reforms that led to the creation of the autonomous Federal
Electoral Institute, to the election of the first opposition-led
Congress and, ultimately, to Fox's election.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently ignoring a recent political riot in the state of
Mexico in which at least nine people were killed, Zedillo added,
``We can attest that suspicions, recriminations and electoral
conflicts have been resigned to history.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has been receiving much colder treatment from his
own party's leaders. They who fault him for the party's losing the
presidency, although the PRI keeps a narrow majority in both houses
of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential loss has thrown the party into the worst crisis
of its history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that the president's relationship with the party is
fragile,'' said a PRI senator, Humberto Roque Villanueva. ``There
is a certain feeling of injustice that the PRI paid the political
costs of the policies, while the government enjoys prestige.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
