<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADSHAW WRITES HISTORY IN LOSS TO SANCHEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Long Way Baby's baby is sweating it out on the
humid Grandstand court. Her name is Alison Jean Bradshaw,
19-year-old daughter of a once-upon-a-time rebel who had done time
on the same asphalt landscape of Flushing Meadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting beyond anything I could have dreamed,'' says
the ex-rebel, Valerie Ziegenfuss, in a courtside seat. ``My kid in
the US Open at the same age as my first, '68. Oh, I know all moms
think their kids are the greatest, but this is pretty remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   And then some. What are the odds that one of Billie Jean King's
original Long Way Babies _ the breakaway pioneers of the Virginia
Slims circuit _ would produce an offspring to spring onto the tour
that she helped build decades ago?
</P>
<P>
   Mom a pioneer? The child isn't very interested. Maybe someday.
Well, did kiddies in 19th century California want to hear about the
old lady's covered wagon ride? Those intrepid Long Way Babies,
trying to establish professional tennis for women in 1970, might as
well have traveled to Houston on the Mayflower as far as Alison
Bradshaw is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   On this Friday she's got her new career to think about, and an
all-timer of a problem across the net named Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario. They're both rookies: Alison, the fugitive from Arizona
State University just turned pro, and Arantxa, the just-married
refugee from spinsterhood. Is this any way to spend a honeymoon _
slaving over a stove-hot tennis court?
</P>
<P>
   A maiden in the big league, Alison, tall, sturdy, redheaded, is
in on a gimme _ a wild card _ as an up-and-coming San Diegan. But,
ranked No. 268, she has exceeded expectations, beating Nos. 46 and
75, France's Sarah Pitkowski and American Marisa Irvin, to crash
the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation looms, however, as Sanchez Vicario races ahead, 3-0.
Mom Valerie remains outwardly stoic. So do the kid's grandparents,
83-year-olds Jean and George Ziegenfuss, as they did when their
Valerie played. They needn't have worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Alison will say later, after acquitting herself
favorably in a 7-6 (7-2), 6-0, defeat, ``it was hard to stay calm
and relaxed with my family and a lot of friends here, and playing
(1994 champ) Sanchez Vicario. A lot of people watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowds and tender phenoms are nothing novel to Arantxa, the
Barcelona Bumblebee. A onetime prodigy herself, winner of the first
of her three French Open titles at 17 in 1989, and a sure-fire Hall
of Famer, she was surrounded by almost as many people at her
wedding in Barcelona. Nearly 1,000 people attended the social bash
of the season, including the president of Spain, a sister of the
king, and a representative of the pope (who presumably brought the
pontiff's prayer for Arantxa's inconsistent forehand).
</P>
<P>
   Though Alison was in with a meat grinder, she pulled herself
together. ``I had to get used to the situation and seeing someone
I'd watched on TV as my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing off a poised selection of early-struck groundies, a
penchant for the forgotten art of volleying, and a sound serve and
smash, she rebounded to a 6-5 lead. Whereupon the thick
encyclopedia of Arantxa's experience and resolve fell on her like
an anvil.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, ``when Alison wants to know the history of her
profession,'' says mom, ``I'll give her the details. But I tell
her, `This is your time.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, a handful of revolutionaries _ the Houston
Nine _ spearheaded by crusading Billie Jean King, defied the US
Tennis Association by setting up a female prize money event in that
city. Masterminded by Gladys Heldman, then publisher of World
Tennis Magazine, and bankrolled by Joe Cullman's firm, Philip
Morris, it was won by Rosie Casals over Judy Dalton, and embraced
as well King, Ziegenfuss, Kristy Pigeon, Kerry Melville, Julie
Heldman, Peaches Bartkowicz, and Nancy Richey.
</P>
<P>
   All were suspended _ Melville and Dalton by the Australian
Association, the rest by the USTA. ``That didn't last long. We were
on our long way; the Slims circuit started the following year,''
recalls Valerie. ``Was I nervous about taking the chance? No. We
had the product. Women's pro tennis. With Billie Jean, Gladys, and
Joe behind us we couldn't miss. Look at what my kid is going into
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Nine cut up a pot of $7,500. Alison Bradshaw
collected $35,000 out of the Open's $4,385,000 female kitty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom never pushed me,'' she says. ``She took me to the club
where she was teaching, and I watched. It looked fun, and I started
at 6. It is fun,'' her blue eyes gleam like the silver rings in her
ears. ``It's my life. I knew I wouldn't finish at Arizona State
when I started, and the coach understood that. I've always wanted
to be a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``But two years of college were great. I needed that to mature.
I can't imagine going on the tour at 16 like some of these kids.
Now I have to get into the gym, work hard on conditioning.
Everybody out here is in better shape than college.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom, ranked as high as No. 7 in the US in 1970, now works as a
western regional USTA coach for 14-year-olds. She says, ``Alison's
on her own. No coach. If she asks for help, I'll oblige. She's a
late bloomer, and that's good. She got as far in the Open this year
as I ever did. But I had some good wins: Billie Jean, Virginia
Wade, Francoise Durr. I'm proud I represented my country in
Federation Cup, and I hope Alison can.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a turning-pro present I gave her a cell phone so she can
keep up with her friends. I told her she won't make many friends
out here. This is a job. But,'' smiles the pioneer, ``Alison's got
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STATEOFSOUTH0903-COX     09-01 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEOFSOUTH0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Digital gap seen in South
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To overcome disadvantages, the South must act quickly
to improve education, increase digital literacy and spread the
``new economy'' prosperity of cities like Atlanta to the rest of
the region, says a major economic study being released today
(Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   The latest biennial State of the South report from Chapel Hill,
N.C.-based MDC Inc., an economic research firm, urges aggressive
action by business, educational, political and philantrophic
leaders, despite ``all that the South has accomplished over the
past 20 years to improve its competitiveness'' in economic
development and public schooling.
</P>
<P>
   A technological disadvantage is among the obstacles that MDC
says imperils small towns and rural areas across the South.
</P>
<P>
   Those places have an opportunity to benefit from the ripple
effect prosperity of what MDC calls ``new-economy cities'' such as
Atlanta, Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill, Orlando and Nashville _ but
only if they're digitally connected to the cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are really going to move the region to a higher plateau
economically, we have to move more people into the information
economy,'' said Ferrel Guillory, a senior fellow at MDC.
</P>
<P>
   An example of what the report suggests can be found here _ in
remote and mountainous Madison County, N.C. _ which is so
economically distressed that half the schoolchildren eat free or
discounted lunches. Eighth-grade entrepreneurs have set up 22
make-believe lemonade stands in a nationwide virtual business on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week, 13-year-old Casey Wilson's stand in Miami
``sold'' seven cups, for a profit of $6.60. Valisha Sutton, 14,
lost 55 cents, but still had $5.70 to keep afloat her virtual
business in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's things like this that bring education to life for kids,''
said teacher Carolyn Franklin, whose rural school's embrace of
technology illustrates what, according to the MDC report, too much
of the South is lacking in the fast-emerging digital age.
</P>
<P>
   The improving technology at Madison Middle School is part of an
educational initiative in southwestern North Carolina. Over the
next few years, a consortium led by Mars Hill College, Western
Carolina University, Montreat College and Brevard College will
train more than 250 teachers to enhance their lessons with the
Library of Congress' vast digitized collection of historical
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the possibility of what it can do in the classroom,''
said Kathryn Zimmerman, the middle school's principal.
</P>
<P>
   But the school's remote location, tucked in a creek bottom
surrounded by hayfields and barns 20 miles northwest of Asheville,
points to one of the worst digital hurdles for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Much of North Carolina's mountainous region remains unconnected
to high-speed fiber optics cable, which is increasingly becoming a
necessity for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, to be connected is not such a big issue because of
the concentration of communications companies,'' Mars Hill College
President Max Lennon said. ``But here we do not have the same
quality of connection and, when we do, it is more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report, MDC reaches beyond its traditional advocacy of
rural areas to urge the bolstering of new-economy cities like
Atlanta, which are grappling with smog, water shortages, traffic
congestion and a lack of affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continued prosperity of new-economy cities _ and indeed,
the prosperity of their states and the entire region _ depends on
their remaining livable as they cope with rapid growth,'' the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, the suggestion that thriving cities need
to be nurtured might have drawn protests from the rural South and
its politicians. But that appears to be changing with the arrival
of the digital age and its promise of economic and educational
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were sitting inside the city limits of Atlanta, we would
not have any greater (digital) access than we have right here in
Douglas,'' said Max Lockwood, mayor of the Coffee County, Ga., town
210 miles southeast of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, where Gov. Roy Barnes is pushing technology in
education, economic development and state government, a rising
number of initiatives is reaching beyond Atlanta to outlying
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since LaGrange officials decided to wire the Troup
County city with fiber-optics cable, it is reaping the digital
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrange, 60 miles southwest of Atlanta, recently won an
international award from the New York-based World Teleport
Association for its broadband infrastructure. Among other services,
it provides free Internet service to residents through cable.
</P>
<P>
   Next, LaGrange plans to provide residents with access to online
college classes through Georgia's Global Learning Online for
Business and Education and the Georgia Virtual Technical College,
said Joe Maltese, the city's director of community and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   Yamacraw, the public-private initiative to make Georgia a leader
in the design of broadband communications systems, devices and
chips, last week recruited San Jose, Calif.-based Cypress
Semiconductor Corp. to join its design center, proposed for midtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, Yamacraw chief executive Jim Foley said,
products designed by the center could be manufactured in Georgia,
probably in outlying areas where labor is cheaper and more
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some of Georgia's rural areas have catching up to do.
Only in recent months has Stewart-Quitman High School in Lumpkin,
near the Alabama state line, been connected to the Internet, said
state Sen. George Hooks (D-Americus).
</P>
<P>
   ``I see very vividly the benefit that Atlanta gives to the
economy of Georgia,'' said Hooks, chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee. ``But there needs to be balance. You have
to strengthen the weakest parts of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the South, leaders are embracing the promise of
technology to bridge educational and economic gaps that have eluded
decades of traditional fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's report of college-entrance SAT test results by the
College Board highlighted the South's enduring educational
shortcomings. Although better than a year earlier, Georgia's
average combined score of 974 out of a possible 1600 on the math
and verbal tests left Georgia 50th out of 51 in the rankings. Only
South Carolina was lower in the rankings of the 50 states and the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Improving education is even more critical in what MDC reports as
``the transformation of the Southern economy. . . .from low-skilled
blue-collar work to higher-skilled white-collar work. Today more
Southerners than ever work in jobs that required postsecondary
education and training.''
</P>
<P>
   MDC's Guillory says the fastest-growing job sectors involve
``knowledge workers.''
</P>
<P>
   National employment in information technology industries grew
from 4 million in 1994 to 5.2 million in 1998, the MDC report said,
quoting Commerce Department figures.
</P>
<P>
   But only two Southern states _ Virginia and Georgia _ ranked
above the U.S. average of 19.6 information sector workers per 1,000
jobs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we're lagging,'' Guillory said. ``We need to
invest in our universities to create more knowledge workers. We're
still behind the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
