<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXCERPTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM INTERVIEW WITH BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (with BUSH)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from an interview with Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, as recorded by The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does the new RNC ad fit in with a changed tone?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is politics. The idea of working with John Breaux and
Bob Kerrey and concerned Democrats about doing what's right for
Medicare is, in my judgment, a different issue. It's a
tongue-in-cheek ad. It is a way to defend, for Republicans to
defend me, against $30 million of negative advertising or whatever
you want to call it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Those ads stuck to your record and issues, though.
</P>
<P>
   A. But there are some interesting implications to it. If this is
what's going to happen in the campaign, we've got to lay the
groundwork. This is a fellow that will say anything. They went
after my education record. Objective people have said the education
record in Texas is superlative. The point is, this is a way to help
inoculate me about what has come and is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So it's a defense against specific claims of a guy who you
say will distort?
</P>
<P>
   A. Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But what about your campaign's promise to ``change the
tone''? Won't this potentially alienate the very nonpartisans,
women, swing voters you need?
</P>
<P>
   A. If they do, then _ I read where someone said this is going to
cost me the election, this ad. Let's let the public judge. The
public will judge. ...
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've said this will be close. As close as the Nixon and
Kennedy race in 1960?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know. It's hard to tell right now. But I think it's
going to be a close race. And if you had asked me a year ago: ``The
economy's strong, we're at peace, you're running against an
incumbent,'' basically running against an incumbent, willing to
wear the mantle, except in times where it didn't go so well, and
you say, ``You're even with 60 days to go or however many, 65 days
to go, would you take it?'' Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you defeat a guy like this? How do you convince voters
to change administrations during good times?
</P>
<P>
   A. Because they realize there are failed opportunities. Failed
opportunities. They have not led. We will.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've said you sometimes get tired, and these next weeks are
going to be exhausting. So how do you get through them without
slips, bloopers and the like?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm going to concentrate and focus. But I'm in good physical
condition. I'm upbeat. And part of how I, what I do on the stump is
how I feel and I feel good. Obviously, this is a long, long pull.
It's been an interesting experience. It's going to be really
fascinating coming down the stretch . . . It's been a great
journey. I'm going to look back on these days. It's an amazing
experience. I understand what's coming up, but I've been in tough
races before. '94. I understand the pressures. And, you know, I've
got great faith in the American voter. I do. I've got faith in the
voters. They are going to discern. They are going to make a
judgment call as to who best to lead this country, and that
includes changing the tone in Washington, that includes setting the
right goals for the country, that includes watching us all,
watching both of us, as we head toward the finish line. And I trust
the judgment of the people. I don't necessarily like their judgment
at times. I didn't like it in '92, obviously. But I trust them. And
it's like on this ad, I told you, there's a filter and that's your
job, that's your purpose, but the American people will judge
whether this is harsh or not. I trust the people's judgment. I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q. And if they judge for Gore?
</P>
<P>
   A. Seriously, I would respect that. I'm not going to like it.
But this is democracy. I love the system and I love the country. I
love what America stands for. I don't want to sound Pollyanna-ish
about it, but I do. This is an important country and an important
process. And it's long and it's exciting and you've got to grip all
of that, hours on the plane, policy, it is an important part, an
important part of what this country's about. I am so honored to be
one of two coming down the stretch. I am. And I think Americans can
see my enthusiasm for what this country stands for.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why are you getting teary?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not teary. I'm tired.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How important are debates? Sway undecideds?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think they're a very important part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think they'll sway a lot of votes?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think they'll confirm votes.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Undecided people will watch and decide?
</P>
<P>
   A. They may. Listen, ask the debate experts. I view debates as
part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why not just end the debate over debates?
</P>
<P>
   A. Because I think there may be some better formats. I want to
explore all options.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Better how?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's hard for me to say until I hear what all the different
options are ...
</P>
<P>
   Q. You and Cheney have been making an issue of military
preparedness. If you become president, would you pull troops
immediately out of Kosovo and Bosnia?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, I wouldn't. I've said that publicly. I would not. Because
I understand the commitment to which we'll be bound, but I will
work with our allies to lay the groundwork to begin to take up more
of the peacekeeping role in Bosnia and Kosovo. The model that I
thought made a lot of sense was the East Timor model where the
United States provided needed logistical support to, in this case,
Australian troops, to help keep the peace. We need to review all
the missions. I think Haiti was a failure _ $2 billion. And our
point is that the mission needs to be focused and Clinton, the Gore
campaign, is trying to say we're the strongest military in the
world. Yeah. That's not the question. I think people recognize
that. The question is, will we be the strongest in the world to the
point where we can keep the peace. I look forward to this debate.
I'm going to continue bringing up the issue. It is a real issue. It
is an important issue. And it's not only what the military looks
like today, it's what the military will look like tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a good opportunity for us to refashion the military.
It'll help bring some fiscal sanity to the defense budget if we
have a strategic plan that redefines, begins to define, what the
military will look like in the long term. There are some very
difficult decisions that have to be made about aircraft and the
missions and how we move combat troops. Those decisions would
better be made, best be made, in the context of a larger strategic
plan, and one of the first things I'm going to do is work with the
secretary of defense, military planners, to develop a cohesive
long-term strategy as to where to spend research and development
money. This is an important issue for me. . . . Q. Are you
concerned about perception problems regarding Cheney and the terms
of his retirement compensation?
</P>
<P>
   A. I looked at them prior to picking him.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So this attention to his retirement package, his stock
options and finances didn't take you by surprise?
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course not. As he said publicly, he will deal with the
options issue in a way that is comforting to the people. He'll deal
with it. Dick Cheney's an honest man, and when he says he'll do
something, he'll do something.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you wish he hadn't have taken those options in Halliburton
as part of his retirement?
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, he took the options way before he was being considered
to be vice president. It's part of his executive compensation
passage. This is a part of how executives are compensated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
