<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service that are
scheduled for release on  &UR; SUNDAY, Sept. 3,  &LR; of particular interest.
We plan to move these stories by 2 p.m. EDT on Saturday, Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   This budget is prepared from preliminary schedules, and some
stories may later be eliminated or altered; please check the
following budgets for additional information: REVIEW-BUDGET,
SUNDAY-BUDGET, SUNBIZ-FINAL-BUDGET and STYLE-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS &LR;   &UR; (Will move in `f' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-ELECTRIC (Undated) _ In a few months, John Welch will
step down as chief executive of General Electric Co., ending a
remarkable 20-year run of earnings growth and near cultlike
devotion. The three front-runners to succeed this 20th-century
business icon fit a pattern: All are gung-ho results-getters for
the company _ and all are white men. Where are the women? The
blacks? The Latinos? The Asians? Together, these groups make up
about 40 percent of GE's domestic workforce, but they are not easy
to find in the executive corps of GE, which is regarded as
America's most admired corporation. By Mary Williams Walsh. (With
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BUSINESS (Undated) _ Despite scandal and huge expense,
Olympic sponsorships remain hugely popular, with revenues from them
setting new records this year. No matter what happens on the track,
in the pool or over the field, there may be no more dramatic an
Olympic comeback in 2000 than the one the IOC has pulled on the
sponsorship front. By Randall Lane. (With photo and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   FIVE-QUESTIONS-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ A decade ago, a trio of
scholars destroyed the myth that most of those seeking refuge from
creditors were blue collar workers. People in every occupation go
bankrupt in rough proportion to their numbers, Elizabeth Warren,
Teresa Sullivan and Jay Lawrence Westbrook found in a widely
praised study of Bankruptcy Court records. Now they have refined
their research and shown that misfortune, not profligate living, is
behind most bankruptcy filings. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRARY-COLUMN-LABOR (Undated) _ In some very important ways,
the U.S. National Writers Union is the union of the future, and the
apparatchiks who run more old-fashioned unions had better take
notice. The United Auto Workers did just that eight years ago, when
it took in the writers' union as one of its locals. By Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW &LR;   &UR; (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as
noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOSQUITOES-GLOBALIZATION-REVIEW (Paris) _ Mosquitoes and efforts
to control them are at the nexus between the poor, infected world
and the rich, scared one. A look at how globalization has
intensified the spread of mosquitoes, exposing rich countries to
the same hazards as poor lands. By Donald G. McNeil. (Moving in `i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   POLS-MENTAL-HEALTH-REVIEW (Washington) _ New disclosures of
President Richard M. Nixon's purported drug abuse and mental health
problems raise important questions. While the physical health of
presidents and politicians has become a fit topic for public
discussion, the majority still hide their mental difficulties. Vast
increases in the willingness of ordinary Americans willing to seek
mental health help and talk about it have not been reflected in the
political class. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RELIGION-REVIEW (Atlanta) _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman's
emphasis on America's need for religious values in public life has
made him popular with the Christian right and raised some concern
among many with more moderate religious views. But Christian
conservatives believe they have a mission to spread the gospel of
Jesus to non-believers, while Lieberman, as a Jew without a
sectarian mandate to proselytize, bears none of the baggage of the
religious salesman, and is thus more palatable to a wider public.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTIDRUG-PROGRAMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ When Colombian President
Andres Pastrana said the key to winning the war on drugs was taming
demand in the United States, he ruffled some American feathers, in
part because he took no account of the myriad demand-reduction
programs already in place. By Alan Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN-APPAREL-REVIEW (New York) _ The death of tennis
whites: a look at how competitors at the U.S. Open have turned to
playing in more colorful and fashionable attire. By Liz Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUBMARINES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Kursk disaster has cast a
harsher light on the secrecy that continues to define submarine
operations. It has also raised the question of whether a little
less cloak and dagger _ and more cooperation among seafaring
nations _ could go a long way toward improving the safety of those
on board the vessels. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-SUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at some recent cases in
which courts in the United States have agreed to hear civil cases
involving human rights violations outside of U.S. territory. By
John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Will move in `e' category or as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-FIENNES-THEATER (London) _ It is almost a rite of
passage for promising Shakespearean actors to play ``Hamlet.'' More
than most, though, Ralph Fiennes seemed made for the part. To
Jonathan Kent, the slim, ascetic-looking Englishman was born to
play the ill-fated monarch in Shakespeare's ``Richard II.'' To this
fairly obvious choice, however, Kent, an artistic director at
London's Almeida Theater Company, added a more innovative idea. Why
not twin ``Richard II'' with ``Coriolanus,'' another Shakespearean
political tragedy. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CORIOLANUS-THEATER (New York) _ Among Shakespeare's tragic
heroes, Coriolanus stands apart. The others seduce us. This one _
Rome's greatest warrior turned Rome's fiercest scourge _ scorns
even to try. Perhaps the Almeida Theater Company's production of
``Coriolanus,'' directed by Jonathan Kent, will challenge
entrenched opinion. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   PUPPET-DANCE (Undated) _ There are two bloodlines in modern
puppetry: the ``low'' subversive tradition of Punch and Judy, which
is sometimes called ``marketplace puppetry''; and the ``high''
tradition of Asian religious ritual and court ceremony, including
Indonesian shadow puppets and Japanese Bunraku. High puppetry is
gestural and exploits the same kind of control that is meaningful
in ballet: it is a language for the superhuman, for gods and
heroes. By Andrew Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   IONIDES-ART (New York) _ Back in the 1920s, the designer Basil
Ionides was one of Britain's brightest aesthetic lights. His books
_ ``Color and Interior Decoration'' and ``The Modern English
Interior'' _ were best sellers, the former chockablock with
watercolor illustrations of his homes, prime examples of a
scientific approach to the play of light on bold but carefully
graded color schemes. Ionides was also an outstanding collector. By
the time of his death, in 1950, he had helped amass an impressive
haul of early Chinese porcelain. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (Will move in `t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ITALY-BASILICATA (Undated) _ A visit to Southern Italy's
storied past: Heading south into remote Basilicata to see ancient
cave dwellings and frescoed churches carved in rock. By Frederika
Randall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SICILY (Undated) _ In Sicily, three newly restored hotels
provide attractive settings from which to explore ancient sites. By
Catharine Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Lead item: Following the Joan of Arc
trail in France. By Ray Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: Holocaust exhibit opens at
the London Museum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROBOT-DOGS (New York) _ After Sony's tail-wagging success with
its Aibo robo-dog _ it sold out its entire 45,000-unit production
run of the $2,500 electric critters last winter _ at least four toy
companies are putting their own, less expensive versions on the
market this fall. By Allen Salkin. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   FALL-FASHIONS-BOOKS (Undated) _ When sorting through the guides
that tell you what is and is not stylish and important, it's
important to know who or what you aspire to, writes Penelope Green.
``Bright Young Things'' by Brooke de Ocampo, a contributing editor
at Vogue and ``card-carrying B.Y.T. herself,'' according to the
book's introduction, displays a huge menu of possibilities, and
possible settings.
</P>
