<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-GILES-NYT &LR;      09-01 0196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUCE GILES, 53, EX-LEADER OF PRESS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Giles, a newspaper executive in the Southeast and a former
chairman of the Freedom of Information Committee of the Associated
Press Managing Editors association, died on Thursday in Tuscaloosa,
Ala. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giles was executive editor of The Tuscaloosa News. Before that,
he was managing editor of The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., and The
Sarasota Herald-Tribune, also in Florida, all owned by The New York
Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   Giles was born and raised in Lincoln, Neb., and earned a degree
in journalism and English from the University of Nebraska. In 1969,
he was hired as a reporter by The Miami Herald, where he eventually
covered the Statehouse in Tallahassee, Fla. He and a colleague
shared the Green Eyeshades Award, presented by the Atlanta chapter
of the Society of Professional Journalists, for a series of
newspaper articles on campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Giles is survived by his wife, Sherie; a daughter, Rebecca Giles
Wood of Auburn, Ala.; his parents, Everett and Velma Giles of
Lincoln, Neb.; and three sisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OXFORD0903-COX     09-01 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXFORD0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Cemetery feud stirs some old ghosts
 &HT;    By Mae Gentry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ga. _ J.P. Godfrey Jr. thought he had left ``separate
but equal'' behind when he joined the Air Force in the 1950s. But
upon returning home decades later, he found vestiges of segregation
in Oxford, 35 miles east of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton County town is home to 2,000 people, including the
600-plus at Oxford College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been quite fond of this old place,'' said
Godfrey, 63, whose grandparents cultivated corn and cotton there.
``My grandfather was proud of the fact that he owned property. He
used to say, `When you own a foot of land, you own something.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Soon after arriving six years ago, Godfrey searched for his
grandparents' graves at Oxford's only cemetery. ``I couldn't find
them,'' he said, so he began making inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey's questions stirred ghosts from Oxford's past,
entangling the city in a debate over the sins of a bygone era, the
cemetery's future and a pile of money.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford Historical Cemetery had been segregated by law and
custom for more than 150 years. Whites were buried in the
southeastern section; blacks were buried on the north side. After
the civil rights movement of the 1950s and '60s ended racial
separation throughout the South, Oxford held fast to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, the city signed an agreement for a private foundation
to maintain the cemetery. But by the time Godfrey returned in 1994,
the foundation had allowed the northern section to grow wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was literally a jungle up there,'' said Virgil Eady Jr.,
65, a fourth-generation Oxford resident.
</P>
<P>
   Trees and underbrush obscured the graves of blacks buried in the
cemetery. In stark contrast, the ``white'' southeastern section was
immaculate, its green spaces manicured, flowers adorning the
headstones.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the foundation's 35-year agreement has expired. If the city
fails to renew it, the foundation stands to lose its authority and
nearly $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has said, `We are not comfortable renewing this
agreement under the present circumstances,' '' Eady said. ``We have
only one cemetery in this town, and we need to have the same
standard for the maintenance of all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Godfrey, Oxford takes pride in its rich heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1839 as the site of a seminary that later became
Emory University, the town is a shrine of the United Methodist
Church. It is on the National Register of Historic Places. The
bones of Methodist ministers, college presidents and the slaves who
built Oxford lie moldering in its graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of inequality were sown decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1965, little old ladies in the community decided that the
cemetery was not well taken care of,'' said historian Marshall
Elizer, 88. ``They raised money by donations _ cake bakes and that
sort of thing.'' They incorporated the nonprofit Oxford Historical
Cemetery Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Elizer, the foundation's president, contends the group never
intended to care for the entire 10-acre cemetery. ``They meant the
southeastern part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the foundation has amassed nearly $200,000. The
interest from that endowment goes to maintain the graves.
</P>
<P>
   Spending that money on the historically black part would be
unfair, Elizer said. ``The money that we have accumulated was
gotten from the white (residents) because they were the only ones
who bought lots.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1968 to 1978, the City Council gave the foundation $600 a
year in taxpayer money. Though the practice ended when Godfrey
began raising a ruckus, the city still has a separate contract with
a landscaper for the rest of the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Elizer has accused the city of ``trying to get ahold of the
(foundation's) money,'' a charge officials deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to arrange is to continue the foundation.
That's the whole objective,'' said city Councilman Roger Gladden,
who is crafting a proposal he hopes will be acceptable to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all live here, and we're all concerned about this thing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Eady cares deeply about the cemetery. His mother was one
of the foundation's founders, but he cannot imagine that she would
have envisioned today's dichotomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that in 1965, there was a different
climate than there is today,'' he said. ``So I think rather than a
conscious decision not to take care of the northern section, it was
a matter of taking care of their family plots.''
</P>
<P>
   Eady credits Godfrey, who was elected to a City Council seat in
1997, with generating interest in the northern side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of became the conscience of the town,'' Eady said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McLurkin, a septuagenarian, knows the cemetery well. She
buried her husband, Samuel, four months ago and asks a visitor to
take her there.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping lightly over trees roots and gravel, she pads across
the northwest section.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the Bryant family,'' she says, pointing with her
wooden cane. ``They're all gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   McLurkin bends to pick up a rusted grave marker lying
helter-skelter on a patch of hard red clay, wonders where it
belongs, then tosses it back to the ground. She has been attending
burials in Oxford since she was a child and used to know,
literally, where the bodies were buried.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city kept poor records, funeral directors have been
known to consult McLurkin before burying Oxford's dead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, workers digging a hole for a 4-year-old's casket
discovered an occupied grave, Godfrey said. And, according to
McLurkin, the city has resold three plots in the potter's field
where people already are buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of straightening out needs to be done there, I know
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, McLurkin was involved in a disastrous effort
to reclaim the African-American side. She was a member of one of
two black churches that asked the city for permission to take care
of the northern section.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, without the city's knowledge, a pulpwood company was
called in to clear the northeast quadrant. Backhoes and bulldozers
devastated graves, leaving headstones broken or buried.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, concerned citizens began working every
other Saturday to clean the grounds. The city launched a plan to
identify graves. And it began to make things right, selling plots
without regard to race.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the northeast quadrant is a green field with a few
monuments. In the center sprouts a colorful flower bed, planted
this spring by Oxford College and Emory University students and
faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers were donated by the Emory Research Center for Myth
and Ritual in American Life, which is researching rural Georgia and
African-American family life, said Oxford College professor Mark
Auslander. Auslander, who calls the situation ``a painful scar for
the community as well as the college,'' said his students were
disheartened to see the cemetery's north side. ``The college was
built by blacks, slave and free,'' he said. ``African-Americans had
been involved with the life of the college.''
</P>
<P>
   The students began working with community members in the
northern section. They raked leaves, cleared brush and repaired
erosion damage.
</P>
<P>
   They also began collecting genealogical information about people
interred there and organized an exhibit, ``Tragic Beauty: Exploring
the Oxford African-American Cemetery,'' dedicated to Godfrey and
the city's black community.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey has made progress in his crusade. A few months ago, he
discovered the foundation's contract had expired. Since then, the
council has extended the agreement month by month while Gladden
seeks a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal would require the foundation to reconstitute
itself, with representatives of the city's four churches, the City
Council and the college as well as two or three at-large positions.
</P>
<P>
   If the foundation agrees to accept responsibility for the entire
cemetery, the city will allocate funds for its upkeep, Gladden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladden has high praise for Elizer's efforts. ``We were lucky,
in one way, that we had the cemetery foundation to maintain a
portion of the cemetery for the last 35 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to try to make it palatable for the foundation
to take on the whole cemetery for perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizer seems resigned to the inevitable but slightly embittered.
After 17 years as president of the foundation, he plans to step
down when his term expires.
</P>
<P>
   Although a new agreement is not likely to be reached before
Sept. 11, when the council meets, Elizer believes a compromise is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we'll be able to come to an agreement by which
there'll just be another group that will maybe rewrite bylaws so
that this foundation will perhaps continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not, another will be formed. And I hope this damn cemetery
can lie in peace now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BANGLADESHI-CONVETION     09-01 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANGLADESHI-CONVETION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE SPLITS BANGLADESHI EVENT INTO TWO
</HEADLINE>
  (Also filed in ``i'' category) 
 By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been a strange month for many
Bangladeshi-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   First, five Bengali-language newspapers received a mysterious
white powder in the mail, with threatening notes alluding to an
annual cultural convention that was the subject of a simmering
dispute. Then, two Bangladeshi groups each claimed to be the
official host of that convention. The two groups, both calling
themselves Bangladesh League of America and contending the other
was an imposter, took each other to court.
</P>
<P>
   The cases are still pending. But after the judge in the case
said there was not enough time to settle the dispute before this
weekend, each group withdrew their motion to block the other's
event. Their decision to withdraw was first reported on Friday in
Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   So the 14th annual convention of the Federation of Bangladeshi
Associations of North America, known as Fobana, is being held in
two places, at Madison Square Garden and at a catering hall in
Astoria, N.Y., in Queens County.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of trouble were planted at last year's Fobana
convention in Atlanta, when New York City was selected as the site
of this year's meeting. Sayeed Rabb, editor of Thikana, a
Bangladeshi newspaper based in New York, accepted the designation
as convention host for the event this year. Shelley E. Mubdi, a
real estate broker, who was absent from the Atlanta event, says
Rabb falsely represented himself as a member of his organization
when he accepted the designation.
</P>
<P>
   Both events began Friday night and were to feature Bangladeshi
artists and cultural seminars and continue through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is still looking into who sent the letters with the
white powder to the Bengali-language newspapers. James Margolin, an
FBI spokesman, said Friday that tests on the powder showed ``no
indication of any chemical agent,'' in the powder, but would not
say what the substance was.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Taher, executive editor of The Weekly Bangla Patrika, one of
the newspapers that received an envelope containing white powder,
recalled that the enclosed letter began, ``Fobana Alert: Take the
sweet taste of nerve gas.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was preparing for his event yesterday, Rabb said he feared
that all the controversy surrounding this year's convention would
keep people away from his convention, at Madison Square Garden,
which he initially said would draw as many as 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to destroy us,'' he said of Mubdi's group.
``They are misleading and lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubdi could not be reached yesterday, but his lawyer, Helen
Lukievics, said Rabb and the woman he says is president of the
Bangladesh League of America, Rani Kabir, were ``identity
thieves,'' who were trying to usurp the leadership of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   According to state records, the Bangladesh League of America was
first incorporated in 1947 under the name the Pakistan League. Both
Mubdi and Rabb claim to be members of that group. But Rabb formed
another organization, called the Bangladesh League of America, New
York, last year, after the Atlanta convention.
</P>
<P>
   Rabb's lawyer, Andrew Moulinos, said Friday that the New York
group was formed as a chapter of the original group. But Mubdi
contended in court papers that Rabb formed the group when Mubdi's
group refused to recognize Kabir as the president of the original
League and ``apparently frustrated,'' went on to create a new group
with a similar name just to confuse matters.
</P>
<P>
   After the conventions are over, the two groups will go back to
court to resolve the question of who are the legitimate leaders of
the Bangladesh League of America.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all this strife has some Bangladeshi-Americans
wondering if the Fobana convention, once a symbol of Bangladeshi
pride and unity, is causing more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirit of Fobana was to get united all the Bangladeshi
living in the United States and Canada,'' said Taher, of The Weekly
Bangla Patrika. ``Now it's a symbol of enmity, a symbol of
division, a symbol of all the bad things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0367 </DOCNO>
