u s BC-TEN-US-OPEN0902-COX     09-01 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US-OPEN0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seles keeps her win streak alive
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They talk about Venus Williams' winning streak, which
stands at 21, but Monica Seles has something going that's just as
amazing if not as impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the U.S. Open quarterfinals for the eighth straight
time Friday, Seles defeated Chanda Rubin 6-3, 4-6, 6-4 for her 58th
consecutive win against players not currently ranked in the top
four.
</P>
<P>
   So when Rubin broke serve for 3-all in the third set, there was
really no reason to worry. Rubin double-faulted, hit a pair of
groundstrokes in the net, then netted a high volley, ruining what
had been an inspiring effort for the former top-10 player from
Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to serve well because my return game was nowhere
where it should be against a player like Chanda if you want to win
the match comfortably,'' said Seles, who faced only three break
points.
</P>
<P>
   Seles hasn't lost to a player of Rubin's stature since Mirjana
Lucic beat her in the round of 32 at Wimbledon 1999. She's 45-0
this year against everyone but Williams, Martina Hingis, Lindsay
Davenport and Mary Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Seles hasn't played No. 5 Serena Williams since last year's U.S.
Open quarterfinals. If Seles can fend off Jennifer Capriati in the
fourth round, she'd likely play Serena Williams here again. No
reason to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be tough for Monica to come up and win, but
like I said, shes a champion,'' Rubin said. ``You can never count
her out.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's field lost 13th seed Amanda Coetzer, beaten by Magui
Serna 7-5, 7-6. That leaves Venus Williams with no potential seeded
opponent until the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's draw, Todd Martin, last year's runner-up, routed
Michael Chang 6-4, 6-2, 6-4. Martin won an astounding 43 of his 44
first serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, he made it pretty easy on me,'' Martin
said. ``He stood on the baseline the whole match, and I served body
serve after body serve, which is the easiest serve to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
