<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COACHES, ONE GAME, AND MANY QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ They coached together, jogged together, even
caught a livestock show or two together while calling College
Station, Texas, their home and the Aggies their team. Now Texas A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum and Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie will face each
other Saturday in an emotional opener.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, in his 12th season at the helm of the Aggies, has heard
rumblings about his job security grow louder after an 8-4 season in
1999. It does not matter that he has won 100 games faster than
anyone except Oklahoma's Barry Switzer and Nebraska's Tom Osborne,
or that his 102 victories represent an average of nine a season.
Aggies fans do not like their team getting shut out in secondary
bowls, as Texas A&AMP;M was by Penn State in the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if he's under fire, I'm under ashes,'' said Davie, who
was Slocum's defensive coordinator before joining Lou Holtz's staff
at Notre Dame in 1994. ``I'm already burned and toasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie, in his fourth year as head coach, is indeed feeling the
pressure after a disappointing season. The Irish lost their final
four games to finish 5-7, their most losses since 1963. The NCAA
handed Notre Dame its first penalty _ probation for two years and
the loss of two scholarships _ because of gifts accepted by players
from a convicted embezzler in the Holtz years.
</P>
<P>
   The combined trauma was enough for the university to hire Kevin
White from Arizona State as its new athletic director and to
realign the department so that the athletic director reports
directly to the university's president, the Rev. Edward A. Malloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the reality is we lost our last four games last year,
and regardless of the reasons, that's not acceptable here at Notre
Dame,'' said Davie, who is 21-16 as head coach. ``I can certainly
see why there may be a perception on the outside that I need to win
X amount of games to save my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people will be tuned to marquee games like Alabama, ranked
No. 3 in the Associated Press news media poll, at UCLA, and No. 22
Southern Mississippi at No. 13 Tennessee. Many more will watch
Davie and the Irish begin what could be a march toward oblivion.
Notre Dame's first five games feature tough opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year playing Texas A&AMP;M, this is probably even
bigger, not just because of how we finished last year, but we have
so many personal ties when it comes to this football game,'' Davie
said. ``We have 20 players on our team from Texas, seven of them
starters, two of them captains.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies are ranked No. 25 in the AP poll. Like the Irish,
Texas A&AMP;M will start an unproven quarterback, Mark Farris, who is a
25-year-old former minor league baseball player. The Irish will
counter with Arnaz Battle, a junior, who has thrown only 35 passes
in the past two seasons as a backup to the departed Jarious
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant Irons, one of Notre Dame's captains, said that critics
should understand that the Fighting Irish spent a focused
off-season reminding themselves of one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come to Notre Dame to be 5-7,'' said Irons, a senior
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum understands his former assistant's precarious position.
But Slocum's response about the stakes of Saturday's game shows he
is confident Davie can overcome it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come late Saturday afternoon,'' Slocum said, ``one of us will
feel pretty good and the other is going to be miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie refuses to look past the Aggies to No. 1 Nebraska next
week in South Bend, or No. 15 Purdue the following week, or
Michigan State and Stanford after that. He also does not want his
team to be distracted by the discussion of his job status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we made progress as a football team, and I'm not
going to spend a second thinking about how many wins this football
team has to have for me to be back here as the head coach,'' said
Davie, who received a five-year contract extension last year. ``I'm
going to focus on each game, and let it rip, and let's go play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
