<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-IXL0902-COX     09-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IXL0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President will leave firm as part of shuffle
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Friday was a rough day for Midtown-based iXL
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a warning that its third-quarter earnings
would miss second-quarter numbers by more than 15 percent, trading
on its stock was halted in the afternoon but not before it hit a
52-week low, and a major executive restructuring was announced that
included the resignation of Bill Nussey, president and director of
iXL Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nussey's resignation comes three months after Consulting
magazine named him ``consultant of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nussey, 34, will be replaced by company founder and Chairman
Bert Ellis, 46. Chief People Officer Barry Sikes, 47, will return
to his previous role as chief operating officer. Sikes will replace
Niraj Shah, 26, who will also return to his previous post as
executive vice president of worldwide operations.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone on Friday, Nussey sounded upbeat and said his
departure from the company had been in the works for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a mutual decision among all the executives at iXL, so
it doesn't come as a surprise to me,'' he said. ``It's part of the
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nussey said it was difficult to leave the company he
helped to build for the past 2 1/2 years. ``It's unfortunate that
I'm leaving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nussey acknowledged that iXL had some challenging financials,
but that the company's reorganization demonstrated iXL's serious
commitment to returning value to its investors. ``We've got great
clients and great people,'' he said. ``The changes we are making
are great for the company now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nussey said Ellis and Sikes are the right people to move iXL
through its difficult times and on to better things. ``The ultimate
challenge facing the company is one Bert and Barry are best suited
for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nussey says he's already accepted another position but wouldn't
say what or where the job was. He hinted that it probably wouldn't
be in the consulting arena. Short-term plans include getting
reacquainted with his 8-week-old baby. ``I'm going to teach him he
has a father,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nussey's resignation coincides with an announcement from the
company late Friday that revenue for the third quarter will be
approximately 15 percent to 20 percent below second-quarter revenue
of $119.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   IXL's woes are part of an overall downturn in the Internet
professional services sector. Companies such as iXL and competitors
such as Viant, Sapient and others are experiencing slowing growth
as the big, ``old economy,'' brick-and-mortar companies that make
up the bulk of their client rosters are feeling less threatened by
upstart dot-com companies and slowing their decisions about Web
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite continued strong demand for our services, larger
clients are focusing on bigger, more complex projects, which has
resulted in extended sales cycles,'' Ellis said in a prepared
statement. Ellis also said iXL was returning to a ``more senior
management team'' that would aggressively reduce costs and realign
the organization to address market and customer demands.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq trading on iXL shares was halted at $8.38 after several
Wall Street firms downgraded the entire professional services
sector. Among those rethinking the company's earnings potential was
Merrill Lynch, the company that led iXL's initial public offering
last year.
</P>
<P>
   BB&AMP;T Capital Markets' Thomas Neuhaus also cut his rating on iXL
Enterprises, lowering it to ``hold'' from ``long-term buy.'' He
also cut his ratings on the entire e-business professional services
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus said he ``previously assumed Global 2000 companies would
continue with their e-business initiatives,'' even though they now
see dot-coms as ``less of a threat.'' For iXL Enterprises, which
has targeted Global 2000 companies ``from day one,'' according to
Neuhaus, that slowdown could present problems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
