<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have been sent as part of tonight's New
York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 09/01/00.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ACLU-GLASER -- Ira Glasser,
who is 62, has ushered the American Civil Liberties Union into the
new century, helping to transform it in his 22 years as executive
director, and yet, it turns out, he left himself behind, at least
in technological terms. But he will have time to catch up and get
his first cell phone and desktop computer, for the ACLU will
announce next week that he is retiring on July 1. (Nancy Siesel/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-5 -- Baseline
veteran Michael Chang was defeated Friday by Todd Martin, unseeded
and the 1999 Open runner-up to Agassi. Martin escaped the steamy
conditions with a 6-4, 6-2, 6-4 win over Chang. Martin had lost to
Chang in five of six previous matches. Chang in action during his
match with Martin. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) IN FLIGHT -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- BUSH-2 -- Returning to
Austin, Texas after a long, hot day of campaigning in Louisiana and
Arkansas on Friday, Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
presidential candidate, settles back with Key Lime pie and ice
cream and wrote thank you notes to supporters. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CARS-NAMES-3 -- Black is
back. Not the color, necessarily, but the name. On Thursday at the
U.S. Open in New York, Lincoln introduced its 2002 Blackwood luxury
truck. Lincoln Blackwood's stainless-steel cargo bed and
power-operated cover. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CARS-NAMES-2 -- Black is
back. Not the color, necessarily, but the name. Buick has put the
final touches on a show car, the Blackhawk, that will make the
rounds of custom-car and hot-rod shows. Buick's Blackhawk custom
car flaunts a 1939 grille and 1940s style body. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CARS-NAMES-1 -- Black is
back. Not the color, necessarily, but the name. Buick has put the
final touches on a show car, the Blackhawk, that will make the
rounds of custom-car and hot-rod shows. Buick's Blackhawk custom
car flaunts a 1939 grille and 1940s style body. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ANTI-CHRONOLOGY-2 -- In the
art world, antichronology seems to be the rage. Numerous U.S.
museums have re-hung their painting and sculpture collections
according to subject instead of chronology. Cezanne's ``Bather,
left, from 1885, in the show ``Modern Starts: People, Places,
Things'' at the Museum of Modern Art. At right, Rineke Dijkstra's
photograph of a boy from 1993 is hung next to the Cezanne, at left,
at the Modern. (Musem of Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK-- Sept. 1, 2000 -- TEN-OPEN-4 -- Todd Martin,
right, walks off the court with Michael Chang after Todd's victory
at the U.S. Open, Friday. Martin defeated Chang 6-4, 6-2, 6-4.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ATLANTA -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CHENEY-STOCKS -- Republican
vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney said Friday he was ``fully
prepared to forfeit'' oil-company stock options that he would
otherwise continue to hold after taking office if he and George W.
Bush win in November. Cheney heads to the podium for a speech on
military readiness during a campaign stop Wednesday afternoon in
Atlanta. (Ben Gray/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3 --
CHOW-HOTSPOT -- In the past year or so, Mr. Chow, the eatery on
East 57th Street, has re-emerged as a destination for all
subspecies of the moneyed and glamorous. Wyclef Jean, the hip-hop
performer, dining with guests at Mr. Chow's in Manhattan. (Aaron
Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3 --
NITEOUT-AMANDA-PEET -- Amanda Peet at the premiere of her new
movie, ``Whipped'' on Tuesday night at Chelsea Cinemas in New York.
Peet has every right to be confident now, even though her manager
and agent anxiously followed her through the night like pilot fish.
She is taping her second season of ``Jack and Jill,'' a series on
the WB Television Network. And ``Whipped'' is a breakout movie for
her, a real starring role. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3 --
ROBOT-DOGS-2 -- After Sony's tail-wagging success with its Aibo
robo-dog -- it sold out its entire 45,000-unit production run of
the $2,500 electric critters last winter -- at least four toy
companies are putting their own, less expensive versions on the
market this fall. A youngster in the Washington Square Park dog run
in New York fascinated by Sony's Aibo robot dog. (David Corio/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3 --
ROBOT-DOGS-1 -- After Sony's tail-wagging success with its Aibo
robo-dog -- it sold out its entire 45,000-unit production run of
the $2,500 electric critters last winter -- at least four toy
companies are putting their own, less expensive versions on the
market this fall. But to a dog is it a dog? Sony's Aibo robot dog
meets a jury of its would-be peers at the Washington Square Park
dog run in New York. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LONDON -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3 --
OLY-BUSINESS-2 -- No matter what happens on the track, in the pool
or on the field at the 2000 Summer Games, there may be no more
dramatic comeback in 2000 than the one the International Olympic
Committee has made on the sponsorship front. Eleven global
sponsorships, as well as all 200 national Olympic committees and
their teams, should bring in $605 million leading up to the Sydney
Games. At Boots Chemists in London, Physio Sport body products on
display with the Olympic logo. (Carlos Lopez Barillas/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SEPT. 3
-- OLY-BUSINESS-1 -- No matter what happens on the track, in the
pool or on the field at the 2000 Summer Games, there may be no more
dramatic comeback in 2000 than the one the International Olympic
Committee has made on the sponsorship front. Eleven global
sponsorships, as well as all 200 national Olympic committees and
their teams, should bring in $605 million leading up to the Sydney
Games. Eastman Kodak Company cameras, from one of the
longest-standing Olympic corporate sponsors. (The New York
Times/Eastman Kodak)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 3 --
JOHNNIE-COCHRAN -- Success is not new to Johnnie Cochran, now 62.
Long before his mustache and sharp ties became a daily staple of
the grisly O.J. Simpson murder trial, he was a big-time lawyer with
a heavy criminal practice. His disciplined, relentless
cross-examination at the trial, however, made Cochran one of the
most famous and controversial lawyers in America. But it didn't
leave him as rich as it left him famous. Now, he is determined to
close that gap. Cochran in Manhattan earlier this month. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SCHAUMBURG, Ill. -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT.
3 -- GENERAL-ELECTRIC-2 -- Women, Blacks, Latinos and Asians
together, together make up about 40 percent of the General Electric
Co.'s domestic work force, but they are not easy to find in the top
executive corps of GE, which is regarded in many management circles
as America's most admired corporation. The GE Women's Network helps
members develop leadership qualities. Members of the Women's
Network at GE Medical Systems meeting in Schaumburg, Ill. (Steve
Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) FARMINGTON, Conn. -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.
SEPT. 3 -- GENERAL-ELECTRIC-1 -- Women, Blacks, Latinos and Asians
together, together make up about 40 percent of the General Electric
Co.'s domestic work force, but they are not easy to find in the top
executive corps of GE, which is regarded in many management circles
as America's most admired corporation. Lloyd G. Trotter, with his
wife, Teri, at home in Connecticut, is the only nonwhite head of a
major GE unit. Trotter is a senior vice president of the parent
corporation. (George Ruhe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- LINUX-BOS -- Nat
Friedman, president of the Cambridge-based Helix Code Inc. Friedman
and software designer Miguel de Icaza, founded Helix Code to
commercialize Gnome software, a user-friendly interface for the
Linux operating system. A quarter-million people have already
downloaded Helix Gnome from the company Web site since it was
released in March. Among the small but influential clique who run
Linux software on their personal computers, Helix Gnome is on its
way to being the gold standard. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
Story moved on Aug. 21, 2000
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LEXINGTON, Mass. -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- RAYTHEON-STRIKE-BOS
-- An estimated 200 Raytheon Co. strikers, members of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 1505,
rallied in Lexington, Mass., Thursday, to support the union's
dwindling ranks and to push for more top-of-the-line manufacturing
jobs. It is corporate America's increased reliance on white-collar
engineering, technical and service staff, and a corresponding push
to subcontract manufacturing jobs or move them to lower-cost states
or countries, that has unions like Local 1505 up in arms. (Bill
Polo/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CLINTON-MISSILES-2 --
President Clinton, saying he lacks ``absolute confidence'' in
existing technology, announced Friday he would leave to the next
president a decision on whether to begin deployment of a national
missile defense. Clinton listens to Georgetown Dean Robert Gallucci
before his speech at Georgetown University, Friday. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times) NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN-3 -- Jennifer
Capriati signs autographs following match against Adriana Gersi,
Friday. Capriati, seeded 15, ousted Gersi of the Czech Republic
6-2, 6-3. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN-2 -- Martina
Hingis returns a shot to Tathiana Garbin Friday during the U.S.
Open. Top-seeded Hingis beat Garbin 6-1, 6-0. (G. Paul Burnett/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- TEN-US-OPEN -- Sixth-seeded
Monica Seles returns a shot to Chanda Rubin, Friday during the U.S.
Open. Seles fought off to lead a parade of favorites into the
fourth round of the U.S. Open tennis championships Friday. Seles
had the hardest time before beating Chanda Rubin 6-3, 4-6, 6-4. (G.
Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LAFAYETTE, La. -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George W.
Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, boards his campaign
plane enroute to Arkansas after a campaign rally in Lafayette,
Friday. Bush pronounced his Republican presidential campaign ``in
excellent shape'' on Friday, claiming he has the momentum against
Al Gore despite distractions and slipping polls. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- NEW-TECHNOLOGY-LAW-B&AMP;W --
Existing law can fit poorly with technological developments, mostly
because the legislators who drafted the laws did not anticipate
them. Legal experts have no trouble thinking of similar examples
from the past. Susan P. Crawford, who specializes in Internet
issues at Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering in Washington, noted the sheet
music industry's challenge to the new player piano technology in
1908. An advertisement for the Angelus player piano in the early
20th century. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- ANTI-CHRONOLOGY -- In the art
world, antichronology seems to be the rage. Numerous U.S. museums
have re-hung their painting and sculpture collections according to
subject instead of chronology. The Tate Modern has Richard Long's
``Slate Circle 1979'' opposite Claude Monet's ``Water Lillies.''
(The Tate Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- CLINTON-MISSILES --
President Clinton, saying he lacks ``absolute confidence'' in
existing technology, announced Friday he would leave to the next
president a decision on whether to begin deployment of a national
missile defense. Clinton is introduced to the audience by Dean
Robert Gallucci before his speech at Georgetown University, Friday.
(Susana Raab/The New York Times) NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 2000 -- BUSH-AD -- The Republican
National Committee is to begin running this 30-second commercial,
titled ``Really,'' in 16 states starting Friday. The ad combines
television images of Gore with cornful dialogue and a not yet
operational Web address. (The New York Times)
</P>
