<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CARTOON-MUSEUM0903-CO     09-01 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOON-MUSEUM0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Museum's financial straits no laughing matter
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mizner Park isn't exactly Camp Swampy, but it
has become a morass for Mort Walker's International Museum of
Cartoon Art.
</P>
<P>
   After a promising start when it opened in Boca Raton four years
ago, the museum ran into fund-raising problems and is now ready to
leave town if things don't get better, Walker said. The museum has
even identified a possible site for the collection in midtown
Manhattan. If the building can be sold for the right price _ it's
worth $10 million, according to Walker _ the board is ready to
move.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the museum is still trying to find a partner to share
space and expenses after several proposals fell through, including
a nearly done-deal with the Florida Atlantic University Foundation.
Walker said he's currently sifting through a half-dozen new offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to leave Boca Raton,'' Walker said. ``We love
the city, and we have a beautiful buiIding. But it's a great
disappointment that we've received little financial support from
this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker initially opened the museum in Greenwich, Conn., in 1974
to house his growing collection of cartoon art. The museum then
found new quarters in suburban New York. The vintage collection
grew to more than 150,000 pieces of art and animated film, and the
museum was offered the Mizner Park site by the City Redevelopment
Agency for $1 a year. The museum moved to Boca Raton in 1992, and
broke ground in 1994 on the first phase of its $15 million project.
</P>
<P>
   The building's first floor opened in 1996, but lack of money has
prevented the museum from completing work on the second and third
floors. At roughly 70,000 visitors a year, attendance is fair but
nowhere near the 150,000 people anticipated. The museum is behind
on roughly $1.1 million in mortgage payments but won a small
victory when a Palm Beach County Circuit Court judge recently ruled
that SunTrust bank couldn't take physical possession of classic
Mickey Mouse drawings that the museum had put up as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early fund raising came from the publishing
industry. With roughly $7.5 million in cash and pledges, the
museum's board decided to begin construction. ``We thought if we
had a building up and the art to show, local individuals would
become as enthusiastic about the project as we were. It didn't
happen, and I don't know exactly why. In retrospect, we probably
made a mistake opening too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had two directors who didn't raise any money,'' Walker
added. ``We probably lost two years there. We need somebody to make
us an offer that would give us some security. But we feel we're
going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Board president Joseph D'Angelo, retired president of King
Features Syndicate, said the museum needs ``$5 to $10 million in
fund raising, which isn't that much for a incredibly wealthy area
like Boca Raton and Palm Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the money isn't raised? ``We'd move to New York in a
heartbeat,'' said D'Angelo. ``As much as it would really disturb us
to have to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
