u s BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      09-01 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES SIGN A NEW DEAL BUT 22 ARE LEFT UNCOVERED
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without so much as a threat of a work stoppage, the new umpires'
union has negotiated a new five-year labor agreement and has
apparently forged a new relationship with Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard it to be a very positive agreement for both sides,''
Rob Manfred, baseball's chief labor relations executive, said
Friday. ``It really lays the foundation for a real good, solid
working relationship with this union, something we haven't had in a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, representatives for baseball and the World
Umpires Association completed work on the agreement, which must be
ratified by the umpires and the club owners, after an intense week
of talks at baseball offices in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, the first negotiated for umpires by someone other
than Richie Phillips, the ousted leader of the former union, does
not cover the 22 umpires who lost their jobs a year ago Saturday as
a result of Phillips' failed resignation strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the new union had worked out a settlement under
which 10 to 13 of the umpires would have regained their jobs as
part of the new agreement and the others would have received
retirement or severance packages.
</P>
<P>
   But the unemployed umpires rejected the plan, preferring instead
to await the outcome of their arbitration hearing, most likely
later this year. The umpires would have had to withdraw their
grievance under terms of the proposed settlement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement includes two elements that are new to umpires'
labor contracts: an annual escalation in pay and a neutral
fact-finder for disciplinary cases.
</P>
<P>
   In past agreements, the negotiated pay scale remained in place
for the life of the deal. In the new agreement, salaries will rise
each year. Details were not disclosed in the announcement of the
agreement, but one person with knowledge of it said the salary of
the most senior umpires would rise from $225,000 in the contract
that expired last Dec. 31 to about $250,000 for this year to about
$340,000 in the fifth year, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of a neutral fact-finder gives the umpires
some recourse if they are fired, suspended for more than seven days
or fined more than $2,000. Although not on the same level as the
impartial arbitrator who decides player challenges to disciplinary
action, the fact-finder will determine the underlying facts in a
disputed case and report them to a baseball official.
</P>
<P>
   Findings on dismissals will go to Commissioner Bud Selig and
findings on suspensions and fines will go to Sandy Alderson,
executive vice president for baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Selig and Alderson will then decide whether the dismissal or
discipline was justified. The union had sought the adoption of the
arbitration system but settled for the fact-finder.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, the result of six months of negotiations, also
includes the creation of a joint committee to establish a new
system of training umpires and evaluating them when they work in
the major leagues. Evaluation has long been a sore practice with
umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long process,'' John Hirschbeck, the union
president, said. ``But with the outcome I couldn't be happier for
the profession, for all umpires and the working relationship we've
established with Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck and the union's other top officials, Joe Brinkman and
Tim Welke, were joined in negotiations by two lawyers, Joel Smith
and Larry Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck and Brinkman led the group of umpires who worked to
oust Phillips and the Major League Umpires Association and install
a new union. The new union prevailed in a vote conducted last
January by the New York office of the National Labor Relations
Board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
