<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-2NDLD     09-01 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO LEAVE DECISION ON MISSILE SHIELD TO HIS SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change `called' to `informed' in 3rd graf of 2nd take.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2,9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(EDS NOTE: The complete text of President Clinton's speech is
available from The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com) By
ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Friday that he did not
believe that the technology was ready yet for an effective national
defense system, and passed the decision on moving ahead with the
politically charged and diplomatically delicate project to his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that the threat of future missile attacks from
states like Iraq or North Korea ``is real and growing'' and that
the United States had to search for new defenses. But after several
failed tests and strong resistance from Russia, China and America's
closest allies in Europe, the president announced that he would not
authorize even initial construction on the missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made progress, but we should not move forward until we
have absolute confidence the system will work,'' he said,
announcing one of his most important foreign policy decisions in a
speech at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Clinton laid out an articulate case, both in
politics and substance, for why it was dangerous to plunge headlong
into a $60 billion program that would violate a landmark arms
control treaty with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national missile defense, if deployed, should be part of a
larger strategy to preserve and enhance the peace, strength and
security we now enjoy, and to build an even safer world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision comes just before the Labor Day holiday
weekend, while Congress is still in summer recess, and just days
before he is to meet world leaders in New York at the United
Nations. He has taken off the table an issue that otherwise might
have soured his scheduled meetings with other leaders, including
President Vladimir Putin of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is also likely to open up much broader debate on
the issue between the presidential contenders, who have adopted
starkly different approaches toward missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee, has
largely embraced the administration's stand of building a limited
land-based system without withdrawing from the Antiballistic
Missile Treaty of 1972. The Republican nominee, Gov. George W.
Bush, favors a broader system that could include sea- and
space-based arms.
</P>
<P>
   On May 23, Bush signaled his support for Clinton's leaving the
decision to the next administration rather than committing the
country to a course based on incomplete information, saying, ``No
decision would be better than a flawed agreement that ties the
hands of the next president and prevents America from defending
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Bush adopted a much sharper tone, criticizing the
administration's handling of the missile defense program. ``I
welcome the opportunity to act where they have failed to lead by
developing and deploying effective missiles to protect all 50
states and our friends and allies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Gore said he supported Clinton's decision, one
that aides said he had discussed with the president, and implicitly
criticized Bush's plan, which would require the United States to
withdraw from the ABM treaty. The accord bars Washington and Moscow
from building national missile defenses, unless Moscow agrees to
changes, which so far it has steadfastly refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I would oppose the kinds of missile defense
systems that would unnecessarily upset strategic stability and
threaten to open the gates for a renewed arms race with Russia and
a new arms race with China,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, leaders throughout Europe, who had been caught
between America's ambitions for missile defenses and the strong
opposition from Russia and China, applauded Clinton's decision,
though they seemed mostly relieved. And Russian officials expressed
satisfaction that their diplomatic campaign, mainly by Putin, to
galvanize opposition against the American program had apparently
helped persuade Clinton to abandon it.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate upshot of Clinton's decision is that the
Pentagon's 2005 target date for having an initial, limited means of
defending all 50 states against attack by a small number of
ballistic missiles has been scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   To stick to that ambitious schedule, Clinton would have had to
authorize the Pentagon by December to award contracts for initial
construction on Shemya Island in Alaska of a powerful new radar
that would provide the missile-tracking ability needed for an
effective missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   But an independent panel led by a retired Air Force general,
Larry D. Welch, determined earlier this year that because of the
program's enormous technical complexity and the likelihood of
technical glitches and other delays, a deployment date of 2006 or
2007 was more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seized on that analysis to assert that his decision
``will not have a significant impact on the date the overall system
could be deployed in the next administration if the next president
decides to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, Clinton's decision probably means that work on
the Shemya radar cannot begin before 2002, which insures that a
national missile defense could not be completed before 2006 at the
earliest. The decision gives the next president leeway to
restructure the program or reorder its priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen, the lone Republican in
Clinton's Cabinet, was the administration's most forceful advocate
of fielding national missile defenses as soon as possible. Cohen
recommended to Clinton last week and in a meeting at the White
House on Tuesday that he go ahead with that initial construction.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse, three-paragraph statement, Cohen said, ``I have
noted on many occasions that several emerging threats warrant the
deployment of an effective missile defense program as soon as
technologically feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had previously said the final decision
to field a missile defense system would rest with Clinton's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   But even the preliminary step of breaking ground and pouring a
concrete foundation at the Alaska site could have been interpreted
as a violation of the ABM treaty, according to some legal analyses
prepared by administration lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russia has refused to permit the United States to change the
treaty, a cornerstone of cold war-era arms control policy, and
Clinton was loath to have his name in the history books as the
president who withdrew the United States from the landmark accord.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the diplomatic repercussions, Clinton's national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, as well as Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and her deputy, Strobe Talbott, the chief
American negotiator with Russia, opposed permitting the initial
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Berger telephoned several Congressional leaders late Thursday to
alert them to Clinton's decision. Albright also called several
world leaders and lawmakers Friday, and Clinton informed President
Jacques Chirac of France.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Democrats, scores of whom had urged Clinton to
defer all decisions on the system, applauded the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's decision gives us time to perfect our
political approach to the ballistic missile threat, as well as our
technology,'' said Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. of Delaware, the
ranking Democrat on the Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican reaction was mixed, with some of the program's
biggest backers decrying another delay. ``Because of the
president's misguided decision, our children will remain completely
unprotected against the weapon of choice for rogue nations and
terrorist groups _ the missile,'' said Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, said, ``This is
yet another example of the Clinton-Gore administration's legacy of
missed opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But two prominent Republican members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Gordon H. Smith of Oregon and Chuck Hagel of
Nebraska, praised Clinton's choice. ``The president made the right
decision today,'' Hagel said. ``There will be dangerous
consequences for America and the world if we rush to meet arbitrary
decision deadlines.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton said American security was based on the
three pillars of diplomacy, deterrence and defense. ``No one
suggests that NMD would ever substitute for diplomacy or for
deterrence,'' Clinton said, using the abbreviation for national
missile defense. ``But such a system, if it worked properly, could
give us an extra dimension of insurance in a world where
proliferation has complicated the task of preserving the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and his top advisers established four criteria to
judge whether to move the system ahead: threat, cost, technology
and impact on American security, including arms control agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a balancing act that has to be taken,'' Berger told
reporters after Clinton's speech. ``The way I ask the question is,
will we be more secure or less secure?''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials did not quarrel about the reality of
the threat, even though Clinton noted that North Korea had
refrained from testing new, long-range missiles. And while the cost
of the system's initial phase, consisting of 100 missile
interceptors and a system of early-warning radars, had increased by
about $4 billion in recent months to a total of $25 billion,
growing federal budget surpluses had eased concern about that.
</P>
<P>
   But the system had run into a number of technical problems.
After a largely successful first test last fall, the next two tests
failed, including the latest on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that crucial elements of the program, like the
booster rocket for the missile interceptor, were behind schedule
and had yet to be tested. Experts still had concerns whether the
interceptors could adequately distinguish enemy warheads from
decoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply cannot conclude, with the information that is
available to us today, that we have enough confidence in the
technology and operational effectiveness of this entire system to
move ahead with deployment,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, China, Russia and European allies all voiced fears that
even beginning the initial construction could violate the ABM
treaty and trigger a new arms race, especially in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Given the potential diplomatic consequences, administration
officials said, there was little reason to push ahead with even the
preliminary construction when chances that an effective system
could be up and working by 2005 were slim.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several months, the domestic politics changed as
well. With Republicans like Hagel and Smith, among others, calling
for Clinton to defer, Gore was shielded to some extent from any
political fallout if the administration decided to leave the
deployment decisions to the next president.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has always been ambivalent about a
limited missile defense system, arguing for years that the threat
did not warrant spending billions of dollars on unproven
technology, which had its origins in the vaunted Star Wars proposal
of the Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House did an abrupt about-face in mid-1998 after
two things happened. First, a bipartisan commission headed by
Donald H. Rumsfeld, a Republican and former defense secretary,
warned that within five years North Korea and Iran could
conceivably reach the United States with long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Then, six weeks later, as if on cue, North Korea took American
intelligence experts by surprise by testing a three-stage missile
with perhaps enough range to hit North America.
</P>
<P>
   By early last year, the White House was pledging its conditional
support and $10.5 billion over six years to a limited system. Last
summer, Clinton signed into law the National Missile Defense Act,
which requires the United States to field a national defense
against a limited strike when technologically feasible. An original
sponsor of the legislation was Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, a
Connecticut Democrat who is now Gore's running mate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MISSILE-REACT-1STLD-W     09-01 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS SEE CLINTON'S DECISION AS DIPLOMATIC VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change `Millennium Summit' to `global summit meeting' in
first graf of optional material.)  
(With MISSILE-DEFENSE and related stories) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As European leaders on Friday applauded President
Clinton's decision to defer building a missile defense shield over
the United States, Russian officials expressed satisfaction that
their diplomatic campaign to galvanize opposition against the
American program had influenced Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   A former Russian ambassador to the United States, Vladimir P.
Lukin, who serves as deputy speaker of Parliament here, called
Clinton's decision predictable and rational and said that Russian
President Vladimir Putin had scored a temporary diplomatic victory.
He cautioned, however, that the contentious international issue
would return early next year.
</P>
<P>
   European officials, caught between America's ambitions for
missile defenses and the strident opposition from Russia and China,
seemed mostly relieved. Across the continent, political leaders
said Clinton's decision removed the issue from American
presidential politics and created needed time for increasingly
complex consultations and debate over missile threats and how to
cope with them.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac, one of the most pointed critics
of the American plan, was the only leader to issue a personal
statement Friday night. He said he had been informed of Clinton's
decision by letter Friday, which he said he received with ``great
interest'' given France's view that the project ``risks undermining
the strategic equilibrium and a return to the nuclear arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain and Germany praised Clinton's decision. A
spokesman in Berlin, Bela Anda, said the government of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder had ``understanding and respect'' for the ``wise
decision,'' adding that Germany's ``reservations about this project
are well known.'' Karsten D. Voigt, who coordinates German-American
affairs in the foreign ministry, said the decision was welcome
because it gave more time for consultations inside the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Foreign Minister Robin Cook said Clinton had ``taken
careful account of the views'' of American ``allies and other
international partners'' in pulling up short on the deployment of
missile defenses, which would violate the Antiballistic Missile
Treaty of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to continuing dialogue on this subject with
the current'' administration in Washington ``and, in due course,
with its successor, and with our NATO allies and others,'' Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, the leader who worked hardest this year at undermining
American justification for going ahead with missile defenses, was
conspicuously silent Friday night in the face of what was seen
here, for now, as a diplomatic victory of sorts. Still, Clinton's
decision only puts off until some time next year the potential
confrontation between Moscow and Washington over the future of
long-standing arms control agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader leaves Moscow this weekend for visits to
Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has said it will not agree to changes in the 1972 treaty,
and has warned that an American decision to break the treaty would
render all arms control agreements signed between Washington and
Moscow during three decades null and void.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Putin undertook an energetic diplomatic
campaign in Europe and Asia against the American plan to erect a
missile shield over the United States, one that would leave Europe
outside the defensive umbrella and that would perhaps incite China
to build up its nuclear arsenal further, thus triggering further
escalation in the arms race in South Asia between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader even flew to the North Korean capital,
Pyongyang, and secured an as yet unelaborated promise from Kim Jong
Il, the country's reclusive leader, to give up North Korea's
long-range missile program in return for Western space-launch
assistance for North Korean satellites.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting this proposal to the large industrial nations at a
July summit meeting in Okinawa, Putin sought to refute the American
assertion that North Korea's long-range missile program posed such
an acute threat to the United States that early deployment of
missile defenses was warranted. Moreover, a budding rapprochement
between North and South Korea, whose leaders met this summer for
the first time since the Korean War, further deflated any sense of
imminent danger from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Lukin, the former Russian ambassador to the United States, said
he believed Clinton made his decision based exclusively on domestic
political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision by Clinton would have been reassessed as soon as a
new administration took over anyway, Lukin said, and Clinton did
not want to do anything that would be detrimental to the Democratic
Party, like making compromises with Moscow that would subject Vice
President Al Gore to political attacks during the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate, George W. Bush, has
criticized the Clinton-Gore administration for failing to
strengthen America's defenses, and has said that if he is elected
president, he will proceed with a missile defense system at the
earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was able to capitalize on serious concerns in Europe and
Asia that the United States was creating ``an unequal security
system'' between itself, its NATO allies and other major powers
like Russia and China, Lukin observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has unified everyone against the United States, including
your allies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lukin added that it would be ``unwise for Putin to
celebrate any victory'' over Friday's decision because ``it is only
temporary and is connected with internal politics in the United
States.'' As of January 2001, he said, a new American president
will face substantial political pressure to deploy a missile
defense system, if further testing proves the system viable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The timing of Clinton's announcement may spare him some
criticism from world leaders assembling at the United Nations next
week for a global summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   China's president, Jiang Zemin, was said to be preparing to
express Beijing's opposition to the American missile defense plan
during a speech to the leaders, according to a senior diplomat in
the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
   Certain countries are still seeking so-called absolute security
for themselves and are speeding up the development and deployment
of advanced anti-missile systems, a senior Chinese diplomat told
reporters in Beijing on Thursday. Jiang had been expected to assert
that American missile defenses would seriously undermine the
positive trend in international disarmament efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The American defense system poses particularly difficult
decisions for European countries like Great Britain and Denmark,
whose territories might be needed to enhance American radar
capabilities to shoot down incoming ballistic missiles from states
like North Korea, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a House of Commons foreign affairs committee urged
the government to encourage Washington to address the nuclear
threat from rogue states by means other than the proposed missile
shield, which would not be able to stop a nuclear, chemical or
biological weapon delivered in a suitcase, or on a ship, or other
than by missile. The committee said it was not convinced the plan
represented an appropriate response to potential threats.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on Clinton's announcement, Menzies Campbell, a
leader of the Liberal Democratic Party in Great Britain, said,
``The British government must seize the opportunity provided by
President Clinton's decision to make a robust case against
deployment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
