<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-1     09-01 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: re-tops, writes thru to include speech
 &HT;    MEXICO'S ZEDILLO TRUMPETS 'MARCH TOWARD DEMOCRACY', DESPITE
PARTY'S DEFEAT
 &HT;    (750&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In his final State of the Nation address Friday
night, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo acknowledged the historic
defeat of his party in July but said Mexico can be proud that ``she
has completed her march toward democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans voted with freedom and in secret. Each vote counted,
and as in any democracy, the majority decided,'' Zedillo said in a
speech laced with personal observations about democracy and his own
struggle to reverse an economic crisis he inherited when he took
office in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Yale-educated economist also spoke of his work with other
Mexican political parties to reform this country's electoral laws
and end years of fraud and unfair advantage for his party, the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common purpose that I expressed on Dec. 1, 1994 has been
fulfilled,'' Zedillo said to applause from the Mexican Congress.
``We were all satisfied with the way in which the election was
held, independent of the results . . . Election day was marked by
tranquility and a high degree of participation, and it was preceded
by the most intense and competitive campaign in our history. At the
end of that day, some won and some of us lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, whose six-year term ends Dec. 1, is the last Mexican
president representing the 71-year presidential reign of the PRI,
which was born from the tumult of the 1910 Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI lost Mexico's July 2 election to Vicente Fox Quesada of
the National Action Party, or PAN, who ran on a platform calling
for change and an end to the PRI's monopoly on power.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Zedillo's greatest legacy when he leaves office in
December may be his party's defeat. He has been praised both at
home and abroad for gracefully acknowledging Fox's victory and
promising to work toward a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's presidency was born from tragedy, after he was
reluctantly drafted to be the PRI's presidential nominee after the
assassination of candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio.
</P>
<P>
   He came into office after Mexico tried to rush headlong into
free-market economic reforms. The over-valued peso was slashed in
half, prompting a crisis that still affects Mexicans today.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is credited with stabilizing the economy, sparking
growth and turning Mexico into a world-class export nation. But
critics say Mexico's poor and middle classes suffered most from his
fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Zedillo defended his public spending cuts and
devaluation, saying the crisis would have been worse without
decisive measures. But left-wing members of Congress held up signs
declaring ``Lies _ 60 million in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo promised to break a 30-year cycle of fiscal crisis in
Mexico that has followed the last five PRI administrations. Because
of careless spending, corruption and other mismanagement by
previous presidents, Mexicans saw the peso's value cut cyclically
and their buying power eroded.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Zedillo has vowed that ``the Mexican economy will
have no jolts or setbacks in connection with the change of
government. It can count on the right conditions to keep growing in
the coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo was given a 69 percent approval rating in a poll
published Friday by Reforma newspaper. That contrasts sharply with
the 60 percent disapproval rating published in December 1995, a
year after he took office.
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo's legacy still includes some low points that proved
embarrassing and politically damaging. Before he spoke Friday night
opposition orators in Mexico's Congress lashed out, reminding
listeners of a long chain of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   During Zedillo's administration Mexicans took on a bank bailout
of more than US$60 billion that has been marked by reports of
corrupt bankers taking advantage of the program. His own campaign
is under scrutiny for allegedly benefiting from illicit
contributions from a banker accused of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   His tourism secretary, Oscar Villarreal, has disappeared after
being accused of embezzling funds while Mexico City mayor several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the anti-drug czar Zedillo had appointed, Gen. Jesus
Gutierrez Rebollo, was charged with colluding with one of Mexico's
most wanted traffickers. And for several years now, vows from
Zedillo's administration to arrest the leaders of a violent
Tijuana-based drug cartel have gone unfulfilled, drawing criticism
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And in December that year, 45 people in a pro-Zapatista rebel
village were massacred by PRI loyalists in the state of Chiapas.
Zedillo expanded the military presence in Chiapas in response,
deported some foreign human rights observers and has faced
criticism for failing to resolve the original conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zedillo: You go with your hands stained with Indian blood,''
said one sign held up in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the July 2 election, election officials here accused
Zedillo of helping his party's presidential candidate by refusing
to pull pro-government ads off the air boasting of achievements
during his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on election night Zedillo was the first to congratulate
Fox, and action that calmed markets but enraged some PRI
hardliners. His willingness to acknowledge defeat won admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernesto Zedillo is going to leave office with a great public
legitimacy. I think few Mexicans have much to criticize. Those who
are criticizing him are a small group of PRI insiders who probably
don't number more than 1,000,'' said political analyst Jaime
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who thought the president could still
engineer fraud to win elections,'' Gonzalez added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zedillo has been unusually stubborn and obstinate,
fundamentalist, and politically, quite clumsy,'' wrote Milenio
magazine columnist Raymundo Riva Palacio. ``But Zedillo is
finishing his term as a president acclaimed throughout the world
for having ushered in the end of a closed system . . . These are
the paradoxes of public life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
