<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OLYMPICS _ &LR;  The Olympic flag is being hoisted high in Sydney,
Australia, and so are the hopes of 11 corporate sponsors that are
spending tens of millions of dollars each for an Olympic-size halo
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Mega-corporations from Coca-Cola to IBM have ponied up an
average of $55 million each for four years as the Games' global
sponsors, a whopping sum that doesn't even include airtime for ads.
The primary benefit is the use of the Olympic name and rings in
advertising, plus ``category exclusivity'' _ FedEx can't advertise
during the games, for example, because UPS is a sponsor.  &UR; BY CAROL
EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINE _ &LR;  California's wine industry uncorked an unprecedented
number of mergers and acquisitions this week, and vintners
anticipate many more deals as wineries combine to gain financial
and marketing clout.
</P>
<P>
   Darwinian forces are shaking up one of the most prestigious and,
at $13 billion a year, one of the biggest industries in California.
The wine business, just like banking and telecommunications, is
becoming a global endeavor in which size does matter.  &UR; BY PETER
SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; XBOX _ &LR;  Microsoft unveiled a slate of 18 companies Friday,
including two Bay Area studios, that will develop video games for
its upcoming Xbox, the software juggernaut's first foray into the
console market.
</P>
<P>
   The company said two subsidiaries of Lionhead Studios _ the
British firm behind the highly anticipated computer game Black &AMP;
White _ will create titles for Xbox. Others include Stormfront
Studios, which makes a popular line of NASCAR games, and Totally
Games, both of San Rafael, Calif.  &UR; BY KELLY ZITO &LR;
</P>
