<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WINE-MERGERS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-01 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-MERGERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WINERIES ARE RIPE FOR THE PICKING  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's wine industry uncorked an
unprecedented number of mergers and acquisitions this week, and
vintners anticipate many more deals as wineries combine to gain
financial and marketing clout.
</P>
<P>
   Darwinian forces are shaking up one of the most prestigious and,
at $13 billion a year, one of the biggest industries in California.
The wine business, just like banking and telecommunications, is
becoming a global endeavor in which size does matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Wine Group, a San Francisco firm best known
for its inexpensive bag-in-the-box Franzia wines, agreed to buy the
bulk of Sonoma's Sebastiani Vineyards in a deal estimated to be
worth more than $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, Australia's Foster's Brewing Group said it
would purchase Beringer Wine Estate Holdings, one of Napa's most
venerable vintners, for $1.5 billion. The same day, Canada's Vincor
International announced a deal for R.H. Phillips of Esparto,
Calif., worth $92 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mergers, consumers still enjoy a multiplicity of
choice. California is home to about 1,060 wineries at last count.
And wine prices are not expected to increase as a result of this
latest wave of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, said San Francisco wine industry consultant Eileen
Fredrikson, ``mergers tend to stabilize prices.'' Big vintners with
lower production costs per bottle and more marketing muscle should
help provide consumers with easy access to reasonably priced
premium wines from around the world, she says.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong economy and premium demand for prestigious
vineyard properties along the California coast, more mergers are on
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major Australian wine companies, Southcorp and BRL
Hardy, have been scouting the states for winery acquisitions,
sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps coincidently, Robert Mondavi Corp. CEO Michael Mondavi
is in Australia visiting BRL Hardy, according to several sources.
Wine Business Insider Editor Cyril Penn suspects Mondavi may be
talking about a distribution deal with the Australians, not a
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Britain's Diageo, owner of various liquor brands
including Smirnoff and Johnnie Walker, is interested in buying
Seagram's wine and liquor brands, according to industry reports. So
is Britain's Allied Dome, which already owns several California
properties, including Atlas Peak, Callaway and Clos du Bois, and
New York's Canandaigua Brands, which produces Almaden and
Inglenook.
</P>
<P>
   As another sign of the international nature of the wine
business, Canandaigua, the largest U.S. winemaker after
California's E&AMP;J Gallo, said this week that it is changing its name
to Constellation Brands to better reflect its global reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are buying California wineries to strengthen their
brands and international presence,'' said WR Hambrecht wine
industry analyst Kristine Koerber. ``Given the limited supply of
grape-growing land in Napa and Sonoma, acquisitions may be the only
way to get into the California premium wine market.''
</P>
<P>
   Some producers also see this as an opportune time to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wine business is booming right now and prices for wineries
have never been higher,'' said St. Helena wine consultant Vic
Motto. ``Some owners and investors read about the high prices and
say maybe this is the time for an exit strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly traded companies such as Beringer and R.H. Phillips
have no doubt felt particular pressure because their stock prices
had been stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently ``winery stock prices haven't done much,'' said
Traci Mangini, a wine industry analyst at Van Kasper &AMP; Co. in San
Francisco. For example, the shares of R.H. Phillips have been stuck
in the $3 to $4 a share range for the past three years despite
growing revenues and profits. Vincor offered $7 a share for
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Beringer's stock jumped 50 percent, to $55.31 from $36.75, as a
result of its deal with Foster. Growing investor enthusiasm about
vineyard values and expectations of additional mergers helped drive
up the shares of other California producers including Robert
Mondavi and Golden State Vintners.
</P>
<P>
   Although growing grapes and making wine sounds like a dream
business and has attracted hundreds of wealthy entrepreneurs and
retirees, historically it is not necessarily an easy way to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   Return on investment is lower in the wine industry than in many
others because of the huge cost of vineyard land and production
machinery that is used only a few months a year. In addition,
inventory must often be stored for years in costly oak casks and
air-conditioned cellars before it is ready to sell.
</P>
<P>
   On top of high costs, add production risks. Wine is essentially
an agricultural business, which makes it difficult to precisely
predict production or profits. A bountiful crop is anticipated for
this harvest season. But depending on the weather, production might
be up or down 20 percent one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, there is the danger of insect invasions. A
decade ago, the Phylloxera root louse laid waste to vineyards.
Today, Pierce's disease, spread by the glassy-winged sharpshooter,
threatens to sap healthy vines throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these risks, wineries do make money, especially
efficient producers of high-quality wines. ``Premium wine is a
double-digit (annual percentage) growth business and that makes it
attractive,'' said Mangini. Last year, California wine shipments
reached a record 446 million gallons.
</P>
<P>
   California vintners account for 72 percent of all wines consumed
in the United States, which makes well-established producers
logical takeover targets for foreign companies like Foster's and
Vincor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gaining a foothold in the United States, they and
the larger domestic producers are intent on getting bigger to grab
shelf space in stores and restaurants and attract the attention of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, smaller wineries face barriers too steep to surmount:
One is the complex state and federal laws governing the sale of
alcoholic beverages in the United States. Another is a distribution
system that often requires wine producers to sell to wholesalers
rather than directly to retailers or consumers.
</P>
<P>
   However, size has not always translated into success in the wine
industry. Coca-Cola, Beatrice Foods and Nestle all bought large
California wine holdings in the past but ended up bailing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food companies didn't always understand the wine business or
the marketing difficulties,'' said Fredrikson. ``Companies like
Foster's and Vincor do.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
