r f BC-OLYMPICS-ADVERTISE-SF     09-01 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-ADVERTISE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ADVERTISERS PAY BIG BUCKS TO BASK IN OLYMPIC GLOW  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic flag is being hoisted high in
Sydney, Australia, and so are the hopes of 11 corporate sponsors
that are spending tens of millions of dollars each for an
Olympic-size halo effect.
</P>
<P>
   Mega-corporations from Coca-Cola to IBM have ponied up an
average of $55 million each for four years as the Games' global
sponsors, a whopping sum that doesn't even include airtime for ads.
The primary benefit is the use of the Olympic name and rings in
advertising, plus ``category exclusivity'' _ FedEx can't advertise
during the games, for example, because UPS is a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The event's estimated television audience of 3.7 billion people
worldwide _ the largest ever for a single event _ is certainly an
attraction for advertisers. But another big motivator _ which is
less obvious but no less unique _ is the unparalleled reverence the
Olympics inspire among people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Games, with their history and association with
heroic figures such as Jesse Owens, are held in as high esteem by
the public as the humanitarian institutions UNICEF and the Red
Cross, according to a survey conducted for the International
Olympic Committee by Edgar, Dunn &AMP; Co., a San Francisco brand
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The main qualities associated with the Games include
``friendship,'' ``peace,'' ``global'' and ``fair competition,''
according to the poll of 5,500 people in the United States,
Senegal, China and eight other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Other highly ranked attributes include ``being the best,''
``determination,'' ``trustworthiness'' and ``honor'' _ qualities
that most commercial brands would love to be associated with.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most popular commercial sporting events, such as the
World Cup soccer tournament and National Football League's Super
Bowl, don't come close to the esteem of the Olympics _ which even
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal has not tarnished, according to
Jonathan Parker of Edgar, Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   The trick for advertisers is to make the connection in
consumers' minds between qualities of the Olympics and corporate
brand attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Foster City, Calif.'s Visa, for example, reinforces the image
that its credit cards are accepted ``Everywhere you want to be'' by
sponsoring Olympics in far-flung cities and heavily promoting the
fact that other cards aren't accepted in the Olympic Village.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy seems to work _ most Americans believe Visa is more
widely accepted than Mastercard, although the two are nearly
identical.
</P>
<P>
   Other key brand attributes Visa believes have rubbed off from
the Olympics include leadership, winning, quality and reliability,
said Tom Shephard, senior vice president for sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming a sponsor in 1986, Visa's market share has jumped
by one-third in the United States while the number of consumers who
consider it the ``best overall card'' has more than doubled to a
commanding 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While part of this improvement can be attributed to other
marketing _ Visa also sponsors Nascar, the NFL and even a bass
fishing tournament _ image surveys show improved consumer
perceptions of the credit card marketer during the Games. Those
perceptions never fall completely back to pre-game levels, Shephard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence: Purchases rung up on a Visa card increase by
15 to 25 percent when a Visa sign featuring the Olympic rings
appears near the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they see that sign, (Visa's support of the Olympics) is top
of mind and top of wallet,'' said Shephard.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. of Atlanta has been an Olympic marketer since
1928, when Coke was served aboard the ship that transported the
U.S. Olympic team to Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic Games give us a unique opportunity to go into 200
countries around the world and build a relationship with those
consumers, connecting our brands to something they're very
passionate about,'' said Scott McCune, vice president of worldwide
sports marketing for Coke. ``There just aren't many sponsorships
that allow you to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Big themes in Coke's Olympic marketing include refreshment,
connection, the best of humanity and global unity, McCune said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other Olympic sponsors, Coke markets its Olympic
association in targeted promotions that vary from market to market.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Aquarius sport drink, for example, is a sponsor of
Japan's Olympic swim team. ``That's front and center in all of our
marketing there and plays to the strong sense of national loyalty''
Japanese people have toward their teams, McCune said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is also giving each Olympic athlete free pins featuring the
Games' ring logo and the athlete's national flag. The sodamaker has
set up three tents in Sydney where the athletes can meet and
exchange pins, creating positive associations with the Coke brand.
</P>
<P>
   For IBM, headquartered in Armonk, N.Y., the Games provide a
perfect platform for promoting itself as a global ``e-business
solutions provider.'' IBM technologies undergird every aspect of
the Games, from its hotel reservations system to score-keeping to
several Olympics-related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But IBM has learned over the years to make its message personal
and human, rather than dry and technological.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 in Atlanta, the company's Summer Olympics advertising
focused largely on its high-tech products and failed to make an
emotional connection with the Games. Since then, the company has
chosen to feature individual athletes in its ads, thereby linking
its brand to qualities such as ``valor''and ``glory.''
</P>
<P>
   The same ads direct consumers to the official Olympics Web site
( &LR; www.olympics.com &LR; ), which IBM designed and hosts, to learn more
about each athlete.
</P>
<P>
   In the ads ``we're not talking about all the servers we're
using, we're really making it meaningful for the fan sitting at
home,'' said Rick Singer, vice president of Olympic marketing.
``It's passion marketing, in essence.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, similarly emotional
ads produced a bump in consumer perceptions of IBM in areas such as
leadership and competence, Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't such blatant commercialism turn off consumers? Not
as much as one might think, according to Edgar, Dunn's Parker. In
fact, Olympics fans seem to cut sponsors slack because of the
companies' financial support for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   In the Edgar, Dunn survey, 57 percent of consumers around the
world agreed with the statement ``I look favorably towards a
company if it is associated with the Olympics.'' Twenty-three
percent disagreed and 20 percent were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 75 percent of respondents agreed with the statement ``I
welcome commercial association with the Olympics if it keeps them
going'' and 60 percent said, ``It's only right that Olympic
sponsors use their associations with the Games to help sell their
products.''
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the sponsorship fee represents only a
fraction of sponsors' spending, noted Bill Chipps, senior editor of
the newsletter IEG Sponsorship Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of thumb is that for every dollar a company spends on
a rights fee, to maximize the sponsorship they spend another $2 to
$3 on leverage'' such as advertising, Chipps said. That means as
much as $165 million is spent on Olympic promotions by each global
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The global sponsors for the Sydney summer games, which begin
Sept. 15, are Coca-Cola, IBM, John Hancock, Kodak, McDonald's,
Panasonic, Samsung, Sports Illustrated/Time magazine, Visa, UPS and
Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of OLYMPICS () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
