<HEADLINE>
FOR CSUN, PLAYING DIV. 1-A TEAMS HAS POSITIVES AND NEGATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It will take just a few hours for the Cal State
Northridge football team to play its season opener today at the Air
Force Academy. In that time, the operating budgets of five CSUN
sports programs will be covered for the season.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN makes $125,000 in guaranteed revenue by playing the
Division I-A school. Last season, the Matadors earned $300,000 from
games against Kansas and SMU.
</P>
<P>
   The positives - the financial windfall being the biggest - of
playing Division I-A opponents are plenty. And the negatives - such
as humiliating losses and costly injuries - are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain: CSUN will continue to play Division
I-A teams and cash the checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we are the cash cow a little,'' CSUN football
coach Jeff Kearin said. ``We are the window to the athletic
department and the university. We're exposed nationally. So is
basketball and baseball. People see this university through those
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN athletic director Dick Dull doesn't mind playing one
Division I-A team each season but two is overdoing it. Dull doesn't
believe the extra money - something CSUN could definitely use -
offsets the negatives.
</P>
<P>
   That's why only one Division I-A team is on its schedule this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's a monetary dimension,'' Dull said.
``Division I-AA teams all over America are relegated to playing one
or two or several games against Division I-A opponents in order to
assist in balancing the budget. I think it should be balanced -
probably one game but no more than two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to get in a situation where we play too many.
I've seen institutions play Nebraska, Oregon and Arizona all in the
same year and come away with $900,000. They also came away with
three major losses and a beat up football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does a disservice to the institution, as well as the
student athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, CSUN suffered its share of major losses to Division
I-A teams. Dull, who was in his first season at CSUN, didn't make
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas clobbered CSUN 71-14 and SMU cruised to a 58-16 victory.
In 1997, CSUN played three Division I-A teams - Boise State, Hawaii
and New Mexico State - and lost by an average of 17.7 points per
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good experience playing Kansas but we got beat up
on,'' quarterback Marcus Brady said. ``You know who can perform. Of
course, you always think you can (win).''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN played nine Division I-A opponents in the 1990s and won
once, 33-0 over New Mexico State in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It's an opportunity of a lifetime for some players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love `em,'' Rodriguez said. ``To me, it's a privilege to go
play in a big stadium in front of a big crowd at a big school.
Playing against those guys is a privilege and you have to take
advantage of it to the fullest. I think it's wonderful. It shows
who has heart. Last year, unfortunately, we didn't have a lot of
guys with heart. This year, it'll be a lot different.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Division I-A teams exploit weaknesses of Division
I-AA teams, which are usually found on the line. And most Division
I-A players are bigger, stronger and faster, perhaps increasing the
the possibility of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Is the money, exposure and experience worth risking injury?
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we played Kansas and SMU and I don't think we lost
one guy in either of those games,'' Kearin said. ``Sure, Air Force
is a Division I team and they have 85 scholarships compared to our
55. My biggest concern is that they're an option team and they do a
lot of cut blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors won't prepare for the option the rest of year
because they play in the pass-happy Big Sky Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're preparing as best we can,'' defensive lineman
Levi Line said. ``From conditioning to doing pushups
</P>
<P>
   it's for one reason: to beat the snot out of Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's also the possibility of doing the unthinkable:
winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
