<SLUG> BC-XBOX-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT SERIOUSLY IN GAMES  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Microsoft unveiled a slate of 18 companies
Friday, including two Bay Area studios, that will develop video
games for its upcoming Xbox, the software juggernaut's first foray
into the console market.
</P>
<P>
   The company said two subsidiaries of Lionhead Studios _ the
British firm behind the highly anticipated computer game Black &AMP;
White _ will create titles for Xbox. Others include Stormfront
Studios, which makes a popular line of NASCAR games, and Totally
Games, both of San Rafael, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about the hardware a lot, but we thought it was
time to talk about the software, because without that, the console
means nothing,'' said Ed Fries, vice president of games publishing
at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deals, Microsoft will publish and market
the games. The company did not disclose the financial terms or
titles, although Stormfront President Don Daglow said his firm is
developing an ``action-combat'' game for the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making all the right moves now,'' said Electronic
Gaming Monthly editor Joe Funk. ``But how it translates into good
games, that remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Xbox, due out next fall, is Microsoft's bid to challenge
established game-systemmakers Sony, Nintendo and Sega. The Xbox and
Sony's PlayStation 2, which ships in the United States next month,
are considered Trojan horses. The two companies hope their
machines, both equipped with broadband support and DVD players,
become entertainment hubs of the home.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft hasn't released details of the Xbox's design, but
Fries said Friday that the company is ``tweaking the space between
the fins.'' He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will announce other game development
partnerships, including some with Japanese firms, later this year
and early next year. Pacts with those companies are key, Funk said,
because the lucrative Japanese market has often proved elusive to
U.S. and European gamemakers. And, the other game-hardwaremakers _
all based in Japan _ have strong ties with Japanese game
developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is the X-factor for Microsoft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daglow, whose firm makes games for PCs, PlayStation and
PlayStation 2, said Microsoft stands a good chance of winning
market share away from the big three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised (when Microsoft announced its plans to make
the Xbox), because it's outside of their normal business, but if
anyone's going to take on the big guys, they're a contender,''
Daglow said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
