<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BEETLEBAILEY-WALKER09     09-01 2563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETLEBAILEY-WALKER0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    The evolution of an American layabout
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On Sept. 4, 1950, a college layabout named
Beetle debuted in a dozen newspapers. He was the star of the last
comic strip approved by legendary publisher William Randolph
Hearst. Six months later, however, the struggling strip had grown
to only 25 papers, and there was talk of cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Then Beetle Bailey joined the Army _ and hasn't left Camp Swampy
in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is the 50th anniversary of ``Beetle Bailey,'' which now
appears in more than 1,800 newspapers around the world. It's read
by an estimated 200 million people. Its creator, Mort Walker, of
Boca Raton, is billed as the most widely syndicated cartoonist in
history, with nine comic strips to his credit, along with more than
100 books and 50 animated films.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Beetle flunk as a lazy college boy but succeed as the
Army's oldest private?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, only about 5 percent of Americans had gone to
college,'' said Walker, who turns 77 today. ``Most people couldn't
relate to a comic strip about college life. College boys were even
resented a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Korean War heated up in early 1951, an editor of the
Philadelphia Bulletin gave Walker some advice. ``He said that
Beetle is a goof-off college kid, and those are the kids being
drafted,'' Walker recalled. ``The minute I put Beetle in the Army,
the strip just took off.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Jerry Dumas, who helps Walker with gags, understands
why. ``'Beetle Bailey' isn't about warfare. In a way, it's not even
a military strip. It's about human beings and human nature. The
military is a good place to have a bunch of characters in conflict
with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumas has worked with Walker for more than four decades, and he
knows the boss. ``Like any good cartoonist, Mort views any
situation from an odd angle, always looking for the possibilities
of humor. He often wakes up in the middle of the night and writes
down gags in bed in the dark. His mind never rests.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has dreamed up the unthinkable to celebrate Beetle's 50th
anniversary. In strips leading to the big day Monday, he's had Sgt.
Orville P. Snorkel retire from the Army. ``I thought it might be
fun to see how Sarge does if he doesn't have Beetle to kick around
anymore,'' said Walker, who splits time between his home and studio
in Stamford, Conn., and Boca Raton, where he moved his
International Museum of Cartoon Art in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Will Sarge stay retired? Walker, who says he has a compulsion to
blurt out an honest answer to any question, wouldn't talk about
Sarge's future. So check out today's funny pages. One thing,
however, is certain _ ``Beetle Bailey'' isn't going anywhere.
``I've got 10 kids, and the strip is their life-insurance policy,''
Walker said. ``Besides, old cartoonists never retire. They just
erase away.''
</P>
<P>
   SELLING CARTOONS AT AGE 11
</P>
<P>
   Mort Walker always wanted to be a cartoonist. Born in 1923 in
the oil-boom town of El Dorado, Kan., he had a hardscrabble youth.
His father was a builder who hopscotched about the Midwestern oil
fields. He built churches, schools and houses. But his own family,
including two boys and two girls, lived in humble abodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no heat or plumbing,'' Walker recalled. ``We had
outhouses and took baths outside in a galvanized tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was a terrible businessman with a big heart. He never
charged enough, so we never had enough. We always had somebody down
on their luck living with us. We had old people from the church.
He'd pick up hobos and bring them home and feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker joked that he formed his philosophy _''poverty sucks'' _
very early.
</P>
<P>
   But his parents had talents. His father was also a painter,
musician and the poet laureate of Kansas. His mother was a
part-time newspaper illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had a radio, so we'd amuse ourselves by drawing and
writing around the kitchen table,'' Walker said. ``I started
keeping a diary when I was 5. When I was a little boy, I told
myself I was going to be a millionaire, a hotshot cartoonist.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker was 11 years old when he sold his first cartoon to a
Kansas City newspaper. It depicted vegetables and fruits attacking
a cup of coffee. Later, he had to borrow $25 to pay his first
year's tuition at Kansas City Junior College. He got a night job in
the shipping division of Hallmark Cards, then called Hall Brothers.
``I'd bring two lunches,'' he said. ``One for school, and then I'd
stop at the park on the way to work and have the other for
dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, Walker answered an ad looking for an artist. It turned
out to be a Hallmark greeting. ``They asked me how I liked their
cards. I said they stink. I wouldn't send one to my grandmother.
They were all soupy and syrupy. Anyway, I was brash, but they hired
me. You could say I moved upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker didn't draw roses or cute critters. His taste tended more
toward funny cars and gags. ``I think I did the first humorous
greeting cards, because I don't remember any before we started
them. Today, that's all you find.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker continued to draw cards (75 a week, earning a buck a
card) at the University of Missouri, where he'd gone to study
journalism. Before finishing school, he was drafted in 1943 during
World War II. He entered the Army as a private and left it as a
lieutenant. The Army also left him with a cast of characters he
would draw on years later.
</P>
<P>
   One was Sgt. Octavian Savou, who became Sgt. Snorkel. ``He was a
big, burly guy. Always yelling at us. We'd run and hide from him.
But, like Sarge, he was really sentimental. One day he left a poem
on our bunks addressed to `my boys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the war, Walker was a lieutenant guarding an
ordnance depot in Naples, Italy. He was 21. He watched the Army
destroy tons of inventory rather than ship it home. Binoculars and
watches were smashed by tanks. Walker's job was to make sure nobody
stole anything before the stuff was officially destroyed. ``I
realized then that Army humor writes itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Walker returned to the University of Missouri,
graduating with a degree in humanities. In 1948, he headed for New
York _ ``the mountain'' _ to make his fortune as a cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   He shared a room in a condemned building for $7 a month. He got
a job editing magazines for Dell publishing. One was a joke
magazine, and cartoonists would come to him with their ideas. He
learned a lot about the business. Eventually, after some 200
rejections, magazines began publishing his cartoons, although The
New Yorker passed, saying Walker ``drew too funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told I was the best-selling magazine cartoonist of
1950,'' he said. ``I made $8,000. My wife said, `If you're a top
seller at $8,000, maybe you should find another line of work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his cartoons featured a lanky college kid named Spider.
Walker based his appearance on a college buddy _ a lovable goofus.
The name Spider came from a fraternity brother who was so drunk one
night that he had to crawl home like a spider. It took Walker only
a week to come up with sample sheets for editors. The Saturday
Evening Post published the cartoons, which Walker eventually turned
into a strip picked up by King Features Syndicate, owned by the
Hearst empire.
</P>
<P>
   All the characters except Spider were dropped for the comic
strip. Spider was renamed Beetle, and then Beetle Bailey _ the last
name of the editor who suggested it. Then one day, Beetle ducked
into an Army recruiting office on a dare _ and an anti-hero was
born.
</P>
<P>
   `RIGHT PLACE AT THE RIGHT TIME'
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mort started out in the early '50s, he had a product that
was in the right place at the right time,'' said Lucy Caswell, a
professor and curator of the Cartoon Research Library at Ohio State
University. ``He wrote from the postwar perspective, and the
simplicity of his graphic style was well-suited for the shrinking
space that comics experienced in the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Caswell also noted that Walker came to strips as a gag
cartoonist. ``He had an understanding of what was funny from a
reader's perspective.'' Gag strips are still popular, she said, and
``Beetle Bailey `` may have grown old, but not out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has a ``genius'' for creating concepts and characters,
but the writing is what keeps the strip alive, agreed Joseph
D'Angelo, retired president of King Features Syndicate and Walker's
longtime friend. ``In terms of a strip's longevity, it's more
important to find the writers who can keep the concept going,'' he
said. ``It's not hard to find someone who can draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to evaluate his own talents, Walker said he likes to draw
funny-looking characters, but he stressed simplicity. ``I don't
overwrite. I think the strip is easy to read and understand. You
have to do two things. You have to create certain shticks for your
characters that people recognize. Beetle asleep. Sarge beating up
on him. People have to quickly pick up on familiar themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you have to come up with universal truths about humanity.
If I see something that everybody does, or talks about, I try to
make a gag out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beetle Bailey'' has about 20 characters. ``You can't have an
Army with two people in it,'' Walker said. They've changed over the
years. Sarge got considerably fatter. Beetle changed from a string
bean to a more normal size. Sarge originally had a wife and kids,
but Walker dropped the idea as too complicated. As for Camp Swampy,
he tried to give it a more identifiable character, but it simply
wound up an ``amorphous mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has gotten into a few messes with the strip over the
years, from trouble with the PC Brigade to even the Army's Stars
and Stripes. In the early '50s, the newspaper's Tokyo edition
dropped the strip because it allegedly fostered disrespect for
officers. Civilian publications played up the incident, and
``Beetle'' added 100 papers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when Walker introduced the African-American Lt. Jack
Flap, the paper thought the character might stir racial animosities
and dropped the strip for a time. So did some civilian papers, but
another 100 papers signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Feminists went ballistic over Gen. Halftrack's ogling of his
secretary Miss Buxley in the '80s. ``It was an innocent thing, but
I got jumped all over by the vociferous 10 percent,'' Walker said.
``The general never harassed her. It was just a case of an older
guy who is over the hill but not over the thrill.'' The general was
sent to sensitivity training, but some women's groups still grumble
over his long-distance infatuation with the sexy blonde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beetle Bailey `` didn't lose popularity during the Vietnam
War, despite widespread anti-war sentiment, Walker said. ``People
who didn't like the military thought I was ridiculing it. Others
thought I was reflecting their experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's characters are distinct individuals. They are his
``repertory company,'' Caswell said. ``He was able to take these
characters and build reader identification with them,'' she said.
``Now, we immediately understand something will be funny because
Beetle says it, or Sarge does it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there always has to be that surprise in the last panel.
``Charles Schulz once said that a good cartoonist must do the same
thing every day without repeating himself,'' she added. ``Mort has
done that.''
</P>
<P>
   THE NEXT GENERATION
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his initial success with the strip, Walker and his
first wife, Jean, moved to Greenwich, Conn. It was close to New
York, the publishing mecca, and dozens of cartoonists and
illustrators made their homes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoonists are like little children,'' Walker said. ``They
like to play tricks on each other. But they're a lovable bunch.''
He recalled one night when about 30 cartoonists plotted to show up
at different times at a colleague's house, and order a different
drink from the flabbergasted host.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and his first wife had seven children. After a divorce,
he married his wife Cathy, who brought three children to the
household from a previous marriage. They recently celebrated their
15th wedding anniversary. Walker is up at 6:30 a.m. and at his desk
by 8:30. He's a prolific worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that first impressed me about Mort was his
work ethic,'' said gag writer Dumas, who also produces the ``Sam
And Silo'' strip created with Walker. ``When Mort has a job to do,
he simply stays in his chair and gets it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker had the habit of doing his Sunday strips around the
kitchen table so his kids would know what he did for a living. ``I
just took it for granted that everybody's father worked at home,''
recalled his son, Brian Walker.
</P>
<P>
   It must have made an impression. Brian, 48, and brother Greg,
50, now help their father with ``Beetle Bailey `` and write the
``Hi and Lois'' strip, which appears in more than 1,100 papers.
Lois is Beetle Bailey's sister, by the way. Mort Walker got the
idea for the strip when Beetle took Sarge home on furlough. Walker
and the late Dik Browne produced the strip for years. Browne's son,
Chance, now draws ``Hi and Lois.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumas, Walker and the two sons lunch once a month at a ``gag
meeting'' at Walker's house. ``When I first worked for Mort, we'd
each do 10 gags a week, and check them out on each other,'' Dumas
said. Some were too naughty for the strip. Others were filed away
for a rainy day. More than 10,000 are collected in a safe at
Walker's ``laugh factory'' in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Always an admirer of his colleagues' work, Walker also began
collecting vintage comic strips and cartoons around 1960. By the
early '70s, he had an ample collection and decided to open a museum
in Greenwich, Conn. The collection continued to grow from gifts,
and moved to suburban New York and then Boca Raton. Numbering more
than 150,000 objects, the museum may be the largest of its kind.
``We were simply trying to maintain a heritage that no one else was
looking after,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker views laughter as medicine, and the comic strips as
social balm. ``I'm a big believer in the print media and the future
of comic strips,'' he said. ``As people move around from town to
town these days, with families living far away from each other, I
think comic strips fill a void. . . . People can turn to the funny
pages and find old friends and shared experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   A BUSY YEAR
</P>
<P>
   This anniversary year has been busy for Walker. His
autobiography is being published this fall by Andrews, McMeel
Publishing. The cartoon museum is doing a Mort Walker retrospective
in November. He's helping raise money for the National World War II
Memorial Campaign. And he has received numerous awards. The French
Embassy in Washington made him a ``chevalier,'' or knight, and the
U.S. Army gave him The Decoration for Distinguished Civilian
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Pentagon ceremony, Walker joked to Secretary of the
Army Louis Caldera that the French had kissed him on both cheeks.
``The secretary shot back, `Well, in today's Army, we don't ask and
we don't tell.' I thought that was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Army humor does write itself sometimes _ with a little help from
Mort Walker and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
