<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS STUMP AROUND THE CLOCK; SENATE SHOO-INS IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS STUMP AROUND THE CLOCK
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is planning a round-the-clock Labor Day
tour of several battleground states to emphasize the ticket's
dedication to workers. Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, his running
mate, start on Sunday in Philadelphia, where they will meet with
construction workers, then fly to Flint, Mich., for an 11 p.m.
visit with hospital workers. Then they are off to Tampa, Fla., for
a 5 a.m. visit to a diner and breakfast with firefighters. The two
split at that point, with Gore flying to Pittsburgh for an
afternoon Labor Day rally which will include John Sweeney,
president of the AFL-CIO. Lieberman breaks off for Detroit. Gore
and his entourage move on to Louisville, Ky., where they finally
hit pillows Monday night after a rally at the Louisville Motor
Speedway. The rest of the week includes visits to Cleveland,
Detroit, New Orleans and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE SHOO-INS IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Florida holds a Senate primary on Tuesday but the outcome is not
in doubt: Democrat Bill Nelson and Rep. Bill McCollum, a
Republican, should trounce unknown challengers to move on to the
general election with independent candidate Willie Logan, a state
legislator. Neither Nelson, the state insurance commissioner, nor
McCollum appears particularly nervous. Nelson goes into the fall
campaign with a double-digit lead in public opinion polls and a $1
million financial edge, prompting Democrats to rate this race as a
top opportunity to pick up a Republican seat now held by Sen.
Connie Mack, who is retiring. The combative tone of the campaign is
certain to strain the relationship between the two men, who had
sleep-overs during their days in high school government and
represented adjoining congressional districts. They have something
else in common _ Bill is neither's first name. McCollum is actually
Ira William while Nelson is Clarence William. ``It's Ira vs.
Clarence,'' said one campaign aide.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   No public appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
