<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN0903-COX     09-01 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    AT HOME WITH THE PRACTICAL MAN
 &HT;    Let our guru of good sense help you take the labor out of Labor
Day weekend
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sweet mother of God!
</P>
<P>
   The practical man has lost his bearings. Here he is in the Home
and Garden section, with misguided readers who spend hideous hours
hoeing bean rows, hanging curtains and hauling hedge clippings to
the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! What are you guys thinking?! Who cares what color your
house is, as long as the roof doesn't leak? How many weeds are you
going to yank before you realize the weeds will win? And _ good
lord! _ don't you know the living room doesn't get any bigger just
because you rearrange the furniture?
</P>
<P>
   But OK, the practical man didn't come to criticize. He's here to
help _ and he has the credentials. Yes, he too has tried to grow
vegetables in the sand. It's a season he still remembers ruefully
as The Year of the $500 Green Bean. He too built a backyard shed _
now a lizard lounge jammed with kid junk he calls The $1,000 Trash
Can. Indeed, the practical man has laid enough tile, built enough
furniture, hung enough wallpaper and painted, planted and pounded
enough to perceive the painful truth: Home improvement is where the
heartache is.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't all in vain. He's distilled his lifetime of labor
around the house into a handy handbook, which he now offers for
homeowners everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRACTICAL MAN'S GUIDE TO HOME IMPROVEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Cut no grass: The practical man does not mow lawns. He deduced
years ago that this hopelessly futile misery is better left to
kids, for only they can profit from battles with Mother Nature. Not
only do they get cold cash (after a job, the practical man
typically hoses them down and flings them a fiver), they also
experience the frustration of a losing battle, which will soon
prompt them to give up their childish nonsense and become practical
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man understands, however, that not everyone has
children. Thus, to his barren brethren, he recommends the next best
thing: A goat.
</P>
<P>
   This bold move may shock some at first (especially neighbors),
but its brilliance will become obvious when Billy begins munching
every blade and branch he can reach, freeing your yard of
aggravation for the very practical price of feed and water.
</P>
<P>
   Build no shed: Expensive garden implements are the tools of
fools, for no matter how carefully you tuck them into your shed
after first use, they soon will migrate _ usually assisted by a
child or spouse _ to a rusty residence against the fence. Thus, the
practical man says skip the shed. Instead, buy the cheapest
possible shovels, hoes, wheelbarrows and the like and leave them
scattered about the yard. This brilliant stroke saves cash, for not
only will you be spared the time and expense of shed construction,
you'll never again be tempted to pay $30 for a spade whose handle
is doomed to rot in six months. As a bonus, it keeps the practical
man's blood pressure in check, for he's less likely to bellow when
Junior hauls a shabby shovel off-site to conduct a requiem for Red
Robin.
</P>
<P>
   Plant no palms: The practical man has a soft spot for trees, for
most require little upkeep and create shade that both cools the
house and kills high-maintenance and meaningless ornamentals such
as grass, flowers, hedges, etc. But one specimen is an exception:
the palm. This pathetic puke of a tree finds no quarter in the
practical man's yard for two reasons: First, a streetlight casts
more shade. Second, it's the enemy of man.
</P>
<P>
   A full-grown queen palm fouls the yard with innumerable seeds,
which, if not immediately dispatched, become a tangle of tenacious
sprouts at Momma's feet. The queen protects her babes by dangling
death-dealing dried up fronds over them _ immense and seemingly
inaccessible _ until you stoop to slaughter her children, whereupon
she drops one on your head.
</P>
<P>
   The queen's cousins are equally egregious. Areca palms create a
wild and unruly hedge that harbors all manner of cockroaches,
snakes and other hideous beasts. Palmetto fronds can slice through
slabs of sweaty flesh. Cabbage palms cunningly tempt tots to climb,
then rip legs wide open on the way down. Coconut palms can kill a
man.
</P>
<P>
   The Amish are right: The practical man doesn't believe in paint,
nor in any cosmetic improvements that create work but serve no
purpose. If he had his way, he'd slap waterseal on the fascia,
primer on the awnings and let the stucco fend for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man, however, is no slave to his own philosophy.
He is aware his position is often not worth maintaining in the face
of unenlightened neighbors and spouses, whose ignorance in these
matters is typically vast and wrathful.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, as a compromise, he paints his house Amish style _ white
with black trim _ and sticks with it. The combination is a winner
for several reasons, among them: 1) It never goes out of fashion,
thus eliminating costly makeovers when pink suddenly becomes passe.
2) Touch-up paint is easily purchased _ with the following words:
``I'll take a gallon of black and a gallon of white.'' Never again
will you find yourself thumbing through color charts in a desperate
but doomed bid to match Sumptuous Sorbet and Concupiscent
Cranberry.
</P>
<P>
   To heck with the deck: The dream: Friends and family gather
round on your beautiful backyard deck, where lemonade is served,
steaks sizzle on the grill and kiddies skedaddle in the sweet
summer breeze. The reality: Blow a grand on lumber, spend a month
sweating, swearing and hammering nails, hold one party to
celebrate, then turn your masterpiece over to the rats, 'coons,
possums and toads that will take up residence beneath it while you
beg and cajole your family to pleasepleaseplease let's eat outside
just this one time tonight _ I swear, it's only 95 degrees and the
bugs aren't even that bad!
</P>
<P>
   Cheer up my brother, live in the sunshine: For the love of God,
people, make a decision and go with it. If you have something to
hide, shame on you but plaster over your windows and be done with
it. If you don't, live in the sunshine and like it. Only mealy
mouthed mulletheads and liberal arts majors are so on-the-one-hand
hobbled that they'll waste money and endure the constant
aggravation of verticals, mini-blinds, curtains and other
cockamamie contraptions designed to keep windows in a perpetual
state of indecision. Rip those suckers down, NOW! You'll save
thousands, and you'll never again curse God's green earth when a
vertical clangs and bangs and slithers a slat to the floor, or a
blind breaks free and brains you, or her cat claws its cuddly way
up the curtains.
</P>
<P>
   Papier touche: Wallpaper is wonderful for couples considering
divorce, for nothing can deliver a swifter, sharper and more
certain coup de grace to love than an afternoon wedged in a
bathroom, working shoulder to shoulder with your betrothed at such
a deliciously doomed venture. Trust the practical man: Harsh words,
evil eyes and perhaps even subpoenas will be exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man avoids wallpaper at all costs and goes one
step further: He paints all ceilings, baseboards, doors, window
frames, closets and walls white _ forever. The genius of this
gesture is immediately apparent, for white is not only tasteful and
a perfect match for all shades of furniture, countertops and
cabinets. It also eliminates trim work. No more masking tape. No
more cheesy edging gadgets that never work. Paint the whole house
with one roller and one brush, and don't wash them out till you're
through.
</P>
<P>
   Wood you, or woodn't you: Single folk can floor as they will,
but carpet is crucial for couples with kids. Dainty decorators
declare tile and wood look prettier, but with them come noises
you'd rather not hear. The sickening splat when a nipper's noggin
knocks marble, for instance. The thunderous thunk when noodle plows
parquet. Even worse are the riotous reverberations that trail a
toddler's every move in a manse unmuffled by a nice, cheap Berber.
Trust the practical man, a tile floor under a vaulted ceiling is no
place to premiere the ``Sonata for Pot and Pan.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
