<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-TOOLBOX0903     09-01 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TOOLBOX0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    The practical man's toolbox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   10 ITEMS NO HOMEOWNER SHOULD BE WITHOUT
</P>
<P>
   1. WD-40: The single most practical product on the planet. The
only thing this spray oil won't unstick is your teenager's behind
from the couch. For that, you'll need a less versatile item with an
equally cool name: the M-80.
</P>
<P>
   2. Axe: Don't have the back to be a lumberjack? Bah! When that
tree gets too intimate with your sewer line, roots are going to
roll. And trust the practical man, with a house full of stopped-up
toilets, you'll be chopping like a champ.
</P>
<P>
   3. Broom handle: Perfect for planting corn, beans, radishes and
other vegetable seeds. Even better for thwack-thwack-thwacking
tubby toads, slippery serpents and neighborhood cats that don't
know a lily bed from a litter box.
</P>
<P>
   4. 1 hoagie (in case of pangs) and 1 stogie (in case of pains _
like biting flies, and critical wives).
</P>
<P>
   5. Chain saw: Oh, the simple life, where Pa bores holes with a
hand drill, smooths lumber with a plane and trims trees with his
pappy's crosscut saw _ Fie! The practical man will trade that
sweat-soaked fuddy-duddy foolishness any day for this blessed
beast. Don't have a banyan to decapitate? Turn the stanky, snarling
son loose on the cherry hedge every now and then just for the rush.
</P>
<P>
   6. Caulk: Not a pro? Neither is the practical man. That's why he
loads up on this goop. Caulk not only protects your house against
moisture. It also protects your handywork from undue criticism, for
it fills the gaps between any number of miscut boards.
</P>
<P>
   7. Spackle: And plenty of it, if you want to patch things up
with minimal fuss after somebody buys a copy of that evil tome,
Metropolitan Home, and runs you through this wringer: Hang the
picture there. (Drill, molly, screw.) Oops! Nope, wouldn't it look
better over there. (Drill, molly, screw.) On second thought, there!
</P>
<P>
   8. Plumbing kit: Pipe tape, check. Pipe wrench, check. Bucket to
hold repulsive crud extracted from drain trap, check. Wait,
something's missing. Oh yeah. Ear muffs to shield the wee ones from
the stream of profanity that will begin spewing from your mouth
approximately 47 seconds after sticking your head under the sink.
</P>
<P>
   9. Electrical kit: Wire nuts, yep. Wire snips, yep. Electrical
tape, yep. Bucket to hold odious ooze that begins pouring from your
pores the instant you kill the main breaker and the A.C. dies? See
Item 8.
</P>
<P>
   10. 20-pound sledge: A sure and swift remedy for all sorts of
suburban snafus. That aluminum shed that shed its beauty within a
year? CLANG! That chipped Chattahoochee that came with the house?
WHOMP! That palm stump that's just a little too in touch with its
roots? THUD! Also effective as a prom-night prop when meeting
daughter's date.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
