<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NEWYORK0903-COX     09-01 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    The big apple for small change
 &HT;    By Luma Muhtadie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you've ever wanted to visit New York City but
never thought you had the means, think again. Whether you're headed
uptown, midtown or downtown, there are tons of inexpensive and even
free activities that let you take Manhattan without taking yourself
to the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, lodging tops the list of expenditures in New York
City. However, if you're ready to go hostel-style in lieu of a
hotel, then yu're well on your way to experiencing New York on the
cheap. A hostel does not necessarily mean overcrowded and
institutional. The Big Apple Hostel in upper west Manhattan offers
rooms that sleep two people ($80 per room) or four people ($30 per
person). If you're making the trip with a few friends, then you
won't have to compromise your privacy and you'll pay a fraction of
the price of a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to saving money on accommodations, the Big Apple
Hostel also has a kitchen and backyard BBQ. This means that you
won't have to spend heavily on dining out for every meal.
</P>
<P>
   UPTOWN: CENTRAL PARK
</P>
<P>
   In 1857, Frederick Law Olmsted drew the ``Greensward Plan'' for
the park. Its ``one great purpose,'' Olmsted wrote, ``is to supply
to the 100s of thousands of tired workers, who have no opportunity
to spend their summers in the country, a specimen of God's
handiwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted's mission seems to have succeeded: Spanning upper
Manhattan from 59th to 110th streets, the park is an 843-acre oasis
that provides a haven not only from hard work, but also from heavy
spending _ because some of the most interesting things to see and
do in Central Park are absolutely free.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Fields is a 2 1/2-acre, tear-shaped garden just off
the park entrance at 72nd Street that was paid for by Yoko Ono. It
is just one of the sites in the park honoring John Lennon, who was
killed in front of the Dakota apartment building nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Park Summer Stage at Rumsey Playfield hosts daily
performances all summer. Everything from concerts to poetry
readings, all performed by professional artists, can be enjoyed for
free.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare and other plays are performed at the open-air
Delacorte Theatre each summer by the New York Shakespeare Festival.
Tickets are required to attend these performances, but they can be
obtained for free.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard Shakespeareans can also walk through the Shakespeare
garden around 79th Street, which contains half the plants mentioned
in his plays.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd simply like to picnic, sunbathe, or throw a ball
around, the Great Lawn is the place to be. Located behind the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, you can relax the day away in a setting
where the tips of the city skyscrapers peek around the edges of the
richest green grass and trees. While in the area, you may also want
to scoot over to the Metropolitan Museum to catch the free summer
concerts given by the New York Philharmonic and the Metropolitan
Opera.
</P>
<P>
   MIDTOWN: ROCKEFELLER CENTER, GRAND CENTRAL TERMINAL, MOMA,
BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   Spanning 11 acres of midtown Manhattan (from 49th to 52nd
streets) the Rockefeller Center is a city within the city. The
centerpiece, 30 Rockefeller Plaza, is the home of the NBC studio
where ``Saturday Night Live,'' ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien''
and ``NBC News'' are taped. Outside the building, there is a list
of all the tapings that can be attended, along with details on how
to get tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockefeller Center Arcade, on Fifth Avenue between 49th and
50th streets, is another must-see. The famous statue of Prometheus
looms over beautiful gardens that lead to an outdoor restaurant.
This subground area (which turns into the skating rink depicted on
many Hollywood films during the winter months) is encircled by
flags of all the nations of the world. A variety of art-deco works,
nouveau murals and mosaics grace the walls throughout the
Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   For starving artists or frugal art aficionados, the Museum of
Modern Art (MOMA) on West 53rd Street lets you ``pay what you
wish'' to enter the museum between 4:30 p.m. and 8:15 p.m. Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Central Terminal, at East 42nd Street and Park Avenue,
offers a perfect venue for people-watching, an activity some find
as intriguing as art. A $175 million renovation that was completed
only four years ago has transformed this train station into a
shrine to transportation. The 120-foot ceiling of the main
concourse is covered by a sublime celestial map. The sound of
musicians pleasantly intermingles with the bustle of commuters.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun goes down, neon signs and billboards illuminate
Times Square. The streets become crowded as locals and tourists
come out to play. While there are plenty of crowded bars, cozy
pubs, restaurants, shops and movie theaters to choose from, the
truly ``playful'' won't want to miss the opportunity to catch one
of many Broadway shows. A discount ticket vendor at the north end
of Times Square offers half-price tickets to the shows. Get there
soon after it opens.
</P>
<P>
   BETWEEN MIDTOWN AND DOWNTOWN: GREENWICH VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich Village, which New Yorkers simply call ``the
Village,'' is one of the most vibrant parts of the city. Ever since
New York University was planted next to Washington Square in 1831,
Greenwich Village has been largely inhabited by students. NYU is
known for its radical politics and tolerant attitudes, which might
explain the influx of writers and artists into the village since
the mid 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Allan Poe, Mark Twain, Walt Whitman, Hart Crane, Norman
Rockwell, Jack Kerouac, Bob Dylan, and many others have chosen to
live and work in Greenwich Village. The brick townhouses and low
rises, the tiny green parks and courtyards and the tree-lined
streets give the area a certain charm at once both serene and
surreal.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNTOWN: THE FINANCIAL DISTRICT
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know a thing or to about how to save money in
Manhattan, you might as well find out a thing or two about how it's
made. Whether you're interested in economics or not, the financial
district is fascinating .
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Stock Exchange, on the third floor of 20 Broad
St., you can view 3,000 companies trade more than 253 billion
shares of stock, valued at more than $11 trillion. The NYSE
Interactive Education Center offers free tours that help to make
sense of the pandemonium on the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the World Trade Center at Two World Trade Center,
Suite 1520, is the highest point from which to view New York City
(yes, higher than the Empire State Building). At 110 stories, it is
actually the highest open-air deck in the world. While the view
comes at a cost ($13 for adults, $11 for students, $10 for
military, and $6.50 for children) the view at sunset, when the city
lights up as the sun disappears, is worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to dine like a New York banker, but don't have the
means to finance a costly dinner at the World Trade Center
restaurant, consider heading down to 160 Broadway, one block east
of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   You will find yourself at the poshest McDonald's ever. There are
fresh flowers on every table, a stock ticker with a 30-second
delay, servers in tuxedos and a baby grand piano played between 11
a.m. and 3 p.m. every day.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND DOWNTOWN: STATEN ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   From Battery Park, the Staten Island Ferry travels to the St.
George terminal on Staten Island. The ferry provides fantastic
views of the New York skyline and scoots right past the Statue of
Liberty. Best of all, it is only 50 cents round-trip!
</P>
<P>
   Once you get to Staten Island, there is an outdoor paradise that
can scarcely be envisioned from the rusty environs of the ferry
terminal. The Greenbelt is a park nearly three times the size of
Central Park where you can spend another afternoon enjoying the
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
