<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Life behind the scenes for child actors
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I've always wondered why any parent would let
their child go into show business. Sure, the potential for huge
paydays is tempting. But is the price that must be paid for that
possible fortune worth it? On Monday, A&AMP;E will air ``Child Stars:
Their Story'': 9-11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child Stars: Their Story `` attempts to reveal what it's
really like being a young star. The two-hour documentary, narrated
by Hayley Mills, assembled an impressive array of talent (over 30
in all) from five generations. Patty Duke (''The Patty Duke Show'')
talks about being forced to go to her dad's funeral in her
character's costume and makeup. David Faustino (''Married...with
Children'') remembers what it was like drinking at Hollywood's
hottest nightclubs at 14. Melissa Gilbert (''Little House on the
Prairie''), one of ``Child Stars''' executive producers, recalls
crying, sweating and breaking out in a rash after forgetting her
lines. Diana Serra Cary (''Baby Peggy'') recalls feeling like a
``senior citizen'' at age 15.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to several interviews, ``Child Stars'' also features
a roundtable during which eight former stars, including Kim Fields
(''The Facts of Life''), Jerry Mathers (''Leave it to Beaver'') and
Sara Gilbert (''Roseanne'') talk openly about drugs, rejection and
the pros and cons of having a sexy image.
</P>
<P>
   Child stars are often robbed of a normal childhood. Growing up
is hard enough. Imagine having to do it in front of millions of
people watching your every move or snickering about every
goofy-looking pimple you get. The pressure to perform is also
insanely intense. Many adult actors can't even take the heat and
often resort to drugs and alcohol to cope. Just think what it's
like for a kid to overhear a producer angrily talking about low
ratings and possible cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   And in a business where rejection is the norm, just what kind of
toll does that take on a child's psyche?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, child stars seem to have it all. They make great
money. Get invited to glamorous parties and have adoring fans
screaming their names. But when the cameras stop rolling and the
director yells, ``Cut!'' the bottom line is, many are just sad,
lonely and scared little kids.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear the term ``former child star,'' most people, I'm
sure, immediately think of such troubled actors as Todd Bridges
(''Diff'rent Strokes''). Bridges' brushes with drugs and the law
are now legendary. In the special, he says he always felt more at
home on the ``Diff'rent Strokes'' set because his real dad was a
raging alcoholic who acted like a ``pit bull'' at home.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the stories are tales of woe. Some are downright
hilarious. Bill Mumy (''Lost in Space''), for example, remembers
shooting an ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents ``episode when he was 7.
Mumy kept fidgeting during his scene, which drove the intimidating
director nuts. So, Hitchcock finally told a terrified Mumy that if
he didn't stop moving, he'd nail his feet to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the blood,'' Hitchcock intoned, ``will come pouring out
like milk.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the always delightful Danny Bonaduce (''The
Partridge Family'') who loved his time as a child star. ``I was
short, fat with red hair and freckles,'' he says, ``and I took two
cheerleaders to the prom...life was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
