<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-     09-01 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1005(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DEFENDS AD THAT ATTACKS GORE'S CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Replaces last 2 grafs with 8 new grafs, beginning ``The tone
of ...,'' which give more details about Bush's attitude to the
campaign.)  
(With BUSH-EXCERPTS) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT5,27 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush on Friday defended a new
advertisement that challenges the credibility and character of Vice
President Al Gore and signaled that his frequent pledge to ``change
the tone'' of politics would not prevent him from raising questions
about Gore's truthfulness and leadership abilities in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In an extended interview on his campaign plane, he repeatedly
remarked, almost as if intoning a mantra, that the Democrats had
now run $30 million in ads against him. And he cast the new
Republican commercial ridiculing Gore and bringing up the vice
president's 1996 fund-raising appearance at a Buddhist temple as a
way to undermine public confidence in Gore's own accusations
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is what's going to happen in the campaign, we've got
to lay the groundwork: This is a fellow that will say anything,''
Bush said, referring to Gore. ``The point is, this is a way to help
inoculate me about what has come and is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   He later added that ``the Republican party is putting people on
notice that he is willing to exaggerate in order to win, to curry
their favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke, for nearly 45 minutes, at a pivotal moment in his
campaign. He was not only heading into the Labor Day weekend and
the final two months of the race, but also trying to emerge from a
bumpy two weeks on the campaign trail, during which he was often
thrown off his chosen message and put on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there have been accumulating signs that Bush's
sustained advantage over Gore in the polls has vanished. In recent
days, several nationwide polls have shown the race to be a dead
heat, and a Newsweek poll released Friday found Gore with a lead of
10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Even on Friday, on his campaign plane, Bush was pelted with
questions that had nothing to do with his designated themes of the
week. During an impromptu news conference, reporter after reporter
sharply questioned him about how the attack commercial, which is
being run by the Republican National Committee, with the approval
of the Bush campaign, squared with his promise to take the high
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was tongue-in-cheek,'' he told reporters. ``This
ad came up after about $30 million of advertisements that had been
attacking me and my record, and I'm glad they came to my defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was raising questions about Gore's
truthfulness, he said, ``No, I'm just saying this is a man who'll
say things like he's for campaign-funding reform and then
conveniently forgets he went to the Buddhist temple.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the subsequent interview, Bush projected a demeanor that
was alternately intense and jocular, cutting and funny, and that
never showed any fissures of worry.
</P>
<P>
   He went out of his way to assert that he was pleased with the
state of the race. ``I just want to tell you what my mood is, if
you don't mind,'' he said, unprompted. ``I feel great. I do. I feel
comfortable. My spirits are high.''
</P>
<P>
   But he exhibited subtle, fleeting flashes of irritation when the
topic turned to questions about the finances of his running mate,
Dick Cheney, and, earlier, when a grilling about the Republican
National Committee's ad went on for more than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this interview on one ad?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Told that there were more subjects to come, he said, ``Then keep
going, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Cheney's retirement package, which includes
lucrative stock options in Halliburton, an energy services company
that could be affected by federal policy, Bush said he had known
about the package when he picked Cheney as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will deal with the options issue in a way that is
comforting to the people,'' Bush said. ``He'll deal with it. Dick
Cheney's an honest man and when he says he'll do something, he'll
do something.'' (Later in the day, Cheney announced that if
elected, he would forfeit the stock options he had not yet been
able to exercise.)
</P>
<P>
   At another moment, his eyes grew wet as he reflected, in an
almost elegiac tone, on the ``amazing experience'' of running for
president. ``I am so honored to be one of two coming down the
stretch _ I am,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was suddenly teary, he said: ``I'm not teary. I'm
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   He also referred several times to his father's presidential
campaigns, drawing comfort from the lessons of the past and the
perspective it gives him. He acknowledged that many political
analysts believe he cannot beat an incumbent administration in
peaceful prosperous times.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that a different kind of conventional wisdom proved
wrong when his father defeated Michael Dukakis in 1988. He recalled
how pundits at the time cited the ``Van Buren factor,'' which was
the idea ``that no sitting vice president could possibly be
elected, because it had never happened since Martin Van Buren.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``Therefore George H.W. Bush could not possibly
win,'' and added that each campaign brings ``a historical certainty
that always seems to get defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush provided some insight into how his campaign would engage
Gore over the next few weeks, making clear that he would keep
trumpeting the charge that Gore and President Clinton had
squandered their time in the White House and failed to do what they
had told Americans they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it amazing _ and I think America will, too _ that some
of the same campaign issues they ran on in '92 are issues they run
on in the year 2000,'' Bush said, lumping Gore and Clinton
together. He mentioned Medicare reform, Social Security reform and
a middle-class tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would convince Americans that the Democratic
administration bore the blame and not the leaders of the Republican
Congress, he said, in reference to Gore, ``It sounds like this is a
campaign where they're going to be willing to say, `Give me credit
for things that went well, but let's blame others for failure.' And
to me, I think Americans will realize that's not what a leader
does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside any suggestion that voters might decide that
his engagement of Gore contradicted his promise to ``change the
tone,'' a claim so central to his candidacy that it was the
designated theme _ printed on banners _ for the week after the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is politics,'' Bush said. He then drew a distinction
between campaigning and governing _ between ads and his
willingness, if he is elected, to work with Democrats like Sens.
John Breaux of Louisiana and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska on issues such
as Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In much the same manner that he used in dealing with questions
about the ads, Bush dismissed any idea that voters were paying
attention to the debate over presidential debates and the fact that
he had not agreed to the three forums proposed by the bipartisan
commission on presidential debates. Gore has accepted those
invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that this was a familiar replay of his campaign for
governor in 1994, when the then-incumbent, Ann Richards, accused
him of dodging debates.
</P>
<P>
   Mocking the Richards camp, he said: ``I remember it clearly. `He
won't debate! He won't debate! He won't debate! He won't debate!'
And we debated, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks about the Republican attack ad, Bush made clear
that he did not like Gore's frequent assertions that the Texas
governor was not offering specific enough policies on matters like
prescription-drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Republicans had chosen to run the ad now, he
referred to $30 million in Democratic commercials and then added,
``The rhetoric started getting a little harsh _ `Put up or shut
up.''' Gore has been using that refrain to goad Bush to give more
specifics on his policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush now plans to release a Medicare prescription-drug plan next
week. Until now he had outlined some broad principles and spoken
positively of one bipartisan bill in the Senate. He insisted Friday
that he had ``always planned'' to provide more detail. He said he
also planned to return next week to the issue of military
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he did not intend to provide more particulars
of his call to divert some of the Social Security payroll tax to
individual investment accounts. ``My Social Security position is
where it is,'' he said, adding that he thought voters understood
the fundamentals of what he was proposing.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, Bush said that despite his and Cheney's
criticisms of the Clinton administration's peacekeeping missions,
he would not pull U.S. troops out of Bosnia and Kosovo immediately
if elected, ``because I understand the commitment to which we are
bound.'' He added, ``But I will work with our allies to lay the
groundwork for them to take up more of the peacekeeping role in
Bosnia and Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of Bush's remarks during the interview meandered from a
serene confidence about his chances of victory to an almost
nostalgic distance from the race.
</P>
<P>
   He talked for a minute or two at one point about how important
it was to use the campaign to build a governing mandate for the
first 100 days of a Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I'm going to win, and when I win, I want to get some
things done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also talked about the privilege of being a part of
history, no matter what the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great journey,'' he said. ``I'm going to look back
on these days.''
</P>
<P>
   He said repeatedly that he trusted the judgment of the American
people, although he did not always like it, mentioning his father's
failed 1992 re-election effort as an example.
</P>
<P>
   And if voters ultimately decided against him, as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, I would respect that,'' he said. ``I'm not going to
like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
