u f BC-WIRELESS-EAVESDROPPIN     09-01 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-EAVESDROPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWS IN DIGITAL WIRELESS TECHNOLOGY SAID TO ALLOW EAVESDROPPING
</HEADLINE>
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
   Two researchers have found that a widely heralded new wireless
technology contains flaws that could permit an eavesdropper to
listen in on a digital conversation or determine the user's
identity.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The researchers are from Lucent Technologies, one of nine
corporations developing the technology, known as Bluetooth, whose
backers say it will make possible a new era of effortless and
untethered communication between all kinds of hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies have recently begun shipping sample quantities
of the Bluetooth technology, which has been expected to be widely
available in the first half of next year, and more than 1,000
companies are backing the standard.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kan, a member of the Bluetooth technical standards group
and a Lucent marketing manager, said he expected that the problem
could be fixed ``relatively quickly'' and would not seriously delay
the technology's deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluetooth system is intended to permit cellular phones,
portable computers, headsets and other mobile devices to exchange
digital information easily without cords or wires. It has a
potential range of 30 feet to 300 feet, but is initially planned
for devices in relatively close proximity.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws were discovered by Markus Jacobson and Susanne Wetzel,
researchers in the secure systems research department at Lucent's
Bell Laboratories unit.
</P>
<P>
   One shortcoming would have permitted an eavesdropper in a
cybercafe to place a bugging device in such a way that the
encryption key used by the Bluetooth devices could be obtained,
Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining the key would let the intruder listen in on a
conversation between two Bluetooth devices.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also discovered that it was possible to obtain
the identity of a Bluetooth device, making it traceable and
potentially compromising the security of a user.
</P>
<P>
   An independent security expert said that the Bluetooth security
model was still untested and that other flaws were likely to be
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably dozens of vulnerabilities,'' said the
expert, Bruce Schneier, founder and chief technical officer of
Counterpane Internet Security. ``The basic problem is that you're
building a system that allows devices who don't know each other to
communicate. I believe there are too many things that can go
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000901.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CFO0903-COX     09-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CFO0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Turnover of CFOs increases sharply
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You can probably name baseball players that have stuck
with one team longer than the CFO of your favorite company has been
with that organization.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it. Job-hopping has become a career path for chief
financial officers. So far this year, 43 of Georgia's 244 publicly
traded companies have replaced their chief financial officers.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover trend is national in scope. It is being driven, say
executive recruiters and chief financial officers, by openings at
new companies, in addition to retirements, promotions, burnout and
firings.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Executives Institute surveyed chief financial
officers in September and found 27 percent of those polled had
changed jobs within the last two years. A quarter of the executives
said they planned to switch jobs within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of a chief financial officer, for whatever reason,
is akin to a key player leaving a baseball team, and it grabs the
attention of investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always concerned; they kind of think of (the CFO)
as the second in command,'' said Roy Vogeltanz, spokesman for
Marietta, Ga.-based CryoLife, one of the companies that changed
chief financial officers this year. Analysts and investors wonder,
he added, ``How long is it going to take him or her (the
replacement) to learn the business?''
</P>
<P>
   In CryoLife's case, the answer was not long, since the new chief
financial officer, Ashley Lee, had been the company's controller
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors are more concerned with why a chief financial
officer leaves than who the successor is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would probably be a mistake to rush out and sell every time
a CFO quits, but it is a red flag,'' said Atlanta money manager
Scott Satterwhite of Artisan Partners. ``What you fear when one of
these things is announced is whether the CFO is cooking the books
or he sees something in the company that looks bad to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Satterwhite's worst fears are seldom borne out, he added. But
that doesn't keep him from worrying. ``It may be a low probability,
but the consequences are high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human nature is always going to fear the worst,'' said Edwin
Cordell, who left the chief financial officer's post at CryoLife
this year. His resignation ``to pursue other career opportunities''
was announced on April 19, and he promptly received phone calls
from a couple of analysts who follow the company.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts, Cordell recalled, were surprised at the news.
``They were trying to find out if there was a disagreement between
the CEO and CFO; if there is a problem with the technology'' at
CryoLife, which preserves tissue for surgical use and makes heart
valves and surgical glue.
</P>
<P>
   Cordell said the analysts' concerns were eased when he let them
know he was headed for another company. The next day, Novoste, a
Norcross company that developed a device to keep arteries from
reclosing after they have been unblocked, announced it had hired
Cordell as chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Cordell is not the only executive to move from one metro Atlanta
company to another. The opportunities in the area are such that a
chief financial officer can switch jobs without changing home
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really have to leave (Atlanta) if you don't want
to,'' said Michael Casey, chief financial officer of iXL
Enterprises since late July.
</P>
<P>
   Casey was chief financial officer at RedCelsius before joining
iXL Enterprises. Prior to that, he was chief financial officer at
metro area companies Manhattan Associates and Colorocs Information
Technologies, and vice president of finance at the since-acquired
IQ Software. He helped take Manhattan Associates and IQ Software
public.
</P>
<P>
   The demand by IPO-minded high-technology companies for chief
financial officers has accentuated the turnover among his
colleagues, according to Casey. His viewpoint is supported by Peter
Crist, founder of Crist Partners, a Chicago-based executive search
firm that's now part of Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had hundreds and hundreds of new companies formed in
the last 12 months,'' noted Crist. He added that new companies
planning to go public want to have a chief financial officer on
board who has public company experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That manifests itself in being constantly bombarded by the
premier executive recruiting firms,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of demand, it's no surprise chief financial
officers are making much more than they did just a few years ago.
According to Business Week, the median pay for a chief financial
officer last year was $1.1 million, almost double the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
   But with more money comes more responsibility and pressure,
according to executive recruiter Crist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is a kind of new strategy where you have a
partnership between the CEO and the CFO,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in general the CFO role has moved beyond tabulating
and communicating (financial) results to adding value in the
operating area,'' suggested Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Chief financial officers now are involved in mergers and
acquisitions, risk management, information technology and research
and development, in addition to tracking and reporting on
financials and serving as a key contact for Wall Street analysts
and institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   All of that really puts them in the spotlight _ and at higher
risk _ according to Chris Allen, spokesman for the Financial
Executives Institute in Morristown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boards and CEOs,'' he said, ``expect consistent results and
have little patience for anything but that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
