<SLUG> BC-EMULAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVACAP ACQUIRES BRITISH TECH FIRM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALENCIA, Calif. _ NovaCap Inc., a subsidiary of Dover Corp.,
has acquired Syfer Technology LTD, a British manufacturer of
specialty ceramic electronic components, a company official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger basically means twice the amount of potential
sales,'' said Vaughn Chicagus, NovaCap's controller. ``The customer
market we serve is domestic and Far East, while they have a minor
presence in the U.S. and dominate Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   No layoffs are planned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition brings together two companies that manufacture
high-voltage safety capacitors, a critical component in modems and
information technology equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Valencia since 1988, NovaCap has been expanding the
company's manufacturing plants in both England and the United
States to satisfy the growing specialty capacitor markets in
telecom, datacom, medical and aerospace industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been hiring all year,'' Chicagus said. ``We have hired
140 people and will continue to hire new employees until we reach
250 total.''
</P>
<P>
   The continued hiring has nothing to do with the Syfer merger, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Syfer is headquartered in Norwich, England, and makes surface
mount capacitors, EMI filters and planner arrays.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of NovaCap's parent company, New York-based Dover Corp.,
fell 0.563 cents, or 1.1 percent, to close Friday at $48.313 on
heavy volume of 472,200 shares traded on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
