<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN BRUINS TURN THE TIDE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Catholics have Lent. Jews have Yom Kippur. Muslims
have Ramadan. And the UCLA football team had its own period of
atonement - the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was karma or coincidence, the Bruins figure they're
paid in full for the sins of the handicapped parking scandal after
last year's injury-wracked 4-7 season, their second-worst since
1971.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, unranked but newly penitent, begin the season today
at 12:30 p.m. at the Rose Bowl against third-ranked Alabama
determined to show the expected crowd of nearly 80,000 and a
nearly-national TV audience that last year was an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins say they don't look at Alabama, a six-point favorite,
with apprehension but with a sense of opportunity. This isn't Boise
State, it's a chance to clear their name. And are the Bruins ever
hungry for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starving,'' said senior linebacker Tony White, one of
the Bruins game captains today. ``It's like somebody who hasn't
eaten in days and they see a big ol' steak. All of a sudden, he
starts drooling out his mouth. That's us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to keep Alabama from knocking the slobber out of them, the
Bruins need to have several questions answered affirmatively:
</P>
<P>
   --Quarterback Cory Paus has looked impressive in fall camp -
throwing crisply and accurately, and making good decisions, but can
he deliver the ball to the Bruins' playmakers and avoid the
critical mistake against an extremely fast, talented defense?
</P>
<P>
   --Can the offensive line, inexperienced and injured a year ago,
protect Paus and provide running room for DeShaun Foster against a
defense that returns eight starters and was ninth in the nation
last year in total defense?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the keys is for our offense to move the ball,'' UCLA
coach Bob Toledo said. ``If their defense just stuffs us and we go
three (plays) and out, three and out, we could be in for some
trouble because they're going to score some points. We have to be
able to run the ball, but it won't be easy to run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   --Can a defense with a banged-up front seven keep from getting
blown off the ball and can a secondary that's been so porous the
past two seasons cover and tackle adequately?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I've been here we haven't lived up to
expectations,'' end Kenyon Coleman said of the defense. ``We've got
a lot to prove. We want to show people the Bruins can play
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tackle Ken Kocher, the Bruins' best lineman against the run,
won't start and is questionable with a high ankle sprain. He won't
be on the field for more than 20 plays, Toledo said. There are also
depth problems at linebacker where Asi Faoa's suspension (fighting)
leaves true freshman Brandon Chillar backing up White, and
weak-side starter Ryan Nece might be limited by a sore shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama will throw all kinds of formations at UCLA, from a
five-receiver shotgun set to the I formation with two tight ends.
It will put a lot of pressure on UCLA to not only defend but
recognize what Alabama's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're extremely diverse,'' said UCLA defensive coordinator
Bob Field. ``You see every personnel grouping and every conceivable
formation. They put a lot of pressure on you to recognize what
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is not without questions of its own.
</P>
<P>
   While it lost just two starters on offense, they are guard Chris
Samuels, the No. 2 pick in the draft, and tailback Shaun Alexander,
who scored 23 of the Tide's 38 offensive touchdowns last season.
Until someone establishes himself, tailback will be a committee of
Shaun Bohanon, Ahmaad Galloway and Brandon Miree.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the weight of expectations. Alabama hasn't been
ranked in the top five since 1994 and fans back home are already
talking of a national championship. As many as 25,000 Tide fans are
expected at the Rose Bowl and they're not there to root a team on
to the Outback Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned because of the hype that's going with
this game, going out on the West Coast, and seeing the Rose Bowl
for the first time,'' `Bama coach Mike DuBose said. ``Good football
teams are ready to play when the ball is teed up.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Tide isn't, count on the Bruins to be.
</P>
<P>
   They've excelled as an underdog at home against ranked
nonconference opponents (4-3 since 1988 with narrow losses to
Michigan, Tennessee and Nebraska). And Toledo will be sure the
Bruins come out swinging - emotionally and tactically.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who loves trick plays, and offensive coordinator Al
Borges have had eight months to pick over film, so if there's a
weakness, they're sure to try to exploit it early. In Toledo's
first three seasons, the Bruins scored on their first possession
against No. 2 Tennessee, Washington State and No. 23 Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet where the Bruins will be at the end of the day even he
wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best team we've played since I've been here,''
Toledo said of Alabama. ``We're ahead of last year, but it might
not show it that much. I hope it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Parking is available on the Brookside Golf Course for $5.
Parking is also available at $5 at the Ralph Parsons Engineering
Building on Fair Oaks and Walnut in Pasadena with a free shuttle
bus to and from the Rose Bowl with service beginning at 8:30 a.m.
... Ticket booths and will-call booths at the Rose Bowl will open
at 9 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
