<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-CASINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TRIBAL STATUS PENDING, PEQUOTS HOPE FOR CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Eastern Pequot Indians, a Connecticut tribe seeking formal
recognition by the federal government, have publicly acknowledged
for the first time that they hope to build a casino as part of a
larger ``world class'' resort.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, the tribe had declined to discuss its economic
development plans, although casino gambling is widely recognized as
perhaps the most lucrative opportunity afforded by official
recognition from the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, and other
local government officials have opposed the Eastern Pequots'
petition for tribal recognition, saying the tribe does not meet the
historical criteria required under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's interest in casino gambling was first reported
Thursday in The Norwich Bulletin and confirmed Friday in a
statement issued by its council. The statement said the tribe hoped
to develop ``a tourism-based family resort'' in partnership with a
local municipality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will develop a plan that may include hotels, restaurants,
entertainment and shopping, along with golf and other outdoor
activities,'' the tribal vice chairman, Mark Sebastian, said in the
statement. ``Subject to the required federal and state approvals,
we will also examine the feasibility of gaming as part of the
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said Friday that his office would continue to oppose
recognition for the tribe. ``The specifics of their economic
development plan really are irrelevant to our position on
recognition,'' he said. ``We've asked probative and challenging
questions about the merits of their petition based on factual and
legal gaps that we see in their application.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``And their statement simply confirms suspicions that
are widely held about the plan to do gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has repeatedly voiced opposition to formal
recognition, last month urging the Interior Department, which
decides the matter, to postpone its decision. But an official at
the Bureau of Indian Affairs, part of the department, has already
issued a preliminary finding favoring recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Tyler, a spokeswoman for the Eastern Pequots, said the
tribe was interested in finding a municipal partner for its
economic development plans. In the past, tribal officials have
thanked the Trump organization for supporting their effort to
achieve recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe shares a reservation of over 200 acres in North
Stonington, Conn., with the Paucatuck Eastern Pequots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
