<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-POLLARD     09-01 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-POLLARD-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON INTERVENES ON SPY'S BEHALF 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton quietly intervened last week
to save Jonathan Pollard, the American convicted of spying for
Israel, from a transfer to a more dangerous unit of the federal
prison where he is serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's action falls short of calling upon President
Clinton to grant Pollard clemency, her Senate campaign is hoping
that the intervention will make clear her sympathies and strengthen
the first lady's sluggish support among Jews.
</P>
<P>
   A number of New York Jewish leaders, who consider Pollard's
sentence too harsh, are increasing pressure on Hillary Rodham
Clinton to call for his release. Such a move would be a dramatic
break from her husband and from the positions of his
administration's foreign policy and defense establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign officials said Friday that Clinton's action,
which was first reported in Friday's New York Post, was not
necessarily a precursor to calling for clemency. ``She did it
because the issue was brought to her attention, and she was
concerned on humanitarian grounds,'' said Howard Wolfson, a Clinton
campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson added that Hillary Rodham Clinton was ``continuing to
study'' the issue. In June, Clinton said that she would ``work on''
forming an opinion before the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, Clinton's opponent, has said that he had not
had the kind of ``secured briefing'' he needed to make a judgment
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard is imprisoned in a special unit of the Federal
Correctional Institution in Butner, N.C. The unit, used primarily
to house nonviolent sex offenders, is considered safer than another
unit to which Pollard was to have been transferred last week.
Pollard's supporters said Friday they worried that he might have
been exposed to rapes, stabbings and other violence there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton intervened after meeting in Manhattan on Wednesday with
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and Assemblyman Dov Hikind of
Brooklyn, an Orthodox Jew whose endorsement she seeks. Although
both men asked her during the hour-and-a-half meeting to call for
clemency for Pollard, it was not until the next day that they
received word of Pollard's impending transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind immediately called Clinton, who quickly contacted ``White
House officials,'' according to her campaign. Those officials,
Wolfson said, got in touch with ``the appropriate authorities.'' He
would not specify more. But by the following day, Friday, Hikind
was informed by Clinton's campaign that the problem had been taken
care of and that Pollard would stay where he was. It was not clear
Friday why prison officials wanted to move Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled that she acted in this particular instance,''
said Hikind, a Democrat who often supports Republicans. ``A lot of
people are gratified by what she did. People see this as positive
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind added that although he is considering endorsing Clinton,
he has not made his support contingent upon her support for
Pollard's release. No such deal was offered at the meeting, he
said, adding that even if the first lady did call for Pollard's
release, that would not be enough for him. ``There are other issues
she needs to address,'' Hikind said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Democrats who support Clinton are divided over how
much Hikind's endorsement matters, and how many votes it would
attract even within his own constituency. The campaign's attitude,
for now, is that his support could not hurt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pollard pleaded guilty to espionage in 1986 for selling some of
the United States' most sensitive intelligence information to
Israel. His supporters say that Pollard, who was a civilian
intelligence analyst for the Navy, simply passed along information
to an ally that was already receiving U.S. intelligence through
official channels. Military officials say he passed along highly
sensitive material about Soviet weapon designs, among other things,
that jeopardized agents working inside Russia.
</P>
<P>
   His case has been the subject of intense political debate for
years, and it almost derailed the Wye peace agreement in 1998.
Since then, the Clinton administration has been reviewing Israel's
request that Pollard be released. Support for Pollard, who has been
championed by Jews on the right, has been growing among mainstream
and more liberal groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
