<SLUG> BC-THQ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME MAKER GIVEN $50 MILLION LINE OF CREDIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ Video game manufacturer THQ Inc. announced
Friday that it has secured a new $50 million line of credit with a
number of financial institutions, including Union Bank of
California.
</P>
<P>
   The new line of credit provides for cash advances or a letter of
credit during the Calabasas-based company's peak selling season,
which is from November to February, according to a company
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Kathy Mendoza explained that the additional credit
line also gives the company up to $25 million in financing outside
the peak selling season.
</P>
<P>
   The company's previous agreement with Union Bank, which recently
expired, provided for cash advances of up to $38 million and a
total line of credit up to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides all the funds to finance the company for the next
year,'' said Fred Gysi, THQ's senior vice president of finance and
administration and chief financial officer. ``It also allows us to
purchase products during the holiday season.''
</P>
<P>
   Gysi said the company develops and designs interactive
entertainment software for video games, then pays either Sony,
Nintendo or Sega to manufacture the game.
</P>
<P>
   The financing allows THQ to then purchase the finished product
back from Sony, Sega or Nintendo and distribute it to Wal-Mart and
other retailers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of THQ lost 18 cents, or 0.88 percent, to close Friday at
$21.188 on light volume of 47,200 shares traded on the Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
