<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-JOBSHARING0903-COX     09-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBSHARING0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    Two for one plan to keep workers who want more balanced lives
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jon Vancleve, a work/life consultant with Hewitt
Associates, recently met an interesting pair.
</P>
<P>
   One of Vancleve's banking clients is now employing two people
who share the same job. They are bank managers who split between
them the full-time responsibility for managerial duties of their
branch.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, each had worked at separate offices. But now the two
share one job _ and a place in a growing workplace trend, said
Vancleve, whose office is in the Chicago area.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are finding is that (job sharing) is becoming more
popular,'' he said. ``It's been on the rise for the past five years
as an option for a flexible work arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hewitt survey of American firms found 28 percent of the
companies polled in 1999 allow job sharing. That figure is up from
18 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Job sharing is a work/life arrangement _ with management
approval _ between two employees who share full responsibility for
one job. A common arrangement is for each employee to work three
days a week, with one day overlapping. There are many variations on
the theme, however.
</P>
<P>
   Job sharing first gained national exposure in 1972 when Barney
Olmsted and Suzanne Smith, founders of New Ways to Work in San
Francisco, job-shared the post of director of the nonprofit firm.
</P>
<P>
   The option often comes into play when a company wishes to keep a
valued employee who seeks reduced hours but holds a job requiring
full-time coverage, reported HR Magazine in a recent case study on
the trend.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more workers strive for greater quality of life and
balance between work and personal commitments, and as employers
everywhere look at creative ways to attract and retain good
workers, job sharing has emerged as a creative solution for
satisfying both sides, Vancleve said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually is one of the best retention strategies in today's
market,'' said Katherine M. Donahue, president of the Marietta,
Ga.-based Mercury Group, a consulting firm that specializes in
organizational effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works the best in jobs where it's a transaction-oriented
job like customer service, accounting,'' for example, Donahue said.
</P>
<P>
   It may not work as well with work that requires long-term
projects and close, collaborative communication with clients and
co-workers, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur, Ga.-based Huddle House Restaurants has incorporated
job-sharing into its training program for about a year now,
according to Mike Wiemers, director of training.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 Huddle House employees in the company's 12-state
system are sharing jobs, Wiemers estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a cook's position that opens up on second shift, if
we have someone who can work part of it and someone can work the
remaining part of it, we do it that way,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The employees receive training at times that meet their specific
scheduling needs, if necessary, Wiemers said. Effective
communication between the job partners is stressed by Huddle
House's training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it `talking out of position,' '' Wiemers said,
describing the way the outgoing employee confers with the incoming
worker about the day's duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to make sure that as one's leaving, he's being
talked out of a position as the other is being talked into a
position, so that they know what needs to be done, whether it's
cooking or serving.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's more: ``We do a shift change checklist also . . .
that lets them know what has been accomplished and what should be
accomplished'' during the shift, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Experts expect the job-sharing option to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are getting interested in job sharing because it's a
wonderful concept to fill positions that need full-time coverage,
not part-time, and that's what you get 52 weeks a year,'' said
Nadine Mockler, principal of Flexible Resources Inc., a staffing
firm in Cos Cob, Conn., that specializes in permanent jobs with
flexible hours. ``Job sharing's only going to get bigger because
the labor market is shrinking, and the cream is thin on the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while some firms have resorted to giving away cars and
large cash bonuses to lure workers, Donahue said job sharing is a
competitive recruiting tool in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge deal to be able to offer something like that,''
she said. ``There are a lot of things important to employees rather
than all the money offers and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money offers are not as likely to entice (potential job
sharers) because they can't get that flexibility and that control''
over their time.
</P>
<P>
   That management will increasingly turn to job sharing is
something Shari Rosen Ascher is betting on. A job sharer in radio
advertising sales with Maggie Sisco since 1995, the two started
ShareGoals in April, a New York-based, job-sharing consulting firm
that offers training for management and employees and individual
counseling for potential job sharers.
</P>
<P>
   Their Web site, www.Sharegoals.com, has free information about
the option. And she and Sisco continue to job share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, Maggie and I have turned managers who were
doubters of job sharing into believers _ and we outlasted them,''
Ascher said. ``It's a way to keep talented people, and we want to
demystify it. Some managers think it's complicated, more expensive,
more work, and clients may not approve. But we have worked it all
through: Maggie and I even worked back-to-back maternity leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ascher said because of job sharing, she gets to go on class
trips with her kids and kick box and lift weights. ``Even when
stuff happens, work goes on when you job-share,'' she said.
``Employers get two minds and 20 fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   And they get more, according to Dana Mazis, sales manager at the
Hyatt Regency hotel of San Diego. ``Employers get the combined
strengths of two people, and they only have to pay for one,'' said
Mazis, who has job-shared with Susan Stoneback since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first sales managers here to job share, and now
three of our seven managers do, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason other Hyatt managers are adopting it: ``It works,''
Mazis said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement works best when employees initiate it, Hewitt's
Vancleve said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen that really makes them work or successful, the
two individuals within job sharing, in that position, really have
to be the ones that approach their manager to recommend the set up,
to make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When management puts forth the idea, they must be prepared to
let go of some of the traditional control they may have had over
other employees, Mercury's Donahue said.
</P>
<P>
   The option works best when the job-sharing pair decides who
works when, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I have seen it work best is if you hire people with
dissimilar lives,'' such as one parent and one student, for
example, people whose lifestyle issues are different. Then, for
optimum benefits with job sharing, managers should ``allow the two
people to decide what hours they're going to work and that the two
of them can work that out as they go,'' Donahue added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
