<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Tim Belcher threw seven scoreless inning pitching on a
rehab assignment for Double-A Erie Friday night. He made 99
pitches, gave up four hits, struck out six and walked none. He
reached 89-mph on the radar gun and seems ready to take the next
step and join the big league club.
</P>
<P>
   But how the 38-year-old Belcher will fit in with a staff that is
full of young pitchers remains to be seen. Belcher started Game 1
of the 1988 World Series for the Dodgers when three of the Angels'
current starters were still in junior high. However, manager Mike
Scioscia won't commit to sticking Belcher into the starting
rotation just yet, leaving open the option to use him out of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, it comes down to getting it done,'' Scioscia said.
''You can talk all you want about intangibles. If it were only
about intangibles, I'd be catching and (pitching coach) Buddy Black
would be pitching. The bottom line is production. Certainly his
experience will be an asset, but it comes down to executing
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher executed his pitches Friday night, and might be a
consideration to start next Thursday in Detroit, moving Kent
Mercker to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher hasn't pitched in a major league game since July 2
because of a strained muscle in his right elbow. He had surgery on
the same elbow last off-season. In four starts this season, he is
2-2 with a 9.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrod Washburn is another option for Scioscia in the starting
rotation, but he is not as close to returning as Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn has a stress fracture in his left shoulder, but is
currently throwing without pain. He is scheduled to throw off the
mound again today.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's still hitting some bumps in the road,'' Scioscia said of
Washburn, who is 7-2 with a 3.74 ERA. ''But he's made consistent
progress, so he's still in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad started his seventh game in a row at designated
hitter Friday, still bothered by a strained muscle in his ribcage
that caused him to miss four games Aug. 20-23 in New York and
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad can hit but can't throw without pain. And he says the
club isn't being overly cautious with him because it's so late in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Put it this way,'' Erstad said. ''If I could throw I'd be out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT WHITE SOX
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 at Comiskey Park
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-9; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Kent Mercker (1-2, 5.71 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Chicago's Jim Parque (10-6, 4.36). Mercker is still trying
to find his command since returning to the active list Aug. 12
after recovering from a brain hemorrhage. He began the season in
the bullpen but was later moved to the rotation because of injuries
to others.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
