<SLUG> BC-NY-PAKISTAN-BAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEWAN   
</HEADLINE>
 
MEMBERS OF VISITING PAKISTANI BAND GO AWOL IN NEW YORK By SHAILA K. c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Pakistani military contingent landed on U.S. shores
last week and marched up Madison Avenue. Then part of it
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was front-page news in the city's Pakistani press _
seven or eight members of an army pipe and drum band who came to
New York for last Sunday's Pakistani Independence Day Parade had
fled. What they left behind were a few phone numbers found on a
host's caller ID box and a string of embarrassed officials
stretching from Pakistan to New York to Washington and back. And
with Pakistan's ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, about to visit for
the United Nations' Millennium Summit next week, the AWOL bagpipers
have engendered a string of denials and recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the band on the run, a spokeswoman for Pakistan's
mission to the United Nations recommended calling the Pakistan
Consulate. The consulate said to call the embassy in Washington.
The embassy, whose spokesmen said they were too busy to give their
names, suggested calling the consulate. All said they knew nothing
about the army band's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Two Pakistani officials visiting New York for the United Nations
event said they were not sure what had happened. Maj. Gen. Rashid
Qureshi, the director general of the army's information services,
and Javed Jabbar, the federal minister for information and media
development, said that they would gather details and call back on
Friday, but they did not.
</P>
<P>
   It was not even clear whether all of the band members were
members of the military. Qureshi said some of them were civilians.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the parade, some (either six or seven) of the
band members failed to appear at a dinner in their honor at the
Kashmir Restaurant in Midtown Manhattan, said Shaheen Khalid, the
restaurant's owner. Khokar told him that they ``fell sick, or
somehow there was some problem and they could not make it,'' Khalid
said.
</P>
<P>
   Azid M. Mian, the U.N. bureau chief for the Jang Group,
Pakistan's leading newspaper chain, said he, too, was at the
dinner, and that Khokar had invited him to go to New Jersey to
search a house there for the band members, but he refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the band _ or what was left of it _ dined at the
Bukhara restaurant on Coney Island Avenue in the Kensington section
of Brooklyn before its flight home from Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   There, another band member fled the restaurant after going to
the bathroom, said a manager who refused to give his name. The
manager said the man was pursued, but not caught. It is unclear
whether that man was the seventh or eighth deserter.
</P>
<P>
   Even the issue of where the band was staying is in dispute.
Lodhi and Khokar said the 24 members, plus the 11 Khattak dancers
who came with them, stayed at the homes of five parade trustees.
</P>
<P>
   But two of those trustees, Muzzafar Chaudry and Inayat Shaikh,
denied that. Chaudry said that all the band members had stayed at
the Brooklyn home of Latif Munawar Chaudry, another trustee.
Chaudry could not be reached for comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mian, the first journalist to report the story, has since become
something of a character in it, clearly relishing his investigative
role. He went to the airport to see which band members boarded the
departing plane, he said, and even warned an airline official to
process the passengers as individuals rather than as a group. He
said Khokar had asked him not to write about the defections.
</P>
<P>
   Khokar, in turn, told a reporter that Mian was using his ``whole
evil power'' to declaim the parade. He said that Mian had been
arrested in Pakistan and had been involved in a scheme to embezzle
port fees from the Pakistani government.
</P>
<P>
   Mian denied those accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani Independence Day Parade has not been without
controversy. Past organizers have been accused of using the parade
as a ver to bring illegal Pakistani immigrants into the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
