<HEADLINE>
PETA OFFERS APOLOGY TO MAYOR FOR MILK ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Pa., Va.)   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After riding a wave of publicity, an animal rights
group apologized Friday to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for using his
face on billboard advertising that linked milk consumption to
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The group, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals,
sponsored four billboards that appeared in milk-producing sections
of Wisconsin and Pennsylvania last week. The ads, which were widely
criticized, clearly angered the mayor, who said they were
exploiting his illness.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter of apology to the mayor, PETA said the ads ``were
not intended as an attack on you, and we're sorry they were taken
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The billboards, already taken down by the advertising companies
that put them up, were ``intended to be provocative, not hurtful, a
fine line that we regret we crossed,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The apology elicited little response from City Hall on Friday. A
spokeswoman for the mayor, Sunny Mindel, said Giuliani had not read
the letter and would withhold comment. Senior advisers to Giuliani,
insisting that their names not be used, complained privately that
PETA's intent was to attract more publicity.
</P>
<P>
   PETA, based in Norfolk, Va., has long been known for abrasive
tactics in promoting animal rights. Its president, Ingrid E.
Newkirk, said in an interview Friday that the group had ``incurred
a lot of wrath'' because of the ads using Giuliani's face with a
milk mustache, but said that it had scored a publicity coup that
exceeded its own expectations.
</P>
<P>
   She said 58,000 people had sought out PETA's Web site on the
issue, www.dumpdairy.com, during the week since the dispute with
the mayor made its way into newspapers and television reports. She
added that of those who called or e-mailed their opinions, most had
been sympathetic to the mayor, saying that the ad campaign unfairly
exploited his illness.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble with PETA began on Aug. 24, when the mayor
threatened to sue the group over its billboards, which were
dominated by an oversized image of his face in a parody of the
ubiquitous ``Got Milk?'' ads that are sponsored by the dairy
industry. One line of text on PETA's ads read ``Got prostate
cancer?'' Another read ``Drinking milk contributes to prostate
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides threatening legal action, the mayor responded with
ridicule. He seemed to delight in the exchange, at one point
spending two hours on stage at a town hall meeting last week in
midtown Manhattan with a half-gallon of milk by his side, and
repeatedly drinking from a glass on his lectern.
</P>
<P>
   Despite PETA's apology to the mayor, Newkirk seemed on Friday to
revel in the publicity, which she said had come at little cost.
Because the advertising companies in Wisconsin and Pennsylvania had
taken down the PETA billboards over the group's objections, she
said the companies had now agreed to either refund PETA's money or
erect new billboards that attack the dairy industry without using
the mayor's face.
</P>
<P>
   PETA said it was already preparing a new campaign featuring Bill
Maher, host of ``Politically Incorrect'' and a supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor drew more attention to this than we could have of
our own devices,'' Newkirk said. ``People usually don't expect us
to act like grown-ups, but they do expect it of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
