<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MAN IS FIRST IN NEW JERSEY INFECTED BY WEST NILE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Jersey reported its first human case of infection
with the West Nile virus on Friday, while New York reported its
seventh, a 61-year-old Staten Island man.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials in New Jersey said a 43-year-old Jersey City
man was hospitalized last month with a headache and a 100-degree
fever. On Friday, the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention confirmed a finding by the New Jersey Department of
Health and Senior Services that the virus had been detected in the
man's blood and spinal fluid. Health officials did not identify the
man but said he had been discharged from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent victim in New York has also returned home, said
Dr. Neal Cohen, the city health commissioner, at a news conference
Friday. The man, who was not identified, lives in Staten Island,
officials said. He was found to be infected after he was admitted
to a hospital complaining of muscle fatigue and was given a
diagnosis of encephalitis, a potentially fatal inflammation of the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six other people infected in New York, only one, an
87-year-old Brooklyn woman who suffered seizures and lapsed into a
coma shortly after becoming infected, remains in a hospital, city
health officials said. The woman, still in critical condition, is
also the only victim who does not live on Staten Island, which has
become the epicenter of this year's West Nile outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said New York City would continue efforts to combat the
virus by spraying pesticides in areas where large numbers of
infected mosquitoes have been trapped.
</P>
<P>
   On Staten Island, the city has found 67 such areas, compared
with seven in Manhattan, three in Queens and two in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Though the number of cases confirmed this year continues to lag
behind the 10 cases reported by this time last year, health
officials urged caution and said they were not ready to declare
their strategy a success, especially with hundreds of thousands of
people expected to be outdoors over the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the past few weeks have been the peak time of the
mosquito season,'' Cohen said, ``it would not be unexpected if we
were to learn of additional cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Smith, a spokeswoman for the New York State Health
Department, added: ``It was just about this time last year that we
started discovering cases. It's certainly too soon to now say we
have this thing beaten. We've got to be vigilant for a number of
more weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New Jersey health officials continue to turn up
infected birds, including 469 dead crows and one cockatiel so far.
The state is awaiting tests on blood and spinal fluid from 19
people who have recently become ill and live near areas where the
birds were found.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Friday's news, New Jersey health officials urged
people not to panic. Instead, said Dennis McGowan, a spokesman for
the state health department, ``take the precautions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
