u a BC-OBIT-CAVANAGH-NYT &LR;      09-01 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAVANAGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES CAVANAGH, FORMER NEW YORK DEPUTY MAYOR, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Cavanagh, a former first deputy mayor who advised Mayor
Abraham Beame during the depth of New York City's fiscal crisis in
the 1970s, died Thursday at a hospice near his home in Boynton
Beach, Fla. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Brooklyn, New York, whose career in city government
spanned four decades, Cavanagh spent many of his early years with
the city as an examiner in the Department of Finance. A longtime
friend and adviser to Beame, he was a senior adviser to the city
comptroller when Beame held that position in the early 1970s. He
was brought to City Hall when Beame took office as mayor in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh, a genial, slightly rumpled man, was widely respected
for his financial acumen, but he nonetheless bore the brunt of
fierce criticism directed at Beame's fiscal management; Wall Street
bond analysts condemned the city's borrowing as excessive and all
but cut off New York's ability to pay its bills through the use of
public financing and municipal bonds. Despite Cavanagh's loyalty to
Beame, the ensuing fiscal crisis led him to resign his City Hall
post under pressure in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a quiet man who wouldn't speak unless asked, and when
asked, he always knew the answer,'' said Julius Edelstein, the
senior vice chancellor emeritus at the City University of New York,
a longtime friend of Cavanagh. ``He was not only a fiscal expert,
but an expert on government operations, and they offered him up as
a scapegoat to the bankers,'' Edelstein said in an interview
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his short tenure at City Hall, Cavanagh was able to
complete a major assignment from Beame: organizing the city's Off
Track Betting Corp., a venture intended at the time to raise
revenue and prop up city finances.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh is also recalled fondly by friends and family members
for a less widely known accomplishment: he completed years of night
classes to obtain his bachelor of arts degree from Empire State
College while serving as first deputy mayor.
</P>
<P>
   After his resignation, Cavanagh dedicated himself to volunteer
work before retiring and moving to Boynton Beach, Fla., in 1982. He
was a trustee of the City University of New York, president of the
Brooklyn Council of the Boy Scouts of America and an adviser to the
Fund for the City of New York, a private foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 22 years, the former Mary Delano
of Boynton Beach; two sons, James of Sarasota, Fla., and
Christopher of Hazlet, N.J.; four stepchildren; and nine
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
