<SLUG> BC-RUN-BERLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE MAKES A GOLDEN STATEMENT FOR THE SYDNEY GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 By ALAN MAIMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Maurice Greene ran to victory in the men's 100 meters
on Friday and concluded the Golden League series with the fastest
time of the year and a suitcase full of gold. Greene's victory in
9.86 seconds at the ISTAF 2000 meet entitled him to a share of the
$1 million jackpot _ which is given out in gold bars _ awarded to
athletes who have won their events in at least five of the seven
Golden League meets this summer.
</P>
<P>
   On a brisk evening at the Olympic Stadium, Greene trailed Jon
Drummond at the start of the race but surged ahead to beat him by
one-tenth of a second. After a disappointing third-place finish in
rainy Gateshead, England, on Monday, Greene believed he had
something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show the world I will be unbeatable in Sydney,''
Greene said before the meet. ``If all the others go to the Olympics
feeling they have no chance, it will be easier for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the race he said, ``I'm exactly where I want to be heading
into the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The ISTAF was the last major meet before the Summer Games in
Sydney, Australia, which begin Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones may have left Berlin without a share of the
jackpot, but she secured a decisive victory in the women's 100
meters. Jones won with a time of 10.78 seconds, matching the year's
best time, which she set in London in August. She has not been
defeated in a 100-meter race since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Jones said after the race. ``The cool weather
we had tonight isn't really my favorite, but I ran really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Greene both ended their evenings with victorious
anchor legs in the 100-meter exhibition relays. Jones made up a big
deficit, while Greene held on to a comfortable lead given to him by
Drummond, Bernhard Williams and Curtis Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   As the late evening wind kicked up, Michael Johnson took to the
track and won the men's 400 meters. His time of 45.00 seconds was a
far cry from his goal of breaking the 43-second mark before he
retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a great performance, but I'm satisfied,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones opted not to participate in the long jump, an event she
has struggled in this summer. Without Jones, it became a showdown
between Heike Drechsler of Germany and Tatiana Kotova of Russia. In
her final jump of the evening, Kotova edged Drechsler by a quarter
of an inch, leaping 22 feet 10 inches to secure her share of the
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. shot-putter Adam Nelson fouled on five of his six
attempts, but his one legal throw of 68-6{ was good enough for
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a Dartmouth graduate taking time off from his job as a
business development manager in Silicone Valley, will face stiff
Olympic competition from his fellow American C.J. Hunter, a
last-minute no-show on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A boisterous crowd of 41,300 watched the meet at the stadium
where Jesse Owens captured four gold medals at the 1936 Olympics. A
sizable portion of the stadium was closed off because of
renovations for the soccer World Cup in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Trine Hattestad, a Norwegian javelin thrower, and Hicham
el-Guerrouj, the Moroccan 1,500-meter runner, continued their
winning ways. Both won for the fifth time in the Golden League.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Devers, who withdrew from Friday's event because of a
strained hamstring, was the fifth athlete to share the prize. She
won the 100 hurdles at five consecutive Golden League meets before
her injury. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
