<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-TRAUTWEIN-NYT     09-01 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TRAUTWEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 THEODORE TRAUTWEIN, JUDGE IN LANDMARK PRESS CASE, DIES AT 80
</HEADLINE>
 By   DAVID CORCORAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore W. Trautwein, the New Jersey judge who sent a reporter
to jail in 1978 in a celebrated case that tested the boundaries of
press freedom and fair trials, died on Aug. 17 in Hollywood, Fla.,
where he had lived for the last two years. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, said his son, Ted.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1978, M.A. Farber, a reporter for The New York Times,
was called to Superior Court in Hackensack, N.J., to testify in the
trial of a 51-year-old surgeon accused of murdering three patients
at a small hospital in nearby Oradell by injecting them with lethal
doses of the muscle relaxant curare. Front-page articles by Farber
in 1976 had led the Bergen County prosecutor's office to reopen the
case, which it had abandoned 10 years earlier, and exhume the
patients' bodies to test for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Though he answered questions from lawyers defending the surgeon,
Dr. Mario E. Jascalevich, Farber refused to turn over thousands of
pages of notes demanded by the defense, saying the First Amendment
compelled him to protect those who had talked to him in confidence.
The trial judge, William J. Arnold, turned the matter over to
Trautwein, who as assignment judge supervised all the Bergen County
civil, criminal and municipal courts.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, 1978, before a courtroom packed with journalists and
spectators (including Jascalevich), Trautwein found Farber and The
Times guilty of criminal contempt and sentenced the reporter to
jail for six months and the paper to fines of $5,000 a day until
the notes were turned over.
</P>
<P>
   A beefy, imposing judge who was all business on the bench and
who favored plain English over legalese, he later told Farber,
``You chose to put your privilege and your concept of your
constitutional rights above the rights of the people of this state
and this defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   With time off for appeals, Farber wound up spending 40 days in
the Bergen County Jail, one of the longest sentences ever served by
an American reporter for refusing to testify about sources.
Trautwein freed him on Oct. 24, shortly before the jury acquitted
Jascalevich after just three hours of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   In upholding Trautwein's action in August 1978, the New Jersey
Supreme Court also overturned the state law shielding reporters
from having to testify about their sources in criminal cases. The
New Jersey Legislature rewrote the law to satisfy the court's
objections, and the state continues to have one of the nation's
strongest shield laws. In 1982 Farber and The Times were
retroactively pardoned by Gov. Brendan Byrne, and the state repaid
the paper $101,000 of the $285,000 it had paid in fines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 Trautwein made a pivotal ruling in another closely
watched murder case, when the State Parole Board asked him to set
restitution payments so it could release Thomas Trantino, who was
serving a life sentence for shooting two police officers to death
in a Lodi nightclub in 1963. The judge refused.
</P>
<P>
   Without the required restitution, the Parole Board never freed
Trantino. His subsequent pleas for parole have all been denied, and
still in prison at age 62, he is New Jersey's longest-serving
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Walter Trautwein was born on March 29, 1920, in
Paramus, N.J. He graduated from Hackensack High School, where he
was an all-star athlete, won a scholarship at Columbia University
and was drafted as a pitcher by the St. Louis Cardinals. But as he
later told an interviewer, he needed to earn money to help his
struggling family, so he went to work as a stevedore. He attended
the Merchant Marine Academy and served in the Navy in World War II.
After the war he went to New York University and its law school. He
became a lawyer in 1953 and a county judge in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   As a District Court judge in the 1960s and 70s, Trautwein upheld
laws that established state control over the Hackensack Meadowlands
and financed the sports complex that brought major league football,
basketball and hockey to New Jersey. He was promoted to the State
Appellate Division in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, Ted, of Cos Cob, Conn., he is survived
by his wife of 45 years, Lorna; a daughter, Lorie Hayman of
Hallandale, Fla.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
